<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 00:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3642 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-GRETZKY-HNS &LR;      04-19 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GRETZKY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEIL HOHLFELD  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ Wayne Gretzky wanted Sunday to be a celebration of his
phenomenal 20-year career in the NHL. He wanted cheers, not tears,
as the theme for his final game.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Easier said than done, even for The Great One. In the end, try
as everyone might, it was impossible to hold back the emotions at
Madison Square Garden. Even Gretzky couldn't keep things in check
when the realization hit that he was skating off the ice for the
last time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were tears of joy,'' Gretzky said. ``Up until then, I
was savoring it. I got emotional a couple times at the end there.
You know, it's going to kill me not to play, but time does
something to you and I know it's time.''
</P>
<P>
   After Pittsburgh's Jaromir Jagr scored in overtime to beat the
New York Rangers 2-1, Gretzky's time was up. It seemed as if a
cold, hard truth suddenly hovered over the ice.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Gretzky was no more. After two decades of rewriting
record books, defining grace and dignity in a rough-and-tumble
sport and putting hockey on the map in the United States, Gretzky
was history.
</P>
<P>
   As he took a brief spin around the ice after the game, tears
started to well up in his eyes. He attempted to choke them back
during an impromptu team photo at center ice. When his two young
sons were brought onto the ice from their front-row seats to join
the photo, emotion overcame Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky twice retreated to the Rangers' dressing room before
coming back for additional trips around the ice. By the end, he was
more composed, smiling broadly, waving to fans and touching the
hands of several youngsters through openings in the glass.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers were tossed onto the ice, and Gretzky picked up a rose.
Tears and roses are not normally associated with hockey, but this
was an extraordinary finish to a career that will have no equal in
the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been pretty welled up with emotion for the last three,
four days,'' said Mark Messier, Gretzky's teammate on the Edmonton
Oilers during the glory days of the 1980s. ``I fought back the
tears a lot today. He was a great player, a great teammate. Just
reflecting on the last 20 years and seeing Wayne and the whole
thing, it has been pretty sad to see it all come down.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky, 38, finished his final season as the Rangers' leading
scorer, but he had only nine goals and 53 assists. It was the first
time in his career he did not reach double figures in goals. In
1985-86 with Edmonton, Gretzky had 215 points on 52 goals and 163
assists. In 1981-82 at the age of 21, he scored 92 goals for the
Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always too soon when you see a great player retire,''
said former Pittsburgh star Mario Lemieux, who retired two years
ago and attended Sunday's game. ``You want them to keep playing and
playing until they're 40, 45 years old. But there comes a time when
you realize you're not the player you were years ago. It's
frustrating for a great athlete to come to that realization, but it
happens to everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, Gretzky assisted on the Rangers' lone goal Sunday by
Brian Leetch. Gretzky finished his career with 894 goals and 1,963
assists. That's 2,857 points in 1,487 games _ nearly two points per
game over 20 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   To put things in perspective, Gretzky finished his career with
more assists than any other player in NHL history has points.
Gordie Howe, Gretzky's hero when he grew up in Brantford, Ontario,
is second with 1,850 points.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky had a chance to score the winning goal in his final game
late in the third period, but his quick shot from the right side
was turned away by Penguins goaltender Tom Barrasso.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would have been sweet, but he made a good save,'' Gretzky
said. ``With 30 seconds left (in regulation), during that timeout
John (Muckler, the Rangers' coach) called me over and said his
daughter had a baby today in Edmonton. He told me that I was going
to get the game-winner on the day his grandson was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe when I was younger, I might have got that game-winner
for him. But I didn't get it today, and that's another sign that
it's time.''
</P>
<P>
   Jagr is nursing a groin injury and was not going to play in the
season finale in order to rest for the playoffs. When Jagr learned
Gretzky was retiring, he wanted to be part of the historic
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr, who won the NHL scoring crown for the second straight
season, ended Gretzky's career with his 44th goal of the season at
1:22 of overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it was fitting that the best young player in the game
scored the goal in overtime,'' Gretzky said. ``Everyone always
talks about passing torches and all that stuff, well, he caught it.
I was happy for Jaromir.''
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake, this was Gretzky's day. He arrived at the
rink with his father, Walter, to complete a cycle that began 33
years ago when Gretzky, at age 5, played in an atom league against
10-year-olds. By the time Gretzky was 10 in 1972, he scored 378
goals with 120 assists in 69 games.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky tells the story that his father once kiddingly told
Wayne's mother to hang up two sheets on the front window instead of
buying drapes because Wayne needed a pair of skates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always tell people that I get all the glory and accolades,
but he deserves it, not me,'' Gretzky said. ``He was a blue-collar
guy who worked 8 to 5 every day and never made more than $35,000.
But everything he had, he gave to his family. Walking in with him
today brought back some special memories.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the historic arena in midtown Manhattan nearly three
hours before the game, fans lined up to buy commemorative programs
for $10. Others stood in line to pay $5 to have a photograph taken
with a cardboard cutout of Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   There were T-shirts celebrating Gretzky's final game selling for
$20. Gretzky sweaters were going for $160. People were begging to
buy extra tickets to the game; others were quietly trying to sell
them for upward of $500.
</P>
<P>
   It was the sort of hucksterism and hoopla Gretzky wanted to
avoid. He did not want the final stage of his career to dissolve
into a season-long farewell tour.
</P>
<P>
   He politely turned down NHL commissioner Gary Bettman's idea he
should return for the 1999-2000 season, a move that would have
ensured packed arenas throughout the league and increased TV
ratings. Instead, the end came quickly and with as little fanfare
as possible. Gretzky announced his retirement Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The less time to draw attention to himself, it seemed. That, in
a nutshell, was Gretzky's way throughout his career. Before the
game, Bettman announced Gretzky's famous No. 99 would not be worn
by any player in the NHL. As if anyone would have the nerve to wear
that number.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you take off that sweater, your jersey, after today's
game you will be the last player in the NHL to ever wear 99,''
Bettman said. ``You have always been and will always be The Great
One, and there will never be another.''
</P>
<P>
   A full hour after the game, Gretzky was still wearing his
uniform while answering questions in a news conference. He was
asked if he was avoiding taking it off for the last time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally I would have changed, but they said you guys (media)
were all waiting, so I came right over,'' Gretzky said. ``Probably
subconsciously I don't want to take it off, though. I'm not going
to put it on ever again. It's hard. I have to be honest, I don't
want to take it off. I haven't wavered one bit since making up my
mind, but that doesn't make this any easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky said that early in his pro career, his father told him
to savor each and every moment on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enjoy every shift,'' Walter Gretzky told his son, ``because
each one brings you closer to your last one.''
</P>
<P>
   The last shift came Sunday, punctuated by the kind of passion
and emotion Gretzky gave to hockey for 20 seasons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
