<HEADLINE>
REAL QUIET DISAPPOINTS, BUT KRONE DELIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
 MILE-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ Real Quiet disappointed some of his fans
Sunday at Lone Star Park, but Julie Krone made up for it.
</P>
<P>
   Krone, making what she says is her final appearance as a jockey,
won with her first three of five farewell mounts before a crowd of
21,124 adoring fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of everyone here, the day turned out to be a wonderful
experience,'' Krone said. ``I didn't think I would be choked up or
feel that nostalgic about it, but I am.''
</P>
<P>
   The 4-foot-10 dynamo was cheered at every turn, even when she
took a cake in the face courtesy of fellow riders after winning the
third race named the Julie Krone Classic in her honor. Her only
regret shows her competitive side; that she didn't also win with
her final two mounts. She was third on Allen's Oop in the $250,000
Texas Mile, and second on Desert Demon in the $300,000 Lone Star
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   But Real Quiet didn't win the Texas Mile, either. He finished
second to defending race champion Littlebitlively after a stretch
duel.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd contributed to record betting. Local wagering on Lone
Star's 11-race program was $1,723,177, which eclipsed the old
record of $1,692,090 set on the same day in the track's first
season of 1997, when Skip Away turned out for the Texas Mile.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away finished third in that race, and Real Quiet's defeat
Sunday made it 0-for-2 for Eclipse Award-winning racehorses at Lone
Star.
</P>
<P>
   With his trademark move around the second turn, Real Quiet took
Gary Stevens past pacesetting Littlebitlively to a half-length lead
entering the stretch of the Texas Mile. Many watchers, no doubt,
were convinced the 2-5 favorite, who came within a nose of sweeping
the 1997 Triple Crown, had the situation under control.
</P>
<P>
   But Littlebitlively had coasted through slow early fractions _
including a half-mile in 47.26 seconds _ and was full of energy
when Real Quiet rolled alongside. Just like last year, when
Littlebitlively was passed in the stretch by Anet, the tenacious
5-year-old battled back along the rail under Carlos Gonzalez and
claimed a neck victory in the state's first graded stakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tough little horse, so I knew there was going to be a
battle,'' said Stevens, riding Real Quiet for the first time. ``He
had a lot of horse coming down the stretch, and so did I.''
</P>
<P>
   Littlebitlively and Real Quiet hit the wire 13/4 lengths ahead
of Allen's Oop in 1:35.65, with a swift final quarter-mile in 24.39
seconds. Local star Mocha Express was a well-beaten fourth in the
eight-horse field.
</P>
<P>
   It was Texas Mile deja vu. A year ago, Gonzalez also was aboard
Littlebitlively, owned by John Franks of Shreveport and trained by
Bobby Barnett. And for the second consecutive time, his
photo-finish victim was a 4-year-old racehorse trained by Bob
Baffert.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's getting on my nerves, that Barnett guy,'' joked Baffert,
who has a mixed history in the Texas Mile. Before losing the past
two in heartbreakers, he saddled Isitingood to defeat Skip Away in
the race's inaugural running.
</P>
<P>
   Barnett also trains Precocity, who upset Real Quiet last month
in the New Orleans Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy it every time I beat him,'' Barnett said of Baffert,
``but it's a friendly competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert knew Littlebitlively would be difficult to beat, and
said he was pleased with Real Quiet's effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ran hard, he ran good,'' Baffert said. ``(Littlebitlively)
is a very good horse, an underrated horse. When I saw the pace, I
said `Uh-oh.' At least he showed some guts and kept trying to get
past that horse in the stretch. You want to win 'em all, but you
get beat.''
</P>
<P>
   In his most recent start, Littlebitlively finished second to
Behrens in the Oaklawn Handicap on April 3. Barnett said he is
considering sending him to Baltimore to join Precocity in the May 8
Pimlico Special.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet also is being pointed for the Pimlico Special,
Baffert said, so another rematch with nemesis Barnett could be in
the works.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
