<HEADLINE>
SUNS SWEEP SEASON SERIES AS SONICS STUMBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ A game official approached Sonics coach Paul Westphal
early Sunday and requested a starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal refused.
</P>
<P>
   When pressed about coaching for the first time in the building
where he was axed three years ago, Westphal recoiled his emotions.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until after the Sonics stumbled down the stretch of
Sunday's 99-93 loss to the Phoenix Suns that Westphal dropped his
shield. Unfortunately for Westphal, his Sonics were not as guarded
as long.
</P>
<P>
   In what was essentially the umpteenth must-win game this week,
the Sonics battled the Suns for 3{ quarters. But it didn't take a
genius to figure out why Westphal screamed: ``Don't foul. Just let
it end,'' with eight seconds left in the game. At that point,
winning was as hopeless as the final six minutes were for the
Sonics at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 85-84, the Sonics committed four straight turnovers
without scoring a field goal. They were beaten to loose balls and
outworked for rebounds. That stretch was enough to allow Phoenix
(21-20) to end with a 14-9 run and beat the Sonics (19-21) for the
third time this season and a first-ever sweep of their
regular-season series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just couldn't finish the game,'' Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat was the Sonics' second straight after Friday's
30-point loss at home to New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to get on a roll for a month, the Sonics are floundering
toward the finish line. It is possible a playoff berth might not be
waiting at the end of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics fell 1{ games behind the Suns, who own the seventh
seed and the tie-breaker edge in the Western Conference playoff
race. The Sonics are clinging to the No. 8 spot, just one game up
on Sacramento and Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're both like 20-20,'' forward Vin Baker said of Phoenix.
``I don't think it means much.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' record tumbled two games below .500 for the first
time this season. The team has 10 games left.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Sonics did not earn a playoff berth was the
1989-90 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a huge game,'' Westphal said. ``If we win enough
games, we can still make the playoffs. If we make the playoffs and
heal up some of the places where we've been hurting this year, then
we can win some playoff games. But we have to find a way to put
together a run. We've been sputtering all season, but we're not
going to give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal continued his course in patchwork, using yet another
starting lineup in an attempt to match the Suns' height and
offensive firepower. Only seven players saw time for the Sonics,
and it was a strange rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Baker started at center in place of Olden Polynice. The boldest
move, though, was starting Don MacLean at power forward. MacLean
had missed 33 games this season. However, he held his own against
the Suns' Tom Gugliotta, who led all scorers with 27 points and 12
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   MacLean, who had scored a total of 21 points this season, had 16
Sunday in 36 minutes. Gary Payton led the Sonics with 21 points and
11 assists.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics were playing their fourth game in five days. They
finish off a grueling week tonight against the Houston Rockets at
the Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   Neither lineups nor fatigue was a major factor. Phoenix edged
the Sonics in rebounding, 41-40. Critical, though, was that the
Suns collected 20 offensive boards and beat the Sonics on the glass
14-9 in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our chance,'' said forward Detlef Schrempf, who
finished with 20 points and 10 rebounds. ``We knocked the ball
loose and didn't come up with it. And we didn't get rebounds. It's
the same old story.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix had beaten the Sonics just five days earlier at
KeyArena, when Seattle collected a record NBA-low 19 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the Sonics tied the game twice in the fourth before
unraveling.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got all of the big rebounds,'' Westphal said of the Suns.
``We were in control of the boards most of the game. Then, they got
the ones they needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what happened to the Sonics, Schrempf shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. Not yet. We just haven't executed,'' he said.
``That's the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   And it could get worse.
</P>
</TEXT>
