<HEADLINE>
HUARD'S FUTURE IN TALENTED HANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The gray skies cleared, revealing snow-capped
mountains set against a gorgeous blue horizon. It was exactly the
kind of day everyone promised Mike Holmgren happens in Seattle, the
kind of weather for which there is every reason to believe
everything is going to be all right.
</P>
<P>
   Brock Huard's NFL fate was sealed last Thursday, under nearly
blissful conditions.
</P>
<P>
   That was the day Seahawks coaches, coordinators and the
franchise's new, impressive leader decided to take a trip across
Lake Washington to the University of Washington. It was time for
the Seahawks to complete their detailed investigation of the
prototypical NFL quarterback whose stock was in the Dumpster.
</P>
<P>
   Was this lefty slinger really the shell-shocked, gun-shy,
off-balance, back-footed thrower his detractors had pegged him? Or
was this Huard a solid pro pick whose potential could be realized
with time, patience and persistence under one of the NFL's master
motivators and cultivators of quarterbacks?
</P>
<P>
   When Holmgren used a third-round pick to take Huard in this
weekend's NFL draft, the answer was obvious. All of Huard's
so-called flaws have been deemed correctable.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a project, but some projects are a risk. Brock is not a
risk,'' Seahawks offensive coordinator Mike Sherman said Sunday.
``For Mike to choose him in the third round means there is a
legitimate amount of expectation that this will be successful, for
both parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brock put himself in a position to come in and be competitive.
... This is a good learning experience for Brock, and when it comes
to quarterbacks, or anyone, Mike Holmgren knows what buttons to
push.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it did not hurt that the day the new Seahawks
leadership posse headed west to Montlake for Huard's last-look
workout, Seattle looked like God's country.
</P>
<P>
   And on that day, one very devout Christian young man who had
worn the weight of the world on his shoulders was helped toward an
instructive revelation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, he's a talented guy,'' Holmgren said about the
newest quarterback he will add to his heady class list that already
has included Joe Montana, Steve Young and Steve Bono in San
Francisco and Brett Favre, Ty Detmer and Mark Brunell in Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``He now just has (to deal with) pressure. The pressure we have
to be careful of is the pressure he will put on himself,'' Holmgren
said. ``I believe he has done that, to his detriment. I sense that
he has put that (on himself.) It's almost like he couldn't make a
mistake. Heck, it's still a game. They are not robots.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve Bono was a classic. He over-analyzed everything. No one
can compute that much information and act upon it. So just have a
couple things and then cut it loose. Throw it. Run. Do whatever,
but don't paralyze yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Things are starting to turn out all right for Huard, who
deserves this chance and who must feel, just like first-round
Seahawks pick Lamar King said Sunday, that coming to Seattle means
playing for one of the best coaches in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren admits that no matter how high up the food chain he
ascends, he is first and foremost still a lover of quarterbacks _
developing them by giving them the techniques, formations, reads,
confidence, instructions and green light to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren puts a premium on this particular talent of his. He
sees Huard as another gem he can help polish, as long as Huard is
willing to ingest the instruction on West Coast offense and let the
pro game come to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our workout the other day, he really had a fine workout.
But you know, one ball sailed a little bit on him, and he went (and
got really flustered and upset)'' Holmgren said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Goodness gracious.' I drove over the bridge, and if
you remember that day, it was fabulous. So I'm seeing the sun on
the lake and the mountains and I'm standing there on the practice
field and I told Brock: `Hey, look around. Look at this. You're
doing fine.' But I think he wants it so bad, one of my jobs is
going to be to get him just to back off and look at it and enjoy
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first NFL draft as both head coach and team vice
president, Holmgren was determined to have fun, stockpile players
at positions where depth was lacking, make an impact on his new
team's talent pool.
</P>
<P>
   For all the hype and paralysis by over-analysis that accompanies
the NFL draft _ a non-event that somehow blusters itself to World
Wrestling Federation proportion _ Holmgren did manage to show as
much about himself.
</P>
<P>
   By picking Huard, Holmgren is giving him the opportunity to
re-invent himself right here at home.
</P>
<P>
   By picking Huard, Holmgren has all but made a commitment to
helping him prove all those critics and naysayers were too hard on
the kid.
</P>
<P>
   Huard may have been born to be a quarterback. He may have been
raised to be a quarterback. He may have dreamed of being an NFL
quarterback. But it is Holmgren who can push him to that final,
ultimate destination.
</P>
<P>
   In this way, Huard may be better off than guys named Kerry
Collins or Ryan Leaf, Tim Couch or Akili Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
