r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-LONGBEACH-SIDE-LA     04-19 0383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-LONGBEACH-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FITTIPALDI MAD DESPITE FINISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Christian Fittipaldi has played second
fiddle to Newman-Haas teammate Michael Andretti for too long.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight week, Fittipaldi beat his much more
heralded teammate to the finish line, taking fifth place in
Sunday's 25th annual Toyota Grand Prix of Long Beach. Andretti
placed seventh.
</P>
<P>
   It's Fittipaldi's best finish on the street course -- the first
time in four tries that he has been around at the finish.
</P>
<P>
   But the Brazilian, who finished third last weekend in Motegi,
Japan was still an unhappy driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am disappointed,'' said Fittipaldi, who is sixth in the
points standings after the first three of 20 races. ``We're still
troubled by the set-up for street circuit and road courses. We
can't contend for the points title if this continues. We need to do
more homework. We came to this race expecting more.''
</P>
<P>
   After a promising start, including two seconds in the
Indianapolis 500, it's been a long road to get near the top for the
nephew of former CART champion Emerson Fittipaldi. Long Beach has
certainly been a road block on the way.
</P>
<P>
   He has qualified 12th or better in each of his four races along
Shoreline Drive. He was involved in crashes in 1996 and '98 and
fell two laps short of finishing in '95 because of mechanical
failure. He did not race the event in '97 because of a broken right
tibia and fibula, caused by a horrific crash at Surfer's Paradise,
Australia, that sidelined him for seven races. He has yet to win a
CART race, but has two second-place finishes and four thirds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This race was good in only that I finally finished,''
Fittipaldi said. ``I'm disappointed because I could have finished
in the top three if our car had been set up better in qualifying.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Fittipaldi, who qualified 11th, gradually moved up in
the field, managing to avoid trouble ahead of him and stay near the
top with nearly flawless pit stops.
</P>
<P>
   Fittipaldi never really was in position to challenge the
leaders, even after the final re-start on Lap 81. Between him and
fourth-place Adrian Fernandez was P.J. Jones, who was running a lap
down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
