<P>
   VIETNAM-MIA (Hanoi, Vietnam) _ At the end of April, on the 27th
anniversary of her son's death on the battlefield at Dak To, a
tired-looking woman named Pham Kim Hy will kneel before a glass
bottle filled with dirt and pebbles, light sticks of incense and
pray for his soul. Since the Vietnam War ended in 1975, Mrs. Hy,
who is now 70, has devoted her life to a search for her son's
remains, writing letters, distributing his portrait, talking to his
fellow soldiers, studying maps and hiking into the jungle, over and
over again, to dig for his bones. Her son, Ho Viet Dung, was 20
when he died. He is one of an estimated 300,000 Vietnamese soldiers
who are still missing in action, and who will probably never be
accounted for. By Seth Mydans.
