u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-SPURS-HNS     04-19 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-SPURS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rockets
</P>
<P>
   Elie sinks game-winner, Rockets' spirits
</P>
<P>
   Spurs erase 23-point deficit to slam division rivals
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JONATHAN FEIGEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN ANTONIO _ Mario Elie blew a bitter kiss and pounded his chest,
screaming at the Rockets' bench with everything he had to be heard
over the Alamodome roar. He lifted his jersey to expose his heart,
as if sure it beat hard enough to show through the skin.
</P>
<P>
   He need not have bothered. The heart of a castoff is clearly
still beating.
</P>
<P>
   Elie more than beat the Rockets on Sunday, nailing a no-doubt 3
with one-tenth of a second left for an 86-83 Spurs win. He punished
the Rockets for letting him go and the insult he carried with him
to San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   He scored the Spurs' last 10 points, and still stinging from
Charles Barkley's comments last week that Elie was concerned last
season only with a new contract, he angrily exacted his revenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just heart,'' Elie said before Spurs officials pulled him
to the locker room, against his wishes, when he was asked about his
feelings about the Rockets. ``I was showing them my heart. It takes
heart to take a shot like that. It will be good to talk trash this
summer knowing we got them 3-0 in the regular season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets had little to say about Elie's vendetta. But they
knew him well enough to know how he felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure,'' Rockets center Hakeem Olajuwon said, ``this made
his whole season.''
</P>
<P>
   For them, the Rockets said it was as crushing a defeat as they
have felt all season, surpassing even the 15-point fourth-quarter
collapse in Utah. This time, they blew a 23-point lead in the first
half but recovered and led by three with two minutes left, and by
two with 52 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   And since rededicating themselves Monday in Minnesota, they had
more at stake in San Antonio than even Sunday's chance to move into
a tie with the Spurs for the third seed in the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time since ,'' Barkley said, unable or
unwilling to capture his emotions. ``I feel disappointed right now.
I'm just disappointed, because we played well. To end on this note
is disappointing. We really wanted this game. I can't even express
how I feel. I feel sad. We really wanted to win this game.''
</P>
<P>
   That was clear from the outset when the notoriously
slow-starting Rockets rushed to a 31-13 lead after the first
quarter. They blew all of that by the time two minutes were gone in
the second half. But they also recovered from the Spurs' comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon struggled most of the night, making eight of 26 shots.
Scottie Pippen, after his 31-point outburst Thursday, took five
shots, finishing with six points.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Rockets down 70-66 with 10 minutes left, Olajuwon
scored eight of his 18 points in a span of six minutes, his hook in
the lane tying the game at 78 with 3:16 left. When Bryce Drew
pulled up on a fast break for a 3, the Rockets led by three with
2:42 left.
</P>
<P>
   But that only seemed to cue Elie, in such situations so many
times, to take over. He had scored the Spurs' previous points on a
fast-break dunk after Pippen slipped and lost the ball. With 1:42
left, he answered Drew's 3 with one of his own, drifting uncovered
to the corner to take a pass from Avery Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a couple of mistakes letting them get that 3-pointer
with a three-point lead,'' Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich said.
``We left a guy in the corner on a pick-and-roll. We never do that.
We definitely never do that with a 3-point lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley (23 points) regained the Rockets' lead, making two free
throws with 52 seconds left. But on an inbounds play under the
basket, Elie set a pick for David Robinson, then slipped to the
basket for a layup, tying the score with 44.1 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs left the Rockets enough time for two possessions. The
Rockets found Pippen wide-open in the corner for a 3 that touched
every part of the rim and possibly some of the net before popping
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just came out,'' Pippen said. ``I had a good look at the
shot. I didn't want to throw up any to get a two-for-one. At that
stage, we needed to come down and make a defensive stop. We didn't.
We allowed a guy to set up at the 3.''
</P>
<P>
   They allowed the wrong guy. With his 7-of-8 shooting game, Elie
has shot 77.3 percent against the Rockets this season and has made
nine of 10 3s. He was covered for all but the last split second.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson used a Robinson pick to head down the lane, drawing
Olajuwon off Robinson. Johnson's pass to Robinson pulled Drew off
Elie. And Elie set up his game-winner as coolly as if playing in
the driveway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Robinson at 17 feet wide-open,'' Drew said. ``My
reaction was with five seconds left to run over there. I was sure
he'd shoot it. When he passed, I knew my man was wide-open. My
heart stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   But Elie's heart beat hard enough for both, until he all but
pulled it from his chest to show off to the team he believed had
left it broken. By the time his celebration began, the Rockets knew
the feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we feel now,'' Barkley said, ``I don't want to ever
feel again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
