<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 00:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3658 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CARDS-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      04-19 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CARDS-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Astros manager Larry Dierker couldn't help but wonder lately if his
team would ever come from behind with one of those late big innings
that became a trademark last season.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Finally,'' Dierker said Sunday after the Astros rallied with a
six-run eighth to defeat the St. Louis Cardinals 8-4 at the
Astrodome. ``I kept looking at the scoreboard, day after day, and
all of these teams were scoring four, five and six runs in an
inning against us. For a team that's supposed to do it a little
more often, we hadn't done it yet.''
</P>
<P>
   After producing 48 come-from-behind victories _ 27 in their
final at-bat _ last season, the Astros entered Sunday's eighth
inning an uncharacteristic 0-6 when trailing after seven. They had
not scored more than three runs in an inning all season.
</P>
<P>
   Releasing two weeks' worth of frustration, the Astros sent 11
batters to the plate during the decisive inning that turned a
two-run deficit into a four-run cushion. Carl Everett began the
rally with a solo home run and later in the inning had an RBI
single as the Astros escaped Mark McGwire's fifth home run of the
season and salvaged one victory in the three-game series against
their National League Central rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a turning point for us to get those runners in,''
said Everett, who was 3-for-4 and has hit safely in 11 of 12 games
this season. ``Everybody chipped in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' eight runs and 16 hits off four St. Louis pitchers
were season highs. But they waited until they were down to six outs
to get things going. Cardinals relievers Lance Painter (0-1) and
Scott Radinsky were victimized for most of the damage, each
allowing three runs in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were going to have another 13-hit, three-run
outburst,'' first baseman Jeff Bagwell said. ``We were kind of
disappointed the last few days. We had been outhitting the
Cardinals every time, and they end up beating us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros outhit the Cardinals in the previous two games of the
series only to lose 5-3 and 8-5. The Cards used a five-run fourth
inning Friday and a seven-run eighth on Saturday to seal the
Astros' fate.
</P>
<P>
   It was a different story Sunday. Everett connected on the first
pitch from Painter in the eighth for his second home run of the
season, and the Astros tied the game at 4 when Alex Diaz doubled
and scored on a single by Tony Eusebio.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Bell, who was 4-for-4 with three RBIs, drove in the
go-ahead run with a bases-loaded sacrifice fly to center field.
Bagwell chipped in a two-run single off Radinsky, and Everett
followed with his second hit of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of expectations are on this offense, and rightfully
so,'' Bagwell said. ``It seemed like we scored eight runs a lot
last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Astros scored eight or more runs 35 times last
season. Before Sunday, however, they had been held to half that or
worse in seven of 11 games this season, five of those losses.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros took a 1-0 lead early on when Craig Biggio and Bell
doubled to start the bottom of the first. St. Louis tied the game
in the second when Astros starter Mike Hampton allowed four
straight hits, including a run-scoring double by Shawon Dunston.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, who received a no-decision, got some much-needed help
from his defense to get out of the inning with only one run
allowed. Diaz, a replacement for Richard Hidalgo in left field,
took Dunston's double off the wall and relayed the ball to
shortstop Tim Bogar, who threw out Fernando Tatis at the plate
after Eric Davis had scored. J.D. Drew then singled up the middle,
but Everett gunned down Dunston at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton allowed four runs and eight hits in seven innings,
walking four and striking out five.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who entered the series finale with one hit in his
previous nine at-bats, gave the Cardinals a 2-1 lead with a solo
home run to left off Hampton in the fourth. With five homers in 11
games, McGwire is ahead of the pace he set en route to a record 70
last year. He didn't hit No. 5 until the Cardinals' 13th game in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``They pitched me pretty darn good,'' said McGwire, who went
2-for-12 in the series. ``The only pitch I really saw was the one I
got the home run on.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Astros pulled even at 2, St. Louis went back in front
4-2 in the seventh on Placido Polanco's two-run single off Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Powell (1-0), who gave up four runs in a third of an inning
a night earlier, pitched a scoreless eighth inning with two
strikeouts to pick up the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get thrown from the horse, the first thing you have
to do is get back on it,'' Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Wagner finished, striking out two of the four hitters he
faced in the ninth. In five innings this season, Wagner has eight
strikeouts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
