<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 00:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3663 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-LONGBEACH-LBPT     04-19 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-LONGBEACH-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTOYA RIGHT ON TARGET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Someone needs to stop Chip Ganassi before
he gets on a plane headed home to Indianapolis and ask the
Target/Ganassi Racing owner if he could please give the Long Beach
streets back to the city. There are hard-working, tax-paying
citizens who need them to get to work this morning.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Ganassi doesn't need the streets anymore, at least
not until next April. His 1999 work schedule at the Beach ended
Sunday at about 3 p.m. in what has become Team Target's home away
from home _ the winner's circle of the Grand Prix of Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody who saw Jimmy Vasser win in 1996 and Alex Zanardi speed
his way to back-to-back victories the past two seasons can't be
surprised about Target's fourth consecutive triumph on the streets
of Long Beach. Until you consider the latest Long Beach winner,
Juan Montoya, is a 23-year-old rookie who until Sunday had a CART
FedEx Championship resume of two races and came from a European
Formula 3000 series that rarely runs on temporary street courses.
</P>
<P>
   The only team to dominate Long Beach in similar fashion was
Galles-Kraco, which won five consecutive races with Al Unser Jr.
(1988-91) and Danny Sullivan (1992).
</P>
<P>
   So what allowed Team Target to coax Montoya to victory, even
though the Long Beach course was different than the previous three
years?
</P>
<P>
   ``California water,'' Ganassi said.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Herta, who traded champagne sprays with Montoya and
runner-up Dario Franchitti, had a different answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's something they do here in particular,''
said Herta, a Valencia native who drives the No.8 Shell car for
Team Rahal. ``They do a good job everywhere. They have a lot of
money, they have a great package, they have a lot of good people,
they have great drivers and they execute races. I mean, they are
the benchmark now and they continue to be the one we are trying to
beat.''
</P>
<P>
   The only one who appeared quick enough to beat Montoya on Sunday
was pole sitter Tony Kanaan, and his day ended on the 45th lap when
he slid his McDonald's Drive Thru car into the tire barrier at the
inside of turn 6. Montoya, who shadowed Kanaan for several laps,
directed his red-yellow-and-white No.4 Reynard-Honda into the lead
and dominated the remainder of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya's lead grew as large as 11.175 seconds over Franchitti
before a yellow flag on the 78th of 85 laps came out when Cristiano
da Matta hit the same tire barriers that claimed Kanaan. But
Montoya was too good, holding off Franchitti by 2.805 seconds to
take his first checkered flag. He averaged 87.915 miles per hour on
the 11-turn, 1.824-mile street circuit.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the top five consisted of Herta, Patrick
Racing's Adrian Fernandez and Newman-Haas driver Christian
Fittipaldi.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya's victory in only his third Champ Car race marks the
second-quickest win for a rookie driver in an open-wheel series.
Nigel Mansell set the standard in Australia when he won his first
CART event, but that came after he established himself as a Formula
One champion before coming to the United States. Zanardi was second
on the list after winning in his ninth start of his 1996 rookie
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is my best win,'' said Montoya, who was the
European 3000 champion and four-time race winner last season.
``This weekend, we put it all together. Now we're just going to try
to keep on winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Montoya sang a different tune after a 10th-place effort in the
season- pener in Miami and a frustrating weekend in Japan. Montoya
was fined $5,000 and put on probation by CART officials after a
Japan qualifying incident with Michael Andretti, and the Colombian
rookie saw a promising race end the next day when he ran out of
fuel while trying to get past eventual winner Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, in Homestead, I don't think we gave him a good
car,'' Ganassi said. ``We had some mechanical failure. We had some
mechanical/mental failure from the team in (Japan). I think we let
him down in the first couple of races.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a difficult final qualifying run, the same can't be
said for this weekend. Montoya was second in the first qualifying
session and had a perfect car during the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important for us to get back to our
no-mechanical-failure ways,'' said Ganassi, whose team is trying to
become the first to win four consecutive points titles. ``I think,
obviously, we have high expectations as a team. I'd like to think
we have a pretty good group of guys that are engineering the car
and screwing it together.''
</P>
<P>
   In Montoya, they also have a pretty good guy joining Vasser _
who finished a disappointing 10th on Sunday _ on Team Target.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever was going to steer (Zanardi's former car) as we all
know had big shoes to fill,'' said Ganassi of his two-time CART
champion driver, who electrified the series with his charisma on
and off the track. ``All of these guys are fast at this level; to
win you have to have someone mentally tough. I knew (Montoya) had
the talent. What I didn't know was if he had the mental toughness
to put those (early season) incidents behind him. You don't see
that much from a guy his age.''
</P>
<P>
   Another youngster, Kanaan, was sitting on the pole for the first
time as a CART driver. He lost that lead quickly when Herta,
starting on the inside of the second row, turned up the power as
the green flag dropped and beat the front row of Kanaan and
Franchitti to the first turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about that start for Bryan?'' said Team Rahal owner and
former CART champion Bobby Rahal. ``That was a great move.''
</P>
<P>
   Herta's only lead of the day lasted one lap before Kanaan dipped
under the Shell car for the lead at the end of the back
straightaway. For the next 44 laps it was Kanaan on the lead, but
that ended when he got caught in the marbles on Turn 6 and crashed
into the tire barriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mistake,'' Kanaan said. ``The track was breaking up
and I just ran off line a little bit and lost it. Sometimes you
learn the hard way.''
</P>
<P>
   Montoya happily accepted the lead, but he also showed a touch of
compassion for his competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was too bad what happened to Tony,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, Montoya, who was trailing by a scant 0.783 seconds at the
time, had a plan against Kanaan even if the No.44 car didn't find
the tire barrier. That plan?
</P>
<P>
   ``Overtake him,'' Montoya said.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya, who qualified fifth, had overtaken Herta on the 22nd
lap and got past Franchitti on the restart following a 27th lap
collision that knocked Tarso Marques out of the race and Scott
Pruett and Helio Castro-Neves down a lap. Once Kanaan exited, it
was Franchitti trying to catch Montoya, but with each lap it became
evident that the Team Kool Green driver would have to settle for
second place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave it everything I had today, but we just didn't have the
car to challenge for the win,'' said Franchitti. ``That's unusual
because we normally have the best car on the street circuits. We
were lacking a little bit, but the guys from Team Kool Green gave
me great stops and kept me in the hunt all day. On the track,
however, we just weren't fast enough today.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchitti, who is the circuit's best street-course operator,
had enough to claim a fourth consecutive top-two finish on a
temporary street course.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 0052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3667 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEROMEHOTEL-AZR &LR;      04-19 1307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEROMEHOTEL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIECE OF JEROME, ARIZ., HISTORY FOR SALE _ GHOSTS AND ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER CORBETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEROME, Ariz. _ Like a fortress atop Cleopatra Hill, this relic
mining-company hospital sat empty for 45 years before it was
brought back to life in 1996 as the Jerome Grand Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   But the hotel's owners pulled the plug in January and the 1926
landmark is back on life support, awaiting an April 30 auction that
could lure a new owner and another revival.
</P>
<P>
   Potential buyers will have to consider the viability of the
hotel, which was in business just 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Although hundreds of tourists visit Jerome's historic hillside
galleries, cafes and taverns each day, most of them are gone by
sundown, winding their way down the ``Hogback'' on the highway to
Clarkdale.
</P>
<P>
   The five-story hotel is perched above the main business
district, nearly a mile above sea level and accessible only by
steep and narrow Hill Street.
</P>
<P>
   Occupancy at the Jerome Grand averaged about 50 percent, and the
restaurant and lounge drew people from all over the Verde Valley
and Sedona. Rates for the hotel's 20 rooms ranged from $70 to $170
per night.
</P>
<P>
   The Altherr family, which bought the presumably haunted property
in 1994, was much better at converting it into a hotel than it was
at running a hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was burning us out managing it,'' Larry Altherr said.
</P>
<P>
   Auctioneer John Weaver of Southwest Real Estate Auctioneers said
bidding for the one-of-a-kind property probably will start around
$2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Altherr said Phelps Dodge was asking $670,000 for the property
in 1994, and his family invested about $1 million in improvements.
</P>
<P>
   When they took over the place, Altherr and his brother, Bob,
tinkered like mad scientists with the electrical control panel to
restart the 70-year-old Otis elevator, which has an accordion door.
They also fired up the original Kewannee steam boiler and switched
the lights on for the first time in 44 years.
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a sight when the hospital on the hill beamed with
light, Larry Altherr said.
</P>
<P>
   A tour reveals that the hospital-turned-hotel has survived the
ravages of time with remarkable grace, save for some leaky windows
and drainpipes. Two-thirds of the 32 rooms have been restored.
</P>
<P>
   The Altherrs, Phoenix natives with a background in construction
and restoration, maintained the architectural integrity of the
Spanish mission-style building while transforming it from its
institutional roots into an interesting historic inn.
</P>
<P>
   Some townsfolk say there was friction between the town and the
Altherrs, particularly over some excavation on the property.
</P>
<P>
   But Mayor Jay Kinsella said the hotel was an asset to Jerome and
he'd like to see another owner have a go at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's all lit up at night, it's absolutely beautiful,''
Kinsella said.
</P>
<P>
   The United Verde Mining Co. hospital was built during Jerome's
lucrative mining era, when the population soared to 15,000. The
30,000-square-foot hospital was a modern marvel, with one of the
state's first self-service elevators. Phelps Dodge bought United
Verde in 1935 and operated the hospital until 1950, three years
before the company shut the mines. Phelps Dodge maintained the
hospital in working order until 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome, 110 miles north of Phoenix on the steep slope of Mingus
Mountain, dwindled to a ghost of its billion-dollar boomtown past,
when miners blew their pay in casinos, bars and bawdy houses.
</P>
<P>
   The population dwindled to a few hundred before a renaissance
began in the 1960s. Jerome, celebrating its centennial this year,
now has about 475 residents.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital's haunted reputation mushroomed from its long
dormancy and tales of mysterious deaths and ghosts. Jerome, after
all, is a ghost town.
</P>
<P>
   As part of their initiation, fraternity pledges from Northern
Arizona University sometimes were forced to sneak into the old
hospital and spend the night, Kinsella says.
</P>
<P>
   A science-fiction cable television program called ``Insights''
brought up a crew and a clairvoyant to explore the hospital's
mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   Among the deaths at the United Verde Hospital was a terminally
ill mining company superintendent who shot himself, a caretaker who
hanged himself and a hospital maintenance man, Claude Harvey, who
was found dead at the bottom of the elevator shaft in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   An inquest was inconclusive, but Altherr said he believes that
Harvey simply had a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   He has seen some mysterious things _ doors swinging open
inexplicably and the old call lights for the nurses going on when
nobody was around to activate them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a deal with the ghost,'' Altherr said, half-seriously.
``I said, `You don't pay rent and you don't hold a paintbrush;
don't bother me and I won't bother you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Not all memories of the United Verde Hospital are so dark.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Schrader was born there in 1929. Her father, John Oscar
Mullen, was school superintendent in Jerome for 40 years and she
lived in the town until 1948.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the hospital a couple of times,'' she recalled. ``At
about age 6, they thought I had appendicitis, but it turned out I
probably just ate too many peanut butter cookies.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, she hit an iron pole in a sledding accident
and woke up in the hospital. Her left side was paralyzed for about
six months.
</P>
<P>
   Schrader, now a Tucson real estate broker, has fond memories of
Jerome, recalling all the recreational facilities and services
provided by the mining company.
</P>
<P>
   She returned in 1997 for her 50th high school reunion and stayed
at the Jerome Grand Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The room was lovely,'' Schrader said. ``The building was
really sad before these people took it over. They have done wonders
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   James Byrkit, a retired NAU professor and author, also began
life in the United Verde Hospital, at dawn on June 16, 1931.
</P>
<P>
   The building holds some vivid memories for him, although he has
not seen the Jerome Grand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember having my tonsils out at age 10 and I was scared to
death when they were putting me under with the ether,'' Byrkit
said. ``They told me it wouldn't hurt. I was in horrible pain when
I woke up, so I thought they had lied to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrkit, a historian who wrote ``Forging the Copper Collar,'' an
unflattering look at the power wielded by mining companies in early
Arizona, recalls ambulances racing up the hill to the hospital
after a miner accidentally set off a dynamite charge or the mine
shaft hoists gave way.
</P>
<P>
   The surgical suite where the injured miners were treated by
longtime Jerome surgeon A.C. Carlson remains intact in the Jerome
Grand. Lighted by a skylight and a bank of windows looking down on
the town, the pale-blue tiled operating room originally was
targeted for a new life as a large hotel suite, Altherr said.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital's dispensary has been transformed into the Grand
View Lounge, which includes a player-piano nickelodeon that
nowadays costs a quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Solariums at the end of the hospital wings have been kept as
sitting rooms for guests. A room that old blueprints call the
``Violet Ray Room'' now is a guest room.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital, now on the National Register of Historic Places,
was designed by Lescher &AMP; Mahoney, a prominent Phoenix
architectural firm.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth hospital built in Jerome. Underground
cave-ins, a common scourge of the town's buildings, weakened the
foundation of previous hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver, the auctioneer, said the hotel is a hard property to
market, but the right buyer could step in and capitalize on the
Altherrs' efforts.
</P>
<P>
   He called it a chance for someone to own a piece of Arizona
history, ghosts and all. &QL; 
Peter Corbett can be reached at (602) 444-4815 or at
peter.corbett(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
