<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GRETZKY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GRETZKY, A GREAT FAREWELL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Only a once-in-a-millennium star could outgrow a
nickname like ``The Great One.''
</P>
<P>
   Hockey will spawn more great players. But Sunday at Madison
Square Garden, it bid bittersweet farewell to retiring Wayne
Gretzky _ ``The Greatest One.''
</P>
<P>
   After 20 seasons of hogging every award, inventing new ways to
put the puck in the net and spreading the gospel of hockey from
frigid Ontario to sunny Miami, Gretzky dished out one last,
glorious assist and called it a career after the New York Rangers'
2-1 overtime loss to the Pittsburgh Penguins before 18,200 raucous
spectators who came for one last glimpse of the most successful
person to wear skates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to kill me not to play, but mentally and physically
I'm really ready to retire,'' said Gretzky, who faked a slap shot
that knocked goalie Tom
</P>
<P>
   Barrasso off his feet before sliding a gorgeous assist to Brian
Leetch for a 1-1 tie and his last NHL point late in the second
period. ``I don't want to take this sweater off, because I know
I'll never put it on again.''
</P>
<P>
   After making the NHL his personal Wayne's World, the league's
human power play was ushered out with a ceremony that felt more
like a royal abdication. With 99 bottles of tears on the walls of
the Garden and an adoring national television audience watching,
Gretzky endured an emotional day in which he received telephone
calls from President Clinton and Michael Jordan, then was showered
with a rink full of going-away presents including Bryan Adams
slipping in an impromptu ``We will miss you Wayne'' into O, Canada!
(''I don't think those words will stick,'' Gretzky said), a
limited-edition baseball glove chair (like the one in Yankees owner
George Steinbrenner's office), numerous standing ovations, a
75-inch TV, a new black Mercedes-Benz (''Of course I'm keeping it,
I earned it,'' he said, joking) and _ best of all _ surprise visits
from stars such as Mark O'Meara, Christopher Reeve, Mark Messier
and Mario Lemieux.
</P>
<P>
   Coach John Muckler ``called a timeout with 30 seconds left and
told me I had to get the game-winner,'' said Gretzky, who used 40
sticks and wore three sweaters during the game. ``When I was
younger I might have gotten it.''
</P>
<P>
   Scalpers asked $1,000 for ice-level seats for the finale,
highlighted by the most famous 99 this side of Nena's 99 Luft
Balloons and Tony Dorsett's record run getting the most
recognizable uniform number in sports history retired. Everywhere.
Forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the ultimate honor,'' said Gretzky, who came out of the
postgame locker room for two tear-filled encores in which players
slammed sticks on the ice and fans covered the surface with hats
and bouquets of flowers to Tina Turner's Simply the Best.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing the NHL is headed toward longer, colder winters
without Gretzky's ballet- dancer magic in a mosh pit full of
billy-club toting rogues, everyone from Hall of Fame legend Gordie
Howe to Gretzky's wife, Janet, and even Canadian Prime Minister
Jean Chretien tried to talk him out of retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so talented he could get by on one skate,'' Howe said.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky can still sneak a puck through the five hole during rush
hour at Grand Central Station and still do for hockey what Elvis
did for rock 'n' roll, but the 38-year-old said he's retiring based
on an undeniable ``gut feeling.'' With the rebuilding Rangers
(33-38-11) years from another Stanley Cup run and his production
noticeably slipping (9 goals this season compared with 92 in
'81-82), Gretzky is allowing himself to feel downright human. Three
months after Jordan quit basketball and maybe months before John
Elway walks away from football, he is tossing the keys to younger,
faster stars such as Paul Kariya, Mike Modano, Eric Lindros and
Jaromir Jagr.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to go out like Michael, but it's not a perfect
world,'' he said. ``They talk about passing torches, and maybe
today it was fitting that Jaromir scored that goal.''
</P>
<P>
   But losing his finale hardly put a damper on the career of a
player who long ago became hockey's been-there, done-that poster
boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He single-handedly changed our sport,'' said Lemieux, who wore
No. 66 because it was Gretzky's 99 upside down. ``I mean, what else
is there for him to do? If anyone accomplishes half of what he did,
it'll be a great career.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers are unfathomable: 4 Stanley Cups, 10 scoring titles,
9 MVP awards, 61 records, 894 goals, 1,963 assists and 2,857 points
in 1,487 games.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Gretzky has more assists than any player has
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really hard to even comprehend,'' Detroit Red Wings coach
Scotty Bowman said. ``It's like he hit .400 with 70 homers every
year for 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   As impressive and unreachable as Gretzky's numbers are, they
only tell a face-off's portion of the story about a star who played
a different style of game and who _ like Jordan, Muhammad Ali and
Babe Ruth _ transcended his sport.
</P>
<P>
   Even with his Ichabod Crane physique (6-foot, 175 pounds),
average skating speed and ho-hum slap-shot velocity, Gretzky became
the game's most feared offensive player with supreme intuition.
More Larry Bird than Jordan, more Tony Gwynn than Mark McGwire and
more Barry Sanders than Jim Brown, Gretzky injected finesse and
grace into a macho sport ruled by blood and fists.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so much more intelligent,'' said his former Edmonton
Oilers coach, Glen Sather. ``While they were using all this energy
trying to rattle his teeth, he was just skating away, circling,
analyzing things.'' Cosell behind the microphone and Roger Staubach
simply behind, ]
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky was most comfortable and dangerous behind the net, which
was often called his ``office.'' He perched there and dangled the
puck as if by a string, his twinkling blue eyes seemingly seeing
the kaleidoscope of swirling patterns in slow motion.
</P>
<P>
   He often made passes off the boards, once pulled off a
give-and-go to himself off the side of the net, and scored the
winning goal in Game 7 of the '93 Western Conference Finals by
purposely flicking the puck off the skate of Toronto defenseman
Dave Ellett.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years after he's retired he'll still be the best passer
in the game,'' former goalie and Rangers broadcaster John Davidson
said. ``Nobody on this planet is even close.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky always had (super)natural talent, from the time he took
No. 99 in honor of his idol Howe (No. 9) and proceeded to earn the
``Great One'' moniker from a reporter who watched him score 378
points in 82 games as a 10-year-old for the Soo Greyhounds in
Brantford, Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   But it's off the ice where Gretzky has grown larger than legend,
promoting hockey more than even Jordan helped basketball. Like the
entrance of Bird and Magic Johnson for the NBA or Alan Ameche's
overtime touchdown plunge for the NFL, Gretzky's move to Los
Angeles is considered the NHL's launching pad.
</P>
<P>
   ``He carried hockey not only by playing it the best but by also
selling it the best,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said, noting that
the optimism Gretzky generated sprouted franchises in warm-weather
cities such as San Jose, Phoenix and Dallas. ``Think of all the
jobs he created and people's lives he's touched just by being Wayne
Gretzky.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Gretzky, shrugging: ``I'm not bigger than the game of
hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   There are countless sports fans, however _ those who can't
recite one rule but nod at the mention of Gretzky's name _ who
disagree. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
