<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE-AGENT SIGNEES, DRAFT MAKE FOR HAPPY COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Teams around the league are looking back today
and surveying what they accomplished in the 1999 NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Cowboys' retrospective, however, entails more than
just the two-day draft.
</P>
<P>
   The restocking of their franchise began in earnest earlier last
week with the signing of free-agent center Mark Stepnoski and
receiver Raghib Ismail and continued with the signing of linebacker
Quentin Coryatt on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   To the Cowboys, those additions were more important in getting
ready for the 1999 season than what they did in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   However, when adding the seven draft picks, led by top pick
Ebenezer Ekuban, a pass-rushing defensive end, the Cowboys believe
they've improved their team as much, if not more, than any team in
the league.
</P>
<P>
   And their satisfaction comes despite the uncertainty surrounding
All-Pro defensive tackle Leon Lett, who according to a source, has
violated the league's substance-abuse policy and faces an
indefinite ban from the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``No team in the NFL did what we did in the last week,'' Cowboys
coach Chan Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said there is no doubt in his mind
that the Cowboys are a better team than the one that ended the 1998
campaign with a playoff loss to the Arizona Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   And he said it's a result of the free-agent moves and the draft
combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about personnel,'' Jones said. ``You have to improve
through free agency. That's how you get to the Super Bowl. You
don't get to the Super Bowl with just good drafts. I am not
satisfied. But I am pretty pleased with how far we have come. We
will have better personnel going into training camp.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys believe they had a good draft, which they credit to
the free-agent moves. Jones said the additions of Stepnoski, Ismail
and Coryatt filled their most pressing needs for starters at
center, wide receiver and linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   It allowed them to stick with their philosophy of picking the
best athletes available in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   After taking West Virginia offensive tackle Solomon Page and
Texas A&AMP;M linebacker Dat Nguyen in the second and third rounds
Saturday, they made five more picks Sunday. Receiver Wane McGarity
of Texas and defensive end Peppi Zellner were taken in the fourth
round.
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Martay Jenkins of Nebraska-Omaha was picked in the
sixth round and tight end Mike Lucky of Arizona and guard Kelvin
Garmon of Baylor and Haltom High School were taken in the seventh
round.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey was also pleased that, while they stuck to their
best-athlete philosophy, they were able to fill needs at several
key positions _ linebacker, defensive end and wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys also wanted a defensive tackle, but refused to reach
for one who was not rated high when it was their turn to pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stuck to the board, but when it was even, we took the
position where we had a need,'' Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   While Garmon, who is still recovering from a broken leg, is
questionable for training camp, the Cowboys believe the rest of the
their picks have a chance to contribute next season. Ekuban will
play immediately. Nguyen and McGarity have the potential to make
immediate impacts, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason the Cowboys believe they are better is because
they will be faster, as speed was the recurring theme with their
moves in the draft and free agency.
</P>
<P>
   The first six picks are considered to be exceptionally fast for
their position, especially Zellner, who ran a 4.5, the fastest time
in the 40-yard dash of any defensive end at the NFL combine. And
Ismail's speed is without question.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey, however, said the main thing he likes is that they are
great football players, first.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to get faster every year,'' Gailey said. ``At
the same time, we want great football players. We want football
players that can run. We believe that's what we got.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
