<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORGAN'S STRONG START IS A BIG LIFT FOR RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Mike Morgan, ex-employee of 10 major-league
teams, is discovering a simple truth about life with the Texas
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Give it time, just a little bit of time, and the Rangers'
offense will usually deliver substantial run support. Perhaps not
every time. Perhaps not against Roger Clemens or David Wells, and
there might be a day when they get shut down by some journeyman
slop artist.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the time, Juan Gonzalez &AMP; Co. somehow find a way to
score runs. All they ask is for their pitcher to hold off the
opposition for a few innings. They're not asking for a no-hitter,
just a couple of measly innings so they have time to pummel the
typical hapless, faceless American League pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   When Morgan did that yesterday, the Rangers responded with some
early offense of their own and went on to defeat the Oakland
Athletics, 6-2, at Network Associates Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Morgan threw great,'' Gonzalez said. ``When a guy pitches like
that, it makes all of us more comfortable. When you're down five or
six runs early, it puts more pressure on everybody. This is what we
need.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan started off with three scoreless innings and gave up just
one run through six. By the time the Athletics scored in the fourth
on Jason Giambi's home run, the Rangers had already built up a 5-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates said three scoreless innings from a pitcher
to start a game, ``changes the whole attitude of the ballclub.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three shutout innings is the bottom line, but not even being
in trouble, facing only nine, 10 or 11 batters. It gives the whole
ballclub a lift. I don't think you can measure it.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the numbers are pretty clear when you break down the
Rangers 7-6 record.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are 7-0 when they score first, and an opponent has
yet to come from behind to beat them.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers opponents have scored in the first inning in six games
this year. The Rangers have lost all six.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have to go out and hit no matter what the pitcher
does,'' second baseman Mark McLemore said. ``The first couple of
games in here we didn't swing the bats well. I think everybody had
in mind today to get a good pitch to hit and be more aggressive,
and we did that for the most part.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan faltered in the seventh, giving up a leadoff double to
Matt Stairs and a run-scoring single to Ben Grieve. That made it
6-2, and Oates quickly got him out of there, turning the game over
to Jeff Zimmerman and John Wetteland
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the kind of pitcher that comes out going hard, one pitch
at a time and one hitter at a time,'' Morgan said. ``I'm usually
pretty good the first time through an order, and I'm usually good
for five or six innings. After that it's when I seem to labor.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers can handle that from a pitcher. It's getting behind
early that's been driving them crazy. But by pitching well early,
Morgan has won both his starts and is off to a 3-0 start (one
victory in relief) for the first time since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things I've seen since spring training is good movement on
all his pitches and throwing all his pitches for strikes when he
wants to,'' Oates said. ``He stays down, going up only when he
wants to, and he changes speeds. From what I've seen, he's doing
all the things he needs to do to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Most important on that list is not letting the other team get
the jump on the Rangers' offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitch well early, score early and play good defense,'' Oates
said. ``All that goes hand in hand. You do that consistently and
you're going to have a successful season.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
