<HEADER>
A3671 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERSNOTES-TEX     04-19 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALMEIRO SAYS HIS TIMING IS COMING BACK
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Rafael Palmeiro, showing signs of overcoming
his lost spring training, went 4-for-4 Sunday with a sacrifice fly
in his five plate appearances. He has six hits in his past eight
at-bats, including a home run on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm now just feeling that my timing is getting there,''
Palmeiro said.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro, who had two knee surgeries in two months and also has
a tight hamstring muscle, showed a little speed when he doubled in
the seventh, his second of the season. He had two line drives off
the right-field wall in the three-game series with the Seattle
Mariners and had to settle for singles both times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call it speed, but the knee feels better,''
Palmeiro said. ``But the hamstring is bothering me a little bit. I
just want to be normal. I want to feel good again so I can run hard
and not hurt my team.''
OQUIST, PHILLIPS EXIT EARLY
</P>
<P>
   Two Oakland starters made premature exits from Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Starting pitcher Mike Oquist was knocked out of the game in the
third inning when he took a line drive off the left wrist. Rusty
Greer hit the ball, a smash that went for an infield hit.
</P>
<P>
   Oquist was taken to a local hospital for X-rays, that showed no
fractures. He's expected to make his next start.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Tony Phillips was ejected in the sixth inning by
home plate umpire Dan Morrison for arguing balls and strikes.
Phillips had just struck out for the second time in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened was between me and the umpire and nobody else's
business,'' Phillips said. ``I'm good for three or four times a
year and that was No. 1. I wasn't doing the team any good, anyway,
two strikeouts and a ground out.''
ZEILE SPARKLES
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Todd Zeile bailed out starting pitcher Mike Morgan
with two nice defensive plays early.
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics had a runner at second with two out in the second
when Zeile backhanded Miguel Tejada's bouncer deep behind the bag
and made a strong throw to first to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile also came through in the third after Morgan started the
inning by walking Eric Chavez. A.J. Hinch followed with a sharp
grounder toward the left side hole and Zeile made a diving stop to
his left, taking away a hit and getting a force at second on
Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big play, getting to that ground ball,'' manager
Johnny Oates said. ``Anytime you make plays like that, the pitching
gets a little better.'' BRONX BROWNOUT
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers open up a two-game series with the New York Yankees
tomorrow night at Yankee Stadium, a place that has not been
friendly to the Rangers in the past. The Rangers are 51-102 in New
York since 1972, their worst record in any city in the American
League. A look at the Rangers record in each city: City W-L Pct.
Oakland 93-91 .505 Cleveland 77-76 .502 Seattle 72-72 .500
Minnesota 85-100 .459 Baltimore 65-84 .436 Detroit 69-90 .434
Anaheim 78-103 .431 Kansas City 76-106 .418 Boston 63-88 .417
Chicago 72-107 .407 Tampa Bay 2-3 .400 Toronto 49-78 .385 New York
51-102 .333
BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Designated hitter Mike Simms, on the disabled list with a
partially torn Achilles tendon, played in his first game with the
Triple-A Oklahoma Redhawks Sunday and had a two-run single and a
walk in four plate appearances. The Rangers are hoping Simms can be
activated when they return to The Ballpark in Arlington next
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Zeile broke an 0-for-11 streak with his fourth-inning home
run. nn
</P>
