<HEADLINE>
STARS DEFENSE STEPS UP TO THE FRONT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The Jennings Trophy was added to the Stars' trophy case
Sunday night, and the accomplishment was not without some
significance both for the past and the future.
</P>
<P>
   In holding down the potent Colorado Avalanche in a 2-1 loss at
McNichols Arena in the season finale, the Stars not only locked up
the honor of the fewest goals against (168) in the NHL during the
1998-99 season, they also made a statement about their defense and
the depth of their goaltending.
</P>
<P>
   With Derian Hatcher (suspended), Richard Matvichuk (groin) and
Shawn Chambers (healthy scratch) out of the lineup, the Stars
relied on a patchwork defense and received steady results. Darryl
Sydor played 28 minutes, 53 seconds and helped replace the physical
presence of Hatcher and Matvichuk. Sergei Zubov logged 30:25 of ice
time. Doug Lidster was good for 17:53 and Craig Ludwig played
16:44.
</P>
<P>
   Rookies Petr Buzek and Brad Lukowich were limited to 13 minutes
or less, but Chambers and Matvichuk should be ready for the playoff
opener on Wednesday, meaning the Stars still have strong defensive
depth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked what I saw; we're playing hard back there,'' Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``Obviously, you can't just replace
Hatcher and Matvichuk, but we've done a good job of playing through
adversity back there.''
</P>
<P>
   Manny Fernandez took the loss in net, but stopped 27 shots and
basically matched All-Star Patrick Roy save-for-save. That
performance is a gentle reminder the Stars have one more name to
consider in their goalie shuffle this summer. The team will be able
to protect either Ed Belfour or Roman Turek in the expansion draft,
and the Atlanta Thrashers will get dibs on either of those goalies,
if one isn't traded beforehand. But with Fernandez, 24, and Marty
Turco, 23, in the system, the Stars should still have a solid
goaltending pair next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manny is proving himself a good goalie,'' said Hitchcock, who
has worked with Fernandez for the past five seasons. ``He's matured
as an individual, he's lost some of the edginess that was a
problem. He's a good goalie.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez, who will be a restricted free agent this summer, said
he would like to stay in the Stars' system, but that he has to
start looking for any chance to move into the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to stay with the Stars, I think they'll be a good
team for years to come,'' he said. ``But at the same time, five
years is enough. I have to start watching out for myself.''
JENNINGS TALK
</P>
<P>
   The Jennings award is given to the NHL team that allows the
fewest goals in the regular season, and the Stars had made the
award a priority throughout the season. They missed the award by
one goal last season, finishing behind the New Jersey Devils.
</P>
<P>
   While the award will bear the name of Belfour (for the fourth
time in his career) and Turek, it's actually something that is
earned by the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot of work and a lot of sacrifice and not a whole
lot of nights off,'' Hitchcock said. ``It's about consistent team
defense and that's something we've tried to build around.'' OLD
FRIENDS
</P>
<P>
   Stars winger Brett Hull wore No. 99 on the back of his helmet as
a tribute to his friend Wayne Gretzky, who was playing the final
game of his Hall-of-Fame career in New York.
</P>
<P>
   While Hull said he enjoyed fond memories with Gretzky, he added
that ``the most bitter moment'' of his career came in 1996 when the
St. Louis Blues acquired Gretzky in a trade with the Los Angeles
Kings and then decided not to sign him as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was ridiculous, embarrassing,'' Hull said. ``You don't
treat the greatest player in the game that way. I'll never forget
that.'' NOTABLES
</P>
<P>
   _ The Stars posted the most victories in franchise history (51)
_ tied for the 19th most in NHL history.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Stars posted the most points (114) in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hull led the NHL in game-winning goals with 11 and tied a
franchise record.
</P>
<P>
   _ Grant Marshall was the only Stars player to play in all 82
games.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Stars had the best home record (29-8-4) in the NHL and the
second-best road record (22-11-8).
</P>
<P>
   _ Avalanche goalie Patrick Roy posted a career best
goals-against average of 2.29.
</P>
<P>
   _ Avalanche winger Milan Hejduk finished as the NHL rookie
scoring leader with 48 points. HATCHER FALLOUT
</P>
<P>
   People in Phoenix are upset by the ``lightness'' of Derian
Hatcher's seven-game suspension. Hatcher was fined $90,731 or two
games worth of $3.7 million salary. That's because NHL players are
officially paid only during the regular season, and the remainder
of Hatcher's five suspended games come in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   However, Phoenix television analyst Jim Johnson, a former
Hatcher teammate on the Stars, said Hatcher should pay the $317,558
fine he would have received had all seven games been during the
regular season. THREE STARS
</P>
<P>
   1. Patrick Roy, Avalanche: Had 30 saves against some great
scoring opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   2. Theo Fleury, Avalanche: Gets game-winner with 12.7 seconds
remaining and assists on first goal.
</P>
<P>
   3. Manny Fernandez, Stars: He deserved a better fate. In his
last two NHL games, he's stopped 59 of 62 shots. X-FACTOR:
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' crippled defense was facing an Avalanche team that
was at full strength and featured three of the top seven scorers in
the NHL. The Stars are proving they have the depth to survive in
the playoffs.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
