<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS FOLLOW WELL-MADE PLAN, FILL MOST NEEDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ Add another handle to Mike Holmgren's
ever-expanding list of job titles _ the man with the plan.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks executive vice president of football
operations/general manager and head coach waded into the first NFL
draft in which he had total control with an aggressive agenda
Saturday morning and emerged Sunday afternoon with a smile and
seven almost handpicked players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question, Mike was in control,'' defensive coordinator
Fritz Shurmur said. ``He had a plan. He exhibited his ability to be
able to take his resources and use them and come up with the best
conclusions for the organization.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, Holmgren had turned five draft picks into
seven players and filled all but one of the team's needs entering
the two-day event.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun. It was exciting,'' said Holmgren, who was hired in
January to control the Seahawks' football operation after seven
seasons as coach of the Green Bay Packers. ``If you look at the
players we did get in the draft, you see that we addressed some
needs as well as got some real fine players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming out it,'' he added, ``I am very, very pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   The two-day efforts of Holmgren and his draft team might not
yield an opening-day starter but did stock an already solid roster
with more depth, talent and versatility _ defensive end Lamar King,
quarterback Brock Huard and wide receiver Karsten Bailey in
Saturday's first three rounds; defensive end Antonio Cochran,
tackle Floyd Wedderburn, kick returner Charlie Rogers and
cornerback Steve Johnson in Sunday's final four rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren added three picks by trading down twice in the first
round and still got the player he would have selected at No. 17 _
King, a 297-pounder who could challenge for a starting job and at
the very least be used in a rotation at defensive end or/and
tackle.
</P>
<P>
   The extra picks the Seahawks got from the New England Patriots
and Dallas Cowboys for moving down five spots in the first round
where used to grab Bailey in the third round and to trade up in the
sixth round to select Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren was not alone in the ``war room'' and shared credit for
all this wheeling, dealing and stealing with vice president of
football operations Randy Mueller, director of player personnel
John Dorsey, his assistant coaches and the team's scouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about the whole process and how we came out of the
draft,'' Holmgren said. ``It was a real team effort.''
</P>
<P>
   But the point man was Holmgren, who cut his drafting teeth under
Bill Walsh as an assistant coach with the San Francisco 49ers and
honed those skills while working with Packers general manager Ron
Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there were any doubts Holmgren could pull off a
successful draft in his first attempt, Shurmer offered, ``Of course
not. No. One of the things that everybody recognizes is that he has
had a great command of offensive football and what it takes to
coach the football team. But there was never any doubt in our minds
about his ability to judge and select talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren showed he also is a team player by going for a
defensive player in the first round when there were tempting
alternatives on the offensive side.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an indication of the fact that he is the head coach of
the whole football team and has an interest in all of it,'' said
Shurmur, unable to hold back a smile.
</P>
<P>
   An indication that Holmgren also is a bit of perfectionist came
in the amount of time he spent dwelling on the one player that got
away _ a pass-catching tight end. He had hoped to draft either
North Alabama's Bobby Collins, who went to Buffalo in the fourth
round, or Michigan's Jerame Truman, who was taken by Pittsburgh in
the fifth round.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like body punches when they were taken,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren didn't recoil, however, he struck back, using a
fifth-round pick to fill a need by taking the best punt returner in
the draft, Rogers, and giving up two picks in the sixth round to
make sure he got the cornerback he wanted, Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   No tight ends, but players who should help that Seahawks end the
league's longest playoff drought at 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than that,'' Holmgren said of not getting a tight end,
``it kind of fell together.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as planned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
