<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAKINGLAWS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA LAWMAKERS MAY LAUGH TO KEEP FROM CRYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE AMPARANO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ (SECOND OF THREE PARTS) The jokes have been making the
rounds all morning in the Arizona House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   They involve Rep. Kathleen Dunbar, R-Tucson, who moderate
legislators believe agreed to cave in to conservative leaders on a
crucial vote on the state budget. Dunbar, an animal rights
activist, has been pushing her own legislation against animal
cruelty and domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Susan Gerard, leader of the moderate ``Mushroom
Coalition,'' repeats one of the jokes to a group of fellow
legislators: ``Did you hear that leadership is threatening Dunbar?
They say they've gone to the animal shelters and they'll be killing
one animal every hour until she gives in.''
</P>
<P>
   The group chuckles and another adds: ``I heard the Mushrooms
have kidnapped her dog. They told her she'll never see her dog
alive again if she caves in.''
</P>
<P>
   More laughter. For a moment, the jokes seem to reflect the
legislators' own brand of cruelty toward a freshman who dared
abandon the moderate coalition. But Gerard explains the jokes are a
cover. The stress is so great that lawmakers are alleviating their
anxiety with humor. The situation, she confesses, really isn't
funny at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Arizona Republic'' followed Gerard from April 5-9 during a
crucial week in this year's legislative session, filled with the
tension of an impending budget deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tuesday _ deals and rumors in the hallways''.``''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the morning, rumors are making the rounds. A Mushroom
is already questioning the loyalty of Rep. Tom Horne, R-Paradise
Valley, and is reporting back to Gerard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Horne says he's solid. He says he's still on,'' she tells some
fellow lawmakers. ``But he says he's heard some other people were
going to double-cross him.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Everyone thinks he knows who is on the verge of changing
positions in the battle over the budget. But in the end, Gerard
says, it may be impossible to know who is jumping sides. By the
time members vote on the issue, she says the budget is bound to be
radically different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless they confess,'' Gerard says, ``we can never know for
sure. And who's going to do that?''
</P>
<P>
   Gerard sighs heavily. The chime summoning legislators back to
work has sounded again.
</P>
<P>
   A House page dashes down the hallway, rounding up stragglers.
Dressed in the blue jacket and slacks that distinguish these House
gofers, a lanky, blond page politely knocks on doors and tells the
lawmakers it's time to go.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the morning, they duck in and out of a private lobby
that connects to the floor. There's news that leadership is
softening on funds for education. Gerard roams the floor and pays a
few visits to the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, she settles in at her desk. But this day's session
already is about to end.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a really short session,'' she says as she steps into
the hallway. ``Leadership must be anxious to work more people over
today.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no time to worry about it, though. Fourth-graders from
Lookout Mountain are visiting the House today and Gerard must
address them.
</P>
<P>
   While waiting for them in the House Gallery, Rep. Roberta Voss,
R-Glendale, storms in, plops herself down on a step and reveals:
``They've called me into their office. What's our story?''
</P>
<P>
   Gerard responds: ``I don't know, but I'm sticking with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, everyone seems to be restless and on edge.
</P>
<P>
   But the children visiting the Legislature don't notice a
thing. &UR; They giggle and whisper as they climb the stairs, enter the
gallery &UR; and peer onto the vacant floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess nothing is going on today,'' a parent tells her
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Just then Minority House Leader John Loredo whips past.
Some &UR; freshman Democrats are in crisis and he's trying to hold
them &UR; together.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're hearing rumors about the budget and I'm trying to
keep &UR; them from joining the leadership,'' Loredo explains. ``If I
can do that, &UR; it gives the Mushrooms more bargaining power. The
moderate Republicans, more or less, want the same thing we do.''
</P>
<P>
   After addressing the schoolchildren, Gerard is eager to get the
scoop. &UR; She persuades fellow Mushrooms Reps. Carolyn Allen and
Lou-Ann Preble to get away for lunch today. At Tom's Tavern, a
favorite hangout for lawmakers, they share the latest intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   All have heard various reports that leadership could be
softening on money for schools. Grilled by House leaders earlier,
Horne confirms the news when they arrive back in the Legislature
for their Republican caucus meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Ushering Gerard into a first-floor hallway, Horne produces a
legal pad and shows her the numbers. Leadership, he says excitedly,
is offering some money for schools but nothing for cities or
community colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to know if this will pass. What do you think?''
Horne asks.
</P>
<P>
   Gerard is pleased with the funds for education. But she's still
concerned about financing for the cities and community colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Oblivious to the development, Republican lawmakers sit in
caucus &UR; and listen to the bills on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   In caucus, legislative analysts read bills and discuss what each
would do. Sitting around a conference table, the lawmakers
ask &UR; questions. Chairs line the walls, and advocates from various
industries &UR; fill them.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with cell phones, pagers and notebooks, the lobbyists
keep &UR; elaborate records on the bills and amendments. At times, some
rush out of &UR; the room to call their employers with the news. When
the caucus is finished, the lawmakers wait again for the session to
adjourn. But there's news that a vote could take place on
the &UR; budget.
</P>
<P>
   About 10:22 that night, the chime sounds and the weary
lawmakers &UR; trudge back onto the floor. If leadership &UR; decides to hear
the budget tonight, &UR; the session could last until dawn.
</P>
<P>
   Gerard crosses her fingers. Sighs of relief go out when the
session is adjourned a minute later. Tired but heartened, coalition
members have won the battle today. Each day they hold off
leadership gives them hope that leadership could make concessions. &QL; 
Tuesday: The chamber and the midnight hour. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
