<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-DRAFT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS GET HIGH MARKS FOR DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Warts and all, the Cardinals' seven second-day
draft picks offer intrigue, not because they are established stars
but because the team's brass believes they can overachieve and
become productive pros.
</P>
<P>
   That's not just the company line. National draft analysts concur
that the Cardinals followed one of their best drafts ever in 1998
with another. Everyone from Mel Kiper, Jr. to Marty Schottenheimer
was quick to offer praise for the manner in which the team got
high-quality players on Saturday and addressed needs in lower
rounds on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   For that to be borne out, though, the Cardinals need some of
those players selected in rounds four through seven on Sunday, who
do not have what Coach Vince Tobin calls ``the measurables you'd
like,'' to make it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a lot of role players,'' said Bob Ferguson, Cardinals
vice president of player personnel. ``We got guys who love to play
the game, character guys, who will be part of the 45-man roster on
Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the intriguing players is sixth-round pick Jacoby
Rhinehart, a cornerback from Southern Methodist who will challenge
1997 third-round pick Ty Howard for a roster spot. Rhinehart was
the Mustangs' most versatile player. He also returned punts, caught
passes and ran reverses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt strongly about his athletic ability,'' Ferguson said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though at 5 feet 10 he is an inch taller than Howard,
Rhinehart still is not as big or as fast as the defensive backs
drafted Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kept showing up on him was that he can really turn his
hips and that he has great catch-up speed,'' Tobin said. ``He
intrigues us as a corner.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, after drafting help at wide receiver, offensive
left tackle, and linebacker in the opening three rounds Saturday,
on Sunday added fullback Joel Makovicka of Nebraska in the fourth.
They've tried for three years to land a big back who can play.
Makovicka, at 234 pounds, can move a pile. But at 5 feet 10 he is
about three inches short and a step behind the big-time prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think he can be a special player for us,'' Tobin said. ``He
can block. He has excellent hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Makovicka acknowledged that concerns over his receiving ability
knocked him down in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people thought I would go on the first day, and when
I didn't, it was kind of frustrating,'' Makovicka said. ``I have a
lot of confidence in my abilities and I come from a program where I
take pride in my blocking. I think the biggest thing I had to show
the scouts was that I could catch. I feel I can come in and do
whatever it takes, whether it's special teams, carrying the
football, or catching it.''
</P>
<P>
   He will be challenged by sixth-round pick Dennis McKinley (6-1,
241), of Mississippi State. McKinley is the perfect size for a pro
fullback, but has limited skills. He is primarily a blocker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a fullback who can move a linebacker out of a hole,''
Tobin said. ``We've been looking for a back like that for some
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Sunday, the Cardinals added depth at safety in the fifth
round with Paris Johnson of Miami (Ohio), who at 6-2, 208 would
have projected higher absent the knee injury that limited him to
five games last season; offensive guard Yusuf Scott of Arizona,
another fifth-round pick, who has battled weight problems but says
he now is down to 320; sixth-round pick Melvin Bradley, who at 6-1,
269 will be moved to middle linebacker because he is too small to
play defensive end in the NFL as he did at Arkansas; and
seventh-round pick Chris Greisen, a contender for the No. 3
quarterback spot after rebounding from a major knee injury in high
school to lead Northwest Missouri State to a 15-0 mark and the NCAA
Division II title.
</P>
<P>
   With this draft, the Cardinals believe they have created
competition along the offensive line, added run-stopping ability to
the defense, and addressed most specific position needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You certainly like to have people think you did the right
thing,'' Tobin said of the national accolades that began pouring in
from national draft analysts. ``We felt like we got some people who
will help the football team.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get to the middle and lower rounds you take players
you think can be really good football players. Whether they've got
all the measurables you'd like is probably doubtful. But we think
they can be productive players.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson said the Cardinals' selections were the product of ``a
lot of changes'' in the way the club approached the draft. He said
the Cardinals make do with an undersized scouting department,
getting away with it because Rod Graves, the new assistant to the
president, has reorganized and computerized the operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been big,'' Ferguson said. ``We got more thorough
reports on players. Also, we now know more about what Vince likes
as a coach. He's not afraid to sacrifice talent for character.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals had evaluations on more than 700 players. They got
11 of the 253 drafted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
