<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS' OFFENSE HAS BEEN A BIG HIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Pitching, pitching and more pitching.
</P>
<P>
   That was supposed to be the cure-all for expansionitis, the
boost the Diamondbacks needed to become a competitive club in 1999
and perhaps even challenge for a wild-card playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   While the remodeled pitching staff has shown flashes of
potential in the early going, it has been the hitters carrying the
load.
</P>
<P>
   They did so again on Sunday in a 12-3 victory over the San
Francisco Giants at Bank One Ballpark, ripping two more home runs
and adding four doubles to score in double figures for the second
time in three games and third in 13.
</P>
<P>
   After four losses to start the season, Arizona has won six of
nine, including five of seven at home. They have home series
victories over two National League West Division opponents, the
Giants and Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no one guy doing it. We all complement each other
well. We all feel that we can help,'' said second baseman Jay Bell,
who produced an RBI double in a seven-run seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Gilkey hit a three-run, pinch-hit homer in that inning
and left fielder Luis Gonzalez added a two-run shot to give Arizona
a major league-leading 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``Success breeds confidence and we enjoy pulling for each
other,'' Bell said. ``That makes it easier to go out and compete.
We like what we've got here. We've played three good teams the last
two weeks (Giants, Dodgers and Atlanta Braves), and hopefully, we
can play like we have been.''
</P>
<P>
   When Giants shortstop Rich Aurilia ripped a three-run homer off
right-hander Armando Reynoso in the second inning, his third of the
series, it appeared the outcome would be a similar to Saturday,
when the Giants scored early and often on the way to an 8-5
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Bell took Reynoso aside and told him, ``You've had a bad inning.
So what? Just make your pitches and we'll score you some runs.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't long before the Diamondbacks backed up Bell's words.
</P>
<P>
   They scored four times in the third off right-hander Russ Ortiz,
on a bases-loaded walk to Travis Lee and a bases-loaded double off
the right-field fence by ex-Giant Matt Williams. It missed being a
grand slam by a couple of feet.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is off to one of the best starts of his career. He is
hitting .322 with three homers, 10 RBIs and five doubles. He has
gone to the opposite field, to right, on many of his hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take what I'm given,'' he said. ``There's not a whole lot of
pitches I've seen that have been driveable. There's no sense trying
to pull an outside pitch. I've tried it and it doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't think he hit the double that well, but it got the job
done.
</P>
<P>
   Damian Miller, catching his ninth straight game due to an injury
to Kelly Stinnett, got the job done with two outs in the sixth
inning. After fouling off several pitches from Ortiz on a 3-2
count, he lined a single just over the head of third baseman
Charlie Hayes and into left field to score Gonzalez with an
insurance run to make it 5-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``That may have been the biggest at-bat of the game,''
Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks scored seven times in the seventh to break the
game open against relievers Rich Rodriguez, Julian Tavarez and
Felix Rodriguez, a former Diamondback.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Finley started it with a single and Bell drove him in with
a double down the left-field line. Lee hit an opposite-field single
and Williams scored Bell with a high chopper to third. Gonzalez hit
his fifth home run of the season for two more runs and tied Bell
for the club lead with five homers.
</P>
<P>
   Tavarez walked Tony Batista and gave up a double to David
Dellucci. Felix Rodriguez came on to retire Miller on a pop-up and
then gave Gilkey a fastball right down the middle that Gilkey hit
into the left-field stands for his fourth homer of the season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
