<HEADLINE>
TALE OF 2 SUNS: GLORY, HEART ACHE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - One sat at one end of the court.
</P>
<P>
   The other sat at the other end until halftime when he rose from
his chair, smoothed his necktie and walked nervously to center
court.
</P>
<P>
   For two men, this was a special day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have many emotions and thoughts,'' one said. But he wasn't
about to share them. Paul Westphal's deepest feelings remain a
secret: ``I've never spilled my guts.''
</P>
<P>
   The other had so much he wanted to say that he didn't know where
to start. Tom Chambers gazed at the smiling faces around him. When
he began speaking from the heart, he had to pause several times and
take deep breaths to gather himself. When he felt the tears
quicken, he quickly made a joke.
</P>
<P>
   They are more than acquaintances. Westphal and Chambers are
long-time friends. They played against each other. They employed
the same agent. In 1988, when the Suns were looking over a list of
free agents, Westphal _ then a Suns assistant coach _ said, ``What
about Tom Chambers?''
</P>
<P>
   Chambers and Kevin Johnson resurrected the Phoenix Suns.
Westphal coached them both in 1993 when the team reached the NBA
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, they sat on either side of the scorer's table, worlds
apart. This was the first time Westphal had been in America West
Arena for a Suns game since the club fired him three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He downplayed the significance of his return. He said his
emotions were irrelevant because they ``had nothing to do with the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   But anyone who knows Westphal's competitive nature knows how
badly he wanted to win.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Colangelo was in the house. So was Cotton Fitzsimmons. So
were Kevin Johnson and Danny Ainge. Paul coached Ainge, too.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety minutes before tipoff, public-address announcer Jeff Munn
went to the visitors' locker room. He informed the Sonics coach
that Ainge would not identify his starting lineup until game time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that how it is?'' Westphal said. A smile touched his lips.
``Then tell him I'm not announcing mine either.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal respects Ainge as a coach. He loved him as a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always had a smile on his face,'' Paul said. ``He always
had ideas. And he wasn't afraid to take the big shot, that's for
sure.''
</P>
<P>
   The room Westphal occupied was small and spartan compared with
his old office down the hall. Ainge's office has a desk. A clock. A
TV. It had to feel strange returning to this building and all the
memories it holds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Different,'' Westphal said, foreclosing questions about his
feelings, and the past.
</P>
<P>
   But Westphal is part of the arena and the Suns. He always will
be. The former Sun is a member of the team's new ``Ring of Honor.''
Other honorees are Alvan Adams, Walter Davis, Connie Hawkins and
Dick Van Arsdale. Chambers joined that select company of former
Suns during a halftime ceremony. Their youthful faces now appear on
the facing of the upper deck.
</P>
<P>
   Like Westphal, Chambers didn't leave here the way he wanted.
Chambers no longer was the star of the team in his last season in
Phoenix. Charles Barkley was. After the '93 Finals, Chambers didn't
attend the downtown parade honoring the Western Conference
champions.
</P>
<P>
   But six years later, he stood at center court, a different man,
a happier man, a changed man.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means more to Tom than the night he scored 60 points
against the Sonics,'' Fitzsimmons said.
</P>
<P>
   How much did this day mean?
</P>
<P>
   Westphal played Gary Payton 48 minutes. That's how badly he
wanted to win. Chambers turned his shining eyes to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm truly blessed . . . life is beautiful . . . thanks so very
much.''
</P>
<P>
   His smile spoke of the priceless joy of hearing it again, the
cheers, one more time.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns won Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``No fouls, Dale,'' the Sonics coach called out to Dale Ellis as
the seconds ticked off the clock. ``Let it end.''
</P>
<P>
   When it did, Westphal walked the length of the court and
congratulated Chambers. ``This is his day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics packed. Westphal got on the bus.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers walked to a white pickup truck. The one with Utah
plates that read, ``HAZ BEN.'' &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at (602) 444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
