<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-SONICS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS MAKE MOST OF 2ND CHANCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It was a momentous day at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   They placed former Suns star Tom Chambers in the Ring of Honor.
</P>
<P>
   Former Suns Coach Paul Westphal made his first return to the
building as coach of the Seattle Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   And the Suns won their third game in a row, beating the Sonics,
99-93, behind a 27-point, 12-rebound performance from forward Tom
Gugliotta, the guy who wears Chambers' No. 24 now.
</P>
<P>
   OK, in most seasons, three-game winning streaks are routine. But
nothing has been routine about this season or the Suns. Now,
however, that's just what the club is getting into. The result is a
7-3 record in April.
</P>
<P>
   The victory gave the Suns a 1{-game lead over the Sonics and
pulled them closer to the Minnesota Timberwolves in the Western
Conference playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think guys are finally settling into their roles,'' said
forward Clifford Robinson, who scored 23 points, grabbed seven
rebounds and made a handful of crucial shots. ``I know it took
awhile, but guys are feeling comfortable now doing what they're
supposed to be doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a matter of us all accepting those roles, whether
it's coming off the bench, defending, scoring. Right now is the
time to make a move, and that's a big part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics are moving just as quickly in the opposite direction
and are not adjusting to their roles.
</P>
<P>
   After learning just before tip-off that Don MacLean would start,
Seattle center Olden Polynice was unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal might have had some second thoughts after MacLean
dropped off Gugliotta with 1:10 to play, giving the Phoenix forward
a wide-open shot from 18 feet that Gugliotta hit for a 94-89 Suns
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm supposed to hit those, and I finally did,'' Gugliotta
said.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal said he went with MacLean because he's trying to win
games, not worry about the feelings of individual players at this
point in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's the way he feels about it, fine,'' Polynice said.
``But show some respect, don't tell me about it a minute before I
go on the court. I've been in this league 14 years. I deserve
respect.''
</P>
<P>
   It might be noted that it's what Polynice has done in those 14
years that dictates the level of respect he deserves. But none of
that matters to the Suns, who would love nothing more than to watch
the Sonics slip. Phoenix swept the season series, 3-0, against
their old nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   The difference was rebounding, particularly in the second half.
The Suns had 15 offensive rebounds and 17 second-chance points in
the second half. Danny Manning had six offensive rebounds.
Gugliotta, Robinson and center Joe Kleine each had four.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny Manning's tip-ins were really big,'' Suns Coach Danny
Ainge said. ``He had six offensive rebounds, and those were huge
because we couldn't make any shots from the outside. Those
second-chance points we got were big.''
</P>
<P>
   Guard Jason Kidd, who is having the best shooting season of his
career, made only 4 of 16 shots. Rex Chapman hit 4 of 10, although
he was 2 of 3 from three-point range and hit a big one with 3:26 to
go that gave the Suns a four-point cushion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't throw it in the ocean,'' Kidd said. ``That's just
how it is sometimes. You have to just keep taking those shots. I
got good looks. Some were short, some were long.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kidd said the club's front line bailed out the guards with
the offensive rebounds, and he cited Manning's one-hand,
rebound-and-shoot basket as the third-quarter buzzer sounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a huge tip-in because they had some momentum going,''
Kidd said. ``I thought that shot took a lot of the wind out of
their sails.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics had trimmed a seven-point deficit to a point before
Manning's tip-in.
</P>
<P>
   With a three-game streak, a game coming up Tuesday night in
Dallas and two games down the road with Minnesota, Kidd said the
Suns might as well shoot for more than just the Timberwolves. With
the Los Angeles Lakers seemingly self-destructing, why not go for
No. 5?
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can win seven or eight in a row, we might finish higher
(than sixth),'' Kidd said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think six is reachable,'' Robinson said. ``As for
fifth, I don't know. We would have to put together a helluva
finish.''
</P>
</TEXT>
