<HEADLINE>
AYALA STARTS LIFE OUTSIDE CELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seventeen years ago, he was a future star. This week, he'll be
an ex-con.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tony Ayala, perhaps the most promising fighter of the early
1980s, will be released Tuesday from Bayside State Prison in
Leesburg, N.J., after serving 16 years of a 35-year sentence for
rape.
</P>
<P>
   Now 36, Ayala hopes to recover all the promise he had when he
was 20. Then, he was an unbeaten junior middleweight (22-0, 19 KOs)
whose ferocity fascinated fans and frightened foes. But his
greatest weapon inside the ropes could not be controlled outside of
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 19, I was a junkie and a drunk, I was out of
control,'' Ayala told the Associated Press. ``Did I deserve to go
to prison? Damn right. Did I deserve to go to prison for 16 years?
That's another matter. The last 10 years were a waste of time and
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala, a San Antonio native, was convicted on a charge of raping
a neighbor in Paterson, N.J. At the time, he was on probation for
beating a woman in the restroom of a San Antonio drive-in theater
and for breaking into a San Antonio home.
</P>
<P>
   He spent the past 16 years thinking about all he lost. And,
through it all, fans have not forgotten him. There's a lingering
fascination with Ayala, who was nicknamed El Torito. It's happened
to other fighters. Unfulfilled talent and long-term trouble always
manages to create a peculiar, almost mythological aura in this
crazy, conflicted business.
</P>
<P>
   Promoters have noticed.  &UR; Don Elbaum is selling Ayala's return to
the ring. Ayala's adviser is  &UR; Brian Raditz, a psychologist who
treated him during his first 4{ years in prison. His father,  &UR; Tony
Sr., will train his son.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen years of prison food and not a single round of sparring
can't have helped. Elbaum says he wants to see whether any of
Ayala's skills are left in a bout against a nobody this summer in
San Antonio. Then, he would hope to put Ayala in against a faded
 &UR; Hector Camacho or an ever-aging  &UR; Roberto Duran.
</P>
<P>
   The dream is  &UR; Oscar De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   In a jailhouse interview, Ayala told ``Sport'' magazine that he
spent time in his cell daydreaming about standing over a fallen,
bloodied De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   Could it happen? Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Ayala has a tougher opponent in himself, anyway. He has
to learn how to live outside of those prison walls.
</P>
<P>
   Mayday, maybe &QL; 
If schedules, faxes and negotiations are any indication,  &UR; Michael
 &UR; Carbajal will be very busy next month.
</P>
<P>
   America Presents has him fighting his second comeback bout on
May 8 on a Telemundo-televised card from Miami. A contract has him
on a Telemundo card on May 15, also in Miami. A third possibility
is a bout on May 5 at Tucson. He figures to fight on one of those
three dates.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, the possibilities indicate that there's still some
interest in the Phoenix fighter, who has not signed a long-term
deal with any of the major promoters. &QL; 
Briefly . . .  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carbajal stablemate  &UR; Ahmed Santos (25-2-4, 13 KOs) won a vacant
North American Boxing Federation title Friday with a unanimous
decision over Detroit super-lightweight  &UR; Patrick Thorns (20-3-1, 15
KOs) at Shreveport, La. The victory promises to put Santos among
the World Boxing Council's top 10.
</P>
<P>
   He's back:  &UR; Fidel Hernandez (15-2, 12 KOs), a promising junior
middleweight from Carbajal's gym, returned to the ring for the
first time in about a year with a second-round knockout Friday
night of  &UR; Ricky
 &UR; Walters (5-5), also at Shreveport.
</P>
<P>
   And  &UR; George Foreman summed it up when he described  &UR; Dennis
 &UR; Rodman-wannabe  &UR; Naseem Hamed 10 days ago in a victory over  &UR; Paul
Ingle by saying: ``I like what he did right there. He did something
stupid, and that's what he does best.'' &QL; 
Information from other media sources included. Norm Frauenheim can
be reached at norm.frauenheim(at)pni.com via e-mail or at (602)
444-8259. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
