<SLUG> BC-CAR-CART-LONG-BEACH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LONG DAY AT LONG BEACH  
 MONTOYA'S LEAD KILLED SUSPENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Juan Montoya was too good, which is too
bad.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad because Montoya's dominance Sunday made the Toyota Grand
Prix of Long Beach too long and too boring.
</P>
<P>
   In one snoozer of a 25th anniversary race, Montoya led the final
40 laps and became the quickest Championship Auto Racing Teams
rookie to win since Nigel Mansell won his debut in the 1993 season
opener.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was a grand moment for Montoya and the Target/Chip
Ganassi Racing team, it almost was too unbearable to watch.
</P>
<P>
   In the final 37 laps in an 85-lap race held over a twisting
11-turn, 1.824-mile temporary street circuit, there were no _
repeat, no _ position changes among the top five finishing drivers,
and only four involving the sixth through 10th finishers.
</P>
<P>
   Yuck.
</P>
<P>
   But for Montoya and Ganassi, it might as well have been
Christmas, and they might as well have been kids again the way they
were high-fiving each other during a jubilant post-race victory
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been in something so big,'' said Montoya, who led
by as many as 11.175 seconds before settling for a non-threatening
2.805-second victory over Dario Franchitti. ``It feels real good.''
</P>
<P>
   Good for Ganassi, too, and no wonder.
</P>
<P>
   It was Ganassi's fourth straight win at Long Beach, including
Jimmy Vasser's win in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Zanardi won the past two here, but when he chose to leave
this season for Formula One, it left Ganassi with a huge void to
fill.
</P>
<P>
   Ganassi chose to fill it with Montoya, last year's European
Formula 3000 champion.
</P>
<P>
   Smart move.
</P>
<P>
   Following respectable finishes of 10th and 13th in the season's
first two oval races, Montoya delivered a five-star performance on
the circuit's first road-course test.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he (Montoya) had the talent for the kind of drive he
had today,'' a beaming Ganassi said afterwards. ``What I didn't
know is would he have the mental toughness to put (last week)
behind him. You don't usually see that in a young guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week in Japan, Montoya was fined $5,000 and put on
probation for a crash he caused involving Michael Andretti.
</P>
<P>
   For Montoya, the incident might as well have happened 10 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just decided to go out and race,'' Montoya said.
</P>
<P>
   And race he did.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Prix's first 45 laps, however, belonged to Bryan Herta
and pole-sitter Tony Kanaan.
</P>
<P>
   Herta, who started third and finished third, passed both Kanaan
and Franchitti on Lap 1 to take the lead in front of a crowd of
more than 90,000.
</P>
<P>
   But Kanaan immediately struck back, taking the lead just past
the start of Lap 2. And Kanaan remained on the point until disaster
struck on Lap 46.
</P>
<P>
   Kanaan slid off-course and slammed nose first into a protective
tire barrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mistake,'' Kanaan said. ``The track was breaking up,
and I just drove off-line a little bit and lost it. Sometimes you
learn the hard way.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart goes out to (Kanaan),'' Ganassi said. ``He was doing
a heck of a job, and I don't know if we had enough for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Montoya, too, was uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a great car,'' Montoya said. ``We were at a pretty even
pace, and it would have been hard to overtake him.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchitti tried to overtake Montoya, but it was fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   Even after rookie Christiano da Matta produced the last of five
caution flags on Lap 77 by smashing into the same tire barrier that
engulfed Kanaan, Franchitti still had nothing to throw at Montoya
when the race resumed on Lap 82.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing but false hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave it everything I had,'' Franchitti said. ``I just didn't
have the car to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there were concerns a reconfiguration of the course
layout might prove disastrous for over-zealous drivers attempting
to make side-by-side moves in the narrower portions of the layout,
most everyone behaved beautifully, and there were no serious
accidents.
</P>
</TEXT>
