<HEADLINE>
STERN TEST NEXT FOR TRACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ If &UR; Paul Tracy thought Sunday was a rough
day, wait until a few days from now.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy and wife &UR; Liisa are scheduled to appear on shock-jock
 &UR; Howard Stern's radio show later this week.
</P>
<P>
   As for Sunday, Tracy was forced out of the Toyota Grand Prix of
Long Beach on Lap 48 after he and  &UR; Michael Andretti made contact on
pit road.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I was leaving the pit lane, someone pulled out in front of
me, and I got hit,'' Tracy said. ``It broke the rear suspension.
It's a shame. We were quicker than everyone down the straightaways,
but it's so hard to pass here, and I just couldn't get by
anyone.'' &QL; 
Numbers game &QL; 
Rookie  &UR; Juan Montoya won in only his third career start.
</P>
<P>
   It took  &UR; Alex Zanardi nine races before he won, and  &UR; Jacques
Villeneuve 14. &UR; 
 &UR; Andre Ribeiro won in his 15th start, and  &UR; Gil de Ferran made it
into the victory lane in start No. 17. &QL; 
Short day &QL; 
Pole-sitter  &UR; Chris Neville of Scottsdale never made it past Lap 1
in the BFGoodrich Trans-Am race.
</P>
<P>
   Neville spun in the treacherous first corner and wasn't able to
continue, finishing 24th in a 25-car field.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Paul Gentilozzi won by 2.707 seconds over  &UR; John Miller. &QL; 
Aloha &QL; 
Here's the latest on the inaugural Hawaiian Super Prix, a $10
million Championship Auto Racing Teams non-points race scheduled
Nov. 13 on the island of Oahu at Barbers Point Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-hour event consists of two 60-minute heats. Sixteen
drivers will earn points each lap depending on where they are in
the running order. For example, the leader of each lap receives 16
points, followed by 15 for second place, 14 for third, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Points are tabulated after the first heat, which will determine
the starting lineup for the second heat.
</P>
<P>
   No points will be awarded in the second heat. The overall winner
will be determined by the driver crossing the finish line first.
</P>
<P>
   The champion receives $5 million, and the remaining $5 million
goes to the next 15 finishers. The pole-sitter gets $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   The event will be shown on Showtime Pay-Per-View at a cost of
$19.95. Starting time is 6 p.m. Eastern time.
</P>
<P>
   Pit stops &QL; 
The last driver to win at Long Beach from the pole position was  &UR; Al
Unser &UR; Jr., who won in 1990. It's only been done five times in the
25-year history of the race.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Greg Moore finished eighth, but he retained a six-point lead in
the drivers standings over  &UR; Adrian Fernandez. Montoya moved from
ninth to seventh and trails by 16 points. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
