<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAMBERS ASCENDS TO RING OF HONOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Suns unveiled their new Ring of Honor in America
West Arena's upper deck of the south end, and inducted forward  &UR; Tom
Chambers on Sunday at halftime of the Suns' 99-93 defeat of the
Seattle Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   Suns President  &UR; Jerry Colangelo also gave Chambers a new
Chevrolet pickup, a horse and a custom saddle.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers joins  &UR; Connie Hawkins, Dick Van Arsdale, Alvan Adams,
Paul Westphal and &UR; Walter Davis on the ring. Westphal was in
attendance, as coach of the Sonics, and got the loudest ovation
from the crowd when the previous honorees were introduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans were really nice, and I appreciated that,'' said
Westphal, who gave the crowd a wave during the ovation as he
conducted a timeout. ``I hope I acknowledged (them) satisfactorily.
I have a lot of great memories here.''
</P>
<P>
   The only previous honoree who was not in attendance was Hawkins,
who is with an NBA contingent that is visiting American troops
stationed in Bosnia, Croatia and other areas of the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he'd rather be here,'' Chambers quipped. &QL; 
Where's the volume? &QL; 
Suns Coach  &UR; Danny Ainge seemed mystified by the muted response from
announced sellout crowd at America West. The noise level was no
greater than the Suns used to get during some exhibition games.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't a lot of excitement,'' he said. ``It wasn't even
close to as loud as it was when we were up in Seattle, and they've
got about the same record we do and they're struggling right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys realize we had a slow start, and we deserved to get
booed earlier in the year. But they're playing well right now, and
these are big games. Let's get some volume.'' &QL; 
Olympic sample &QL; 
Never mind the pressure of hitting a game-winning shot.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jason Kidd and  &UR; Tom Gugliotta learned what real pressure is.
After the game, they were asked by U.S. Olympic officials to
provide a urine sample for a mandatory drug test that all players
who will compete at the Olympic qualifying tournament in Puerto
Rico this summer must take.
</P>
<P>
   After a 2-hour, 20-minute basketball game, both were a little
dehydrated.
</P>
<P>
   An hour after the game, Gugliotta and Kidd were still guzzling
bottled water and dipping their toes in the team's hot tub. Results
were pending. &QL; 
Selected short subjects &QL; 
The Suns moved above the .500 mark for the first time since March
24. And they improved to one game over .500 on their home court for
the first time since Feb. 28.
</P>
<P>
   The club swept Seattle in three games. It's the first time in
franchise history Phoenix has swept the Sonics, but there will be
an asterisk because of the shortened season.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's  &UR; Don MacLean had scored only 21 points all season. He
had 16 against the Suns, but also surrendered a wide-open shot to
Gugliotta late in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns have not allowed an opponent to score 100 points in 14
consecutive games, a franchise record.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
