<HEADLINE>
BOOK LOVERS SEEK TO FILL SHELVES OF INDIAN RESERVATION'S LIBRARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BETTY BEARD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GILA RIVER COMMUNITY, Ariz. _ One January day, journalist Claude
Jackson was in the Gila River Indian Community's only public
library and decided to look for his favorite author.
</P>
<P>
   A 26-year-old Pima Indian, reporter for the ``Gila River Indian
Newspaper'' and English literature graduate of Arizona State
University, Jackson likes to read a few passages in his spare time
from the Bard of Avon.
</P>
<P>
   To his dismay, the Sacaton library's only William Shakespeare
offering was a copy of ``King Lear''.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare isn't the only thing the Ira Hayes Memorial Library
is missing. It's missing most of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The library's only globe shows the Soviet Union, which crumbled
in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``World Book'' encyclopedias are from 1988, the big dictionary
is the 1986 version of ``Webster's Third New International,'' and
the Funk &AMP; Wagnall's ``New'' ``Encyclopedia of Science'' is dated
1986.
</P>
<P>
   Some reference books are ancient, such as the yellowed but
charming ``Little'' ``Journeys'' series of biographies from 1928.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no new atlases. I'm afraid to look at them to see how
old they are,'' said librarian Elaine Stephens, a former school
librarian who began working at Ira Hayes in August.
</P>
<P>
   The Hayes library, founded in 1985 by the Sun Lakes Kiwanis
Club, is the only public library in the sprawling 620-square-mile
Gila River Indian Community. Many patrons drive 30 minutes to check
out a book.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 2,500 to 3,000 books are old, Stephens said. The
library is especially short on books about Native American culture,
arts and crafts, space travel and modern fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Kids ask for the popular Goosebump books or other scary stories,
but the library has none. Adults ask for Tony Hillerman mysteries,
but there are only three.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its shortcomings, Stephens said, the library has
survived in the poor Native American community south of Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Stephens credits former librarian Eleanor Pasqual Whittier, now
in her late 60s, with the library's tenacity. ``She had no
training. She wanted to keep the library open and learned on the
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Whittier, who has retired, couldn't be reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``The library is kind of a forgotten entity. We're getting new
people, but a lot of them are the old faithful. . . . There's still
people who don't know about the library,'' Stephens said.
</P>
<P>
   Like any other library, the Ira Hayes Library loses books to
borrowers who never return them. Stephens finally began listing
their names in the ``Gila'' ``River Indian Newspaper,'' but said it
hasn't done any good.
</P>
<P>
   But just when things seem bleak, something happens to cheer her
up. One day a little girl with an overdue book explained that her
uncle's dog had chewed it up. She offered to pay for it and brought
in a penny bank full of coins. Stephens only had the heart to
charge her $2.
</P>
<P>
   She also gets reference questions about the Pima and Maricopa
Indians who live on the community. Her oddest query was ``What did
your tribe do for Christmas before they became Christians?''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the community has casino revenue, the library is slowly
improving. It has three new Dell computers, although they have yet
to be hooked up, because the phone lines need to be upgraded.
</P>
<P>
   Gambling money has also increased book-buying power, with the
library's book budget at $3,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   There's even talk of building a library to replace this one,
housed in a 1920s former Bureau of Indian Affairs office, a blue
schoolhouse with plastic glass windows and a touch-and-go
air-conditioner.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Jackson is spearheading a library book drive,
one he began with $40 from his wallet to buy a copy of the
``Complete Works of William'' ``Shakespeare.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson then contacted a former teacher, Laura Tohe, a Navajo
poet and assistant English professor at ASU, and asked for a list
of suggested Native American children's books to someday buy.
</P>
<P>
   Tohe was sympathetic without ever having visited the library.
After all, she grew up on a Navajo reservation and eventually
became a writer and poet and earned a Ph.D. in English.
</P>
<P>
   She contacted other Native American writers, and within weeks,
the library received about 40 books, mostly from Native American
writers. Donors included an African-American woman who remembered
dismal segregated libraries from her childhood, Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Tohe also contacted a Barnes &AMP; Noble Booksellers store in
Ahwatukee Foothills and persuaded the store to collect books for
the library. The store is offering a 20 percent discount for any
book bought into the store for the library through April.
</P>
<P>
   ``It totally caught me off guard. All I wanted to do was donate
one book,'' said Jackson, who grew up in Phoenix and is just
beginning to learn about the reservation and his cultural history.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the donations, the library still has no copy of Dee
Brown's ``Bury My'' ``Heart at Wounded Knee,'' the 1971 classic
told from a Native American perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (Native Americans) are much more interested in their
culture than the ordinary person,'' she said. Pimas come in often
to ask what houses looked like in the old days, what people ate or
how they dressed. ``Stories written by old-timers are impossible to
keep on the shelves,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The library is named after the late Ira Hayes, a Pima who became
famous after his picture was taken with four other Marines and a
Navy corpsman raising the flag at Iwo Jima in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Photographer Joe Rosenthal won a Pulitzer Prize for the World
War II photo and Hayes became a reluctant hero. He died in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the challenges, Stephens said, she's wanted this job a
long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started I knew it was not going to be easy. I told
myself, `I want to make this the best library I can and let people
know it's here.' I want it to be for the people, where they can be
comfortable and where it reflects their different interests.''
</P>
<P>
   She wants others to share her main passion in life: ``Books are
my life, although some people say they're a poor substitute for
life.'' &QL;  Betty
Beard can be reached at (602) 444-7982 or at betty.beard(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
