<HEADLINE>
ROENICK EXHIBITS TOUGHNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS AND BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Coyotes center  &UR; Jeremy Roenick said the simultaneous
slash that broke his thumb and hit by Dallas defenseman &UR; Derian
Hatcher that broke his jaw in three places and resulted in a
probable loss of eight teeth happened so fast Wednesday that it was
a blur.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I did was feel my jaw and wiggled my hand a
little,'' Roenick said. ``Everything happened so fast, I got
slashed (by  &UR; Craig Ludwig) and hit, and I didn't know whether to go
to the bench and cry, or go to the referee and say, `Look at my
jaw,' and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Lost amid the confusion was the fact that Roenick did return to
the game and played a shift on a five-on-three power play and
tossed a perfect pass to
 &UR; Keith Tkachuk for a shot at a wide-open net, but the puck hopped
over Tkachuk's stick on the terrible ice surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out there and got hit a little bit and my whole jaw
jiggled, so I thought something must really be wrong, so I went
back to the bench,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes Coach &UR; Jim Schoenfeld said Roenick's to return to the ice
``with his lips flapping all over the place'' is why nobody should
ever question his toughness, competitiveness or fortitude.
</P>
<P>
   Roenick, who attended final regular-season game against Dallas
after undergoing 5{ hours of surgery to repair his jaw on Thursday,
said Saturday was his most painful day since the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been the toughest so far,'' said Roenick, who has been
given a supply of bean and potato soups by his favorite local
restaurant. ``With all the drugs and Novocain, it was a little
easier to get through yesterday. When I woke up today, I was sore
and I was hurting, but I still looked forward to coming to the
game.'' &QL; 
What's going on? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He played a key role in helping the New York Rangers win the
Stanley Cup in 1994, but after the Coyotes rescued him from the
minor leagues late this season, right wing  &UR; Brian Noonan has mostly
sat as a healthy scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Acquired while the team was ravaged with injuries to its
forwards, there has been little room for ice time now that the club
is mostly injury-free. Does he expect his role to change in the
playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you, sometimes I have feelings since I've
been here that I really don't know what's going on,'' said Noonan,
who has 275 points in 629 career NHL games. ``The guys who have
been here all year are going to get their chance to play, but
sometimes, just sitting around, you wonder what their plans are for
you.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been frustrating, but I've got to stay positive. I want
to be playing, but I'm not the type of guy who's going to barge
into the room and demand to play. At the same time, that doesn't
mean I'm content with just sitting out. I'd like to play, I feel I
can help, but I'm just going to have to wait my return and see how
things unfold.''
</P>
<P>
   Noonan's experience could be his greatest asset. But it likely
will take an injury for Schoenfeld to use him in the upcoming
playoff series against the St. Louis Blues, which begins with Games
1 and 2 Thursday and Saturday at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld threw Noonan a bone on Saturday, letting him suit up
for the Coyotes' regular-season finale. &QL; 
Ending the drought &QL; 
It took 31 games and more than seven months, but winger  &UR; Stephen
Leach finally scored his first goal of the season with a
third-period shot Saturday that helped the Coyotes defeat the
Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good,'' Leach said. ``Certainly, it's tough when you
keep looking at the stat sheets and you've got a big goose egg
there. It was good to get it off. Hopefully, I can pop one in here
and there, and I think the third- and fourth-line guys, hopefully,
can do that throughout the playoffs. That's an important part of a
team's success.''
</P>
<P>
   Leach began the season with Ottawa, was waived, and the Coyotes
signed him as a free agent on Dec. 3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
