<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 PLAYERS SAVOR RARE STARTS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Given baseball players' competitive nature, it is
doubtful they will ask the manager for a breather. So the manager
often walks a fine line in determining when that should occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to get to know the guys enough to get a sense
for when it's good for them,'' Diamondbacks Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, a change is as much of a benefit for the player being
put into the lineup as it is for the man being removed. A good
example of that came Saturday, when  &UR; Dante Powell replaced  &UR; Steve
Finley in center field, and Sunday, when  &UR; David Dellucci spelled
 &UR; Tony Womack in right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Steve to take advantage of it because you never know,
it may not happen again for a while,'' said Showalter, who had
Finley back in the lineup Sunday and batting leadoff. ``You know,
though, that these guys will need a day off at some point and you
need the other guys to stay fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Dellucci, who made his first start of the season on Sunday:
``Nothing has changed. I want to try to do the same thing I did
during the spring: put the ball in play and play solid defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Dellucci had a double in four trips to the plate, walked once
and scored two runs. &QL; 
Stinnett sits 1 more &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Catcher  &UR; Kelly Stinnett was ready to resume his duties behind
the plate Sunday, but there still was uncertainty about his running
because of a bruised left quadriceps. Showalter was cautious and
decided to not start him until the tonight's first game of a
three-game series against the Philadelphia Phillies at Bank One
Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long recovery period, but he's at the point where
he needs to be,'' Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   Stinnett has been participating in pre-game defensive drills in
full gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do those drills until you're blue in the face but
they're only beneficial to a point,'' Showalter said. ``It's like a
pitcher throwing on the side. It's a different level of play in a
game situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Stinnett admitted he isn't quite 100 percent to run full speed,
but he could get behind the plate. Was he anxious, or was it better
to rest one more day?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit of both,'' Stinnett said.  &UR; ``Damian
( &UR; Miller, the second Arizona catcher) has done a good job (he has
started each of the nine games since Stinnett's injury), but he
needs a breather, too.'' &QL; 
Where's Barry? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With a .647 average (11 for 17), two home runs and nine walks
against Diamondbacks right-hander  &UR; Armando Reynoso, it seemed
strange that Giants left fielder  &UR; Barry Bonds would not be in the
lineup on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   There was a reason. Bonds was out because soreness in his left
arm prevented him from getting off a strong throw or getting the
proper extension on his swing. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 0143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
