<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-ARIZONANS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAINE NOT SURPRISED AT BEING DRAFTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After years of ``people telling me no,'' someone finally said
``yes'' to Joe Germaine.
</P>
<P>
   That someone was St. Louis Coach Dick Vermeil, who called the
former Mesa Mountain View High School standout at home Sunday and
told him he was about to be drafted by the Rams. The 6-1, 200-pound
quarterback from Ohio State was the sixth pick in the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, it's not mind-boggling,'' Germaine
said. ``I've dreamed about being an NFL quarterback ever since I
started playing Pop Warner. I've played the scenario over and over
in my mind. I guess I just expected it.''
</P>
<P>
   Also drafted Sunday were Arizona offensive linemen Edwin
Mulitalo, who went to Baltimore in the fourth round, and Yusuf
Scott, who was selected by the Cardinals in the fifth. Wildcats
tight end Mike Lucky went to Dallas in the seventh round.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State was shut out on the second day of the draft after
two players _ center Grey Ruegamer and fullback Jeff Paulk _ were
taken Saturday. The Sun Devils had 13 players selected in the two
previous seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Several area players signed free-agent contracts, including ASU
wide receivers Kenny Mitchell (Washington Redskins) and Lenzie
Jackson (Jacksonville Jaguars) and Arizona tight end Paul Shields
(Baltimore Ravens).
</P>
<P>
   Germaine finds himself in an encouraging scenario in St. Louis,
which signed 28-year-old Trent Green to a contract in the
off-season. Although Green is the man of the moment, he is not
perceived to be the Rams' quarterback of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Germaine is used to the underdog role. After playing on a
run-oriented offense in high school, he wasn't exactly bombarded
with Division I scholarship offers, he said. ASU liked him, but as
a defensive back.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback was his love, so he opted to play at Scottsdale
Community College before accepting a scholarship at Ohio State,
where he platooned much of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been fortunate with the success I've had,'' Germaine
said. ``I guess I've just been determined. A lot of people have
told me `no' during my career.''
</P>
<P>
   After hearing from Vermeil, Germaine headed to a Valley mall to
buy as many Rams hats as he could find for his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could only track down three,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mulitalo, who spent two years on a Mormon mission before playing
his junior and senior seasons at Arizona, goes to a Baltimore team
that lost two offensive linemen _ Wally Williams and Orlando Brown
_ to free agency.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons had several needs to address, including fullback,
which is good news for Paulk. Atlanta's starter, Bob Christian,
went down with a knee injury on Dec. 13 and is still not fully
healed.
</P>
<P>
   Paulk wasn't expecting to get drafted on Saturday, so he was
surprised when the phone rang.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden (Coach) Dan Reeves calls me up, and it took me
a while to even realize what was going on,'' Paulk said. ``He said,
`Can you play special teams, son?' and I said, `Whatever you need.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Paulk, a standout at Tempe Corona del Sol, made the most of his
ability to block at ASU. He has played a key role in the success of
the Sun Devils' running game during the last few seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``My stay at ASU was great,'' he said. ``Coming up out of high
school, I never thought I'd be in this position.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 0147EDT &QL; 
