A3702 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-SCOTT-AZR &LR;      04-19 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-SCOTT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOTT GOES HOG WILD AFTER SELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Please keep this a secret, but Arizona offensive
guard Yusuf Scott celebrated being picked in the fifth round by the
Cardinals by feasting on barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't tell Coach (Vince) Tobin, but I've got a lot of ribs in
my sink,'' Scott said from Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin heard the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's lean meat,'' Tobin said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, who has battled a weight problem, was in a partying mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' he said of being picked by the Cardinals. ``My
fiancee (UA point guard Lisa Griffith) loves it. The Cardinals were
my No. 1 team. I wanted to be close to my fiancee and family, and
you can't beat the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott, who turned pro after his junior season, is so excited
about joining the Cardinals that he plans to come to the team's
Tempe training facility today.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would gain weight if the coaches asked him to or shed
a few pounds if requested. He weighed 330 pounds last season and
now weighs 320.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they need me to gain weight, I can easily go to
McDonald's,'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ferguson, vice president-player personnel, described Scott
as ``Nate Newtonish,'' referring to the longtime Dallas Cowboys
offensive lineman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, he'll be that good, not that fat,'' Ferguson said,
smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Scott not only was one of the Wildcats' most popular players, he
also was one of the most effective. He was voted the Pac-10's best
lineman in a vote by opposing defensive linemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just powerful,'' Ferguson said. ``On the highlight film,
you see him chasing an Oregon linebacker down the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like drafting tackles and making them into guards. He's an
exception. He's a guard. But I like what he brings. I like his
size. I like his attitude and temperament.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott took pride in making so many crushing, pancake blocks, he
ate pancakes for breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tough guy,'' Cardinals offensive line coach George
Warhop said. ``He finishes everything. I saw the tape of the Iowa
game. He got on a linebacker and took him out of the picture frame
and off the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Warhop plans on using Scott at both the right and left guard
spots, where he will back up Lester Holmes and Chris Dishman,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The only reason Scott still was available in the fifth round was
because of his disappointing performance at the NFL's scouting
combine in February in Indianapolis. He was bothered by a pulled
Achilles' tendon and a sore left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   UA Coach Dick Tomey said Scott, like many big guys, might always
battle his weight, but that ``the thing I admire about him the most
is his work ethic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cardinals asked about his personality,'' Tomey said. ``He
has a very outgoing personality. He's very affable and
enthusiastic. He's a joy to coach and be around.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott is looking forward to being around Cardinals quarterback
Jake Plummer, formerly a rival at Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a winner, regardless if he's a Sun Devil,'' Scott said.
``He gets in offensive linemen's faces. If he sees a wide receiver
isn't open, he lowers his shoulder pads and gets those yards on his
own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I'm going to do when I see him is go up to him
and shake his hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott said he also planned to have a friendly bet with Plummer
on next year's UA-ASU game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll bet dinner, and I'm going to (remind) him I can eat,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
