<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3711 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-DRAFT-NOTES     04-19 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-DRAFT-NOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW QB FAMILIAR WITH TOBIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 and LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Rookie quarterback  &UR; Chris Greisen doesn't need
any biographical information on Cardinals Coach  &UR; Vince Tobin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a legend (around here),'' said Greisen, a seventh-round
draft pick from Northwest Missouri State. ``You say the Tobin name,
and everyone knows him and his brother (former NFL executive
Bill).''
</P>
<P>
   That's because the Tobins played for Maryville High School, home
of the Spoofhounds. Maryville also is the site of Northwest
Missouri State.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin, who grew up in nearby Burlington Junction, Mo., has a
charity golf tournament each summer in Maryville.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four years ago, Northwest Missouri was 0-11,'' Tobin said of
the Division II school. ``They were 15-1 in 1997. They were 16-0
this year and won the national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Division II national championship game, Greisen,
pronounced ``Gry-zun,'' threw five touchdown passes, including a
74-yarder.
</P>
<P>
   Yet because he played at a small school, he wasn't expected to
be drafted. In fact, Baltimore, Cincinnati and San Francisco called
him during the draft and asked him about signing as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   One reason the Cardinals drafted him was a year ago, they hoped
to sign Colorado State's  &UR; Moses Moreno as a free agent and bypassed
him in the seventh round. The Chicago Bears then drafted Moreno.
</P>
<P>
   Greisen has an excellent chance of making the Cardinals. They
have only three quarterbacks on their roster and will carry three
all season.
</P>
<P>
   He is expected to face some competition for the No. 3 job after
the team signs a rookie free agent at quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my strength is my ability to make plays, kind of like
 &UR; Jake
 &UR; Plummer, and just being smart out there,'' said Greisen, 6 feet 2,
223 pounds, who was a Division I recruit in high school out of
Sturgeon Bay, Wisc., until he suffered a knee injury his senior
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have a knack for the game, just instinctive things.
A weakness might be speed, but quarterbacks really don't need great
overall speed.'' &QL; 
Popular analyst
</P>
<P>
   While the national analysts were gushing over the Cardinals'
picks, none was more astute than a neophyte to the business.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive back  &UR; Corey Chavous, a rookie last season, was crisp
and sharp in his assessment of the team's draft during a two-day
draft stint on a national radio show.
</P>
<P>
   He was so impressive in his national broadcasting debut, ESPN
also asked him to evaluate the draft during their telecast.
</P>
<P>
   Chavous, a draftnik who has a videotape library on 400 players,
told ESPN that cornerback  &UR; Jacoby Rhinehart, a sixth-round pick
from Southern Methodist, was the ``Senior Bowl South Team Most
Valuable Player'' and had ``15 pass break-ups last season.''
</P>
<P>
   But he really opened some eyes when he proclaimed Arizona
cornerback
 &UR; Chris McAlister, a first-round pick of the Baltimore Ravens, the
best cornerback to come out of college in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll give you a 9.5 from the judges,'' ESPN's  &UR; Mike Tirico
told Chavous. &QL; 
Short shots
</P>
<P>
   Tobin, who was brought into NFL coaching with the Chicago Bears
by  &UR; Mike
 &UR; Ditka, laughed when he saw his buddy wearing a dreadlocks wig on TV
Sunday. Ditka, given the wig by Saints offensive coordinator  &UR; Danny
Abramowitz, was poking fun at the hairstyle worn by Saints first-
(and only) round pick  &UR; Ricky
 &UR; Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike likes to have fun,'' Tobin said. ``He really enjoys life.
He's tremendously quick-witted. He's a special guy, no question.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals wide receiver  &UR; Andy McCullough caught touchdown passes
of 23 yards and 43 yards to help Frankfurt beat Berlin, 31-20, in
the NFL Europe League season opener on Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
