<HEADLINE>
ABDUL CASTS A SPELL AS ONE SHARP KID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're interviewing the state's best speller, you might as
well ask him to tackle some tough words.
</P>
<P>
   Some might think the request a bit rude, putting him on the spot
like that. But to his credit, Abdul Kahsai showed none of the
reluctance of a doctor at a cocktail party who balks at listening
to someone drone on about an ingrown toenail. The 12-year-old
seventh-grader at Taylor Junior High School in Mesa jumped right in
and clicked off ``pestiferous'' (CQ) and ``diagenesis'' (CQ)
without a hitch.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, since he won the state spelling bee April 10, this was
nothing that all his classmates haven't been asking of him every
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just ask Abdul,'' Andy Flambouras, one of Abdul's teachers,
said. ``He's our built-in dictionary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my job,'' Abdul said with justifiable pride and a grin.
``I'm the state spelling-bee champion.''
</P>
<P>
   He's a good sport, Abdul. Monstrously hard-working and
competitive as all get-out, but a good sport nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say he's perfect. He faltered a bit on
``chrysanthemum'' and ``meprobamate'' (CQ) in our impromptu session
(blame the dubious pronunciations of his inquisitor). But if his
work habits hold true, he won't misspell them again.
</P>
<P>
   TOUGH DAD, SADISTIC JOE
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Abdul lost at the district level. Missed
``etiquette.'' Still pains him, you can tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so disappointed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So much so that he has studied lists of words every day since
the middle of December. Not just looked them over, studied them,
all 150 words per page.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was to miss just one word, my dad would make me go back
and study the whole page'' again, Abdul said last week in
Flambouras' classroom. ``The second (miss), he made me look up the
definitions. The third time, he made me write a sentence with (the
word) in it.''
</P>
<P>
   There weren't many third times. Or, for that matter, seconds.
Just ask Joe Halcomb. The 13-year-old Joe, Abdul's self-described
spelling coach, tagged along with Abdul for an interview and
revealed his methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I helped him by reading the words, and he spelled them out,''
Joe explained. Sounds simple. Deceptively so. Joe also had a
punishment worked out: Every time Abdul missed a word, he owed Joe
10 push-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ONLY ONE PROBLEM
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't missed any yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Joe's career as a sadistic and demanding coach is getting
off to a slow start. On the bright side, all the work is helping
Joe, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm starting to get used to all these big words,'' he
said. &QL; 
ABDUL GOES TO WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to his study habits, Abdul buzzed through ``nyctalopia,''
``lobscouse''and ``prosateur'' (CQ) in the state bee.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's getting ready for the national bee in Washington, D.C.,
in June. He and Joe will continue their work. Meanwhile, Abdul
answered the question I've always had about good spellers: Does he
see the word in his mind and just spell what he sees? Or does he go
by spelling rules?
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to sound it out phonetically,'' he said. ``Then it comes
out into my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   As you can see, Abdul is adept at answering dumb questions. He
should be. He's been on television and been interviewed by
newspapers. He's even had a scheduled appearance on a local morning
show rescheduled at the last minute _ by now, he's an old pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``People I never knew before come up to me and say, `Hey, you're
the spelling-bee man,' '' Abdul said. Does that include girls?
</P>
<P>
   Huge blush.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's getting a little bit too personal there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry. But his embarrassment pointed out what a normal, cool _
if extremely smart _ kid Abdul is. He likes basketball, swimming,
rap, hip-hop, video games _ all the things 12-year-olds do.
</P>
<P>
   Since there is no market for professional spellers, Abdul
already has started thinking about career plans. He wants to be a
basketball player. And if that doesn't work out?
</P>
<P>
   ``A journalist.''
</P>
<P>
   Told you he was smart. &QL; 
Reach Bill Goodykoontz at 602-444-8828, &QL; 
or at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
