<HEADER>
A3730 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-ANGELS-S     04-19 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-ANGELS-SPI </SLUG>
  
 M's ESCAPE BRAWL WITH WIN OVER ANGELS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Brett Hinchliffe had never started a major
league game before Sunday night. He'd never been bitten on a
ballfield before Sunday night, either.
</P>
<P>
   But that's what happened to the Mariners' right-hander in the
finale of a rollicking three-game series with the Angels. Not only
did someone chomp his calf, he also got a bone bruise when someone
stomped on his left hand.
</P>
<P>
   Hinchliffe was ejected in the fourth inning of Sunday night's
8-5 Mariners win when he drilled Todd Greene after allowing a home
run to Troy Glaus. Greene charged the mound with fists flying, and
both benches and bullpens emptied.
</P>
<P>
   The melee, in a nationally televised game whose highlights
delighted the clubhouse afterward, was the culmination of an
intense weekend that began with a near-brawl Friday after M's
pitcher Jamie Moyer hit two batters in a 9-5 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Junior was hit because of what happened the other night,''
said Mariners manager Lou Piniella. ``We understand that. It's good
to see Brett protect the hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. did not charge or curse when he was hit on the
backside by a fastball from knuckleballer Steve Sparks in the third
inning. Instead, Griffey calmly and deliberately pointed his bat
toward the Anaheim dugout. Call it the tremor before the quake,
because a rumble was coming.
</P>
<P>
   It arrived when Hinchliffe hit Greene _ accidentally, he
insisted _ and suddenly had a 5-foot-10, 208-pound former catcher
charging his 6-foot-5, 190-pound frame. Greene, who homered Friday
and Saturday, did something he didn't do often this weekend: swung
and missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm quick on my toes,'' Hinchliffe said. ``I'm not going to
get caught. He was coming at me and I was ready, and then he
stopped. He tried to get in a couple of haymakers, and I slipped
out of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Hinchliffe said Greene had been crushing pitches low and away
this weekend, but he retired him in the first inning when he jammed
him with a fastball. Hinchliffe said he was only trying to come in
there again ... but acknowledged this weekend's tensions had to
come out sometime.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of guys were hit the first day, and again the third
day,'' Hinchliffe said. ``It was good to get it out of the way. If
he hadn't charged, they were probably just going to hit another
guy. It might have started too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Hinchliffe said he was surprised he got ejected, since umpires
did not issue a warning even after Griffey pointed his bat. Of that
gesture, Griffey said, ``It doesn't matter. It's over and done
with. Just leave it like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim manager Terry Collins was similarly evasive about what
he told Griffey on the field during the brawl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him it's a beautiful day and a nice crowd,'' Collins
said. ``I told him I didn't want him to get hurt on the bottom of
that pile.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Sparks said he wasn't trying to hit Griffey,
claiming he threw him the same kind of cut fastball he retired him
on in the first inning. Piniella noted one good thing about the six
hit-by-pitches over Friday and Sunday's games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hitters that were hit were hit in the middle area,''
Piniella said. ``There was no head-hunting or anything else. We
don't advocate that, for sure. ... (But) our pitchers protect our
hitters. Every club in baseball does the same. Our pitchers know
what they have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   So did the Mariners' hitters Sunday night. Griffey was hit with
two outs and the bases empty in a 2-2 game. Edgar Martinez followed
with a run-scoring double down the right-field line, and Jay Buhner
homered one batter later to give the M's a 5-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always want to get the best of that inning, because
obviously you don't want your main guy to get hit,'' Martinez said.
``This team gets pretty pumped up after something like that
happens. It's great to see that work to our advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez pulled a double in the fifth inning to score Griffey
again, and Butch Huskey accounted for the rest of the offense with
a run-scoring single and solo homer. Ken Cloude (1-1), Jose
Paniagua and Jose Mesa worked 41/3 scoreless relief innings to
secure the Mariners' second victory in a row _ and the series win
over Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels were runners-up to Seattle in 1995 and '97, the teams
had a post-game scrap this spring training, their third base
coaches went at it Friday night and Piniella had to be restrained
from charging a fan that same evening.
</P>
<P>
   So is it over now?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is over in my mind,'' Greene said, ``but no one in this
clubhouse is going to run away from it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's over right now, because we're not playing them anymore,''
said Mariners first baseman David Segui. ``I would assume it is. I
think.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels visit Seattle for a three-game series June 22-24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
