<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3733 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-GRETZKY-BOS &LR;      04-19 1346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GRETZKY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAYNE'S WHIRL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wayne Gretzky bundled up his passion and his points
here Sunday, his legendary run complete after 20 years, 894 goals,
and 1,963 assists, and waved goodbye to Broadway, the Blueshirts,
and a lifetime as hockey's most prolific and best-known performer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to a good friend of mine today that this is not a
passing on,'' said Gretzky in the moments that followed the
Rangers' 2-1 overtime loss to the Pittsburgh Penguins at Madison
Square Garden. ``It's a moving on. It's a great game to watch, to
play, and it's going to kill me not to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``But time does something to you _ and it's time.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of a Bell Canada lineman, who already was being called
The Kid prior to joining the NHL in 1979, Gretzky fittingly picked
up an assist in his 1,487th game. The assist was always his
signature, and he helped set up a Brian Leetch goal to make it 1-1
with 29.9 seconds to go in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   For the 2,857th time, for the last time, the best known hockey
name in the world was entered on the scoresheet. Gretzky would be
sitting on the bench when Jaromir Jagr's game-winner, 1:22 into
overtime, went in the net, and at 5:57 p.m. Gretzky's career came
to an end before a hushed sellout crowd of 18,200.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky played 22 shifts for a total of 22 minutes, 30 seconds,
including two shifts late in the third period when everyone not
dressed in Penguin gold-and-white looked for the Great One to end
it with a goal, which would have been akin to Ted Williams exiting
with his home run swat in 1960. But it was not to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could have been (Michael) Jordan, hitting the last
shot to win a championship,'' said Gretzky, who became accustomed
to heroics and the thrill of victory in his heyday, winning four
Stanley Cups with the Oilers in the '80s. ``But that wasn't going
to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   To provide the perfect segue, it was Jagr, who became the game's
greatest current player even before the post-Gretzky era began, who
ultimately buried the winner. Collecting the puck down low near the
right post, he magically played with it before sweeping his
backhander past Rangers goalie Mike Richter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fitting,'' said Gretzky, who made a point of hugging Jagr for
an extra second or two after the game. ``Everyone thinks about
catching that last pass to win the game . . . and that's what I
told him, `You caught it.' He said he didn't mean to do that and I
told him, `That's what I used to say.' ''
</P>
<P>
   For farewells, the three-hour-plus show just south of Broadway's
famous playhouses was a smooth, touching tribute to the 38-year-old
Gretzky. It did not rank among the emotional, pathos-evoking,
almost painful farewells of Bob Cousy or Lou Gehrig.
</P>
<P>
   Who could forget the Cooz, family at his side on the Garden
parquet floor, making his tearful farewell speech. And Gehrig's
adieu at Yankee Stadium, his words, ``Today, I consider myself the
luckiest man on the face of the earth,'' echoing through the Bronx
Canyon, his career, and soon his life, shortened by amyotrophic
lateral sclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky was more emotional Friday when he stood before a large
media gathering inside MSG's Paramount Room and officially
announced his retirement. He said then that he had hit the wall, he
had the urge for goin', and Sunday he hoped would be a rite of
celebration, more in context of a wedding than a funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good cry before I left home,'' said Gretzky,
reflecting on how he felt Friday. ``It's hard to get up and tell
the world you're leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony did hold its surprises, the most poignant of which
was NHL commissioner Gary Bettman announcing before faceoff that
Gretzky's No. 99 never would be worn in the league again. It was
not raised to the MSG rafters _ that ceremony will come another
time _ but Bettman's mandate made it clear that no NHLer would
skate in Gretzky's shadow or his sweater.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will miss you,'' said Bettman, ``and there will never be
another.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky also received a black S500 four-door Mercedes sedan from
the Rangers, wheeled to center ice with his father Walter Gretzky
in the passenger seat. The senior Gretzky, now 60 years old,
reminisced with reporters outside the Rangers dressing room before
the game. He talked of his son's first skates, hand-me-downs he
received at age three, and the day the greatest scorer that ever
would be took his first skate on the Don River in Brantford.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Gretzky's son was small, frail, and he gave his father no
reason early on to think the family name would become synonymous
throughout the world with the game of ice hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has said to me, `Sometimes I have to pinch myself, this
whole thing is like a dream,' '' said Walter Gretzky, echoing his
son's words to him over the last two decades. ``Even he says that,
so you can imagine how I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago, father asked son about the prospect of
retiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he said to me, `Well, dad, you have to understand,' ''
said Walter, `` `every year I go to training camp, and the guys are
bigger, stronger, faster . . . and I am getting older.' I don't
think he ever wanted to get to the point where someone said to him,
`Wayne, we think you should retire.' He wouldn't like that.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was not so old that he had lost his effectiveness.
Gretzky's assist in his final game gave him 62 points in 70 games
for the season. It pales in comparison to the four 200-plus point
seasons he had with the speedy, talented Oilers in the '80s, but it
still made him a valuable commodity in today's clogged-up,
slowed-down NHL. The Rangers were hoping he would return and told
him last week that they'd pick up the $5 million option on his
contract. By the time they made their decision, however, Gretzky
already had made the emotional commitment to walk away while he was
still an effective, even if lesser, performer.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived at the interview room after the loss, the game
finished for more than hour, Gretzky was still in full uniform. The
dark blue Ranger sweater was drenched across the chest. He still
wore his padded pants. There hadn't been time, he said, to talk
with teammates, friends, and family and shower before his final
news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``And probably, subconsciously, I don't want to take it off,''
said Gretzky, who also wore the sweater of the Oilers, Kings, and
Blues in his NHL career. ``I mean, I'm not going to put it on ever
again. It's hard. To be honest with you, I don't want to take it
off.''
</P>
<P>
   The Garden crowd was treated to an afternoon more of melancholy
and memories. Mario Lemieux, whom Gretzky acknowledged as the
greatest player he ever played against, flew in from Pittsburgh.
Old pal Mark Messier, still adored by the Rangers crowd for leading
the Blueshirts to their first Cup in 54 years in 1994, made the
trip from Vancouver. Paul Coffey made it. Ulf Samuelsson, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were close when (Samuelsson) played here,'' said Gretzky.
``I didn't know he was coming. That threw me over the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Within three minutes after the game ended, Gretzky was at center
ice with his fellow Rangers, posing for a final team picture. He
disappeared down the runway at 6 p.m., only to return three minutes
later for the first of two curtain calls. He looked awkward at
times, as if not knowing what to do, where to go, how to express
himself, the ice surface for once in his career strange, uncharted
territory.
</P>
<P>
   He picked up a bouquet of flowers tossed to the ice. He picked
up baseball caps. Near the Zamboni entrance, he spotted Christopher
Reeve, the actor confined to a wheelchair from a horseback riding
accident, and gave him a hug.
</P>
<P>
   He left the ice for good at 6:13 p.m., his face alternately
smiling and stoic, offering a last, emphatic goodbye with a wave of
his arms. There wouldn't be a third curtain call. He was done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not only mentally ready,'' he said, ``but I'm physically
ready to retire. I'm ready.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
