<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-FLYERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS DROP TO SIXTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Greensboro, N.C., doesn't exactly come to mind
when discussing hockey hotbeds. Not in the way that, let's say,
Toronto does.
</P>
<P>
   Even Bruins president/general manager Harry Sinden said that in
terms of hockey interest, the cities ``are from one extreme to the
other.''
</P>
<P>
   But Greensboro is just where the Bruins are heading, as their
opponents for their best-of-seven, first-round series are the
Carolina Hurricanes. Games 1 and 2 are Thursday and Saturday at the
Greensboro Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   By virtue of Sunday's 3-1 loss to the Flyers, which was a
snoozer of epic proportions, the Bruins finished in sixth place in
the Eastern Conference and will be matched against the third-seeded
Hurricanes, who finished with a worse record than Boston (34-30-18
versus the locals' 39-30-13) but earned their seed by winning the
Southeast Division.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Bruins won or tied Sunday, they would have faced the
Maple Leafs, against whom they went 3-1-1 in the regular season.
Boston tied the season series with Carolina, 2-2-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got some winners on that team who have won before,''
said coach Pat Burns. ``We didn't exactly walk away with all kinds
of success against them. We'll be a good match for them, and
they'll be a good match for us. It'll be an interesting series. It
will be a long one.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the undermanned Bruins, who looked as if they were
suffering from an emotional hangover after their 2-1 win over
Buffalo Saturday, played even with the Flyers for one period. At
the 3:44 mark of the first, with the Flyers on the power play,
right wing Mark Grieg dished a feed to left wing John LeClair, who
tried to tip a shot past Rob Tallas. The goalie made the stop, but
LeClair put the rebound on his backhand and flipped it in for the
1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins came right back, with Sergei Samsonov tallying his
25th goal of the year on the team's first shot of the game.
Samsonov took a pass from Ken Belanger, skated through the left
circle, and beat goalie John Vanbiesbrouck with a backhander inside
the left post at 4:54.
</P>
<P>
   Boston had six shots in the first period and just five in the
final 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia took the lead for good at the 15:30 mark, just six
seconds into another power play. With Mattias Timander off for
tripping, defenseman Eric Desjardins teed up a slapper from the
right point through traffic that beat the screened Tallas.
</P>
<P>
   In the dull second period, which slowed to an absolute crawl,
Rob Brind'Amour made it a two-goal lead with his 24th of the season
at 13:08.
</P>
<P>
   In the scheme of things, Sunday's game was one worth forgetting
_ quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were missing a lot of elements,'' said Burns. ``All my
penalty killers weren't there today. Not that I fault Robbie
Tallas, but Byron Dafoe is a big part of our penalty killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could sit here and talk all we want, but the game today,
good luck to the Flyers. It wasn't very good; it was awful. We had
two games in two days. The last two weeks, I've liked. You can't
count today. I didn't like nothing today. I just liked when I heard
the last buzzer.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Burns was pleased with how the season ended. ``At the
start of the year, if I said we would've played the Flyers for
fifth place today, you probably would've laughed at me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If Sunday was hard on anyone, it was Tallas, who for the second
time in recent weeks was in net when his team was going through a
letdown. The last time was April 8, one night after the Bruins had
clinched a playoff spot against Florida; they then fell flat
against Tampa Bay in a 3-0 loss.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Sunday, however, Tallas and his teammates were in a very
positive frame of mind. ``We had a great game (Saturday) night at
home, we had a few injuries and a few guys sitting out, and that's
the way it's going to happen sometimes,'' said Tallas. ``We've been
together for 81 games, and if you look around the league, you want
to get it done and get into the playoffs. Now we have a new goal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
