<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOYLE TOPS FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
 SENIORS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH GARDENS, Fla. _ Always, he felt he had to prove
himself. He knew he could play, but ``everywhere I've gone people
have dismissed me as a guy probably not very good.''
</P>
<P>
   So Allen Doyle did Sunday what he always has done _ let them
chuckle at his golf swing as he knocked down the pins. Only this
time he did it in a most spectacular fashion at a most special
event. The one-time hockey player at Catholic Memorial and Norwich
University shot a closing 8-under-par 64 to come from four shots
back and win the 60th PGA Seniors' Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle finished at 14-under 274, blistering PGA National's
Champions Course with nine birdies and one eagle. It was his second
win of the year, a 22-putt final round, the lowest close in tourney
history, a win worth $315,000, and left many stunned. When told
that his playing partner, New Englander Dana Quigley, had called it
``one of the greatest rounds of golf I have ever seen,'' Doyle
shook his head, almost in disbelief. ``Me, too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He had started the day four shots behind Vicente Fernandez and
Bruce Fleisher but gave little thought to what it would take to
win. But he certainly was confident enough to let that homemade
swing do its thing. Doyle grew up in Norwood, learned the game as a
caddie at Spring Valley CC in Sharon, and would practice his swing
during cold winter days in a cellar with a low ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the backswing is low and the follow-through quick, though
``in my mind it isn't as fast as it looks.'' What was fast was his
move up the leaderboard in this oldest major in professional senior
golf.
</P>
<P>
   He made a birdie from 4 feet on the first hole, then drained a
45-footer on No. 2 to go to 8-under. ``That's when I was thinking
that it might be my day,'' said Doyle.
</P>
<P>
   Two holes later, Doyle gave back both shots, making his only
double-bogey of the tournament. ``That's when I thought I was
playing for a good paycheck.''
</P>
<P>
   He was, though the price soared when Doyle made birdies at five,
seven, and nine to make the turn in 33 to get to 9-under, then
shaved two more shots off par with a chip-in eagle from 80-90 feet
at the par-5 10th. Though he gave one back at the 11th, Doyle ran
off birdies at the next three holes to get to 13-under. ``That's
when I got the feeling I was a little blessed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention applying some pressure to the guys behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' said Fernandez, ``I was looking at the leaderboard, so
I knew what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't quite know the worst of it, however, because the lead
groups were heading into what they call ``The Bear Trap,'' the
final four holes of this grueling course that was re-designed by
Jack Nicklaus 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   At the par-3 15th, a mere 164 yards that is all carry over
water, Doyle made his three, then drove it perfectly at the
toughest hole on the course, the 428-yard par-4 16th. He was one
shot out of the lead and facing a 4-iron shot from 193 yards. ``But
I don't carry a 4-iron,'' said Doyle, ``so I hit 3. I aimed it 25
feet left of the pin.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle cut it beautifully and it held into the wind, the ball
coming to rest a mere foot from the pin. ``If it was 4 or 5 feet,''
he said, ``I don't know if I could have made it. But I can make 'em
from a foot.''
</P>
<P>
   It put him in a tie for the lead, but only momentarily. As he
went to mark his ball on the green at the par-3 17th, Doyle heard
the crowd react. Looking up at the scoreboard, Fernandez's score
went from 14-under to 12. The Bear Trap had bit him with a
double-bogey at 15. ``He played a great round,'' said Fernandez,
who shot 70_276 to finish alone in second, ``but I helped him a
little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleisher shot 73 to finish in a tie for third with Jose Maria
Canizares (72) at 279. Quigley got it to 10-under through 14, but
saw his chances sink with a shot in the water at 15, too. He
finished 70_280, tied for fifth with Bruce Summerhays (70).
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, pars at 17 and 18 brought Doyle home to an ovation.
The championship hardware sat just off the 18th green as Doyle went
through formalities no one could have predicted for this man who
figured he would be an amateur forever.
</P>
<P>
   There had been temptations to turn pro, but he felt he was too
old. That's when he was in his 30s and fresh off a military stint
in Korea. ``You don't play much golf in the DMZ,'' he said. So he
racked up a bunch of amateur championships in Georgia, played some
Walker Cups, left the textile business, and made a decent living
with a driving range.
</P>
<P>
   When it become apparent that the Senior PGA Tour was for real,
Doyle gave in to temptation. He was 47 when he turned pro in 1995
and the road since has been one test after another, from Nike Tour
to PGA Tour to this, his first full season as a 50-year-old
professional golfer.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle was told his name would go on a trophy alongside those of
Sam Snead, Arnold Palmer, Nicklaus, and Gary Player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can believe all of this,'' said Doyle, ``but I do have to
pinch myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
