<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX OFFENSE FAILS AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-DEVIL RAYS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It could be worse. Just ask Don Zimmer, provisional
caretaker of the supposedly greater-than-ever New York Yankees, who
have lost four straight to match their longest losing streak of
1998. Zim's knee may not be all that needs reconstructive surgery
after George Steinbrenner gives him the obligatory earful.
</P>
<P>
   But to a constituency that seldom sees beyond that insular world
bounded by Lansdowne Street, Van Ness, and Yawkey Way, the big
picture is usually eclipsed by whatever daily calamities have been
visited upon the Olde Towne Team.
</P>
<P>
   And for the 27,589 present at thawing Fenway Park for Sunday's
5-1 loss to the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, their third loss against just
two wins in their first homestand, there were no more pressing
concerns than the condition of Tom Gordon's elbow, the lack of
muscle shown by the Red Sox offense, and the worrisome start of
rookie right fielder Trot Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon was placed on the 15-day disabled list even before
undergoing a magnetic resonance imaging exam Sunday at UMass
Medical Center in Worcester.
</P>
<P>
   How bad is it? The Red Sox claimed they were still awaiting word
after the game; for now, it's still being called a strain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flash has been pointing up at the Lord all this time,''
pitching coach Joe Kerrigan said. ``Maybe it's time for the Lord to
point down to him. No sense worrying about it until we get the
results.''
</P>
<P>
   The results have been just as slow in coming for the Sox
offense, which couldn't take advantage of Nomar Garciaparra
reaching base on all four of his plate appearances Sunday with a
double, single, and two walks.
</P>
<P>
   Canton's Bobby Witt limited the Sox to a run on four hits in six
innings, then turned the game over to a bullpen that allowed just
Jason Varitek's eighth-inning single the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Any time the Sox did stir, the Devil Rays answered with a
silencing play afield. Tampa Bay rookie left fielder Danny Clyburn,
who should have a closetful of Gold Gloves based on his play
against the Sox, made two diving catches to take hits away from
Jeff Frye, and second baseman Miguel Cairo spun a rally-killing
double play in the seventh, spearing Jose Offerman's grounder up
the middle with a backhanded stab, then flipping the ball with his
glove to shortstop Kevin Stocker.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Sox rank last in the American League in home runs
with six, the Devil Rays Sunday hit three home runs, including the
third in three games here by designated villain Jose Canseco, who
has as many home runs as his former team.
</P>
<P>
   Canseco's sixth-inning home run Sunday off Sox starter Pat Rapp,
who struck out seven and gave up just four hits in seven innings,
was another one of those
boo-me-any-louder-and-I'm-hitting-the-next-one-into-the-river jobs,
just like the previous two. It landed among the cars in the back
row of the parking lot beyond the Green Monster, hard by the
railroad tracks next to the Mass. Pike.
</P>
<P>
   Canseco has scorched Sox general manager Dan Duquette many times
in the past, but didn't swing when lobbed a fat pitch about what he
thought about having as many home runs as the Sox nearly two weeks
into the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do I think about it?'' said Canseco, who hasn't lost his
sense of humor, mugging and waving to the kiddies on Kids' Opening
Day Saturday even as the boos rained down. ``I don't think about
it. What am I supposed to think about it?''
</P>
<P>
   Witt wasn't biting at the idea that the 1999 Sox lineup poses
fewer threats than its predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not at all,'' Witt said. ``They've got guys over there
that can play baseball. They know how to play it and they know how
to win. Granted Mo's gone, but Nomar's back and there's (John)
Valentin and (Mike) Stanley. I don't ever take a team lightly.
They've got just as good a team as anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, that idea seems a stretch as it applies to Nixon,
who has no hits in nine at-bats on the homestand, was 0 for 4 with
two strikeouts Sunday, and overall is 2 for 25 with an .080
average.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times I find myself aggressive, right where I want to be,''
said Nixon, whom Valentin engaged in a very visible heart-to-heart
chat in the clubhouse after the game. ``Other times I find myself
being passive, I don't know why. It's like I'm trying to read the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the home fans are offering their customary support
when one of their own is struggling. Canseco was the only person
who heard more boos than Nixon. ``That's really going to make it
easier,'' Frye said, shaking his head. ``Booing him.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon took the defiant approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what the fans do,'' Nixon said. ``I play for the
team. I play for the fans, too, and the organization, but if
they're going to say something derogatory, that just shows their
class.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, manager Jimy Williams has yet to invite the fans to fill
out his lineup card.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing him,'' Williams said of Nixon. ``If I thought
there was any type of situation involved, watching a player, I'd do
something. But watching him, he's still having good at-bats, he
feels good about himself in the batter's box.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, he's a player. Things can happen in one at-bat, one
game. Things can change very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   It was still 3-1 in the ninth when Devil Rays third baseman
Bobby Smith dropped a fly ball into the right-field seats, just
inside the Pesky Pole, off pitcher-for-the-day Brian Rose, called
up just for the afternoon from Pawtucket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a job to do,'' Rose said. ``A 3 to 1 game, I'm trying to
get them back in the dugout. I was praying, hoping that it would
come down, but the ball kept carrying. That home run was like
taking the air out of a balloon.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing to do but sleep fast for this morning's matinee, when
the Sox face Devil Rays ace Rolando Arrojo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't get any easier (Monday),'' Frye said. ``Eleven
o'clock start, against that guy. Nothing to do but just keep
swinging.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
