<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEERS LEFT COLD BY PATRIOTS' DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ No dean's list for New England this year.
</P>
<P>
   For the third year in a row the Patriots' draft got mixed
reviews from a panel of their peers interviewed Sunday night when
the draft was over.
</P>
<P>
   Four general managers and a coach participated, with the
agreement that they remain anonymous. Two were from the AFC, three
from the NFC.
</P>
<P>
   They all were asked to talk about the players the Patriots took,
and what grade they would give them overall.
</P>
<P>
   AFC general manager: ``Damien Woody is a very good pick. With
the right coaching, he could be a heck of a player. Whether he will
or not remains to be seen, because he didn't play with a lot of
intensity at Boston College last year. He seemed indifferent about
playing. But he has talent. We had him and Andy Katzenmoyer rated
between 20 and 30 on our board, or just about where they went. Both
should be good players. Katzenmoyer has to play a little smarter
than he's been playing. He doesn't make a lot of good decisions
when you watch him play on tape. Kevin Faulk was a good pick. I
like their top three guys. Faulk can make some plays in space. He's
not a full-time back. The rest of the guys they picked are just
guys. We wouldn't have drafted the last two guys they took (Michael
Bishop and Sean Morey); they weren't on our board. They already
have four safeties (Lawyer Milloy, Willie Clay, Chris Carter, Larry
Whigham) _ why would they draft two more?'' Grade: B.
</P>
<P>
   AFC coach: ``We had Woody rated between 25 and 35. He was the
best center in the draft. We would not have taken Katzenmoyer. In
our opinion, what you see is what you get. We looked at his film
for three years, and he is the same player he was as a freshman. It
makes you believe this is how good he is going to be. He had a
tremendous workout, an all-time workout, and that brought him back
in the eyes of some teams. But those kinds of workouts can be
dangerous. Faulk got taken where he should have. He's a Dave
Meggett kind of player. We like Tony George, but we think he will
be a backup player in this league, and not a starter. There is no
way we would have drafted Derrick Fletcher. The man is totally out
of shape. He will be a coach's nightmare. We thought about taking
Marcus Washington late; he was a seventh-round pick on our board.
And we would not have drafted either of the last two guys.'' Grade:
C.
</P>
<P>
   NFC GM No. 1: ``To end up with what they got, starting out with
11 picks and two in the first round, is terrible. We had Woody a
second-round pick, and we didn't see any reason why they traded up
to get him. The Giants weren't going to draft him. We just didn't
like the way Woody played his senior year. Katzenmoyer, same way, a
boom-or-bust guy. A year ago the kid would have been a Top 10 pick,
but after last season he is very questionable. We liked Faulk. He's
a spot player, 10 to 12 carries a game, some kick returns. He can
help them. We didn't like any of the players they drafted after
that. Tony George rated just about where they drafted him. Michael
Bishop is worth taking a shot at, but he has very low test scores.
With the number of picks they had, they just should have done
more.'' Grade: C minus.
</P>
<P>
   NFC GM No. 2: ``We liked Woody a lot. They got him right about
where we thought he might go, 18 to 22. He's big, fast, good feet,
and very athletic. We didn't understand the Katzenmoyer pick. Don't
they have enough linebackers already? We didn't like him because he
gets knocked off his feet too much. Faulk is good, but not great. I
call him a system runner. He just gets what is there, no more. We
like Fletcher, but he's a project. He had tremendous size and moves
well. He is a guy with a lot of upside, but right now he is just
too heavy and he has no motor. He doesn't give it to you two plays
in a row. We like Tony George. Overall, I like their top four guys
and think they can help them.'' Grade: B.
</P>
<P>
   NFC GM No. 3: ``Woody is a talent, but he'll never be a great
player unless he learns to play harder and stay in shape. He was
not in shape when our team worked him out. Katzenmoyer is a real
gamble. He has size, speed, and can hit, but he is green as grass.
Faulk's not a feature back, not your No. 1 guy. He can be effective
as a third-down guy or in the kick return game. Of the rest of the
guys they drafted, the only one we had some interest in was Marcus
Washington, because he has a lot of athletic ability, but so far he
has been an underachiever. On the whole, they should have done
better with so many picks, but the top three guys they drafted
should be able to help them.'' Grade: B.
</P>
<P>
   Their consensus was that the Patriots blew three picks trading
up to get Woody and Faulk when they didn't have to.
</P>
<P>
   Woody should be a very good player. Katzenmoyer has great
physical skills but seems to be getting worse instead of better.
Faulk can be an effective part-time player. The safeties, George
and Washington, are backup players; and Fletcher, Bishop, and Morey
have very little chance of being solid players in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   To set the record straight, the Patriots did talk to other teams
about including Terry Glenn in a trade if it could have brought
them Ricky Williams.
</P>
<P>
   What the Patriots tried to do was to fill in the holes left by
the injury to Robert Edwards and the free agency defections of
center Dave Wohlabaugh and linebacker Todd Collins. The drafting of
two safeties seems to indicate that they are ready to get rid of
ones they have.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
