<HEADLINE>
FANS HOPE NIXON GETS GOING SOON 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-NIXON-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's happening much too soon for Red Sox outfielder
Trot Nixon. Only 11 games into the season, the same fans who
cheered him on Opening Day at Fenway Park last week were on his
case Sunday . . . big time.
</P>
<P>
   It is a message that Nixon must grasp quickly if he is to
survive in Boston. The fans are responding in part to a sudden dip
in the Red Sox' fortunes _ three losses in the last four starts
against the White Sox and Devil Rays. They are directing catcalls
his way, a strong reminder that his 0-for-9 slump on the homestand
has not gone unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   But No. 7 will be in right field Monday despite an .080 batting
average, because the Sox have a lot invested in him. There are no
plans to back away from the commitment first made to him in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his minor league career, Nixon has been an aggressive
competitor. The Red Sox are counting on Nixon's growth as a hitter
much like they counted on that of a young John Valentin or Nomar
Garciaparra. His stats have not been great, but they've been very
good, and who knows what could happen down the road?
</P>
<P>
   This is the next level, however. Nixon earned his shot by
batting .310 in 135 games at Pawtucket last year. He played 18
games in spring training and came north as the regular right
fielder. He was determined to do better. So don't think something
like a little early slump is going to stop him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to help the team win,'' he told a crowd of reporters
Sunday. ``Sometimes I try too hard when I go to the plate. But
that's just me. Perfection is what I want.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said in the past that this could be my downfall, but it's
hard to change something when you've been doing it since you were
15-16 years old. I don't know if it's healthy or not. But it's a
motivator.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon's luck hasn't been very good thus far this season. He has
lost four or five possible hits when he batted balls right at
people. He has struck out eight times in seven games, not good from
a man expected to help hold up the bottom half of the order. That
part of the order hasn't done well collectively, with center
fielder Darren Lewis benched Sunday (.167) as well as Donnie Sadler
(.174). All three contributed to the strong Sox hitting this
spring. Somebody has to step up.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing wrong with Trot,'' said hitting coach Jim
Rice. ``He's just got to go out and get some hits. A lot of guys
are not hitting. You just can't say Trot. This is Trot's first
year. He has to learn a little bit more about pitchers and about
himself. That's going to come. It's a little more work, but we're
not worried about that. What we have to do is build up his
confidence. If we didn't think he could do it, he wouldn't be here
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon doesn't think a lot of those fans who yelled insults. His
game preparation is excellent and he works hard on his offensive
and defensive skills. ``I don't care what the fans do,'' he said.
``I play for the team. I play for the fans, too, and the
organization, but if they're going to say something derogatory,
that just shows their class.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon says he often has agonized about his slow starts, and
things usually work themselves out. It helps that he is surrounded
by veterans like Valentin, who spoke to him privately after the
game for 15 minutes before the press got to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably try too hard during the game to make things
happen,'' said Nixon. ``It's always been mental, and I know you
can't afford to mentally defeat yourself. I don't feel like I'm
doing anything wrong at the plate. I just try to be perfect and see
every ball instead of just going out and attacking the ball. No
matter what happens, I've just got to keep going.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is funny. It can be going good, and then all of a
sudden you just crumble. It's a long season at times. But I try to
remain constant in that I go out and work just as hard the next
day. I want to prove I belong here. I'm going to keep working. I'm
not going to give up. I've been down these roads before. Somehow,
someway, it all turns around.''
</P>
<P>
   Sox manager Jimy Williams reserves the last word on Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think his numbers so far reflect how he's hit the
ball,'' Williams said. ``If you look at his last at-bat, he took
some good swings against a very good pitcher. Some good rips. To
me, the kid's a player. He is ready. Maybe it hasn't happened
enough for those people who write and who have microphones. I like
the kid a lot. I look at the person. I look at the man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
