<HEADLINE>
GALDERISI WEIGHS VALUE OF LOSSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ After a month of MLS games, the Revolution
have not yet lost in regulation time. But a victory over the
Columbus Crew Saturday might not have been as beneficial as the 0-0
regulation time result and shootout loss.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that was Giuseppe Galderisi's assessment after his
second match as unofficial assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't lose, and we were playing against a good team,''
Galderisi said. ``But maybe it would have been better if we had
lost because we played a bad first half. If we played a bad game
but won in the shootout, how can I be happy?
</P>
<P>
   ``In six months, 1 point more or 1 point less is not going to
change anything. We have to finish ahead of two teams and we will
be in the playoffs. And for that, we need to play better.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Revolution never have had a winning record since
being founded in 1996, even adding in the successes in shootouts.
The team has earned 102 points in 100 games, second lowest per-game
average in MLS. The team's official records of 15-17, 15-17, and
11-21 have been deceptive, especially since the core of the defense
was stripped away with the loss of Francis Okaroh to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Player-coach Walter Zenga and Galderisi have been attempting to
restore the team's confidence, as well as its defensive
organization. Though the Revolution have earned only 3 points from
four games, they have outscored the opposition, 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   And this is one of the toughest stretches of the year for the
Revolution, since they will meet D.C. United for the second time in
two weeks Saturday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Galderisi's status remains unclear as contract
negotiations continue. The Revolution likely will get their money's
worth from Galderisi, no matter the price.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in this team, but we need time, we need to work,''
Galderisi said. ``It's going to take more than two hours a day. We
might need to train six hours a day. And if we need to, we will
work in the night, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to work on everything, physical, tactical, technical.
Mostly, it is mental. The mind is the most important thing, not the
legs. The littlest things can affect the confidence. One little
thing can totally change the mentality of the team. And this is
what the team needs to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no goals scored in the Columbus game, only the fifth
time that both teams have failed to score in the Revolution's
history. But there were several crisis points to provide drama.
Zenga's extraordinary goalkeeping kept the Revolution in contention
in the first half. Then, midfielder Edwin Gorter volatilely
confronted Galderisi after being substituted early in the second
half, one of the few outward signs of potential discord on the
team.
</P>
<P>
   Though Gorter was sparking midfield play, the Revolution seemed
more comfortable without him. They were less threatening
offensively but more compact defensively, raising questions about
the direction and dynamics of the team. Things could be further
complicated by the expected return of Imad Baba (groin) this week
and John Harkes (knee ligament) for the visit of Colorado May 1,
when the Revolution are expected to attract the millionth fan for a
regular-season match; their home attendance is 987,265 after a
crowd of 14,732 for Columbus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
