<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-WIZARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALKER LOST IN CELTICS' WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rick Pitino is busy adding favorite wins to his
list. Friday night's comeback over Miami was one. Sunday's had to
be another (even though he may have lost captain Antoine Walker for
the season with an ankle sprain).
</P>
<P>
   With two starters (Kenny Anderson, Ron Mercer) out and a third
(Walker) gone after 5 1/2 minutes, the Celtics still hung on for a
wire-to-wire, 101-98 victory over the Wizards before 14,964 at the
MCI Center. The Celtics came close to reprising Miami's el foldo
Friday, looking more and more like Harold Lloyd hanging onto the
clock hands as Washington closed within a point. But a last-gasp
Wizards possession yielded only a Chris Whitney no-hoper.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino said he was ``remarkably shocked and pleasantly
surprised'' by the outcome. It was Boston's sixth win in eight
games and second over the Wizards in 11 days. But it also was
costly. The team's leading scorer sprained his left ankle after
making a layup and won't be back anytime soon. Monday's game at the
FleetCenter against Indiana will mark the first time he has missed
a game in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Making up for the MIAs were rookie Paul Pierce, who matched his
season high of 26 points, and Walter McCarty, who had 16 points and
eight rebounds in his first feel-good game of the year. Four other
Celtics were in double figures including Vitaly Potapenko, who made
two big free throws down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   However, Potapenko was the only Celtic who did make freebies and
that almost cost them the game. Comfortably ahead throughout by as
many as 17 and by 10 with 2:12 to go, the Celtics almost ``donated
one to charity,'' as Robert Parish would say. The Wizards cut a
91-81 Boston lead to 99-98 with 12.6 seconds left thanks to four
missed free throws and some last-minute heroics by Mitch Richmond
(13 points in the fourth) and Whitney (a parabolic trey).
</P>
<P>
   McCarty then was fouled and missed both. ``They felt good,
especially the second one,'' he said. The rebound was knocked out
of bounds and the ball was awarded to Washington. Rod Strickland
(12 assists) tried to penetrate, but was cut off. He got the ball
to Whitney, whose off-balance bomb barely grazed the rim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to make something happen,'' said Strickland.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was surprised Boston won given the manpower
situation, Strickland said, ``We don't have any manpower either.''
Washington was without Juwan Howard (ankle) and Terry Davis (shin
bruise). Its best center all year has been 53-year-old general
manager Wes Unseld.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce was sensational in taking over the offense in the first
half, scoring 19 points. He also had five steals. But he was held
to just four shots and two hoops in the second half. The Celtics,
who shot out to a 26-9 lead in the first 10 minutes, led by 10 at
each of the first three checkpoints and by 14 after a McCarty layup
with 8:05 left.
</P>
<P>
   McCarty, Greg Minor (13 points), Potapenko (15), and Dana Barros
(11) alternated keeping the team afloat as every Wizard thrust was
met by a countering Celtics parry until the last two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to keep it interesting,'' Barros said.
</P>
<P>
   They did do that. The fourth quarter took 51 minutes to play
because of all the free throws (34) and timeouts (four by each
team). The Celtics thought they had things in hand, but should have
known better.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing an opposing coach likes to see less than
Strickland with the ball, time running out, and the game on the
line. The Hoop God smiled on the Celtics again, however.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino will take the win. He's not so sure how many more of
these finishes he can take.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
