<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CHESS GAME, PATRIOTS MAKE NICE BISHOP MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Drew Bledsoe isn't in danger of losing his
starting job in the immediate future, but the Patriots drafted
young quarterback Michael Bishop Sunday. He runs, he's mobile, and
he's the second black quarterback ever drafted by the franchise.
(Jay Walker was the first).
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Heisman Trophy runner-up Bishop, a
6-foot-1-inch, 200-pounder, in the seventh round highlighted the
Patriots' second day of the NFL draft. New England, which was
without a fourth-round pick, selected Baylor offensive lineman
Derrick Fletcher in the fifth round, Colorado defensive back Marcus
Washington in the sixth, and Bishop and Brown receiver Sean Morey
in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why a Heisman runner-up would slip to the final round,
Bishop said, ``I'm not concerned about what other people think
about that. There are a lot of great players taken in the later
rounds, and I appreciate the chance to do it for the Patriots.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop, who runs a 4.71 40-yard dash, will not have an offense
designed to take advantage of his skills, but coach Pete Carroll
said if the team has to use him, he will bring unique talents to
the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a chance to bring a change of pace to our quarterback
game,'' said Carroll. ``If you've watched Kansas State games you
can see the great offense they built around him and all of the
things he can do. He has tremendous arm strength, he can run, and
he can scramble and use the whole field.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said he would not use Bishop as the Pittsburgh Steelers
used Kordell Stewart early in his career as a third-down
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't use him like that, but when he has the chance to play
he'll bring some unique aspects to our game,'' said Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop, one of several black quarterbacks drafted, including
Donovan McNabb No. 2 overall and Akili Smith No. 3, said, ``You
look at the whole college level and it means a lot to get the
opportunity to show the nation and the world how many great black
college quarterbacks there are.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop said he thinks he had the versatility to catch passes,
play safety, or run with the ball, but the Patriots don't have
those plans for him. They want him to spend this season learning
the system.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher, 6-6 1/2, 374 pounds, is considered a physical wonder.
He runs a 5.25 40, which makes him one of the quickest offensive
linemen in college football. He may have lasted until the fifth
round because there is some question about his consistency and
effort.
</P>
<P>
   There's also some question as to whether he's a guard or a
tackle. He played both at Baylor, last year seeing all of his
action at tackle, but the Patriots are looking at him as a guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has big upside,'' said Carroll. Fletcher is a former
defensive lineman who was a part-time nose tackle in his first two
years until moving to offense his junior year.
</P>
<P>
   The problem? Fletcher has some trouble controlling his weight.
He said his ideal playing weight is 340 or less, but when asked his
current weight he said he weighed 370.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weight is not a problem,'' insisted the physical education and
health major. ``I know I can shed the weight.''
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher says he's an excellent run blocker and believes his
main attributes are ``power and quickness. I think I'm a smart
player. I analyze and think a lot to help myself and my
teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher said he was at first apprehensive about his move to
offense two years ago, but is now glad he made the switch. He said
a coaching change at Baylor led to the change.
</P>
<P>
   At the scouting combine in Indianapolis, Fletcher was very
impressive with his 40 times. But on his second attempt he pulled a
hamstring. Fletcher said he's just about recovered and is now able
to run.
</P>
<P>
   With No. 1 pick Damien Woody, a center, the Patriots may be
pushing veterans Todd Rucci and Zefross Moss, who have big
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, the 180th player taken, played cornerback and free
safety at Colorado and it appears as if he'll be a free safety.
That gives the Patriots two young free safety types; they also
drafted Florida's Tony George, and that may not bode well for
incumbent backup Chris Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, a shade under 6-2 and 220 pounds, started two games
at corner and seven at free safety. He has decent speed, and is an
aggressive player who can bump at the line of scrimmage, but it
doesn't appear he'll challenge Steve Israel, Chris Canty, or
Tebucky Jones for playing time.
</P>
<P>
   He is in a decent position, however, since Willie Clay is in the
final year of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see an opportunty for myself no matter where I was drafted
because I think I'm a pretty good player,'' said Washington, who
once roomed with Patriots linebacker Ron Merkerson with the
Buffaloes. ``I'm not a one-dimensional player. I can go out there
and play anywhere in the secondary. I love to play. Anywhere I
would have ended up, I see an opportunity for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington said he didn't have any contact with the Patriots
after the combine, ``but I had a great meeting with Coach Carroll
at the combine and I can't wait to wear the red, white and blue. I
can't wait to see Mr. Bledsoe again. His younger brother (Adam)
plays at Colorado. He and I are pretty good friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have liked Morey for the past couple of years. He
worked out for New England two weeks ago and Carroll came away with
the feeling he'd like to have him around.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings an obvious attitude about the game,'' said Carroll.
``He has a real knack for adjusting back on balls. We'll use him on
special teams and then see what he can do as he learns the
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Morey, who originally wanted to go to Boston College, said ``I'm
going to do whatever it takes to do the things the Patriots want me
to do. I've worked with the same speed coach (Mike Morris) they
have, so I understand some of the things they emphasize.''
</P>
<P>
   Morey said he dreamed of a chance to play for the Patriots, but
he didn't know whether he'd be drafted or signed after the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was confident to get an opportunity to play,'' he said. ``I
knew I had a chance to be drafted and I knew I'd get a chance
either way. I have a lot of goals and aspirations for this game and
this is the start of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
