<HEADLINE>
SAMUEL, AZUMAH BEAR UP WELL 
</HEADLINE>
 DRAFT-NEW ENGLAND-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ When the NFL draft entered its second and
final day on Sunday, Mark Hatley, the director of pro personnel for
the Chicago Bears, said it was his team's intention to stock its
roster with the best athletes available.
</P>
<P>
   By the fifth round, Hatley adhered to that
best-athlete-available theory when the Bears landed two of the best
the Atlantic 10 Conference had to offer: University of
Massachusetts linebacker Khari Samuel, who was selected with the
144th pick, and University of New Hampshire running back Jerry
Azumah, who was taken three picks later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny, it definitely is,'' said Samuel, who was a
defensive ringleader of the Minutemen's national championship team
last season. ``But it's good, too. A couple of small-school guys
are going to be up there watching each other's back. I feel good
about that also. He grew up in Worcester and I grew up in
Framingham; we're two Massachusetts guys, so it's going to be a
good situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Massachusetts native son, Marc Megna of Fall River,
became the third A-10 player selected when he was taken in the
sixth round by the New York Jets with the 183d pick. Megna was a
linebacker at Richmond. Rounding out the New England selections was
Sean Morey of Brown, who won't be going very far to try his hand
professionally, because the Patriots drafted him in the seventh
round (see Patriots' story, Page D13).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very excited about it (being selected), because it's been
a dream of mine ever since high school to be able to play
professional football,'' said Megna, who was overlooked in high
school and received only one scholarship offer. Last season the
6-foot-3-inch, 255-pounder was recognized as Defensive Player of
the Year. ``Coach (Jim) Reid was the only one who gave me a chance,
and I'm so grateful that he did,'' said Megna. ``Now I'll have a
chance to play for a Bill Parcells, who's one of the most
respected, if not the most respected, coach in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   To Azumah, a 5-10, 198-pounder who rushed for 2,282 yards and 22
TDs last season to win the Walter Payton Award as the nation's best
Division 1-AA player, it was ironic he wound up with the Bears,
where Payton began and ended his Hall of Fame career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like a little coincidence, but to me it's a nice
fit,'' said Azumah, who wowed scouts at the NFL combine with his
speed and 43-inch vertical leap. ``I'm just glad I'll be getting
the opportunity. I'm just kind of speechless right now. I just want
to take full advantage of it and whatever happens happens, so
hopefully good things will happen. I'm not sure exactly where they
want me to play yet.''
</P>
<P>
   There was some speculation that, because of Azumah's
athleticism, he might be a better pro prospect at cornerback. And
while he was not totally opposed to the idea, he did indicate,
``I've never played the position before, so I'm inexperienced at
that. At (New Hampshire), I never ran backwards a day in my life,
so it's going to be something new, but I'm sure I'll adjust if they
need me to.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had talked to the Bears about the possibility of
playing running back, Azumah said, ``I haven't talked to them
specifically about that. Today was a day where we talked about
flight reservations and things like that, because we'll be coming
in this weekend. I'm not exactly sure what's going to happen, but
I'll find out when I get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty sure they'll give me that chance (to run the
football),'' he added. ``It's what I did best in college.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the 6-2, 242-pound Samuel? His strongest suit in college
was his toughness and his ability to play from sideline to
sideline, which has been a hallmark of the Bears' long and
illustrious line of linebackers. ``Definitely, and that's another
reason why I like the situation,'' he said. ``I'm proud to be able
to go there and to experience that. I'm really, really excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it will help to have a familiar face in Azumah. Asked
if he had any messages for the New Hampshire star, Samuel laughed
and said, ``See you in Chicago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
