<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS' PROBLEMS MULTIPLY 
</HEADLINE>
 DRAFT-AFC EAST-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Throughout an interminably long offseason,
nothing good happened to the New England Patriots. While the Miami
Dolphins, New York Jets, and Indianapolis Colts kept improving with
free agent signings, the best the Patriots could do was stand pat.
Unfortunately, they couldn't even manage that for long.
</P>
<P>
   Fate and finances entered into the AFC East equation and New
England lost center Dave Wohlabaugh to the expansion Browns and
punter Tom Tupa to the hated Jets, and, in the cruelest blow,
running back Robert Edwards went involuntarily into civilian life
with a likely career-ending knee injury only a month after
completing a rookie year in which he rushed for more than 1,000
yards.
</P>
<P>
   With everyone else in the hyper-competitive AFC East improving
one way or another, New England's hydra-headed braintrust of Pete
Carroll, Bobby Grier, Andy Wasynczuk, and Bob Kraft couldn't wait
for Draft Day to come because, with two first-round choices and 11
picks overall, it was at last a chance to do SOMETHING.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two days, they succeeded in that. Unfortunately
for them, so did the Colts, Dolphins, Bills, and maybe even the
Jets, which leaves New England improved but facing a divisional
landscape greatly altered in an uphill way since the end of last
season. Here is a look at how all five teams fared:
</P>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Nobody in the division has improved more, but
that figured because the Colts had the furthest to go. Yet general
manager Bill Polian took a major gamble the week of the draft by
unloading three-time Pro Bowl running back Marshall Faulk and then
bypassing Heisman Trophy winner Ricky Williams in favor of Miami's
Edgerrin James.
</P>
<P>
   Faulk was coming off the best year of his career, rushing for
1,319 yards and catching 88 passes for another 908, but he created
bad blood with Polian by claiming late last season to have found a
contractual loophole that would make him a free agent if he
finished among the league's top five rushers.
</P>
<P>
   Polian disputed that and got his legendary dander up. Although
it became a moot point when Faulk fell 13 yards short, when he
continued to talk of renegotiating with two years left on his
contract, Polian traded him. Then he shocked the draft world by
taking James, who was rated on par with Williams by many but
started only 17 college games while Williams rushed for more than
6,200 yards at Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Polian liked James's pass-catching skills and believed he was a
better fit for the Colts' offensive approach than the power-running
Williams, who had averaged seven fumbles a year at Texas. If James
fills Faulk's shoes, this was a bold move. If Faulk shines in St.
Louis and Williams becomes the next Earl Campbell in New Orleans,
Polian never will live it down.
</P>
<P>
   After taking James, Polian continued the rebuilding of one of
the worst defenses in football, grabbing tackling machine
linebacker Mike Peterson on the second round. Every scout who went
to Florida to watch Jevon Kearse came away noticing Peterson made
more plays even though he is only 224 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Guard prospect Brandon Burlsworth followed, and he could compete
for a starting job this season. After that third-round selection,
the draft becomes a crapshoot, but the landing of Peterson in
particular adds help and production where Indianapolis needed it
most. Added to free agents Chad Bratzke (defensive end with 11
sacks for the Giants last season), Shawn King (defensive end),
Cornelius Bennett (linebacker), and Chad Cota (safety), it means an
entirely revamped defensive look for the Colts, and they needed
one.
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Jimmy Johnson wanted one thing out of this draft and he
got it: a power running game.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins artfully traded down twice to get out of the first
round and still landed three of the draft's top half-dozen backs,
getting James Johnson and Syracuse fullback Rob Konrad at the top
of the second round and Cecil Collins in the fifth plus a total of
1,600 pounds of new offensive firepower.
</P>
<P>
   First they grabbed Johnson, a back the Patriots coveted, then
the 251-pound Konrad, the top-rated fullback, and finally the
troubled but vastly talented Collins, who could become a superstar
or a car wreck. All can catch the ball out of the backfield, and
any one could solve a major problem in Miami. A year ago, the
Dolphins were the worst short-yardage team in football, and that
caught up with them several times in close games. Johnson had to do
something about it and he did, adding three big runners with
potential and 300-pound No. 3 pick Grey Ruegamer.
</P>
<P>
   When you add that tonnage to Johnson's offseason acquisitions,
you get a lot of suet. Johnson previously signed 330-pound free
agent guard Kevin Gogan, 240-pound fullback Roosevelt Potts,
234-pound back Tyrone Wheatley, and 250-pound tight end Hunter
Goodwin. Add another 1,600 pounds on draft day and it's a load. If
Johnson and Konrad are more successful in short yardage than Karim
Abdul-Jabbar and John Avery, the Dolphins have the look of a
contender. If Collins pans out, they're more dangerous than that.
</P>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ Like New England, the Bills had to wait until the
draft to add anything of note, and when their time came they got
exactly the player they wanted in Ohio State cornerback Antoine
Winfield.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the other stars on the Buckeyes, Winfield was the
team's MVP and the winner of the Jim Thorpe Award as the nation's
No. 1 collegiate defensive back. Champ Bailey and Chris McAlister
were both rated ahead of Winfield by pro scouts because Winfield is
only 5 feet 9 inches, but the Bills like shorter, quicker defensive
backs and they got one who not only can cover but willingly knocks
your block off in run support.
</P>
<P>
   General manager John Butler then might have gotten one of the
best bargains in the draft in Tennessee wide receiver Peerless
Price on the second round. With Quinn Early gone and Andre Reed
beginning to age, Price will have an opportunity to step in and
contribute and he may have the skill and hands to do it. Some
scouts questioned him because he often seems off balance, but he
made his biggest plays in Tennessee's biggest games.
</P>
<P>
   After that, things slowed down in Buffalo, but the Bills didn't
need much to improve. Winfield shores up a weakness in the
secondary and Price gives them depth where only Reed and Eric
Moulds were productive. Add to that the fact Buffalo has the best
quarterback situation in the division with Doug Flutie and Rob
Johnson, and the Bills seem as sound as a year ago. If Price pays
off, they'll be more than that.
</P>
<P>
   NY JETS _ The Jets finally finished paying off the ransom for
Bill Parcells, which meant they had no No. 1 pick and not much
chance to improve themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that, Parcells was very active in free agency, adding
eight-time Pro Bowl safety Steve Atwater, solid run-stuffing
linebacker Roman Phifer, punter Tom Tupa, and 280-pound tight end
Eric Green. Green's bulk gives the Jets another tackle on the
field, for all intents and purposes, and Parcells tried to add to
that by drafting guard prospects Randy Thomas and David Loverne
with second- and third-round choices. Thomas is more of a finesse
player than Parcells would like, but at 300-plus pounds he won't be
for long.
</P>
<P>
   If Thomas or Loverne start at guard, Parcells will have done all
he could with a draft that left him few options but to watch for
too long.
</P>
<P>
   NEW ENGLAND _ Stymied by salary cap problems and bad luck, the
Patriots couldn't do much to help themselves until this weekend and
they succeeded, even though they couldn't swing a trade to get
James or Williams.
</P>
<P>
   They managed first to replace departed center Dave Wohlabaugh
with the one guy scouts say is capable of stepping in and starting
at center this year, Boston College's Damien Woody. They traded up
three spots to do it, and whether that was necessary or not is moot
because they didn't want all 11 picks anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Woody has to play immediately for this to really pay off, and
New England is counting on that. If he does, the Patriots move
Heath Irwin to right guard, Max Lane to right tackle, and improve a
line that looked like a weak link after Wohlabaugh left.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of tiny LSU runner Kevin Faulk on the second round
gives them a third-down back who has shown he can catch the ball,
which is important in Ernie Zampese's offense. Whether he is an
every-down back who can replace Edwards is questionable, but New
England signed veteran backup Lamont Warren Saturday as insurance
and likely will sign another veteran in June, after teams release
players for salary cap relief.
</P>
<P>
   Florida safety Tony George, a third-round pick, was another
``just in case'' kind of move. He has played both corner and safety
but is projected as the latter and will be groomed to possibly
replace veteran Willie Clay, who will be a free agent at the end of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   New England may have gotten lucky or may have made a huge
blunder with the final Parcells Pick, however, taking Ohio State
linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer with the No. 28 pick. If Katzenmoyer
plays the way he did his first two years at OSU, he'll be a major
addition. If he plays the way he did last year, he won't play much.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are banking on the former, believing Katzenmoyer's
production was affected by the off-field controversy over his
questionable academic performance and a change in the way he was
asked to attack the line of scrimmage. He was considered a top-10
pick just a year ago and still has the size, speed, and strength to
justify those opinions. All he has to do is play up to his physical
gifts and he'll start at weak-side linebacker next to Ted Johnson,
which is why this pick was made.
</P>
<P>
   With Todd Collins gone, New England kept insisting Tedy Bruschi
could step in full-time even though he showed when he had to last
year he couldn't hold up. He is an undersized role player who can
be productive in the right situation. The right situation is not
playing every down. Enter Katzenmoyer.
</P>
<P>
   If Woody and Katzenmoyer start and Faulk plays effectively
enough to keep Edwards's name out of the papers while he's in
street clothes, this will have been the draft Grier was hoping for.
</P>
<P>
   Of the five teams, Indianapolis took the biggest Draft Day
gamble, the Jets did the least, Buffalo improved, and Miami found a
new set of widebodies with which to try and create a running game
Jimmy Johnson can be proud of. But the team that may have done the
most was the Patriots. Whether it was enough to counter all the
other moves by their division rivals is a matter to be decided on
another day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 0246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
