<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 04:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3759 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWEATSHOP-REFORM-SFCH     04-19 1475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEATSHOP-REFORM-SFCHRON(W/UNIVERSITY) </SLUG>
  
 U.S. APPAREL COMPANIES STARTING TO CUT DOWN ON ABUSES  &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Prodded by controversy over exploitation in the
foreign factories that make much of America's clothes and shoes,
major corporations and universities have turned the tables by
pushing for sweatshop reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Nike and Reebok, long the targets of criticism, are now raising
their foreign wages, improving working conditions and defending
human-rights advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of universities nationwide have jumped on the bandwagon,
reacting to a growing student protest movement by taking steps to
bar labor abuses in the manufacture of clothes that bear college
logos.
</P>
<P>
   The moves have boosted a new White House-sponsored alliance, the
Fair Labor Association, which its backers say is the only feasible
way to raise standards in the complex factory networks that now
form the core of global free trade.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not surprisingly, all these changes have produced yet
more controversy. Some anti-sweatshop activists call them cynical
attempts to prevent real reform, while many corporations view them
as liberal meddling in the boardroom. But either way, the
initiatives may have a lasting effect on the U.S. public debate
over foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the changes have come in a rush, including the
following:
</P>
<P>
   --Wages. Nike and Reebok have raised wages and benefits in their
Indonesian footwear factories, which employ a total of more than
100,000 workers, making base compensation 43 percent higher than
the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   --Working conditions. Nike is cooperating with independent
monitors to end health and safety problems at its 37 shoe factories
in Vietnam and other nations. Dara O'Rourke, a Berkeley expert who
embarrassed Nike in 1997 with a highly publicized expose of one of
its Vietnam factories, revisited the plant and issued a report last
month March  &LR; verifying major improvements.
</P>
<P>
   --Human rights. Reebok and Nike have taken unprecedented steps
to defend labor rights activists who have long been their
adversaries. In January, Reebok sent a letter to Indonesian
President B.J. Habibie urging the release of imprisoned labor
leader Dita Sari. Last month, Nike publicly repudiated a top
executive, Vice President Joseph Ha, after he criticized Vietnam
labor activists _ criticism that in previous years would have been
considered routine.
</P>
<P>
   --Fair Labor Association. Fifty-six universities, including the
seven Ivy League schools, the University of Southern California,
Santa Clara University and California State University at
Sacramento, have joined the FLA, a White House-sponsored alliance
of human rights groups and corporations such as Nike, Reebok, Liz
Claiborne and Phillips-Van Heusen that is setting up an elaborate,
worldwide factory monitoring system to try to eliminate sweatshop
abuses.
</P>
<P>
   --Youth initiative. Nike, Mattel, the World Bank and the
Baltimore-based International Youth Foundation have founded the
Global Alliance for Workers and Communities, a vaguely defined, $10
million project to ``enhance the lives'' of young workers in
clothing, toy and athletic footwear factories in Indonesia,
Thailand, China and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime critics say these steps leave much to be desired. For
example, the Indonesia wage raises by Nike and Reebok put total
minimum compensation at only 20 U.S. cents an hour, less than what
is needed to support a family and well below the 27 cents per hour
that Nike paid until Indonesia's currency devaluations and economic
crisis began two years ago. But the moves are a good start, the
critics say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that industry leaders are taking these new steps, as
insufficient as they are, is because so much public pressure has
been put on them,'' said Medea Benjamin, co-director of Global
Exchange, a San Francisco group that has spearheaded a nationwide
campaign against Nike in recent years. ``It's a sign of real
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   The FLA was formed in November after three years of organizing
and arm-twisting by the Clinton administration. Its rules for
member companies' foreign factories include the freedom to organize
unions and bans on child labor, forced or prison labor, and
physical abuse by supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   By 2001, after its monitoring system has been operating for a
year, participating companies will be able to use the FLA logo on
their labels and in their advertising, helping portray the firms as
cutting-edge, ethical corporate citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Ethics-minded consumers, in turn, will be able to look for the
FLA logo while shopping to guarantee that what they buy is free of
moral stigma.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FLA isn't perfect, but it's a move in the right direction,
and the important thing is that it's on the ground and it exists,''
said Maria Eitel, a Nike vice president who is in charge of the
company's reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Eitel applauded the 56 universities' decisions to join the FLA.
In fact, Nike had pressured the universities to join the FLA, which
the company apparently sees as a means of helping its bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Nike and Reebok saw their profits fall 37 percent and
65 percent, respectively. Company executives blame the drop mainly
on the overall slump in U.S. athletic footwear sales, which fell an
estimated 9 percent, but also on negative publicity from the
sweatshop controversy. Company executives now hope the FLA logo
will improve their products' image and boost sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Footwear and apparel are incredibly competitive industries,
but strengthening the FLA and making it viable will help us, too,''
Eitel said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the FLA's emphasis on foreign exploitation, sweatshops
remain alive and well in the United States. They were prevalent in
the U.S. garment and footwear industry until around World War II,
when pressure from social reformers, union organizing and new
federal wage-and-hour laws caused dramatic improvements in working
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But by the 1990s, increasing competition brought by free trade
created a new system of contractors and subcontractors at home and
abroad _ mainly in Mexico and Southeast Asia _ that undermined
wages and working conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The apparel industry, with annual U.S. retail sales of $70
billion, and the footwear industry, with $36 billion, now make only
45 percent and 7 percent, respectively, of their products in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, U.S. Department of Labor inspections of garment
contractors found violations of wage-and-hours laws at 61 percent
of factories in Los Angeles and at 63 percent of factories in New
York, the nation's two largest garment centers. (In the Bay Area,
however, where local garment firms have cooperated with federal
regulators, the rate of violations was only 13 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say the apparel and footwear industries may be too
complicated and politically powerful to be fully reformed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are powerful, intractable economic forces at work in the
sweatshop issue,'' said John Dunlop, a Harvard professor who was
secretary of labor under President Gerald Ford. ``If we can't
eradicate sweatshops and child labor at home, how do you think
we're going to do it for Indonesia or Bangladesh?''
</P>
<P>
   In Sacramento, some lawmakers are trying to reform California's
own sweatshops. A major labor-law reform bill, sponsored by
Assemblyman Darrell Steinberg, D-Sacramento, would make garment
manufacturers and retailers with their own fashion labels jointly
liable for labor violations at their contractors' factories.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is backed by labor unions and by Latino and
Asian-American organizations. But it is opposed by the apparel
industry and by major retail stores, which are big campaign donors
to Republicans and Democrats alike.
</P>
<P>
   Similar legislation was vetoed in 1990 by Governor George
Deukmejian and in 1992 and 1994 by Governor Pete Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Ilse Metchek, executive director of the California Fashion
Association, an industry group in Los Angeles, warned that this
year's bill would cause garment manufacturers to move to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this bill passes, it would drive the industry out of the
state,'' she said. ``It would create unlimited civil liability for
real and imagined labor violations. It would be a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill cleared a key hurdle April 7 winning approval by the
Assembly Committee on Labor and Employment on a 6-to-2, party-line
vote, with Democrats in favor and Republicans opposed. It now goes
to the Assembly Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Activists say the overall reform process will be long and
complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweatshops were eradicated once in the United States through
decades of organizing and passing legislation,'' Benjamin said.
``It will take a protracted struggle _ a global one this time _ to
eradicate this new wave of sweatshops.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 0414EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 04:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3760 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLDMAN-AWARDS-SFCHRO     04-19 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDMAN-AWARDS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 7 WIN TOP ENVIRONMENTAL PRIZE
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By GLEN MARTIN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ A Burmese activist who publicized human
rights abuses and rain forest destruction in Southeast Asia and a
Newfoundland commercial fisherman who campaigned against the
overexploitation of global fisheries are among the seven recipients
of the 1999 Goldman Environmental Prize, the world's most
prestigious environmental award.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the winners _ collectively representing six continents _
will receive $125,000, with the exception of two co-recipients from
Australia, who will share a prize.
</P>
<P>
   The prize is awarded annually by the Goldman Environmental
Foundation, a San Francisco organization devoted to grassroots
environmental activism.
</P>
<P>
   The award was established in 1989 by philanthropists Richard and
Rhoda Goldman. Winners are selected from anonymous nominations
submitted by 21 environmental organizations and a confidential
panel of consultants representing 50 countries.
</P>
<P>
   One of the winners is Ka Hsaw Wa, 28, a member of Burma's
minority Karen community who has spent several years hiding in the
rain forests of Burma and Thailand documenting human rights abuses
and environmental destruction reportedly conducted by members of
Burma's military junta.
</P>
<P>
   Ka Hsaw Wa _ meaning White Elephant in Burmese _ is a nom de
guerre for the prizewinner, adopted because he fears reprisals from
government authorities if he uses his real name.
</P>
<P>
   He was arrested and tortured for three days by soldiers in 1988
when he joined massive student protests against military rule in
Burma. The demonstrations ended in a bloody crackdown, and Ka Hsaw
Wa fled to the forests near the Thai border.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he has led an incognito existence, reporting on the
plight of indigenous people who say they have suffered abuses
ranging from expulsion to murder of family members by soldiers in
the employ of logging and petroleum companies. He said
international corporations are decimating Burma's pristine forests
and abundant wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terribly sad,'' he said. ``We've found tigers that have
either been shot by the soldiers or killed by land mines.''
</P>
<P>
   He will provide testimony next year in a U.S. District Court
case charging Unocal and other companies with human rights and
environmental abuses in a gas pipeline construction project
traversing Thailand and Burma.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian commercial fisherman Bernard Martin, 45, won a prize
for founding an organization of family fishers opposing large
``factory'' trawlers.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, a fourth-generation fisherman, predicted the collapse of
the Grand Banks cod fishery several years before it occurred in
1992, a situation widely blamed on ``strip mining'' of the sea
floor by huge trawlers of the international fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Martin has been travelling the world advising other
communities on fisheries conservation.
</P>
<P>
   He is also working on programs designed to reduce the threat of
``ghost nets'' _ lost or abandoned gill nets that float the seas,
entangling and killing marine creatures indiscriminately.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said Canadian cod stocks are slowly recovering thanks to
tough regulations, but that other species are now subjected to
excessive pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government is still allowing the overfishing of capelin, a
small fish popular in Japan but critical as a food source to a wide
variety of commercial and sport fish, including cod and Atlantic
salmon,'' he said. ``The problem isn't the small, inshore line or
seine fleets _ it's the huge deep-sea trawlers. They're a
scourge.''
</P>
<P>
   The other winners are:
</P>
<P>
   _Jacqui Katona, 33, and Yvonne Margarula, 41, two Australian
aboriginal women who have led a fight against the mining of a huge
uranium deposit surrounded by Kakadu National Park, the country's
largest park and a United Nations-designated World Heritage Site.
The mine is located on lands owned for millennia by the Mirrar
aboriginal people.
</P>
<P>
   Katona said the battle against the mine has been tough, but that
it has galvanized the country's aborigines and environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say to fight on, win or lose,'' she said. ``It's about
our heritage and our integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   _Samuel Nguiffo, a Cameroon lawyer who is fighting in his
country's courts to stop the liquidation of the world's
second-largest contiguous rain forest and the slaughter of
chimpanzees and other rare wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Nguiffo travels Cameroon's forests to keep indigenous tribes
apprised of their rights, and he is trying to obtain guarantees
from the Cameroon government that a planned oil pipeline from Chad
won't result in increased logging, social dislocation and marine
pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have to understand that many of the trees that are
targeted by loggers are terribly important to villagers for food,
building materials and even as sacred sites,'' he said. ``Their
traditional value essentially supersedes their commercial value.''
</P>
<P>
   _Jorge Varela, a Honduran conservationist who is successfully
fighting destructive shrimp farming practices in Honduras' Gulf of
Fonseca.
</P>
<P>
   Once one of the richest fishing grounds in Central America, the
Gulf has lost much of its biodiversity because shrimp farmers have
stripped it of mangrove forests, which serve as nurseries for a
wide array of species.
</P>
<P>
   Varela formed a conservation group that successfully pressured
the Honduran government to institute a moratorium on new shrimp
farms, form an oversight agency for the industry and establish fish
and wildlife refuges on some of the Gulf's lagoons.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a worldwide problem,'' he said. ``Industrial shrimp
are cheap to buy, but they come at tremendous environmental cost.
The real price is too much to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   _Michal Kravcik, a Slovakian hydrologist who successfully fought
a government plan to build a large dam on the Upper Torysa River to
provide drinking water for East Slovakia's cities. The dam would
have forced the evacuation of four villages.
</P>
<P>
   Kravcik gained widespread grassroots support by promoting an
alternative plan that relied on ``microbasins'' and a series of
weirs and small dams. As a result of local opposition, the
government cancelled plans for the Torysa River dam in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're now working on a sustainable development program for 24
villages,'' said Kravcik. ``We have a new prime minister who is
sympathetic to us. The main problem is turning around some of the
old bureaucrats who are still in place.''  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 0415EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
