<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 04:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3765 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-HOSPITALS-SFCHRON     04-19 1473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-HOSPITALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HOSPITALS SAY THEY CAN BEAT THE MILLENNIUM BUG  &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ Despite some frightful warnings from Y2K
watchdogs, hospitals and other health services nationwide claim
they will be ready for nearly anything their computers might throw
at them January 1.
<P>
   Nobody can predict just what will happen when the calendar rolls
over to 2000. Archaic bits of date-deficient software often are
deeply embedded in computer systems, raising fears of cascading
shutdowns even if there's no outward sign of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The fears were not helped by a recent congressional review of
Y2K preparedness, which found that the health industry was woefully
behind in the race to search out and neutralize Y2K bugs.
Investigators plan  &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
c,12p2  &LR; to take a fresh look next month.
</P>
<P>
   But Fred Brown, chairman of the American Hospital Association,
offered assurances that the critical systems _ those that could
directly affect patient care _ will be bug-free in time.
</P>
<P>
   After a nationwide survey of hospitals last month, the trade
group concluded that only a tiny  &LR; fraction of mostly smaller
hospitals feared any serious Y2K meltdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Even if something does happen, all hospitals already are
required to have elaborate contingency plans, including backup
power generators, for any emergency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything to do with patient care certainly will be ready,''
Brown said. ``I'd be very comfortable being a patient on January
1.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals alone will have spent at least $8.2 billion on the Y2K
problem by the end of the year, according to the trade association.
In California, about $820 million is being spent to identify and
fix suspect computer systems and devices.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser Permanente, the Oakland-based HMO giant that provides
health care to about one in three Northern Californians, has about
1,000 employees, contractors and consultants working on Y2K
matters.
</P>
<P>
   Crews have had to deal with 139,000 pieces of medical equipment.
Some 4,200 had date-related coding problems and were either patched
with up-to-date software or junked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, everything is on track'' to be finished by year's
end, Kaiser spokesman Tom Debley said.
</P>
<P>
   Industrywide, most experts see little cause for alarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of dates are simply used for
record-keeping,'' said Allen Falcon, president of a Boston-based
technology consulting firm, Horizon Information Group, which has
produced a Y2K guide for small businesses. ``Pacemakers stopping,
microwave ovens exploding, elevators skyrocketing to the top of the
shaft _ these things just aren't going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite such reassurances, no one offers any absolute
guarantees. And some analysts insist that patients are not yet safe
from malfunctioning microchips.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Ackerman, executive director of Rx2000 Solutions Institute,
a nonprofit research organization based in Minneapolis, said
medical devices seem to have fewer Y2K problems than expected even
six months ago, but questions remain about drug manufacturing and
distribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a lot of risk out there,'' he said. ``I think
there will be some patients hurt by Y2K problems. Even if it's only
one computer chip in 1,000, or one in 10,000, or even one in
100,000,'' someone will be affected, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, devices that are Y2K compliant could malfunction
when networked with other devices, particularly if they use
different technical strategies for handling dates.
</P>
<P>
   Some problems may take months or even years to reveal &LR; 
themselves. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  And not every hospital can afford to test every device in
every conceivable situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are thousands of computer chips in every hospital,''
said Lori Aldrete, senior vice president at the California
Healthcare Association, a group of hospitals and health-care
networks. ``Even if a vendor tells you a particular model is Y2K
compliant, without testing each piece of equipment you really don't
know for sure. So it's been a huge job.''
</P>
<P>
   The much-feared millennium bug stems from software set up to
record dates in two-digit format only, such as ``76'' for the year
1976. Unless fixed, such programs can't distinguish 2000 from 1900.
</P>
<P>
   The list of imagined consequences reads like an excerpt from a
disaster-movie script: Cancer patients blasted with the wrong
dosage of radiation. Surgeons unable to rely on diagnostic
scanners. Ambulances sent to the wrong address.
</P>
<P>
   Medical experts say most such scenarios seem fanciful. ``There's
a lot of hype,'' said Dr. Vincent Riccardi, president of American
Medical Consumers Inc., a nonprofit health-advisory organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not clear to me that all these concerns are &LR; 
legitimate.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  If problems do occur, they are likely to be more annoying than
life-threatening, many experts say. A hospital elevator's automated
control system may shut down because it wrongly concludes that
service is 1,000 or so years overdue. Or, someone's medical bill
may be delayed or contain an error.
</P>
<P>
   Still, observers like Ackerman point to serious potential &LR; 
problems. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   , some involving interactions among different devices and &LR; 
computer systems. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   , often not from the same manufacturer. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Machines with more serious repercussions are being examined
for possible glitches, including bedside monitors that feed
information to nurses' stations; MRI units hooked to laser imagers;
terminals for ordering drugs that are drug-ordering &LR; 
terminals &LR; wired into central pharmacies; and hospital laboratory
computers that receive test results from outside labs.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller facilities tend to be the least prepared, hampered by &LR; 
tight budgets and less experienced in-house computer staff. But &LR; 
they also have the advantage of less technology-intensive &LR; 
operations _ and thus fewer things that can go wrong. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Tiny Surprise Valley Community Hospital in Modoc County, for &LR; 
example, does no high-tech diagnostic scanning, does no &LR;  surgeries
under general anesthesia and sends out most blood and &LR;  tissue
samples for analysis. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty much no-frills,'' said hospital administrator &LR; 
Joyce Gysin, adding that her staff tested all the hospital's own &LR; 
lab equipment and found no sign of any Y2K bugs lurking. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Suppliers, which stand to be liable should any preventable
problems occur, have shouldered much of the Y2K testing burden.
</P>
<P>
   Medtronic Inc., one of the nation's biggest medical-technology
companies, began checking its products in 1997 and found seven
product lines with Y2K-related problems that had to be fixed. as
well as software that would fix them. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  But  &LR; The most serious, according to Medtronic Y2K overseer
Mike Bars-ness, was a monitor that couldn't upload data properly if
it were running during the transition from December 31 to January
1. None of the errors were deemed critical to the safe operation of
any devices.
</P>
<P>
   Fear may turn out to be one of the biggest dangers _ and one
that can't be readily fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Internet Y2K sites are warning of widespread breakdowns in
transportation and communications networks that hospitals rely on
to get drug shipments.
</P>
<P>
   Drug companies, meanwhile, are warning customers not to hoard
drugs, which they say could pose a bigger threat to the medical
supply system than computer problems.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman disputes this reasoning. Not all dangers have been
addressed: There are ``many points of potential failure'' in the
system, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Given the risks, the state Office of Emergency Services, the Red
Cross and other agencies are advising consumers to make hard copies
of their medical records and prepare for the possibility that
prescriptions won't get refilled for a time after New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   The issue will be debated _ and worked on _ for months to come.
The Veterans Administration, for example, sent formal requests for
Y2K-compliance details to 1,600 suppliers, posting the replies and
other materials on the Internet. Many of the devices with
compliance problems are still being fixed, but readiness is
expected by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The workload is achievable,'' said Leonard Bourget, the VA
system's Y2K project manager.
</P>
<P>
   After repeated rounds of surveys, fixes and follow-ups, FDA
officials say they, too, are confident that Y2K malfunctions won't
wreak havoc.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of medical devices turned up with problems,
including some older electrocardiogram machines and other equipment
that printed out incorrect dates.
</P>
<P>
   The most critical technology _ such as pacemakers and other
implanted devices _ should function properly regardless of the
date, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   `'The defibrillator may show a wrong date,'' Falcon said. ``So
what? It will still bring the patient back to life. It will just
say that it brought him back in a different century.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 0418EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 04:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3766 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNIVERSITY-SWEATSHOPS     04-19 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSITY-SWATSHOPS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 A MOVEMENT AT NATION'S SCHOOLS TO FIGHT SWEATSHOPS  &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In recent months, a powerful anti-sweatshop
student movement has emerged on campuses across the nation and in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Sit-ins, teach-ins, demonstrations and mock fashion shows have
become common, pressing administrators to crack down on the
companies that are licensed to provide foreign-made sports
uniforms, T-shirts, mugs, banners and other merchandise sold with
the colleges' logos.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is big business _ $2.5 billion in annual college
merchandise sales nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every student has some kind of UC clothing, but we have little
idea under what conditions these items are made,'' said Smriti
Rana, a student activist at the University of California at
Berkeley. ``The college shirts and hats that we wear with pride
shouldn't be manufactured in demeaning and abusive conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressure also has come from Congress and the California
Legislature, which have approved resolutions sponsored by Rep.
George Miller, D-Calif., and State Senate President John Burton,
D-San Francisco, calling on all universities to bar sweatshop labor
in the manufacture of their licensed products.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the University of California enacted a preliminary
code of labor rights for its licensees. And since mid-March, 56
universities _ including three in California _ have joined the Fair
Labor Association, a new, White House-sponsored coalition of
corporations and human-rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens more universities are expected to join the FLA in the
coming weeks. The American Council on Education, which represents
nearly all the nation's 1,800 colleges and universities, is urging
all its members to join.
</P>
<P>
   However, many student activists say that the FLA's code of
conduct and monitoring system are unacceptably weak and that
colleges should not rush to join.
</P>
<P>
   On UC campuses, a coalition of students and faculty is demanding
that the university cancel its expected decision to join the FLA.
Instead, they say UC should strengthen its own code of conduct _
for example, by requiring all licensees to publicly disclose the
locations of their factories _ and should set up its own
organization to visit factories suspected of violations.
</P>
<P>
   In a March 25 letter to the coalition, UC Senior Vice President
Wayne Kennedy warned that although some of the students' demands
are ``eminently fair,'' they risk becoming ``an empty gesture
because of the virtual, if not literal, impossibility of
enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   FLA leaders predict that a compromise will be reached under
which UC and other schools use the FLA monitoring system to enforce
strengthened versions of the universities' own codes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 0418EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 04:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3769 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFUGEES-BUCKETS-SFCH     04-19 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEES-BUCKETS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SIMPLE WAY TO CLEAN UP REFUGEE CAMPS' MESS  &HT;     By MICHAEL TAYLOR 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ The Clinton administration is urging the United
Nations agency coordinating refugee relief in the Balkans to adopt
a Bay Area engineer's plan to ease the ``horrendous'' sanitation
problems in the refugee camps by issuing inexpensive five-gallon
plastic buckets to the nearly half a million Kosovars now huddled
in Macedonia and Albania.
<P>
   The buckets, which are normally used by supermarkets to hold
bulk food items, have tightly sealable lids and might cost from 60
cents to $1 each, depending on the supplier. About 1,000 of them
could be stacked on a pallet that is deliverable by helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   At the camps, refugees would use the buckets in the privacy of
their own family compounds or circles, then eventually dump the
contents at a central disposal area where lengths of plastic pipe
lying in a ditch are hooked up to a deep pit.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; x  &LR;  The bucket proposal was developed by Berkeley engineer and
inventor Bill Wattenburg, who over the past 20 years has come up
with such varied ideas as a helicopter-towed blanket of chains and
harrow blades for exploding acres of postwar mine fields, and using
surplus railroad flatcars for makeshift bridges over washed-out
roads.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; uncx  &LR;  ``When you have these masses of refugees in these camps,
you can't control sanitation,'' Wattenburg said last week. ``But
give them each a five-gallon bucket and it would help a great
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   As it is right now, the refugees _ about 129,000 in Macedonia
and 339,000 in Albania _ are living in abject squalor, according to
those who have just returned from the camps. There are few toilets,
and people stand in lines for hours or simply relieve themselves in
the fields or in the buildings where they are housed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just two days ago, I visited three sites and it was just
horrendous,'' said Maha Muna, deputy director of the Women's
Commission for Refugee Women and Children. ``One place, in the town
of Korce (Albania), there was a stadium where 900 refugees were
sleeping on a basketball floor. They had one bathroom with two
toilets and the system had backed up. On the floor was an
accumulation of excrement and children and women were wading into
that area, trying to get water from a sink.''
</P>
<P>
   In the town of Albassan, refugees were sleeping on cement floors
of a warehouse that had no sanitation facilities. Muna said nearby
Albanian families were inviting refugees into their homes to take
showers and use the facilities.
</P>
<P>
   At this warehouse, Muna said, children are dehydrated, many have
diarrhea and they are ``sleeping in cold, humid conditions. A lack
of sanitation is compounding all these problems and if there isn't
much more relief, we will have an overflow of infectious
diseases.''
</P>
<P>
   Wattenburg forwarded his idea to the White House within the past
two weeks, and it went from there to the National Security Council
to the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   A Clinton administration official who declined to be identified
said the Wattenburg proposal ``sounds very straightforward. You
take these buckets to the camps and each one becomes a family's
private latrine. It all makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon, Army Colonel Jay Erb said, ``It's a great idea.
It's certainly better than anything I have at the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Erb, who is one of the Pentagon officers working on the refugee
problem, said armed forces and international relief organizations
that are helping the refugees have already installed portable
toilets and latrines, ``but we still have a sanitation problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So even if we build latrines, I like this (bucket) idea as an
option.''
</P>
<P>
   Erb said the Wattenburg proposal was forwarded, through
channels, to the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees in Geneva. The
commissioner's agency is the one that coordinates the huge relief
efforts being mounted worldwide for the Kosovo refugees.
</P>
<P>
   b Judith Kumin, the commissioner's spokeswoman, said from Geneva
that she had not yet seen the proposal and therefore could not
comment on it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
