<HEADER>
A3873 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-KOSOVO-SAFEWAR-REVI     04-19 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-KOSOVO-SAFEWAR-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON KILLING FROM BEYOND HARM'S WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
(jt) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ I flew on a B-52 raid once. The enormous plane took
off from Guam, refueled over the Philippines, dropped its bombs on
North Vietnam through a dense overcast, turned around, refueled
again and landed safely back on Guam. In 16 or 18 hours, we sighted
no enemy. All we saw was sky and clouds, and the whole mission felt
antiseptic and unreal compared with the nasty, muddy, often lethal
reality that the foot soldiers faced.
</P>
<P>
   The war in Kosovo, if war is the right word, is a lot like that.
</P>
<P>
   This is a war in which one side _ the United States and its NATO
allies _ has set out as a matter of policy to hold itself
harm-free. So far it has worked, though a pilot could be killed or
captured at any moment. One American pilot was shot down, but he
escaped. Three hapless American soldiers wandered too close to the
border and fell into enemy hands; they were roughed up a bit, but
as far as Washington knows, they are in reasonably good shape.
</P>
<P>
   In a typical year, more than 200 American servicemen are killed
in accidents of one kind or another, which is roughly four a week.
In almost four weeks of war in Kosovo, not a single American has
died. No body bags have been unloaded at Dover Air Force Base in
Delaware, and no Americans have been dragged through the streets of
an enemy capital, as in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness. But meanwhile, substantial numbers of Serbians
have died, including a fair number of civilians. An unknown number
of ethnic Albanian refugees _ the very ``innocent civilians'' that
President Clinton said the operation was designed to help _ were
killed Wednesday by allied bombs. Inevitably, military forces are
intermixed with the civil population. No bomb, no missile and no
pilot is smart enough to avoid hitting both on occasion. No
electronic system can eliminate human fallibility.
</P>
<P>
   The point here is not that the attacks should stop. The point is
that baby boomer warfare does not work. Bill Clinton and Tony Blair
were born too late to experience World War II, however indirectly,
and they have grown up in an age mesmerized by technology.
Impressed by their ability to kill from afar, with almost no risk
of retaliation against those firing the weapons, Clinton has
launched cruise missiles at Afghanistan, Sudan, Iraq and Serbia in
the last six months alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Limited actions beget limited results,'' said Sen. John McCain
of Arizona, a Navy pilot in Vietnam who is seeking the Republican
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has not only ruled out using ground troops; he has told
the world (including Slobodan Milosevic) that he has done so, which
is rather like a pitcher announcing that he intends to throw
nothing but curve balls. Until recently, NATO has used mostly
fast-flying (and, in the case of the refugee column, high-flying)
jet aircraft, making accidents more likely. This is not the kind of
work for which high-performance planes are ideally suited.
</P>
<P>
   The slower-flying A-10 Warthogs that were designed for close-in
ground-support and tactical bombing have only recently come into
action, and Apache helicopters have not been used yet. They might
have been able to avoid the mistakes that killed most of the
civilians. But they would also have been more vulnerable to ground
fire.
</P>
<P>
   No president wants to expose his forces to heedless casualties.
No general, either, not even George S. Patton, who assured Third
Army troops on the eve of D-Day that only 2 percent of them would
die in a major battle, because they would never be committed to
Verdun-style trench warfare.
</P>
<P>
   Fair enough. But minimizing one's own casualties while slugging
it out with an enemy on the ground, trying to maximize his losses
in pursuit of a clearly attainable if costly objective, represents
one kind of morality. It is another thing altogether to expose
innocents to death to preserve a strategy of self-protection that
may never work and will take a lot longer to work, if it ever does,
than one that exposes some of our troops to danger.
</P>
<P>
   Again, when hundreds of thousands of refugees were forced into
the woods without food, water or shelter, NATO briefly considered
low- or high-altitude air drops. The idea was abandoned as too
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Civilian officials at NATO headquarters acknowledged that they
were skittish about losing cargo planes, too, given the
capabilities of Serbian air defenses that remain intact. And Maj.
Gen. Charles Wald, the vice director of strategic planning at the
Pentagon, added that ``airdrops are very, very dangerous, and there
is no indication at all that Milosevic would allow us to fly
airdrops in that area.''
</P>
<P>
   If allied troops were involved, instead of refugees, the
airdrops would never have been questioned. During the Battle of the
Bulge in World War II, American pilots flew through murderous flak
to drop supplies and ammunition to the beleaguered garrison at
Bastogne. French pilots did much the same thing during the siege of
Dienbienphu in the first Vietnam war.
</P>
<P>
   The essential nature of combat is the fear that you may die
before you can kill your enemy. Isn't that what gives scale and
meaning to an essentially savage act? And doesn't removing the
element of sacrifice through push-button warfare somehow corrupt
even the most nobly motivated war?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-17-99 1113EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
