<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MALAYSIA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW GLOBALISM RUINED AN ASIAN SUCCESS STORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
(jt) 
 By MARK LANDLER   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia _ His children were weeping, and his wife
looked shell-shocked. But as the guards led him away to serve a
six-year prison sentence last week, Malaysia's ousted deputy prime
minister, Anwar Ibrahim, seemed to be prepping himself for the next
round of a boxing match.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hold fast to the struggle,'' Anwar said in a fiery statement
just after he was found guilty of corruption. ``Love Malaysia. And
if we do love Malaysia, then the fight against injustice must be
invigorated.''
</P>
<P>
   While Anwar, 51, vows he will lead a campaign to unseat
Malaysia's strong-willed leader, Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad,
it is not clear he can be much of an insurgent from behind bars. If
Malaysia recovers from the ravages of the Asian economic crisis,
the 73-year-old Mahathir seems likely to survive the most serious
threat to his 18-year rule.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the downfall of Anwar shows how outside economic forces
can sunder the political culture of even a well-governed country.
Before the Asian crisis devastated Malaysia's economy, Anwar and
Mahathir rarely disagreed. Now, the two men are locked in a feud so
bitter that Anwar likens his former mentor to Hitler, while
Mahathir accuses his protege of being a sodomist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economic crisis unfolded into a political crisis, with
changes in regimes throughout the region,'' said K.S. Jomo, a
political economist at the University of Malaya. ``That scared
Mahathir, and it emboldened Anwar.''
</P>
<P>
   Anwar's wife, Wan Azizah Wan Ismail, believes her husband had
become too much of a threat to Mahathir. ``It was a foregone
conclusion that he was going to be found guilty,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For two decades, Mahathir and Anwar were inseparable, united in
a drive to turn this former British colony into Exhibit A of the
Asian miracle. With foreign money pouring in, Malaysia became a
wonderland of development. American companies built factories to
take advantage of the cheap work force, and the living standard
rose.
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir and Anwar flexed their muscles in different ways. The
prime minister built the world's tallest skyscrapers in Kuala
Lumpur, while Anwar cultivated an image as a new-style Asian
leader. In his book, ``The Asian Renaissance,'' he tried to square
Asian values with Western capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   But last year Malaysia got caught in the riptide of globalism,
and the strain drove both men to extreme positions. Mahathir argued
that Malaysia should shield itself against the predations of
foreign currency speculators by erecting barriers around its
markets. Anwar favored the International Monetary Fund's castor-oil
remedy of open markets and high interest rates. He said the prime
minister was just trying to protect his cronies.
</P>
<P>
   Just when Mahathir seemed to be on the ropes, he lashed back _
imposing controls on Malaysia's currency markets and sacking his
deputy. Three weeks later, Anwar was arrested and charged with
corruption and sex crimes.
</P>
<P>
   It is tempting to cast the feud between Mahathir and Anwar in
Manichean terms. Anwar's trial had all the appearances of a
railroading. And Dr. Mahathir has won few friends outside Malaysia
with his inflammatory remarks about the influence of the financier
George Soros and Jewish currency speculators.
</P>
<P>
   In an article in The New York Times on Thursday, written from
prison, Anwar accused Mahathir of being ``a has-been leader who had
descended to cruelty in desperate bid to cling to power.''
</P>
<P>
   But such a portrayal is simplistic. Political analysts here said
Mahathir mixes populist, anti-Western rhetoric with a sophisticated
understanding of the global economy. Even critics credit him for
fashioning a harmonious country out of a combustible mixture of
Malays, ethnic Chinese and Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Anwar is no helpless victim. Analysts describe him as
a skilled and even ruthless politician who did not hesitate to hand
out his share of plum government contracts to solidify his power
base. Anwar has honed his image overseas, through a network of
Western-style spin doctors.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Anwar's downfall is yet more evidence that global
capitalism can be a powerful destabilizing force. It set off
poisonous animosities in two leaders who shared a common vision of
Malaysia's future. And the resulting power struggle left this
once-peaceful and prosperous country sadly diminished.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-17-99 1114EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
