<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 09:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3911 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELLSOUTH-QWEST-COX     04-19 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-QWEST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth buys stake in Qwest
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BellSouth Corp. today announced plans to pay $3.5 billion for 10
percent of Qwest Communications, one of the nation's more ambitious
providers of high-speed data and long-distance services.
</P>
<P>
   The move, BellSouth's first acquisition in more than five years,
is aimed at improving BellSouth's readiness for global competition
in an industry in which big players have been teaming up to provide
ever greater muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sign that we want to enhance our great growth,'' F.
Duane Ackerman, BellSouth chairman and chief executive, said today
in a CNN interview. ``For us, it's about data, electronic commerce,
Web hosting, Internet telephony. It's also about an alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Although BellSouth officials have long shrugged off the notion
that they were under pressure to act, rivals have been getting
bigger and adding a range of services. Despite BellSouth's $23
billion a year in revenues and record profits, the company has gone
from the nation's largest regional phone company to the second
smallest. Meanwhile, BellSouth was starting to look like a muscular
boxer whose arms were just too short. The lion's share of BellSouth
revenues was still coming from its dominance of local service in
its nine-state region. While BellSouth stayed on the sidelines,
other regional Bells were bulking up.
</P>
<P>
   SBC purchased Pacific Telesis and Ameritech. Bell Atlantic has
swallowed Nynex and has a deal to buy GTE. Meanwhile, long-distance
rival AT&AMP;T has bought business provider Teleport and is making a
long-term bid for consumers by acquiring Tele-Communications Inc.,
a huge cable company. WorldCom bought MCI and a host of other
companies, putting much of its focus on high-speed services.
</P>
<P>
   Consolidation is in the air: News about BellSouth and Qwest came
as European markets were roiled by word that two telecommunications
giants _ the national phone companies of Germany and Italy _ were
in merger talks.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with Denver-based Qwest, in the works for several
months, gives BellSouth access to 18,500 miles of high-speed lines,
as well as LCI, which sells long-distance services. BellSouth,
which has still not won federal approval to offer long-distance
service, is limited to a 10 percent ownership of a long-distance
company.
</P>
<P>
   But the investment in Qwest gives BellSouth access to the
company's resources and offers a route to national long-distance,
as soon as BellSouth is permitted into that market. At the same
time, it gives Qwest a local service presence that it has lacked.
BellSouth is paying $94.50 a share for its stake in Qwest stock,
which closed Friday at $82 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
