   Consolidation is in the air: News about BellSouth and Qwest came
as European markets were roiled by word that two telecommunications
giants _ the national phone companies of Germany and Italy _ were
in merger talks.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with Denver-based Qwest, in the works for several
months, gives BellSouth access to 18,500 miles of high-speed lines,
as well as LCI, which sells long-distance services. BellSouth,
which has still not won federal approval to offer long-distance
service, is limited to a 10 percent ownership of a long-distance
company.
</P>
<P>
   But the investment in Qwest gives BellSouth access to the
company's resources and offers a route to national long-distance,
as soon as BellSouth is permitted into that market. At the same
time, it gives Qwest a local service presence that it has lacked.
BellSouth is paying $94.50 a share for its stake in Qwest stock,
which closed Friday at $82 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
