A3914 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-SNAKES-KAN &LR;      04-19 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-SNAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINALLY A LITTLE GOOD PRESS FOR THE LOWLY SNAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1999 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because I'm behind on nearly everything in my life, I've only
recently caught up with the January issue of ``Animal Behaviour''
and the disclosure therein that snakes are smarter than we
thought. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No, I'm not dumber than you thought because I misspelled
``Behavior.'' ``Behaviour'' is the way the magazine spells it. And
no wonder. It's published in London. The English are always tossing
extra u's into various words. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, they've got us Americans doing it, too. Just look at
the word various. What good is the u in there? Why, no good at all.
But just try spelling it varios(CQ) and see what happens. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I don't mean to be writing about the behavior of English
persons here. If I cared about that I'd read ``People Behaviour,''
just as, if I wanted to know about turnips, I'd read ``Vegetable
Behaviour,'' and so on. Rather, I mean to write about snakes, which
are definitely animals. Certainly the snake that used to live in my
house was. His name was Monty Python. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One day Monty escaped from the flimsy home his teen-age keeper
had constructed for him. I didn't sleep well for a week or more
until Monty's quite-dead remains were discovered in eternal rest
until the clothes dryer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Which seemed pretty stupid to me. Why would you escape a nice
house where you got regular food only to wind up dead and probably
pretty hungry under a large home appliance? Well, unless you were a
dumb snake. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's why I'm a little skeptical about this ``Animal
Behaviour'' report on a study done by David Holtzman, a
neuroscientist at the University of Rochester, a fine New York
state institution I once attended part-time. I suppose had I known
it was the kind of school that countenanced snake handlers, I might
have made another choice. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Holtzman studied 24 corn snakes _ which no doubt some of
you know better by their scientific name, ``Elaphe guttata
guttata,'' or by their other nickname, red rat snake. He and his
fellow snake scholars determined that these slithering things are
pretty bright, in a relative way of speaking. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Snakes,'' he says, ``exhibit spatial learning that rivals the
learning abilities of birds and rodents.'' I guess that's meant to
be a compliment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the things Holtzman did was to challenge the snakes to
escape from a black plastic tub about the size of a child's wading
pool. When my children were little it sometimes took them no longer
than 11 nanoseconds to escape from such a pool if one of them
realized the other one was doing something, well, indiscreet in the
pool. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The snakes, however, were slower. At first it took them 700
seconds to find the correct escape hole. But they worked that down
to about 400 seconds on the fourth day of testing, and some got out
in less than 30 seconds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Holtzman says he and his team found, to everyone's
surprise, that snakes use vision to locate places, not just ``the
chemical cues picked up by flicking their tongues out, as many
snake biologists assume.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rochester snake experimenters say all of this may help them
figure out how to offer new therapies for people with brain damage,
and maybe that's right. But my guess is they do this for the same
reason an Indianapolis 500 driver zooms around the track at 205 mph
_ because it's cool. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Snakes haven't had good press since one of them conned Eve into
eating the forbidden fruit. People instinctively dislike snakes. So
what could be cooler than to be able to tell people that your
professional career is dedicated to teaching snakes how to escape?
Well, unless it's to tell people you work for a magazine that
misspells its name. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
