</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Serbs' feigned outrage at civilian casualties
sickens
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If real people weren't really being killed, the eruption of Serb
outrage at NATO's mistaken bombing of a caravan of fleeing Kosovars
could be amusing.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a government _ and increasingly, sad to say, a
population as well _ pretending for world consumption to be
distressed at NATO's accidental killing of the very people Serbia
itself is energetically and very, very purposely brutalizing.
</P>
<P>
   Even the fatalism embedded in the old saw that the first victim
of war is truth is strained by a whopper like that one. Yet make no
mistake: Serbia is scoring PR points with its phony indignation,
not least by its manipulation of the television images _ and by the
confidence it can have that most TV reporters are incapable of
modulating their reports with even a little perspective.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a year now _ and vigorously for going on a month _
the Serbian military and paramilitary have been been murdering
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. They have been burning down civilians'
homes. They have been leveling whole towns. They have forced well
more than half a million utterly unoffending noncombatants _ women,
children, the sick, the aged _ into dreary, often deathly marches
to forced exile. They rape. They steal the deportees' meager funds.
</P>
<P>
   Of none of this, of course, have the Serbs permitted any news
coverage. We know about the horrors second-hand, from the testimony
of the surviving victims. We have no images, except as we
reluctantly imagine them ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   But with NATO's misfire, Serbian authorities quickly hustled
reporters and camera crews to the site. The result was long
minutes, gratifying to Serbia, of gruesome pictures of the
grotesquely killed, the horribly wounded. And some reporters
furthered Slobodan Milosevic's game by treating NATO's early-on
confusion over just what had happened as if that were a cover-up
scandal in the making.
</P>
<P>
   To anyone who has been paying the slightest attention, it has
been clear that NATO has been going to extraordinary lengths to
minimize civilian casualties, even in culpable Serbia itself. The
caution has been inhibiting, especially in Kosovo, where NATO
planes have often held their fire rather than risk hitting the
civilians and nonmilitary facilities the Serbs use for cover.
</P>
<P>
   But as President Clinton, forced by the circumstances to
emphasize the obvious, said, this is war and in war, at best an
untidy business, even the greatest care can't prevent the
inevitable unintended damage and casualties. Many of the weapons
NATO is using may look like video games, but where they land there
is havoc and death that do not disappear when the game is over. The
weapons, and the crews, are good. They are not perfect.
</P>
<P>
   The air cover that Serbia is flying for its atrocity on the
ground is a propaganda war pressed on television, the scenes
stage-managed by what Serbia will allow to be shown (itself as
victim) and what it will not let be seen (itself as victimizer).
Television images are Serbia's air-to-ground missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
