<SLUG> BC-RICK-SCHRODER-IN-NYPD-BLUE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BLUE: RICK SCHRODER IS `NYPD BLUE'S' LATEST ROOKIE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Rick Schroder with Dennis Franz in a
scene from ``NYPD Blue.'' 
 By DAVID KRONKE  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't call him Little Boy Blue.
</P>
<P>
   Eyebrows were raised across America when producer Steven Bochco
announced that Rick Schroder would be Jimmy Smits' replacement on
the long-running ABC hit, ``NYPD Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   Not Ricky Schroder? The adorable tyke from ``The Champ'' (1979)
and the 1980s sitcom ``Silver Spoons?''
</P>
<P>
   No, definitely not Ricky. Right from his first entrance as
Detective Danny Sorenson, Schroder vividly brought to life a cop
who was young, but old enough to have demons of his own. No
adorable tykes need apply.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate stamp of approval came from ``Mr. NYPD Blue''
himself, Emmy Award winner Dennis Franz, who plays Detective Andy
Sipowicz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis told me today, `Rick, it's finally done. You're part of
the show _ the transition worked,''' Schroder says. ``That was cool
for him to say that to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The series' ratings have actually risen since his arrival, which
Schroder writes off to people's curiosity about impending disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectation level for me to fail was so great,'' he says,
``that when I didn't fail, it was a bigger deal than it would've
been if there hadn't been any expectations for me.''
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, relaxing over a French-dip brisket sandwich at a
West Los Angeles deli, Schroder has no complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know sometimes, when you have a dream, it comes true and
it's not as good as you imagined?'' he says. ``This one's as
good.''
</P>
<P>
   The most disorienting aspect of the show, the actor says, may be
that he had to begin by filming disconnected snippets from a number
of episodes during the show's annual trek to New York for location
shooting _ which actually wasn't so different from normal, since
co-creator David Milch prefers not to give actors their scripts
much ahead of time. It adds to the show's energy and spontaneity,
he claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way he writes,'' Schroder says with a shrug. ``You
don't get the whole episode, ever. You're lucky if you get your
scenes the night before you shoot them. So you don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way they want it,'' he says. ``It's hard to
prepare, but I learned early on, you've got to trust the men
involved with the show. You've got to give up some of your
control.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his character, Schroder says the writers have based it to
a considerable extent on the actor himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess a lot of what people like is just me being me,'' he
says. ``There's a lot of me in Sorenson. It's not forced _ I'm not
acting a lot of the time. It's not that big a stretch for me. I've
had a full life already, and a lot of it I was just born that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of people out there, executives at networks,
that wanted me to do a real stock family show,'' he adds, ``and
that's not what I wanted to do. I was proud of myself that I was
patient and waited, I had opportunities to do other shows, and I
was just really, really lucky to get this one. Because it's
everything I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing a cop is a challenge, however, because of the kind of
life-or-death situations that his character regularly encounters.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, when they're getting ready to roll and you're
sitting there with your own thoughts _ like 30 seconds, 10 seconds
before a take _ you'll do crazy sh-t in your head, your
imagination,'' Schroder says. ``If you have to get excited or
tensed up or hyped up for a scene where you know you can meet a
bullet, you might want to say four-letter words in your head 10
seconds before the take. Or think nasty thoughts about the guy
that's going to put bullets in you. And just fantasize in a sense.
That'll get you in the mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I could've been a cop,'' he says. ``Where I grew up in
New York, a lot of cops and firemen were friends of the family. I'd
gone on ride-alongs and always liked cops. I just like the guys
they are _ they're very can-do, and I respond to that sort of
attitude, I like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New York cops are huge fans of the show,'' he adds.
``We're treated like royalty. And they really opened up _ you'd be
surprised. They really told you stories about the real way they do
their job, not the way they show everybody, and stuff that probably
could've gotten them in a lot of trouble when it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   If the cops had any reservations about the former Ricky joining
the ranks of television police officers, they kept them to
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't say much,'' Schroder says. ``I mean, they were
friendly as could be and they were big fans of mine, but they
didn't say much about, `Oh yeah, kid, you're gonna do great.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if they believed that, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   The steel and concrete of Manhattan is a long way from
Schroder's home, a 500-acre Colorado ranch which he bought in 1990
after visiting the area to film ``Return to Lonesome Dove.'' He was
20, and knew nothing whatever about ranching.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all new,'' he recalls. ``I fell in love with the
Southwest. It took two years to find the perfect ranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never my intention to live there,'' he adds. ``It was
my intention to have it as a second home, a place to go visit and
enjoy. Then we had our first baby, and we built a house and just
never left. Before I knew it, I'd been ranching for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now on my ranch there's 400 pairs of cattle,'' the actor
says. ``A pair is a mother and a baby. We pull calves (assist in a
birth) sometimes _ I've done that. I've actually had my hand up to
my shoulder inside of a cow pulling on calves, literally putting
your feet up on her butt and trying to pull it out. I love working
the ranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go home every weekend,'' he adds. ``I've only missed two
weekends in seven months. I'm very proud of that.''
</P>
<P>
   All in all, Schroder seems to have survived child stardom better
than most, but he doesn't have similar aspirations for his
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't let my kids do it, no,'' he says thoughtfully.
``But I'm glad I did it. I mean, it's cool. It's an interesting
life. I'm just protecting them from, I guess, losing those very
special young carefree years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying I lost all mine,'' he adds, ``but it was tough
to be a normal kid and have normal experiences, doing what I was
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother did the best she could to provide a normal childhood,
Schroder recalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``She never made me be a little professional,'' he says. ``She
let me be a boy. She let me get messy and she let me get in
trouble. When Universal sent letters to the production company
about me terrorizing the tour buses on the Universal Studios back
lot, setting off the `Jaws' exhibition by myself and all these
other crazy things I did growing up on Universal's lot, she would
just ignore them or rip them up.
</P>
<P>
   ``She knew you're supposed to have fun, you're supposed to get
in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (David Kronke is the Los Angeles-based senior writer for TV
Guide Canada.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``NYPD Blue,'' consult the ABC
Website at www.abc.com. And don't forget to visit The New York
Times Syndicate Website at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on StarBeat and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 1106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3997 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROCK-BASSIST-BILL-WYM     04-19 1459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCK-BASSIST-BILL-WYMAN-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTERLIFE: BILL WYMAN ON MUSIC, THE STONES AND THE REST OF THE
WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of rock bassist Bill Wyman. 
 By SCOTT COOPER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Bill Wyman quit the Rolling Stones seven years ago, but he's
still a Stone at heart.
 &HT;    Wyman may no longer be holding down the simple, steady bass
lines to anchor Mick Jagger's sexy singing and Keith Richards'
raunchy guitar riffs, as he did for 31 years. But he's still the
unofficial historian for a group that has plenty of history.
 &HT;    ``I think they appreciate that someone keeps a record for
posterity,'' Wyman says.
 &HT;    His collection of Stones memorabilia was a great source for his
1990 memoir, ``Stone Alone,'' but it also adorns the walls of
Wyman's three British restaurants _ which bear the name Sticky
Fingers, lifted from one of the band's greatest records.
 &HT;    The Stones have kept rolling without their founding bassist, but
they keep him involved by sending packages of tour programs,
stickers, tickets, T-shirts and even the daily newsletter,
providing an insider's look at the life of a Rolling Stone.
 &HT;    ``When you're on tour, you get your daily newsletter stuffed
under your door every morning, which tells you everything that's
going on that day, even if there's nothing going on,'' the bassist
explains. ``It tells you where you are, what you're doing, where
the good restaurants are if you want to go, the good shopping
areas, and there's the doctor's phone number if you need him.''
 &HT;    Wyman doesn't miss receiving that newsletter directly, he
hastens to add.
 &HT;    ``I hated traveling in hotels and suitcases and living in
airports and hotel rooms,'' he recalls. ``I loved the times on
stage, of course _ that's the thing you do. All the rest of that's
bulls--t that goes around that. You have to deal with that for the
other 22 hours of the day, and then you only play once every three
days, so it's even longer.
 &HT;    ``It just used to drive me nuts,'' the bassist adds. ``But then
you couldn't go out, because people knew you were in town and the
hotel was surrounded and all that. So you ended up in the room all
the time. If you were lucky, you might go to a restaurant very late
on.''
 &HT;    This de-facto incarceration was only one of the restrictions
that came with membership in one of the biggest rock 'n' roll bands
ever. Wyman was equally frustrated by the fact that almost all of
the band's songs were written by Jagger and Richards.
 &HT;    ``You did an album every 18 months,'' Wyman says. ``You had two
writers who wrote bloody good songs for the band over the years.
You had nine or 10 songs to record for the album, and 30 songs
ready when you arrived at the studio. So there was no room for
anybody else to write, really.''
 &HT;    Even though he respects their songwriting talents, Wyman felt
that the Jagger-Richards songs eventually began to lose their
individuality.
 &HT;    ``Track after track tended to start the same as the tracks on
the last album,'' he says. ``There was nothing fresh coming through
for me.''
 &HT;    The only original Stone to leave the band before Wyman was
founder and multi-instrumentalist Brian Jones, who quit shortly
before his drug-related death in 1969.
 &HT;    ``If Brian hadn't died,'' Wyman says, ``I think the band would
have probably broken up in the '70s. Brian was very susceptible to
experimenting with substances, and Keith's the same. So you
wouldn't have ended up carrying one junkie _ you'd be carrying two,
and it wouldn't have worked.''
 &HT;    Jones' replacement, guitarist Mick Taylor, left the band in 1975
after experiencing frustrations similar to Wyman's. In stepped
guitarist Ron Wood, whom Wyman also credits as the current group's
peacemaker, a ``catalyst'' responsible for keeping the harmony
among a group of strong personalities who aren't averse to
squabbles, major and minor.
 &HT;    His own departure, Wyman says, was primarily a result of his
``horrendous'' personal life during the late 1980s. After leaving
the band he remarried, and he and his wife are now raising three
girls.
 &HT;    ``We've got a lovely family now,'' the musician says. ``It's
just great to be around them.''
 &HT;    When Wyman quit the Stones in 1991, he adds, they didn't believe
him.
 &HT;    ``They left the door open for me right up until four months
before they started working in '94,'' he recalls. ``Then Mick and
Charlie (Watts, the band's drummer) came around and spent the
evening with me. I said, `But I left two years ago, I really did. I
did leave.'
 &HT;    ``But when I make decisions, they're decisions.''
 &HT;    In spite of their famous internal struggles, Wyman adds, the
Stones remain tight.
 &HT;    ``We're great mates and we see each other a lot, even in the
present day,'' he says. ``When Charlie's in town he comes around
for dinner. And I go to see them and stay with them over the
weekend. We're still great friends. It's not sour grapes _ it just
doesn't really interest me any more.''
 &HT;    What does interest Wyman varies wildly _ television
documentaries, blues history, archeology, astrology, photography,
art and his family among them. This marks a big difference between
him and the other Stones, he says.
 &HT;    ``I think the problem is, knowing them quite well, there's very
little else they like to do,'' Wyman says. ``Some of them have got
one other interest: Ron is into art. He has his exhibitions and
he's good at it. Mick's been trying on and off over the years to be
involved in movies, either as an actor or a producer or whatever.
That's his other interest _ apart from girls. And Charlie's into
jazz. He has a little jazz band that he plays with when the Stones
aren't working _ that's his hobby.
 &HT;    ``But that's about it,'' he concludes. ``I don't think Keith's
got anything else that's as interesting for him. He plays with
other people a bit, but it's music again.''
 &HT;    Wyman may have left the Stones, but he defends the band against
its detractors, many of whom claim that Jagger and Richards are
simply too old to live up to their own past.
 &HT;    ``Rock 'n' roll hasn't been going long enough for there to be
elder statesmen until now,'' he says. ``It's not like jazz, which
was going from the turn of the century. You had Louis Armstrong and
all those people playing when they were ancient, because the music
let them grow up and get old in it.
 &HT;    ``But this is the first time in rock 'n' roll that people have
got to the 50s and 60s,'' he says. ``There was never an opportunity
for people to grow old within that music before, because it didn't
exist before 1953 or 1954.
 &HT;    ``I don't really think of it as a young person's music,'' the
bassist says. ``The only thing that relates it to young people is
the energy that a lot of young performers put into it and make it
really stand out, which maybe we don't achieve quite as well as we
did when we were younger.''
 &HT;    So instead of testing his own theory of youth, Wyman has opted
to follow Armstrong's example. He recently released a CD of jazz
and blues titled ``Anyway the Wind Blows,'' featuring cameos from
Eric Clapton, Peter Frampton and even Mick Taylor.
 &HT;    ``When you get into semiretirement like I am _ although I'm
working my a-- off more than I've ever worked in my life and loving
every minute of it,'' the former Rolling Stone says, ``I can record
that kind of stuff and play on stage.
 &HT;    ``I'm not worrying about chart positions and pleasing record
labels and having a radio hit anymore.''
 c.1999 Scott Cooper  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Scott Cooper is a Santa Cruz, Calif.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Anyway the Wind Blows,''
consult Wyman's Website at www.stickyfingers.co.uk. And don't
forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
