<HEADER>
A3999 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CATHERINE-ZETA-JONES-     04-19 1445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHERINE-ZETA-JONES-IN-ENTRAPMENT-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING UP WITH THE JONES: CATHERINE ZETA-JONES IS MAKING STARDOM
WORK THE SECOND TIME AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Catherine Zeta-Jones in a scene from
``Entrapment.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Five years after she completed a fairly traditional 15 minutes
of fame and saw herself consigned to washed-up status, Catherine
Zeta-Jones doesn't look like a has-been.
 &HT;    Relaxed and apparently confident for an interview at Los
Angeles' Four Seasons Hotel, Zeta-Jones looks stunning and every
inch a movie star. Dressed in a black skirt and white shirt, she
flashes amber eyes accentuated by dark, smoky liner, her full lips
a deep, ruby red.
 &HT;    But she doesn't mind admitting that her second spin on fame's
merry-go-round _ this time in America instead of England _ has her
a little edgy.
 &HT;    ``I have to admit that I'm a bit nervous,'' she says.
 &HT;    The results should be in soon. Last summer's ``The Mask of
Zorro'' paid her way onto the Hollywood hot list, and two films in
the next four months should tell whether she has what it takes to
stay there: the jewel-thief movie ``Entrapment,'' which opens on
April 30, and Dreamworks' highly anticipated ``The Haunting,'' a
ghost story co-starring Liam Neeson that will open July 23.
 &HT;    If everything clicks, she'll have a chance to find out if the
American version of stardom is any better than the British version.
 &HT;    ``Oh, it can't be worse than the first time when I was famous,''
the 29-year-old Zeta-Jones says, rolling her eyes.
 &HT;    That came via stage success and a British television series,
``The Darling Buds of May.'' For a while there, Zeta-Jones was as
hot as anyone barely out of her teens could be _ though not as hot
as she may become, if her big-screen career takes off.
 &HT;    ``She is positioned to be a major movie star in the
old-fashioned sense of the word,'' says Anthony Hopkins, who played
her long-lost father in ``The Mask of Zorro.'' ``I think Catherine
is a return to old-fashioned movie-goddess time, which we've been
lacking for years.''
 &HT;    She's appearing opposite an old-fashion movie god, Sean Connery,
in ``Entrapment,'' which casts them as rival art thieves who team
up in business and, of course, in romance.
 &HT;    Her pairing with the 69-year-old Connery has provoked some
controversy, but Zeta-Jones simply shrugs.
 &HT;    ``I've heard a lot of, `Oh, it's the older-man/younger-woman
thing again,''' she says. ``But it's really more business partners,
which I think is interesting. I'm high tech and he comes from the
old school of thieving.''
 &HT;    Besides, Zeta-Jones wasn't in any position to argue with the
casting, since it was Connery _ in his capacity as producer _ who
went to bat for her in the part.
 &HT;    Twentieth Century Fox wanted a bigger name for the role, but
Connery remembered Zeta-Jones from the little-seen action film
``The Phantom'' (1996) and invited her to Rome for a reading.
 &HT;    ``I was so nervous,'' Zeta-Jones admits. ``But I always get
nervous before I shoot or go on stage. I just have stage fright all
the time, which I think is great. I'm sure if I lost that I'd
completely fall apart. I think my nerves are my edge.''
 &HT;    Meeting Connery put her at ease, she says.
 &HT;    ``He was exactly the way I imagined him,'' the actress recalls.
``That was great, because you have such high expectations of icons
and, if you meet them and they're a pain in the a--, it's so
upsetting.''
 &HT;    Zeta-Jones got the part, and the box-office numbers for
``Zorro'' soothed the studio heads. She was quickly off to sets in
such exotic locales as Malaysia, Hong Kong and Scotland _ quite a
tour for the native of Swansea, Wales, a small fishing town where
she grew up with a seamstress mother and candy-factory-manager
father.
 &HT;    ``People get so confused and think the family is British,'' she
says. ``We're really black Welsh. I'm Tom Jones kind of Welsh.''
 &HT;    Swansea did have something of an artistic tradition _ its gifts
to the world include Dylan Thomas and Anthony Hopkins _ and she
began acting as a child with the Dylan Thomas Theater Group.
 &HT;    ``Afterward, I fell for those big publicity stunts where someone
would put up a poster to find a kid for a play in London,'' she
recalls.
 &HT;    Most kids who responded never even got an audition. But at age
11 she got the lead in ``Annie,'' and soon found herself a child
star in London. ``Bugsy Malone'' and ``The Pajama Game'' led to the
now-teen-age Zeta-Jones winning an understudy role in ``42nd
Street'' and moving up to the lead, which she played for two years.
 &HT;    ``I loved doing the musical. That was my dream,'' Zeta-Jones
says. ``As a young girl, I never, never, never saw myself as a
movie star. I always wanted to be a theater actress.''
 &HT;    But ``42nd Street's'' eight performances a week left her
exhausted, and she decided to look into straight acting. At 19,
Zeta-Jones was cast in ``The Darling Buds of May,'' the story of a
decadent 1950s family, and she awoke to find herself a teen idol,
the object of affection for 23 million fans.
 &HT;    ``There was puppy fat all over my face _ I wasn't that pretty,''
she says, still bemused by it. ``My life changed drastically. The
press attention I got was unbelievable _ every time I had a coffee
with someone, he became the new love of my life, we were
immediately talking marriage and children. I was dating royalty and
sheiks.
 &HT;    ``It became ridiculous. I was only 20.''
 &HT;    The capper came when four paparazzi cars converged on
Zeta-Jones' car as she emerged from a studio parking lot.
Panicking, she hit the gas and swung onto a side street.
 &HT;    ``I was looking in the mirror to see if they were still behind
me,'' the actress recalls, ``when suddenly a lamp post came up.''
 &HT;    The next thing she heard was grinding metal and the sound of
shattering glass falling into her lap. The photographers approached
the car only to snap a few pictures, then drove away without
bothering even to check if she was hurt.
 &HT;    ``It was so intimidating that I wanted to quit show business,''
she recalls.
 &HT;    Instead, she moved to Malibu, Calif., and started over, sleeping
in a pal's closet while trying to launch an American career.
Meanwhile, one London tabloid wrote: ``Poor Catherine Zeta-Jones is
a has-been at age 24.''
 &HT;    ``I was sleeping in my friend's closet, but it still bothered me
that I was suddenly labeled a failure back home,'' she says, still
nettled. ``I recall the word `loser' being used.''
 &HT;    ``The Phantom'' didn't do much for her career. Nor did ``The
Titanic,'' a 1997 CBS miniseries that beat James Cameron's epic
film on the calendar but nowhere else.
 &HT;    ``The Mask of Zorro'' was another story, offering romantic
scenes with Antonio Banderas, touching ones with Hopkins and even a
major sword-fighting sequence.
 &HT;    ``I trained so hard with the sword,'' she recalls. ``In the end,
one arm was toned and my non-fighting arm was so flabby. I also got
to ride horses and learn Spanish _ it was a fabulous experience.''
 &HT;    Ditto her love scenes with Connery, who dazzled her with his
technical skill.
 &HT;    ``He held my face and my chin just in the right position, so my
profile would look really fabulous,'' she says. ``Sean held my back
just right, so I would arch in this sexy way. He was fabulous and
very sexy.''
 &HT;    She giggles.
 &HT;    ``It made me glad I didn't quit acting.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Entrapment,'' consult the 20th
Century Fox Website at www.foxworld.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
