<HEADER>
A4002 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTIAN-BALE-IN-MET     04-19 1462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIAN-BALE-IN-METROLAND-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDEPENDENT THINKER: CHRISTIAN BALE GROWS UP AND HEADS FOR
INDIE-LAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Christian Bale with Emily Watson in a
scene from ``Metroland.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Christian Bale won his latest role by a hair. Or, rather, by his
lack of same.
 &HT;    Really.
 &HT;    In Philip Saville's drama ``Metroland,'' opening across the
country through April and May, the 27-year-old Bale plays one
character at three ages _ 18, 23 and 31.
 &HT;    ``A week before filming started, Philip Saville called and said,
`Christian, do you have a hairy chest?''' says the soft-spoken
Bale, best known for his debut role as a British boy in a Japanese
prison camp in ``Empire of the Sun'' (1987). ``I said, `No,' and
Philip said, `Wonderful, would you like to play all three roles?''
 &HT;    Bale laughs.
 &HT;    ``I didn't know what the connection was, and I still don't,'' he
says. ``I just liked the challenge of playing three versions of the
same character.''
 &HT;    Based on Julian Barnes' 1980 novel, ``Metroland'' centers on
pals Chris (Bale) and Toni (Lee Ross), growing up in the late 1960s
in a suburban section of London called Metroland. The two start out
seeking adventure, but Chris ends up marrying, moving back to
Metroland and fathering a child, while Toni lives an exciting life,
crisscrossing the globe.
 &HT;    When Toni returns for a visit, it prompts Chris to wonder
whether or not he's truly happy.
 &HT;    ``It's a character study about two friends, their idealism and
black-and-white viewpoints of life,'' Bale says. ``I found it quite
nice that the younger Chris is forthright and believes he knows
exactly what he's about and then, by 30, life has taught him there
are a lot more answers to every question than he originally
thought.
 &HT;    ``The older he gets, the less he knows himself,'' the actor
says. ``Situations and perspectives change, but why? Did you
compromise? Did you lose your passion and will?
 &HT;    ``And if you answer that, how do you deal with your answers? Is
it all right to feel content being a 32-year-old, married father
who may not have fulfilled a lot of his dreams?''
 &HT;    Bale couldn't exactly relate to Chris' doubts, though.
 &HT;    ``I never had a place I wanted to escape from,'' he says during
an interview at the Manhattan office of ``Metroland's''
distributor, Lions Gate Films. ``I also don't have straitlaced
parents.
 &HT;    ``My ultimate rebellion would be to get a job at a bank,'' he
says with a laugh. ``My parents are not boring, and I've never
said, `Oh, Christ, I never want to become like them.' My mom was in
the circus for a while, and my dad was a pilot. He took a 9-to-5
job for two weeks and went mad.
 &HT;    ``He essentially does whatever he feels like doing,'' Bale says.
``At times that wasn't fun, like when we were sitting in trucks
outside a house we'd just gotten kicked out of. Other times, things
were going well and we moved to Portugal for a bit.
 &HT;    ``But I think anyone can empathize with the idea of not being
able to see the woods from the trees until somebody kicks you in
the a--.''
 &HT;    Even with critical raves _ not to mention the presence of
two-time Oscar nominee Emily Watson as Chris' wife _ ``Metroland''
faces an uphill battle at the box office. Bale agrees, but doesn't
mind.
 &HT;    ``I have to make the experience of making a film the most
important thing,'' he says. ``I don't ever want to not make a film
I'd be interested in watching because the audience for it may be
limited.''
 &HT;    Indeed, a glance at Bale's credits reveals a preponderance of
art-house films. There's ``Henry V'' (1989), ``Portrait of a Lady''
(1996), ``Velvet Goldmine'' (1998) and the upcoming ``William
Shakespeare's A Midsummer Night's Dream.'' His occasional studio
films have included ``Swing Kids'' (1993) and ``Little Women''
(1994).
 &HT;    ``My doing studio films just hasn't happened very often,'' Bale
says. ``It's not a conscious thing.
 &HT;    ``I started out with the luxury of `Empire,''' he adds. ``There
was a huge amount of money _ we had time to do take after take
until we got it right. Now, with my smaller films, I've gotten used
to getting two or three takes and moving on. It's bang-bang-bang,
and that's good for an actor.
 &HT;    ```Metroland' was done in 26 days,'' he concludes. ``I met the
director two days before we started, and we had no rehearsal.''
 &HT;    ``Empire of the Sun,'' directed by Steven Spielberg, made Bale a
star and a teen idol, but he still grimaces at the mention of it.
 &HT;    ``It feels like a long time ago,'' says the actor, who's single
and splits his time between London and Los Angeles. ``It was a
great experience making it.
 &HT;    ``It's a good thing feeling the distance,'' he adds, ``because I
can see the good aspects again. There was a period where I sort of
resented it, because of the sudden lack of anonymity. At 14, I
didn't want people pointing at me.''
 &HT;    The actor responded to the spotlight's glare by retreating into
his private life and working primarily in smaller films that were
less likely to draw attention to himself.
 &HT;    ``I've never wanted and was never prepared for a lot of volume
about myself,'' he says. ``Having had so much volume after `Empire'
and having hated it so much, I'm sure that affected me.
 &HT;    ``It didn't touch my love of acting, but it made me question
everything else.''
 &HT;    The answer, clearly, has been to avoid teen-heartthrob roles.
His next film, ``All the Little Animals,'' casts him as a mentally
handicapped youth who befriends a reclusive animal lover (John
Hurt).
 &HT;    Next up is an even less boyishly charming role, as the title
character in ``American Psycho,'' based on Bret Easton Ellis' novel
about a brutal serial killer.
 &HT;    Hardly the stuff of teen dreams, but it briefly attracted the
high-profile attention of current idol Leonardo DiCaprio last year.
Bale and director Mary Harron, who had been committed to the
project for years, suddenly found themselves on the verge of being
ousted from what would suddenly have become a ``big'' picture.
 &HT;    ``I didn't feel like a pawn,'' Bale says. ``I always felt it was
more my film than anyone else's short of Mary. People told me to
forget about it, but I always believed I'd end up doing it, and
Mary did as well.
 &HT;    ``The whole thing, frankly, has become the most boring
subject,'' he says. ``I'm doing the film.''
 &HT;    The subject matter has also drawn considerable controversy _ the
novel, after all, was widely condemned as exploitive
quasi-pornography.
 &HT;    Bale rejects criticism from anyone who hasn't seen the film _
which, these days, includes everyone.
 &HT;    ``The film will be powerful,'' he says. ``It's a psychological
thriller about a serial killer, yet it's funny. That's an
incredible dichotomy _ it's funny and cold and ugly, often
simultaneously.
 &HT;    ``I've never experienced anything like it as an actor,'' he
says. ``I'm trying to make people laugh and hate me, really, at the
same time.''
 &HT;    Bale doesn't envy DiCaprio's cover-boy status. On the other
hand, he'd like to boost his own profile _ just a bit.
 &HT;    ``I'd love to be in a position where people don't say, `You'd be
great in this, but we've got to cast So-and-So,''' he says. ``I'd
like to be So-and-So.
 &HT;    ``I'd like to be in a position where people say, `Here's the
money. Christian Bale can be in it.' I think that's where I'm at
with independent films, and ... well, I just don't want to have any
more situations like `American Psycho.'''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Metroland,'' consult the Lions
Gate Films Website at www.lionsgate-ent.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
