<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 11:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4004 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV25-NY     04-19 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO LOOKS HEAVENWARD FOLLOWING A SWAG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 25)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The numbers came in high,'' a senior administration official
told John Harris of The Washington Post, about an estimate of NATO
troops needed to protect Kosovo. ``No one said yes, no one said no;
it was taken off the table. ... It was a complete  &UR; eye-roller &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   This is an example of an unfamiliar word that is immediately
understood. To ``roll one's eyes'' upward (the usual direction is
 &UR; heavenward &LR; ) is to visibly express astonishment, dismay or
disbelief. An  &UR; eye-roller &LR;  is the compound noun that describes a
situation or remark that causes such a reaction.
</P>
<P>
   The useful word apparently has a Pentagon origin or association.
On Dec. 1, 1987, Edwin M. Yoder Jr. reported in The Washington Post
that at a breakfast meeting Caspar Weinberger, the former defense
secretary, was ``cheerfully rattling on, and some of his listeners
are rolling their eyes upward in an unmistakable `oh, brother'
expression.'' Yoder described Weinberger's claim that record
defense budgets had nothing to do with high deficits in the Reagan
era as ``the big  &UR; eye-roller &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   The defense jargon spilled over, as it often does, into sports:
``the Bills' winning score in the fourth quarter,'' wrote Nick
Cafardo in The Boston Globe in 1996, ``was a head-shaker and an
 &UR; eye-roller &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   One synonym is  &UR; stunner &LR; , connoting ``a revelation that leaves
one thunderstruck or dumbfounded.'' Another is  &UR; mind-boggler &LR; , from
something that `` &UR; boggles &LR;  the mind'' (originally ``frighten,''
from the 16th-century  &UR; bogle &LR; 's dialect root in  &UR; goblin &LR; , but now
denoting a high degree of amazement rather than fear). However,
these synonyms do not carry the connotation of skepticism in
 &UR; eye-roller &LR; ; that new term's  &UR; heavenward &LR; -looking association
suggests ``Lord, save us from this baloney.''
</P>
<P>
   The Post's Harris, on a linguistic roll in his report of the
troop estimate that so staggered Pentagonians, went on to write:
``NATO's analysis, officials said, was not a comprehensive study.
Instead, it was an initial review that some officials called a
`SWAG' _ military parlance for a `scientific wild-ass guess.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Tribune reported in 1984 that Col. John Stewart,
testifying in a libel suit brought against CBS by Gen. William
Westmoreland, recalled admitting to his commander years before that
an estimate of enemy strength was based on ``the SWAG principle,''
and that the courtroom erupted in laughter at the explanation of
the acronym.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Army's home page lists the acronym merely as  &UR; swag &LR; ,
defining it as ``a gross estimate or guess.'' This is in error;
when not printed in all capitals,  &UR; swag &LR;  is an old slang term for
``money, booty.'' Only when printed all uppercase does SWAG become
an acronym for ``Scientific Wild-Ass Guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Army phrases defined on its home page include  &UR; ankle
biters &LR; , ``people who criticize one's position but offer no
constructive alternatives'';  &UR; readahead &LR; , ``material sent to
officials to prepare them for upcoming visits'';  &UR; shotgun
coordination &LR; , ``sending duplicate packages to several offices
simultaneously to save time,'' and  &UR; wrapped around the axle &LR; ,
``lacking progress because of immersion in details or inability to
see the big picture.'' Presumably concerned about the third word in
SWAG, the Web page warns readers to ``avoid using these terms in
official correspondence, at formal briefings, when dealing with
outsiders.''
</P>
<P>
   At ease; the attributive noun phrase  &UR; wild ass &LR;  is not a
vulgarism. On the contrary, the juxtaposition of words (as
adjective and noun) can be found five times in the King James
version of the Bible, most famously reflecting well on donkeys in
Job 24:5: ``Behold, as  &UR; wild asses &LR;  in the desert, go they forth to
their work.''
</P>
<P>
   FRIARING PAN
</P>
<P>
   When competing theories come to the same result, the simplest is
preferred. That cutting of complication is encapsulated in the
metaphor of  &UR; Ockham's razor &LR; , from the parsimonious work of the
13th century's William of Ockham, described here some months ago in
this simple sentence: ``The old Franciscan friar (probably bearded;
shaving gear was hard to come by in the abbey) was figuratively
cutting out details.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Your reference to a  &UR; friar &LR;  in the  &UR; abbey &LR;  was a  &UR; non
sequitur &LR; ,'' writes the Rev. Thomas J. Paprocki, chancellor of the
Archdiocese of Chicago, ``unless the Franciscan's barber happened
to be a Benedictine monk.''
</P>
<P>
   He explicates: ``Franciscan  &UR; friars &LR;  usually live in a  &UR; friary &LR; ,
defined as a monastery or place where friars live. An  &UR; abbey &LR;  is a
monastery headed by an  &UR; abbot &LR;  or a nunnery headed by an  &UR; abbess &LR; .
The Benedictines are probably the best-known example of monks and
nuns governed by abbots and abbesses, respectively. Franciscans,
however, are not governed by an abbot. St. Francis of Assisi
preferred the term  &UR; guardian &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   And this just in, as the TV newsies say, from the Conventual
Franciscan Center in Toronto: `` &UR; Monks &LR;  are members of monastic
Orders,'' writes Friar Phil Kelly, ``those who live in larger
communities and follow some sort of monastic rule. Benedictines,
Cistercians (as in Thomas Merton) or Carthusians are such groups.
 &UR; Friars &LR;  are members of the four mendicant orders founded in the
Middle Ages somewhat as a reaction to monasticism. They are the
Augustinians, the Carmelites, the Dominicans and the Franciscans.''
</P>
<P>
   Although even I know that a  &UR; novice &LR;  lives in a  &UR; novitiate &LR; , who
lives in a  &UR; priory &LR; ? (All Cartesians live  &UR; a priori &LR; .) ``Some
houses of friars, such as the Dominicans and Servites, are headed
by a  &UR; prior &LR; ,'' notes Paprocki, ``and some nuns, like the Discalced
Carmelites, are governed by a  &UR; prioress &LR; , all of whom are said to
live in a  &UR; priory &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   As Ockham would put it: Monks and nuns usually live in  &UR; abbeys &LR; 
and  &UR; friars &LR;  in  &UR; friaries &LR; , though some are in  &UR; priories &LR; . ``Your
explanation of Ockham's principle was better than what we received
in the seminary,'' notes Kelly in the spirit of charity, ``but
whining is part of my nature.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
