<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, April 19, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for the Tuesday.
If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MAD-COW (San Francisco) _ A new study of more than 1,500
veterans who received blood products from people who later died
from the human equivalent of ``mad cow'' disease has found no
evidence that any of them came down with the rare ailment. The
study ratifies other inquiries that have yet to find evidence that
Cruetzfeldt- Jakob disease is transmitted by blood or blood
products. By ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   JASPER-KILLING (Jasper, Texas) _ For 10 months, how and why
James Byrd Jr. died has forced the town of Jasper to look at itself
and reflect on its character. Rather then shun the spotlight of the
brutal killing of the black man, the people of Jasper have used the
exposure to try to demonstrate that they are good people who work
together. By CARY CLACK.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN-PRIZES (San Francisco) _ A lawyer in Cameroon fighting
the destruction of Central African rain forests and two aboriginal
women working to prevent uranium mining at an Australian site where
their ancestors lived for more than 40,000 years are among seven
winners of this year's Goldman Environmental Prize. The $125,000
awards are given to grass-roots activists from around the world who
surmount obstacles to win protection for the environment. By
KATHERINE SELIGMAN.
</P>
<P>
   PATAKI-WEALTH (Albany, N.Y.) _ New York Gov. George Pataki's
family earnings slid in 1998, but he's getting a boost from his
wife's marketing work with businesses run by family friends. Income
tax documents that the Patakis made public showed $246,417 in gross
income in 1998, $95,000 from Libby Pataki's two marketing jobs. By
JAMES M. ODATO.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ANTI-MASTECTOMY (San Francisco) _ Andrea Fox will do many things
to stay healthy and keep breast cancer from recurring. But at 32,
she will not have her breasts removed. One of the biggest paradoxes
for doctors and experts is that some healthy women are choosing to
remove their breasts to prevent cancer, while those already
stricken with cancer are refusing to have them taken off. By MARSHA
GINSBURG.
</P>
<P>
   SHAKESPEARE-CENTURY (Albany, N.Y.) _ We're making much of the
turn of the century this year. With William Shakespeare's birthday
coming up on April 23, an Academy Award-winning film about him
playing at theaters, and Harold Bloom's new book, ``Shakespeare:
The Invention of the Human,'' on best-seller lists, let's pause for
a moment to consider the turbulent times that Shakespeare faced in
the waning days of the 16th century. By RICHARD MATTURRO.
</P>
<P>
   TWO-OVENS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Cooking can be frustrating when
trying to cook several dishes at different temperatures in one
oven. To address this dilemma, Maytag Appliances is introducing an
electric range with two ovens, which lets you cook different menu
items simultaneously at different times and temperatures. By
FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   GARDENING-TOOLS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Gardening became a recognized
status symbol a few centuries ago. Early well-to-do homeowners had
only to hire notable landscape architects such as Andrew Jackson
Downing, Frederick Law Olmsted or Edwin Lutyens. But many
homeowners have since begun to find pleasure themselves in the
tasks of gardening, and buying new tools and other landscaping
accessories is part of the fun. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-MOUNTAINS (Undated) _ David Guterson captivated
readers with his 1994 novel, ``Snow Falling on Cedars.'' Now the
teacher-turned-novelist has given us a second novel, ``East of the
Mountains.'' It shares the Washington state setting of its
predecessor, but little else _ except, we're delighted to report,
the writer's gift for spellbinding storytelling. By JUDYTH RIGLER.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Every time a new nurse, lab
technician or doctor came into M.E.'s nook in the emergency room,
she or he would say to me: ``Are you her daughter?'' Each time, I
answered the same way: ``No, just a friend.'' Why did I tack on
that diminishing qualifier? Just a friend. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
