A4006 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN20-C     04-19 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Y2K keepsakes are plentiful
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Some people fear that when Jan. 1, 2000, arrives, a
date-sensitive software flaw, commonly called the Y2K bug, will
cause massive computer breakdowns. Others hope the date will offer
spiritual redemption as Christ returns for the Second Coming. Still
others think New Year's Day will bring nothing more dramatic than a
hangover from the previous night's party.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how differently we view the coming of 2000, we are
united by one desire: We want millennium souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   All over the country, companies are stepping up production of
T-shirts, books, champagne flutes, stuffed animals, countdown
clocks, baseball caps, jewelry and other items that will remind us
that WE WERE THERE when all four digits of the year rolled over.
</P>
<P>
   Fancy champaign glasses seem especially popular, judging by
gifts being sold through Internet shopping sites. ``People are
ordering them for the whole family or for big parties,'' said
Patricia Heller, owner of Heller Glass in Venice, Calif. ``They
want them to say 'January 1, 2000' and their names.'' The glasses
are $44.95 a pair.
</P>
<P>
   Heller, who started her glassware business in Atlanta before
moving to California in 1993, said she spells out millennium
messages with a nontoxic acrylic paint on crystal flutes. She is
getting orders from customers such as travel agents who plan to
give pairs to customers booking big millennium trips and party
hosts who want their New Year's Eve guests to remember where they
were at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the souvenirs are tied to the Year 2000, or Y2K,
computer flaw. That's the computer software glitch that could cause
malfunctions as a result of a misreading of the date change. Some
companies are selling T-shirts or jewelry featuring bugs. Many
authors are using Y2K as a marketing angle, pushing ``doomsday''
books and survival product.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reports that stores specializing in
Christian products are seeing big increases in sales of books about
``end-time'' prophecies and Y2K calamities. The Christian
Booksellers Association reports that three of the top seven books
on the nonfiction best-seller list deal directly with Y2K
predictions.
</P>
<P>
   Other Christians believe that, rather than mark the ``end
times,'' Jan. 1 should be celebrated as the start of Christianity's
third and greatest millennium. And surely a keepsake is needed for
that. One jewelry maker is selling a ``Christianity 2000'' pendant,
minted from one ounce of fine silver and guaranteed to ``become a
family heirloom to be passed down for generations to come,''
according to the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Another company, called Me2!, is trying to counteract the
popularity of doomsday products. On the Me2! Web site, buyers are
informed the stock is geared to people who aren't ``wringing their
hands about a global computer crisis.'' The products include: the
``Millipede,'' a stuffed bug for children; mugs; golf balls and
shot glasses with upbeat millennium messages.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the millennium gifts on the market, perhaps the most
practical is the set of ``Millennium Bug Cuff links'' for $21. Each
link features a bug clambering over a computer keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   How can you go wrong? If it turns out that Y2K causes no real
trouble, then you have a cute souvenir that doesn't have to be
displayed or take up a lot of room in a drawer. But if the computer
flaw does cause economic and social chaos, just pop off the gold
cuff links, melt them down and trade the metal for a loaf of bread.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, here are some Web sites:
</P>
<P>
   www.everything2000.com/shopping/ashopping.asp
</P>
<P>
   www.shopping.yahoo.com
</P>
<P>
   www.year2000.com/y2kbooks.html
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
