<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Family of faith extends far and wide
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ There are times in life when you are helpless. It
happened to me recently when my brother, who lives in California,
underwent triple bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Like many families today, we are scattered across the country.
When my brother was told he would need this surgery _ his second
bypass _ we tried to put in motion a plan to care for him,
thousands of miles away from his family in Texas and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   After his first bypass surgery, my mother went to California,
staying a month and nearly doing herself in. This time, my sister
and I felt it would be too hard emotionally and physically for her
to do it again.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, my brother would have his own family or community that
would rally around him. He does have friends, but the care he would
need was more than even good friends could provide.
</P>
<P>
   So we put together a plan as best we could. My sister offered to
fly out the day he was released from the hospital. She would stay
two weeks and then, hopefully, they could fly back together to
Missouri _ where the rest of my family lives _ for his
recuperation.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed the wisest course, but it also meant no one would be
with him before, during or in the immediate days after his surgery.
It was incredibly painful for us, so far away, to think of him
alone at such a time. I could not imagine how lonely and
anxiety-ridden it would be for him.
</P>
<P>
   As one who is constantly supported by her community of faith, I
turned to that larger family for help. I first called the hospital
where the surgery was to be performed and asked for the chaplain's
office. The staffer I spoke to assured me, after hearing our
situation, that she would personally meet with my brother before
surgery and check on him throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   With my pastor's help, we found a church of our denomination
that was close to my brother's home. I called and asked for their
assistance. The pastor was away, but I was connected with his
assistant.
</P>
<P>
   It must have seemed an odd call to this faithful church staff
member as she listened to a harried woman from half-way across the
continent explaining her family's situation. But she listened
patiently as I asked if someone in the church would be willing to
visit my brother after his surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will see if there is someone who can go, and if there isn't,
I promise you I personally will go,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the days that followed, each of these strangers showed great
kindness and compassion to my brother and our family. The chaplain
called my mother at least twice the day of the surgery to update
her on my brother's condition. A social worker gave us the names of
home health care providers, and the pastor's assistant went to
visit my brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just come from the hospital,'' she told me on the phone.
``It was such a joy to meet your brother. There is great tenderness
in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I told him who I was and that you had arranged for me to
visit him, his eyes welled up with tears. He very clearly knows how
much his family loves him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have three brothers of my own,'' she told me, ``and one of
them is in Texas. I would like to think that if he needed help,
someone would go to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides,'' she added, ``it's kind of what it's all about,
isn't it? Each of us helping the other?''
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't be there for my brother. I couldn't call for the
nurse or bring him ice chips or smooth his blanket. And I couldn't
be there to hold his hand and pray with him.
</P>
<P>
   But another could be _ and was.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald. She can be
reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
