<HEADER>
A4008 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANE-COLUMN20-COX     04-19 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Legislative symbol fight is for the birds
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ It is a political axiom that the smaller
the stakes, the bigger the fight. Legislators will fall asleep on
their ``yea'' buttons for millions of dollars in state programs but
argue furiously about license plates, the names of roadways or what
to include in the state's collection of official flora and fauna.
</P>
<P>
   Florida has an official state soil _ myakka fine sand, duh! _
and we have an official state reptile. We have an official
beverage, official butterfly, official fish, official flower,
official wild flower, official gem, official litter-control symbol,
official shell, official stone, official tree and official water
mammals, freshwater and saltwater.
</P>
<P>
   The last state-symbol fight was two years ago when
African-American House members objected to the official state song,
``Suwannee River.''
</P>
<P>
   They had a point. Lines like ``still longing for de old
plantation'' give off the faint aroma of burnt cork. But lacking
any good alternative song to this bit of tired minstrelsy, their
objections went nowhere. And in these clean-living times, I suppose
substituting ``Margaritaville'' would have been politically
incorrect.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Legislature debates a less offensive state
symbol, the state bird.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's state bird is the mockingbird. As insistent as a
lobbyist, as noisy as a journalist, as aggressive as a first-term
representative with bigger ambitions _ these are birds legislators
understand.
</P>
<P>
   But there is nothing Floridalike about them. Mockingbirds are
found anywhere in the United States and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Most people can't name their state bird. Most people assume the
flamingo is the state bird. Flamingos are printed on all the
lottery tickets, and no Floridian I know has ever put a plastic
mockingbird in his front yard.
</P>
<P>
   But the flamingo is not an environmentally correct choice. It is
an introduced species, brought here from somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   To my mind, this makes flamingos even more representative of
Florida, The Land of People Who Came Here from Somewhere Else.
</P>
<P>
   A fitting symbol of a transplanted people, however, is not the
stuff of a stately indigenous official symbol. Environmental groups
are pushing instead to make the scrub jay Florida's state bird.
</P>
<P>
   One would think this would not be a big deal. The scrub jay is
the only bird found solely in Florida. The only local candidate
around.
</P>
<P>
   They also are threatened. There are only about 11,000 left.
Scrub jays, unsurprisingly enough, live in scrubs, a habitat that
is giving way to houses, golf courses, roads, 7-Elevens and
whatnot. Some development interests take offense that a bird they
are crowding out of existence might become the state bird.
Property-rights activists smell an attempt to Get in the Way of
Progress.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association's lobbyist, the aptly named
Marion Hammer, blasted the idea. She characterized the bird as
``lazy'' with ``a welfare mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They eat the eggs of other birds,'' she huffed. ``That's
criminal conduct, that's robbery and murder.''
</P>
<P>
   Harsh stuff. Supporters countered that mockingbirds are no gems
among birdkind, either. They're mean and will go after squirrels
and cats.
</P>
<P>
   When legislators and lobbyists debate the relative morality of
wildlife species, you know things are getting strange in the state
capital.
</P>
<P>
   True to form, the right-wing House has opted for the mockingbird
while the moderate Senate is looking favorably on the scrub jay.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe as a compromise the Legislature will make the scrub
mockingbird the state bird and embark on an ambitious and expensive
cross-breeding program to produce a few. They would be indigenous
to the House speaker's district.
</P>
<P>
   I'm for making everyone happy. They could declare the flamingo
the official state lawn-ornament bird and the scrub jay, the
temporary official state bird. After we develop the jays out of
existence, the mockingbird could resume its title. Nobody wants an
official dead bird.
</P>
<P>
   With the matter thus disposed of, legislators could move to more
vital matters. Like naming an official state insect. I nominate the
palmetto bug. I expect the tourism industry already is mobilizing a
counter-campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
