<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUALITY ASIDE, COST OF MARINER BALLPARK EMBARRASSING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Sometime during the Behring reign of error, but before
the Seahawks announced the ill-fated attempt to move to Los
Angeles, a club official confided in me the estimated cost to fix
up the Kingdome to new NFL standards.
</P>
<P>
   He was searching for clues as to how the remodel cost would play
publicly. I told him his figure would get him and most of his
colleagues shot at sunrise. No blindfold. No cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   The cost: $120 million.
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, when it comes to stadiums, $120 million is
just a cost overrun. Offer to fix an old stadium for $120 million,
and insiders would say don't bother, because that pittance will buy
fresh paint, new carpet and two speakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Public Facilities District announced that the price tag on
the Mariners' new park had risen to $517 million, which struck me
two ways:
</P>
<P>
   -- It was announced on opening night, which challenges the
Mariners' record for atrocious timing _ November 1997, when the
club said Randy Johnson's contract wouldn't be extended while Ken
Griffey Jr. was announced as the winner of the American League MVP
award.
</P>
<P>
   -- Is anybody embarrassed by this figure?
</P>
<P>
   Public expressions of dismay seem mild. Oh, the state's teachers
plan to gather near the ballpark April 22 to demonstrate on behalf
of higher salaries, figuring the stadium is a classic case of
society's misplaced priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from that, the apparent shrug over costs that top the 1989
figure on Toronto's SkyDome (which also included a hotel and a Hard
Rock Cafe) to make it North America's most expensive jock joint,
indicates that the public is either inured to sticker shock or so
jaded it doesn't care.
</P>
<P>
   But some people are paid to care. So I asked one of them: Are
you embarrassed?
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is being cavalier about this,'' said Ken Johnsen, the
PFD's executive director. ``No one is saying, `Oh, that's just what
it costs.' Everyone has been cost-conscious on this project. The
contractors and managers of this project have a really good track
record of coming in at or under budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Whew. That's good to know. Imagine if they had been reckless or
foolish.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's two categories to the answer,'' Johnsen said. ``One is
that some of the increases were due to conscious decisions that are
improvements for fans. The other is: Do we wish we could have
understood some of the costs better going in? Yeah, sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``But did anyone here really screw up? No.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the obvious delays created by this winter's wretched
weather, Johnsen cited two major underestimations: the removal of
contaminated soil from the site, and the concrete work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't fully comprehend,'' he said, ``the complexity of
concrete work in the stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   He also cited at least four recent improvements added to the
bill by the Mariner owners, who are on the hook for costs beyond
the $417 million in tax money.
</P>
<P>
   The scoreboard was enlarged, the broadcast communications system
was upgraded, concessions areas were increased and the parking
garage expanded.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnsen allowed as to how each of those items would also
produce more revenue for the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's true, but is it a cost overrun if it brings in more
revenue?'' he said. ``In the long run, these things make the asset
more valuable.''
</P>
<P>
   By far the biggest problem with the stadium was change orders,
the construction term for alterations requested by owners after
plans were drawn up and bid upon or, in some cases, work was
completed.
</P>
<P>
   One example is the clubhouse whirlpool. The Mariners wanted the
large, walk-in kind sunk into the floor. Problem was, the concrete
was already poured. Tons had to be jackhammered out to accommodate
the pool, plumbing and wiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more change orders here than with any project I've
ever been involved with,'' Johnsen said. ``Everyone wishes that the
drawings were further along, but once you make the decision to go,
you go.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``go'' decision is what made this park so expensive. The 29
months from the March 1997, groundbreaking to the July 15 opener is
the shortest construction time among any of the new generation of
parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about 2000, but the Mariners were interested in
keeping the 1999 schedule,'' Johnsen said. ``They knew of the
potential for cost overruns, but there was not a doubt in their
minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnsen echoed what many other previewers have said about the
park.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take anyone through this who knows anything about
construction, I'm sure they would say this is a quality project,''
he said. ``I'd be really disappointed if the park was built without
the features and quality that will make this the best in the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   The yard, to most baseball followers, indeed will be grand. To
taxpayers and some citizens, whatever the explanations and
rationalizations, the place will be a civic indulgence beyond the
imagination of anyone with a sense of shame.
</P>
<P>
   For the Mariners, it's Safeco Field. For me, from here on, it's
the Guilty Pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 1108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
