<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plan for the planet
 &HT;    By Theresa Walsh Giarrusso
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Earth Day is just three days away _ do you have a plan
for the planet? Head to www.worldwildlife.org to find out
information about animal species at risk, global warming, the
endangered seas and forests for life. You can visit the World
Wildlife Fund's photo gallery featuring more than 40 animals,
including this hippo at left. Plus, find out how to help with the
annual Pennies for the Planet campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Mush mush!
</P>
<P>
   Follow 11 explorers as they journey to the North Pole at
www.aspirations.com. The team is using 20 sled dogs and
cross-country skis to navigate a sea of ever-shifting ice. On the
site, you can meet the team, its brave dogs and find out why it
calls its food GLOP! There will be daily updates on the team's
progress, plus scientific experiments for you to conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Rescue Me!
</P>
<P>
   Earn money for your school and clean up your environment through
the Kroger School Recycling Program. For every pound of clean, dry
plastic grocery bags, schools earn $1. A company called Enviro-bag
collects the bags and recycles them into new trash bags to sell in
Kroger stores. Kids from 250 Georgia schools have raised $20,000 by
rescuing 1.5 million plastic grocery bags from landfills. To learn
more call 1-800-866-3954.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 1111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4014 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NFK-FEATURE20-COX     04-19 0453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elementary school students join National TV-Turnoff Week
 &HT;    By Keith Still
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For most kids, a week without television would be
unthinkable. Unplug the Nintendo 64, and you're talking cruel and
unusual punishment.
</P>
<P>
   But students at Cobb County's Davis Elementary School are out to
prove that not only can it be done, it also can be fun.
</P>
<P>
   For a week starting Thursday, kids at Davis will voluntarily
join their families and millions of others in turning off their TVs
for the fifth annual National TV-Turnoff Week. The kids and their
parents have signed pledge cards not to watch TV.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the national event want people to see how too much
TV can keep them from reading, thinking, creating and interacting
with family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the kids at Davis don't think they watch a lot of
TV, this will be the first time many of them go without it
completely.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time I care for TV is when I ask my mom if we can
watch `Full House,''' said third-grader Andrea Brown. ``I like that
show because it's funny and not boring. Most TV is boring.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's fifth-grade sister, Kristin, also will forgo her
favorite shows in the popular Friday lineup on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth-grader Anne Kimball said she and her first-grade brother,
John, sometimes watch a lot of TV, but they'll turn it off this
week to spend more time with their family and play more games.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone will have an easy time with it. Kindergartners
Jared D'orazio and Krista Miller think it's going to be a long
week. And several kids think their parents or younger siblings will
probably sneak a peek at the news or ``Arthur'' while they're at
school.
</P>
<P>
   The school and PTA have a list of fun ideas to help the kids and
their families get through those tempting moments. Suggestions
range from making animals out of pipe cleaners or learning sign
language to taking a family walk or going to the zoo.
</P>
<P>
   If that's not enough, kids can consult veterans Devin Arch and
Will Spence. Spence took part in last year's TV-Turnoff and found
that it really wasn't that hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think television is really good for you,'' said
Spence, a fifth-grader. ``You see the characters the way they want
you to see them. It's not like in a book, where you can imagine
things.''
</P>
<P>
   For second-grader Arch, a week without TV is nothing. Every
year, her family unplugs the television, VCR and video games for
the entire month of August.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fine with me,'' Arch said. ``I forget about the TV. My
(16-year-old) brother doesn't like it very much though.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
