<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4015 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH20-COX     04-19 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATO bombings continue
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) forces
continued to pound military targets in Belgrade, Yugoslavia's
capital city, and in the Yugoslav republic of Montenegro last week.
Hundreds of thousands of refugees from Kosovo poured into
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
   More than a half-million people have fled or been driven from
Kosovo since March. Kosovo is a province in Yugoslavia that wants
to be independent. Kosovar Albanians, who are Muslim, have been
fighting with the Christian Serbs, who run Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials are investigating the accidental bombing of
Kosovo refugees fleeing the country. Serb officials say the NATO
air attack killed 75 civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Schools ban little monsters
</P>
<P>
   Be careful if you hang out with Pikachu or Jigglypuff _ they
might get you into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Principals around the country are banning students from trading
their Pokemon cards at school. Millions of the cards based on the
Japanese cartoon and video game have been sold in the United States
since January.
</P>
<P>
   The principal at Colonial Elementary School near New York City
has banned trading between pupils ``because some of our younger
kids were getting suckered out of their more valuable cards.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Wolski, a second-grader at the school, doesn't bring his
cards to school anymore. ``The teachers don't like it and the
principal said he'd better not catch us trading.'' Besides, he
said, ``Somebody was stealing them!''
</P>
<P>
   Planet system found
</P>
<P>
   Look! Up in the sky, it's a bird, it's a plane _ no it's a new
solar system.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists discovered for the first time three large planets
spinning around a star. The star, similar to our sun, is 44
light-years away. Lone planets circling a star have been spotted
before, but this is the first time multiple ones have been found.
</P>
<P>
   This discovery tells us that many of the galaxy's stars are
likely to have planets too, said Debra Fischer of San Francisco
State University. ``It implies that planets can form more easily
than we ever imagined.''
</P>
<P>
   The star the planets circle, Upsilon Andromedae, is usually
visible with the naked eye, though it is currently behind our own
sun and will not be seen until June.
</P>
<P>
   Bye-bye Wohlers
</P>
<P>
   The Braves traded troubled relief pitcher Mark Wohlers to the
Cincinnati Reds on Friday. The Braves received relief pitcher John
Hudek in return.
</P>
<P>
   In nine seasons with the Braves, Wohlers had 31 wins, 22 losses
and 112 saves. Wohlers, 29, refused a minor-league assignment last
week, and had to be traded or released. He's had problems
controlling the ball since last season.
</P>
<P>
   Hudek, 32, has a 10 wins and 14 losses during his career with
Houston, the New York Mets and Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
