<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4016 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHARP-DRIVING20-COX     04-19 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARP-DRIVING20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hummer likable even if you don't need one
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It has rubber floor mats, no air bags, no 5-mph
bumpers and a sticker price of $97,100. I've never felt safer in
any vehicle in my life. What is it? It's a Hummer, of course.
</P>
<P>
   When offered the opportunity to test drive the Hummer, I
halfheartedly accepted. When I would see a Hummer being driven on
the street, I would scowl, ``Disgusting display of excess.'' And,
yes, a Hummer probably is more vehicle than anyone really needs.
</P>
<P>
   But after a week with my competition yellow civilian version of
the same vehicle that our troops are using around the world, I came
away a fan.
</P>
<P>
   The evolution of AM General Corp. and its High Mobility
Multi-Purpose Wheeled Vehicle _ Hummer to civilians _ can be traced
to Willys-Overland Co. and its world-famous Jeep. It introduced
America to the small, four-wheel-drive utility truck.
</P>
<P>
   With some 350,000 vehicles produced during the 1940s in support
of the war effort, the jeep became a symbol of the U.S. Army. Soon,
peacetime commercial applications of the vehicle became popular,
and America embraced off-road driving in the Jeeps of today, such
as the Grand Cherokee and Wrangler.
</P>
<P>
   Look closely at your mail carrier's vehicle, and you can see a
similarity to the Hummer. AM General builds those little vehicles
mail carriers use.
</P>
<P>
   So how did the World War II jeep evolve into the Hummer?
</P>
<P>
   As technology changed, the Army's requirement for a new
generation of off-road, 4x4 vehicles became evident. In 1979, as a
subsidiary of American Motors Corp., AM General began preliminary
design work on the M998 series HMMWV. AMC also was the parent
company of Jeep, which later was purchased by Chrysler Corp., which
in turn has become DaimlerChrysler. AM General has remained
independent.
</P>
<P>
   The Army awarded AM General a prototype contract in 1981 that
led to the initial production for HMMWVs in 1985. Since then, more
than 170,000 HMMWVs have been produced for the U.S. armed forces
and foreign armies. The HMMWV proved prominent in the U.S. military
action in Panama and Operation Desert Storm. There are HMMWVs in
areas adjacent to Kosovo right now.
</P>
<P>
   AM General's introduction of a civilian Hummer in 1991 enabled
the general public to experience the off-road performance of a
military-based vehicle. The civilian Hummer has retained the same
drivetrain (a General Motors V-8, 6.5-liter 195-horsepower diesel
hooked to a GM four-speed automatic), full frame, double-wishbone
chassis with coil springs and basic body construction as the
combat-proven military version.
</P>
<P>
   Although a number of changes have been incorporated to produce a
more commercial vehicle (cruise control, electric windows, heated
front window, carpeted console that is large enough to hold three
full-size pizzas, adjustable armrests, CD/cassette stereo, rear
window defogger and, of course, cup holders), the design integrity
and superior off-road capability have been maintained.
</P>
<P>
   About as far off-road as I got was Atlanta's freeways, but you
never know when that $2,500 optional front bumper winch might come
in handy during rush hour, not to mention the central tire
inflation system that allows you to increase and decrease air
pressure in the Goodyear RunFlat tires without leaving the driver's
seat.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, with a ground clearance of 16 inches and the ability
to climb a 60 percent grade, the Hummer will just about allow you
to make your own road.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sharp's column is written exclusively for Cox News
Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 1111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
