<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 11:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4019 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A20-COX     04-19 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane S. Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm going to France soon and was wondering how much wine I
could bring back. I'd like to buy a bottle or two from each region
I visit. When I return, I would like to have a wine-tasting party.
_Toni K.
</P>
<P>
   A: You are 21, I assume ... and the wine is for your own use and
not commercial purposes. Every state has its own laws regarding the
importation of alcoholic beverages. When there is a conflict
between state and federal laws, the stricter is enforced by the
U.S. Customs Service.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If one's VCR is not compliant with Y2K, is it true you can
set the year to 1972 because the days and dates are the same as
year 2000? _Bill C.
</P>
<P>
   A: Should work. These years have the same calendar, including a
29-day February. Calendar refresher: Leap years are those divisible
by four except _ in the Gregorian Calendar's efforts to remain
precise _ years ending in ``00'' that are not divisible by 400. So
1600 and 2000 are leap years; 1800, 1900 and 2100 are not.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In her book, ``Hill Country,'' Janice Woods Windle said that
in 1918 your newspaper's name was the Austin Statesman. If that is
true, when and why was the ``American'' added? _ Jeanne Hewitt
</P>
<P>
   A: The Austin Statesman was the evening paper; the Austin
American, the morning. The two merged in 1924 and combined for
weekend editions, but it wasn't until November 1973 that
subscribers received ``The Austin American-Statesman'' on a daily
basis.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have the question of all questions. My best friend and I
are scuba divers intrigued by dangerous marine life. We are looking
for a professional dive crew to take us out into the Pacific in an
anti-shark cage to dive in LARGE shark-infested waters. Any way?
_Hunter C. Westbrook
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh ye of little faith. Contact Diversion Dive Travel and
Training, P.O. Box 7026, Cairns 4870, Australia, to sign up for
six- or nine-day excursions departing Adelaide. The trips cruise
the breeding grounds for sea lions and fur seals _ both look
appetizing to the great white shark. Meals, scuba tanks, weights
and belts are provided, but you must bring _ among other things _ a
warm, full-length wet suit, ``farmer john pants,'' regulator, mask
and hard-sole dive boots. Price? $3,125 plus air fare. Q: I do not
understand why stamp rolls are upside down. Who is responsible and
where do I voice my opinion?
</P>
<P>
   _A.R.
</P>
<P>
   A: Direct your ire to Stamp Management, U.S. Postal Service, 475
L'Enfant Plaza SW, Washington, D.C. 20260. Stamp coils are made for
the convenience of high-speed affixing machines, not Joe Consumer.
According to Don Smeraldi of Stamp Management, thousands of these
machines exist. He suggests you remove the stamps from the inside
of the coil.
</P>
<P>
   Q: After having a baby shower I noticed punch cup rings on my
antique, marble-top table. Mild soap and water didn't remove them.
I tried a small amount of toothpaste and a soft cloth _ no luck.
Help!!! The punch had fresh lemon and pineapple juice. The table is
a family heirloom. _Dolores D.
</P>
<P>
   A: The acid in the punch probably caused the rings. Christy
Stasswender of Southwest Marble &AMP; Granite Works says a poultice may
remove them. If not, you need a professional repolishing. Here's
Stasswender's poultice prescription. Dampen the area first. Mix
powdered chalk or talc with a 12-percent hydrogen peroxide solution
(the consistency of peanut butter). After applying it thickly (
1/4- to 1/2-inch thick) cover with plastic and allow to dry (24 to
48 hours). Remove, rinse with distilled water and buff with a
clean, dry cloth. Repeat if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently filed bankruptcy. I'm trying to find a credit card
for which you send money that is put in savings to establish
credit. Some cards don't accept someone with a bankruptcy; others
want your checking account number. Can you help? _B.S.
</P>
<P>
   A: A secured credit card requires a cash deposit as collateral.
In most cases, this deposit earns interest. Some banks issuing
secured credit cards report your status to a credit bureau.
Accounts in good standing may be eligible for an unsecured credit
line in several months. To re-establish credit, do not apply for
cards for which you will not qualify, says Nancy Bolitho, education
coordinator for Consumer Credit Counseling Service. An unsuccessful
inquiry (read: rejection) may show up on a credit report.Visit
www.bankcard.com for a list. Before you sign up for any credit
card, check the requirements, as this is a changing industry. Q: We
have been reading books by Louis Sachar. We wanted to know if he
goes to schools and talks to kids. How can we get in touch with
Louis Sachar? _Mrs. Horak's Third Grade Class
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, the winner of the Newbery Award and the National Book
Award for young people's literature for ``Holes'' does speak to
students. Unfortunately his schedule is full for this school year.
To contact him about speaking next year (there is a fee) write to:
Jeanne McDermott, Farrar Straus &AMP; Giroux, Inc., 19 Union Square
West, New York 10003.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am racking my brains trying to come up with a sentence of
the bluebonnet song. I learned it in elementary school:
``Bluebonnets, bluebonnets, with your coat so blue; Your white eyes
are shining through the silvery dew. ... and that you'll return
again to Texas in the spring.'' Could you find the missing words?
None of my Texas friends knows it! _Camille Yale
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, you missed Dianne Schoss, a teacher at Will Davis
Elementary School. The missing line is, ``I know you're a dolly
offered for the rain.'' Makes sense if you know the inspiration
behind the song, Tomie De Paola's book ``The Legend of the
Bluebonnet.'' Do not confuse this with the state flower song,
adopted by the Legislature in 1933, ``Bluebonnets,'' written by
Julia D. Booth and Lora C. Crockett. Its chorus ends, ``Texas chose
you for her flower, And we love you best, Bluebonnets.'' Q: How
might I get tickets for the Emeril Live shows in New York? _T.Z.
</P>
<P>
   A: The 1999 Emeril Live (New Orleans chef Lagasse) random ticket
lottery system closed Jan. 15. Sign-up for the lottery occurs once
or twice a year. Next season's info will be posted at
www.foodtv.com and on the Emeril Live hotline (212) 997-8836.
</P>
<P>
   Upshot/Update/Uproar
</P>
<P>
   Here is a reader recommendation for a roach cocktail. Mix one
part boric acid crystals (not powder) with one part sugar and three
parts cornmeal. Place in a small lid; put under sinks and in the
garage. Apparently this will deliver even the never-say-die variety
of roach to that great roach motel in the sky. Change the mixture
twice a year. Boric acid is a poison and should never be within
reach of children or pets.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin, TX, 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 1112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
