card, check the requirements, as this is a changing industry. Q: We
have been reading books by Louis Sachar. We wanted to know if he
goes to schools and talks to kids. How can we get in touch with
Louis Sachar? _Mrs. Horak's Third Grade Class
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, the winner of the Newbery Award and the National Book
Award for young people's literature for ``Holes'' does speak to
students. Unfortunately his schedule is full for this school year.
To contact him about speaking next year (there is a fee) write to:
Jeanne McDermott, Farrar Straus &AMP; Giroux, Inc., 19 Union Square
West, New York 10003.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am racking my brains trying to come up with a sentence of
the bluebonnet song. I learned it in elementary school:
``Bluebonnets, bluebonnets, with your coat so blue; Your white eyes
are shining through the silvery dew. ... and that you'll return
again to Texas in the spring.'' Could you find the missing words?
None of my Texas friends knows it! _Camille Yale
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, you missed Dianne Schoss, a teacher at Will Davis
Elementary School. The missing line is, ``I know you're a dolly
offered for the rain.'' Makes sense if you know the inspiration
behind the song, Tomie De Paola's book ``The Legend of the
Bluebonnet.'' Do not confuse this with the state flower song,
adopted by the Legislature in 1933, ``Bluebonnets,'' written by
Julia D. Booth and Lora C. Crockett. Its chorus ends, ``Texas chose
you for her flower, And we love you best, Bluebonnets.'' Q: How
might I get tickets for the Emeril Live shows in New York? _T.Z.
</P>
<P>
   A: The 1999 Emeril Live (New Orleans chef Lagasse) random ticket
lottery system closed Jan. 15. Sign-up for the lottery occurs once
or twice a year. Next season's info will be posted at
www.foodtv.com and on the Emeril Live hotline (212) 997-8836.
</P>
<P>
   Upshot/Update/Uproar
</P>
<P>
   Here is a reader recommendation for a roach cocktail. Mix one
part boric acid crystals (not powder) with one part sugar and three
parts cornmeal. Place in a small lid; put under sinks and in the
garage. Apparently this will deliver even the never-say-die variety
of roach to that great roach motel in the sky. Change the mixture
twice a year. Boric acid is a poison and should never be within
reach of children or pets.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin, TX, 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
