<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4025 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYBERSCENE20-COX     04-19 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Net a great source for free images
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the earliest days of computing, graphics and images
weren't very important. It was much the same during the earliest
days of the Internet and the Web, it was a text-based world here in
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   That made good sense because images take up a lot of space _ and
storage memory was at a premium in those days. And, because image
files tend to be large, they took a long time to download or
display while online.
</P>
<P>
   But the world has changed with faster computers and connection
speeds. And, since many of us have personal Web pages, a good
source of free images can be important. They're also useful for
decorating homemade invitations, as accent points in letters and to
create projects for school. The Web is a great source for these
free images and, today, we'll find some of the best spots to get
the picture.
</P>
<P>
   If it's Web page art you'd like, there's a site just for you.
It's called Design-it.Net Free Resources and is located at
design-it.net/graphicsdesigners/freefram.htm. This is a good
resource for the sort of images you'll need for a Web page, but if
that was all this page offered, it wouldn't be too exceptional. The
Web is full of catalogs of art. It's an added feature that makes
this a valuable resource, a great collection of links to Web design
programs and tutorials. After all, it's not enough to just have the
art, you need to know how to use it.
</P>
<P>
   So, browse the links here and you'll find a great way to brush
up on your Web design skills. And it's fairly up-to-date with
information on using the animated images that, over the past couple
of years, have become popular in Web design.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if animated images are your thing, we have a terrific
source that promises (and delivers) thousands of animated images
free for the downloading. You'll find that page at
www.auctionsww.com/freemall
</P>
<P>
   /animations.htm.
</P>
<P>
   You'll not only be impressed with the assortment of images
available here, you'll also like the way the page is organized. If
you've ever tried to search for a specific image on a page that
contains thousands of pictures with subject matter that ranges from
trees to trucks, you know what a chore it can be to find what you
want. But this page makes it easy with categories of images such as
sports, cartoons and signboards (made to be customized with your
own text and used as part of a Web page).
</P>
<P>
   The next Web page we'll visit offers instruction on using your
browser _ whether Netscape or Internet Explorer _ to download
images you find as part of a Web page you visit. The page, located
at webclipart.miningco.com
</P>
<P>
   /library/Tips/blhelp7.htm, has step-by-step instructions for
both PC and Macintosh users on grabbing images and saving them to
your computer. This will be a great help to many novices.
</P>
<P>
   There's one caveat we need to address. Some images are free and
available to anyone. But other images have copyrights and _ while
they can be downloaded _ it isn't legal or proper to do that. So
make sure, when you're mining the Web for images, you respect the
property of others and avoid violating copyright laws.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, since the image you need may be very specific, it could
be you'll need resources other than the usual Web libraries of clip
art we've mentioned. Use your favorite search engine to find the
image you want. Remember, you can use it to search for images, too.
Just include search terms such as ``clip art'' or ``image'' or
``download'' to narrow the search.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
