<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4026 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETWATCHER20-COX     04-19 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCHER20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Net a new dimension in the coverage of war
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ These are stories about life during wartime.
Real-time, ``you are there'' stories of how people cope daily when
the bombs are dropping nightly.
</P>
<P>
   Only in the age of the Internet could these wartime dramas come
from Belgrade radio station B92 (www.b92.org). That's the
independent Serbian radio station the government shut down April 2.
The station signed off with the words, ``We will never surrender.''
</P>
<P>
   Last May, Matt Drudge, the one-man Web-based gossip machine who
broke the Monica Lewinsky scandal, spoke to a skeptical crowd at
the Harvard Conference on Internet and Society. The crowd took a
dim view of Drudge's ``one-man-band'' approach to journalism, while
he insisted that in the future anyone with a computer and a modem
could become a publisher and report exactly what they want, and do
it just the way they feel it should be reported.
</P>
<P>
   While Drudge has pretty much dropped off the national radar, in
Serbia there are hundreds of populist journalists bringing their
own perspective to the war _ from angry condemnations of NATO, to
pleas for peace, to simple descriptions of everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   Even though B92 was shut down, a mirror site was immediately set
up in the Netherlands called ``Help B92'' (helpb92.xs4all.nl/). The
site continues to tell the stories of the people of Yugoslavia with
a special section called ``Personal Diaries.'' The diaries are
stories of the station's friends and colleagues who post, under
their own names, their personal wartime experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``To whom it may concern and to everyone who cares,'' begins one
diary. The writer is from Batajnica, a suburb of Belgrade not far
from a military airbase. He writes, ``I have been in Batajnica up
till now but the situation has become unbearable and terrifying.
The people of this community rarely have the chance to leave the
air raid shelters, since bombs are falling ever closer to my home,
day and night, with few and short interruptions of cease-fire. The
shelters are literally packed with people.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most chilling accounts comes from Vladislava Gordic,
an assistant professor of American and English literature at the
University of Novi Sad. Nightly, she says, she runs back and forth
from the air raid shelter to get her computer and use it to get her
story out to the world, ``as long as phone lines and my modem
permit, I will keep on writing, taking this down.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing of her experiences, she says she is reminded of a Kate
Bush lyric, ``As people around me grow colder, I turn to my
computer.'' She writes of trying to keep up her daily routines _
going to the university to check her mail and talk with the
students still coming to class, along with daily shopping trips to
stock up on supplies.
</P>
<P>
   She notes that as the bombings intensify, so do the items people
consider essential. ``In pharmacie (sic) everybody is asking for
the cheapest tranquilizer _ bensedin. ... The only person I know
that is not taking anything is me, even though everybody else in my
family is taking, not to speak about friends and colleagues. ...
The most animated debates often are around this topic _ what to
take, when and in what quantity.''
</P>
<P>
   Ducking in terror in air raid shelters, talking with friends
about the best tranquilizers to cope with another round of bombs _
this is what life is like in Yugoslavia right now, today. As
freedom of the press literally grinds to a halt in Serbia and
Kosovo, these online diarists sending e-mail from air raid shelters
are one of the few ways the rest of the world can find out about
the war and its aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the online community Egroups also posts as
many daily dispatches as it can on a discussion list called
Kosovo-Reports (www.egroups.com/list/kosovo-reports). It features
postings from anyone actually living in Yugoslavia. Most of the
postings are from Serbs vehemently attacking NATO's bombing
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   One list member, Zoran Radoslavjevic, writes that he was sitting
and talking to friends when the bombings began in his town. ``We
knew from cable TV that bombardment would start. But somehow, no
one seemed to believe that, at the end of the 20th century, such
thing was possible. OK, but why Novi Sad, the most peaceful
multiethnical town, that knows no bounderies (sic) among the
nationalities? Suddenly we heard the terrible detonation,
earthquake? No, it has began (sic). We rushed down the stairs, no
sirenes (sic), just children screaming, women crying. ... The
shelter was locked, nowhere to go.... We stood in the street, in
shock, in despair.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
