<HEADER>
A4027 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-CENTERPIECE-HDTV     04-19 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-CENTERPIECE-HDTV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Evolution of the television: HDTV
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's supposed to be the greatest advance in television
since color sets, but almost nobody has access to it _ at least not
yet.
</P>
<P>
   This advance is called High Definition Television, or HDTV. It
offers super-sharp clarity and CD-quality sound. The problem is
HDTV sets are big, some the size of refrigerators, and expensive _
they can cost from $5,000 to $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the cost, though, HDTV is slowly but surely entering the
marketplace. Some 13,000 sets were sold by the end of 1998, and the
electronics industry estimates a total of 150,000 sets will be sold
by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``HDTV is inching along,'' says Bill Wall, technical director of
the subscriber network unit at Scientific-Atlanta. ``Progress is
made relatively slowly. It's slow but sure.''
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, three stations are already airing some HDTV content.
They are ABC affiliate WSB, NBC affiliate WXIA and CBS affiliate
WGNX.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Scientific-Atlanta has begun shipping a version of
its Explorer 2000 digital cable TV set-top box that can receive
HDTV signals.
</P>
<P>
   While struggling to gain market share, HDTV will command top
attention among broadcasters this week as they gather for their
annual convention in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Some 100,000 network executives, station managers and TV
engineers are expected to attend the show, held by the National
Association of Broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   Attendees include the top brass of Scientific-Atlanta and
Atlanta's seven major commercial stations and Cox Broadcasting,
which owns WSB radio and television stations. Cox Broadcasting is a
unit of Cox Enterprises Inc., which also owns The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   And, in a first, cable TV pioneer Ted Turner will attend the
convention, speaking today at a luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   TV executives will be examining digital equipment, discussing
how to make it work and pondering whether to charge viewers for
additional channels carved out of their new spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   It will cost the industry _ the networks and their affiliated
stations _ from $5 billion to $10 billion to convert their
operations to handle digital TV. In addition to the high cost,
viewers appear content with TV as it is _ at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   So then, ``How will the broadcasters make money off digital
TV?'' asks Tom Wolzien, a media analyst at New York investment bank
Sanford Bernstein &AMP; Co. ``What's the demand? There's no way yet to
gauge the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Too bad, because HDTV is truly a revolutionary improvement in
television. It's based on digital technology, which can transform
video, sound and data into a stream of ones and zeros.
</P>
<P>
   The same technology powers personal computers and the Internet,
and now it's moving to TV.
</P>
<P>
   HDTV is an advanced form of digital television that provides
video at a very high resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The resolution is four times sharper than that of current
TVs,'' says Wall.
</P>
<P>
   HDTV, for example, delivers 2 million pixels _ those are the
dots that make up the picture on the screen _ in contrast to the
current system's 250,000. The higher the number of pixels, the
sharper the picture.
</P>
<P>
   And an HDTV picture has 1,080 lines per screen, nearly double
the current number. The result is a lifelike picture.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is so sold on HDTV that he struck a deal with
broadcasters last year to expedite its rollout. The deal gave every
station a free second channel. In exchange, broadcasters are to use
it to begin airing HDTV programming.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission pressed the nation's 1,500
stations to begin broadcasting now. So far, 42 of them have agreed
to do so. Today, these stations are airing select movies and
sporting events filmed in HDTV format.
</P>
<P>
   Many stations, though, are reluctant to embark on upgrading
their facilities to broadcast HDTV. The technology leaves them in a
Catch 22. HDTV is not just expensive for viewers. It costs, on
average, $5 million to $10 million to equip a station to produce
and send HDTV signals. Stations have to buy new cameras, editing
equipment and antennas, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   Converting existing films to HDTV isn't cheap, either. A movie
like ``101 Dalmatians'' costs on average $100,000 to reformat in an
editing studio.
</P>
<P>
   Such high costs are hard to justify when only a handful of
people will be watching HDTV. It's not just that the sets are
expensive. Imagine a refrigerator hung sideways on a wall. That's
the size of most sets today, and few homes can accommodate them.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if you're interested, you can find sets at various local
stores, including HiFi Buys, Circuit City and Best Buy.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise that industry consultant Forrester Research has
concluded HDTV will capture only 1 percent of the market in the
near term.
</P>
<P>
   How then, some wonder, will the TV industry meet the
government's deadline of 2006 for making HDTV the standard?
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't forget,'' says Yankee Group media analyst Bruce
Leichtman, ``we were under government mandate to switch to the
metric system in the 1980s.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Scientific-Atlanta's Wall: ``No one believes the FCC can
stick to its schedule.'' Nonetheless, Wall is convinced HDTV will
someday become the standard for television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite all the problems, HDTV is clearly coming,'' he says.
``Remember, color TV was adopted slowly, but almost no one uses a
black-and-white TV today. It will be the same with HDTV.''
</P>
<P>
   To buy or not to buy?
</P>
<P>
   PROS
</P>
<P>
   _ Bright, crystal-clear pictures that make television images
seem almost real.
</P>
<P>
   _ Six-channel, digital surround sound (for folks with properly
equipped audio systems).
</P>
<P>
   _ A new wide television screen, shaped like a movie screen.
</P>
<P>
   _ Digital transmission of the TV signal means the pictures will
be totally free of interference.
</P>
<P>
   _ Digital television signals also can be used to send e-mail,
Web pages, computer software and interactive programming.
</P>
<P>
   CONS
</P>
<P>
   _ High-definition sets sell for $5,000 to $10,000, and the price
probably won't dip below $1,000 for five or six years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Most of the sets are huge rear projectors, nearly as large as
a Volkswagen Beetle.
</P>
<P>
   _ The ability to receive high-definition programming carried by
cable is in its infancy (Scientific-Atlanta has begun shipping a
set-top box that can receive HDTV signals).
</P>
<P>
   _ Television programming filmed or taped in the last 50 years
was shot for today's square screen sets.
</P>
<P>
   _ The new wide-screen HDTVs will show programs in a vertical
``letterbox,'' with broad gray bands on the left and right of the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
