<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PC World lends advice on Windows 2000
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   In print
</P>
<P>
   For many PC owners, the big question is whether to stick with
Windows 95, upgrade to Windows 98, or wait _ and based on
Microsoft's track record of missing deadlines for new versions of
Windows, it could be a long wait _ for Windows 2000. No one knows
the answer for sure, but you'll get some helpful advice in the May
issue of PC World magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The cover story is ``Ultimate Windows ... Insider's Tips for
Windows 95 and 98.'' And, in the same issue, you'll get the
editors' opinions on whether you should wait for Windows 2000. One
tip offers information on how to speed up Windows by disabling some
of the features that come with Windows 98 including the feature
Microsoft calls the Active Desktop.
</P>
<P>
   If you've never picked up a copy of PC World, this may be a good
time to give it a try, because a third story in the magazine has
some surprising news of Intel loyalists. The magazine reviewed the
new K6-III chip from AMD (a competitor to Intel in the
microprocessor marketplace) and found that chip was actually faster
than the Intel Pentium III chip. Since it's also less expensive,
you may want to read the review and decide for yourself if you'd
like to break ranks with the Intel world.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   Do you have designs on a new home, or to remodel your old one?
</P>
<P>
   It can be a confusing process and involves expensive
professionals. Now there's a computer program from a company called
Dream Home Source that claims proudly on the package it's for
``do-it-yourself architects.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that may be a bit too ambitious for most folks but the
program _ called My House 3-D Home Design _ can help you organize
your thoughts and dreams into both interior and exterior drawings
that will, at the least, allow you to communicate your ideas in a
form easy to understand when you meet with an architect or
contractor.
</P>
<P>
   The program lives up to the 3-D brag on the box by letting you
rotate the views you design and to even use a feature called 3-D
MovieMaker to create virtual reality tours of the home. You'll also
find templates of typical home layouts that make the process of
designing faster and easier.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   It's the queen of the mountains. Men have died climbing her and
the fascination holds to this day. It's Mount Everest and the
National Geographic has created a Web site that celebrates Everest.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find the site at www.nationalgeographic.com/everest/.
Once there you can read about the Millennium Expedition that plans
to gather some basic information. You may be surprised, for
instance, to learn scientists don't know the exact height of this
famous mountain _ estimates vary. The new expedition intends to
answer this and other questions.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
