<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4032 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEB-DIARY20-COX     04-19 1320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-DIARY20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Online diarists put it all on the line
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Pamie's on a rant at her Web site, ``Squishy'' _
this time about how relationships change over time, with a handy
``before and after'' guide. After a few months, she says,
television viewing for couples changes:
</P>
<P>
   ``You watch thirty minutes of `Law and Order' and he changes the
channel. `I only like the Law part,' he says. You watch ten minutes
of `Seinfeld.' The commercials come on. He flips, flips, flips,
flips and only pauses on women's golf. `I am not watching this' you
say. `I'm just watching the sports ticker,' he says. He flips back
to `Seinfeld,' just in time for the final `bah-chicka-bah-bah ...
pock-a-pooka-pock.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Television time is his remote control,'' Pamela Ribon (known
as Pamie to her readers) writes on her Web site. Jump to another
Web site: Kramer Wetzel's ``Fishing Guide to the Stars.'' Wetzel is
excited because he just met Amy of ``Amy's Ice Cream'' fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been singing a sweet song about her ice cream for
years,'' Wetzel writes. ``Finally I get to meet the person behind
it all. `Come on by and I'll buy you an ice cream,' she said to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Television has MTV's ``The Real World.'' The big screen has
fictional versions life as we know it in ``Ed TV'' and ``The Truman
Show.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has online diaries such as Ribon's and Wetzel's
that turn life as they know it into virtual entertainment for their
readers.
</P>
<P>
   Some diarists just want to write. Others seek interaction with
readers. Still others have an exhibitionist streak.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the episodic nature of online diaries makes them
popular daily reads, and a growing number of writers are opening up
their diaries to the world.
</P>
<P>
   According to Diarist.net, the most comprehensive list of Web
journals on the Internet, there are about 1,100 active diaries
online. That's not counting thousands more that are unknown or
unavailable to the public. Journals can be as varied as real-life
diaries; some are little more than detailed lists of each day's
events. Others are less linear, putting style over truth and taking
extreme liberties with reality.
</P>
<P>
   Ribon, who performs with the comedy troupe Monk's Night Out and
is in tech support at Tivoli Systems, and Wetzel, a professional
astrologer, are Austinites who have turned their lives into open
books _ or rather, open Web sites _ posting their daily diaries on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   They write about their triumphs (performing at an HBO showcase
in Los Angeles for Ribon, Wetzel's new passion for lawnmower
racing), their tragedies (a three-month ordeal in which Ribon went
through testing for cancer, a near-death experience Wetzel had last
year), and all the minutiae in between.
</P>
<P>
   When Ribon began writing ``Squishy'' last June, she figured it
was a good way to exercise her writing skills. Almost a year later,
she has 500 readers who log in daily for her autobiographical
comedic essays.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a kid I used to pretend that I was on `The Pam
Channel,' '' Ribon said. ``Other people say they did this as kids,
too _ believing you're exposing yourself to the world. I guess
`Squishy' is a grown-up version of `The Pam Channel,' only this
time it's not just my cat watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Ribon, who says the makers of ``The Truman Show'' ``totally took
my premise,'' writes about her parents, her boyfriend, her stage
performances and her work at Tivoli. When Wetzel began writing a
Web journal as an offshoot of his astrology Web site, his goal was
to chronicle his life and to write about his ongoing love affair
with Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where else can you chronicle great things in Texas like
lawnmower racing on Auditorium Shores?'' he said in an interview.
``Can you think of a place that's weirder than Austin?''
</P>
<P>
   Wetzel said he's gotten in trouble in the past writing about
friends or romantic interests. In one instance, a woman who cuts
his hair was upset about a comment he made on site about a hair
streaking she'd performed.
</P>
<P>
   Deb, who asked that her last name not be used, recently removed
her online diary, ``Sometimes Deb,'' from the Web when the pressure
of keeping herself anonymous became too great.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never give the Web address to someone I know in real
life,'' she said in an interview. ``I knew there'd be someone out
there reading it, but I didn't really have to deal with their
reactions.''
</P>
<P>
   The diarist's secret life
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Ozawa runs Diarist.net in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often times, online journals are just the next evolutionary
step for people who keep logs of changes to their sites, or people
who write open letters to their family members in lieu of
snail-mail letters or family newsletters,'' Ozawa said. ``Others
see it as therapy, shouting to the world things they might not be
able to whisper to even their closest friends.''
</P>
<P>
   There are also those who promote themselves as the product of
their Web journals. Many writers use their online journals as a way
of sparking interest in their work and some take the idea of an
online identity to another level by adding still photos or live
video. ``There's a certain level where you become a voice,'' Ribon
said. ``And whatever face you have isn't going to match the face
the readers have for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Deb posted a photo of herself with each daily entry. ``Taking a
picture of myself before I started writing was a way for me to
become introspective,'' she said. ``I go to work, take care of the
kids, but when I would sit down to write, I'd shift the focus to
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   In real life, Ribon and Wetzel could be your neighbor or an
office-mate.
</P>
<P>
   Wetzel, who uses Threadgill's World Headquarters restaurant as
his base of operations for astrology reports, has long hair, a
Texas tan and favors Hawaiian shirts and baggy shorts. He is
self-deprecating, using his Texan lifestyle to skewer
preconceptions readers may have about him: ``Just because I live in
a trailer park, and just because I have fishing poles and a dead
cow skull on my patio, and just because I take a serious dislike to
any kind of a tie besides a bolo tie, does that make a me a
redneck? `` he wrote recently. ``It's warmed up nice in Texas, and
anything besides a pair of shorts is probably too much attire. Is
that so wrong?
</P>
<P>
   When the mood strikes him _ if he's talking to a waitress who
says something particularly insightful or when he gets an
interesting e-mail from a reader, he'll sit down to write, his
short entries leaping in points of reference from ``King of the
Hill'' to ``As You Like It'' to Jupiter's position in the heavens.
``There's not a lot of people out there who can work Shakespeare
and lawnmower racing into a coherent metaphor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ribon, on the other hand, takes about an hour each day to write
an essay on a chosen topic. Ribon, who posts conversations from her
life as dialogue on ``Squishy,'' has written about everything from
nose trimmers to her childhood to her recent use of Tae-Bo exercise
videos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have started to feel that tiny muscle that connects your hip
and your thigh. That is the first step to the new Pamie.'' she
wrote in one entry. ``I will have thighs like a stallion, a stomach
like... like a... flat...thing... I'll be the new me.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeting them, be warned: The conversation you're having might be
broadcast the next day, used as fuel for tomorrow's entry. ``I was
interviewed for the local paper yesterday afternoon about
`Squishy,''' Ribon wrote after an interview earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, this Saturday there should be an article. And of course
now that hours have gone by since the interview I'm thinking to
myself, ``Did I say the right things?''
</P>
<P>
   And on Wetzel's site: ``I have nothing to fear from another
reporter. The interview went just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
