<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    To: Uncle Sam, Re: Kid tax ideas
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A few months back, the folks at Intuit sponsored a
contest that asked kids to tell the government, in 25 words or
less, how to spend our tax dollars.
</P>
<P>
   It was win-win for everyone. Intuit makes TurboTax, a popular
brand of tax preparation software. And kids, apparently, say the
darndest things.
</P>
<P>
   The winning entry came from a St. Petersburg, Fla.,
third-grader. In all, 500 entries were received.
</P>
<P>
   St. Pete's Eric Burkett said the government should ``develop a
system that pays kids for doing different types of community
service. Turn the account over to them at the time they get
married.''
</P>
<P>
   For his suggestion, Burkett received a $1,500 contribution to an
education IRA set up by Intuit in his name.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 semi-finalists won $50 U.S. savings bonds.
</P>
<P>
   All the winning entries were delivered to President Clinton, in
plenty of time for their parents to be audited.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Henderson, a fourth-grader from Alpharetta, was the No.
2 semi-finalist. Henderson wrote, ``The government should spend tax
dollars figuring out how to make taxes easier. Parents should spend
time with kids instead of working on taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Maldonaldo, a fourth-grader from Cumming, suggested the
government spend tax money on NASA to enable them ``to destroy
giant meteors before colliding with Earth, destroying all life and
environments, like scientists believe happened to Mars.''
</P>
<P>
   A complete list of the winning entries is available at
www.turbotax.com.
</P>
<P>
   Turning back PC time
</P>
<P>
   Just in time for the Year 2000 bug, comes a software program
called GoBack.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by Wild File, a Minnesota-based company, GoBack bills
itself as the ``missing piece of the operating system. It is
neither a backup/restore product nor a utility product. It is a
remarkable tool that integrates itself into the operating system to
protect you from data loss.''
</P>
<P>
   The software, which retails for $69.95, recovers files that have
been deleted or written over, lost from virus attacks, or lost from
problems stemming from installation and system crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Wild File claims the software lets you back out of the problem,
regardless of whether you caused it or a system crash or a virus
attack did. The GoBack software keeps track of every move that
affects your hard disk. The software usually takes up about 10
percent of hard disk memory. It can maintain about a week's worth
of information.
</P>
<P>
   GoBack, according to Wild File, is different from a standard
backup function in that it does not copy the data to a separate
tape or disk.
</P>
<P>
   This is how the technology works: Once a glitch occurs, a
computer user picks the time he or she wants to go back to, up to
one week. Then the user presses a button to either revert the hard
drive or see the hard drive as it appeared at that time. The user
can see the older version of the hard drive through the Internet
browser.
</P>
<P>
   Once installed, GoBack runs automatically. The program is not
designed to replace traditional backup methods. It is intended to
provide the ability to recover information since the last backup.
It also lets a user recover from a system crash without using a
reboot or an operating system disk.
</P>
<P>
   The software, released in December, is designed for users of
Windows 95 and Windows 98. A Windows NT version is to be available
by mid-summer. The software is available at www
</P>
<P>
   .goback.com; www.supershops.com, www.virtual-world.com and www
</P>
<P>
   .tigerdirect.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
