<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    World of backup options explained for benefit of all
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A reader dropped me a line last week asking about
options for backing up his data, which for most of us is one of
those actions that kids refer to as ``let's don't, and say we
did.''
</P>
<P>
   There is probably nothing, outside the pulpit of a church, which
is preached about more and heeded less than backing up one's
computer data. It's a drag, and we think our hard drive, like our
hearts, will go on ticking forever.
</P>
<P>
   If there's anybody reading this who hasn't been bitten by hard
drive failure or accidental or negligent erasure, then they simply
haven't been computing long enough.
</P>
<P>
   There was a day not long ago when the individual computer user's
only backup option was a couple of boxes of 1.44 meg floppies. You
sat there like a frog on a log, popping disks in and out of the
hard drive every few minutes. Needless to say, it was boring.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there are a lot of more or less feasible ways of backing up
your hard drive, some of which will probably not even require your
attendance at the ritual. The first thing to consider is what and
how much you're going to back up. Do you want to back up only your
files, or do you want to back up your programs, too? Unless you
have a great abundance of backup space, or you have extensively
personalized and modified your programs, there's really no reason
to back them up. You can simply reinstall them in case of a hard
drive crash.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing you really need to back up are the files and
documents you have created with these programs. To this end, files
and documents ought to be kept in their own directories, and not
lumped in with the program files. It makes setting up a backup much
easier if you can efficiently order entire directories backed up,
instead of thumbing through everything on your hard drive, file by
file.
</P>
<P>
   Word processor documents ought to be kept in their own
directories, under one general master directory such as Windows' My
Documents. Same for worksheets and database files.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget other files that are created more or less
automatically, but are nonetheless irreplaceable. A good example is
your e-mail address book. Identify it and back it up. Same with
your Web browser bookmarks.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for the hardware options. The cheapest way by far to back
up vast amounts of data is a tape drive. Hewlett Packward, for
instance, has a 5 gigabyte internal drive using Travan technology
for a mere $169, and a 5-gig tape cartridge is just $25. That's the
cheapest backup option for serious amounts of data I could find.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I have little faith in tape drives. I've had several
and they've all been cranky. They're all slow, too, but that
doesn't matter too much since you can simply schedule the backup
for a time when you're away getting a life.
</P>
<P>
   For small amounts of data, there's the ubiquitous Zip drive from
Iomega. The 100-megabyte size can now be had in the internal model,
which is to be preferred, for less than $100. I've found Zip drives
to be perfectly reliable. The problem with the 100-MB kind is
you're likely going to have to preside over the operation, for one
disk may not hold it all. The disks are also rather pricey for the
capacity _ you can buy a pack of five for $60.
</P>
<P>
   You can go on up the Iomega range to the 250-MB Zip for around
$200 and the 2-gigabyte Jaz drive for about $350. The disks for
that baby run $125 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the optical drive class. I have no experience with
optical drives. A typical one seems to be the Fujitsu DynaMo, which
will store 640 MB on a $25 cartridge. It costs $329, and you'll
need an SCSI card to run it.
</P>
<P>
   Some people install a second hard drive and use it as a mirror
of the main drive. That strikes me as a little risky.
</P>
<P>
   There are computer failures that render the whole machine
senseless, in which case neither hard drive would be accessible
until the problem was fixed. A bad lightning strike, for instance,
could conceivably zap both drives. A fire would do the trick, too.
That, other than various schemes for storing backups in cyberspace
where they would be difficult to reach if your only computer
crashed, pretty well sums up backup options as I understand them.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
