r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECHNOBUDDY20-COX     04-19 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Enjoy the ads for the Pentium III but don't buy one
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The other night I started thinking about all the money
I've spent that wasn't mine.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, writing a technology column, I've urged you _
with just a touch of hysteria in my voice _ to rush out and buy
faster modems, bigger computers, more memory for the computer you
own, scanners for your photographs, shortwave radios and even a
fancy telescope.
</P>
<P>
   If I got a small cut, based on what the readers of this column
have purchased based on my recommendations, I'd now be out of the
big city and safely back in Arkansas, living happily with my
demented cat in a fieldstone house sitting near the juncture of the
Ouachita and Caddo rivers.
</P>
<P>
   That fieldstone house still sits somewhere in the future since I
don't get a cut. But I guess I do owe you some money and today,
I'll make a payment on that debt. I think I can save you a few
bucks if you're considering buying a new computer.
</P>
<P>
   You've been reading about the new Pentium III chip from Intel
for a few weeks. And the advertising barrage has begun in earnest
now. If you are like most computer users, the first nagging
feelings of inadequacy are beginning. That practically ancient
Pentium II _ my gosh could it be a year old? _ just doesn't seem up
to the complex technological challenges that face it such as
sending e-mail to Aunt Sally, playing Mutant Giant Spiders from
Planet Wazu and designing an invitation for your next party.
</P>
<P>
   You'll pay hundreds of dollars extra for a Pentium III compared
to a Pentium II. And here's what you'll get for your money: Almost
nothing. Your favorite programs may run a millisecond faster. And,
by and by, as new software is created that takes advantage of some
of the unique features of the Pentium III, you should get solid
speed improvements. But it'll be months before that happens.
</P>
<P>
   I'll bet, if you've been around computers longer than four days,
you already know what will happen by the time those months pass.
Raise your hand if you know the answer. OK. You, over there in the
blue lounging pajamas ... what's the answer? Yep. You're right.
Prices will nosedive by then.
</P>
<P>
   So, enjoy the ads for the Pentium III but don't buy one.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, just in case you just have to get more speed out of
your Pentium II, there are some things you can do that will give
you more bang for your dollar. In every case, these are
improvements you'll be able remove from the Pentium II and install
in a new machine when prices do fall.
</P>
<P>
   _ Add more RAM. If you have 32 megabytes of RAM, move to 64; if
you have 64 megabytes, double that amount. Windows 98 and 95 make
good use of RAM, translating the added memory into raw speed.
Here's the good news. You can expect to pay anywhere from $80 to
$100 for a 64 megabyte chip suitable for PCs with a 100 megahertz
bus and much less for slower RAM chips.
</P>
<P>
   _ Get a faster video card. After all, computing is mostly smoke
and mirrors. Everything you do with your computer, from slaying
monsters in a game down to writing a letter using your word
processor is based on graphics written to your screen. So if you
have a video card with 4 megabytes, get one with 8 or even 16
megabytes of VRAM (video random access memory).
</P>
<P>
   _ Consider a faster connection to the Net. Nowadays, most of you
spend hours on the Net. The math works like this: add a slow
connection to a fast computer and you end up with a slow computer.
If you're using an analog modem, make sure it's a good one and that
it operates at 56k bps. If cable modems are available in your area,
consider getting one, the speed increases are more dramatic than
anything you could believe without experiencing it.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the best thing about these small improvements:
</P>
<P>
   As soon as software is written to take advantage of the Pentium
IIIs _ and just as important, when the price comes down _ the
faster Net connection, additional RAM and better video card can be
used with the new machine.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
