<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4041 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIARY-HEATHER20-COX     04-19 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIARY-HEATHER20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Confessions of a diarist: Heather is me
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ ``Writing is supposed to be a kind of
confessional, transmogrified a little, but ultimately the place
where your triumphs of pride and the sins of your past are blended
with fictions.'' _ Heather Yi
</P>
<P>
   About six months ago, I had one of those creative bursts of
energy, the kind of sunbolt energy that warrants more than the
production of a greeting card or a short story. The kind that can
lead, when used, to novels or skyscrapers or symphonies.
</P>
<P>
   But I wasn't that ambitious. I just wanted to write a little
something and e-mail it to a few friends. I created a character
named Heather Yi, who wrote a first-person account of her life at
the University of Texas and about a classmate, Gina. The fictional
diary was e-mailed to friends, but I didn't tell anyone that
Heather Yi wasn't real. After a while, interest spread and I
decided to post the entries on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The result, ``gina,'' was more writing exercise than magnus
opus, but as an experiment, it taught me about more than just
writing consistently. Putting the journals on the Internet, under
the conceit that Gina and Heather were real people living their
lives on the site, showed me how malleable identity can be on the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   Most Internet users at some point have run into a case of
mistaken identity _ the person in the chat room who isn't who they
say they are, the person who may have the same last name and a
similar e-mail address, e-mails from anonymous spammers whose name
you will never know.
</P>
<P>
   But for a few months, as the Gina and Heather saga developed
into a 200-page mini-novel with character arcs, subplots and an
evolving theme, people read the journals religiously because,
unlike a novel, these people were real. The difference between
following the life of a fictional character and the life of a real
person is enormous. As Heather wrote her journal entries, readers
offered advice, admonished her for being too critical and related
their own stories about similar situations .
</P>
<P>
   And, while great writers consistently make characters that live
and breathe on the page, the rapport readers developed with Heather
Yi (who had an e-mail account on Hotmail) had more to do with the
anonymous, open nature of the Net than to the writing skills of
Heather's creator.
</P>
<P>
   Whether ``gina'' was successful as a work of writing doesn't
matter; the experiment, at least for me, succeeded because readers
began to care for these characters, following their lives, sharing
their dreams and disappointments. The fictional adventures of
Heather and Gina became an experience for this audience. And,
because it was supposed to be real, even a casual reader could
write in and affect the outcome _ which they did. The immediate and
often very frank feedback shaped the story and the writing as it
continued.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has become a place where those who want attention
can set up cameras in their home and broadcast their lives to the
world. It has become a place where a child's birth can be witnessed
live, in color, on any computer capable of watching. It has become
a place where, just like on television, celebrities can hawk bad
products and let the world see their plastic surgery as it is being
performed.
</P>
<P>
   But, most importantly, it's a place where strangers have learned
to care about other strangers and to reach out, communicating with
those they would never otherwise meet.
</P>
<P>
   For those of us who partake in that confessional, putting our
most intimate thoughts and our best words out there for anyone who
cares to read, there are few things more rewarding.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
