<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4046 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     04-19 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING TO CHAINSAW THE MEDICINE WHEEL HISTORIC PRESERVATION PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c. 1999 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once again, the drive for profit would invade sacred ground. A
Wyoming sawmill company has filed a civil suit against the U.S.
Forest Service for closing off a portion of the Bighorn National
Forest to harvesting timber. That portion of the national forest
contains a site sacred to many American Indian tribes, including
the Crow, Arapaho, Shoshone, Bannock, Blackfeet, Sioux, Plains Cree
and the Northern Cheyenne.
</P>
<P>
   The disputed area lies within the boundaries of the Forest
Service's Historic Preservation Plan for the Medicine Wheel
National Historic Landmark and Medicine Mountain. The Medicine
Wheel, an 80-foot-diameter circle with 28 rock spokes radiating
from a central, hollow cairn, is located atop the 10,000-foot
Medicine Mountain in Big Horn County, Wyo.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Medicine Wheel and the mountain are considered sacred
to tribes and are a significant part of the cultural heritage of
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   For over six years, numerous diverse groups participated in
developing the Medicine Wheel preservation plan: the Big Horn
County Commissioners, Advisory Council on Historic Preservation,
Medicine Wheel Coalition for Sacred Sites of North America,
Medicine Wheel Alliance, State Historic Preservation Office,
Federal Aviation Administration (which operates a long-range radar
facility located on Medicine Mountain), and Forest Service managers
of the Bighorn National Forest. They worked together to protect a
valuable cultural and spiritual resource.
</P>
<P>
   But trees must be cut for timber. So Mountain State Legal
Foundation out of Denver, which has an unfortunate tendency to see
the protection of American Indian sacred sites as a violation of
the First Amendment's Establishment Clause, filed suit for Wyoming
Sawmills Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The Bighorn National Forest includes more than a million acres;
approximately 40 percent of that acreage contains timber that can
be harvested. The land set aside for the Medicine Wheel Historic
Preservation Plan is a mere 18,000 acres, and less than 60 percent
of it is forested. It hardly seems necessary to go after timber
situated within a cultural landmark.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit filed by Mountain States Legal Foundation alleges
that the Forest Service's Historic Preservation Plan for the
Medicine Wheel National Historic Landmark and vicinity cancels
timber sales and timber harvesting for the ``sole purpose of
furthering Native American religions'' and ``to advance the
practice of Native American religions.''
</P>
<P>
   The four other claims made in the lawsuit allege that the Forest
Service did not follow federal guidelines when establishing the
Historic Preservation Plan. They are the obligatory, kitchen-sink
allegations found in most lawsuits. In a preservation plan that is
so complex, it is possible some federal guideline was overlooked.
It is clear the lawsuit hinges on the legal foundation's allegation
that setting up this historic preservation plan and closing off
portions of the forest to timber harvesting violates the
Establishment Clause: ``Congress shall make no law respecting an
establishment of religion.''
</P>
<P>
   The Medicine Wheel is the main feature in the preservation area.
But the surrounding acres contain various alignments of rocks, tipi
rings, travois trails, and caves used for tribal ceremonies. One
trail leads from the Yellowstone National Park over the Bighorn
Mountains to the Medicine Wheel. Although the origin of the
Medicine Wheel has been lost in antiquity, there is little doubt of
its ceremonial significance to American Indian tribes. Evidence
indicates that the area had been used by Indian tribes for nearly
7,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 20,000 visitors who came to view the Medicine Wheel
last year may have sensed the spiritual nature of this sacred site.
While there are non-Indians who scoff at the very notion of sacred
sites, it is deeply embedded in European tradition. There are
temples in Greece, Turkey and other parts of Europe that were built
over centuries, one upon another to glorify different deities. At
one site in Greece, a temple built to a goddess of fertility was
rebuilt to worship Athena, and much later rebuilt again to
celebrate the Virgin Mary. Those sites were recognized as somehow
sacred, somehow deeply spiritual.
</P>
<P>
   But the complex spiritual nature of Medicine Mountain and its
Medicine Wheel does not lend itself easily to such comparisons.
Many Indian tribal leaders regard Medicine Mountain as the
significant spiritual landscape and the Medicine Wheel as a
component of that landscape.
</P>
<P>
   How then, does a sawmill company, which must bid on timber sales
in national forests, lose if a small percentage of the total
acreage of the Bighorn National Forest is closed to timber
harvesting? And if there is a loss, what is it compared to the
preservation of sacred ground?
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has lived near logging roads knows the dust and
noise, the whine and roar of truck engines. Anyone who has heard
chainsaws used to down trees knows the unrelenting buzz and brack
of steel against live wood. How is one to seek the spiritual with
the shrill screech of profiteering ringing in the soul? Where there
is no silence, there is no spiritual solace.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has walked in mountains anywhere knows the importance
of silence, the importance of feeling at one with the land we walk
upon, the importance of recognizing some essence beyond ourselves.
Silence allows us to explore that realm.
</P>
<P>
   The Medicine Wheel Historic Preservation Plan accommodates
American Indian religions, as it should. The plan does not prohibit
Wyoming Sawmills Inc. from making a profit from timber harvesting
in other areas of the Bighorn National Forest. There is no clash of
one against the other. And there is no Establishment Clause
violation here, only wise accommodation to the best in all of us _
a recognition that every culture's religious beliefs deserve
protection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 1127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
