<HEADER>
A4079 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-REVIEW-MOUNTAINS     04-19 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-MOUNTAINS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUTERSON IS BACK WITH A COMPELLING DRAMA
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) 
 By JUDYTH RIGLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Guterson captivated readers with his 1994 novel, ``Snow
Falling on Cedars,'' a tightly crafted literary thriller about a
racially charged murder trial in post-World War II Puget Sound.
</P>
<P>
   The book's engrossing plot line aside, Guterson's gift for
descriptive passages stirred an interest in the Pacific Northwest
something akin to what ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil''
did for Savannah, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snow Falling on Cedars'' has sold more than 3 million copies
in hardback and paperback.
</P>
<P>
   Guterson's name and pictures (invariably showing his ruggedly
handsome frame clad in flannel shirts and jeans, seated on a tree
trunk on his Bainbridge Island property) have been splashed all
over newspapers and magazines. The movie version of ``Snow,''
starring Ethan Hawke, will be released in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the teacher-turned-novelist has given us a second
novel, ``East of the Mountains'' (Harcourt Brace, $25). It shares
the Washington state setting of its predecessor, but little else
(except, we're delighted to report, the writer's gift for
spellbinding storytelling).
</P>
<P>
   Guterson doesn't keep the reader in suspense about his plot line
for very long. Here's his opening sentence: ``On the night he had
appointed his last among the living, Dr. Ben Givens did not dream,
for his sleep was restless and visited by phantoms who guarded the
portal to the world of dreams by speaking relentlessly of this
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben is a 73-year-old retired heart surgeon who has inoperable
colon cancer; the near-constant pain in his gut and a rapidly
declining energy level are steady reminders of what lies ahead.
Still reeling from the death of his beloved wife, Rachel, a year
and a half earlier, Ben has decided to go off in the woods with his
hunting dogs and stage an ``accident'' rather than die in agony,
slowly.
</P>
<P>
   As he sets off on his final hunt, Ben indulges himself in
memories: of growing up on his father's apple farm; of falling in
love with Rachel and enduring a separation while she served as an
Army nurse in France during World War II and he fought in Italy; of
the pleasures of the outdoors and the joys of bird-hunting with
well-trained dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Ben recognizes the irony of spending a career saving lives, yet
being unable to save his own; but he is not bitter. The reader
quickly decides that Ben would be a good man to spend time with, as
do several characters Ben meets when his carefully crafted plan
begins to unravel after he wrecks his car.
</P>
<P>
   Just when he has decided that there is nothing left to lose, no
reason to go on, Ben learns that life always has some surprises in
store and that, sometimes, what you think is the end is only
another kind of beginning.
</P>
<P>
   To Guterson's everlasting credit, there is not a shred of
sentimentalism here despite the well-traveled and oft-cliched
territory of loss and pain.
</P>
<P>
   Using his skills of characterization and description, he makes
Ben's difficult journey bearable, our insights both personal and
universal.
</P>
<P>
   With a first printing of 500,000 copies, Harcourt Brace has
shown faith in Guterson's second time at bat; from here, it looks
as if he's hit another home run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 1208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4096 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHAKESPEARE-CENTURY-H     04-19 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAKESPEARE-CENTURY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOIL, TROUBLE WELCOMED SHAKESPEARE'S NEW CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RICHARD MATTURRO  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ We're making much of the turn of the century this
year. With William Shakespeare's birthday coming up on April 23, an
Academy Award-winning film about him playing in the theaters, and
Harold Bloom's new book, ``Shakespeare: The Invention of the
Human,'' on best-seller lists around the country, let's pause for a
moment to consider the turbulent times that Shakespeare faced in
the waning days of the 16th century.
</P>
<P>
   When Shakespeare was born in 1564, Queen Elizabeth had been on
the throne for six years, and she would remain the only monarch
Shakespeare knew for most of his life. It was a heady time in
England. In 1588, the small navy of that small island had defeated
Spain, the greatest sea power on Earth. The religious conflicts
that plagued the continent and even plagued Britain before
Elizabeth's reign were largely absent due to the queen's shrewd
tolerance of religious differences.
</P>
<P>
   There was a thriving economy. There were voyages of discovery to
the New World. And in literature, Elizabeth presided over the
greatest flowering since the Golden Age of Greece.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many saw a serpent lurking in Gloriana's garden. Elizabeth
had no heir. For reasons which were perhaps political, personal or
both, she never married. The recent film about Elizabeth shows her
cavorting in bed with her lover, the Earl of Leicester. Considering
the unreliability of birth control in Renaissance England, it is
doubtful that such a scene ever took place.
</P>
<P>
   Intelligent and prudent in all her other dealings, Elizabeth is
unlikely to have taken such a risk. She may indeed have earned the
title, ``Virgin Queen,'' which we can scarce utter without a smirk.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of an heir, however, was a serious problem. The English
Wars of the Roses, which Shakespeare himself dramatized on the
London stage, had ended barely 100 years before, more recent to
Shakespeare's audience than our own Civil War is to us. And what
the Red and the White Rose factions had fought over was the
succession. No one wanted that chaos to come again.
</P>
<P>
   Not having produced an heir, Elizabeth was urged by her council
to name a successor, something she steadfastly refused to do.
Again, her reasons might have been personal or political, but in
any case she kept mum.
</P>
<P>
   The dawn of the new century brought the crisis. Elizabeth was in
her late 60s, and her new favorite, the Earl of Essex, tried to
incite a rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   We don't know what Shakespeare thought about Elizabeth. His only
surviving reference to her in her lifetime is a brief poetic
tribute embedded in ``A Midsummer Night's Dream,'' a play the queen
probably attended. Nor do we know for sure what he thought about
Essex, but Essex was a close friend of the Earl of Southampton, the
man to whom Shakespeare dedicated ``Venus and Adonis,'' arguably
the most popular poem of the age.
</P>
<P>
   It was Essex, too, who paid Shakespeare's company to revive an
old play, ``Richard II,'' on the eve of the rebellion on Feb. 8,
1601.
</P>
<P>
   It was the closest Shakespeare ever got to being in trouble with
the law. Richard II, a flawed monarch, is deposed in the course of
the play, and Essex imagined that the London public would see the
parallel with Elizabeth and rally to his cause. They did not, and
Essex was quickly apprehended.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare's company was hauled in for questioning, but
exonerated.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth lived for two more years, and died never having named
a successor. Yet, for all the anxiety over who would rule after
her, the transition of power was one of the smoothest in English
history.
</P>
<P>
   Upon her death in 1603, Elizabeth's council offered the crown to
her distant cousin, James, the king of Scotland. James readily
accepted, thereby merging the two kingdoms.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Shakespeare may have felt during this eventful time,
his company certainly benefited from the new regime. King James, it
turned out, loved the theater, loved it almost as much as he loved
demonology and witchcraft. He adopted Shakespeare's company, and
they became known as the King's Men from then on.
</P>
<P>
   To honor their patron, Shakespeare wrote a new play. Set in
Scotland, not overly long (for James had a short attention span),
it told an old tale from Scottish history, and for the king's
special delight, Shakespeare filled it with witches and necromancy.
</P>
<P>
   We know the play as ``Macbeth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 1231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0151 </DOCNO>
