<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-KILLING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TOWN STRUGGLES WITH LESSONS OF BRUTAL KILLING
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) 
 By CARY CLACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ For 10 months, how and why James Byrd Jr. died
has forced the town of Jasper to look at itself and reflect on its
character.
</P>
<P>
   On June 7, 1998, three young white men allegedly beat Byrd
before tying him to the back of a pick-up truck and dragging him
for three miles along a rural road, a gruesome journey that ended
when the black man's body slammed into a concrete culvert that tore
off his head and right arm.
</P>
<P>
   John King, has been convicted in the murder; his accused
accomplices, Russell Brewer and Shawn Berry, await trial.
</P>
<P>
   Since the crime, the people of Jasper have sought to understand
how their town could have produced one of the most notorious racist
crimes in the United States since the civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   Rather then shun the spotlight, the residents have used the
exposure to try to demonstrate that they are good people who
shouldn't be judged by what happened to James Byrd; that, yes, they
have racial problems, but it's a town where people try to work
together and in which blacks, who make up 45 percent of the
population, hold a number of important and elected positions,
including mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper, population 7,120, is an ordinary town defined by an
extraordinary horror. But what should frighten the rest of the
nation about Jasper is that it is so ordinary, a community like any
other that was coasting along the road of unresolved and unspoken
racial problems until a mad pre-dawn ride slammed it into reality.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than use Jasper as a scapegoat for America's racist sins,
the nation had best use it as a cautionary tale of the consequences
of unchecked hate.
</P>
<P>
   For just as Jasper peers into Byrd's tomb to examine itself, the
nation need only to look at Jasper to see its own reflection.
</P>
<P>
   There is no corridor of burning crosses and nooses hanging from
pine trees to greet you as you drive into Jasper on Texas 96, the
main strip through town cluttered with fast-food restaurants and
other businesses.
</P>
<P>
   It is in eateries, gas stations, the grocery store, the car wash
on Pollard Street, Sandy Creek Park, on the streets and in
neighborhoods whose lawns blush with azaleas that the blacks and
whites of Jasper mingle, talk and laugh. And, of course, there's
that great multiracial meeting place of American democracy,
Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   This is how they lived before June 7, 1998, as well as since,
though perhaps with a bit more thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's helped this town,'' Diane Cox, owner of the Book
Emporium &AMP; Gallery, said about the Byrd killing. ``The whole
community is making an effort to be nice.''
</P>
<P>
   The people of Jasper are working harder at a civility that they
once took for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, the comments are made by whites such as Cox. But she
isn't one to paint a picture of a Jasper devoid of race problems.
She said that when she moved here from Birmingham, Ala., 23 years
ago, ``It was like stepping back in time.''
</P>
<P>
   She scoffs at the removal, in January, of the rusty iron fence
in the Jasper City Cemetery that separated the graves of blacks
from those of whites.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the most ridiculous thing,'' she said. ``Not that I
agreed with the fence. But when they bury someone of color on the
white side, then I know there would have been change. But I don't
think it's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   In the cemetery, on an overcast Good Friday, Vaye Wood, a
37-year-old black woman who grew up in Jasper but now lives in
Dallas, drove up to Byrd's grave with her mother, Juanita Walker.
She rolled down her window and stared pensively at the grave.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my first time seeing it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Byrd case indicated the town had a racial problem,
both women emphatically answered no.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not,'' Wood said. ``I never had this kind of problem.
When I was a girl I went over to white girl's houses and they came
over to mine.''
</P>
<P>
   At Billy's BBQ, a small wooden red building on North Main, a
middle-aged black woman with short hair tinted blue waited for her
order.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the `The Jewel of the Forest,''' Willie M. Sharp proudly
called her hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't resent it,'' she said of Jasper's stigma since the
Byrd slaying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think it's making us stronger. Everyone knows that's
not the way it is here. We're showing the world that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Willis Webb interviewed for the job of editor and publisher
of the Jasper Newsboy eight years ago, he asked about the state of
race relations in the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, everything is great,'' was the overly enthusiastic reply
he received.
</P>
<P>
   Now Webb is able to offer his own assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been unfairly stigmatized,'' said Webb, 61.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, ``Unless we kid ourselves, all is not right with
race relations. We have a lot of disenfranchised black people. If I
were black, I'd be angry as hell.''
</P>
<P>
   With an unemployment rate of 11 percent in Jasper County, the
county seat is struggling economically, creating, said Webb, an
invisible wall that blocks residents economically whether white or
black.
</P>
<P>
   Webb is a member of the Mayor's Task Force 2000 that was formed
by city leaders and clergy, after Byrd's death, to help reconcile
racial differences.
</P>
<P>
   He is ``cautiously hopeful'' that something good will come out
of it.
</P>
<P>
   What's most important, he said, is for everyone to accept
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We each have to ask ourselves, what little have I done that
might have contributed to this, that allowed this to happen. I
didn't know the three guys but if I did and heard one of them say,
`I hate blacks' and didn't challenge him, I contributed to it.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the disenfranchised young blacks Webb spoke about is
Derric Muhammad, a 33-year-old sales representative who belongs to
the Nation of Islam.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like any other town, city or village,'' the Jasper native
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world ain't nothing but a ghetto. I don't care where you
go. I can go down to Houston and get the same kind of treatment
from anybody. The world ain't nothing but a ghetto, so I don't just
stigmatize Jasper, but I do know Jasper. A lot of people were
surprised and I was shocked at it (Byrd's murder), but I ain't
going to say it caught me by surprise. That's just some mentality
anywhere you go. They just happened to act on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad also is a member of the Mayor's Task Force 2000, albeit
a skeptical one. ``You can't help none who doesn't want to help
themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every discussion about the Byrd case is punctuated with
praise for the Byrd family and the way they have conducted
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they'd not been the kind of family they were, this place
would have been burned to the ground,'' Webb said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Byrd family really kept this town together,'' Cox
said.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, James Byrd Sr. and his wife, Stella, have become the
first family of Jasper, a position attained by the dignity and
strength they have displayed.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Byrd politely declined a request for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'm up to it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It was understood.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Cary Clack is a columnist for the San Antonio Express-News,
P.O. Box 2171, San Antonio, TX 78297.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
