<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE THAN `JUST A FRIEND' 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Every time a new nurse, lab technician or doctor
came into M.E.'s nook in the emergency room, she or he would say to
me: ``Are you her daughter?''
</P>
<P>
   Each time, I answered the same way: ``No, just a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Why did I tack on that diminishing qualifier? Just a friend.
</P>
<P>
   As if friendship were some minor league entity in the great game
of human relationships.
</P>
<P>
   The only person who didn't get the ``just'' answer was a
Catholic priest we'd gotten out of bed at 4 a.m. because M.E.
already knew she'd had a heart attack and suspected she might buy
the farm. The reverend father didn't want to know who I was but
only, ``Would you like to take communion, too?''
</P>
<P>
   All the while that I was with M.E. in the emergency room and the
intensive care unit (until they took her for a heart
catheterization and suggested I go home and sleep), our friend
Carolyn was back at M.E.'s house. Her task was to watch over M.E.'s
roommate of 37 years, a woman who is disabled by Alzheimer's
disease and cannot be alone.
</P>
<P>
   As the days wore on into the next week _ M.E. did not buy the
farm _ Carolyn, I and a handful of other just-friends coalesced
into a sort of multiheaded rescue unit.
</P>
<P>
   Phoning each other several times a day, we coordinated with a
terrific agency called Help at Home for 24-hour care for M.E.'s
roomie. We called M.E.'s sisters and other kin back East and her
closest friends in the San Francisco area. We canceled standing
appointments the two women had for everything from mammograms to
hair cuts.
</P>
<P>
   After M.E.'s name went on the prayer list at our church, fellow
parishioners asked what they could do. Grocery lists were compiled,
filled and delivered. Fresh flowers and communion made their way to
M.E.'s hospital room.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody brought her the newspapers she ached to catch up on,
and somebody else gathered up some makeup so she could put on a
little lipstick and feel less like something the cat dragged in.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes, some folks actually put aside their revulsion at used,
stinking kitty litter and cleaned out the box that M.E.'s pair of
poor, confused cats had saturated.
</P>
<P>
   If I make the whole process sound seamless and easy, it wasn't.
Everyone on the multiheaded unit has a full-time, demanding job
except M.E.'s friend Joan. She's retired but carries around a
fairly sizable load of stress herself these days because her own
housemate is undergoing mega-chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Joan found (or created) the time to pitch in. Funny how
you can do that when you absolutely have to. And want to.
</P>
<P>
   I tried to explain this to a man earlier this week when he asked
what I'd been doing lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's great,'' he said. ``Then when you need help down the
road, somebody might be there for you.''
</P>
<P>
   I said it didn't have anything to do with down the road or
trying to sow good karma. It had to do with being somebody's friend
NOW.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, after I'd relieved Carolyn and taken M.E.'s
roommate out for a walk in the sunshine, I was driving back to
work, listening to Dr. Laura Schlessinger practice her
healing-through-humiliation on the usual sorry lineup of radio
clients. (I make myself listen to Dr. Laura at least once a week as
a reminder of how much money there is in emotional S&AMP;M.)
</P>
<P>
   On this day, the good ``doctor'' was on a roll about the
throw-away mentality of people who ``shack up,'' men and women who
``cohabitate and fornicate'' and then ditch their alleged loved
ones at the first sign of rough road.
</P>
<P>
   Properly married people who've made a ``real commitment'' to one
another, she said, know they must hang in there and take care of
each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the difference between being married and shacking up,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   I thought about all the gay men I know in this town who've
nursed lovers and friends through years of pain from AIDS. I
thought about unmarried heterosexuals who've taken care of lovers
and friends through mental and physical illness, injury and
poverty. And I thought about our multiheaded rescue unit that had
materialized almost as swiftly as the paramedics did the night of
M.E.'s heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   All of us certainly seem bound and committed, but by what? Not
blood or formal vow.
</P>
<P>
   Might the glue be love? That deep, powerful force that (sorry,
Dr. Laura) is not the exclusive domain of properly married women
and men. The kind of love that shows there is no such thing as
``just'' a friend.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter &LR; examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
