<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4144 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CHILDREN-ART-B     04-19 1623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHILDREN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR KOSOVO'S CHILDREN, WOUNDS RUN DEEP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRAZDA, Macedonia _ In the days before Jeton Hasani saw what a
5-year-old should never see, the warmest moments of his life were
spent sitting in his grandmother's lap as she darned socks and he
watched cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   Then Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic unleashed a brutal
campaign that forced more than a half-million Kosovars, most of
whom are children like Jeton, out of their homes and running for
their lives from burning villages.
</P>
<P>
   Deep wounds _ physical and emotional _ have befallen the
youngest refugees of the war for Kosovo. Childhood, for them, is no
longer just a time of innocence and play. The inheritors of
Milosevic's destruction, they are now children of war.
</P>
<P>
   You can't see the damage in Jeton's eyes or in the shy smile he
gives a stranger. But it is there, his parents say. He doesn't
sleep. He is easily frightened. He won't leave his mother's side.
</P>
<P>
   On the second night of NATO's airstrikes, Serb forces fired a
mortar shell into Jeton's hometown of Metrovica. It exploded in the
garden. His grandmother, trying to find cover, was hit.
</P>
<P>
   The blast knocked out electricity. The family cowered in deep
darkness inside their home. They heard Arifa Hasani, 57, a
matriarch of five children and 10 grandchildren, gasping in the
hallway. Jeton's uncle lit a lighter. In the flickering glow, Jeton
saw his bloodied grandmother, dying.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is at an age where he will never forget,'' said Fatmire
Hasani, 30, his aunt. ``We're afraid this image will never
disappear. He wakes up at night and he is very afraid and never
lets his mother leave him.''
</P>
<P>
   Fatmire, a teacher with a gift for dealing with children, said
Jeton was extraordinarily close to his grandmother. They spent
every day together, and the boy smiles now when his mother shows
him a cracked photograph of his grandmother holding him as a baby.
He asks for her at night.
</P>
<P>
   The morning after the family buried Arifa in the garden, armed
Serb paramilitaries came to the home and ordered the family to
leave. The family clambered into a tractor and began a one-week
odyssey through Kosovo. They landed in the misery of the ``no man's
land'' on the Macedonian border. Ultimately, they ended up in tent
number D-284, where the family has been for over a week. Inside the
tent on Thursday night, Jeton sat in his mother's lap, clinging to
her and staring out at a descending darkness.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of this conflict has already taken a deep toll on
children. But international relief workers here and in Albania say
they are bracing for the new wave of as many as 200,000 more
refugees fleeing Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   These refugees, they fear, have seen even more violent episodes
and experienced more physical suffering. Many families have camped
out in snow-covered mountains hiding from Serb troops for as long
as two weeks. Medics are already seeing an increased caseload of
hypothermia, malnourishment, pneumonia, and diarrhea, says Dr.
Dieter Jacobi of the German Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   In an emergency medical tent at the camp, the tiny, wrinkled
faces of 3-month-old twins, Ghani and Garip Hysa, peered out of the
thick glass of an incubator. Their cries were muffled through the
glass, and the sound of a machine mechanically pumping oxygen into
the incubator was a steady rhythm in a pediatric medical full of
coughing and crying children. Severely malnourished and suffering
from pneumonia, the twins weigh 6 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were so happy when they were born, and they were so
healthy,'' said their mother, Farizad, who was wrapped in blankets
and lying on a canvas stretcher next to them.
</P>
<P>
   She said they arrived in the camp Thursday night after two weeks
of hiding in the fierce cold and forbidding terrain of the
mountains. Like tens of thousands of refugees forming the second
wave out of Kosovo, she, her husband, their 3-year-old daughter,
and the infants were hemmed in between the mountains and the
Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   She said she could feel her children dying in her arms. The two
boys shivered in the cold and slowly drifted into deep sleep that
she feared was death, except she heard a faint wheezing in their
lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Alkan, a member of the Israeli army's medical corps
treating the twins, said, ``It is very touch and go. They are on
the edge of their lives. We pray we can keep them.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams of pediatricians, child psychologists, and teachers are
gathering here and in Albania to help children through the crisis.
The United Nations Children Fund is building schools and day care
centers to help bring some sense of normalcy and routine back into
young shattered lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hope is to engage them, to help them cope with their
distress by getting them to draw, play soccer, read books, and to
do, as much as possible, what normal children do,'' UNICEF
executive director Carol Bellamy said while touring camps in
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Rune Stuvland, a Norwegian child psychologist who set up a
UNICEF-funded program to assist the children of Bosnia, has seen
the devastating Balkan hatred and violence before. He is now
training counselors, social workers, and teachers from the Albanian
community to spot the signs of post-traumatic stress in children.
The obvious manifestations of trauma, he said, are insomnia,
depression, lack of attention, and withdrawal. In boys over age 12
there is also aggression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children live in a very small world,'' Stuvland said.
``Suddenly it has all been taken away: home, school, friends. They
are all gone now. So what we have here is a whole population that
has been traumatized by what's going on. The Albanian family
structure will help them a great deal.''
</P>
<P>
   But scores of children here and in Albania have lost even that.
A 5-year-old girl, Jehona Alieu, was found wandering the ``no man's
land'' between Yugoslavia and Macedonia two weeks ago. As of
Friday, her parents had not been found. Three elderly women from
the same village have taken her in, and in the late afternoon
Jehona was gleefully going back and forth on a swing that the women
had fashioned out of rope and a blanket at the entrance to the
tent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have three grandmothers,'' Jehona said, giggling.
</P>
<P>
   Many parents are desperately searching for missing children.
Xhavit Cecielija and his wife were separated from their two sons,
ages 6 and 3, in the chaos of the border crossing into Macedonia on
April 1. Tired and with deep rings under their eyes, they spend
every day scanning lists, hoping to find their children's names.
They check the camp's bulletin board where handwritten notes
recount fractured stories of families torn apart. On Friday, news
trickled in that their sons were found in a camp a few miles away.
On Friday, they were working with the Red Cross to locate them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope tomorrow we will see them. My God, I just want to see
them to know they are alive,'' said Cecielija. ``I am most worried
about the older one. He is a very sensitive child.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuvland said there is no precise treatment within child
psychology that can be applied to all these children. Much of
helping them heal, he said, just comes from love and understanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents have healing power and often instinctively do the
right things,'' he said. ``We don't have a magic stick to make all
these bad things go away.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are practical ways to help, such as building
playgrounds and schools. On a grassy hill overlooking the canvas
tents in the Brazda refugee camp stood, as the children decided to
call it, ``The Kosovo Is Waiting for Us School.''
</P>
<P>
   The camp has become home to 20,000 refugees, 15,000 of whom are
estimated to be children. Friday was the first day of classes. Some
80 children fidgeted at rows of desks as UNICEF-supplied notebooks,
crayons, and paints were handed to them.
</P>
<P>
   Fatmir Elezi, 28, a math teacher who had fled Pristina, said,
``Children are so resilient. Look at them.''
</P>
<P>
   After the children had finally quieted down, students were
invited to speak. And Besnik Hajdini, 12, shot his hand into the
air. He stood at the front of the class and without notes began
reciting words that he later said he took from his own thoughts and
books in school.
</P>
<P>
   This is what he said in his native Albanian:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are people with bad souls who leave us to die.
</P>
<P>
   How can they have no souls, destroying our schools.
</P>
<P>
   The sun is not shining.
</P>
<P>
   Blood is covering legendary Drenica.
</P>
<P>
   But Kosovo, we will not let you close your doors.
</P>
<P>
   Have mercy on us, grant us freedom.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the reading, he stood with his arms straight by his side.
He said what he remembers most about his family's ordeal fleeing
their home in Ferizay was that his Serbian neighbors did not help
them.
</P>
<P>
   Dafina Sejdiu, 11, from Grabanica, was wearing shoes that were
too big and a red sweatshirt with smiling teddy bears that formed
the word ``Music.'' She ducked her head while children volunteered
to speak. But during the art period, she was very busy.
</P>
<P>
   Without looking up from her painting, she said, ``I miss my old
school. None of my friends are here. And I don't know what happened
to them.''
</P>
<P>
   With a new watercolor set, she painted flowers, trees, and a
warm yellow sun. The color of the sun blended nicely into the green
of the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my village, this is my house, and this is our
garden,'' she said. ``I want to paint all the things of Kosovo so I
don't forget.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
