<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4147 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALKANS-CONFLICT-BOS &LR;      04-19 1270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALKANS-CONFLICT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEYOND KOSOVO: FLASHPOINTS IN A WIDER CONFLICT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ The events of this week heightened fears
that the crisis in Kosovo could burn beyond its borders and inflame
the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, there were reports of an incursion into Albania by the
Serbian forces in a mountain village stronghold of the Kosovo
Liberation Army guerrillas. It was the first incident to raise the
spectre of a widening conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the steady flow of thousands more refugees crossing
into Macedonia refueled resentment against the ethnic Albanians
arriving by the busload. The Slav majority and Serb minority
whisper of war as their concerns of a ``greater Albania'' seemed,
to them, to be developing before their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   And Friday, Montenegro awoke to plumes of black smoke over the
capital after a night of NATO bombing. This deepened the divisions
in the smaller of the two Republics that make up what's left of
Yugoslavia and leave it dangerously poised on the edge of a coup or
a possible civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Travelling the perimeter of a burning Kosovo over the last three
weeks, the streets of bordering Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro
are crackling with tension. From the educated elite to plant
workers the same sentiment is expressed.
</P>
<P>
   At a cafe in the Montenegran capital of Podgorica, Ranko
Krivokapica, 32, a refined and Western-educated member of the
liberal party that supports the ``neutral'' Montenegran government,
watched one of the growing street rallies in support of Milosevic
gathering steam across the street. ``I think it is all going to go
out of control. I am afraid there is a momentum here that will
overtake us,'' he said as the crowd chanted their support of
overthrowing his government.
</P>
<P>
   In Macedonia, Slavic and Serbian workers at an asphalt plant
glared in hatred at busses packed with ethnic Albanian refugees
winding down the country road from the Kosovo border and into their
economically strapped and fledgling country.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do not belong here,'' said Zurin Petrovic, 38, the
manager of the plant. ``They want to take this land and make it
part of Albania. They have no place here and they should not think
they will stay here without a war.''
</P>
<P>
   A certain fatalism has set in here. It holds that Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic has intentionally put in motion a
chain of disasters that could unfold in the smoldering aftermath of
the NATO airstrikes. ``He (Milosvic) seems to have had a master
list for creating hell, and unfortunately it all seems to be coming
true,'' said John Drewienkiewicz, chief of operations for the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe's mission in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO forces see the potential for a spill-over effect of the
Kosovo crisis as precisely the reason why their mission is so
important. Jamie Shea, NATO spokesman in Brussels, was asked by
reporters last week if he thought Milosevic's ethnic cleansing of
some half million refugees was designed to ignite the Balkans and
threaten his neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has always been one of Milosevic's intention . . . He has
threatened them directly, and one of the great achievmenets of the
alliance has been to prevent that (widening of the conflict) from
occuring.''
</P>
<P>
   There are three scenarios on three borders of Kosovo which
present the potential for a widening conflict. Based on interviews
with experts and officials in the region these are the scenarios in
order of their likelihood.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Albania, border skirmishes between Serbian forces and the
KLA along the border are considered likely to continue. An
estimated 200,000 refugees are believed hemmed in along the
border's snow peaked mountains having fled their burning villages
inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA has taken up a cat-and-mouse guerrilla war against the
Serbian forces, sniping at the troops at night in retaliation for
their ethnic cleansing campaign of burning and looting which is
carried out during the day. The KLA has also fought to open a
corridor, NATO officials say, to permit a stream of refugees to
pass into Albania.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Montenegro, tension on the streets of the capital Podgorica
is evident. Half the roughly 600,000 population of the republic is
loyal to Milosevic and the Yugoslavian Army, which is believed to
have roughly 12,000 troops stationed there. The other half is loyal
to the Western-leaning government in power there, which has
officially declared neutrality in the conflict and is backed by a
well-trained and heavily armed Montenegran police force of roughly
9,000. The Yugoslav army and the Montenegran police eye each other
on the streets of the tense capital.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders on both sides say a coup is possible, and could erupt in
a civil war. In the first week of the bombing, the two sides
represented in the parliament held a tense, but ultimately
conciliatory debate in which they agreed neither side wanted to see
an outbreak of fighting within the republic. Since then, the
rallies for the pro-Milosevic forces which support his Serbian
nationalist aspirations have been growing in numbers and anger. The
steady stream of ethnic Albanian refugees, now numbered at roughly
70,000, staying in the homes of families and friends, add to the
tension.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Macedonia, the refugees there are also stirring tensions
and threatening to upset a fragile demographic balance. A Slavic
majority is apprehensive about the influx of Albanian refugees in
their country. Already some 120,000 ethnic Albanians have descended
on Macedonia in refugee camps and in the homes of relatives and
friends.
</P>
<P>
   And now, as their numbers rise, the majority fear that the
ethnic Albanians and the supporters of the KLA desire a ``greater
Albania.'' Certainly, the Albanians' rhetoric to that effect has
heightened amid the chaos and confusion and despair of the
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The government in Albania as recently as last week sought to
assure its neighbors that they do not desire to extend their
borders. But Albania, the poorest country in Europe with a Gross
National Product less than half the worth of one B-2 bomber, is
suffering under the strain of the influx of some 300,000 refugees.
Some say it could face economic collapse and political unrest if it
does not receive massive aid from Western countries.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts consider a conflict for a ``greater Albania'' a
relatively remote possibility, but its ramifications would be
enormous, splintering the vaneer of states and boundaries across
this least-developed corner of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility cuts along the fault line of the southern
Balkans. On one side are Orthodox Christian groups in charge of
Serbia, Montenegro, Macedonia and Greece. On the other side are
Muslim Albanian-speaking minorities in all three countries which
have a Muslim protectorate in Turkey. This raises the worst case
scenario of a conflict that would ultimately pit Greece and Turkey
_ two North Atlantic Treaty Organization allies and historic
enemies _ against each other.
</P>
<P>
   A Western diplomat, who asked not to be named, said these kinds
of fears were understandable, but unfounded. He said Milosevic
would like the region to unravel, but that NATO has for the first
time in 50 years attacked a sovereign nation to prevent that from
happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had left Slobodan (Milosevic) to his own devices in
Kosovo it would have unraveled,'' he said. ``I don't believe in the
prophecy that it (a wider conflict) is inevitable. I just believe
we have to do everything we can to stop it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
