<HEADER>
A4149 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALBANIA-US-BOS &LR;      04-19 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANIA-US-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANIANS EAGERLY GREET US PRESENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ Once, armed guards at Tirana's sleepy airport
spent the day in a crumbling barracks, disturbed by as few as three
flights before the airstrip closed for the night.
</P>
<P>
   Rusted Soviet planes lay scattered in the field, left over from
the country's communist days. Concrete bunkers lined the road,
symbols of the paranoia that gripped the land.
</P>
<P>
   But with the NATO bombings of Yugoslavia, those quiet days have
vanished, along with the last remnants of the old Albania that once
defined the airstrip.
</P>
<P>
   Some 30 American air traffic controllers now run the guard
tower. Hundreds of green US military tents line the fields. A
20-foot radar dish juts out from the horizon, and even the dirt is
covered with gravel, ready for thousands of foreign troops.
</P>
<P>
   The Tirana airport is, by all accounts, a sign of what could be
called the ``USS Albania'' phenomenon, the transformation of this
small country into a giant military headquarters for the United
States and NATO as they escalate the airstrikes on neighboring
Yugoslavia. And yet the most startling part of the occupation of
Albania might be the enthusiasm of Albanians themselves, as a
nation that once surpassed the Soviet Union in its hatred of the
West welcomes the invasion by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Becoming America's 51st state would be a great thing for us,''
said Ylli Vejsiu, a member of Albania's parliament, without a trace
of irony.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to belong in the rest of the world,'' said another
member of parliament, Jonuy Begaj. ``Our territory is at their
disposal.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, Albania has ceded control of its airspace, ports and
roads to US and NATO leaders. Hotels in the capital are jammed with
foreign dignitaries, humanitarian aid officials and journalists.
Convoys of Land Rovers with foreign plates race up and down the
roadways, and helicopter traffic is so overwhelming that police are
worried about the rising rate of car crashes, as local drivers lean
out their windows to point at the sky.
</P>
<P>
   A massive foreign presence is expected in a crisis such as this.
But even by modern standards, the overtaking of Albania seems
unusual, with every corner of the nation's 11,000 square miles
playing host to citizens from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   In the north, foreign aid officials have overwhelmed the town of
Kukes, renting office and hotel space in residents' living rooms
because of the lack of hotels. So many relief workers now stream
through the western port of Durres that the line for customs can
last days. Some 8,000 NATO troops are on their way to Tirana to
carry out the humanitarian effort, and NATO's commander, General
Wesley Clark, has described the capital as ``one of the hubs of our
activity.'' During a visit Saturday, Clark predicted the airport
would become ``one of the busiest spots in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the concentrated presence is obvious: Of the
nations bordering Kosovo, only Albania is in a position to oppose
Serbia loudly. Macedonia, an ethnically mixed state, still has ties
to Serbia, and Montenegro still coexists within the Yugoslav
federation, so it is in no position to open its doors to outside
troops, even if it wanted to.
</P>
<P>
   Only Albania, home to dozens of training camps of the Kosovo
Liberation Army and now, 300,000 ethnic Albanian refugees, can
encourage NATO ground troops as it has in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the political metamorphosis of this tiny nation is
almost incomprehensible to many of its citizens, who spent decades
learning to despise the West. Until the fall of communism in 1991,
they lived in what was considered the most xenophobic country in
Europe, a place so dogmatic that it once cut diplomatic ties with
the Soviet Union because it had become too liberal, and later cut
off relations with China for embracing capitalism too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would never have been imaginable 15 years ago,'' said
Vejsui. ``The US was viewed as the representative of imperialism,
and under communism, the government would do anything to keep the
US out.''
</P>
<P>
   Even two years ago, a massive foreign presence would have been
unthinkable, as a network of government-endorsed pyramid schemes
collapsed, sparking riots and ruining the economy. Since then,
Albania has struggled to find its place in Europe under a new
administration. But only now, as the rest of the Balkans teeters on
the edge of chaos, and as Serb troops shell the northern border, do
Albanian officials believe the country has a chance to flourish.
Hysen Selfo, a leader of the National Democratic Party, said he has
already seen ``a big symbolic change.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw the airport looking like this, my first thought
was, `Albania still has friends,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling is clearly mutual, at least among the dozens of
dignitaries who have paraded through Tirana over the last week. As
Clark met with Albanian leaders Saturday, expressing NATO's
gratitude for their cooperation and promising to help defend the
northern border, a delegation of US senators flew into town to talk
to American troops, and a delegation from Greece held meetings
throughout the capital. The Tirana Airport proved so busy that
Elizabeth Dole, the former head for the American Red Cross and a
potential candidate for president, was turned away when she tried
to fly in.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as 24 Apache helicopters prepare to make Albania their home
base for attacks on Kosovo, civilians and officials alike are doing
everything they can to open the borders further. Albanian officials
say they are ready for ground troops, and have already authorized
the placement of NATO fuel tanks throughout the north. Albanian
soldiers have willingly taken a back seat throughout the country,
with orders to defer to NATO and US leaders if the need arrises.
Even a bumper sticker is making the rounds, showing the peace sign
against a backdrop of the US flag.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
