<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY ARE SPRING PEEPERS SO LOUD? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I heard an incredible chorus from a swampy area in the
Middlesex Fells at dusk, enough to make your ears ring. It went on
for hours. Was it tree frogs, or crickets, and why were they making
so much noise?
</P>
<P>
   J., Medford, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You probably heard frogs, probably males calling out their
version of: ``Hey Baby, what's your sign?'' They were trying to
attract a mate and it is hoped that frog croaking is more
persuasive than ``Hey Baby, what's your sign?''
</P>
<P>
   The first few weeks of April are prime time for the guttural
quack-like honk of the wood frog. Matt Burne is a herpetologist
with MassWildlife, the state agency that tries to manage a healthy
peaceful relationship between wildlife and humans. Burne says wood
frogs only breed in vernal pools, the temporary ponds that form in
low-lying areas in the early spring. Which means they have to get
their croaking and mating done in a hurry, since vernal pools dry
up by summer.
</P>
<P>
   They usually croak only under the protection of darkness.
Croaking draws more than female frogs. It also draws hungry
predators looking for unfried frogs legs. At the peak of the wood
frogs' breeding season, the biological imperative to reproduce
overpowers their instinct for self preservation and they croak all
day.
</P>
<P>
   But Burne says you probably heard a frog duet, trio, or maybe
even an amphibian quartet. Spring peepers, who make that sweet high
little ``Peep. Peep,'' are also singing their mating song this time
of year, in a wide variety of wetlands habitats, not just vernal
pools. They're also sometimes known onomatopoetically for their
sound as ``pinkletinks.'' Their habitat flexibility lets them breed
throughout the spring and summer, and you can hear their peeps,
mostly at dusk and overnight, well into August.
</P>
<P>
   You might also have been hearing the high trills of the American
toad, or the Fowler's toad. (Toads are the ones with the bumpy
skin. Frogs have smooth skin.) Those two toad species are also
singing out their best ``Hey Baby'' this time of year, through late
May, in a variety of wetlands habitats.
</P>
<P>
   And if you have a good ear for low notes, you might have heard
the bass player of the amphibian quartet, the leopard frog, which
sings from underwater, an ingenious protection from predation.
Burne describes their call as ``like snoring, low and hard to
hear.''
</P>
<P>
   As the wood frog fades out in May, the pretty, rising
``twrrrRRRR'' of the grey tree frog (it sounds like a raccoon, for
those of you who may know what raccoons sound like) takes its place
for most of May. Green frogs (a low-pitched twang) and the pickerel
frog (a faint low ``grrrr-grrrr'') add their romancing ``ribbets''
in late May and sing until the end of July. Bull frogs, with their
gruff low ``rrrrrRRRR, rrrrrrRRRR'' sing all summer.
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear what attracts female amphibians to the particular
prince of their choice. One study suggests it may be that the
frog/toad that calls longest, wins. It takes a lot of energy for
amphibians to inflate their air sacs (most are under the chin...the
wood frog has one on either side of its body) and expel the air.
The longer a frog/toad can keep calling, the more fit he may be,
and the more attractive to females who evolved to pick a mate with
good genes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The buzzing sound you hear at night in meadows I always
thought was crickets. Someone told me it's tree frogs. What is it?
</P>
<P>
   B.S. Somerville, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Jeepers. Creepers. Can't you hear those Peepers? And those
cicadas, and crickets and grasshoppers and katydids, the major
insects that add their voices to the outdoor chorus of spring and
summer nights.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Simmons, Entymologist with the state's Natural Heritage and
Endangered Species Program, says the same basic rules apply to bugs
that apply to frogs and toads. The guys do the calling, looking for
mates. They call at night to get lucky, not devoured.
</P>
<P>
   Crickets wait until they're fully grown to rub the spines of
their legs on their wings and make their chirping sound. Big
crickets eat little ones. A young cricket doesn't want a
prospective mate to come over and turn him into a meal. That's why
cricket chirping grows near the end of summer, as more of them grow
big enough to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Katydids, also named for their sound, are, like crickets. They
call from summer to fall. Grasshoppers, which produce their sound
in the same way, have evolved to call mostly during the day,
probably because they're down in the grass and camouflaged, not up
in bushes or trees and vulnerable to birds. They also call in
flight by rattling their wings.
</P>
<P>
   Cicadas, which we sometimes call locusts, have a special
sound-producing organ in their abdomen that's filled with air,
which vibrates when they want to buzz their best ``Hey Baby.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write
to How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
