<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4160 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-DUNCAN-BOS &LR;      04-19 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-DUNCAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUNCAN PLAYS ROXIE `FROM THE INSIDE OUT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- ``You're just a little too much in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   When Sandy Duncan's 16-year-old son Jeffrey mentioned this, more
off-handedly than unkindly, to what was then his full-time mother,
she recalled a therapist's reaction in a discussion they'd had
about the Manhattan-based Duncan returning to the stage again. The
therapist said that work may help when you're the mother of two
teenage boys _ Duncan's other son, Michael, is 15 _ because you can
expect that no matter what ``you'll be blamed for everything.''
</P>
<P>
   So Jeffrey's observation struck theater and TV star Duncan, 53,
almost as a cue. She took it that way. Which is why she's coming to
Boston as the vivacious bombshell Roxie Hart, a hoofer turned
killer, in Kander &AMP; Ebb's winner of six Tony Awards, ``Chicago _
The Musical. '' The rest of the family will stay in at home in New
York while the show has its second Boston run Thursday through May
16 at the Shubert Theatre. It played a sold-out engagement at the
Colonial last December through mid-February.
</P>
<P>
   The show, a new incarnation of the legendary Bob Fosse's gritty
mid-'70s musical, is set in the garishly violent Chicago of the
Roaring '20s. Also along for the ride on this brassy vehicle is
Ruthie Henshall, who originated the role of Roxie in the London
production. She's now playing the ``venemous vixen'' Velma Kelly.
Adrian Zmed, Danny Zuko in the Broadway and national tour of
``Grease,'' is the scheming, media-savvy attorney, Billy Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Duncan said an almost genetic determination is
the key to her survival as both a performer and the mother of
teenage boys _ she and her dancer/husband Don Correia have been
married for 20 years. That determination, she added, is not unlike
that of her character Roxie Hart who, Duncan says, she plays from
``the inside out.'' Here's the back story Duncan has created for
her character:
</P>
<P>
   ``Roxie will do anything to get what she wants, but she won't
kill. Yes, she killed a person, but she's just an innocent. There's
a little bit of Roxie in all of us.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roxie is ``not evil or bad, she's just a bit of a teenager,''
Duncan says. ``She thinks, `This is what I want' and goes after it.
She's also a quick study. She's the kind of person who, when she
gets sentenced to prison, quickly gets into prison work. She's
complex. You can't read her like a book. She killed a person, but
she's still just an innocent. There are a lot of people like that
out there. She's been abandoned by people around her all her life.
Her father committed suicide. She's always had people leaving
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, born and raised in Texas, had a very successful New York
stage career, finally getting her big break in the Broadway musical
``Canterbury Tales,'' for which she received her first Tony Award
nomination in 1969. Her second Tony nomination was for her starring
role in 1971's ``The Boyfriend,'' for which she received the New
York Drama Desk and Outer Critics Circle awards. She also earned a
nomination for her starring role in ``Peter Pan.'' She appeared in
Tommy Tune's award-winning production of ``My One and Only'' and
starred opposite Tune in national and international tours of the
musical.
</P>
<P>
   She had her own TV comedy series ``Funny Face'' for which she
was Emmy nominated for the 1971-72 season. The series came to a
screeching halt after 13 episodes when Duncan learned that she had
a brain tumor resting on an optic nerve.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, she told a reporter in an interview, she thought
she was going mad. ``I was working until 3 every morning, only
getting three hours of sleep a night, and I weighed 86 pounds . .
.I started fantasizing that I was in an insane asylum.''
</P>
<P>
   The brain tumor was benign, it turned out, but 10 hours of
surgery at the UCLA Medical Center in California failed to prevent
the loss of sight in her left eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fine,'' she says today. ``CAT scans became available a
year after my surgery. With a CAT scan, I wouldn't have lost an
eye. It shows you what a difference progress makes. With time, I
learned how to survive. In fact, I have some of Roxie's qualities.
I couldn't wallow in self pity. What I've found is that there are
times when a lot of denial works. People were around me telling me
not to deny that my career was over. That notion never entered my
mind. My good eye, the right one, is fine, although I'm
nearsighted. I don't wear contacts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how to compensate for depth perception. I do symphonies
around the country. I block all my movements out beforehand. I have
my own radar. The audience helps me a lot. I have a general feel
for audiences, for an audience's range of responses to things. It's
not something you see. You feel it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
