<HEADLINE>
`ARGUING THE WORLD' A GRIPPING DOCUMENTARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES: ``Arguing the World'' _ Remember when ideas meant
more than money? Return with us now to those thrilling days of
yesteryear when smart people argued as if their lives depended on
it and no one mentioned gross revenue. In this gripping documentary
by Joseph Dorfman, intellectual battlers Irving Howe, Nathan
Glazer, Daniel Bell, and Irving Kristol go head to head. Call it
Mentalmania.
</P>
<P>
   ``One Tough Cop'' _ Stephen Baldwin and Chris Penn, the altar
boys, star as cops in this sluggish thriller about the rape of a
nun in New York City. Nothing new here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scooby-Doo's Greatest Mysteries'' _ Compared with such
animated stars asBugs Bunny and Donald Duck, Scooby-Doo is strictly
B-material _ somewhere between Fred Flintstone and Augie Doggie.
But his career has been revived on cable, and this tape is for any
children who love the goofy dog.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DVD UPDATE: The only thing holding back an avalanche of DVD
releases is the strain on manufacturing the discs. Last year, 59
million discs were produced, and the industry estimates it will
produce 95 million this year and 170 million in 2000, according to
a survey by market researchers, Cambridge Associates of Stamford,
Conn. Sony, according to Video Business magazine, expects 3 million
DVD players in homes by the year's end and 10 million units by
2001.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LET FREEDOM SING: ``The Paris Concert for Amnesty
International,'' the musical celebration held on Dec. 10 in Paris,
is out on DVD and VHS. Bruce Springsteen, Shania Twain, Radiohead,
Alanis Morissette, Jimmy Page, Robert Plant, Tracy Chapman, and
Youssou N'Dour highlight the concert, held to celebrate the 50th
anniversary of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights. Look for
the Dalai Lama in a cameo. The VHS runs 120 minutes for $19.98
while the DVD is $29.99 for 172 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMING ATTRACTIONS: April 20: ``A Bug's Life,'' ``Monument
Ave.,'' ``Simon Birch,'' ``Corporate Ladder,'' ``Kissed,'' ``Apt
Pupil,'' ``A Night at the Roxbury.'' April 27: ``Elizabeth,'' ``Ten
Benny,'' ``Stepmom,'' ``Life of Jesus,'' ``Happiness,'' ``Ground
Control,'' ``The Thief,'' ``Twists of Terror,'' ``Implicated,''
``Striking Poses,'' ``Future Fantastic,'' ``Streetwise,'' ``At
First Sight.'' May 4: ``Babe: Pig in the City,'' ``You've Got
Mail,'' ``The Leather Boys,'' ``Frank Sinatra: The Best Is Yet to
Come.'' May 5: ``Gloria.'' May 11: ``Star Trek: Insurrection,''
``Another Day in Paradise,'' ``Velvet Goldmine,'' ``As Time Goes
By'' (BBC), ``Teletubbies Hanging Garden,'' ``Bent,'' ``A Cool, Dry
Place,'' ``Rowing With the Wind.'' June 8: ``From the Earth to the
Moon.''
</P>
