<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (FU)  &UR; !! &LR;  ``Goodbye Lover'' This film never becomes the dark,
edgy, eccentric criminal comedy it sets out to be, with its
schemers on parade and treachery everywhere in an LA powered by
greed and driven by lust. The plot twists, initially intriging,
pile up so furiously that the film becomes weightless, then silly,
wasting Patricia Arquette's amoral vamp, Don Johnson's immoral
lothario and Ellen DeGeneres's world-weary, gimlet-eyed cop. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
(FD)  &UR; ! &LR;  1/2 ``Life'' Eddie Murphy continues his free-fall from
comedic grace in this bland buddy film that spans 60 years in the
lives of Ray (Murphy), a small-time hustler, and Claude (Martin
Lawrence), an aspiring bank teller, who are wrongfully imprisoned
for murder. Straining for a poignant blend of humor and humanity _
and falling far short of both _ with recycled jail-cell jokes and
ditch-digging scenes from a Southern plantation-prison, ``Life''
makes you wish Murphy would get back in touch with his inner
wiseguy, and leave the dramedy to De Niro. (R) (Joan Anderman) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! &LR;  ``The School of Flesh'' Benoit Jacquot's film not only leads
its older woman (Isabelle Huppert) and younger man (Vincent
Martinez) into love, but leads them out again, or, rather, allows
them to emerge intact after their affair runs its course in this
humane look at amour fou in a film that for once doesn't punish the
older woman. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! &LR;  ``Tax Day'' Laura Colella's noodling little film about two
Providence women bound for the post office on April 15, is less
concerned with plot (there isn't one) than with highlighting the
city, its residents, and the extraordinary moments primed to the
plucked from the everyday. (Unrated) (Renee Graham)
</P>
</TEXT>
