<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PEYTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVISITING PEYTON PLACE'S `FORBIDDEN' FRUITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Ardis Cameron wanted to use the once-notorious, now dimly
remembered ``Peyton Place'' in the course she teaches on New
England culture, she had to ``scour the local libraries'' to find
enough copies for her students.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years since it was first published in 1956, Grace
Metalious's novel had sold 12 million copies, but it had long been
out of print.
</P>
<P>
   So Cameron, director of American and New England Studies at the
University of Southern Maine, went to Northeastern University Press
with a proposal to reprint the book _ with an introduction by
Cameron putting the novel in its social and cultural context.
</P>
<P>
   That new edition is being published this month. It is a coup of
sorts for the small university press, as trade giant
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster, which had published the most recent edition,
10 years ago, had been planning to bring it out again as part of
its own 75th anniversary _ not knowing that Northeastern had
secured the rights.
</P>
<P>
   With bookstores now overstocked with novels hyped as
``shocking'' or ``explosive,'' ``erotic'' or ``sensuous,'' it may
be hard to imagine the impact ``Peyton Place'' had more than 40
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The tale of passions and problems in a small town, written by an
unknown young author from New Hampshire, sold 60,000 copies in the
first 10 days (at $3.95) _ to the outraged indignation of
self-appointed defenders of public decency.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Manchester (N.H.) Union-Leader editor William Loeb
wrote that the book revealed ``a complete debasement of taste and a
fascination with the filthy, rotten side of life that are the
earmarks of the collapse of civilization.''
</P>
<P>
   A friend recalled for Cameron how she once heard her mother and
a friend ``whispering in the kitchen. As soon as I entered, they
whipped a book into a bag, but they were too slow. I had caught my
mother reading `Peyton Place,' a book banned in our town library.''
</P>
<P>
   Cameron herself was only 7 when ``Peyton Place'' was published,
but she remembers the lingering aura of forbidden pleasure that
continued as the book became a motion picture and then a television
serial in the mid-1960s. ``My first memory of it is coming home and
seeing my parents watching it,'' she said. ``They wouldn't let us
into the study while it was on.''
</P>
<P>
   What the uproar was all about was a novel about a small town
that was on the surface, as Metalious put it, ``as peaceful as a
postcard picture,'' but where ``if you go beneath that picture it's
like turning over a rock with your foot. All sorts of things crawl
out'' _ abuse and incest, alcholism and poverty, the shacks of the
region's backroads and, perhaps most shocking in 1956, abortion.
</P>
<P>
   As Cameron writes, Metalious had ``tweaked the mythologies of
tourist New England, turning the familiar postcard portrait into a
voluptuous pinup poster.'' Ironically, when Hollywood filmed
``Peyton Place,'' it was not in the backwoods New Hampshire town
Metalious had envisioned but in the picture-postcard coastal town
of Camden, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Metalious apparently drew on several New Hampshire communities
to create her fictional town. The fact that a murder similar to the
one she describes _ a young woman killing her abusive father and
hiding his body _ had occurred in nearby Gilmanton Ironworks just
10 years before, raised local suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   Metalious, who lived in Gilmanton, wasn't exactly run out of
town _ she actually bought an antique colonial there with the
proceeds from the book, but her then-husband lost his job as a
grammar school principal there. Metalious had grown up in poverty
and, she once commented, ``I think I began writing `Peyton Place'
the day I was born.'' She died in 1964, with her personal and
financial affairs in disorder.
</P>
<P>
   But, writes Cameron, she had ``unbuttoned New England.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that unbuttoning that prompted Cameron to use ``Peyton
Place'' in her course, which studies how representations of New
England have been created. Along with Metalious's novel, she has
also used books as varied as Sarah Orne Jewett's ``The Country of
the Pointed Firs,'' E. B. White's ``One Man's Meat,'' and Carolyn
Chute's ``The Beans of Egypt, Maine.'' ``I wanted to look at the
notions of New England, the eroticized landscape and the smugness
of New England towns which Metalious was trying to refute,''
Cameron said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 1338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
