<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4184 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-POP-BOS &LR;      04-19 1697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE FACE OF CHANGE, A POP MUSIC CONFERENCE BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Aspiring rock bands and industry insiders will
converge on Boston next weekend, when the third annual NEMO Music
Showcase and Conference rolls into town. There will, as usual, be
much music-making and demo-tape delivering. We can expect the
familiar dialogues about the role of managers, creating a band
image, getting noticed by the critics. But this year's New England
Music Organization event will also bear the mark of radical,
tumultuous change, coming as it does in the midst of massive
upheaval in the music industry.
</P>
<P>
   Artists and executives are being slashed from record company
rosters like so much deadwood, thanks to the Seagram's Co.'s
gobbling of Polygram Holdings Inc. At least 500 employees and 250
acts have been dropped so far in the biggest corporate
restructuring in the history of the music industry. The rapid
growth of technology _ most prominently MP3, which allows
CD-quality recordings to be downloaded, often free of charge, from
Internet sites _ is wreaking havoc on established modes of music
distribution and financial compensation. The current mood could be
measured at the recent South by Southwest conference (SXSW) in
Austin _ the Big Kahuna of music conventions _ where the usual
throngs of A&AMP;R (artists and repertoire) scouts from major labels
were conspicuously thin, top executives were all but nonexistent,
and typically lavish spending on parties and promotion was scaled
back dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   All of this might be construed as bad news for Boston's
fledgling music conference, established in 1997 by Boston Music
Awards founder and executive director Candace Avery. NEMO lacks the
cachet and clout of behemoth industry cavalcades like SXSW and the
CMJ festival in New York, and one could argue that if the gloomy
business climate is keeping the brass from turning out for the main
events, the upstart in Beantown doesn't stand a chance. But it's
precisely NEMO's relative youth, and corresponding attitude, that
helps to distinguish it from well-established relations.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the sense of chaos and low spirits inspired by
recent events in the music business, Boston is still considered a
hotbed _ not only for breeding new music, but as a key location for
breaking new acts. There are more than 200,000 college students _
who comprise the core modern rock demographic _ in the Boston area.
That statistic is hardly lost on the labels' marketing departments.
Neither is the fact that those students will be fanning out to
every corner of the country during school vacations _ with their
favorite new CDs in tow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labels look to establish bands here because we're very
receptive to new music,'' says Oedipus, program director at
WBCN-FM, one of NEMO's sponsors. ``There's a lot of attention at
the NEMO showcases.'' Even in the current shrinking industry,
Oedipus says, ``the labels are always looking for the next big
thing. There are labels who are just waiting for bands to be
dropped so that they can scoop them up. Yes, it makes it
competitive for the new bands. But what else is there?''
</P>
<P>
   SXSW, once the cultural barometer for the cutting edge and
ground zero for the best unsigned bands, has over the years become
largely a showcase vehicle for signed artists and a high-profile
shmoozefest. While Avery says that she used SXSW as her model while
conceiving NEMO, one key difference is that more than 90 percent of
the 200 bands (selected from 1,000 submissions) playing showcases
at area clubs during the NEMO gathering are still unsigned. Fifty
panels and workshops are all geared toward educating and empowering
emerging artists, with topics like National Touring for the
Underground Band, Marketing on the Internet, and individual
mentoring sessions with the pros.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't do those peripheral panels on Sex and Drugs and Rock
'N Roll or Women in Rock,'' says Avery. ``Mine are very
informational.'' And in a unique display of integrity, NEMO is the
only music convention in the country to give showcasing artists
free admission to the two-day conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I stress over and over to bands,'' says Avery, ``is
that while it's important to showcase, it's equally important to go
to the conference, to learn to oversee business, to network, to
promote the showcase. They're not getting paid to play, so this is
like their payment. A&AMP;R people from just about every label are here
doing mentoring.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Avery's well-intentioned appeals, some showcasing
artists are inclined to concentrate their time and energy on making
music at NEMO. Suzanne Wyllie, an Australian who gave up a thriving
jazz career Down Under to pursue fame as a folk-pop
singer-songwriter in the States, will be at Club Passim Friday.
She's currently in the studio with Eric Rosse, who has produced
tracks for Tori Amos, among others. ``The chaos in the business
does concern me. It's harder to be heard. And for a new artist,
trying to do something a little different and unique, I think it's
even harder. But I'm going to send my manager to the conference;
it's too frightening for me. I'm hoping to expose my music, to
start cultivating an audience in Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Pulling Birds, a 2-year-old modern rock band from Clearwater,
Fla., rented a van and booked club dates up and down the coast to
finance the trip to NEMO. Armed with a self-produced CD, ``County
Fair'' (recorded in lead singer Wade McMullen's parents' bedroom)
and a glowing notice in Billboard, Pulling Birds will play a
showcase at Bill's Bar on Saturday. According to McMullen--at 22,
the band's oldest member--Pulling Birds is also planning to pack
its manager off to network on the band's behalf. ``Yeah, I think
the odds are off now. But a band as young as we are, we're not
really thinking about that right now. We're concentrating on
writing songs.'' And while McMullen acknowledges that his band's
youth is an advantage in today's market, he's savvy enough to know
that ``some industry people think we should just develop for
free.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet no one would deny that clinching a record deal is the holy
grail. While Avery is reticent to take credit for any signing that
results from a NEMO showcase, last year's conference did produce
one extraordinary success story in the pop group My Favorite
Relative. The band, formed by Swiss expatriates Adrian Hierholzer
and Kurt Uenala, played their first live gig ever at a showcase at
the Hard Rock Cafe. After hearing the band's homemade tape at the
NEMO Demo Derby, WBCN's Juanita, also a scout for MCA records,
passed the tape to the label, which resulted in a demo deal for the
band. High-powered entertainment lawyer Peter Paterno (Metallica,
Smashing Pumpkins) came calling, as did a handful of interested
record labels. No deal has officially been inked _ mainly because
three of the A&AMP;R reps courting the band lost their jobs in the
Universal-Polygram merger. But the band, who is nominated for six
Boston Music Awards this year and plays at Bill's Bar Friday night,
is cautiously optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is sure now. It's probably the worst time to get
signed,'' Hierholzer says. ``But we have a lot of good songs, and
we are patient.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, one has to wonder if the recent sales slump and
industry downsizing will impact the typically enthusiastic scouting
that characterizes the conferences. In recent years, Fastball, Lisa
Loeb, Cake, and Hanson all set deals in motion at SXSW. This year,
one A&AMP;R rep admitted he went to SXSW expressly to prevent his label
from signing a band.
</P>
<P>
   Avery concedes that ``the industry is somewhat circumspect. Like
any industry, this one is cyclical. But it's not dead, or going
away. I think a lot of indie labels will be stepping in and signing
now. I do think there's a hunger for alternative methods of getting
music heard and making contacts. The industry has changed so much,
especially in the last year. The internet is having a major impact.
Two years ago, .3 percent of music was sold on the internet; last
year 1.1 percent was sold online. I mean, it's in its infancy, but
that's a significant increase. And MP3...that will change the
industry radically.''
</P>
<P>
   NEMO's response to the trends in the industry is a point of
pride for Avery. New panels created this year include Technologies
of Change: The Internet, MP3 and More; Artist Development at an
Indie Label; Examining the Success of Indie Hip-Hop; and
Establishing a Scene that Supports Urban Culture. There will also
be two nights of rap and hip-hop showcases, in an effort to shed
light on a genre which--while the hottest thing going in mainstream
popular music--has been woefully neglected in the Boston area.
``There's lots of talent; there are just no venues,'' Avery says.
``The hip-hop community here hasn't been very cohesive and focused.
And Boston's history as a segregated city exasperates that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Stephens, vice president of A&AMP;R at Atlantic Records, is
coming to NEMO from one of the few labels not affected by the
plethora of mergers. Stephens, who signed Matchbox 20, Collective
Soul, and Edwin McCain to Atlantic, plans to attend a number of
showcases in addition to participating in a panel, Major Label A&AMP;R:
Are You Ready For It?.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about the others, but my company is still looking
for talent,'' Stephens states emphatically. ``I came across a
couple of bands (he declined to name them) last year that I thought
showed promise, and I'll definitely check them out again this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   NEMO, while still considered the new kid on the block, is
growing steadily. In its first there were 850 registrants; last
year there were 1,200, and this year Avery is expecting about
1,500. That doesn't compare to the 6,800 who streamed into SXSW
last month. But at this time of great flux in the music industry,
poised on the edge of a new millennium, size does matter. There's
value in a small conference _ one that may not pack the glamor or
attract the attention of its heftier counterparts, but gets back to
the basics of making new music.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
