<HEADLINE>
CANADA STILL BEARS IMPRINT OF REVOLUTION-ERA LOYALISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHELBURNE, Nova Scotia _ The first wave of dispossessed arrived
by ship in May 1783. Within a year, this fishing port on Nova
Scotia's rugged south shore ranked among the biggest centers in
North America, in a league with Boston, New York, and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Shelburne's brief boom owed everything to war and the often
vengeful politics of a fledgling republic called the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our settlers came fleeing for their lives from up and down the
13 former colonies, from the Carolinas to Boston,'' said Finn
Bower, curator of the Shelburne County Museum and descendant of one
of the town's founders. ``They were escaping mob terror.''
</P>
<P>
   For if the American War of Independence forged a new sort of
nation, one dedicated to individual liberty, it also made refugees
of tens of thousands of men, women, and children driven from their
homeland for refusing to pledge allegiance to the revolutionary
regime.
</P>
<P>
   They called themselves loyalists, although their former
neighbors applied harsher sobriquets, often along with a slathering
of tar and feathers.
</P>
<P>
   And though Americans seldom think of it, the forced exodus of
the loyalists gave birth to another new country on the continent _
one equally democratic, but to this day profoundly different in
tone and temperament.
</P>
<P>
   When New Englanders celebrate Patriots Day, April 19 this year,
Canadians in the three provinces more or less created by loyalist
exiles _ New Brunswick, Nova Scotia, and Ontario _ prepare opposite
observances, celebrating the influx that so shaped the character of
their nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're proud of our loyalist past. It sets us apart from the
US,'' said Bernice Wood Flett of London, Ontario, former president
of the United Empire Loyalists Association of Canada and descendant
of a Mohawk Valley loyalist who joined the King's Royal Regiment to
fight George Washington's rebel army.
</P>
<P>
   Loyalist spirit still runs deep in Canada, especially in the
Maritime Provinces and Ontario, where Union Jacks flutter atop
front yard flagpoles and many citizens take stubborn pride in the
country's loyalty to English royalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Canadian attitudes owe much to loyalist tradition,'' Flett
said. ``The loyalists sought peace, order and good government _ not
the American dream of life, liberty, and pursuit of happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   The wealthy few were able to flee to England, but roughly 80,000
loyalists had little choice but to sail or trek overland to
Britain's sparsely inhabited Canadian possessions, an extraordinary
upheaval for those times.
</P>
<P>
   Most had not so much opposed the goals of the Revolution _ tax
relief, more democratic representation, home rule _ than the
violent means. Many had simply feared that replacing monarchy with
a revolutionary republic would cost them the cherished liberties
guaranteed by English common law.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the loyalists carried north a yearning for
stability as much as for freedom, and Canada _ stolid and
law-abiding, although in some ways a more tolerant society than the
United States _ still reflects their cautious vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``These exiles had been threatened by mobs, seen their lands and
possessions stolen in the name of `liberty,' and given the option
of renouncing their principles or fleeing their homes,'' said
Christopher Moore of Toronto, author of ``The Loyalists,'' a
historical account. ``It made them a bit mistrustful of ideology.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a myth, in both Canada and the United States, that the
loyalists, or ``tories,'' were merely pampered aristocrats fearful
of losing their profits and perquisites. But they were just
ordinary Americans of the time _ farmers as well as upper-class
Harvard graduates; barrelmakers, shipwrights, fishermen, artisans
and herdsmen along with the more stereotypical prosperous merchants
and plantation owners.
</P>
<P>
   Some loyalists were blacks who escaped slavery by casting their
lot with the British redcoats.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, your American land of liberty wasn't exactly
paradise for black people,'' said Anna Scott Smith of Shelburne,
descended from one of the thousands of black loyalists who sided
with King George III simply because so many southern slave-owners
supported the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``My ancestors sure didn't come to Canada for the sunny
weather,'' said Smith, who presides over a spectacular rock garden
on land that has been her family's for centuries. ``And I don't
think it was because they were crazy in love with the king or
queen. They just needed a place to get on with their own
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, descendants of the loyalists are entitled by royal decree
to append the initials ``U.E.,'' for ``United Empire,'' to their
names _ the only hereditary title recognized in Canada. Last year,
Ontario joined Nova Scotia and New Brunswick in officially
proclaiming a day in honor of the loyalists and their contribution
to Canadian history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Loyalism is a part of our national identity, and reverberates
to this day,'' said John Aimers, dominion chairman of the
Monarchist League of Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Partly because of their loyalist history, Canadians have always
been alternately amused and horrified by the sort of rah-rah
jingoism and chest-thumping patriotism that sometimes surface to
the south.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like America and Americans, but walking the Freedom Trail
during a visit to Massachusetts last summer, I found my hackles
rising a bit _ all those historical markers with their stunning
oversimplifications,'' said Moore. ``Americans seem to believe they
invented the only and perfect path to freedom. But Canada also
managed to create a free, democratic and just society, and did so
without taking up arms against the imperial power.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans view the Revolution as a heroic rising against a
tyrannical monarchy. That notion ignores the view that Britain of
the 18th century was the freest society on earth, and that the
inhabitants of the 13 Colonies enjoyed prosperity and liberties
``nearly inconceivable in most of the rest of the world,'' in
Moore's words.
</P>
<P>
   There were unjust taxes, there were injustices in the way
Colonial interests were represented in Parliament, there were
legitimate grievances against a system that was repressive in a
bureaucratic sense _ but few Americans were squirming under the
boot heel of a serious oppression.
</P>
<P>
   And those that were weren't exactly victims of the English.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 10,000 refugees who would eventually settle Shelburne
beginning with the first loyalist landing in May 1783, about 1,500
were blacks, many of them runaway slaves, including two who had
belonged to George Washington, by local account.
</P>
<P>
   There would be racial tensions in Canada, too, and many early
black settlers in Nova Scotia went on to resettle in Sierra Leone,
in West Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But many also stayed on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our roots go deep in this rocky soil,'' said Smith, whose
dining-room wall is lined with photographs of Nova Scotia
forebears.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands more loyalists settled in other parts of Nova
Scotia, New Brunswick, Ontario and the Eastern Townships of Quebec,
north of Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, loyalist memories remain long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nearly all of us come from families stripped of lands, homes,
and possessions,'' said Flett. ``For example, New York's World
Trade Center is sitting on land stolen from the Ryerson family, now
of Ontario.''
</P>
<P>
   Loyalist land claims remain an issue between Canada and the
United States, one unlikely ever to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   It was only partly in jest that three years ago Canadian
lawmakers, parodying the US Helms-Burton law that allows Americans
to use US courts to claim property lost in Cuba's communist
revolution, introduced a bill in Parliament in Ottawa meant to
force the United States to cough up billions of dollars' worth of
confiscated loyalist lands and property.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 3 million Canadians descended from uprooted loyalists
should be allowed to sue for return of our stolen property,'' said
one of the bill's sponsors, John Godfrey, whose ancestral land was
seized in Virginia. ``What happened to loyalists in the US is no
less outrageous than what happened in Cuba.''
</P>
</TEXT>
