<SLUG> BC-SCI-OLDER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVING A `SENIOR MOMENT'? RELAX. YOU HAVE NOT LOST YOUR MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lorraine Harding, who retired from a Massachusetts Institute of
Technology administrative job 18 months ago, still lives near MIT
and often runs into her former colleagues. And that can pose an
annoying little problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go nuts trying to remember people's names,'' says the
71-year-old Cambridge resident. ``I see someone whose face is
familiar but I have to go through the alphabet trying to find their
name. It's a little embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   People beyond a certain age _ 50 seems to be the rough threshold
_ often joke about these ``senior moments.'' The familiar
tip-of-the-tongue feeling. The where-did-I-put-those-keys or
park-that-car episode. The word, book title, or celebrity's name
you know you know, but can no longer produce on demand.
</P>
<P>
   Harding was concerned enough to take a workshop on ``Brainergy''
at the Cambridge Center for Adult Education run by Gessner Geyer, a
self-described ``popularizer'' of the fashionable notion that
mental calisthenics, such as name games, reading upside-down text,
and mental arithmetic, along with one-nostril-at-a-time breathing
exercises, can tone up the brain the way weight-lifting builds
muscle. ``It helped a little,'' Harding reports. ``It was very
energizing.''
</P>
<P>
   Practicing physicians and aging experts say the ``senior
moment'' issue pops up frequently these days. ``Memory is the
problem that worries people most about aging, and it's because of
the specter of Alzheimer's disease,'' says Dr. John W. Rowe, a
leading gerontologist who is president of Mount Sinai-NYU Medical
Center in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The concern is understandable. Alzheimer's disease, which
typically begins with forgetfulness and progresses at varying rates
to profound dementia, afflicts as many as four million Americans _
many of them parents of people who are themselves turning 50 at the
unprecedented rate of more than 9,000 a day. The prevalence of
Alzheimer's doubles every five years after age 65; as many as 30
percent to 50 percent of those over 85 are affected.
</P>
<P>
   But memory lapses of the type that plague Harding are virtually
universal by late middle age, and have nothing to do with
Alzheimer's or any other disease, experts say. The forgetfulness
that signals Alzheimer's arises from a different part of the brain
than the region involved in ``senior moments,'' and it manifests
itself differently.
</P>
<P>
   People with early Alzheimer's often cannot call up ordinary
nouns, such as the names of familiar objects like ``fork'' or
``radio,'' and they're less aware they're forgetting things than
those with the occasional memory problems of normal aging.
</P>
<P>
   People with normal memory lapses typically have trouble
retrieving information, especially names, from their accumulated
store of knowledge. They may not be able to absorb the name of a
new acquaintance, for instance, without extra effort. And they have
more trouble attending to several things at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, a misplaced object or proper name is not a
worrisome event,'' says Dr. Ronald C. Petersen, director of the
Mayo Clinic's Alzheimer's disease center. ``But when people tell me
they've been missing appointments or things they really care about,
I start to worry. Once or twice is OK, but when this kind of
behavior happens repeatedly, that's more bothersome.''
</P>
<P>
   Molly Wagster, a neuroscientist at the National Institute on
Aging, agrees: ``Those worried about `senior moments' should worry
when it becomes more than a moment. I don't think we know how many
senior moments it takes to make a demented individual. If you start
with one a week and progress to 10 and stabilize there, is
everything going to be OK? The answer is probably yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Another useful test to distinguish between normal age-related
memory changes and early Alzheimer's is whether the ``lost'' word,
or key, or parked car, is ultimately found _ and what your reaction
to it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you and I can't remember where we parked the car or put
the keys, and then we remember, we usually have a sense of
recollection,'' says Marilyn Albert, director of gerontology
research at Massachusetts General Hospital. ``We think, `Oh yes,
now I remember: When I came in the phone rang and I put my glasses
down there.' People in the very early stages of Alzheimer's tend
not to have that sense of recollection, even when they are
reminded.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news,'' adds Dr. Robert Schreiber, a Lahey Cliic
geriatrician who sees several patients a month worried about balky
memory, ``is that if you're eventually able to recall what you were
trying to remember, you don't have a problem. Over 95 percent of
the time it's just normal aging.''
</P>
<P>
   The cognitive problems of normal aging can be broken down into
several types, researchers say:
</P>
<P>
   _ Sluggish retrieval of words and proper names, a phenomenon
called (even in sober scientific papers) the ``tip of the tongue''
problem;
</P>
<P>
   _ Greater difficulty learning new material; and
</P>
<P>
   _ Impaired ``executive'' functioning, such as an inability to
locate the car in a parking garage, tend to several tasks at once,
switch from one thing to another, or carry out intentions (``Why
did I come into this room?'').
</P>
<P>
   All of these functions involve the brain's frontal lobe, and
indeed, sophisticated brain imaging techniques show diminished
frontal-lobe activity in older versus younger individuals asked to
perform such tasks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to do with manipulating information and keeping it
on-line,'' says Albert.
</P>
<P>
   In Alzheimer's disease, the main problem area is the
hippocampus, a structure deep in the temporal lobe, or mid-brain,
that is important in maintaining moment-to-moment memory _ the
normally continuous thread of consciousness. In imaging studies of
healthy older people, Albert notes, ``we see very little change in
the hippocampus, but a lot of change in the frontal lobes.''
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Burke, a Pomona College psychologist, is a leading
expert on the tip-of-the-tongue phenomenon, which she has found is
``the top complaint of older adults.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has tip-of-the-tongue problems, even children, but we
have found that word-finding ability gets worse in middle age,''
Burke says. ``And healthy 65-to-75-year-olds report more of these
experiences than 35-to-45-year-olds.''
</P>
<P>
   When young adults search for a word or name, more associations
and clues come to mind than when elders do the same task. ``In
older adults, fewer alternate words come to mind,'' she says.
``They say to us, `My mind just feels blank.' That's quite
different from younger adults, who often get the first letter or a
similar-sounding word.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke's husband, psychologist Donald McKay of the University of
California at Los Angeles, has also found that spelling ability
deteriorates with age.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost as if the neural links that permit rapid retrieval
of words and letters fade with age, Burke says. That is why
remaining ``verbally active,'' as she puts it, through activities
such as conversaton, reading, writing, and crossword puzzles, seems
to help maintain word-finding fluency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you retrieve information in memory, it strengthens
the connection,'' Burke says. ``It's sort of a renewing
phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   But while researchers expose the memory problems of aging, it's
important to keep in mind which cognitive functions do not wane
with advancing years.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Charness of Florida State University has shown that older
chess players were every bit as skilled at playing the game as
younger players of matched ability _ even when their memory was
demonstrably worse. In fact, older players tended to choose the
equally good chess move in less time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turns out that experience is a very important determinant
of performance,'' Charness reports. ``The knowledge and experience
that people have allows them to compensate for age-related memory
deficits.''
</P>
<P>
   That's an important message as societies around the world
confront aging populations and the challenges of keeping people
healthy and productive into their advanced years. ``There is a
strong relationship between age and memory,'' Charness says. ``But
there's virtually zero correlation between someone's age and job
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Richard A. Knox is a member of the Globe staff. His e-mail address
is: knox(at)globe.com.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
