<HEADLINE>
FROM CHIC TO SCHLOCK FOR J. PETERMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can a catalog have ambience? If ever one did, surely it was the
J. Peterman catalog. That may have been just about all it had _
ambience _ but it worked, for just over a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The catalog broke all the rules. A small, vertical format. Lots
of white space. No photographs. Just line drawings and watercolors.
It was the copy that put it in a class by itself, although just
which class was debatable. Some thought the copy evocative,
romantic, literary. To others it was pretentious, overblown,
ridiculous:
</P>
<P>
   ``D. H. Lawrence appears to be smiling and sipping warm scotch.
Lady Ottoline's party is the usual mix: authors, beautiful women,
eccentric painters, and an occasional prime minister. Lawrence
appears dignified and shy in a muted woolen suit, fortified against
the chill with a high-necked alpaca waistcoat . . .''
</P>
<P>
   The D. H. Lawrence waistcoat. The Gatsby shirt. The Hemingway
cap. The Bacall blouse. The merchandise was described anecdotally
in short, short stories designed to make people think, ``I've got
to have that!'' J. Peterman didn't sell mere clothing, it sold
fantasy at inflated prices. It became a target for satirists,
including the writers of ``Seinfeld,'' who had Elaine working for
the company, headed by a fictional J. Peterman given to declaiming,
in orotund tones, language that might have been lifted from the
catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Now the J. Peterman company has filed for bankruptcy and its
remaining stock is being offered at 60 percent to 80 percent off
catalog prices. In the Boston sale, it'll cost you $2 admission and
$6 to park. It's surprising how many people are eager to pay. Such
is the lure of a bargain and of J. Peterman.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't much ambience at the sale. It's housed in a
cheerless room the size of an airplane hangar. There are tables
full of merchandise, some of it still bearing a whiff of the J.
Peterman mystique _ a ``Romanov'' caviar keeper for $26.99, a set
of four ``Havana'' rum glasses for $9.99. And there are racks and
racks of clothes, hanging dispiritedly in the harsh overhead
lighting, almost as if they know how low they've sunk. Gone is the
romance that once was divine, to borrow a line from an appropriate
song.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it never was romantic, really, much less divine. The
J. Peterman success story was built on illusion, a risky
foundation. The company moved steak by selling sizzle. It offered
intangibles: romance, class, adventure. It held out the impossible
hope that you can buy cachet from a mail-order catalog.
</P>
<P>
   The fall of J. Peterman, a sorry tale of greed and
mismanagement, was described by reporter Leslie Kaufman in the
April 2 New York Times. Toward the end, as the company faced ruin,
a decision was made to use cheaper materials for the clothing line.
The result is apparent at the sale. There are some quality items
and a few genuine bargains. But there's a lot of tacky stuff that's
overpriced even at 60 to 80 percent off.
</P>
<P>
   Browsing through the racks, it was impossible not to try to meet
the challenge of writing J. Peterman-style copy for some of the
unlikelier items, a Nehru jacket, for instance: ``Late '60s. Vegas.
The Sands. The Rat Pack. Backstage, I was knocked out by Sammy's
threads . . .''
</P>
<P>
   The sale is a long way from the catalog, a far cry from those
florid descriptions of signature J. Peterman items like the
Hemingway cap: ``He probably bought his in a gas station on the
road to Ketchum, next to the cash register, among the beef jerky .
. .'' And you can be sure he didn't pay $35 for it, the catalog
price.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
