<HEADLINE>
PILLS, EXERCISES ARE TRENDY, BUT PROOF IS WANTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brain tonics, brain preservatives, brain calisthenics.
</P>
<P>
   The booming Boomer market for memory aids is producing a new
wave of products that may be hard to resist, even for people who
consider themselves too sophisticated to swallow many New Age-y
nostrums.
</P>
<P>
   But should you believe?
</P>
<P>
   Will ginkgo biloba in your One-a-Days keep you mentally sharp?
Should you start chewing Brain Gum for the tonic effect of
phosphatidylserine? How about the antioxidant properties of vitamin
E? Post-menopausal estrogen for the gray matter as well as for
maintenance of heart and bone?
</P>
<P>
   And then there are new books and workshops with names like
``Neurobics'' and ``Brainergy.'' Should you embrace claims that you
can pump up your mental ability with maneuvers like brushing your
teeth with the non-dominant hand, taking a roundabout route to
work, or getting dressed with your eyes closed?
</P>
<P>
   It all depends on how gullible you are. When leading
neuroscientists recently met to plan an upcoming meeting, ``We went
through the world's literature looking for anything reasonable'' as
a memory-enhancer, says Dr. Richard Wurtman of MIT. ``We included
none of this stuff because there's no there there.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, researchers who study the aging brain say there are
varying degrees of likelihood that this or that remedy may actually
do something.
</P>
<P>
   Ginkgo and phosphatidylserine (the ingredient in a
``memory-enhancer'' called Brain Gum) are at the bottom of the
list. Yes, there are some studies suggesting possible benefits in
animals and humans, and maybe some reason to do more. But not
enough evidence for mainstream researchers to take these products
themselves, let alone start recommending them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ginkgo biloba is not on my plate,'' says Dr. John Rowe,
coauthor of a recent book, ``Successful Aging.'' However, Rowe _
and many gerontologists _ do take daily doses of vitamin E (Rowe
takes 800 units), because of studies suggesting a benefit for the
heart and possibly the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, recent evidence suggests supplemental estrogen may
maintain memory and brain function in older women. (The effects of
male hormones on the brain have not been much studied.)
</P>
<P>
   As for mental exercise, research supports a general positive
effect from staying mentally active and engaged _ and physically
active too. One surprising finding of a large MacArthur Foundation
research project on healthy elders is that good lung function was
strongly associated with good mental function.
</P>
<P>
   But an effect from supposedly mind-stretching calisthenics like
word games and sensory ticklers? No basis, just thin hypothesis.
</P>
<P>
   And in the future? Stay tuned. Scientists now know they were
wrong about the still-popular notion that the brain loses billions
of neurons as we age. What is lost, according to Yale University
neuroscientist Amy Arnsten, are other cells, which nourish and
support the gray matter, or the ``thinking'' brain.
</P>
<P>
   That's actually great news. If ways can be found to restore the
``neurochemical environment'' of the brain, that might renew
youthful function or at least prevent deterioration. ``We're trying
to see if we can give drugs to restore function in aged monkeys,''
Arnsten says.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Arnsten is taking her daily vitamin E. For her heart
or her head? ``Oh, who cares!'' she replies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
