<HEADLINE>
IN OLKAHOMA, OLD WOUNDS, NEW DIVISIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ On the fourth floor of the old Montgomery Ward
building, where federal housing employees took refuge four years
ago, the tombstone simply appeared one late-summer day.
</P>
<P>
   Gray and no more than 3 feet tall, it was etched with 35 names.
Each one represented a housing secretary or manager, attorney or
director, killed when a truck bomb tore through the Alfred P.
Murrah federal building on April 19, 1995. The survivors had to
face the horror of what had happened to their colleagues, of what
had happened to them, every time they stepped on or off the
elevators.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very controversial, and it said a lot about how
different people were dealing with what happened,'' said an agency
employee who was in the Murrah building that morning, but who still
asked to remain anonymous for fear of appearing insensitive. ``One
group said, `These were our friends.' Another group said, `They
were our friends, too, but we're tired of looking at it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Today &LR; , four years after 168 of their own _ 19 babies and
toddlers among them _ died in the deadliest act of terrorism ever
committed on US soil, the almost instinctive unity that sent
strangers running into the Murrah building to help has given way to
subtle, sometimes painful divisions over how to honor the memory of
the deceased while respecting the needs of the living. Grieving,
always personal, is also communal in this city of 480,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone dies, people think, `How can the world go on?'
But the world does go on,'' said Dr. Stewart Beasley, an Oklahoma
City psychologist. ``But in Oklahoma, you can't drive far without
coming close to it again. People here are constantly facing it and
each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The tombstone has long since been tucked away in what US
Department of Housing and Urban Development employees call the
``reflections room,'' an in-house memorial that some visit often,
some never. But at least two other monuments to the murdered will
be unavoidable: the memorial and museum slated to open next spring
on the site where the Murrah and several other buildings stood, and
the upcoming state trial of one of two men already convicted in
federal court for the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Painful as a memorial may be to pass every day, most of the
people who live and work in this city praise the idea as
appropriate and life-affirming. But the state trial of Terry L.
Nichols, already sentenced to life in prison after a federal trial,
has caused a deep rift among survivors and victims' relatives.
</P>
<P>
   One side insists that justice demands the death penalty, the
sentence co-conspirator Timothy J. McVeigh received for murdering
eight federal agents, among other charges. They say it is
unfathomable that at the federal trial Nichols won the right to
watch his son and two daughters grow to adulthood while they can
only visit their parents' and children's graves.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols, who was not in Oklahoma City the day of the blast, was
convicted in the federal trial of conspiring to bomb the building
and of involuntary manslaughter in the eight agents' deaths. Now he
will stand trial for the deaths of the 160 other victims.
</P>
<P>
   As Doris Jones, whose 26-year-old daughter, Carrie Lenz, learned
she was carrying a son the day before she died, put it, ``He was
not tried specifically for my daughter's murder, and I want to see
that.'' Added Erik McKisick, a district manager with the Social
Security Administration who was covered in debris but otherwise
uninjured in the blast, ``I would like to see him get more than
what I consider a slap on the wrist.''
</P>
<P>
   But many people here say that they accept Nichols's federal
sentence, and that another trial, even one held in Tulsa, would be
too tough on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us have taken a giant step forward, and this will be
a step backward,'' said Emmett ``Bud'' Welch, an anti-death-penalty
activist whose 23-year-old daughter, Julie, was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Added Richard Williams, the Murrah building manager, whose
injuries required surgery after surgery over two years, ``It won't
be helpful at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma County District Attorney Bob Macy defended his decision
to put Nichols through a state trial as the will of the people. In
the days after the devastation, he said, they made him promise to
put the bombers to death. Now, with a roomful of documents
accumulated in the federal government's $82.5 million prosecution,
he has $800,000 in state funds to do that. McVeigh will be tried in
Oklahoma only if his death sentence is overturned on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it will reopen old wounds,'' Macy said. ``A lot
of people feel like they need this before they can close the
chapter on it and stop the hurting.''
</P>
<P>
   That argument infuriates Randall Coyne, an associate law
professor at the University of Oklahoma who also scoffed at Macy's
contention that an impartial jury can be found anywhere in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ears are starting to tune out the shrill and repetitive voices
of the people who have made a life out of the bombing,'' Coyne
said. ``The ones who are quiet don't want to look back every
anniversary.''
</P>
<P>
   This anniversary, the Federal Employees Credit Union is
dedicating a garden at its new offices to the city's tears, with
granite from the Murrah building used in the small reflecting pool.
More than half of the 33 employees then working for the agency were
killed.
</P>
<P>
   Another monument to remembering that most everyone in Oklahoma
City seems to approve is the downtowm memorial and museum. People
call the land ``sacred ground'' and say it must be commemorated.
</P>
<P>
   Created by Boston's Butzer Design Partnership, whose entry won
out over 623 others, with Watertown's Sasaki Associates as
architects, the design is intended to combine the enormity of what
happened with the hope that it will never happen again. As many as
450,000 visitors a year are expected the 3-acre site, where 168
empty chairs will represent the dead and an orchard will represent
rescue workers. Stories of survivors and rescuers will be available
on tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``People heal at their own pace, and some have been able to go
on without forgetting and some haven't,'' said Williams, the Murrah
building manager, who served on the memorial selection committee.
``We're a unique fraternity. We understand each other in a way no
one else can. . . . People ask why we keep opening up old wounds.
Well, they never closed. But our goal is to show the world we can
go on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
