A4205 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-MATRIX-BOS &LR;      04-19 1542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-MATRIX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAETA THE GURU BEHIND THE TRICKS OF `THE MATRIX' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Matrix,'' the semi-dark $60 million sci-fi flick that has
resurrected Keanu Reeves's career, has been the No. 1 movie in the
country for the last two weeks, grossing $72.9 million. Some people
find the plot a bit muddled or, at the least, hard to follow: The
dreams keep blending into reality, and reality itself seems to play
out inside a computer. Others find the tangled web a very cool
thing, an ``Alice in Wonderland''-cum-``Blade Runner'' for the
pre-millennium computer-graphics generation. Or they just
don't &UR;  &LR; care. That's because the buzz is about the jaw-dropping
special effects.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the work of John Gaeta, 33; the people at his northern
California company, Manex; and two Australian companies, DFilm and
Animal Logic. Over the phone from his San Francisco office last
week, the visual-effects supervisor is tossed a big fat softball,
right over the plate: How many times should a fan plunk down his or
her $7.75 to figure this ``Matrix'' thing out?
</P>
<P>
   ``Three,'' he says, without a moment's pause. ``One: for the
emotional impact. Two: to understand the story. And three: to
understand the deeper story.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't, you may note, mention that he wants people to gorge
on and marvel over the special effects. ``It's inevitable'' that
folks will, he says, ``but it's not my goal. My goal, actually, is
to have shots that work seamlessly. That is, the most gratification
I have ever gotten has been on this project and with people saying
it was seamless. . . . We're filmmakers. We're desperate to feel
part of the process, and when we're detached and used as glitter,
then _ I mean, some people are content with that, but that's not
the case with someone like myself who is a designer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Matrix,'' which opened March 31 to mixed reviews, stars
Reeves as a computer hacker who lives in a future disguised as the
present, controlled by computers (the Matrix). There are rebels,
and they think Reeves is their savior. But it was the effects, not
the plot, that pushed the movie to set box-office records for early
spring.
</P>
<P>
   On ``60 Minutes'' a few weeks ago, ``Star Wars'' maven George
Lucas discussed with Diane Sawyer the artifice involved with
special effects _ and the people who complained about what they saw
as this newfangled computerized trickery. Hey, he said, in effect,
wake up. It's movies! It's all make-believe, every bit of it.
Filmmakers have always used whatever tools and technology have been
available to attempt to enhance the cinematic experience. Georges
Melies did it in ``A Trip to the Moon'' in 1902. Even poor old Ed
Wood did the best he could with strings and wires in ``Plan 9 From
Outer Space'' in 19591959.
</P>
<P>
   ``Totally, absolutely,'' says Gaeta, wholeheartedly backing
Lucas's comments. ``It's like Impressionism. What are you going to
do? Shoot down Impressionism bcause it's not totally realistic
paintings like the masters did?'' The anti-special-effects comments
``are like a joke as far as I'm concerned. Technology and movies
were made for one another.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A curious role &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the special-effects teams are in a curious position: They're
an integral part of the overall package, yet they are detached from
the actual assembly of the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' says Gaeta, ``it's up to the creators of the film, the
producers and directors, to decide whether it's going to have a
seamless integration, and most of them decide not, because of, I
guess, naivety or thinking visual effects is a service that is
snapped on as a post (-production) process to attract viewers in a
razzly-dazzly way, but not necessarily with any shots they rely on
to tell stories.''
</P>
<P>
   And what movies might fall into that category? ``Without naming
names?'' says Gaeta, with a laugh. ``There are a lot of films that
I find so absolutely pristine that it seems the stories were
propped up to deliver that visual, whether these be dinosaur movies
or where there's a twister'' and the plot seems ``a vehicle to get
you to that image.'' (Whew. At least Gaeta didn't name names.)
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't the case with `The Matrix,' '' he continues. ``The
Wachowski brothers (writer-directors Larry and Andy) and I hit it
off from the beginning. We're the same age; we have the same
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Which are? ``The whole Gen X-alternative entertainment needs,
ranging from comic books to deviant cult movies to taste in sci-fi
and music in general, which is an unspoken tie.'' Also, and
obviously, a love of the Japanese-style animation called anime, in
which a camera follows an object in motion while moving the
audience's viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Gaeta relates the techno flash of ``The Matrix'' _ its sometimes
dizzying pace, its mix of darkness and light, of edginess and
seeming randomness _ to the mostly instrumental musical genre known
as electronica. ``It's a movie made for and by peole who have grown
up with computer technology, digital presentation, and electronica,
where the end result is a composite of samples of other things, a
blend of influences leading to a higher state. I think the movie
business is going to experience some form of this digital blender,
and I think the Wachowski brothers . . . hit an audience which is
basically comfortable with snappy digital presentation, the
nuances.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros., the studio that released the film, liked the early
scenes Gaeta and company were working on so much it allowed the
filmmakers to more than double the number of special-effects shots
to over 400. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The beauty of flo-mo &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gaeta has a lot to be proud of, including a scene in which
Reeves appears to dodge and outrun bullets. This is a multiple
still-camera effect that Gaeta equates with stop-motion
photography, something he calls ``flow-mo.'' (The cameras shoot
multiple images of an undulating Reeves.) There are several scary
roof-to-roof-in-a-single-bound jumping scenes. (How'd he do that?)
There are many odious creatures and face-bending effects, but Gaeta
says after the flow-mo he is most pleased with the creepy ``fetus
field,'' in which the machines that look like men harvest the
humans they need to supply their life-giving electrical charge.
``It took over a year to do, and it's a miraculous achievement in
computer graphics,'' he says. ``It contains some of the most
complex textures I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaeta, who admires the work of H. R. Giger, the designer of the
aliens in the ``Aliens'' movies, went to film school at New York
University, worked on the ``Saturday Night Live'' animations, and
cut his teeth on animated-TV ads. He spent five years in the
Berkshires with Mass Illusions, the company that evolved into Manex
when it moved to the West Coast 1 1/2 years ago. (Manex employs
between 20 and 100 people, depending on the work needed to be done,
and 40 at the moment.) Gaeta says he served as an associate
visual-tech supervisor on ``Starship Troopers,'' ``Eraser,'' and
``Judge Dredd.''
</P>
<P>
   One potential downside of today's whiz-bang effects might be
that fans become so inured to and numbed by what they see that they
shrug and say, ``So what?'' It almost seems that with today's
technology, if you can visualize it in your head, you can bring if
off on film, via computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not entirely true,'' says Gaeta. Anyway, he says, his task is
to make the visuals ``truly engaging'' even to an audience that is
``to some extent jaded by the intensity of visual effects.'' The
upside of that, he adds, is that if people aren't obsessing over
the special effects or how they were done, they'll pay attention to
the story. One of the criteria for the ``Matrix'' effects was that
each have ``a story point _ some critical information that moved
the story one beat further.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like,'' Gaeta continues, ``when the helicopter crashed into
the (office) building. I could have had it just explode into the
building and it would be like eye candy, but we wanted to avoid it
solely being that. We wanted to use it as another vehicle to show
that the material integrity of a virtual reality is not what you
think it is. When the copter hits the building, the building reacts
like a pebble in a lake, when you drop a pebble in and it ripples.
The lack of material structure supports (the theme) of the dream
state, and that the Matrix, the city, is supposed to be the prison,
the mental prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard-core fans may note, says Gaeta, that the ripple frequency
of the building matches the ripple frequency of a mirror shown
earlier in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even something as simple as the plastic Joel Silver Explosion
moment is turned into something more cerebral,'' he says,
``Cerebral Silver.Gaeta is both praising and kidding the producer
of ``The Matrix,'' and less intellectual blow-'em-ups such as
``Commando,'' ``Lethal Weapon,'' and ``Die Hard.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to future possibilities, Gaeta is one happy
special-effects supervisor. It's a brave new world out there. ``We
have just started scratching the surface of the beginning of doing
virtual environments,'' he says. The day of ``not 3-D, but
three-dimensional movies is five to 10 years away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
