r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDENING-TOOLS-HNS &LR;      04-19 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-TOOLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TODAY'S GARDENERS ENJOY BOUNTIFUL TOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gardening became a recognized status symbol a few
centuries ago. Early well-to-do homeowners had only to hire the
likes of Andrew Jackson Downing, Frederick Law Olmsted or Edwin
Lutyens, among other notable landscape architects of the day, to
design and care for their lavish gardens.
</P>
<P>
   But many homeowners have since begun to find pleasure themselves
in the tasks of gardening.
</P>
<P>
   While that trend continues today, gardeners are often looking
for new conveniences while continuing to borrow landscaping ideas
from the past.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, buying new tools and other landscaping accessories is
part of the fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to start with the new gardening catalogs each year,
which are very helpful when doing research,'' said Cassandra Danz,
the ``Mrs. Greenthumbs'' of television fame. ``You can find just
about anything you need for gardening, from tools to compost bins
and plants to trees and shrubs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are also more garden tools now than ever before,'' Danz
said. ``One of the newer tools that I like very much is the
poacher's or garden spade, which you can find in most English
gardening catalogs or perhaps order it through a local garden
store. They are now pretty easy to find. This tool is good for
getting in and around plants in an established garden. You can use
it for planting bulbs and for weeding. It just pushes the weeds
right up.''
</P>
<P>
   Danz said that she also received a garden hoe as a gift, which
she likes using very much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely sharp, almost like a weapon,'' she mused. ``I
never really hoe, but it's also good for getting rid of weeds,
especially from gravel paths.''
</P>
<P>
   Age is not an obstacle to the pleasures of planting. According
to a survey conducted by Ace Hardware at the Chicago Flower and
Garden Show in March, 54 percent of those polled who have young
children said the youngsters get involved as well, and 43 percent
of young gardeners have a special section of the garden set aside
just for them.
</P>
<P>
   But some adult chores, such as raking, can be back-breaking. To
that end, many garden centers carry a lighter-weight selection of
tools for women.
</P>
<P>
   A handy carry-around tool is the 7-inch folding pruning saw,
which cuts on the pull stroke and is good for green wood, hard,
dead and frozen limbs.
</P>
<P>
   There's actually a lot more these days of almost every kind of
tool, such as pruning shears, which come in every size.
</P>
<P>
   You can also get a pair of gardening gloves for every function
from those with a better grip to rose gloves with leather,
thorn-resistant palms and extra-long cuffs.
</P>
<P>
   If you're planning on planting more than two bulbs, consider the
long-handled bulb planter, which also comes in a few different
styles, for less than $20. With this hand tool, extracting the dirt
is easy, as you have only to push down on the scoop with your foot,
as you would with a shovel. Lift the scoop, drop the bulb in and
tap the soil out into the opening.
</P>
<P>
   If you suffer from arthritis or chronic joint pain, there are
ergonomically designed hand tools. Harmony catalog (800-869-3446)
features stainless-steel and latex-free BS plastic tools that keep
your hand and wrist in a neutral, stress-free position.
</P>
<P>
   The Fist Grip Trowel and Fist Grip Cultivator, which both sell
for $15, can be used for planting, weeding or potting. These also
help the gardener to use the arm, not just the wrist, offering
better leverage in tough soil.
</P>
<P>
   Although they have been out for a few years, foam pad knee
cushions now come in a variety of colors.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond tools, there are also architectural elements to add
interest to your gardens.
</P>
<P>
   Many garden centers sell metal obelisks that add an aged look,
as they already have a rusted patina. Use them as sculpture, a
focal point in the garden, or to grow climbing flowers and vines.
</P>
<P>
   Faux terra cotta pots in plastic look like the real thing, but
are 90 percent lighter than their clay counterparts. In addition,
these pots resist chipping and cracking in freezing weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the new light-weight containers, even the plastic
ones, look like Italian terra cotta from about 20 feet away,'' Danz
said. ``These big containers are really great, especially if you
ever want to lift it again and not pay $200 per pot. I wouldn't
want to pass the plastic ones every day going into my house, but if
you plant them with lush things trailing over the sides and/or dot
them with real terra cotta pots, nobody will ever be able to tell
the difference.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
