<HEADER>
A4208 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-GROUND-BOS &LR;      04-19 1365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GROUND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORPHEUS GETS DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE GROUND BENEATH HER FEET 
By Salman Rushdie. Holt. 
575 pp. $27.50. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oh, Orpheus, son of Calliope, you with your magic lyre and your
great lost love! Following his Eurydice to the underworld, he
brought her out again, only to have her snatched away at the last
moment. Composers and writers have plumbed the Greek myth for
centuries, finding there parables about the failure of art as well
as sheer inconsolable longing. But it takes a certain perverse
genius to transform the tragedy into a story about rock 'n' roll.
Not to mention irony: If a hipster Orpheus and his electric guitar
wind up in the mosh pit, how much worse can Hades really be?
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred by having a galaxy's worth of history to draw from,
Salman Rushdie has used his tale of Orpheus Descending as
scaffolding for an even wider novel: one that brazenly roams among
such subjects as the nature of tragedy, mass culture and celebrity,
global politics, photography, comparative religion, and the cosmic
significance of earthquakes. Replete with the surpluses of
intellect and fancy that define Rushdie's earlier fiction, ``The
Ground Beneath Her Feet'' very much wants to be Joycean in its
cantankerous reach _ a three-pound novel of exile that also manages
to be an ode to literature, a satirical political commentary, and,
of course, a love story. With the same geographical prowess of
Rushdie's earlier fiction, the work is sensate with the smells and
noises and overload ambience of both Bombay and New York. Its
challenges are so panoramic, so against the grain of contemporary
anti-epic fiction, that it will beg the usual Homeric adjectives
(brilliant and dazzling and so forth). Some of them are deserved.
But it should also be said that ``The Ground Beneath Her Feet'' can
be enervating in its unrelenting cleverness and tedious in its
wholesale erudition. It's a bit like having an internationally
renowned scholar seated next to you at a five-course dinner: At
first you're snowed, then you're captivated, and eventually _ when
you still don't know what makes the guy tick _ you just want to go
home, or at least take off your shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly the failings are ones of excess, and they're in direct
proportion to the gauziness of the novel's vast cast. A novelist of
ideas, Rushdie invents his characters not to understand them, but
to employ them: They become vehicles for his narrative journey,
flesh-and-blood manikins for his designs of thought and language.
This isn't necessarily a death-knell trait for a novelist to have
(George Eliot could succumb to something similar, though with
greater sympathy for her team of workers), but here it results in a
particular kind of novel, mind-stretching without being emotionally
engaging. In many ways, Rushdie's cerebral, fabulist fiction is the
loose and baggy monster of the modern age: In a post-tech world
where a war zone can be a ticket to celebrity and John Lennon is as
revered as Mother Teresa, how do you choose what to leave out?
</P>
<P>
   Given the nightmarish banality and false intimacy that now
define much of multimedia's reach, the Orpheus myth, with its
classical elements of doomed love and violent obsession, may be
ripe for resurrection. To refresh the story: Orpheus was a
god-gifted musician in love with Eurydice, who died from a
snakebite while fleeing the advances of Aristaeus. Orpheus pursued
her into Hades, where he charmed even the Furies, and sang and
bargained for Eurydice's return. The gods relented, under the
condition that he never look at his bride until they had safely
reemerged in the upper world. Fearing he had been tricked, Orpheus
glanced back at Eurydice in his last few steps, whereby she was
lost to him forever. He eschewed all other women, and was torn to
pieces for his abstinence in a bacchanalian revel.
</P>
<P>
   Rushdie has reinvented the myth through the viewpoint of
Aristaeus, who here is an Indian photographer called Rai, the
first-person narrator of the novel. ``The Ground Beneath Her Feet''
opens in 1989, when this Eurydice, a 44-year-old Greek-Indian rock
goddess named Vina Apsara, is killed in an earthquake in Mexico.
Rai has loved her since they were childhood friends in India; her
partner and soulmate, Ormus Cama, is a musical prodigy with a deep
shadow to his psyche _ his twin brother died in utero, then his
older brother tried to murder him. In pursuit of both Vina and
musical transcendence, Ormus has been blighted or blessed by his
occasional psychic trips to a parallel universe, that visa of
double vision having been provided by his dead twin. The real
world, where Vina and Rai and Ormus reside, is a place where
President Kennedy barely escaped a bullet in 1963, where Lou Reed
is a woman, and where the famous novelists of the age have names
like Yossarian and Stephen Dedalus.
</P>
<P>
   So: Reality itself is a fiction, in other words, and fiction _
the invention of a reality we can all agree on, even transiently _
may provide the greater truth. Casting about in this ``limbo of
lost possibilities,'' as Rai calls them, Rushdie has created a
multilayered world of exile and dualism, where Western myth and
Eastern religion are equally suspect (or at least populated by
martyred fools), where higher love is as cheap and ephemeral as
last year's rock lyrics. If all of history has been derailed and
the gods themselves are not to be trusted _ if yesterday's gone _
then maybe Einstein was even more right than he knew: The
space-time continuum really is the last frontier, the only place
left to put your faith.
</P>
<P>
   Poor doomed Ormus, with his round-trip rail pass to the other
side, experiences rather than knows this idea; that task of
understanding will be left to Rai, who can create or defy reality
simply by photographing it, and who (as Rushdie's doppelganger)
will be the ghostly synthesizer who ties the story together.
Assuming that the center cannot hold, as this seismic disaster tale
repeatedly insists, rock 'n' roll is the rough beast being beamed
onto screens across the planet: Vina the ``exaggerated avatar'' of
mass confusion, her beauty and trouble and soul-baring to the beat
a way to make people feel. Rai's name means ``hope,'' which, one
assumes, is supposed to offer some relief, though his double
exposure as a man with a camera has, he tells us, compromised him
irreparably.
</P>
<P>
   Rai's confession of his own fatal flaw comes halfway through
``The Ground Beneath Her Feet,'' and Rushdie's treatment of it
suggests the greater problems with the novel. He has wrapped Rai's
relaying of his darkest hour within a long allusion to Molly
Bloom's soliloquy at the end of ``Ulysses,'' which _ with its
triumphant close of ``yes I said yes I will Yes'' _ is surely the
greatest last-gasp affirmation in all Western literature. That
Rushdie has used it here to describe a fallen man's revelation
feels despairing, even nihilistic. If this was supposed to be a
post-Joycean commentary on the state of the planet or the death of
hope, it nonetheless has the effect of trashing the altar to
complain about the congregation.
</P>
<P>
   Swirling with puns and allusions, ``The Ground Beneath Her
Feet'' is Rushdie's own novel of exile and alienation, his love
triangle cursed by the sins of the past and hellbent on repeating
them. He has delivered a disheveled epic about the lethal victories
of contemporary culture, where East and West have traded their most
dangerous weapons _ from rock music to religion _ and thereby
doubled their arsenals, with each emerging the stronger and the
worse for the trade. For all the interpretations of the Orpheus
myth over the centuries, the one that seems to me the most enduring
is Orpheus's ultimate inability to put his faith in the gods. The
only unequivocally holy truth, for Rai, is ``the willing,
disbelieving belief of the reader in the well-told tale.'' That
seems to be Rushdie's Grail as well, and it's offered here as a
coda of half light, amid the suffering, madness, and horrifying
comedy that modernity ensures.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Gail Caldwell is the chief book critic of the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 1353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
