u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-LOOP-BOS &LR;      04-19 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-LOOP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`INFINITE LOOP' TAKES A BITE OUT OF APPLE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
INFINITE LOOP 
How Apple, the World's Most Insanely Great Computer Company, Went
Insane 
By Michael S. Malone 
Currency/Doubleday, 597 pp., $27.50 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another book about Apple Computer? You bet. And it's no use
pretending you've lost interest in Silicon Valley's longest running
soap opera. The extraordinary success of Apple's comeback product,
the iMac, proves otherwise. What other company could put a mediocre
computer in a pretty blue box, charge $200 more than it's worth,
yet have people lining up to buy it?
</P>
<P>
   A great many of those iMac sales were purchases of the heart,
having more to do with aesthetic and emotional appeal than
megahertz and megabytes. It's always been that way with Apple
Computer. No other American business, except perhaps Walt Disney
Co, has ever formed such an enduring bond of love with its
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Which is especially striking when you consider the thoroughly
unpleasant people who built Apple into a great corporation and
nearly destroyed it. It's fashionable to sneer at the rapacious
ambition of Bill Gates. But Michael Malone's new book reminds us
that Apple's creators and leaders are as greedy and domineering as
Microsoft's _ just not as good at it.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the material here is familiar, but it's highlighted by
Malone's deep understanding of the technical and commercial aspects
of the industry. He's especially good in the early part of the
book, retelling the story of the Two Steves _ Apple's technical
genius, Steve Wozniak, and master entrepreneur Steve Jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows that Wozniak was the technical brains of the
outfit, but Malone reminds us of just how brilliant he was.
Nowadays we're accustomed to portable computers, and so it's hard
to remember what a dramatic effort it took to condense all the
functions of a room-sized mainframe onto a single circuit board. At
IBM, it took a crack team of engineers to do it with the company's
original PC. Wozniak did it almost entirely alone, and wrote
software for the original Apple I machine to boot. By rights, ``The
Woz'' ought to be remembered as one of the great inventors of our
times.
</P>
<P>
   But it wouldn't have meant a thing if not for Jobs _ arrogant,
undisciplined, ignorant, but a quick learner possessed of blazing
ambition. An instinctive businessman, Jobs knew what it would take
to make Apple a success. He needed working capital, a solid
management team, and above all, a unique, user-friendly sense of
style that would attract customers who'd never dared to approach a
computer before. Jobs knew what he needed, and he made it all
happen. Indeed, Malone makes a good case that Jobs, not Wozniak, is
Apple's truly indispensable man. After all, if Jobs hadn't found
Wozniak, he would almost certainly have latched onto some other
genius and built some other remarkable firm.
</P>
<P>
   The early period of Apple _ its founding, the introduction of
the hugely popular Apple II, and the birth of the Macintosh _ is
the period that established the firm's reputation and management
style for all time. Which is too bad, because for all its technical
and stylistic excellence, Apple became a profoundly dysfunctional
place. Much of the blame goes to Jobs, an abusive and inconsistent
leader who introduced bitter divisions in the firm that would never
entirely heal. He also introduced Pepsi-Cola chief executive John
Sculley, who proceeded to purge Jobs from the company he'd founded.
</P>
<P>
   Sculley was ambitious all right, and ruthless. But not ruthless
enough. He lacked the nerve to license the Mac's remarkable
software to other computer makers _ a policy that could have
established Apple, not Microsoft, as the world's leading software
company. Besides, with Jobs gone, so was the magic, and Apple was
destined to spend the next 15 years in search of its lost vision.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the second half of the book is a tragic but
familiar recital of Apple's wanderings in the wilderness. All the
horror stories are here, right up to what was arguably the most
appalling: the project to devise a version of the Macintosh
operating system that could run on a standard Microsoft-type PC.
The project succeeded, but Apple decided not to bring the software
to market. The decision meant a wide-open playing field for
Microsoft's Windows 95 software. It also meant that the battle for
domination of desktop computer software was over forever.
</P>
<P>
   Malone tells this part of the story at considerable length but
in an almost perfunctory fashion. One gets the feeling that Malone
began his work at a time when he and nearly everybody else expected
Apple's imminent demise. Otherwise, it's hard to explain why Malone
gives such very short shrift to Apple's extraordinary comeback, led
by the resurrected Steve Jobs. Especially in its latter chapters,
Malone leaves you feeling that there's a great deal more of the
Apple story waiting to be told. Surely enough for at least one more
Apple book.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
