<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4239 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEA-DRUGS-NYTSF &LR;      04-19 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEA-DRUGS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUGS FROM THE SEA  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    THREE COLOR SLIDES are available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent by mail or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne deliverynumber. Please specify that
you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----- This article is also available in Spanish.-----
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ROSIE MESTEL  
 c.1999 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Outside the Scripps Institution of Oceanography in La Jolla,
Calif., the sights, sounds and smells are all of a seaside
paradise. Inside, in biologist William Fenical's lab, it's good-bye
to the sea's charms and hello to the disgusting and fascinating
world of creatures scooped from that ocean outside, ground up and
thrown at every frightening disease Fenical can think of.
</P>
<P>
   This is the medicine chest of the next millennium _ agar-filled
dishes, flasks full of brown nutrient broth and beakers bubbling
like omelets in hell's kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   What's brewing in these potent pots? Stews of fungi and bacteria
that once lived in ocean sediments, rotting driftwood, weeds,
coral, sponges and grasses. Any one of these containers might
harbor a brand-new cancer drug or a compound to wipe out some of
the scariest viruses known to humankind.
</P>
<P>
   With the glory days of antibiotics over, Fenical's quest may be
critical to the future of medicine. Bacterium after bacterium is
gaining resistance to our arsenal. Doctors are desperate for
compounds to attack cancer, Alzheimer's, AIDS and a long list of
other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Since that momentous day in 1928 when Alexander Fleming
discovered penicillin, researchers have been looking in
increasingly exotic locations for the next strain of antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   Fenical's answer is surprisingly simple: Search the sea. Since
the 1980s he has been plunging into the ocean to find the next wave
of medicines. Already he and his colleagues have dredged up some
promising candidates: chemicals that soothe swelling, a compound
from a yellow soft coral that disrupts cell division in cancer
cells and virus-killing proteins from ocean molds that live in sea
grasses.
</P>
<P>
   Fenical is not alone in this effort. Today the list of novel
potential anticancer drugs at the National Cancer Institute's
Natural Products Branch includes more candidates from the ocean
than from the land. Several promising drugs from the sea that might
be used to treat leukemia _ including one from a creature called
Bugula, which clings to the bottoms of boats _ are involved in
human trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ocean is by far the major habitat on the planet _ it's 70
percent of Earth's surface,'' Fenical explains. ``It's teeming with
unique organisms. More than half the organisms in the ocean don't
even occur on land.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the good news. The bad news is that it's difficult to
know just where to look. When it comes to marine life, the rich
history of ethnomedicine provides hardly any clues. Still, Fenical
and his colleagues have come up with strategies to narrow their
search.
</P>
<P>
   The first strategy is to go to a place where life is diverse and
concentrated, such as a reef in the Caribbean. An environment rich
in sea life is more likely to yield varied specimens.
</P>
<P>
   Fenical suspects that creatures loaded with biologically active
molecules _ the kind that they'd need to defend themselves
chemically _ could be the richest sources for all manner of drugs.
Take the strange case of a glorious feathery sea fan called
Pseudopterogorgia elisabethae.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put a bit of tuna out on the reef, fish come from
everywhere, and it's gone,'' Fenical says. ``But if I grind up this
animal and mix in some extract with the tuna, the fish will come
up, take one bite and go `Yuck!' No way will they eat it.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the sea fan's chemical arsenal is a family of molecules
called pseudopterosins which do more than make fish want to barf.
In people, they soothe swelling caused by sunburn or chemical
irritants. They do so by reining in a key enzyme involved in
inflammation, and they do it with more clout than does
hydrocortisone.
</P>
<P>
   Psoriasis, sunburn and arthritis all involve inflammation, and
one or more of the pseudopterosins might one day be the drug of
choice to treat these afflictions.
</P>
<P>
   Fenical reckons that a sea fan extract might also be great as an
additive to toothpaste or for soothing inflamed gums. The extract
is already being added to cosmetics like face creams. Of course,
the hope is to hit the jackpot with far stronger drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of a potential cancer killer, the trick is to ferret
out drugs that kill a range of cancer cells but leave healthy cells
unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   Next, the compound must be purified, its molecular structure
determined and either a drug company or the National Cancer
Institute has to decide to fund testing on animals. Finally, the
drug must be tested on people.
</P>
<P>
   At any stage, testing may be dropped _ for reasons as simple as
the drug's being either too toxic or too weak.
</P>
<P>
   Although that outcome is common in the drug development
business, Fenical is excited about a substance he discovered
several years ago, called eleutherobin, in a remote shallow sea off
the coast of Australia. It comes from a mottled yellow
pickle-shaped soft coral.
</P>
<P>
   Eleutherobin stops malignant tumors from growing in much the
same way taxol does, by binding to a protein called tubulin and
disrupting cell division.
</P>
<P>
   The continuing nemesis of experimenting with sea drugs is supply
_ getting enough material to test, let alone produce, a drug. In
many cases, it's simply too hard to make a drug from scratch. The
chemistry is too complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Microbes can be grown in vats if researchers can figure out what
to feed them, but other substances can prove more daunting to
reproduce. When researchers became interested in halichondrin B, a
promising anticancer chemical from a sponge fondly known as
``yellow slimy,'' they had to collect a whole metric ton of sponges
to derive 300 milligrams of drug _ the amount needed to begin
preliminary trials.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, The National Cancer Institute put out a call to
marine biologists and word came back that the sponge thrives off
the coast of New Zealand. Now researchers are trying to farm the
sponge in Wellington Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent progress, no marine drug has reached the
pharmacy shelf. But Fenical is not discouraged. In fact, he is
passionate about the possibilities: ``If we need new drugs, where
are we going to go? Space? No.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses and waves his hand expansively out the window toward
the wide blue Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sitting right there. It's diverse as hell. And it's
waiting for us.''
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Rose Mestel is a free-lance writer.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
