<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Burning up the grocery aisles
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ Walking the aisles of the supermarket, humming
an old song, ``If I Only Had a Match.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you remember it. Maybe not. Frank Sinatra did a version
way back when he was recording for Columbia, early 1950s or before.
</P>
<P>
   Something like this ...
</P>
<P>
   If I only had a match, I could have a cigarette, if I only had a
cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   But if I did have a cigarette, I could watch the smoke curl and
think about my girl, if I only had a girl.
</P>
<P>
   But if I did have a girl, we could get married and live happily
ever after.
</P>
<P>
   If I only had a match.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that I was looking for matches.
</P>
<P>
   Can you imagine, being out of matches?
</P>
<P>
   I'd turned the house and most every drawer in it upside down the
night before looking for a match. So I could light the gas logs in
the fireplace. So my teeth wouldn't chatter.
</P>
<P>
   If I only had a match.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody runs out of matches. I'd run out of matches.
</P>
<P>
   You don't know how hard it is to find a match until you need a
match.
</P>
<P>
   All those signs in a supermarket from one aisle to the next:
</P>
<P>
   Canned goods ... Sugar ... Snacks ... Baby food ... You name it
...
</P>
<P>
   On and on, but not one mention of matches.
</P>
<P>
   So I'm going up one aisle and down another, pushing a buggy just
in case I see something else I need.
</P>
<P>
   A man can go broke going up and down supermarket aisles, buying
stuff he sees that he needs.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I could have asked. But ...
</P>
<P>
   It's a man thing. You don't ask for directions when you're
driving your car. You don't ask for directions when you're pushing
your buggy.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I figured it out. Barbecue. Charcoal. Matches. You got
one, you gotta have the other.
</P>
<P>
   Where do you find charcoal? I'm closest to the meat department
so I check with the meat department.
</P>
<P>
   A nice lady working behind the meat counter is talking to a man
wearing a tie and a name plate. Figure him for the manager,
especially the way the conversation is going.
</P>
<P>
   She's doing all the talking, all about how Memorial Day weekend
is coming up, and how they'd planned so long, and it was her
husband's 30th birthday ...
</P>
<P>
   She stops in mid-sentence. Customers can have that effect on
employees when their manager is standing there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matches?''
</P>
<P>
   ``With the paper products,'' she suggests.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, an aisle over,'' the manager says.
</P>
<P>
   He adds, ``Come on, I'll show you.''
</P>
<P>
   I think he was glad for the excuse to get away. Employees can
have that effect on their managers.
</P>
<P>
   Not in paper products. Not on the next aisle either. Finally, we
find matches. They're with the barbecue supplies. That's what I get
for asking.
</P>
<P>
   Only _ can you believe it? _ the supermarket has run out of
matches, too, leastwise the big boxes of kitchen matches like I
need to light the gas.
</P>
<P>
   All that's left on the shelf are those little penny boxes of
matches that cost heaven knows how much nowadays.
</P>
<P>
   The manager goes to check with the stock boy. No luck. Matches
are on order.
</P>
<P>
   So instead I end up buying a fire gun, if that's what you call
it. Anyway, that's what it looks like:
</P>
<P>
   A small pistol with a long, slender barrel. You pull the trigger
and, Pop!, the end lights up. A bargain at $3.99. Never have to buy
a match again, leastwise not until this thing runs out of whatever
fires it up.
</P>
<P>
   I check out. Total bill, what with all the stuff I found I
needed while pushing the buggy up and down the aisles, $70.44.
</P>
<P>
   Which would have bought a whole lot of penny boxes of matches,
regardless what they cost.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.; web page,
http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
