<HEADER>
A4246 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN21-CO     04-19 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: A funereal contrast in athletes
 &HT;    (For release April 21, 1999. Moving on commentary and sports
wires.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The weather was cool by Miami standards, overcast and
generally depressing. My wife was holed up in the front bedroom,
battling a strep throat and not wanting any company. It was just me
and the TV set.
</P>
<P>
   Following the repetitive litany of those Sunday morning talking
head programs in which every expert on the Kosovo situation seems
to be saying the right thing until the next expert comes on the
screen and says something different, there was the choice of old
movies, infomercials or sports.
</P>
<P>
   The great hockey player Wayne Gretzky was retiring Sunday, and
it was the second day of the professional football draft. With both
on TV, it was an opportunity to surf between them.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast became remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   As Gretzky skated around the ice to appreciative cheers in New
York City's Madison Square Garden, just several floors below _ the
same building, mind you _ the National Football League was dividing
up the last hundred or so prospects for next season.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky epitomizes everything we want in a sports hero: talent,
modesty, family, gratefulness. He's a person I wish I could say is
the embodiment of an all-American hero, but he's Canadian; he's an
all-Canadian hero. How fortunate for Canada!
</P>
<P>
   When the network broke for a commercial, I switched over to the
draft just in time to see the Miami Dolphins select a running back
who has been kicked off teams at two colleges, has failed three
drug tests, has recently pleaded guilty to two counts of
unauthorized entry and two counts of simple assault, has five years
of suspended jail time, is on four years' probation, requires
weekly drug testing and periodic counseling, must make good on a
$2,500 debt owed to a battered women's shelter, is not allowed to
have any contact with his victims and is banned from walking onto
the Louisiana State University campus.
</P>
<P>
   So who would you rather have baby-sitting your kids, Wayne
Gretzky or Cecil Collins, a.k.a. Cecil the Diesel?
</P>
<P>
   The two represent the polar caps of the sports world.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky, of course, never needed another chance; he didn't flub
the first one. But men like Collins and Darryl Strawberry _ another
sad sports story of last week _ constantly are being awarded an
opportunity to fall astray again, and be paid handsomely as well.
</P>
<P>
   I kept pushing the remote. There was Gretzky with his wife and
kids, his old teammates, the greats he played against _ all
admiring each other, the fans holding up signs thanking the great
athlete for his 20 years of professional hockey.
</P>
<P>
   And there was Jimmy Johnson, the coach of the Miami Dolphins,
defending his selection of Collins _ saying he had great football
potential and should have another chance. When the draft shifted to
the studio analysts, an interesting question was put to Marty
Schottenheimer, a former quality NFL coach: ``Should a football
coach be responsible for the conduct of his players both on and off
the field?''
</P>
<P>
   After hedging a bit, Schottenheimer agreed that the coach does
share a significant degree of responsibility. Last year, Johnson
brought another bad seed into the Dolphins camp, a running back
(and woman abuser) named Lawrence Phillips, who had unceremoniously
been booted from another NFL team for his failings both as a player
and a human being. Johnson gave Phillips another chance; he blew it
in a bar near Fort Lauderdale, another woman roughed up.
</P>
<P>
   He's now playing in the European league; someone gave him
another chance again. I'm all for giving a guy another chance, but
how many is ``another''?
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of the afternoon, I stayed with Gretzky as he
played his final game. Often, my eyes turned misty when I thought
of what he has brought to the troubled world of sport and how we
will _ and should _ cherish this humble, great athlete.
</P>
<P>
   And then I thought of Collins; but just for a second, because
compared to Gretzky, that's all he was worth.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
