<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
 (Repeating to fix date)  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, April 20:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ NATO gives a briefing on the convoy
incident, with video; saying NATO forces may have killed the
civilians. NATO also blames the Yugoslav Army for having military
vehicles mixed with civilian vehicles. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PILOTS (Washington) _ Peering down at the ground from
15,000 feet or higher, NATO pilots like those who apparently
attacked civilians in Kosovo by mistake rely on a combination of
technology and their own eyesight to identify what they are seeing.
By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ Developments from Washington on
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Washington) _ President Clinton talks with
Russian President Yeltsin for first time since NATO attacks
started. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Skopje, Macedonia) _ Aid agencies worry as the
refugee flow seems to stop everywhere. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHILDREN (Brazda, Macedonia) _ In Macedonia alone, the
International Committee of the Red Cross has found 276 children who
arrived here with no adult relatives. They are now cared for by
strangers, and aide workers have posted lists of their names and
pictures of them in camps here in the hopes their parents will
materialize. Another 600 parents are searching for their missing
children. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic and map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NOVISAD (Novi Sad, Yugoslavia) _ Journalists taken to see
bomb damage in Serbia's second-largest city. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-VOTE (Istanbul) _ The far-right nationalist party,
strongly anti-Kurd, surprises everyone with 2nd-place finish behind
Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit's party; Islamists were third. In the
east, Kurds win many municipalities. By Steven Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-BERLIN (Berlin) _ Chancellor Schroeder declares a new
``Berlin Republic'' as the German Parliament moves into Reichstag.
By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ The long, tangled relationship
between Benjamin Netanyahu and Labor's Ehud Barak, the prime
minister's chief rival in the May 17 election, provides an odd
backdrop to the campaign. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-MOSQUE (Jerusalem) _ The Israeli government says that a
mosque can be built in Nazareth, a town where there has been
Christian-Muslim violence. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S. (Washington) _ President Clinton has promised Prime
Minister Zhu that China will get into the WTO, but the question
remains whether he can sell this to Congress. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ A roundup: The Supreme Court agrees to
hear the question of whether a defendant has the right to represent
himself on appeal; it is already well established that such a right
exists at trial. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   DEECEE-CONGRESS (Washington) _ An appeals court hears arguments
in the District of Columbia suit seeking full representation in
Congress. By Irvin Molotsky.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-PROFILE (Washington) _ A political profile of Bill
Bradley, the New Jersey Democrat; the first in series of occasional
profiles of presidential contenders. By Richard L. Berke. (1800
words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FLA-FIRES (Miami) _ An Everglades fire that already has consumed
70,000 acres threatened to expand today as erratic winds and dry,
warm weather remained in the forecast. By Pamela Mercer.
</P>
<P>
   MRSCLINTON (New York) _ The first lady in New York, with a
packed schedule. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   LA-SCHOOLS-PROMOTE (Los Angeles) _ The Los Angeles Unified
School District has scaled back its plan to end social promotions,
which advances unready students into higher grades. By Don Terry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TELECOM (Rome) _ Telecom Italia and Deutsche Telekom appear
poised to announce a merger, which would be Europe's largest deal
ever. Boards of both companies are meeting, and an announcement is
scheduled Tuesday morning in London. Olivetti says it is going
ahead with its $65 billion offer for Telecom Italia. Deutsche
Telekom shares rise as much as 4 percent in Frankfurt. By John
Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   TELECOM-EURO (Frankfurt, Germany) _ What a Telecom
Italia-Deutchse Telekom deal might look like. What would a linkup
mean for European telecommunications? By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   CITIGROUP-EARNINGS (New York) _ Citigroup reports first-quarter
earnings that sharply exceed Wall Street forecasts. First-quarter
profit was more than any other financial services company, and
exceeded the most recent profits of Microsoft, General Motors and
General Electric Co. Earnings rose 9 percent, to $2.36 billion, or
$1.01 share, surpassing forecasts of 87 cents a share. Bank of
America also posts earnings above estimates. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   COMPAQ (Undated) _ After the weekend ouster of its chief
executive, what are the challenges awaiting Compaq's next chief?
And who would want a job with a board dominated by the chairman and
founder, Ben Rosen? By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH-QWEST (Undated) _ BellSouth Corp. is buying a 10
percent stake of Qwest Communications for $3.5 billion. Bell South
will be able to use Qwest's high-speed data and long-distance
network to offer more services to business customers. By Seth
Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:20 p.m., the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 69 points, after having been up over 200 earlier, as
better-than-expected results from Citigroup lead financial services
stocks higher. Nasdaq was down 82. In London, the FTSE 100 rose
1.44 percent. The Nikkei fell 177 points, or 1 percent. Hong Kong
rose 276 points, or 2.2 percent. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   LILLY-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Elil Lilly reports earnings that
match Wall Street estimates. But growth in sales of Prozac, Lilly's
biggest drug, fell 4 percent in the quarter. By David J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Undated) _ Brazil is tapping international credit
markets for the first time in a year, selling at least $1 billion
of five-year bonds in a reflection of the country's strong rebound
from economic paralysis only three months ago. This week's offering
is the first of up to $5 billion of sales in the coming months by
Latin America's biggest economy. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA-INVEST (Hong Kong) _ Stock markets from Seoul to Singapore
have been rising sharply, and many analysts here say the rallies
are proof that foreign investors are returning in droves to the
recession-ravaged economies of Asia. Foreign fund managers are
steering more money to the region, in part because technology
stocks in the United States have lost some of their luster
following the troubles at Compaq Computer. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   BANANA-TRADE (Geneva) _ The WTO approves U.S. sanctions against
European Union members because of its banana regime, but whether
such sanctions can be retroactive is still in dispute. By Elizabeth
Olson.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Thomas L. Friedman's ``Foreign Affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
