<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Monday, April 19, 1999    
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee or Mark
Helm at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all
sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-LEVIN (Washington) _ Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., just back
from a weekend in Albania, Macedonia and Brussels, says the
American people should be prepared for a long air war, one lasting
``many months,'' over Kosovo. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-EDUCATION (Washington) _ About half the science teachers
in a new survey say they lack confidence in the school science
programs they teach. Dr. Mae Jemison, a former astronaut, comments
on the findings, which are consistent with past studies showing
severe problems in science education. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Originally First Lady Hillary
Clinton was picked on for being bossy, brassy and too brainy. Now
she's being scoffed at for planning to write a book about
entertaining at the White House, supposedly a homebody subject
inappropriate for a putative U.S. Senate candidate. This is silly.
The female Clinton has never been one-dimensional. By MARIANNE
MEANS.
</P>
</TEXT>
