<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ATTN. EDITORS: IN THE FOLLOWING PROVOCATIVE ARTICLE, THE
INDEPENDENT OF LONDON'S RESPECTED CORRESPONDENT, ROBERT FISK, PICKS
UP THE PIECES _ AND DAMNING EVIDENCE _ OF NATO'S MASSACRE OF KOSOVO
ALBANIANS WEDNESDAY. &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When you stand at the site of a massacre, two things happen.
First, you wonder about the depths of the human spirit. And then
you ask yourself how many lies can be told about it.
</P>
<P>
   The highway of death between Prizren and Djakovica _ on which
the Serbs say NATO slaughtered 74 Kosovo Albanian refugees in a
series of bombing raids _ is no different.
</P>
<P>
   Only hours after I slipped on a dead man's torso near an old
Turkish bridge, less than a day after I stood by the body of a
young and beautiful girl _ her eyes gently staring at me between
half-closed lids, the bottom half of her head bathed in blood _ I
watched James Shea, NATO's spokesman, trying to explain why NATO
still didn't know what had happened on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps The Independent can help clear up this unhappy state
of affairs with some evidence _ damning perhaps, certainly
important _ from the scene...
</P>
<P>
   Of the four air-strike locations, I have visited the first three
_ at Velika Krusa, Gradis and Terzick Most. At the third, I came
across four bomb craters. I saw _ and in some cases collected _ a
number of bomb and missile parts.
</P>
<P>
   NATO intelligence authorities should be able to work out some of
their codings within a few minutes... &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (STORY MOVED IN TWO VERSION: A LONG TAKE WITH THREE
USER-FRIENDLY OPTIONAL TRIMS _ TOTALING 1,075 WORDS _ AT 225 (375
WORDS), AT 1,025 (100 WORDS) AND AT 1,200 (600 WORDS). SHORTER
VERSION IS 1,000 WORDS.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-PROOF-NATO-GUILTY-FISK-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SHORT VERSION:
BC-PROOF-NATO-GUILTY-2nd-TAKE-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
