</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Tuesday, April 20,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CONFLICT
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STRIKES _ WASHINGTON _ The latest developments in the
U.S.-led NATO bombing campaign including NATO briefing on last
week's convoy attacks. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TROOPS _ RINAS AIR FIELD, Albania _ Paratroopers of the
U.S. Army 82nd Airborne Division stepped off air transports here
late Sunday and early Monday, then made preparations to move north
to the troubled border area of northern Albania. The paratroopers
are the lead elements of the 2nd Battalion of the 505th Parachute
Infantry Regiment of the 82nd. The 505th Parachute Infantry
Regiment was the one Gen. Eisenhower dispatched into Normandy by
parachutes at the very start of the D-Day offensive. This is an
escalation of pressure on Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic,
not only because of the 82nd's reputation as troops who fight to
win, but that the 82nd is the first unit from outside the
traditional NATO troop pool in Europe to be sent to the combat
zone. (Albright, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Monday
submitted a $5.9 billion emergency spending request for military
operations in the Balkans _ a sum that Congress is expected to
quickly increase and approve. What remained uinclear was whether
the measure would prompt a more general debate on the war policy.
(Deans, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES _ KUKES, Albania _ Yugoslav military forces
abruptly turned off the spigot to halt the flow of Kosovar Albanian
refugees into Albania and Macedonia Monday, leaving the families
and humanitarian aid officials to wonder what has happened to the
more than 80,000 refugees expected to cross the border over the
last few days. Developing.
</P>
<P>
   (Kunstel, Cox News Service). 25. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   JOURNAL-ALBANIA _ KUKES, Albania _ I always thought I would take
stringent care before putting the term ethnic cleansing in print. I
wondered about news stories from the Balkans _ stories I didn't
cover myself _ and questioned whether it was justified to describe
long-running civil conflicts as something of broad consequence,
something that is the younger brother of genocide. Now I know.
(Kunstel, Cox News Service). 20. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-HEALTH-FLA _ WASHINGTON _ Local Medicare beneficiaries
are generally in better health and receive more preventive and
surgical care than their counterparts nationwide, but they also pay
more for treatment, according to a report issued Monday. (Lipman,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADES-FIRE _ The celebrated River of Grass now has a wall
of fire. About 70 acres of the Everglades has burned. What does
this mean for the natural area? (King.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   COMDEX _ CHICAGO _ Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates and Linus
Torvalds, creator of the Linux operating system, give back-to-back
speeches Monday at the Comdex computer show. The speeches come at a
time when Microsoft's Windows is under siege in a federal antitrust
suit and the company's products are pressured by production delays
and falling PC prices. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   COMDEX-TRENDS _ CHICAGO - The portion of U.S. households with
Internet access is expected to peak at about 75 percent, according
to a forecast made at the Comdex show. Story looks at
computer/Internet trends. Glass. With COX-COMDEX. Moving in
financial and Washington categories. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Both stories moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-HEROES _ ANAHEIM,Calif. _ Atlanta heroes Matt Moseley and
Ivers Simms attend a parade in their honor today at Disneyland.
Moseley, an Atlanta fireman, rescued Simms, a crane operator, from
atop a crane where he was trapped during a large fire last week.
(Rogers, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH _ BellSouth Corp. today announced plans to buy a 10
percent stake in Denver-based Qwest Communications for $3.5
billion. Qwest is one of the nation's more ambitious providers of
high-speed data and long-distance services. (Kannell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: An early version has moved for Monday afternoon papers.
</P>
<P>
   FLIGHT-GLENN _ John Glenn helps 2003 Committee unveil its latest
plans for celebrating the 100th anniversary of flight at a big gala
at the Air Force Museum. (Gaffney, Dayton Daily News). 20.
</P>
<P>
   GORE _ CINCINNATI _Vice President Al Gore hits Cincinnati with
Tony Hall, Ohio's ranking democrat, in tow. Most interesting event
promises to be a public discussion on health care at the Jewish
community center. (Hershey, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN _ ATLANTA _ GOP presidential hopeful U.S. Rep. John
McCain of Arizona speaks to the Georgia Public Policy Foundation
Monday as part of a ``Road to the White House'' speaker series. Dan
Quayle is scheduled to address the group April 28. George W. Bush
and others have been invited to speak. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
