<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTI-MASTECTOMY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG BREAST CANCER PATIENT RESISTS RADICAL TREATMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARSHA GINSBURG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ One of the biggest paradoxes for doctors and
specialists is that some healthy women are choosing to remove their
breasts to prevent cancer, while those already stricken with cancer
are refusing to have them taken off.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Fox, 32, is among the women who are appalled by the
notion of removing a piece of their anatomy that is part of what
makes a woman a woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were talking about a toe, I'd care less,'' said Fox, an
athlete who runs, swims and bicycles. But a mastectomy ``is
extremely invasive and extremely barbaric ... and unnecessary in
most situations.''
</P>
<P>
   If taken to its logical end, she wondered, ``Why not take
everything I don't need to survive?''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who has no family history of breast cancer, discovered a
lump in her breast last summer. Two days later, a biopsy delivered
the news no woman wants to hear: breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   She had the textbook treatment _ a lumpectomy to remove the
tumor. Then she went in for a second surgery to remove more
surrounding tissue that might contain cancerous cells.
</P>
<P>
   A month after her surgery, she started chemotherapy, and
followed it with radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer specialists estimate that breast cancer recurs in about
30 percent of women who get it once, though the risk varies
depending on the size of the tumor and how aggressively the cancer
cells replicate. There are cancer-fighting drugs like tamoxifen
that can lower a woman's risk of recurrence, and an experimental
drug raloxifene, under study to see if it reduces risk with fewer
side effects.
</P>
<P>
   In the process of interviewing a myriad health professionals,
preventive mastectomy was recommended. Fox cried.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had gone through two surgeries to save the breast and not
do mastectomy in the first place. I thought this was all behind
me,'' she said. ``I walked out and said, `No way.' I wasn't going
to be paranoid about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who is an urban planner, had misgivings many single women
in their 30s might have about preventive mastectomy.
</P>
<P>
   She said losing sensation in her breasts would be bizarre, and
believed that having a mastectomy could lower her self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   Although artificial implants can create breasts that appear very
real, she worried that the surgery would cause discomfort or limit
her in her many sports. If she has children someday, as she hopes,
she couldn't breast-feed.
</P>
<P>
   Among other issues: how would she explain to a boyfriend or
prospective husband about her artificial breasts?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard enough to date anyway and to find your soul mate,''
she said. ``And you add that complication on top of it ... I don't
know how most men feel about that and cancer and women without
breasts. It would probably be very scary because it deals with
their own mortality.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of her decision was based on vanity, Fox acknowledged, but
a larger part was based on the fact that doctors could offer no
guarantee that breast cancer would not recur after the mastectomy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My breasts are definitely a part of me and who I am,'' she
said. ``It would be a huge loss for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Before she ruled out the operation, doctors recommended she take
the blood test for the BRCA gene mutation, which can raise a
woman's risk of breast or ovarian cancer to between 60 and 80
percent. Fox declined, concerned about discrimination in future
health coverage plans if she tested positive.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, her doctors suggested she take the drug tamoxifen,
which has been shown in studies to reduce the risk of cancer
recurrence in women by up to 45 percent. But the drug also raises
the risk of uterine cancer and birth defects, so Fox declined.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she takes Chinese and Tibetan herbs and listens to
positive healing tapes at night. She eats organic foods and
exercises rigorously.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said she sees cancer not as a dark cloud, but as ``something
you get through.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the future is going to bring,'' she said.
``But I'm too young for this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
