<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4434 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-DISASTER-     04-19 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-DISASTER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CONSEQUENCES OF NATO'S AIR STRIKES: A NEW WORLD DISORDER, A NEW
ARMS RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By MIKHAIL GORBACHEV  
 c.1999 La Stampa  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   In the three weeks of war in the Balkans it is estimated that
NATO planes have flown 6,000 missions and 800 cruise missiles have
been launched.
</P>
<P>
   The tragic result is that the Kosovo conflict has turned into a
catastrophe, with hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanians leaving
their homes and enduring appalling hardships. Many of them have
died in bombings or in the crossfire of fighting between the Kosovo
Liberation Army and Yugoslav forces.
</P>
<P>
   With the war sowing death and destruction throughout Yugoslavia,
the damage to it has been estimated at $200 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the conflict, many people warned that a military
operation against Yugoslavia would be a mistake, an unwarranted and
disproportionate measure, and urged a political solution. NATO took
a different course, which has resulted in an ignominious failure _
a defeat for NATO and for the policy of force generally.
</P>
<P>
   This could have untold consequences for Yugoslavia and for all
of Europe, unless urgent steps are taken to stop this madness.
Henry Kissinger, who was initially critical of President Clinton's
actions, is now saying that if NATO is to avoid breaking up it
cannot afford a defeat in Yugoslavia. He is apparently little
concerned about what would happen to the Albanians or to the Serbs
in the event of NATOs ``victory.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the leaders of the alliance speak of a political
solution, they in fact mean Yugoslavia's capitulation. But that is
just another dangerous illusion, a way to unpredictable,
catastrophic developments. The only alternative to a wider conflict
is a search for compromise.
</P>
<P>
   As I am writing this, news agencies report that the Turkish
authorities are conducting a major offensive against Kurdish
rebels. The long-seething conflict has erupted with fresh force,
but no one is saying a word. What will the United States and NATO
do? Give more weapons to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   And in Colombia, another friend of the United States, where
20,000 people die each year and the number of refugees has exceeded
1 million, even U.S. newspapers are wondering why the United States
chooses to ignore the responsibility of Colombia's government for
that tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, why? This is more than just a double standard. A much
broader hidden agenda is now being revealed. It is clear that the
Kosovo problem could have been resolved politically and that NATO's
military action can only make things worse. It is also clear that
this is a no-win situation for Europe.
</P>
<P>
   So why was the United States in such a hurry, why was it not
interested in political solutions? On the eve of NATO's 50th
anniversary, the Kosovo conflict is cynically being used to show
the world who's the boss.
</P>
<P>
   The international community is given to understand that the U.N.
Security Council and other international organizations are
ineffective, indeed helpless, thus forcing the United States to
``lead'' in this way. Even worse, to make arbitrary action look
legitimate, the conflict is being internationalized and other
countries are drawn into it, in a way that compromises them. But
that logic is fatally flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the Soviet Union ceased to exist, the United States
has been boycotting all attempts to reform the United Nations and
circumventing its Security Council. It has also thwarted efforts to
create a new European security architecture, as called for in the
Charter of Paris, thus forcing Europe to accept NATO's ``security''
services.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kosovo conflict, the United States has defied the opinion
of Russia, China and India, which together represent half the
population of the world. It has shown its European allies that
Europe remains a political dwarf, that even its economic might
cannot stop U.S. hegemony. That, today, is how Washington envisions
a new world order.
</P>
<P>
   Such behavior has already done serious damage to the
international system. The danger is becoming real that the Yugoslav
tragedy could engulf the entire Balkan region and even all of
Europe. Even if the conflict is stopped soon, it is clear that the
world could hardly go back to what it was before March 23.
</P>
<P>
   A new arms race appears inevitable. There are dozens of
countries where this ``model'' can be replicated _ creating and
exacerbating latent conflicts and then ``settling'' them with
bombs, cruise missiles and ``surgical strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, there was an imperfect world order based on
international organizations trying to resolve crises politically.
Now, nations will want to rely on arsenals of weapons. And since
sophisticated modern weapons are too expensive for most countries,
they will not play by the rules of the rich; instead, they will
seek weapons of mass destruction _ nuclear, chemical and
biological, which can be cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, terrorism _ the cheapest weapon. No one can hope
to protect themselves from this dread threat with purely technical
or military means.
</P>
<P>
   It should be clear to all that this is a road to disaster. Not
only Russian politicians but most ordinary Russians as well have
been badly shaken by the conflict. It is giving ammunition to the
forces of the past, those who were always against new thinking and
resented any reforms, any cooperation with the West.
</P>
<P>
   I am convinced that the Russian people are wise enough not to
allow their country to be drawn into a war. But it would be
irresponsible to ignore the fact that the danger of a wider
conflagration is growing. Of course, we should keep a clear head,
but Russia will now have to rethink a great deal in its strategy,
its treaties and certainly its relations with NATO.
</P>
<P>
   It will now be impossible to overcome the crisis at no cost _
but overcome it we must. The way out is to resume efforts to build
a new world order based on equitable cooperation of different
civilizations. No one has given NATO the kind of functions that it
has arrogated to itself and seems ready to proclaim as the basis of
its new doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   Washington must resist the urge to try to manage increasing
global complexity with police operations. We must not condemn the
world to disorder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __ Translated from the Russian by Pavel Palazchenko. &LR; __
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Mikhail Gorbachev, the last leader of the Soviet Union before
its collapse in 1991 and a Nobel Peace Prize winner, heads the
Gorbachev Foundation for International Peace and lectures
frequently around the world on subjects related to post-Cold War
politics.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
