<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4465 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENWORTH-TRUCK-SPI &LR;      04-19 1389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENWORTH-TRUCK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENWORTH GEARING UP FOR THE TRUCK OF TOMORROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BILL VIRGIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Kenworth Truck Co.'s new version of its T2000 probably
has a better home video, audio and computer system than your house,
and a better security-surveillance system.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, your house can't do 60 on an interstate.
</P>
<P>
   Kenworth's advanced technology truck has been making the rounds
of shows and customers, giving drivers and fleet operators the
chance to ogle such gee-whiz touches as dual cup holders that offer
individual hot/cold temperature controls for the driver and the
passenger.
</P>
<P>
   But Kenworth's truck is loaded with some serious-minded
technology, like cameras that give the driver a view of the blind
spot along the right side of the trailer.
</P>
<P>
   And there's a serious business purpose to Kirkland, Wash.-based
Kenworth tricking up a heavy duty truck with technology that puts
most people's homes to shame. The 42-inch flat-panel television in
the sleeper cab might seem like a frill, but Kenworth has as solid
a business reason for putting that on a truck as it does installing
the camera system.
</P>
<P>
   Those who write the checks for new trucks ``are quite willing to
spend money on improving safety and anything that improves the
lives of drivers,'' says Jim Mele, editorial director of Fleet
Owner magazine. ``In those two areas, the wallets are open.''
</P>
<P>
   For Kenworth, the advanced technology truck is a way of showing
fleet owners and drivers what's possible and finding out from them
what they're likely to want on future trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Brown is one of those who has looked the truck over. Brown
is the chairman of Contract Freighters Inc. in Joplin, Mo., which
operates 1,900 trucks, the majority of them Kenworths.
</P>
<P>
   He started driving trucks 35 years ago; he remembers trucks that
have required manipulating two levers to shift gears, had no power
steering or air conditioning (or if they did the a.c. usually
didn't work or dripped water on the driver). He also remembers
driving as a team in a truck equipped with a 24-inch bunk. ``I'm
wider than 24 inches,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   So Brown looks at trucks with the eyes of both a driver and an
operator. ``We continue to look for new technology that enhances
productivity, reduces costs and improves safety,'' he says. At the
same time time, he says, anything that makes the life of the driver
more comfortable, ``I support.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the features in the new Kenworth truck that caught
Brown's eye was a dashboard system for providing directions. ``It's
something our drivers are concerned with each time we pick up a
load'' in unfamiliar territory, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Another is a computerized driver log. Instead of fumbling with a
pencil-and-paper log, the driver can enter information at a touch
of a button; not only does the system record mileage data and other
information, it can also shoot it back to the home office. ``You
don't have the age-old problem of time lapse,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Trucks of the future may also free drivers from doing a lot of
the shifting with what's known as an automated transmission. It
differs from an automatic transmission in that the driver still
uses a clutch. ``You use the clutch once when you start, once when
you stop,'' says Ted Scherzinger, who is with Kenworth's advanced
concepts group (but who describes his job as ``they let me build
nice trucks'').
</P>
<P>
   In between starting and stopping, the driver can use a steering
column-mounted control to tell the transmission to shift up or down
or maintain a particular gear.
</P>
<P>
   Automated transmissions aren't cheap, but fleet owners think
those systems allow drivers to concentrate on the road, Mele says.
``I thought drivers would be the last ones to give up that
multispeed gear box, but drivers like it,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   To improve safety, Kenworth is showing off a sophisticated
vision system that features miniature cameras in the side mirrors
and on the outside of the sleeper; that will be valuable for
eliminating blind spots, changing lanes, backing up and turning
tight corners.
</P>
<P>
   Future enhancements to the vision system will reduce the glare
of headlights and allow drivers to ``see'' beyond their headlights
or through fog. The system might also enhance the image to provide
more information to the driver; if that car on the right is closing
in dangerously, the vision system might highlight it with a bright
color.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the cameras were a nicety, but I've heard a lot of
big operators say `we need to get these on trucks now,''' says Dan
Farmer, Kenworth's assistant chief engineer. They're interested in
having cameras record what's going on outside the truck, for
liability protection.
</P>
<P>
   Truck comforts have come a long way from the days of that
24-inch bunk in the truck Brown drove, and more are on the way.
Kenworth's model truck features an alphabet soup of consumer
electronics _ DVD, VCR and CDs, not to mention satellite and
Internet links.
</P>
<P>
   Those features are not just for flash. The trucking industry
continues to face a problem in recruiting and retaining drivers;
fleet owners figure that with drivers virtually living in their
trucks while they're on the road, making those trucks more
comfortable might help attract and keep employees.
</P>
<P>
   Kenworth officials acknowledge that at least some of what
they're showing isn't cost-effective now for most customers.
</P>
<P>
   But Scherzinger says it's worth it to Kenworth to understand the
technology now. It's likely to become less expensive, and when it
does Kenworth wants to have done the work on how to incorporate
that technology into a truck.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of off-the-shelf technology also hasn't been readied for
the rough environment, with vibrations and extreme temperature
swings, of the commercial truck `You can't just take a laptop PC,
strap it down to the seat and expect it to live,'' Scherzinger
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the technology is available but not in the form we
want to put in the truck,'' Farmer adds. Consider global
positioning systems, for example. GPS technology is readily
available, but Kenworth wants a system that provides information to
the driver without requiring him to do a lot. ``You can overload
the truck; you can overload the driver,'' Farmer says.
</P>
<P>
   In fact some of Kenworth's new information systems are designed
to provide less, not more. If the rear axle temperature is fine,
the information panel won't bother the driver with a gauge telling
him that. That way, as Brown puts it, ``drivers can deal with
exceptions rather than the norm.''
</P>
<P>
   Truck manufacturers have other reasons for getting a head start
on tomorrow's technology. Right now, with a glut of orders and
strong backlogs, truck builders like Kenworth (a unit of Bellevue,
Wash.-based Paccar Inc.) are manufacturing trucks as fast as they
can.
</P>
<P>
   For several years the industry has defied forecasts of a
slowdown. But eventually those forecasts will prove to be right,
and truck makers will want to hold on to market share, or even
seize a few percentage points from competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a truck with all the bells and whistles can be
important'' to build market share, says Paul Latta, research
analyst with McAdams Wright Ragen Inc. in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   As feature-intensive as the advanced technology truck is,
Kenworth has hardly drained the well of potential improvements. Ed
Caudill, Kenworth's general manager, has been talking to groups
about such innovations as electronically programmed engines (so
that fleet operators could change the horsepower of a truck
depending on whether it was operating in the mountains or the
plains) and radar warning systems for tracking the speed and
distance to other vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   One interesting technology that may show up on a future Kenworth
``truck of the future'' is ``brake by wire,'' using electronics
instead of pneumatic systems to activate a truck's brakes.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic braking could get the signal to the brakes faster
than conventional systems, and balance the braking over the wheels
of the tractor and trailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brake by wire is a no-brainer,'' Brown says. ``If you can fly
a 747 or a jet fighter without attached cables, it makes sense to
me you should be able to do the same thing with a
tractor-trailer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
