<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4471 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUREOFMECCA-TEX     04-19 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUREOFMECCA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY MUSLIMS ARE DRAWN TO MAKE A ONCE-IN-A-LIFETIME PILGRIMAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TARA DOOLEY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five times a day for most of his 38 years, Hasan Hasan-Ali has
knelt and prayed toward Mecca.
</P>
<P>
   When he was a child and a teen in Kuwait, this receptacle of
prayer was a city in a neighboring country to the southwest _ the
most holy city of the Islamic faith and the dwelling place of the
``House of God.''
</P>
<P>
   When he became a student and later an engineer in Texas, Mecca,
though geographically farther than before, remained central to his
daily thoughts, his rituals, his faith.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, for the first time, Hasan-Ali beheld Mecca.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like something I've been looking for all my life,''
Hasan-Ali said. ``You feel the presence of God, and you feel like
crying.''
</P>
<P>
   For Muslims, making a pilgrimage to Mecca _ a hajj _ is a
once-in-a-lifetime obligation of faith for all who can gather the
money and strength for the journey. Annually, it attracts more than
2 million of the faithful.
</P>
<P>
   During the five-day ritual, believers aim to follow in the
footsteps of Abraham and Mohammed, chief prophets in Islamic
tradition. But the goal of the journey is to repent of sins and
return home with a renewed devotion to God and commitment to
leading a pious life, said Imam Mohamed El Ajami, the spiritual
leader of Dar Eleman mosque in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hajj that God accepts, there is no reward but paradise,''
said El Ajami.
</P>
<P>
   Mecca is a city in southwest Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Muslim teachings, it is also where God told
Abraham to build a house, or what tradition refers to as the Ka'ba.
The area is also where God is said to have told Abraham to
sacrifice his son, Ishmael, who was saved at the last minute by the
hand of God. (Jewish and Christian teachings hold that Isaac was
that son.)
</P>
<P>
   According to the Koran, the prophet Mohammed considered the
Ka'ba to be the house of God and instructed Muslims to pray toward
it. Shortly before his death in 632, Mohammed made a pilgrimage to
Mecca, setting the pattern for the hajj.
</P>
<P>
   While participating in the hajj, Muslims are urged to shed
worldly concerns and concentrate on their devotion to God, said
Associate Professor Yushau Sodiq, who teaches Islam in the Texas
Christian University religious studies department.
</P>
<P>
   But the hajj also unites Muslims from distant countries,
creating an Islamic Ummah, or community. Though women can wear what
they want, men shed their street clothes and wear an ihram, or two
white sheetlike pieces of cloth, intended to eliminate social
distinction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Status is unified,'' Sodiq said. ``Everyone is equal before
God.''
</P>
<P>
   And they are also made humble before God.
</P>
<P>
   ``After going through this experience, I feel that if I thank
God every second of my life, that is not enough,'' said Colleyville
resident Abdul Rashid Khan, who recently returned from the hajj
with his wife, Zohra Khan.
</P>
<P>
   Though all the rituals are performed in a period of about five
days, the main portion is conducted on the ninth day of ``the month
of hajj.'' This year, the five-day observance took place March
25-29. The time of year it occurs changes annually because the
Islamic calendar is based on the lunar cycles.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most important moments of the hajj takes place in
Arafat, outside of Mecca, Khan said. Here, pilgrims spend most of
the day praying outside, which means they find themselves in
temperatures as high as 100 degrees, given the time of year. At
sunset, the pilgrims move to Muzdalifah, where they pray for
forgiveness throughout the night, without shelter and surrounded by
millions of unknown faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very frightening,'' Zohra Khan said. ``It gives one the
perspective of the reality of how the day of judgment is going to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Another important ritual of the hajj is one in which pilgrims
pray as they circle the Ka'ba seven times surrounded by throngs of
people, each trying to get close to the black stone that sits to
one side of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a strange feeling you don't have in regular
life,'' Hasan-Ali said. ``... You are next to others, there is no
room, no space. It's an emotional sea that everyone gets into.''
</P>
<P>
   Though a spiritual journey, there are practical matters to
attend to when traveling from Texas to the center of Islam, and
those require some planning.
</P>
<P>
   Hasan-Ali decided a year ago that he needed to attempt the hajj
while he is still young and strong. So he started planning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the feeling, an urge, that I needed to do it,''
Hasan-Ali said. ``This year I decided, `This is it. No matter what,
I'm going.' ''
</P>
<P>
   An engineer for Parkland Hospital in Dallas, Hasan-Ali took
nearly three weeks off and traveled to Mecca with Dar El-Eiman, an
international company with three U.S. offices.
</P>
<P>
   For between $2,700 and $6,500, Dar El-Eiman handles everything
from securing visas and booking hotels to planning meals and
arranging transportation within Saudi Arabia, said Fawaz Mushtaha,
company vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone who makes it to Mecca for the hajj can afford the
accommodations or has the connections to make the arrangements.
Hasan-Ali said he saw pilgrims sleeping on medians in the street,
unable to find or pay for hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   But Americans, in particular, seem to have an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabia grants visas for the hajj based on the percentage
of a country's population that practices Islam, said Tarik
Allagany, information supervisor for the Royal Embassy of Saudi
Arabia in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Muslims in American make up a relatively small percentage of the
population, meaning most who want to make the trip can. And often
they have an opportunity to make the journey more than once.
</P>
<P>
   In some Islamic countries, there are waiting lists, and most
pilgrims usually get to make the journey only once in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``You leave your heart there,'' said Yassin Siyyadeh, a
Carrollton resident and a Dar Eleman mosque member who this year
made his second hajj. ``I've tried to explain that, but I don't
think there is a word in my dictionary.''
</P>
<P>
   Though perhaps inexpressible, it is a sentiment Hasan-Ali would
probably understand. Despite still fighting a flu that he picked up
from a lack of sleep and the proximity to 2 million people,
Hasan-Ali said he will probably return _ next time with his wife,
Tamie.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to do it exactly like the prophet did,'' he said.
``... Like everything you do, the first time is not perfect, so you
want to do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
