<P>
   SCI-ASHTEKAR-PHYSICS (Undated) _ Scientist at Work: Dr. Abhay
Ashtekar, the leader of a worldwide effort to unify the two most
profound, abstract and mathematically baroque theories of physics
discovered in this century, now is explaining his work in a
six-month workshop in California. His passion boils down to this:
An attempt at creating a sort of cosmic nouvelle cuisine by merging
Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity with the laws of
quantum mechanics. By James Glanz. (2250 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MERCK-MANUAL (Undated) _ The first edition of the Merck
Manual, the venerable medical textbook first published in 1899, was
reissued this week in a commemorative centennial package along with
the 1999 edition. On seeing it, there is a surge of relief that we
have come so far. Back in 1899 a patient with asthma might well
have marched under doctors' orders directly to the tobacconist for
a cigarette: ``smoking is sometimes beneficial'' for this
condition, the manual reports. An alcoholic might have been dosed
up with opium, or sent off to suck an orange and drink a pint of
hot water before meals to curb his craving. For baldness, the
doctor might have suggested applying ammonia to the bare pate
(``very useful'') or taking a little arsenic by mouth. By Abigail
Zuger, M.D. (925 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PLANETARY-SYSTEMS (Undated) _ A major discovery announced
last week has given birth to a new field of science, the
comparative study of planetary systems. At last, after centuries of
speculation, often more fanciful than scientific, and recent years
of expectant searching, astronomers have found a family of planets
to compare the solar system with. They detected three large planets
_ two of them with masses much greater than Jupiter's _ orbiting
another solar-type star, Upsilon Andromedae, 44 light-years away.
Scientists confidently predict that this will be the first of many
similar discoveries. By John Nole Wilford. (1550 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PARKINSONS-FETAL (Undated) _ In a controversial experiment,
half the subjects in a study of Parkinson's patients underwent
brain surgery to have fetal cells implanted in their brains. The
other half had the surgery but received nothing. On Wednesday,
results of the controversial experiment will become available and
those receiving the placebo will decide if they want to try the
real thing. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg. (1600 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRAIN-PLASTICITY (Undated) _ In a fascinating set of
experiments, researchers at the Center for the Neural Basis of
Cognition in Pittsburgh have found a way to teach native speakers
of Japanese to reliabaly hear the difference between ``L'' and
``R'' _ after just one hour of training. The new findings are
``extremely compelling,'' said Dr. Edward Jones, a neuroscientist
at the University of California at Davis and president of the
Cognitive Neuroscience Society, who is familiar with the research.
They shed light on how the adult brain changes - a phenomenon
called plasticity _ and on mechanisms that make it resistant to
change. The experiments show that the adult brain is capable of
substantial change, even late in life. By Sandra Blakeslee. (1400
words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Short items on science: the speed of tiny
shrimplike crustaceans, genetically engineered crops and a new
record for the most distant galaxy ever viewed. (650 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GOD-DEBATE (Washington) _ What if Jerry Springer decided to
do a show pitting one particle physicist who believed in God
against another who did not? And if he asked them to hash out,
before a live audience, whether the universe is the product of
divine design? The result might be something like the refreshingly
rousing debate between the Nobel Prize laureate Steven Weinberg and
the knighted physicist-turned-theologian John Polkinghorne that
invigorated hundreds of people here at a conference meant to bring
science and religion closer together, and highlighted the current
twists on an age-old dispute.God and science seminar. By Carey
Goldberg. (1280 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GIANT-BACTERIA (Undated) _ German, Spanish and U.S.
researchers have discovered the largest bacteria ever found,
according to an article published Friday in the journal Science.
The giant bacteria, found off the coast of Namibia, are 100 times
bigger than the previous record-holders and in some cases are even
visible to the naked eye. By Henry Fountain. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Personal Health column: Recent
studies have highlighted a wide variety of foods and beverages that
offer the promise of a healthier heart, often with other protective
benefits as well. In fact, if weight is not a problem, some people
may not have to eat low-fat at all, as long as the fats they eat
are the right kinds of fats. An overview of foods shown to have
healthful results. By Jane E. Brody. (1340 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-RESEARCH (Sydney, Australia) _ The hopes of researchers
in seeking a non-virulent strain of HIV. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LYMPH-NODES (Undated) _ A new procedure for testing the
lymph nodes of women with early-stage breast cancer is so promising
and is gaining in popularity so rapidly that leaders in the field
are concerned that some surgeons may try it without being properly
trained. And any errors that result can be fatal. By Holcolm B.
Noble. (640 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FITNESS-SCULLING (Undated) _ A look a sculling, by a novice
inspired by Tori Murden of Louisville, Ky., who last summer set out
from North Carolina in a 23-foot boat hoping to become the first
woman to row across the Atlantic solo. A former collegiate sculler,
Ms. Murden rowed for 85 days and was two-thirds of the way across
when Hurricane Danielle forced her to give up. A look at the sport,
which involves rowing with two oars or sculls. Although there are
two- and four-person boats for sculling, it is most often a
solitary pursuit. By Martha Barnette. (1350 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STEROIDS (Undated) _ Two new anabolic steroids appear to
have helped kidney dialysis and AIDS patients regain some of the
weight they had been losing uncontrollably as a result of the
illnesses. This discovery represent a return to the original
purposes for which the drugs were developed. By Holcolm B. Noble.
(900 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PHARMACOGENOMICS (Undated) _ The ten pharmaceutical
companies that announced last week they were setting up a genome
mapping consortium are hoping to buy a seat at a revolution that
may soon start to sweep over their industry. But like all
revolutions the impending advance, known as pharmacogenomics, is
unlikely to be bloodless. The basic idea is to match patients, on
the basis of a genetic test, to the drugs that will do them most
good and least harm. By Nicholas Wade. (1300 words)
</P>
