<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY 
 
BETWEEN IRS AND FOES, BUSH TAXED BY TAXES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ These are taxing times for would-be presidents,
and they promise to get worse.
</P>
<P>
   The $3.77 million federal tax payment that Gov. George W. Bush
and his wife, Laura, coughed up was enough to inflict pain, even on
someone who made an estimated $18.4 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the man is always crying out for ``tax relief.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Internal Revenue Service will probably be the least
taxing ordeal that the governor will encounter as he continues to
gear up his White House campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Early front-runners, as we all know, don't always win the big
prize, but they certainly serve a practical purpose in the
meantime. They are tasty entrees for non-front-runners, the media
and just about everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   As is already obvious, every effort will be made by reporters
and Bush's political opponents to uncover and regurgitate his
distant past.
</P>
<P>
   In the present tense, his leadership capabilities also will be
questioned if state lawmakers _ who are eagerly heeding his plea to
be boring _ don't follow through on his other legislative
priorities as well.
</P>
<P>
   And with six weeks remaining in the legislative session, Bush's
scorecard will soon start taking shape.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most controversial items on his wish list, a bill to
require parents to be notified before their minor daughters can
have abortions, is scheduled for a committee hearing this week in
the House, where a similar bill got derailed two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters are optimistic that the measure, which already has
won Senate approval, will make it to the governor's desk this time.
But if the bill fails again, there will be a lot of chattering
about how Bush failed to deliver on a key promise to the Republican
Party's right wing and seriously damaged his chances to win the
party's White House nomination.
</P>
<P>
   All of which may or may not prove to be true.
</P>
<P>
   A bill to use tax-backed vouchers to pay private school tuition
for some Texas students _ another high-profile Bush priority _ is
struggling but isn't dead yet.
</P>
<P>
   Although the governor may take some of the blame for a voucher
failure, it may pose less political damage for Bush than for Lt.
Gov. Rick Perry, who has been a much stronger advocate for vouchers
but isn't running for president.
</P>
<P>
   Then, of course, there is the matter of tax relief, which may
prove to be the biggest problem on Bush's gubernatorial record,
less for what happens this spring than for what Bush tried to do
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature will reduce taxes this year. But the reduction
will likely be less than the $2.7 billion cut Bush proposed during
his re-election campaign, thanks to a lower-than-anticipated budget
surplus. And lawmakers may rearrange the governor's tax cut
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   The governor will take whatever tax cut the Legislature gives
him and use it to try to bolster his national campaign _ or
minimize any damage he incurred on the tax issue during the 1997
session. That was when he tried to trade higher state taxes for
lower local property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature rejected Bush's ambitious tax plan and a revised
tax overhaul that he also supported two years ago. In the end,
lawmakers simply raised the homestead exemption on school property
taxes, and Bush declared victory, bragging that he had cut Texans'
taxes by $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Collectively, that was the savings. But each individual
homeowner saved only about $140 a year, and many taxpayers never
saw that much because some school districts ate up the savings by
raising their tax rates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is potentially vulnerable on taxes because of his proposed
1997 trade-off. He proposed cutting school property taxes by almost
$3 billion a year in exchange for raising the state sales tax by
one-half cent per dollar and substituting a controversial, general
business tax for the more limited corporate franchise tax.
</P>
<P>
   The governor would have used a budget surplus to produce an
overall, net tax reduction. And he could be commended for trying to
improve an outdated state tax structure.
</P>
<P>
   But good policy doesn't always make for good politics. Other
presidential contenders will ignore the tax cuts and attempted
trade-offs and simply fire away at the tax increases that were in
Bush's plan.
</P>
<P>
   One Republican opponent, Steve Forbes, already has called Bush
``that tax man in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush certainly doesn't consider that a fair characterization.
But if such attacks keep coming _ and they probably will _ he may
find them more annoying than even the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
