r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LONGHORNHERD-TEX     04-19 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONGHORNHERD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGHORN HERD TRAINING FOR JUNE DEBUT AS LIVING REMINDER OF COWTOWN
HERITAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINSCOTT RANCH, Texas _ On a windswept pasture of bluebonnets
and spring grasses, 16 longhorn steers are in ``spring training''
of sorts. They're being prepared to become living reminders of Fort
Worth's cowtown heritage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two of the herd's newest recruits proved their agility and
independence one day last week by jumping a 4-foot barbed-wire
fence to a dramatic, but short-lived, freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The two steers were part of the herd that was unloaded in a
holding pen on Ed Bass' Winscott Ranch in southwest Tarrant County,
where the cows will be settled and trained before moving to their
permanent home in the Fort Worth Stockyards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of work to do before we get them down there,''
trail boss Dennis Merrell said after the wayward steers were
reunited with the herd. ``But this is the day we've been waiting
for. The cowhands are ready, the horses are trained, we're ready to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrell said he and his crew will work daily with the herd until
its public debut June 12 when the longhorns will be driven from
downtown to the Stockyards as part of Fort Worth's sesquicentennial
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the herd program is to teach tourists the
significance of the cattle industry in Fort Worth's 150-year
history through authentic re-enactments of cattle drives and
exposure to the herd.
</P>
<P>
   Cowhands will drive part of the herd through the Stockyards to
the Trinity River each day, beginning in June. Part of the herd
will remain in pens for display.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is as impressive a herd as I've ever seen,'' said herd
historian and curator Tom B. Saunders. ``They are just tremendous
looking.''
</P>
<P>
   Saunders, whose family has been in the cattle business for
generations, said it will take time to settle the new herd. They
are big and used to going where they please, he said of the massive
steers. ``That is the nature of the beast,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've got a good mixture here,'' he said. ``The colors
really depict the diversity of the breed. The horn size shows they
are sure enough, straight-blooded Texas longhorn cattle.''
</P>
<P>
   The steers range in age from 5 to 15 years, weigh between 1,700
and 2,000 pounds and have horn spans of 4 to 6 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Laughing at the short but exciting escape of the two steers,
Saunders recalled what the ``old-timers'' often said about the
longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They look awfully clumsy just standing around,'' he remembered
the old cowhands saying. ``But they are as quick as a cat, as fast
as a deer, and they have the disposition of a grizzly bear.''
</P>
<P>
   The herd was first assembled in South Texas a month ago. Ned and
Curley, two veterans of the 1995 Great American Cattle Drive from
Fort Worth to Miles City, Mont., were the first members, donated by
Bob and Mary Mike McKenzie of Aledo.
</P>
<P>
   The two steers were sent to the El Coyote ranch in South Texas
where they were joined by the rest of the herd, donated by several
others including the King Ranch, and Lee and Ramona Bass, owners of
El Coyote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to feed them and let them settle a little,''
Merrell said. ``We're going to let them get used to the horses.
They've been together for awhile, but they were on a 2,500-acre
pasture all by themselves. This is a little different.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrell said he and Saunders also will work with the Texas and
Southwestern Cattle Raisers Association on an elementary school
curriculum that explains the importance of the cattle industry to
Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Merrell, Saunders and the entire crew will be on hand Thursday
at a special Fort Worth Chamber of Commerce luncheon at the
Stockyards Station Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket prices and additional information can be obtained by
calling the chamber at (817) 336-2491, Ext. 231.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
