<P>
   ATTENTION FOOD AND FEATURES EDITORS,
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The San Francisco Chronicle, whose articles are a part of The New
York Times News Service, is pleased to announce a new column,
``Learning to Cook,'' by well-known food writer Marion Cunningham. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Even in this food-savvy age, many people don't know how to cook.
Though supermarkets bulge with products unavailable just a decade
ago and TV cooking shows abound, many are embarrassed by their lack
of basic skills. For example, consider the divorced executive with
a recipe telling him to toss sliced apples in a bowl. He stood
across the room and threw in the pieces. Or the woman searching the
dairy case in vain for softened butter. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Marion Cunningham, who has been called the modern Fanny Farmer for
her work in revising two editions of that famous cookbook, offers
solutions for these novice cooks through the column and her new
book, also called ``Learning to Cook,'' to be published in May. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Beginning the week of April 19, the San Francisco Chronicle offers
``Learning to Cook,'' available regularly through The New York
Times News Service. The column, slugged BC-LEARING-TO-COOK-SFCHRON,
will move on Tuesdays with a ``d'' dining-category code. If you
have questions, feel free to call Holly Ocasio Rizzo at The
Chronicle, at (415) 777-8811. &QL;
</P>
