<HEADER>
A4503 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMOKING20-COX     04-19 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOKING20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS URGED TO SAVE TOBACCO SETTLEMENT FOR THE STATES
 &HT;    By SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sens. Bob Graham and Kay Bailey Hutchinson joined
the National Governors Association on Monday in urging Congress to
keep the federal government from claiming states' tobacco
settlement money.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, D-Fla., and Hutchinson, R-Texas, made the appeal to a
House-Senate conference committee that is working on a compromise
version of an emergency spending bill. The bill contains items such
as such as hurricane aid to Central America and humanitarian
efforts in Kosovo in addition to the tobacco settlement measure.
</P>
<P>
   The states received $246 billion settlement from the tobacco
industry after suing it for reimbursement of medical costs. The
federal government contends it deserves 57 percent of the
settlement because of its contribution to the Medicaid health
insurance program for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Graham and Hutchinson introduced legislation in January to stop
the federal Health Care Financing Administration from seizing any
of the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every member of the Senate and the House of Representatives is
from a state that will be negatively affected if the federal
government succeeds in stealing what the states earned on their
own,'' Graham said at a news conference. ``It's bad federalism for
the federal government to step in now and dictate how states spend
money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're calling on the House to join the Senate in a united
voice to the federal government: Hands off the states' money,''
Hutchinson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a states' rights issue,'' said Gov. John. G. Rowland
of Connecticut. ``State legislatures and governments should decide
how to spend the money and on what programs.''
</P>
<P>
   A letter to conference committee members signed by 30 senators
said that the fiscal 2000 budget that President Clinton submitted
in January assumed the federal government would recoup $18.9
billion from the tobacco settlement through cuts in Medicaid
payments to the states.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the Senate Appropriations Committee included the
protection initiative in its version of the supplemental
appropriations bill. The Senate also defeated an amendment in March
that would have required states to spend part of their tobacco
settlement on certain goals.
</P>
<P>
   Graham said that Gov. Jeb Bush of Florida has proposed using the
state's tobacco settlement toward a $2 billion endowment named
after the late Gov. Lawton Chiles and aimed at children and older
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland added that many states are planning to spend the money
in a variety of ways, including anti-smoking programs, education,
and nursing home care.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
