<P>
   TELECOM (Rome) _ The boards of Deutsche Telekom and Telecom
Italia met separately late into the night tonight to discuss a
merger that would create one of the world's biggest telephone
companies. But after scheduling a news conference in London on
Tuesday to announce a deal, they abruptly canceled it because of
unspecified difficulties and did not set a new date. It was unclear
whether the cancellation was the result of a major obstacle in
negotiations for a merger, which, investment bankers have said
could be valued as high as $106 billion. That would make it the
largest takeover in history, far higher than the $84 billion
Exxon-Mobil merger announced last November. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Computer-related and Internet shares dragged
the Nasdaq Composite Index to its worst drop since October. It was
around 5.6 percent. Investors sold Microsoft Corp. and America
Online Inc., among the biggest gainers in recent months, and bought
laggards such as oil, aluminum, steel and chemicals stocks. The Dow
Jones Industrial Average surrendered a 272-point gain as General
Electric Co., Wal-Mart Stores Inc. and Merck &AMP; Co. slumped.
Citigroup Inc. spurred a rally in financial shares after reporting
unexpectedly strong earnings. The Dow was down around 76 points. By
Kenneth Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PARKINSONS-FETAL (Undated) _ In a controversial experiment,
half the subjects in a study of Parkinson's patients underwent
brain surgery to have fetal cells implanted in their brains. The
other half had the surgery but received nothing. On Wednesday,
results of the controversial experiment will become available and
those receiving the placebo will decide if they want to try the
real thing. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg. (1600 words)
</P>
