<HEADLINE>
NAME, RANK AND JOB REFERENCES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the employment world, there aren't many things as frustrating
as making a bad hire _ except maybe firing that bad employee.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid the pain, managers go out of their way to make sure
they don't hire a dud. But that's not so easy any more because
companies are very reluctant to comment on the job performance of
previous employees.
</P>
<P>
   Employers have been warned for years by their lawyers that they
shouldn't reveal any information _ good or bad _ about a former
employee. That way, they don't have to defend the truthfulness of
Joe's bad attendance problem or Sue's inability to get along with
co-workers in a defamation lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, companies typically will reveal only the dates of
employment and the position held by the former employee, commonly
known as ``name, rank and serial number,'' in human resource
circles. But that means another company gets stuck with the same
problem employee.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're giving references, we give as little as possible,''
said Larry Williams, director of human resources for the Marek
Family of Cos., a Houston construction company. ``But if we're
getting references, we try to get as much as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   To ease the frustration that employers such as Williams face,
the Society of Human Resource Management has promoted legislation
across the country that would try to limit the liability of
employers who give out truthful references.
</P>
<P>
   The association has met with success: 32 states now have laws
that are supposed to make it easier for employers to give out
references.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, a reference-checking bill sailed through the House on
Wednesday in an overwhelming vote of support and will now head to
the Senate, where it apparently has some strong supporters.
</P>
<P>
   But even if it passes, don't be lulled into thinking that it's
OK to spill your guts about a former employee.
</P>
<P>
   Employers already are protected by the law if they give a
truthful reference, said T.J. Wray, an employment lawyer with
Fulbright &AMP; Jaworski in Houston. The bill doesn't eliminate the
problem that faces companies today: the cost of defending a
defamation case.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, employers don't often lose the defamation cases, Wray
said. They just don't give out references to avoid the cost of
spearheading a defense.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Obdyke, an employment lawyer in Austin who also represents
employers, agreed with Wray that the bill wouldn't prevent angry
former employers from filing defamation lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   But Obdyke, who has testified on behalf of the bill and is
shepherding it through the Legislature, said he hopes it will give
employers a measure of comfort to pass along comments about former
employees.
</P>
<P>
   But is the lawyer taking his own advice?
</P>
<P>
   In a touch of irony, Obdyke said that if the bill passes, he
will continue to advise his clients who want to avoid defending
themselves in defamation lawsuits that they better not say anything
about their former employees other than their dates of service and
position held.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe over time the statute would make employers feel more free
to disclose information, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The measure _ which Rick Levy, legal director of the Texas
AFL-CIO, dubs the ``right-to-lie bill'' _ is opposed by trial
lawyers and labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   It might provide cover for employers to engage in blacklisting
of former employees, Levy said. But he suspects, like Wray, that it
won't free up the tongues of reticent employers frightened about
having to defend themselves.
</P>
<P>
   One human resource manager in Houston isn't counting on the bill
to give her carte blanche to discuss previous employment records.
</P>
<P>
   It's still too risky, she said, asking not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   If employers really wanted to make it safe to give references,
they need a law that gives them immunity from reference-related
lawsuits, Wray said. But then there would be the danger of some
unscrupulous employers _ a minuscule number, of course _ who would
use the legal shield to pass along false information.
</P>
<P>
   Or the Legislature could make it more difficult for former
employees to sue by raising the burden of proof or requiring
employees who lose to pay the legal defense bills of their
ex-employer.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the best thing is for employers to step up to the plate
and accept the risk of giving out references as the cost of doing
business, Wray said. It's to the advantage of the community to get
the information out and there probably wouldn't be a big rush to
the courthouse if employers gave out references.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
