<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4557 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CATHOLICUNIVERSITIES-     04-19 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLICUNIVERSITIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC UNIVERSITIES IN TEXAS RESIST CLOSER TIES WITH VATICAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A Vatican effort to forge closer church ties
to Catholic universities could stifle academic freedom, impair the
ability to draw quality faculty and threaten some forms of student
grants and loans, the president of Texas' largest Catholic
university says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like being a Catholic school, but from where I sit, if some
of these proposals are approved, it would be very problematic for
us,'' said the Rev. John Moder, president of the 4,100-student St.
Mary's University in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Moder is one of several Catholic university presidents _
including those from Notre Dame, Fordham and Boston College _ who
are concerned about proposals made in a draft document scheduled to
be voted on this fall by U.S. Catholic bishops. It would affect 236
U.S. Catholic universities.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II has long been concerned with the growing
secularization of Catholic schools. Some institutions, for
instance, have removed crucifixes from their classrooms. The new
rules are meant to bring the universities back to their religious
roots.
</P>
<P>
   Proposals now in the draft that have raised concerns include:
</P>
<P>
   _Demanding that presidents of Catholic colleges be ``faithful
Catholics'' and take an oath of fidelity to the church.
</P>
<P>
   _Requiring theology professors to get certification to teach
from local bishops.
</P>
<P>
   _Urging that most of the faculty members be Catholics in good
standing and that most trustees be members of Catholic churches.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul, in a 1990 letter called ``Ex corde Ecclesiae''
(From the Heart of the Church), formally expressed his demand that
Catholic schools identify closely with their religious heritage. He
left it up to bishops of each nation to decide how to do that.
</P>
<P>
   American bishops approved a proposal in 1996 by a vote of 226-6.
But Vatican authorities rejected it in 1997, saying it lacked
``juridical,'' or legal, language needed for enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Monsignor Milam Joseph, president of the 3,000-student
University of Dallas in Irving, said he has few concerns about the
draft document but will make final judgments when it's completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always been proud of our Catholicity,'' he said. ``I'm
sure this whole matter can be worked out and can be very
beneficial.''
</P>
<P>
   Moder said his school also cherishes its Catholic roots. But if
the plan requires theology professors to receive permission from
local bishops to teach, it could raise questions about academic
freedom and threaten some forms of federal aid, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think many of us would be prepared to do without
federal student aid,'' Moder said.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 percent of the students at St. Mary's and 90 percent at
the University of Dallas receive some form of federal or state aid,
school officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Monika K. Hellwig, executive director of the American
Association of Catholic Colleges and Universities, said she doesn't
believe that student aid programs would be threatened at Catholic
schools.
</P>
<P>
   More of a concern, she said, is that Catholic universities could
be ineligible to receive state grants available in New York,
Washington and some other states if there is too much church
control. The funds help build classrooms and pay for research
projects, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hellwig is a nonvoting member of the bishops' committee drawing
up the draft document.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're under the gun to explain to the Vatican why some of
these proposals can't be stated in a legal manner; they need to be
stated in a pastoral way,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hellwig said the Vatican wants to add ``teeth'' to make the
requirements enforceable. But if the rules are stated in a legal
way, accrediting agencies and organizations that give schools
financial support could see the schools as answerable to an outside
religious power, the Vatican. Those groups require that the schools
be governed by an independent board of trustees.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Kinsey, assistant to the president at St. Edward's
University in Austin, said the pope's concerns about the drift away
from Catholic connections are well-taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened was that late in the 1960s a lot of lawyers were
giving Catholic schools advice to get arm's length from the
institutional church or they would not be able to get any federal
money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kinsey said most, but not all, presidents of Catholic-related
universities are Catholics. He said some proposals in the draft
document could hinder the schools' efforts to minister to students
of all faiths.
</P>
<P>
   James Patrick, provost of the College of St. Thomas More, a
small liberal arts Catholic college in Fort Worth, says most major
U.S. Catholic universities have been steadily drifting away from
their Catholic identity.
</P>
<P>
   His school, which has about 80 full- and part-time students,
emphasizes its Catholic heritage, and he would like to see larger
Catholic universities that have become more secular do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to restore Catholic education in this country,''
Patrick said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Major Catholic universities in Texas
</P>
<P>
   University of Dallas, Irving, 3,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   Our Lady of the Lake University, San Antonio, 3,689 students.
</P>
<P>
   St. Edward's University, Austin, 3,422 students.
</P>
<P>
   St. Mary's University, San Antonio, 4,100 students.
</P>
<P>
   University of the Incarnate Word, San Antonio, 3,600 students.
</P>
<P>
   University of St. Thomas, Houston, 2,700 students.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
