<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEMINARY-DIPLOMAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEMINARY FILES SUIT OVER DIPLOMA LAW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VERONICA PUENTE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Sunday school teacher Alan Askins was in
search of a better understanding of the Bible when an advertisement
for Tyndale Theological Seminary in a Christian magazine caught his
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Askins said he was drawn to Tyndale's evening classes and low
cost _ ideal for a husband, father of three and investment firm
manager.
</P>
<P>
   More important, though, Askins said, ``It lined up with our
beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   Askins, of Fort Worth, may never see the master of arts level
diploma he has worked toward for four years. State officials
contend that Tyndale is illegally awarding degrees without approval
from the state or one of three accreditation agencies recognized by
the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't have recognition by one of those accrediting
bodies, they have to get approval from us to offer a degree,'' said
Ray Grasshoff, assistant director of media relations for the Texas
Higher Education Coordinating Board.
</P>
<P>
   Seminary President Mal Couch, who founded the school more than a
decade ago, disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can't push the church on the state, the state has no
right to push itself on the church,'' Couch said last week at his
office at 6800 Brentwood Stair Road.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Tyndale has raised constitutional questions about the
state's role in regulating religion and is asking the courts to
decide.
</P>
<P>
   Through its parent company, HEB Ministries Inc., Tyndale has
sued the Coordinating Board and Commissioner Don W. Brown,
contending that the state is violating the Texas and U.S.
constitutions by requiring biblical schools to get state approval
or accreditation before awarding degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Bible Institute in Dallas and Hispanic Bible Institute
in San Antonio have joined as plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   Tyndale sued after the state fined it $173,000 last summer under
a revised law that allows for hefty penalties against unaccredited
institutions granting degrees or using such academic terms as
``seminary.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the Texas Education Code, post-secondary institutions may
not award degrees or credits toward degrees without a ``certificate
of authority'' from the Coordinating Board or accreditation by the
Commission on Colleges, Southern Association of Colleges and
Schools; the American Association of Bible Colleges; or the
Association of Theological Schools in the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 Legislature broadened the law to include seminaries and
schools of law and medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Tyndale became the first institution to be fined
under the revised law, for awarding 34 degrees and using
``seminary'' in its name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our law is designed to be a temporary oversight to protect the
public from fraudulent or substandard degrees while the institution
is working toward accreditation,'' said David Linkletter, associate
director for institutional certification at the Coordinating Board.
</P>
<P>
   Linkletter said the fine does not indicate that Tyndale is
``fraudulent or substandard.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, both parties appeared in court in Austin before state
District Judge Paul Davis to argue for a pretrial ruling on the
legal issues of the case. Davis is expected to rule within a few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth attorney Shelby Sharpe, who is representing Tyndale,
argued that the state is violating the institutions' freedoms of
speech, press and religion.
</P>
<P>
   The state said the regulations ``are aimed at ensuring a
baseline consistency among all institutions offering academic
degrees in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Flowers, chairman of the religion department at Texas
Christian University, said that the dispute raises constitutional
questions, but that it's not clear-cut. Flowers is also president
of the North Texas chapter of Americans United for Separation of
Church and State.
</P>
<P>
   To be accredited or certified, institutions may have to spend
more on a library or hire faculty from accredited institutions,
which can mean ``reshaping'' a school, Flowers said.
</P>
<P>
   But protecting the public from fraud is also a public concern,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets down to the definition of fraud,'' he said. ``Is
Tyndale defrauding people by using the word `diploma'? The
Coordinating Board thinks so. It is generally confusing for the
general public. But I'm not sure what we have here is malicious
fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   In almost 11 years, Tyndale has awarded about 600 certificates
and diplomas in studies ranging from missions to biblical
counseling. Students can take extension courses or study on campus
_ a building east of Handley Drive that houses six classrooms, a
small library, a modest bookstore and Seminary Fellowship Bible
Church.
</P>
<P>
   Couch said Tyndale has never sought accreditation from a
state-recognized agency because seminary leaders believe they
should not be required to obtain permission or direction on how to
teach religion courses. Tyndale is accredited through the
Association of Christian Colleges and Theological Schools, which
Couch says does not dictate school policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no problem with medical schools being accredited,''
Couch said. ``But when it comes to religion, that's personal.''
</P>
<P>
   Couch said he hopes the lawsuit will succeed in giving religious
institutions the option to operate without government interference.
</P>
<P>
   Askins, 43, a manager for Fidelity Investments in Dallas, said
he doesn't know whether he'll get credit for his work with a
diploma from Tyndale.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he doesn't, Askins said, he has no regrets about
choosing the seminary, which he credits with teaching him how to
interpret the Bible and how doctrine affects everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really doesn't matter,'' Askins said. ``It comes down to a
spiritual issue.''
</P>
<P>
   With or without a diploma, Askins said, ``at some point, God is
going to take me in the direction that he wants to.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
