<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4567 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-PLANETARY-SYSTEMS     04-19 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PLANETARY-SYSTEMS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DISCOVERY PROVIDES GRIST FOR PLANETARY COMPARISONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Texas, Mass.)  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A major discovery announced last week has given birth to a new
field of science, the comparative study of planetary systems.
</P>
<P>
   At last, after centuries of speculation, often more fanciful
than scientific, and recent years of expectant searching,
astronomers have found a family of planets to compare the solar
system with. They detected three large planets _ two of them with
masses much greater than Jupiter's _ orbiting another solar-type
star, Upsilon Andromedae, 44 light-years away.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists confidently predict that this will be the first of
many similar discoveries. Dr. Geoffrey Marcy of San Francisco State
University, leader of one of the discovery teams, has his eye on
another star, 55 Cancri, where there is mounting evidence of
multiple planetary companions. Observers are tracking other nearby
stars for planetary systems but are cautiously refraining from
making any claims.
</P>
<P>
   They are further encouraged by other discoveries over the last
four years. Examining the telltale motions of almost 20 other
stars, astronomers have inferred the presence of at least one
Jupiter-class planet close to each of them, exerting slight
gravitational disturbances. Smaller or more distant planets may
also accompany these stars, but their detection would require more
prolonged observations and may be beyond current technology.
</P>
<P>
   If there were astronomers with comparable technology in the
Upsilon Andromedae system, they would be unable to detect any of
the Sun's planets, not even mighty Jupiter, because they lack
sufficient mass or are too distant from the Sun. So it is possible,
scientists said, that observers have yet to take the full measure
and census of the Upsilon Andromedae system or others nearby in the
Milky Way galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   Spacecraft being planned for flight in the next couple of
decades are expected to find many more planetary systems, including
any Earth-size objects that might harbor some forms of life.
</P>
<P>
   The Terrestrial Planet Finder, a mission planned by 2010, should
be able to detect and photograph the full retinue of planets around
other stars. Its instruments will also be designed to determine the
constituents of atmospheres, which could reveal signs that the
planets may be habitable.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 years later, a spacecraft called Life Finder, which is
being planned by the Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena, Calif.,
would carry remote-sensing instruments for a more detailed study of
planet atmospheres. The presence of methane and ozone together, for
example, would be a sure sign of some kind of life on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretical astrophysicists have already seen enough, though, to
suspect that the sun and its family may not be a typical planetary
system. They have been surprised to find so many examples, at
Upsilon Andromedae and also among the solitary planet detections
around other stars, of Jupiter-class objects existing much closer
to their stars than Jupiter is to the sun. And none of the current
theories predicted what they discovered at Upsilon Andromedae: that
three such giant worlds could form and survive around a single
star.
</P>
<P>
   ``True giant planets are not that easy to form,'' said Dr.
Douglas Lin, a theorist at the University of California at Santa
Cruz. ``Finding three around one star, and extremely close to it,
is quite significant and puts more constraints, limits, on any
theory of planetary formation and evolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Alan Boss, a theoretical planetary scientist at the Carnegie
Institution of Washington, noted that 10 times more mass is locked
up in the three Upsilon Andromedae giants than in all the planets
of the solar system. The innermost of these has a mass
three-quarters that of Jupiter, and the middle one a mass at least
twice Jupiter's. The outermost, at more than four times Jupiter's
mass, is not much farther from its star than Mars is from the sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried that our conventional ways of explaining giant
planets is inadequate,'' Boss said.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing that has not astonished astronomers is the
discovery itself of another planetary system. As early as the
classical Greeks, philosophers have contemplated the possibility of
other worlds. In the 17th century, writers began entertaining ideas
about ``a plenitude of worlds.'' In recent decades, scientists had
said the laws of probability favored the existence of other
planetary systems.
</P>
<P>
   Because the sun is a common and ordinary star, scientists
reasoned, groups of planets probably formed around some other stars
like it. Because there are 200 billion stars in the Milky Way
alone, planetary systems are probably abundant, in many cases a
natural result of the process of star formation. Recent
observations by the Hubble Space Telescope of disks of dust around
many young stars, which appeared to be an early stage of planetary
formation, supported this line of reasoning, astronomers said.
</P>
<P>
   The first breakthrough, in 1992, was both encouraging and
disappointing. Radio astronomers detected two or three planets
orbiting a stellar object, but it was not a normal star. It was a
pulsar, the spinning relic of an exploded star.
</P>
<P>
   Though the discovery gave astronomers hope, as the first
evidence of planets beyond the solar system, this was nothing like
the solar system, nothing to encourage speculation about
extraterrestrial life. No one could conceive of the conditions for
life, if they existed, surviving the cataclysm of a stellar
explosion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The first detection of a planet around a normal shining star, 51
Pegasi, was made in 1995 by Dr. Michel Mayor of the Geneva
Observatory in Switzerland, and was soon confirmed by Marcy.
</P>
<P>
   This and subsequent solitary planet discoveries prepared
astronomers for the possibility that the first multiple-planet
system they observed would differ considerably from the solar
system. Most of the planets discovered were larger than Jupiter.
The ones traveling circular orbits, like solar planets, hugged
close to the searing heat of the star, closer than Mercury comes to
the sun. The others follow eccentric, oval-shaped orbits, unlike
solar planets, but they remain at distances from their stars
corresponding roughly to those of Venus and Earth from the sun.
</P>
<P>
   The problem has become even more complex for theorists now that
they have encountered three such huge planets in one system, one
planet in a close circular orbit and two in elliptical orbits. It
had been generally assumed that such large bodies, presumably gas
spheres like Jupiter, could have coalesced only in the cold regions
far from their star.
</P>
<P>
   In an article prepared for publication later this year, Marcy,
Mayor and Dr. William Cochran of the University of Texas at Austin
wrote, ``This `pile-up' of planets near stars suggests that inward
orbital migration occurred after formation,'' probably through
gravitational interactions with other planets that, in reaction,
were nudged outward into distant orbits where they are not yet
detectable.
</P>
<P>
   The astronomers also concluded that the eccentric orbits ``arise
from gravitational interactions with other planets, stars, or the
protoplanetary disk'' in their early history.
</P>
<P>
   In the nascent field of comparative planetary systems, the new
discovery has already given scientists a few insights. They are
more certain than ever that planetary systems are ubiquitous. They
think they are observing what is probably close to the upper mass
limitations for planets. And they feel sure that what they are
detecting are, indeed, planets.
</P>
<P>
   A few scientists had argued that many of the discoveries over
the last four years might not be planets but some new class of
astronomical bodies or possibly substellar objects known as brown
dwarfs. These are stars that failed to attain sufficient mass to
ignite the thermonuclear fusion that makes stars shine. Dr. Robert
Noyes of the Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics in
Cambridge, Mass., leader of the other team that independently made
the new discovery, said the configuration of the three Upsilon
Andromedae objects should quiet those critics.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers said they could not rule out a habitable planet or
moon in the Upsilon Andromedae system. But the unsettling
gravitational forces from such large planets in close proximity
could have cleared the neighborhood of smaller bodies.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, Earth-size bodies will probably fall below the
detection limits of today's telescopes for many years. Astronomers
will probably find several more systems similar to Upsilon
Andromedae's before they find something with some of the familiar
hallmarks of the solar system. The next major milestone, they said,
would be finding a planet about the size of Jupiter at about the
same distance from another star as Jupiter is from the sun.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few years, the Hubble Space Telescope will try to
examine nearby stars for the slightest flickering change in their
light. These could reveal the transit of a Jupiter-size planet at
Jupiter distances across the face of the star. The French space
mission Corot, to be launched in 2001, will in this way monitor the
light of 25,000 stars in search of extra-solar planets.
</P>
<P>
   The American Space Interferometry Mission, planned for launching
in 2005, will use an array of telescopes to look for smaller
extra-solar planets, possibly as small as Saturn or Neptune. It
will probably be less than 10 years before the Terrestrial Planet
Finder begins looking for Earthlike planets, and 20 before the Life
Finder spacecraft begins its work. That could usher in another new
field of science, comparative planetary biology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
