<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4572 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-LYMPH-NODES-ART-N     04-19 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-LYMPH-NODES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROCEDURE HELPS DETECT CANCERS OF BREAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Fla., Calif.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By HOLCOMB B. NOBLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new procedure for testing the lymph nodes of women with
early-stage breast cancer is so promising and is gaining in
popularity so rapidly that leaders in the field are concerned that
some surgeons may try it without being properly trained. And any
errors that result can be fatal.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure, sentinel-node biopsy, has been developed to
determine whether the cancer has spread to a few lymph nodes under
the arm near the breast.
</P>
<P>
   These few, called sentinel nodes, are the first ones to which a
tumor will drain and have been found to be accurate in gauging
whether cancer has spread to the entire lymph-node system of some
20 to 30 nodes.
</P>
<P>
   If the sentinel nodes are free of cancer, the disease has not
spread to the rest and no more nodes are removed. If a sentinel
node is cancerous, however, more nodes must be removed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, surgery to remove the entire system of pea-size lymph nodes
remains the standard at most institutions.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 100,000 women a year undergo the operation and as a
result risk developing lymphedema, a debilitating and long-term
swelling of the arm. Use of the new procedure could avoid that risk
for 80,000 of them.
</P>
<P>
   The sentinel-node biopsy is attracting wide attention at medical
meetings among doctors interested in performing it. Dr. Peter I.
Pressman, a cancer surgeon and professor of surgical oncology at
Albert Einstein College of Medicine in the Bronx, N.Y., said
patients should carefully question their own doctors to determine
what training they have had in the procedure and how many they have
done.
</P>
<P>
   His and other warnings come as a new study is being reported in
the current issue of Annals of Surgery by researchers at Memorial
Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in New York on their finding that two
types of material _ a blue dye and a radioactive isotope _ used in
combination with the sentinel-node procedure markedly improved its
accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Patrick Borgen, chief of breast service at
Sloan-Kettering and one of the authors of the report, also
emphasized how important it was that the teams of surgeons and
radiologists who plan to do the procedure receive thorough
training.
</P>
<P>
   If the biopsy misses cancer in the sentinel nodes, the disease
can spread irreversibly, as several oncologists point out, and
result in the death of the patient.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure, as done at Sloan-Kettering, involves injecting
both the blue dye and the isotopes into breast tissue around the
tumor.
</P>
<P>
   A small incision is made in the arm minutes later. Surgeons and
radiologists then look for traces of the dye or radioactivity that
will be present if the cancer has spread, in fluid that travels to
the sentinel nodes.
</P>
<P>
   The team needs to be trained in, among other things, the use of
a gamma counter to recognize the radioactivity traces.
</P>
<P>
   The American College of Surgeons and other institutions are
giving courses for surgeons and radiologists on the biopsy, and it
is being introduced in medical schools. Edward M. Copeland III,
chairman of the department of surgery at the University of Florida
Shands Hospital at Gainesville, said that doctors needed training
not only in nuclear medicine, but they also needed detailed
instruction and close supervision on detecting the blue dye.
</P>
<P>
   The sentinel-node biopsy was developed in research reported in
1997 by Dr. Armando E. Giuliano of the John Wayne Center Institute
in Santa Monica, Calif., who initially used the blue dye. The basic
procedure, Borgen said, holds the promise, if long-term results
hold up, of being the most important advance in breast surgery
since the development of breast reconstruction as a replacement for
a mastectomy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
