<HEADER>
A4573 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-SECRETARIES-2TA     04-19 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-SECRETARIES-2TAKES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATING SECRETARIES' CELLULOID LEGACY  
 (FOR RELEASE WEDNESDAY, APRIL 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUE ADOLPHSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ April 19-23 is Professional Secretaries Week, a
good idea that probably should be retitled and filed under A for
administrative assistant.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever you call them, secretaries are the unsung heroes of
the office world, professionals who do indispensable work, often
know more about the business than the boss and yet rarely get the
respect they deserve _ especially from Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Since the early days of filmmaking, there have been movies
featuring secretaries as central characters. In the 1930s and '40s,
most of the plots were near carbon copies, involving a secretary
whose primary goal was to type a ``Mrs.'' in front of her name.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things those early films did was reinforce the
stereotype that all secretaries were women,'' says Virginia
Solomon, a film buff who is also president of San Francisco's
Golden Gate Chapter of the International Association of
Administrative Professionals (formerly Professional Secretaries
International).
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, in the early part of the century, a lot were men,''
Solomon says. ``It wasn't until the movies came along that the
stereotype came out. Make the secretary a woman and, not only that,
a beautiful one. So the secretary became a sex object.''
</P>
<P>
   In later films, getting the job done (``Paris When It Sizzles'')
or getting ahead (``Working Girl'') became the more important
focus. But there was still romance involved _ it is Hollywood,
after all _ and the image still wasn't quite right.
</P>
<P>
   ``In `Working Girl,' for example, they showed being a secretary
as being blue collar,'' Solomon says. ``I won't say I was offended,
but it was sort of a turnoff to me. They had (Melanie Griffith) in
garish makeup and clothes _ another stereotype. Most secretaries I
know don't dress like that. They don't get hired if they look like
they just walked in from the mall.''
</P>
<P>
   While Solomon can enjoy most of these films for what they are _
entertainment _ she is partial to films that show secretaries
actually doing the work, not just going after the guy, such as in
``9 to 5.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was a pretty good one,'' she says. ``It was done
for comedy and there were lots of stereotypes, but the Lily Tomlin
character was right on the money. She was hardworking and
underappreciated. Lily is the best (depiction of a secretary) _
running the office from the sidelines, but (set ital) running (end
ital) the office.''
</P>
<P>
   Following is a selection of movies about secretaries, listed by
release date, that are available on video. You may have to do a
little digging to find the older ones, but they're out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Business Girl'' (1931) _ A very young Loretta Young plays
Claire ``Mac'' MacIntyre, who goes to work for an amorous ad man
(Ricardo Cortez) to earn money while her true love Johnny (Frank
Albertson) tries to make it as a musician in Europe. Interested
more in her legs than her typing skills, the boss helps her move up
in the company while pursuing her romantically. Misunderstandings
abound when Johnny returns. There's plenty of sexist dialogue, but
also some sexy scenes between Young and Albertson in this film,
which came out before the Hays Code imposed decency regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Red-Headed Woman'' (1932) _ You know she's trouble from the
opening scene in a dress shop when Jean Harlow asks a sales clerk,
``Can you see through this?'' The clerk says yes, and Harlow
replies, ``I'll wear it.'' In this Anita Loos story, Harlow is a
ruthless secretary who will stop at nothing to climb the social
ladder, including getting her boss (Chester Morris) to divorce his
loving wife and marry her, then cheating on him with men who might
improve her status further. Another pre-Code film with some lusty
dialogue and skin shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wife vs. Secretary'' (1936) _ This one's worth it just for the
stars. Clark Gable is magazine editor Van Stanhope, who is happily
married to Linda (Myna Loy) and happy with his super-efficient
secretary Whitey (Harlow again, as the polar opposite of her
``Red-Headed Woman'' character). Linda isn't at all jealous of the
beautiful Whitey, and has no reason to be, until the power of her
mother-in-law's suggestion overtakes her. Look for newcomer James
Stewart as Harlow's boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (MORE) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  ``Paris _ When It Sizzles'' (1964) _ William Holden is
Richard Benson, a procrastinating writer with a fondness for drink,
a script assignment and a fast-approaching deadline, who hires
secretary Gabrielle Simpson (Audrey Hepburn) to get it all down on
paper in his Paris apartment. As the plot unfolds, backtracks,
twists one way and then veers in another, Holden takes Hepburn on a
frantic ride through the City of Light for inspiration, falling for
her along the way. This comedy didn't get raves, and it probably
won't have you laughing out loud, but fans of Holden and the
always-lovely Hepburn will find it pleasant entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``9 to 5'' (1980) _ Secretaries Doralee (Dolly Parton), Violet
(Lily Tomlin) and Judy (Jane Fonda) all work for the despicable and
heartless Franklin Hart (a deliciously wicked Dabney Coleman).
Bonding in their suffering, the women share a marijuana cigarette
and describe their fantasies about doing in the boss _ a scene in
itself worth the price of a rental. When an opportunity for real
revenge presents itself, the three trio &LR;   &LR; literally hold Hart
prisoner in order to improve conditions at the office. Good therapy
for oppressed office workers everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Working Girl'' (1988) _ In this Mike Nichols comedy, Melanie
Griffith plays Tess McGill, a smart young woman from the wrong side
of the tracks with too much hair and an extensive lingerie
collection. She gets a secretarial job at a high-profile Wall
Street firm and does her best to learn from her hard-edged boss
Catherine (Sigourney Weaver). But when Catherine is laid up out of
town after a skiing accident, and Tess finds out her boss has been
stealing her ideas, she hatches a scheme to close a big deal on her
own, passing herself off as an executive at the firm and even
completing a successful merger with Catherine's boyfriend Jack
(Harrison Ford) in the process.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
