<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4577 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     04-19 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 25)  
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE ARCHIVIST &LR;  By Martha Cooley. Back Bay/Little, Brown, $13. A
widowed archivist at a university library becomes friends with an
intense graduate student whose questions force him to confront the
painful memory of his wife and her suicidal obsession with the
Holocaust. In 1998 the reviewer Brian Morton called this ``a
thoughtful and well-written first novel, suffused with intellectual
and moral integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GUNS, GERMS, AND STEEL: THE FATES OF HUMAN SOCIETIES &LR;  By Jared
Diamond. Norton, $14.95. Why did Europeans and Asians always
succeed in their conquests of other civilizations, instead of the
other way around? A physiology professor, delving into many
disciplines to answer that provocative question, chalks it up less
to technological or political superiority than to an accidental
head start in agriculture and the devastating export of Old World
diseases. In 1997 in The New York Times Book Review, James Shreeve
called this Pulitzer Prize-winning history ``an ambitious, highly
important book.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SEEING LIKE A STATE: HOW CERTAIN SCHEMES TO IMPROVE THE HUMAN
CONDITION HAVE FAILED &LR;  By James C. Scott. Yale University, $15.95.
This book seeks to explain why so many grandiose experiments in
social engineering in the 20th century _ from Mao's Great Leap
Forward to the construction of Brasilia _ have ended up as
disasters. The result is ``one of the most profound and
illuminating studies of this century ... in recent decades,'' John
Gray wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JACK MAGGS &LR;  By Peter Carey. Vintage International, $13. In this
crafty novel about a convict who illegally returns from Australia
to 19th-century London, the characters are shadows of real and
imaginary people in the life and work of Dickens. ``Carey creates a
rousing old-fashioned narrative, and brings to it a distinctly
modern, unromantic sensibility,'' Caryn James wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HENRY MITCHELL ON GARDENING &LR;  Mariner/Houghton Mifflin, $13. The
author, whose celebrated gardening columns appeared in The
Washington Post for more than 20 years until his death in 1993,
never strayed far from his small backyard garden in Washington. In
this collection, ``he alludes to this garden in a remarkable
variety of tones,'' Verlyn Klinkenborg wrote in 1998. ``It's always
tempting to quote Mitchell, but once you start it's hard to know
where to stop. He is the gardener for all of us who know better but
do worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher has reissued Mitchell's two earlier
collections of newspaper essays. Reviewing  &UR; ONE MAN'S GARDEN &LR;  ($14)
in The New York Times Book Review in 1992, Anne Raver said: ``Every
page is filled with his irascible, wholly unpretentious voice. ...
Mitchell never tries to be funny or erudite. He just is.''  &UR; THE
ESSENTIAL EARTHMAN &LR;  ($14) ``may be the most soul-satisfying
gardening book in years,'' Neal Johnston wrote in 1982. ``One
gathers that the garden Mitchell has worked on for years is a
rather wild, jungly affair with a startling variety of arresting
and much worked-over specimens turning up in odd places. ... His
book is much the same.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DEAR MR. JEFFERSON: LETTERS FROM A NANTUCKET GARDENER &LR;  By Laura
Simon. Delta, $11.95. A novelist employs a series of letters to
Thomas Jefferson (an enthusiastic vegetable gardener) to explore
American garden history while writing about her own patch. The
result is ``an avid testament by a confirmed yet highly
knowledgeable amateur,'' Michael Pollan wrote last year. ``The
historical passages are swift, sure-footed and fascinating.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; I KNOW THIS MUCH IS TRUE &LR;  By Wally Lamb. Regan Books/Harper
Perennial, $16. Everyone is bereft in this novel, especially the
protagonist, who despite the loss of his mother, wife, baby
daughter and career must somehow rouse himself to care for his
schizophrenic twin brother. ```I Know This Much Is True' ... never
grapples with anything less than life's biggest questions,'' Karen
Karbo wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE PRIEST FAINTED &LR;  By Catherine Temma Davidson. John
Macrae/Owl/Holt, $13. In this first novel, a young American travels
to Greece to investigate her heritage, linking her adventures to
those of the denizens of Mount Olympus. ``Davidson has created an
admirable, appealing heroine, a kind of female Odysseus who must
survive the dangers and beauties of a foreign place that happens to
be her ancestral homeland,'' Lisa Shea wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AMAZING GRACE: A VOCABULARY OF FAITH &LR;  By Kathleen Norris.
Riverhead, $12.95. Returning to the Christian church after 20
years, the author seeks to give weight and meaning to the ``scary''
words and phrases that once clouded her faith. ``She is an ideal
escort along the semantically bumpy road to her conversion,''
Michael Milburn wrote in 1998. The book's ``strength lies in its
depiction of a fallible woman engaged in spiritual inquiry.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ROCK 'N' ROLL BABES FROM OUTER SPACE &LR;  By Linda Jaivin.
Broadway, $13. What happens when three green-skinned female aliens
set down their spaceship in Sydney, Australia, and take up with a
slacker in pursuit of good times and a rock career? ``There's
plenty of gender bending, drug gobbling and rude high jinks when
the Babes and their human comrade do the town,'' Sally Eckhoff
wrote in 1998. ``Jaivin's Tom Robbinsish sex writing gives the
story ... gratifyingly sweaty palms.''
</P>
</TEXT>
