<HEADER>
A4589 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITNEYBIENNIAL-TEX     04-19 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITNEYBIENNIAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITNEY BIENNIAL INVITES OUTSIDE CURATORS _ AND CRITICISM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the nation's most infamous high-profle exhibition of
contemporary art presented regularly.
</P>
<P>
   And, even though the next Whitney Biennial doesn't open until
2000, it's already a hot topic. That's because the artists for the
2000 Whitney Biennial Exhibition will be chosen by six curators
from outside New York City _ including Michael Auping, chief
curator for the Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The unprecedented decision to go with a committee of outsiders
breaks the single thread _ a staff curator _ that has connected the
museum's survey shows since they were inaugurated by Gertrude
Vanderbilt Whitney in 1932. Whitney had founded the institution as
a venue for contemporary American art, and its surveys long have
provided a refreshing counterpoint to its other, more narrowly
focused exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney Director Maxwell Anderson's idea to choose outside
curators has generated hopeful anticipation among regional artists
_ and perhaps a certain amount of anxiety in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   New York Times art critic Roberta Smith no doubt expressed the
sentiments of many Manhattanites, who consider the Whitney their
hometown museum, when she recently fretted: ``Is it really a
Whitney Biennial if it is farmed out?''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. Maybe not. One thing is certain: The names may belong to
out-of-towners, but the show will be consistent with recent
Biennials. It will feature piles of surburban detritus and a
selection of easel paintings, video installations and drawings, big
bombastic photographs, and at least one work suspended from the
ceiling. Some of the art will be about art, some about
self-expression and some about contemporary cultural issues.
</P>
<P>
   That's because artists from the hinterlands are so well-tuned to
New York-centric trends that ``regionalism'' becomes a moot point.
Nor are members of the curatorial team walking around with straw
between their teeth. To wit:
</P>
<P>
   _Auping is a well-traveled veteran on the contemporary-art
scene. His curatorial projects range from ``Tatsuo Miyajima: Big
Time'' to ``Clyfford Still,'' and to serving as curator of the
American Pavilion of the 1990 Venice Biennale.
</P>
<P>
   _Valerie Cassel, director of the Visiting Artists Program for
the School of the Art Institute of Chicago, has demonstrated her
awareness of contemporary topics through exhibitions and symposiums
on black sexuality, lesbian identity and art activism.
</P>
<P>
   _Hugh Davies, director of the Museum of Contemporary Art in San
Diego, has organized exhibitions that include ``Francis Bacon: The
Papal Portraits of 1953'' and ``Blurring the Boundaries: 25 Years
of Installation Art.''
</P>
<P>
   _Jane Farver is director-designate of the List Visual Arts
Center at MIT. She has held posts at two important New York
exhibition spaces and curated such exhibitions as ``Adrian Piper:
Reflections'' and ``Out of India: Contemporary Art of the South
Asian Diaspora.''
</P>
<P>
   _Independent curator Andrea Miller-Keller is former curator of
contemporary art at the Wadsworth Atheneum in Hartford, Conn. She
has organized shows for Daniel Buren, Sherrie Levine, Lorna Simpson
and Richard Tuttle, among others. She also was the U.S.
commissioner for the 23rd Sao Paolo Bienal.
</P>
<P>
   _Larry Rinder is director of the CCAC Institute at the
California College of Arts and Crafts in Oakland and San Francisco.
He served as adviser to the 1991 and 1993 Whitney Biennials.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the fact we all reside in different parts of the country
can't help but affect ``who'' will be in the Biennial,'' says
Auping, who met with his colleagues for the first time in early
April.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be looking at aesthetics, but also at content, at what
is most pertinent to this moment in time,'' Auping adds.
</P>
<P>
   Curators aren't confined to representing their respective
regions, Rinder says. And _ even if 2000 goes down as the Year of
the Faux Biennial _ participating artists likely won't care:
They'll still receive once-in-a-lifetime exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Biennials attract thousands of art-wise visitors and much press
analysis. Exposure may lead to New York representation or national
recognition. Being in a Biennial boosts an artist's reputation back
home _ which can lead to more regional shows and sales. At the very
least, the artist gains a psychological edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a validation,'' says Talley Dunn, director of Gerald
Peters Gallery in Dallas, who represents several Biennial alumni.
``It makes you part of a national conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not the nation's only survey of contemporary art _ there's
the Corcoran Biennial, the Carnegie International and Site Santa Fe
_ but ``nothing like it creates a similar buzz,'' Dunn says.
``Normally, nobody but artists and other curators question who gets
included in an exhibition. But, with the Whitney, everyone
questions the whole thing. It makes you think.''
</P>
<P>
   The Whitney's surveys haven't always been so notorious, however.
The museum reached out to a popular audience under Thomas
Armstrong, director from 1974 to 1990. Then, under David Ross'
tenure (from 1991 to '98), the Whitney apparently turned to baiting
the bourgeoisie: Ross oversaw thematic shows investigating sexual
identity, suburban corruption, racism and social class.
</P>
<P>
   For that, and because New York remains the nation's art capital,
the Whitney receives attention organizers of other art surveys only
dream of, Corcoran Biennial curator Terri Sultan says. Presented by
the Corcoran Gallery of Art in Washington, D.C., that survey was
inaugurated in 1907 and focuses exclusively on painting.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, though, the Whitney Biennial's reputation
often overshadows its substance, Sultan says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to sound like a Pollyanna, but I think museum
curators are responsible people who try to bridge the gap between
artists and the people out there in the world,'' Sultan says. ``And
if a biennial is a way to get people into the museum to have a
conversation about art _ and possibly even have a life-changing
experience _ it has value even if the show is a failure.''
</P>
<P>
   (Janet Tyson is art critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. You
can call her at (817) 390-7679, or e-mail:
vizart(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
