<HEADLINE>
PATAKIS PAY $70,000 IN TAXES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES M. ODATO  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki's family earnings slid in
1998, but he's getting a boost from his wife's marketing work with
businesses run by family friends.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth ``Libby'' Pataki earns $80,000 per year as a part-time
employee of Ron Lauder, of the Estee Lauder cosmetic fortune, and
she has a new part-time consulting job, according to income tax
documents made public by New York's first couple.
</P>
<P>
   The documents showed the Patakis earned $246,417 in gross income
in 1998, $95,000 from Libby Pataki's two marketing jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady received $15,000 for a job she started in
November as a consultant for Premier Heart, a Portland, Ore.,
start-up developing a heart disease diagnostic service.
</P>
<P>
   Her job is to write and deliver speeches in a campaign to alert
people to the risks of heart disease, her new employer, an old
family pal, said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hayden, the chief executive of Premier Heart, said he
thought Libby Pataki is worth $7,500 per month because ``she's very
good.'' Hayden graduated in 1967 from Yale University with the
governor and attended Columbia University Law school with Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   He said Pataki's daughter is his daughter's roommate now at
Yale.
</P>
<P>
   Libby Pataki, he said, will be ``developing a campaign to raise
the awareness of women of the dangers of heart disease. It's a
campaign of speeches to women's groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Premier, a six-month-old company with eight employees, is based
in Portland. But it has a presence in New York state and in Ocean
Ridge, Fla., Hayden said.
</P>
<P>
   The company will be marketing a diagnostic service that
physicians will use on patients. ``We will be selling the test, the
service ... $400 per test,'' Hayden said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not committing herself full-time to us,'' Hayden said.
</P>
<P>
   If she maintains her job as a marketing consultant to companies
operated by Ron Lauder, for which she received $80,000 over 12
months of last year, and keeps working at the current rate with
Premier Heart, as Hayden expects she will, Libby Pataki will make
almost as much as the governor's new salary of $179,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki tax forms, released Friday, showed that the family
returns indicated real estate losses last year of almost $61,000,
mostly from buying high and selling low on his Saratoga Lake
condominium. Pataki also reported a loss of almost $8,700 from a
farm he owns in Washington County.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican governor, who collected his $130,290 state salary
plus $74,460 in speaking and book sales receipts, and his wife had
$246,417 in gross earnings last year.
</P>
<P>
   The total income fell from $337,455 in 1997 and $267,483 in
1996, largely because Pataki cut back on speaking appearances and
didn't have the capital gains from real estate sales.
</P>
<P>
   The couple, who live in Garrison, N.Y., paid taxes of $69,805,
or 30.5 percent, on adjusted gross income of $228,417.
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki's overpaid their taxes by $9,766 to the Internal
Revenue Service and $6,003 to the state.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First-term Democratic Attorney General Eliot Spitzer reported
that he and his wife, Silda Wall, accumulated $472,784 in earnings
last year, most of which came from Spitzer's work with his father,
real estate magnate Bernard Spitzer. The attorney general also took
in $171,973 in profits from renting his 200 Central Park South
building.
</P>
<P>
   Their tax burden, at $199,388, represents 42 percent of their
taxable income.
</P>
<P>
   The tax payments include $140,289 to the IRS. The couple had to
write a $60,489 check for underpaying taxes, including the $2,292
penalty for underpaying.
</P>
<P>
   State taxes amounted to $50,299. Again, the couple underpaid and
had to send $13,270 more, including penalties, to New York's tax
agency.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general reported a $730,508 sale of his share of a
limited investment partnership, Cramer Partners LP, to help him pay
for his 1998 campaign against Republican Dennis Vacco.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Comptroller H. Carl McCall and his wife, Fashion
Institute of Technology President Joyce Brown, reported a combined
1998 income of $365,652, a McCall spokesman said. The couple paid
$122,703 in income taxes and gave $6,475 to charity.
</P>
</TEXT>
