<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXPLAINER-DAMS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT DAM-BREACHING COULD COST FARMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB TAYLOR  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To understand the impact of shipping costs on a wheat farmer,
consider a typical 2,500-acre dry-land wheat farm operated by two
generations of the same family.
</P>
<P>
   Producing about 100,000 bushels of wheat a year, the farm could
sell its crop for about $290,000 at recent price levels. After
expenses, that nets about $80,000 for a year's work.
</P>
<P>
   That's not much for a farm worked by several people who have
invested hundreds of thousands of dollars in land and machinery.
But raise shipping costs, and the earnings start to evaporate.
</P>
<P>
   Boost rates by a dime per bushel, about the average boost
expected by some economists, and net earnings drop by $10,000. A
35-cent boost, in the range expected by some farmers, would drain
$35,000, or 44 percent of the farm's earnings. If expenses rise or
prices fall, the farm could easily fall into bankruptcy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0274 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4636 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRLINE20-COX     04-19 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    US AIRWAYS TOPS ANNUAL AIRLINE QUALITY RANKING
 &HT;    300&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    Eds: Chart showing overall quality rankings follows story.
 &HT;    By DAVID McNAUGHTON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Delta Air Lines ranks fourth among the 10 major
airlines in quality, trailing US Airways, Continental Airlines and
American Airlines, according to the latest study by Wichita State
University and the University of Nebraska at Omaha.
</P>
<P>
   The annual Airline Quality Rating (cq), released Monday in
Washington,
</P>
<P>
   ranks the biggest carriers in four areas: on-time arrivals,
passenger bumping, mishandled baggage and customer complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, airline quality declined in 1998, according to Dean E.
Headley, an associate professor of marketing at Wichita State
University and coauthor of the report.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's philosophy toward passengers, he said, seems to
be ``get them on the plane, take their money, and don't make them
too mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Headley noted that complaints per 100,000 passengers increased
more than 25 percent last year, following a 20 percent rise in
1997. ``I don't know why, but people don't seem to be happy,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines' increase in customer complaints _ 23.4 percent
_ was slightly below that of the industry. Its ranking among
airlines in number of complaints per 100,000 passengers was
unchanged from 1997, at 3.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based carrier's on-time record improved, to 79.6
percent in 1998 from 74.1 percent a year earlier. The industry's
on-time performance declined, to 77.2 percent from 77.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines also improved in passenger bumpings per 10,000
boardings, which fell 14.4 percent, and in mishandled baggage per
1,000 (cq) passengers, down 5.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The overall 1998 rankings are not comparable to the prior year's
results because of changes in the criteria. Statistics used in the
rankings are from the Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The results of the latest report give ``reasonable cause for
Congress to pass the Airline Passenger Fair Treatment Initiative,
commonly called the Airline Passengers' Bill of Rights,'' the
authors concluded.
</P>
<P>
   That proposal would require that passengers be given more
information about flight delays and other problems, increase
airline liability for lost and damaged luggage, and raise the
penalties for passenger bumping.
</P>
<P>
   But if passengers' rights are spelled out, so should their
responsibilities, Headley said.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers can help make the system work better, he said, by:
</P>
<P>
   _ Cancelling reservations over the phone instead of just not
showing up for a flight.
</P>
<P>
   _ Checking unwieldy baggage instead of carrying it on board.
</P>
<P>
   _ Knowing their rights under current rules.
</P>
<P>
   The major airlines ranked this way in this year's overall
quality rating:
</P>
<P>
   1. US Airways
</P>
<P>
   2. Continental Airlines
</P>
<P>
   3. American Airlines
</P>
<P>
   4. Delta Air Lines
</P>
<P>
   5. Southwest Airlines
</P>
<P>
   6. America West
</P>
<P>
   7. Trans World Airlines
</P>
<P>
   8. Alaska Airlines
</P>
<P>
   9. Northwest Airlines
</P>
<P>
   10. United Airlines
</P>
<P>
   Source: The Airline Quality Rating 1999
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
