<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Magazines covering `Star Wars' in full force
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The next generation of ``Star Wars'' heroes wields
light sabers on the cover of Time ($3.50) heralding the opening of
``Star Wars: Episode 1 _ The Phantom Menace.'' The long-awaited
prequel opens May 19 on 2,500 screens, setting aflutter the hearts
of sci-fi film fans hoping for thrills to equal those from 1977,
and warming the bottom lines of studio executives yearning for a
``Titanic''-sized blockbuster. Along with the usual slice of hype,
Time presents a gatefold guide to the new movie's cast of
characters (including such digitally generated ``actors'' as the
lizardish Jar Jar Binks), plus, strangely enough, a conversation
between PBS savant Bill Moyers and ``Star Wars'' creator George
Lucas on the spiritual side of Lucas' spacy world. Time is printing
75,000 additional copies for an expected boom in newsstand sales,
said Todd Polkes, Time's manager of public affairs. About a
purported battle for an ``exclusive'' on the film coverage,
Newsweek's ($3.50) Roy Brunett points out that his magazine put the
new movie on the cover of its Asian editions in March, and that
numerous other magazines have given the film a front page ride,
including the current Wired. Of Lucasfilms, he notes drily, ``They
are getting their story out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The e-truth will out: Dear Computer User: If you're one of 96
million Americans using e-mail, and you're not worried about what
happens to the flaming messages you've sent to friends and foes,
it's time to worry. We learn in Wired ($6.95) (which also features
coverboy Lucas) that e-mail lives forever, and that the ``delete''
key is no protection. Incriminating e-mail has played a significant
role in the anti-trust lawsuit against Microsoft and in the
investigation of Salt Lake City's Olympic officials. The story
quotes John Jessen, president of Electronic Evidence Discovery, a
Seattle-based company that digs e-dirt out of your computer's past,
who says e-mail is ``one of the most devastating liabilities in
corporate America today. Which is why everyone is so afraid of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rights and liberty: Do sweeping searches of public housing
projects infringe on the rights of residents, if the majority of
the residents approve of the searches? Using the issue as a
jumping-off place, the Boston Review ($3.50) presents a spirited
debate on the concept of rights from a panel of law experts and
professors from universities around the country, including Harvard
law professor Alan Dershowitz, professors Tracey Meares and Dan
Kahan of Chicago Law School and Franklin E. Zimring, director of
the Earl Warren Legal Institute at the University of California at
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mistakes were made: With a cute cover line _ ``Apologize Now!
Everyone's doing it'' _ Civilization ($2.95) paddles in the sea of
``sorries'' inundating the culture. Guest editor Deborah Tannen
(author of ``You Just Don't Understand: Women and Men in
Conversation'') sorts through the mea culpas. Civilization also
hears from ``Love Story'' author Erich Segal, the source of the
line, ``Love means not ever having to say you're sorry,'' to find
out what the heck he meant. ``There may have been a time when I
knew,'' writes Segal, ``but it's significance has long escaped
me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Real raiders of the lost ark: In 1952, a mysterious copper
document was discovered in the same area that produced the Dead Sea
Scrolls, with messages written in a welter of ancient languages
pointing to untold riches. Using global positioning satellite
systems, metal detectors and various translations of the cryptic
copper scrolls, Tucker (Ga.) writer Mike Fillon traveled through
the hills of Qumran this past January, searching for treasure. You
can read of his adventures in the current issue of Popular
Mechanics ($2.95).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Trend alert: Niche marketing gets nicher with Bride Again
($4.99), a new wedding magazine aimed at those who think the second
(or third or fourth) time's the charm.
</P>
<P>
   Bo Emerson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
