r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOAP-OLDSTARS-LADN     04-19 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOAP-OLDSTARS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH AGE COMES RESPECT FOR `GENERAL HOSPITAL' PAIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL BIDWELL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In an industry that considers anybody over 40 a
senior citizen, John Ingle and Anna Lee are an anomaly.
</P>
<P>
   The two, cornerstones of TV's venerable ``General Hospital,''
play characters who, respectively, meddle and mend, coerce and
cajole, scheme and soothe.
</P>
<P>
   Ingle, who plays conniving Edward Quartermaine, patriarch of the
fictional Port Charles, N.Y.'s, first family, is a robust 71. Lee,
who plays Edward's long-suffering, genteel wife, Lila, is a
fragile, but still game 86.
</P>
<P>
   And the two, according to ABC-TV viewer surveys, are fan
favorites in a medium that prizes hot-blooded hunks with flexing
pecs and sassy sirens with big bazooms.
</P>
<P>
   Lila and Edward ``are not just wallpaper,'' said Sallie
Schoneboom, spokeswoman for ABC Daytime. ``They're very important
characters that link other characters together and deserve their
own stories.''
</P>
<P>
   And, after a long, dry spell of providing background for the
rest of the quarreling Quartermaines, they're center stage again.
</P>
<P>
   Lila _ fed up with her duplicitous husband _ is having her
memoirs written in an effort to show the world that the big,
battling Quartermaine family has !ital!something!off! it doesn't
have to be ashamed of. But Edward is scheming to derail the project
_ and ``GH'' is hinting that viewers will learn some shocking
secrets about Lila's life as the story unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had a story for years, so this is wonderful,'' Lee
said, sitting in the wheelchair she's used since hurting her back a
dozen years ago in a fall from a horse, then again in an auto
accident several months later. ``Apparently I've got deep, dark
secrets in my past _ and Edward knows about it. I like that. Lila's
been so sweet, I'd like her to show a little gumption, a little bit
of the other side of her.''
</P>
<P>
   Ingle is equally pleased to have an expanded showcase for his
character.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, of all the `white hairs' in town, I've got the brass
ring,'' Ingle chortled. ``There don't seem to be a lot of older
people with roles in this town.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Lee, who lives in West Los Angeles, has been part of the
``GH'' family since 1978. Trained at the Central School of Speech
Training and Dramatic Art in London, she was a film star in England
in the 1930s before coming to the United States and starring in
dozens more movies, eight of them as director John Ford's favorite
heroine (including in 1941's best picture Oscar winner, ``How Green
Was My Valley'').
</P>
<P>
   In the early days of her career, Lee even did her own stunts,
being shot out of a cannon in one film and diving off a moving
train in another. Appointed an honorary private by Gen. George
Patton during World War II, she spent several months visiting field
hospitals throughout the Mediterranean _ and she still receives fan
mail from soldiers she visited then.
</P>
<P>
   The widow of the late novelist and poet Robert Nathan, Lee
boasts that she's the oldest working actress in TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's wonderful that I get to do what I do,'' Lee said.
``I think a lot of the best actors are the older people because
they've studied their profession. Nowadays, the young people don't
get that training.''
</P>
<P>
   For many years, it was Ingle's job to train up-and-coming
actors. The founder of drama programs both at Hollywood and Beverly
Hills high schools in the 1950s and '60s, his students included
Richard Dreyfuss, Nicolas Cage, Albert Brooks, Barbara Hershey,
Stefanie Powers and David Schwimmer. He also taught drama classes
at Los Angeles City College, UCLA and Occidental College, his own
alma mater, while performing for 10 years in summer stock at
Occidental.
</P>
<P>
   When he was offered early retirement from teaching in 1984, he
jumped at the chance _ then began to consider a late-in-life career
as an actor.
</P>
<P>
   But an agent warned him that roles would be few and far between
for an actor who, professionally, was a 56-year-old beginner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `You know, it's a young market,''' Ingle recalled.
``I said, ``Yes, but this young market has mothers and fathers and
teachers and doctors and priests who support them. There have to be
roles out there for people my age, too.''
</P>
<P>
   He was right. It didn't take him long to land roles on
``Dallas,'' ``Doogie Howser, M.D.'' and ``Cheers,'' as well as a
succession of movies _ usually as a judge, police commissioner or
other authority figure _ including ``RoboCop 2,'' ``Batman and
Robin'' and ``Death Becomes Her.'' He provided the voice for the
animated ``The Land Before Time II.'' He also got big, red smooches
from supermodel Cindy Crawford in two Revlon lipstick commercials.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1993 that Ingle, a Pasadena resident married for 44
years and the father of five daughters, joined ``GH,'' replacing
the original Edward Quartermaine, actor David Lewis, who was ill
and ready to retire.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, many younger members of the soap's cast have sought
out the former drama teacher for advice on how to play a scene or
delve into their character.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're there not in a sit-at-the-feet-of-the-master kind of
thing, but we do rehearse a lot,'' Ingle said. ``The minute we get
to work, we go to my dressing room to work on our scenes. It
matters that acting is fun and that you're not scared to death
because you're unprepared. I will do a scene right or I will not do
it. I hope I can show an example that hard work pays off.''
</P>
<P>
   When you put the two old pros together, fireworks happen on
screen.
</P>
<P>
   Edward blusters and yells and connives, then Lila drops him in
his tracks with a well-timed but ladylike, ``Oh, Edward, shut up!''
before wheeling her chair out of the room. It's a payoff fans of
the show relish.
</P>
<P>
   Off screen, there's great affection between Lee and Ingle, who
gently tease and chide each other almost as if they're the same old
married couple viewers see when the cameras are rolling.
</P>
<P>
   And both say they'll stay part of the ``GH'' family as long as
there are stories for Lila and Edward to tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my brain stops working or, God forbid, my health would
go, I'd quit,'' Ingle said. ``Until then, I'll be around.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll die with Lila Quartermaine's boots on,'' vows Lee.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if she says she will, she will,'' added Ingle. ``You can
count on it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; !end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
