<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-LEVIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEN. LEVIN SAYS NATO'S AIR CAMPAIGN COULD LAST FOR MONTHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., just back from an
inspection trip to Albania and Macedonia, said Monday that
Americans should be prepared for an air war over Yugoslavia that
could last ``many, many weeks or months.''
</P>
<P>
   Levin was among 21 Senate and House lawmakers who traveled to
the Balkan region to get a first-hand look at the conflict in
Yugoslavia. The group also met with North Atlantic Treaty
Organization officials in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strongest impression I have is that this is going to take
awhile,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said some Americans may have gotten the mistaken impression
that the air war, which began March 24, would be over within a
matter of days.
</P>
<P>
   Levin also said public expectations about the effectiveness of
24 U.S. Apache helicopters being sent to Albania are
unrealistically high.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should avoid looking for magic answers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The helicopters, which fly at lower altitudes than NATO jets,
will be used to knock out Serb tanks and other armor.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's bombing campaign against Yugoslavia hasn't interrupted
the Serb assault on ethic Albanians living in Kosovo. Kosovo is
located in the southern portion of Serbia, the dominant republic of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanians have been forced out
of Kosovo by Serb forces and are currently living in refugee camps
in bordering Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Levin said it is premature to consider sending U.S. ground
troops to the region. The Clinton administration has repeatedly
said it has no plans to use ground troops but some lawmakers have
urged the administration to begin planning for such a possibility
in case it becomes necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Levin said NATO officials told him that a discussion of ground
troops is ``distracting'' and would divide the NATO alliance at a
time when it needs to focus on continuing its air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we put ground troops in, there still must be a lengthy
air campaign,'' Levin said, noting that United States and its
allies bombed Iraq for 44 days during the Gulf War before allied
ground troops invaded Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Levin, like most lawmakers, said he supports the $6 billion in
emergency spending the White House formally requested Monday to pay
for the air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the funding request, about $5.1 billion, will be used to
pay for the air campaign through the end of the fiscal year on
Sept. 30. The rest of the money would be used for refugee aid.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Lew, director of the White House's Office of Management and
Budget, said the United States is paying 25 percent of the cost of
helping the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans want to expand the White House's request to
include funds for a military pay raise and other defense items.
</P>
<P>
   ``This emergency funding measure cannot be shortsighted,'' said
House Speaker Dennis Hastert. ``It cannot simply replace bullets
for bullets and bombs for bombs spent in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said the price tag could rise to as high as $18
billion. All of that money would come from this year's anticipated
$110 billion budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Levin said he would support a larger funding bill only if it's
related to the air campaign and providing humanitarian relief in
the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Congress could approve the Kosovo spending bill later this week
or next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
