<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDMAN-PRIZES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDMAN AWARDS HONOR ENVIRONMENTAL ACTIVISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATHERINE SELIGMAN  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A lawyer in Cameroon fighting the destruction of
Central African rain forests and two aboriginal women working to
prevent uranium mining at an Australian site where their ancestors
lived were among seven winners Monday of the Goldman Environmental
Prize.
</P>
<P>
   The $125,000 awards are given annually to grass-roots activists
who surmount obstacles to protect the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stakes are very high. All the activities that are
destroying the environment bring a lot of money to the people doing
it,'' said recipient Samuel Nguiffo, who traveled from Cameroon to
San Francisco for Monday's award ceremony. ``What we are doing is
seen by them as a way to reduce or stop their incomes.
</P>
<P>
   Nguiffo, 33, directs the Center for Environment and Development
in Yaounde, Cameroon's capital. He and his organization have worked
to educate forest dwellers about agriculture that doesn't rely on
cutting down trees.
</P>
<P>
   Nguiffo said he would use part of the prize money to start a
teaching farm where villagers can learn about sustainable
agriculture methods.
</P>
<P>
   Jacqui Katona and Yvonne Margarula hope to preserve the
ancestral land of the Mirrar aborigines in Kakudu _ Australia's
largest national park that also contains Jabiluka, one of the
world's largest uranium deposits.
</P>
<P>
   Mining is prohibited in the park, but mining has been approved
in Jabiluka. Opponents say the activity will release material that
will remain radioactive for some 300,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   The national park contains 196 aboriginal art sites and has been
designated as a World Heritage site for its cultural and natural
significance.
</P>
<P>
   Katona and Margarula have mounted protests against the mining,
including a massive on-site act of civil disobedience that drew
5,000 people over a several month period.
</P>
<P>
   Katona, 33, was one of those arrested, serving 10 days in jail
last year. She and Margarula, 41, hope to convince the World
Heritage Committee to designate the park as endangered to stop the
mining.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be an extreme embarrassment for the government,''
Katona said. ``Morally the case has already been argued
successfully, but the government is prepared to be recalcitrant.''
</P>
<P>
   Katona traces her activism to her family's heritage as Mirrar
people. She said her mother was removed from her family as a child
and raised in an institution. Later she was told her family had
died. Katona moved to Jabiluka about 10 years ago, where, she said,
illiteracy and poverty are widespread.
</P>
<P>
   Katona is executive director of the Gundjehmi Aboriginal
Corporation, a Mirrar-run nonprofit organization. Margarula is
chairwoman of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   The prizes were created in 1990 by philanthropists Richard N.
Goldman and the late Rhoda Goldman, the great-grand-niece of Levi
Strauss, to honor the world's outstanding environmental heroes.
</P>
<P>
   This year's winners were selected from nominations anonymously
submitted by a network of 21 environmental groups around the world
and a panel representing nearly 50 nations. The other winners
include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Ka Hsaw Wa, from the Karen ethnic minority in Burma, who has
endured torture and risked death to oppose environmental and human
rights policies of the military government. He documented forced
labor, execution, rape and confiscation of property carried out by
the military in support of a pipeline project by an international
consortium.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bernard Martin of Canada, a fourth-generation fisherman who
advocated reduced fishing quotas after seeing that factory trawlers
were decimating once-abundant species in the Grand Banks cod
fishery. He has traveled around the world with an organization he
co-founded educating the public about the perils of over-fishing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jorge Varela, a Honduran who promoted a model of shrimping
that respects fragile resources in the Gulf of Fornseca, where
commercial shrimp farms have led to clearing of coastal mangrove
forests, poisoning of estuaries and the loss of common fishing
grounds. Varela is a co-founder of an organization that has secured
two consecutive moratoriums on the expansion of shrimp farming.
</P>
<P>
   _ Michal Kravcik of Slovakia, a hydrologist who succeeded in
gathering support to stop an environmentally destructive dam that
had been planned during the Communist era.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
