<HEADER>
A4669 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CARDIAC-DEATH-NYT     04-19 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CARDIAC-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCH LINKS SUDDEN CARDIAC DEATH TO HEREDITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(lb) 
 By NANCY BETH JACKSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   French scientists say they have documented that sudden cardiac
death, like cardiovascular diseases, may be hereditary.
</P>
<P>
   In a long-term study of middle-aged Parisian civil servants,
French researchers have found that workers with one parent who died
suddenly were almost twice as likely to die that way themselves.
The risk was nine times as great if both parents had died within an
hour of the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The workers also tended to die at about the same ages as their
parents, said Dr. Xavier Jouven, the lead author of the study,
reported in the current issue of Circulation, a journal of the
American Heart Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a positive and significant correlation in the study,
but the goal of the article was to provide information, not to make
predictions,'' said Jouven, a cardiologist at Boucicaut Hospital in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Every year in the United States, about 250,000 men and women
suffer a sudden cardiac death, with only about half of them
suspecting they have cardiovascular problems, according to the
American Heart Association. The attack may be the first sign of
heart disease. As the name implies, many victims die before they
can receive treatment.
</P>
<P>
   For purposes of the study, Jouven and his associates defined
sudden cardiac death as natural death that occurs within an hour
after onset of symptoms, which are similar to those of a heart
attack, whether or not heart disease was previously diagnosed in
the victim.
</P>
<P>
   The genetic link has long been suspected, but information has
tended to be gathered retroactively in interviews with surviving
family members, which may not be accurate.
</P>
<P>
   The French study was based on medical information gathered
through physical examinations and questionnaires administered to
more than 7,000 men aged 43 to 52, from 1967 to 1972. Researchers
followed them for an average of 23 years, including after
retirement, tracking cause of death and correlating the information
with history of parental sudden death. The researchers found that
22 (18.6 percent) of the 118 men who had sudden cardiac deaths had
a parental history of that type of death.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that many of the factors that increase the risks
of heart disease, like smoking, extra weight and lack of exercise,
also raised the risk of sudden cardiac death.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Valentin Fuster, director of the Zena and Michael A. Wiener
Cardiovascular Institute at Mount Sinai Hospital in New York and
president of the American Heart Association, encouraged people with
a family history of sudden cardiac death to examine their habits
and take advantage of cardiac screenings. Only men were studied,
but other studies have shown that sudden cardiac death also affects
women, though at lower rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we don't know if a parental history of sudden death is
also an independent risk factor for women, it would be prudent for
women who have a family history of sudden death also to consider
preventive health measures,'' Jouven said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 1749EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4670 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMDEX-TRENDS-0420-CO     04-19 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMDEX-TRENDS-0420-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KING COMPUTER MAKERS DECLARED DEAD
 &HT;    Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO -- It takes only a glance at the
</P>
<P>
   268-page program guide for the spring
</P>
<P>
   Comdex/Windows World conference, which opened in Chicago
</P>
<P>
   Monday, to see what's going on in the
</P>
<P>
   computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   Computer hardware manufacturers, which at one time
</P>
<P>
   dominated such large trade shows, are gone from the
</P>
<P>
   huge exhibit areas or present only in token strength.
</P>
<P>
   Their places have been taken up by companies that offer Internet
and online networking services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep your eye on applications and back away from
</P>
<P>
   tools,'' advised Aaron Goldberg, principal analyst for
</P>
<P>
   Ziff-Davis Inc., which organizes the semi-annual
</P>
<P>
   event.
</P>
<P>
   ``The long era of the computer makers is over,''
</P>
<P>
   said Clay Ryder, chief analyst for Zona Research Inc.
</P>
<P>
   and an early developer of the Internet. ``They are like the
steel companies. There are no real profits to be
</P>
<P>
   found there anymore because essentially they are
</P>
<P>
   selling a commodity.''
</P>
<P>
   As if to highlight these points, the Comdex
</P>
<P>
   floor buzzed with talk of Sunday's top-level
</P>
<P>
   executive shake-up at Houston-based Compaq Computer
</P>
<P>
   Corp. The departure of Chief Executive Officer Eckhard Pfeiffer
and Chief Financial Officer Earl Mason came after the company's
profits were
</P>
<P>
   dragged down by declining sales and a shift by users into
lower-margin machines.
</P>
<P>
   But there's good news too, as seen by Microsoft
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Bill Gates, a Comdex keynote speaker: Sales
</P>
<P>
   of personal computers continue to rise rapidly. Some
</P>
<P>
   100 million PCs will be sold this year, Gates said, including
7.6 million laptops.
</P>
<P>
   Those purchases are increasingly tied to consumers interest in
cyberspace. Gates estimated that 42 percent of
</P>
<P>
   adult Americans now have Internet access at home
</P>
<P>
   while virtually every office worker is
</P>
<P>
   able to get online through a business link.
</P>
<P>
   A major growth area, said Howard Anderson,
</P>
<P>
   managing director of the Yankee Group, an industry
</P>
<P>
   consulting firm, is broadband access, through
</P>
<P>
   digital subscriber lines or cable modems.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 10 percent of U.S. homes have a high-speed connection
to the
</P>
<P>
   Internet. High-speed access enhances multimedia
</P>
<P>
   services as music and video, while vastly increasing
</P>
<P>
   downloading speeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will give up your first-born before you give
</P>
<P>
   up your cable modem once you get one,'' Anderson suggested.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that by 2003, non-PC devices
</P>
<P>
   connected to the Internet would likely outnumber links
</P>
<P>
   through personal computers, which now dominate 99-to-1. These
devices, he said, will include most telephones and range from
television set
</P>
<P>
   top boxes to remote controls all of kinds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not be surprising to see
</P>
<P>
   Internet access penetration of 75 percent by the end
</P>
<P>
   of 1999, which is, more or less, a natural limit,'' said
Anderson. In
</P>
<P>
   the business world, he added, the ability to link to
</P>
<P>
   the World Wide Web should reach full saturation
</P>
<P>
   by the middle of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   These trends, analysts in Chicago said, are
</P>
<P>
   having a big impact on electronic commerce, with books
</P>
<P>
   and music the hottest categories among buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 190 million U.S. adults who bought goods
</P>
<P>
   from any source during the year-end 1998 holidays, 5.7
</P>
<P>
   million shoppers purchased books and 5.8 million
</P>
<P>
   purchased music CDs. About half the overall book and
</P>
<P>
   music sales were on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Mobile and wireless services are also being
</P>
<P>
   heavily showcased in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Many exhibit booths feature small communication
</P>
<P>
   devices, some of which can directly access the
</P>
<P>
   Internet. For example, BellSouth Wireless Data has
</P>
<P>
   showcased its advanced wireless units, which offer
</P>
<P>
   E-mail and links to corporate intranet databases.
</P>
<P>
   As Goldberg, the Ziff-Davis analyst put it: ``What we're seeing
is a fundamental transformation of the industry. We are moving away
from
</P>
<P>
   general-purpose computer design that has been the norm
</P>
<P>
   for the first 50 years of the business to a consumer
</P>
<P>
   electronic device type of design where the demand is
</P>
<P>
   for a device to do only a single thing well.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
