A4672 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMDEX-TRENDS-0420-CO     04-19 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMDEX-TRENDS-0420-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KING COMPUTER MAKERS DECLARED DEAD
 &HT;    Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO -- It takes only a glance at the
</P>
<P>
   268-page program guide for the spring
</P>
<P>
   Comdex/Windows World conference, which opened in Chicago
</P>
<P>
   Monday, to see what's going on in the
</P>
<P>
   computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   Computer hardware manufacturers, which at one time
</P>
<P>
   dominated such large trade shows, are gone from the
</P>
<P>
   huge exhibit areas or present only in token strength.
</P>
<P>
   Their places have been taken up by companies that offer Internet
and online networking services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep your eye on applications and back away from
</P>
<P>
   tools,'' advised Aaron Goldberg, principal analyst for
</P>
<P>
   Ziff-Davis Inc., which organizes the semi-annual
</P>
<P>
   event.
</P>
<P>
   ``The long era of the computer makers is over,''
</P>
<P>
   said Clay Ryder, chief analyst for Zona Research Inc.
</P>
<P>
   and an early developer of the Internet. ``They are like the
steel companies. There are no real profits to be
</P>
<P>
   found there anymore because essentially they are
</P>
<P>
   selling a commodity.''
</P>
<P>
   As if to highlight these points, the Comdex
</P>
<P>
   floor buzzed with talk of Sunday's top-level
</P>
<P>
   executive shake-up at Houston-based Compaq Computer
</P>
<P>
   Corp. The departure of Chief Executive Officer Eckhard Pfeiffer
and Chief Financial Officer Earl Mason came after the company's
profits were
</P>
<P>
   dragged down by declining sales and a shift by users into
lower-margin machines.
</P>
<P>
   But there's good news too, as seen by Microsoft
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Bill Gates, a Comdex keynote speaker: Sales
</P>
<P>
   of personal computers continue to rise rapidly. Some
</P>
<P>
   100 million PCs will be sold this year, Gates said, including
7.6 million laptops.
</P>
<P>
   Those purchases are increasingly tied to consumers interest in
cyberspace. Gates estimated that 42 percent of
</P>
<P>
   adult Americans now have Internet access at home
</P>
<P>
   while virtually every office worker is
</P>
<P>
   able to get online through a business link.
</P>
<P>
   A major growth area, said Howard Anderson,
</P>
<P>
   managing director of the Yankee Group, an industry
</P>
<P>
   consulting firm, is broadband access, through
</P>
<P>
   digital subscriber lines or cable modems.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 10 percent of U.S. homes have a high-speed connection
to the
</P>
<P>
   Internet. High-speed access enhances multimedia
</P>
<P>
   services as music and video, while vastly increasing
</P>
<P>
   downloading speeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will give up your first-born before you give
</P>
<P>
   up your cable modem once you get one,'' Anderson suggested.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that by 2003, non-PC devices
</P>
<P>
   connected to the Internet would likely outnumber links
</P>
<P>
   through personal computers, which now dominate 99-to-1. These
devices, he said, will include most telephones and range from
television set
</P>
<P>
   top boxes to remote controls all of kinds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not be surprising to see
</P>
<P>
   Internet access penetration of 75 percent by the end
</P>
<P>
   of 1999, which is, more or less, a natural limit,'' said
Anderson. In
</P>
<P>
   the business world, he added, the ability to link to
</P>
<P>
   the World Wide Web should reach full saturation
</P>
<P>
   by the middle of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   These trends, analysts in Chicago said, are
</P>
<P>
   having a big impact on electronic commerce, with books
</P>
<P>
   and music the hottest categories among buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 190 million U.S. adults who bought goods
</P>
<P>
   from any source during the year-end 1998 holidays, 5.7
</P>
<P>
   million shoppers purchased books and 5.8 million
</P>
<P>
   purchased music CDs. About half the overall book and
</P>
<P>
   music sales were on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Mobile and wireless services are also being
</P>
<P>
   heavily showcased in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Many exhibit booths feature small communication
</P>
<P>
   devices, some of which can directly access the
</P>
<P>
   Internet. For example, BellSouth Wireless Data has
</P>
<P>
   showcased its advanced wireless units, which offer
</P>
<P>
   E-mail and links to corporate intranet databases.
</P>
<P>
   As Goldberg, the Ziff-Davis analyst put it: ``What we're seeing
is a fundamental transformation of the industry. We are moving away
from
</P>
<P>
   general-purpose computer design that has been the norm
</P>
<P>
   for the first 50 years of the business to a consumer
</P>
<P>
   electronic device type of design where the demand is
</P>
<P>
   for a device to do only a single thing well.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
