<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4674 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-FITNESS-SCULLING-     04-19 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FITNESS-SCULLING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXERCISE THAT GIVES A ROWER WINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ky., Fla.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MARTHA BARNETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until last summer, my hometown of Louisville, Ky., was better
known for horse racing and baseball bats than the genteel sport of
sculling. Then, a 35-year-old Louisvillian named Tori Murden set
out from the North Carolina coast in a 23-foot boat with the hope
of becoming the first woman to row solo across the Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   A former collegiate sculler, Ms. Murden rowed for 85 days and
was two-thirds of the way across the Atlantic when Hurricane
Danielle forced her to give up. Even though she did not make it,
Louisville was suddenly talking about sculling.
</P>
<P>
   I have decided that I would like to try this sport, which Ms.
Murden had described in interviews as having a mystical allure as
well as physical benefits. When I telephone her, she tells me about
the Florida Rowing Center on Lake Wellington, near West Palm Beach,
where she is planning to brush up on her own skills, so I sign up
for a weekend sculling class for novices.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's session begins at 7:30 a.m., as the mist burns off the
150-acre lake, revealing a mirror-smooth surface. On the pier,
pelicans ruffle their feathers and regard us in silence. The rowing
center, little more than a trailer and a fleet of 30 boats, was
founded by a retired justice of the New York Supreme Court, Arnold
Guy Fraiman, who switched from marathons to rowing out of
consideration for his arthritic knees.
</P>
<P>
   I am in my early 40s, but the instructor, Todd Haynes, says that
many people take up sculling in mid-life. His oldest student, he
says, was 92. I am relieved to hear this, since my exercise regimen
had been a sort of fitness lite, involving twice-weekly workouts
with free weights and leisurely spins on the stationary bike at the
gym. Occasionally, I would switch to the rowing machine, but found
it terminally boring.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike sweep rowing, in which each crew member is responsible
for a single oar on either side of the boat, sculling involves
rowing with two oars. Although there are two- and four-person
boats, sculling is most often a solitary pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   Almost anyone can learn to row, Todd assures us. All that is
required is the ability to swim in case the boat tips over, a
common experience for beginners. There are three important rules to
sculling, he adds: relax, relax and relax.
</P>
<P>
   This is not easy. From afar, the boats look sturdy. But when I
sidle up to one of them and try to figure out how to get in, I
realize the narrow boats are extremely unstable. Relaxing in one is
like trying to relax while sitting on a floating log.
</P>
<P>
   Todd assigns me one of the more forgiving boats. Still, it is
more than 21 feet long and only 19 inches across at the waterline,
tapering to a point at each end. I am supposed to steer the thing
with two nine-foot-long sculls, as the oars are called.
</P>
<P>
   Once in the boat, I sit on a sliding seat, facing the stern.
This means I will be rowing with my back to my destination and
turning to look over my shoulder after every few strokes. Lifting
one oar handle, even slightly, causes the boat to dip precariously
to the opposite side; lift the other and suddenly it tilts the
other way. Take a stroke with the right oar, and the boat veers to
the left.
</P>
<P>
   Another surprise: the sculler's legs, not her arms, supply most
of the power. During a stroke, scullers move their blades backwards
over the water, while sliding the seat toward the stern until they
are in a sort of crouch, then drop the blades in and push hard with
the legs. Straightening the legs, then leaning back and pulling
with the arms forces the blades through the water, propelling the
boat. This explains why rowing provides a superb workout; it uses
all the major muscle groups: arms, legs, trunk and back.
</P>
<P>
   Scullers also use subtle shifts of the hands to turn the blades
parallel and perpendicular to the water at different points in the
stroke. Learning to synchronize all the movements to create a
smooth, graceful motion can take months of practice.
</P>
<P>
   Todd fusses over my grip, placing my thumbs on the ends of the
handles, and separating my fingers so that my grip seems absurdly
loose. Beginners naturally grip the oars tightly, struggling to
force the boat to balance. It seems counterintuitive, but a
delicate grip is better for balancing a wobbly boat.
</P>
<P>
   Experimenting, I discover this is true. The boat is very
unsteady, but responds to the slightest movements of my hands.
</P>
<P>
   In the next hour, Todd and two other instructors circle the lake
in motorboats, videotaping students and dispensing advice.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at your hands,'' Todd calls to me. Glancing down, I am
surprised to see that I still have a death grip on the oars.
Offering a Zenlike pronouncement, he reminds me, ``Less is more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Also,'' he says, ``stop watching the oars. Your eyesight is
the very last sense you need. Try rowing several strokes with your
eyes closed.''
</P>
<P>
   I am skeptical, but soon I am balancing the boat solely by feel,
and sensing the action of my oars by their sound alone.
</P>
<P>
   After breakfast, the coaches use the videotape to critique our
performances. The camera does not lie. I am holding on to the oars
for dear life. Todd repeats, ``Less is more.''
</P>
<P>
   After some stretching exercises to prevent soreness, we are back
on the water, and I find I have a new incentive to loosen my grip
on the oars: four nasty blisters on my hands. Novice rowers, it
turns out, go through a lot of Band-Aids.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, my blisters are so tender I cannot help but hold
the oars properly. I have graduated to a boat that is narrower,
faster and less forgiving, but after more practice and another
critique, I feel increasingly comfortable on the water.
</P>
<P>
   By Saturday afternoon, I transfer into an even narrower and,
therefore, faster, boat, a mere 10 inches across at the waterline.
The wind whips up, and the oars make a scuffing sound as each
stroke sends the boat zipping across the water's corrugated
surface.
</P>
<P>
   Across the lake, Tori Murden whizzes past with near-perfect
form, and gives me an appreciative nod. I close my eyes and listen
to the whooshing of the seat, its rhythm like breathing. I
concentrate on the splash of my oars, the satisfying tug on my
blades. I am putting together more and more good strokes.
</P>
<P>
   I look up. A pelican glides overhead, its wings a perfect
imitation of my oars. I push harder, thinking that this must be the
most sensuous sport in the world. I am the bird, I am the boat, I
am flying, I am ... suddenly leaning way over to the left, then way
over to the right, then farther to the left, then farther to the
right, then dumped into the water.
</P>
<P>
   I am still not sure what happened, though I suspect it had to do
with forgetting that ``less is more.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, by the end of my stay on Sunday afternoon, I am
comfortable in the narrowest boats. I leave pleasantly exhausted,
with that scrubbed-all-over feeling that comes from spending hours
on the water in the wind and sun.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, I make no plans to row across any oceans, but I do go
out on the river every chance I get. On days when I cannot, I use
the rowing machine. And if I close my eyes and remember to relax, I
can almost look up and see wings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sculling lessons are offered around the country at different
times of the year. The Florida Rowing Center operates from December
through mid-May, while others, like the Rocky Mountain Rowing
Center in Lake Dillon, Colo., run from late spring through early
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Many camps charge $75 to $125 per day for coaching, videotaping,
breakfast, and use of sculling equipment, but participants must
find their own lodging. Others, like the Craftsbury Sculling Center
in Craftsbury Common, Vt., offer on-site accommodations as part of
a total package. Peak-season rates, July and August, at Craftsbury
are $775 for a week and $455 for a weekend.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call U.S. Rowing at (800) 314-4769.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web, visit: row2K.com or rowing.miningco.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 1753EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
