<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4676 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-PHARMACOGENOMICS-     04-19 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PHARMACOGENOMICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATCHING PATIENTS TO DRUGS FOR OPTIMUM RESULTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 10 pharmaceutical companies that announced last week that
they were setting up a genome mapping consortium are hoping to buy
a seat at a revolution that may soon start to sweep over their
industry. But like all revolutions, the impending advance, known as
pharmacogenomics, is unlikely to be bloodless.
</P>
<P>
   The basic idea is to match patients, on the basis of a genetic
test, to the drugs that will do them the most good and the least
harm.
</P>
<P>
   This simple concept may engender broad changes. It should mean
better drugs, overall, but they will serve much smaller markets,
and come with complex tests, maybe attracting shoals of tort
lawyers when the tests fail. The drugs should be cheaper to
develop, since fewer will fail in testing, but will cost a lot
more. Patients will surrender a snippet of their genetic privacy
with each test. Health care costs should fall on balance as
patients get more effective drugs, though at higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   If medicine is still an art, it is so in large part because of
the variability with which people respond to drugs. Because
individuals metabolize drugs differently, depending on the precise
genetic makeup of the enzymes in the relevant biochemical pathways,
a drug may work well in some patients but not in others. Most colon
cancer patients, for example, are given a drug known as 5-FU, but
only 30 percent respond to it.
</P>
<P>
   A valuable drug may also be safe for most people but cause side
effects in a small minority. Zyflo, a drug for chronic asthma,
causes side effects that include liver failure in 4 percent of
patients. Drug side effects in general have been estimated to cause
106,000 deaths a year, the fourth-largest cause of death in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Genetic tests that could predict the positive and adverse
responses should in principle match drugs to the subgroups that
would most benefit from them. ``Lazarus'' drugs, those that failed
because of side effects, could be resurrected and sold to patients
whose genetic profile proved they were not the kind whom the drug
would kill.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in drug responses has long been studied by
experts known as pharmacogeneticists. With new methods for
examining the full set of human genes, or genome, it is now
possible to do pharmacogenetics on a genome-wide scale, hence the
name pharmacogenomics.
</P>
<P>
   One kind of test is based on identifying the small variations in
people's DNA where a single nucleotide, or unit of DNA, differs
from the standard sequence. These single nucleotide polymorphisms,
or SNPs (pronounced ``snips''), serve to fingerprint people's DNA
so well that they can be used to trace particular variants of
common genes, such as those that cause disease.
</P>
<P>
   Drug experts hope that merely by associating a particular
pattern of SNPs with a positive response to a drug they will be
able to define the subset of the population for whom the drug would
work best.
</P>
<P>
   Genset, a biotech company in Paris built around the work of Dr.
Daniel Cohen, has constructed a human genome map of 60,000 SNPs.
The company is searching for a pattern of SNPs that will predict
the likelihood of developing side effects to the asthma drug Zyflo,
which is made by Genset's partner, Abbott Laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   The SNP Consortium announced last week by 10 pharmaceutical
companies and Wellcome Trust of London plans to develop a
finer-grained map made of 300,000 SNPs. The map will be placed in
the public domain from the first moment of its construction.
</P>
<P>
   There are several other ways besides SNPs of monitoring changes
in genetic activity. The genes in diseased cells often show a
different pattern of activity, or expression, from that of normal
cells. Millennium Predictive Medicine, a division of Millennium
Pharmaceuticals of Cambridge, Mass., is looking at changes in
proteins and in messenger RNA, the intermediaries between the genes
and the proteins they specify, as well as at SNPs.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Conway, president of Millennium Predictive Medicine,
said that based on these patterns he hoped to develop a test
predicting which of the available breast cancer drugs would be best
for a given patient. The company is working on similar tests for
ovarian and cervical cancer with Becton Dickinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Pap smear used today we are waiting to see abnormal
cells,'' Conway said. ``But in the future we will identify
differential expression that shows up before you can see visual
changes in the cell.''
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacogenomic tests would also make drug development
considerably more sophisticated, although at a cost. The obvious
downside for pharmaceutical companies is that the tests will
fragment the market for a drug by showing it is ideal for only a
small genetic subset of the patient population. Critics have
scoffed that pharmacogenomics will make every drug an orphan.
(``Orphan'' drugs are those with potential sales of less than
200,000 people a year, so unenviable a market that the Food and
Drug Administration offers tax breaks to companies that make such
drugs.)
</P>
<P>
   There's an obvious advantage, too: Companies will be able
exclude from clinical trials the patients likely to have unpleasant
side effects. More drugs will pass clinical trials, but they will
have to be administered with a genetic test, and the drug and test
package will doubtless command premium prices.
</P>
<P>
   Conway believes the demand for such tests is sure to increase.
``At present, when there are two or three drugs available for a
disease, the physician is basically guessing which one is best,''
he said. ``But if there's a test, my guess is they will all use
it.''
</P>
<P>
   If the first tests are successful, that will create a demand for
more tests, and regulators will then require new drugs to be
packaged with genetic tests, Conway predicts. ``Instead of a
company wanting one drug that fits all, they will want to develop a
portfolio of five drugs, one of which will match whatever category
you fall into,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This brave new world of pharmacogenomics will require a lot of
genetic testing, conceivably one with every aspirin, and that
raises concerns about privacy. Probably each test will narrowly
measure genetic elements associated with the drug in question,
revealing little else about a person's genotype. But if large
amounts of genetic information about individual patients should get
into health care company databases, the need to safeguard privacy
would become even more acute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
