<HEADER>
A4680 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-755(2     04-19 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-755(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Mo., Okla., Mass., Mich., Ind., Fla., Nev., Texas,
N.Y., Pa., Fla., N.J.)  (The Science Times) 
(Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sniffle-and-Sneeze Hotbeds in a Hot Race
</P>
<P>
   Early last week, Atlanta was in the news for its astonishingly
high pollen count: 4,371 grains of tree-spawned pollen per cubic
meter. The National Allergy Bureau, a nonprofit pollen-counting
network that provides local readings three times each week from
stations across the United States, considers up to 15 pollen grains
per cubic meter a low count, and any reading over 1,500 as ``very
high.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost before the pollen could settle in Atlanta, a new
front-runner in the runny-nose, itchy-eye derby emerged. Tulsa,
Okla., reported a tree-spawned pollen count of 6,299, while Kansas
City, Mo., and St. Louis entered the very high zone with tallies of
1,992 and 2,520, respectively, making all three places hotbeds for
histamine production.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pollen is higher this year than last year,'' said Dr.
David Hurewitz, professor of medicine at the University of
Oklahoma-Tulsa and a pollen counter for the National Allergy
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oklahoma is located in the middle of a variety of plant types
from cottonwood to pecan,'' Hurewitz said.
</P>
<P>
   This time of the year, pollen from trees is responsible for most
sniffles and sneezes. Grass becomes more irritating in May and
June, and ragweed causes late summer and fall hay fever for many
people.
</P>
<P>
   The American Academy of Allergy, Asthma and Immunology says that
weather conditions can make the pollen count rise or fall. ``Warm,
windy and dry conditions create the perfect environment for the
dissemination of pollen, which can travel up to 400 miles from its
origin,'' said Dr. Donald Pulver, another pollen counter and
allergist in private practice in Rochester, N.Y. On the other hand,
``Heavy spring rainfall reduces the amount of pollen in the air,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Boston, Detroit, Indianapolis, Tampa, Fla., Las Vegas, and
Austin, Texas, all ranked ``high '' on the tree-pollen charts. No
figures were available for New York City, but Rochester checked in
at 143, making it ``high'' on the charts.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the pollen spectrum, Baltimore, Washington,
Pittsburgh and Miami showed pollen counts of 81, 88, 41 and 10, in
the low to moderate range, making them temporary havens for those
who are allergic.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALISHA BERGER
</P>
<P>
   Testing the Smells of Joy and Fear
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're happy and you know it, clap your hands,'' goes the
song. But if a new study is correct, a better suggestion might be
to cover your armpits.
</P>
<P>
   Like other animals, humans appear to send complicated signals
about their emotional states through shifts in their body odor,
said Dr. Denise Chen, a postdoctoral fellow at Monell Chemical
Senses Center in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   In research presented last week at the Association for
Chemoreception Sciences meeting in Sarasota, Fla., Dr. Chen and a
co-author, Dr. Jeannette Haviland-Jones of Rutgers University,
found that other humans seemed able to read these signals
correctly, identifying people who were happy or afraid by sniffing
their underarm odor.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, 25 men and women were asked to wear cotton
underarm pads while they watched an excerpt from the movie ``Ace
Ventura, Pet Detective.'' They then exchanged the pads for clean
ones and watched a scary scene from the movie ``Indiana Jones and
the Temple of Doom.''
</P>
<P>
   The used underarm pads were sorted by mood and by gender, and
stored in glass bottles. A ``control'' bottle contained unscented
cotton pads. One week later, 77 male and female subjects were asked
to sniff the bottles and identify which one contained ``the odor of
people when they are happy,'' and which held ``the odor of people
when they are afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Both male and female subjects succeeded in identifying the smell
of fright at a rate better than chance, the researchers found. But
while women accurately picked out the odor of both male and female
happiness, men in the study could only identify the happy odor when
it had been emitted by a woman. Several subjects said after the
experiment that the ``fear'' odor was stronger and more unpleasant
than the ``happy'' odor.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence that olfactory signals carry information about
emotional states has been found in many species, including
earthworms, ticks, honeybees, minnows, rats and mice, Dr. Chen
said. And in folklore, people are said to have a ``foul'' odor when
they are afraid, or to smell ``sweet'' when they are happy.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Chen said her study was the first to test whether humans
also signaled moods with changes in odor.
</P>
<P>
   _ ERICA GOODE
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
