</P>
<P>
   What's Wrong? Ask Patient, Not Doctor
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the doctor doesn't know best. In a study from Purdue
University, published this month in the American Sociological
Review, researchers suggest that people, particularly
African-Americans, may be better predictors of their health than
doctors.
</P>
<P>
   In the study of about 7,000 patients ages 25 to 74 that began in
1971, Dr. Kenneth Ferraro and his colleagues asked participants to
answer a questionnaire about diseases they had and to rate their
overall health from poor to excellent.
</P>
<P>
   Then a physician reviewed the patients' comments, conducted an
extensive health examination and made a separate assessment of the
patients' health. About 20 years later, Ferraro compiled records of
patients who had died and compared their self-assessments of health
with the physicians' evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In each case, the patient's self-report of health, including
what diseases he or she had, was an equal or better predictor of
how long he would live compared to the physician's assessment,''
said Ferraro, a sociology professor at Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest discrepancies was between African-Americans'
health assessments and how healthy the white physicians in the
study perceived them to be. ``The results of the physician
examinations did not predict African-American health well at all,''
Ferraro said.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers suspect that either the doctors did less thorough
examinations of the African-American patients or the patients did
not disclose full information to the doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Previous studies have suggested that in medical situations where
doctor and patient are of different ethnic backgrounds,
communication between the patient and the doctor can be limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``African-Americans have, in the past, faced economic,
geographical and cultural barriers in receiving health care,'' said
Dr. Stephen Thomas, director of the Institute for Minority Health
Research at the Emory University School of Public Health in
Atlanta. ``This historical discrimination may have caused some
subjects to be mistrustful of the medical system and not as open
with the doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Blendon, a professor of health policy at the Harvard
School of Public Health, called the study a ``wake-up call for
doctors to listen carefully to their patients.'' But it does not
mean that people should try to diagnose themselves, Blendon added.
</P>
<P>
   _ MALIA McKINNON
</P>
<P>
   Doctors' Choice of Drugs May Be Influenced by Ads
</P>
<P>
   A team of Massachusetts General Hospital researchers has found
that advertising may influence the choice of hypertension drugs
that doctors prescribe for their patients.
</P>
<P>
   Though the doctors said they could not prove the link between
the ads doctors see and the drugs they prescribe, they believed
that marketing efforts might have spurred physicians to switch from
older, established, less expensive high-blood-pressure medications
to newer, costlier drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a good amount of information suggesting that
physicians aren't following the national guidelines for treating
hypertension, which call for beta blockers and diuretics to be used
as first-line treatment for most patients,'' said Dr. Randall
Stafford, the study's senior author.
</P>
<P>
   The authors point out that the use of newer classes of drugs _
ACE inhibitors, which interfere with production of a chemical that
constricts arteries, and calcium channel blockers, which reduce the
heart rate and relax blood vessels _ has increased dramatically
since the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, say the authors, ads in selected issues of the
New England Journal of Medicine for calcium channel blockers
quadrupled from 1985 to 1996, while ads for beta blockers decreased
from 12.4 percent to 0 percent and those for ACE inhibitors dropped
from 4.2 percent to 0 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't suggest that anyone stop taking a medication that is
working for them,'' said Stafford. ``But patients who are about to
start a medication may want to discuss the benefits of the various
drugs with their doctors before deciding on their individual
treatment plans.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LINDA VILLAROSA
</P>
