<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4685 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-AIDS-RESEARCH-2TA     04-19 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-AIDS-RESEARCH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LONG-DELAYED ILLNESS SHATTERS A HOPE ON AIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN, M.D.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ The ultimate dream of AIDS researchers is to
find a nonvirulent strain of HIV and turn it into a safe, effective
vaccine. Since the late 1980s, a team of Australian scientists has
believed such a strain existed in a small group of people
inadvertently infected with HIV through transfusions from one blood
donor.
</P>
<P>
   People in the group were never treated for HIV infection, yet
they have carried the strain for up to 17 years without developing
AIDS symptoms. Because no similar group has been found elsewhere,
world attention has focused on the Australian effort to use this
strain of naturally weakened live virus to make a vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scientists talked about a Nobel Prize,'' said the
40-year-old donor, John, who dreamed that development of a
successful vaccine from his HIV would make him a medical hero and
rich.
</P>
<P>
   But now the dreams are shattered.
</P>
<P>
   In February, after losing 75 pounds in five months, John, who
asked that his last name not be used, was found to have an
AIDS-related infection of the brain and spinal cord. And two
recipients have shown signs of weakening immune systems but have
not become ill. Three other group members remain healthy. (The
remaining three died from causes believed unrelated to AIDS.)
</P>
<P>
   John's extraordinary good luck of surviving HIV without
treatment for more than 17 years while suffering nothing more
serious than a cold lulled him into a false sense of security. He
was confident that he would escape AIDS, he said in his first
interview about his odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've had HIV for so long, and the worst you'd ever had
was a sore throat or cough, you feel you can go on ignoring it, and
you think why should I start treatment now,'' John said.
``Obviously, I had not learned my lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   John is one of the rare individuals to publicly discuss his
feelings about having infected someone else with HIV through a
blood transfusion.
</P>
<P>
   Australian Red Cross officials initially rejected his request to
meet the people he had inadvertently infected. Jennifer C.
Learmont, the Australian Red Cross social worker whose research
identified the rare cluster in the late 1980s, said she discouraged
John from meeting recipients, fearing it could harm him
psychologically. But after learning that John had repeated the
request, Ms. Learmont promised to try to arrange a meeting between
John and any infected recipient willing to meet him.
</P>
<P>
   John said he ``expected that they would have very angry things
to say to me, but if they didn't, then I'd sit down, just listen,
see how they are doing, and take it from there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say I was sorry that it happened but that I acted in
good faith and that it was just one of those things,'' John said.
</P>
<P>
   John gave blood 26 times from 1977 (four years before doctors
recognized AIDS) to 1984. His main motivation, he said, was to be a
good samaritan, but a secondary reward was an afternoon off work.
</P>
<P>
   John is gay, he said. In late 1984, one of the men with whom
John said he had been intimate told him he was infected. John then
got tested for the first time and was relieved to learn he had
apparently escaped infection.
</P>
<P>
   But a repeat test showed the opposite. John was HIV-positive.
Later research by Ms. Learmont's team showed that John had been
infected since 1981.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, John was in college, and he feared dying before
graduation. ``I just took things day-by-day, which then became
day-by-day-by-day-by-day,'' he said, eventually forgetting about
being infected.
</P>
<P>
   John said he stopped giving blood in 1984 as soon as he got the
bad news, but said he did not recall why he had donated after blood
banks asked people at high risk for AIDS not to donate before HIV
testing was available.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Ms. Learmont told John that his blood had infected
others. ``At first I felt some guilt,'' he said, ``but then I
analyzed it rationally and realized it was bad luck rather than bad
faith.''
</P>
<P>
   First in Sydney and later in Melbourne, scientists began
analyzing the molecular makeup of the virus from John and those he
had infected. Eventually, tests showed that one of HIV's nine
genes, the nef gene, was defective in the strain identified in the
cluster. Tests also showed that the man who had advised John to get
his first HIV test had a different strain.
</P>
<P>
   By 1992, the Australian team began publishing articles about the
cluster, and they raised hopes that the defective strain could be
turned into a vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   John was elated. ``It was an exciting but unfortunate time in my
life because the corporate and unattractive side of my personality
took over for a while,'' he said. ``I was told there was a dollar
to be made out of it, and I became quite commercial about it.''
</P>
<P>
   John hired a lawyer and financial adviser, signed an agreement
with a company for a share of any royalties, and was paid a small
consultant's fee for three years. ``The thing that most excited me
was how much money I could make out of this,'' and ``the talk about
a Nobel Prize,'' John said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Beginning three years ago, the standard blood test used to
monitor the immune system showed a steady but gradual fall in the
number of crucial immune cells, CD-4 cells, in John's blood. His
count fell from about 600 to 320 this month, with 500 or more
usually considered normal.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors advised John to start taking combinations of drugs that
were beginning to change the face of AIDS by allowing many people
to live with the disease. Doctors also recommended that John take
other drugs to prevent AIDS-related infections. But John rejected
the advice because ``I had it in my head that after 15 or so years,
I did not need to worry about AIDS.''
</P>
<P>
   Last September, John began to feel tired and lost his appetite.
At first, he attributed the symptoms to work-related stress. Not
until February did his doctors learn what was troubling him: a
central nervous system infection from an AIDS-related condition.
But by then John's weight had dropped to 160 from his usual 235
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The brain infection has cleared with treatment, and he has begun
taking three drugs to combat HIV. Before such treatment, the amount
of HIV in the fluid that bathed his spinal cord was a very high
750,000 and a high 100,000 in his blood. Under therapy, the HIV
count has dropped to 1,800 in his spinal fluid and is not
detectable in his blood.
</P>
<P>
   Many human vaccines are derived from weakened live viruses.
Experiments on primates have shown that a live virus vaccine made
by artificially removing the nef gene in the laboratory has
achieved the best protection in monkeys against simian AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   However, more recent findings have found that some monkeys
injected with artificially weakened simian vaccine have died or
become ill from simian AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   For unknown reasons, the Australian HIV strain had been weakened
by a natural deletion of the nef gene, and it was an obvious
candidate for a human vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dale A. McPhee, a member of the research team that works on
the strain at the Macfarlane Burnet Center for Medical Research in
Fairfield, Australia, said if a vaccine had been developed, he
would have been willing to follow scientific tradition and test the
vaccine from John's blood on himself. But, McPhee said, the new
proof that the strain is virulent has changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Mills, who heads the team in Fairfield, and other
scientists expressed hope that knowledge gained from research into
John's strain would contribute to the development of an AIDS
vaccine. For example, Mills said, deletions of additional genes
from HIV may yet help produce a successful AIDS vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists plan to continue monitoring the three infected
recipients who remain healthy. No correlation has been found
between a declining CD-4 cell count and the length of time the
recipient has been infected with the mutant strain. For example,
the first recipient of John's blood has fared best, but the second
has a failing immune system.
</P>
<P>
   John links his long period of good health to his faith as a
practicing Roman Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   HIV had made him more dependent on God, and faith broadened his
perspective. ``Once you've got to confront something like HIV and
AIDS, your priorities change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Had he not become infected, John said, he ``might have climbed
the greasy pole of the corporate ladder, to get as much money and
power'' as he could. Now, he said, he ``enjoys every day for what
it is and sees life and health as gifts.''
</P>
<P>
   John's recent illness has made him confront issues that he had
put aside. One was hiding his infection from family. ``I was so
terribly disappointed and ashamed when I developed AIDS that I told
people not to come visit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But John said he changed his mind after a talk with a brother.
John had thought only two family members knew about his infection.
But the brother told John that for a long time the entire family
had known and that they had gotten over the shock. ``AIDS has
brought the family closer together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, John says he has returned to work and assumes he ``will
stay well and have a long life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 1801EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
