<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4688 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRUFFAUT-BOOK-REVIEW-     04-19 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUFFAUT-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TRUFFAUT': THE SHY, CONFLICTED MAN WHO LOVED THE MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a 1957 article Francois Truffaut, who was not yet a director
but a young and controversial film critic, predicted the rise of
the French New Wave and its reconfiguration of contemporary
filmmaking. He also mapped out the course his own idiosyncratic
work would take.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film of tomorrow appears to me as even more personal than
an individual and autobiographical novel, like a confession or a
diary,'' he wrote. ``The young filmmakers will express themselves
in the first person and will relate what has happened to them: It
may be the story of their first love or their most recent; of their
political awakening; the story of a trip, a sickness, their
military service, their marriage, their last vacation ... and it
will be enjoyable because it will be true and new.''
</P>
<P>
   As this workmanlike new biography by Antoine de Baecque and
Serge Toubiana makes clear, Truffaut's own films were all acutely
autobiographical in impulse: not just the celebrated movies
featuring his favorite alter ego, Antoine Doinel (``The 400
Blows,'' ``Stolen Kisses,'' ``Bed and Board,'' ``Love on the Run''
and the short ``Antoine and Colette''), but even films like ``The
Soft Skin,'' ``The Story of Adele H.'' and ``Jules and Jim,'' which
were ostensibly based on newspaper articles, historical figures or
other writers' novels.
</P>
<P>
   Truffaut's fascination with children (evinced by movies like
``The 400 Blows,'' ``The Wild Child'' and ``Small Change'') grew
out of his own unhappy childhood, just as the central theme of all
his work _ the equation of love with suffering, passion with
obsession _ was rooted in his contentious relationship with his
mother and in his multiple affairs with a succession of women. With
many of his scripts, the authors of this biography reveal, Truffaut
practiced what he called ``verification through life,'' concealing
his personal investment in a story with details and anecdotes
collected from others, details that ``made the autobiographical
more concrete but also more universal.''
</P>
<P>
   The hero of ``Shoot the Piano Player'' (based on the David
Goodis novel ``Down There'') became, in Truffaut's telling, a kind
of double of himself: a shy, deeply conflicted man with a passion
for women. The long confession delivered by Catherine Deneuve in
``Mississippi Mermaid,'' de Baecque and Toubiana contend, was based
on excerpts of a tape Truffaut made of his first live-in
girlfriend, reminiscing about her delinquent youth, ``receiving
public welfare, acquiring her first pair of high heels at 14,
stealing money from wallets, having kleptomania and going to reform
school.'' And the obsessional passion Adele H. harbored for a
British Army lieutenant seems to have mirrored the unrequited
passion Truffaut felt for Isabelle Adjani, the star of ``Adele H.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the authors of this biography (both editors of Cahiers
du Cinema, the French film magazine, which was once home base to
Truffaut) do a nimble job of excavating the autobiographical
sources of this director's art, they inexplicably shrug off any
attempt to convey the power of his movies: their unique blend of
comedy and darkness, their tenderness and sardonic humor, their
anomalous ability to locate the mysterious in the mundane.
</P>
<P>
   Where ``Truffaut'' is more successful is in providing a nuanced
portrait of the director, a portrait that draws heavily upon
Truffaut's own correspondence, particularly his revealing letters
to his friend and translator Helen Scott. The man who emerges from
this book is a melancholy man, awkward yet seductive, generous but
judgmental, a man who seemed incapable of being faithful to a
single woman but who simultaneously depended upon the bourgeois
stability of his marriage, a man who once wrote that his ``critical
attitude'' prevented him ``from falling in love.''
</P>
<P>
   De Baecque and Toubiana vigorously sketch in Truffaut's
tumultuous childhood and youth: the unwanted son of an unwed mother
who spurned him, once she had settled down to married life, as an
embarrassing reminder of her wayward youth. Young Francois grew up
with his maternal grandmother and developed a fierce resentment
toward his mother and a deep-seated suspicion of authority and
convention. After a stint in reform school, he enlisted in the army
but was granted a discharge on grounds of an ``unstable
character.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout these difficult years, Truffaut's consuming passion
was going to the movies. Ever the autodidact, he set himself the
goal as a teen-ager of seeing three movies a day and reading three
books a week. He saw Marcel Carne's ``Children of Paradise'' nine
times and Renoir's masterpiece ``The Rules of the Game'' at least a
dozen.
</P>
<P>
   Under the mentorship of the critic Andre Bazin, Truffaut began
turning his love of movies into a career, and through a series of
wildly controversial essays articulated the essentials of what
would become known as ``auteur theory.'' He would also forge what
de Baecque and Toubiana hail as ``a new form of film criticism _
frank, direct, violent, sectarian, founded on value judgments,
always detailed but often provocative and scathing, with no qualms
about being peremptory and unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Truffaut's writing obviously did little to endear him to
the French film establishment, his first full-length feature, ``The
400 Blows,'' took the 1959 Cannes Film Festival by storm. The movie
won the 28-year-old Truffaut acclaim as a ``child prodigy'' and
helped fueled the rise of the New Wave.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 25 years, Truffaut, who died of brain cancer in
1984, would make another 20 movies, working at a frenetic pace to
escape his bouts of depression. Unfortunately for the reader of
this biography, de Baecque and Toubiana do little to explicate his
achievement. Instead of revealing how Truffaut's work developed and
matured, they lay out a dry, uninflected chronicle of his
filmmaking filled with dreary details about casting and the rigors
of production. Instead of providing us with a critical appraisal of
his work, they give us plodding summaries of reviews and box office
sales.
</P>
<P>
   In the end Truffaut himself summed up the passion he felt for
movies better than anyone else. In ``Day for Night,'' his movie
about making movies, the character of the director, played by
Truffaut himself, turns to his young protege and says: ``Movies are
more harmonious than life. There are no traffic jams in movies, no
dead spots.'' But while his biographers laboriously chronicle the
reasons Truffaut felt compelled to turn his own life into art, they
fatally neglect to communicate the imaginative alchemy and magic he
effected on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TRUFFAUT'
</P>
<P>
   By Antoine de Baecque and Serge Toubiana
</P>
<P>
   Translated by Catherine Temerson. 462 pages. Alfred A. Knopf.
$30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
