<HEADLINE>
`SPIDERS': AGAINST VIRTUAL REALITY, THE SPIDERS LOSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(nk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   So what is it that spiders do besides populating nightmares and
hanging around in corners of the house where they have not been
invited? Mainly, as Alan Alda learns in Tuesday night's final
episode of this season's ``Scientific American Frontiers,'' they
busy themselves with weaving their remarkable silky webs, an art
they have perfected over the last 400 million years.
</P>
<P>
   Besides being things of beauty, particularly when the sun
strikes, these intricate miracles of craftsmanship provide food
(the bugs that are ensnared by the sticky strands and never find
their way out) as well as mates enraptured by the melodies created
by vibrations of an amatory spider's hairy legs against the web's
delicate strings.
</P>
<P>
   Alda watches while experts use computers to help them understand
what is in a spider's mind as it goes about its work. Since the
creatures seem to be prone to promiscuity and think that images on
a screen are the real thing, virtual reality must be frustrating
for those hoping to establish a relationship.
</P>
<P>
   A spider's life turns out not to be all romance, however,
particularly in Australia, where vicious looking hunter spiders use
what a researcher calls the ``dynamics of deceit'' to trap and kill
the hosts whose webs they invade. It's enough to give a hospitable
spider a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   The program does not fail to note that many humans are put off
by spiders for no particular reason outside of unreasoning
squeamishness. Happily, hope for the human arachnophobe is
available in a report on a woman who overcomes an advanced case of
spider-detestation with the help of virtual-reality therapy. Now
she is able to watch a Mexican red-kneed tarantula crawl onto her
hand without a squeak or shudder. Congratulations. But why would
anybody want to do that?
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   SCIENTIFIC AMERICAN FRONTIERS
</P>
<P>
   Spiders!
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Tuesday, at 8 p.m. ET
</P>
<P>
   John Angier and Graham Chedd, executive producers; Alan Alda,
host. Produced by the Chedd-Angier Production Company in
association with Scientific American magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
