<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, April 20, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cool weather will continue to grip the northern third of the
nation Tuesday as the jet stream dips south of its normal position
across the U.S.-Canada border. In the Northeast, low pressure
poised off the New Jersey coast will circulate cool, Atlantic
moisture westward, bringing spotty light showers to the Northeast
Seaboard. Meanwhile, further inland, chilly light showers may mix
with a bit of wet snow atop the higher peaks of the Catskills and
Berkshire mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Sinking air currents associated with high pressure along the
Gulf of Mexico Coast will bring mainly sunny and warm conditions to
the Southeast Tuesday. Unfortunately, the dry conditions will
likely remain over the state of Florida during the next several
days, fueling additional brush fires across the peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   The clockwise circulation of air around the Gulf of Mexico high
will direct increasingly humid air into Texas and the southern
Plains. As this corridor of sultry air intercepts a slow-moving
warm front, thunderstorms will erupt later Tuesday over the Middle
Mississippi and lower Ohio Valleys. Winds changing direction and
speed with increasing altitude will induce of few of these storms
to rotate. These rotating thunderstorms, called supercells, are
capable of spawning tornadoes and large hail.
</P>
<P>
   Cooler air will filter into the Northwest Tuesday behind a
departing cold front while abundant sunshine prompts near record
warmth in interior southern California and the Southwest deserts.
Gentle sea breezes will temper the heat along the southern
California coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Warm Alaska
</P>
<P>
   Record warmth was common across the Tanana and Yukon Valleys of
interior Alaska on Sunday. At Fairbanks, the mercury soared to 68
degrees, while at nearby Eielson Air Force Base, temperatures
peaked at a summer-like 70 degrees. The 64-degree reading at the
town of Healy smashed the record high for the date of 51 degrees
while also establishing a new record high for the month of April.
Sunday's warm wave was fostered by stationary high pressure
centered over western Canada, which blocked the normal advance of
wet Pacific disturbances with cold air in their wakes.
</P>
</TEXT>
