<HEADER>
A4705 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MET-GREEK-CORRIDOR-2T     04-19 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MET-GREEK-CORRIDOR-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLORY COMES HOME TO THE CLASSICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The most spectacular space to be opened in New York
City since the renovation of Grand Central Terminal is being
unveiled Tuesday, and like Grand Central it is also a refurbished
landmark: the 140-foot-long neo-classical barrel-vaulted corridor
south of the main lobby, or Great Hall, in the Metropolitan Museum
of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Can you picture it? If not, that may be because for half a
century it has been an architectural Cinderella, its virtues
obscured by the job it had to do. In 1948 it became essentially a
passageway between the lobby and the museum's cafeteria. Its
skylights had already been blacked out and artificial lights
installed during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   For decades it haphazardly displayed Cypriot and Roman art,
which most people seemed barely to notice on their way to lunch.
Grime accumulated. Coffers on the ceiling began to crumble. It's
amazing that no one was conked on the head by falling debris before
the museum shut the space two years ago to remodel it.
</P>
<P>
   Now the skylights are open again: immense shafts pierce the
reconstructed barrel vault, rising to windows 62 feet high. On a
sunny day, light cascades off the walls and spanking-clean pink
stone floor and onto the sculptures, now Greek, which have been
arranged artfully for a change. The corridor has become one of the
greatest public places in the city.
</P>
<P>
   It is being reopened as the centerpiece of the second phase of a
three-part campaign to overhaul all the Met's galleries of Greek
and Roman art. The campaign has grown to $150 million. This vast
undertaking is deeply, admirably unfashionable.
</P>
<P>
   When the Met opened in 1870, collecting antiquities was
universally regarded as fundamental to the mission of a great
museum. The first work the Met acquired was a Roman sarcophagus.
Greece and Rome were the cornerstones of Western civilization, and
all educated children were supposed to learn Greek and Latin. That
was the way of the world.
</P>
<P>
   But tastes and philosophies change _ except at the Met, which
fortunately seems to take the long view of civilization.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first parts of the museum to be put together, the
antiquities collection is the last major department to be
overhauled. The initial phase of the renovation, completed in 1996,
was the refurbishment of what is now the Belfer Court for
prehistoric and early Greek art, a large room with beamed ceiling
designed by Richard Morris Hunt in 1902.
</P>
<P>
   The second phase encompasses the immense corridor (inspired
partly by the Braccio Nuovo at the Vatican) and six large,
classically proportioned rooms, three on either side of the
corridor, which were added to the museum in 1917. With the current
redesign, they serve the purpose for which they were conceived by
the architects McKim, Mead &AMP; White, displaying the art that
chronologically succeeds what's in the Belfer Court next door:
Attic sculpture and decorative materials from the sixth through the
fourth centuries B.C., the Archaic and Classical periods.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fair guess that these rooms and the collection in them
have never looked better. For one thing, the walls of the corridor,
which had been stuccoed because the museum could not acquire enough
stone when the place was being built during World War I, are now
sheathed in gray limestone, as had been intended. For another, all
the works of art _ around 1,200 objects _ have been cleaned, a
monumental feat.
</P>
<P>
   The presentation is logical, spacious and handsome, though you
wouldn't quite say it is simple. Antiquities displays, often the
oldest in a museum, traditionally tend to be stuffy and shopworn,
geared to specialists. Objects are usually grouped by style and
material. Endless cases of broken pots come to mind.
</P>
<P>
   In the reinstallation at the Met, Carlos Picon, the curator in
charge, along with Jeffrey Daly, the museum's chief designer, tried
something different. ``I realized,'' Picon has said, ``that I would
continue to lose all my customers to the 19th century if I showed
my art in long rows of objects of diminishing size.''
</P>
<P>
   So works are now arranged in various configurations: thematic,
stylistic and chronological. Sections deal with theater in ancient
Athens, the Olympics, civic life, death, war, education, gods,
myths and heroes. It's interesting how, with antiquities and
non-Western objects, relating art to social and political history
does not seem particularly radical, although with Western painting
it remains a point of bitter contention among scholars and museum
officials who debate whether social history obscures esthetic
appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, rooms of pots now feature related materials to
liven things up and convey a larger sense of culture. A couple of
early-fifth-century B.C. water jugs painted with chariots, for
example, share a case with a tiny bronze charioteer from the same
period.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One case of objects focuses on a single artist to illustrate how
archeologists isolate a particular hand. Long wall texts survey
history, terminology, burial practices, artist techniques and so
on.
</P>
<P>
   Only the most patient, diligent visitor will scope out all the
themes and connections, but the best permanent installations repay
multiple visits. The guiding principle here is, as it should be:
Keep your eyes open. Works that have not been seen for years
because they were in storage or that have not been shown to
advantage finally get their due.
</P>
<P>
   One is a kylix, or shallow terra-cotta drinking cup from around
490 B.C., attributed to an artist named Douris. It shows a young
woman at her wash basin, exquisitely drawn.
</P>
<P>
   Picon has mixed in loans as well, hoping they will become gifts.
They include a late-fourth-century B.C. head of a veiled woman that
belongs to a collector in Belgium, the cloth sculptured to look
swept across her face, as if by a gust of wind, and a big
calyx-krater, a bowl for mixing wine and water, from the late sixth
century B.C., signed by Euphronius.
</P>
<P>
   It is prominently placed in the corridor to make perfectly
clear, to anyone who couldn't otherwise guess, just how much the
museum would love to have it.
</P>
<P>
   Picon has made various recent acquisitions of curios like a
marble sculpture in the shape of a pelican's foot shell, from
around 400 B.C., paper thin so that light shines through it, and a
pair of larger-than-life eyes with bronze eyelids, monumentally
surreal. They're not the foundation of an antiquities collection in
the making, but they're smartly suited to a collection already
formed, like the Met's.
</P>
<P>
   The final and most ambitious phase of the renovation of the
Greek and Roman galleries won't be completed for several years. The
restaurant will move, the space it occupies becoming a skylighted
court for Roman art, which it used to be. Administrative offices on
a mezzanine adjacent to the court will turn into galleries for
Etruscan art, special exhibitions and open storage. Cypriot
sculptures will go to the second floor. A new restaurant will be
built atop the octagonal Lehman Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   The museum will end up with 60,000 square feet for the Greek and
Roman collection, slightly more than it had before the restaurant
took over the court in 1948. More significantly, perhaps, traffic
patterns will shift after the restaurant relocates, so that the
entire south end of the Met should more closely approximate what
McKim, Mead &AMP; White envisioned: a soaring, classical suite of rooms
for antique art.
</P>
<P>
   The renovated corridor, now called the Mary and Michael Jaharis
Gallery, will then be the central spine of a museum within the
museum.
</P>
<P>
   Until then it is, above all, a sublime relic of America's
cultural ambitions and insecurities of a century ago. And once
again it's a good place to show art.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the corridor near the restaurant is a
fourth-century B.C. marble head of a goddess. It is said that she
may be Persephone, daughter of Demeter, or Hygeia, the daughter of
Asklepios, the god of medicine, but it doesn't matter. Whoever she
is, she epitomizes what we imagine when we think of the serene,
fresh-faced perfection of Greek art. The sculpture is given new
prominence by the reinstallation. In the flooded light of the
gallery her head shines like a beacon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
