<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Tuesday, April 20. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ NATO gives a briefing on the convoy
incident, with video; saying NATO forces may have killed the
civilians. NATO also blames the Yugoslav Army for having military
vehicles mixed with civilian vehicles. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Washington) _ President Clinton talks with
Russian President Yeltsin for first time since NATO attacks
started. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-BERLIN (Berlin) _ Chancellor Schroeder declares a new
``Berlin Republic'' as the German Parliament moves into Reichstag.
By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-PROFILE (Washington) _ A political profile of Bill
Bradley, the New Jersey Democrat; the first in series of occasional
profiles of presidential contenders. By Richard L. Berke. (1800
words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Computer-related and Internet shares dragged
the Nasdaq Composite Index to its worst drop since October. It was
around 5.6 percent. Investors sold Microsoft Corp. and America
Online Inc., among the biggest gainers in recent months, and bought
laggards such as oil, aluminum, steel and chemicals stocks. The Dow
Jones Industrial Average surrendered a 272-point gain as General
Electric Co., Wal-Mart Stores Inc. and Merck &AMP; Co. slumped.
Citigroup Inc. spurred a rally in financial shares after reporting
unexpectedly strong earnings. The Dow was down around 76 points. By
Kenneth Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   WIS-WELFARE (Milwaukee) _ Michelle Crawford's odyssey _ from
desperation to distinction, from welfare to work _ is indeed a
powerful, inspiring story. It is also an incomplete one, at least
in its official telling. After years of severe anxiety and
depression, Ms. Crawford, 39, is indeed off welfare and on the job
at a plastics factory outside Milwaukee. Her diligent record
recently earned her a raise, to $8.20 an hour. But behind the
scenes, her accomplishments have also placed new burdens on a life
that is much more difficult than her admirers realize and less
steady than the Governor may hope. By Jason DeParle.
</P>
<P>
   NY-ZONING (New York) _ Moving to overhaul New York City's zoning
laws for the first time in 40 years, the Giuliani administration
will propose on Tuesday the city's first absolute limits on the
height of skyscrapers. Also for the first time, developers could no
longer build higher buildings in exchange for creating plazas or
other public amenities. The changes are among several in the
planned zoning overhaul.
</P>
