<HEADLINE>
LILLIAN WHELTON, AT 69; FOUNDED SHARE THE HARVEST TO FEED POOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lillian Patricia (Rock) Whelton, the founder of Share the
Harvest, a nonprofit New Hampshire group that gathers and
redistributes excess food from farmers' fields to families in need,
died Saturday in her home in Brookline, N.H. She was 69.
</P>
<P>
   Share the Harvest was recognized by President George Bush as one
of his Thousand Points of Light.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we do doesn't take any money or any special skills,''
Mrs. Whelton said in a story published in the Globe's New Hampshire
Weekly section on Jan. 12, 1992. ``All you need is a pickup truck
and some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we can't do anything about people starving in
Ethiopia,'' she said, ``but we can sure do something about people
starving in our own backyard.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she was inspired to form Share the Harvest by ``The
Gleaners,'' a PBS television show about a group of retirees who
gleaned leftover vegetables from farmers' fields to feed the
hungry. After coaxing a local farmer into participating, she called
some friends and arranged to distribute the surplus produce from a
pickup truck in the parking lot of the Nashua welfare office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know what to expect,'' Whelton said of that first
trip to the city in 1990. ``We pulled into a courtyard between the
courthouse and the abandoned mills, put a handmade `free food' sign
on the side of a pickup half-filled with corn and other produce,
and waited to see what developed.''
</P>
<P>
   The passersby were skeptical. ``They couldn't believe it at
first. They wanted to know what the catch was.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Whelton and her all-volunteer organization gathered
leftover fruit and vegetables from local fields as well as
irregular produce not readily salable at grocery markets.
</P>
<P>
   She was raised in Nashua. She was employed by the Bank of New
Hampshire in Nashua for more than 10 years until her retirement,
when she opened a gourmet food business with a friend in Hollis,
N.H., where she lived for more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   She leaves her husband, George B. Jr.; three daughters,
Elizabeth Whelton and Sarah Buckley, both of Hollis, N.H., Tara
Marie Dyer of Cape Coral, Fla.; a son, Christopher of Chittendon,
Vt.; a sister, Eunice (Rock) O'Leary of Marlborough, Mass.; and 12
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
