<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   COMDEX _ CHICAGO _ Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates and Linus
Torvalds, creator of the Linux operating system, give back-to-back
speeches Monday at the Comdex computer show. The speeches come at a
time when Microsoft's Windows is under siege in a federal antitrust
suit and the company's products are pressured by production delays
and falling PC prices. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   w/COMDEX-TRENDS _ CHICAGO - The portion of U.S. households with
Internet access is expected to peak at about 75 percent, according
to a forecast made at the Comdex show. Story looks at
computer/Internet trends. Glass. With COX-COMDEX. Moving in
financial and Washington categories. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Both stories moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington
categories.
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH _ BellSouth Corp. today announced plans to buy a 10
percent stake in Denver-based Qwest Communications for $3.5
billion. Qwest is one of the nation's more ambitious providers of
high-speed data and long-distance services. (Kannell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (f) financial and (a) General News categories.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: An early version has moved for Monday afternoon papers.
</P>
<P>
   TURNER-BROADCASTERS _ Ted Turner speaks for the first time at
the National Association of Broadcasters. He can now move among the
broadcasters because, as vice chairman of Time Warner, he has sway
over the hot new WB network. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING _ When offered the opportunity to test drive the
Hummer, I halfheartedly accepted. When I would see a Hummer being
driven on the street, I would scowl, ``Disgusting display of
excess.'' And, yes, a Hummer probably is more vehicle than anyone
really needs. But after a week with my competition yellow civilian
version of the same vehicle that our troops are using around the
world, I came away a fan. (Sharp, Atlanta Jounal-Constitution)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   THE-MECHANIC _ This column will not move today.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDS: Here is the budget for the CoxNet PTECH page for the
current week. This layout is now available. Art includes 3 color
photos and 3 color illustrations
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH 0420 _ Move over, Beanie Babies. Pokemon have
seized the day. And like those cuddly, stuffed, fabled toys of
yesterday's trend, there's seemingly a million of 'em. Since
hitting the U.S. market in September 1998, Nintendo has sold 1.5
million units, making it the fastest-selling Gameboy game ever.
(Hill, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes one 3-column
color illustration and two 1-column illustrations of Pokemon
characters. Also, one 3-column photo from Pokemon Web site.
</P>
<P>
   w/TECH BRIEFS _ Computers and operating systems break down all
too often. Now you can find solutions to some problems in the April
issue of Windows magazine. Its cover story is devoted to fixing 15
common PC problems. (Staff, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art
includes one 1-column color photo of a printer.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY _ It wasn't too long ago that computers were fairly
easy to understand and fix. Nowadays, computers are so complex that
most of us are way over our heads when it comes to working on them.
(Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) Art includes 1 column color
sig of columnist.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK COLLEGE TECH _ Students at historically black colleges and
universities have less access than most other students to the
computer technology that is a key to today's cutting-edge jobs,
experts say. (Mollison, Cox Washington Bureau)
</P>
<P>
   TECH-CENTERPIECE-HDTV _ Weekly centerpiece on personal
technology, from products to trends to advancements. (Haddad,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY_ Popular column about personal computing written for
the average user. This week: Don't buy that Pentium III just yet.
(Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECHTOOLS _ Software reviews. This week: Backing up files and
programs. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCHER _ What's new on the Web. This week: Personal stories
of terror in Kosovo on the Net. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ What's new on the Web. This week: Free images on
the Net. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MEDIA _ What the tech magazines are writing about. This
week: Should you wait for Windows 2000? PC World offers some
advice. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ This column will not move today. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT _ Tech briefs on new products and developments. This
week: Kids offer their ideas on what the government should do with
tax dollars, a contest sponsored by TurboTax. (Clothier, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   POWERUSER-COLUMN _ This column will not move today. (Yandel,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WEB-DIARY _ When Pamela Ribon isn't working her day job at
Tivoli or performing with her comedy troupe, Monks Night Out, she's
exposing herself to an audience of 500 on the Net. Ribon writes
``Squishy,'' an online journal in which five days a week, she
chronicles her life in daily essays. A look at a burgeoning form of
self-expression and voyeurism, the Web diary. (Gallaga, Austin
American-Statesman). 35. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED SATURDAY.
</P>
<P>
   w/DIARY-HEATHER _ About six months ago, I created a character
named Heather Yi, who wrote a first-person account of her life at
the University of Texas and about a classmate, Gina. The fictional
diary was e-mailed to friends, but I didn't tell anyone that
Heather Yi wasn't real. After a while, interest spread and I
decided to post the entries on the Web. (Gallaga, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED SATURDAY.
</P>
</TEXT>
