<P>
   N A T I O N A L &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-PREPAREDNESS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Nobody can predict whether the Y2K bug will cripple or
inconvenience the civilized, computer-dependent world, but this
much is sure: Preparedness won't be cheap. Some opportunists have
found in the Y2K craze the chance to cash in on customers'
escalating fears. Others who are concerned about chaos spilling
into the streets in 2000 have turned their living rooms into mini
grocery stores. Driving this booming cottage industry are plenty of
people eager to buy preparedness products, even if it means a hefty
investment. By JOHN AUSTIN and JAN JARVIS. Story will move in ``a''
general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LONGHORN HERD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WINSCOTT RANCH, Texas _ On a windswept pasture of bluebonnets
and spring grasses, 16 longhorn steers are in ``spring training''
of sorts. They're being prepared to become living reminders of Fort
Worth's cattle industry, which prompted the nickname Cowtown. The
herd will make its public debut June 12 when the longhorns will be
driven from downtown to the Stockyards as part of Fort Worth's
sesquicentennial celebration. By ART CHAPMAN. Story has moved in
``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEMINARY-DIPLOMAS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Sunday school teacher Alan Askins was in
search of a better understanding of the Bible when an advertisement
for Tyndale Theological Seminary in a Christian magazine caught his
attention. Askins said he was drawn to Tyndale's evening classes
and low cost _ ideal for a husband, father of three and investment
firm manager. More important, though, Askins said, ``It lined up
with our beliefs.'' Askins, of Fort Worth, may never see the master
of arts level diploma he has worked toward for four years. State
officials contend that Tyndale is illegally awarding degrees
without approval from the state or one of three accreditation
agencies recognized by the state. By VERONICA PUENTE. Story has
moved in ``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CATHOLIC UNIVERSITIES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A Vatican effort to forge closer church ties
to Catholic universities could stifle academic freedom, impair the
ability to draw quality faculty and threaten some forms of student
grants and loans, the president of Texas' largest Catholic
university says. ``I like being a Catholic school, but from where I
sit, if some of these proposals are approved, it would be very
problematic for us,'' said the Rev. John Moder, president of the
4,100-student St. Mary's University in San Antonio. Moder is one of
several Catholic university presidents _ including those from Notre
Dame, Fordham and Boston College _ who are concerned about
proposals made in a draft document scheduled to be voted on this
fall by U.S. Catholic bishops. It would affect 236 U.S. Catholic
universities. By JIM JONES. Story has moved in ``a'' general news
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   T E X A S &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RESTORED COURTHOUSE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HILLSBORO, Texas _ When the Hill County Courthouse burned on
Jan. 1, 1993, a few distraught residents wondered whether the
historic structure should be torn down. After all, the clock tower
had fallen to the courthouse's ground floor and there were
questions about whether the limestone exterior was structurally
sound. But that vocal minority was quickly drowned out. For most
residents, giving up on the old building was unthinkable. Now the
lovingly restored building is about reopen. By BILL HANNA. Story
will move in ``n'' regional category for Texas points only. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   L I F E S T Y L E &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LURE OF MECCA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Five times a day for most of his 38 years, Hasan
Hasan-Ali has knelt and prayed toward Mecca. When he was a child
and a teen in Kuwait, this receptacle of prayer was a city in a
neighboring country to the southwest _ the most holy city of the
Islamic faith and the dwelling place of the ``House of God.'' When
he became a student and later an engineer in Texas, Mecca, though
geographically farther than before, remained central to his daily
thoughts, his rituals, his faith. Last month, for the first time,
Hasan-Ali beheld Mecca. By TARA DOOLEY. Story has moved in ``l''
lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAR SEAT WARS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ The child car seat: at one point or another, the bane
of every parent's existence. Bulky, inconvenient, stinky, the car
seat is nonetheless an essential accouterment of child-rearing.
After all, it saves lives. But the road to car-seat satisfaction is
no easy journey. In fact, some families never achieve the spiritual
plane of car-seat contentment. By LIZ STEVENS. Story will move in
``l'' lifestyle category. (Accompanied by CAR SEAT-FACTS and CAR
SEAT-BEST.) &QL; 
