<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4729 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-MACEDONIA-042     04-19 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-MACEDONIA-0420-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LETTER FROM MACEDONIA: WANTED BY NO ONE -- REFUGEES STRUGGLE TO
FREEDOM
 &HT;    With Photo mug of Holmes.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TANUSHEVCI, Macedonia _ In the frigid highlands on the
Yugoslavia-Macedonia border, they appeared first as tiny specks in
the distance, almost invisible against a backdrop of high mountains
on one side and the rising smoke of fires in the villages of Kosovo
far away in the valley below.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, they emerged Monday from this surreal panorama, soon
identifiable as a line of weary refugees. The group of nine came on
foot, adults, children and a baby being carried by his mother on
horseback.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians from Kosovo, the Hajdari family found freedom.
But it was a rude welcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Fleeing the terrifying squads of Serb fighters who on Thursday
emptied their village of Lubishte in Kosovo, they ran headlong into
a country, Macedonia, that doesn't want them, either.
</P>
<P>
   The Hajdari family arrived on Friday morning in these remote,
mile-high mountains, among 130 refugees from their village. They
said they soon found themselves being forced at gunpoint back
toward Kosovo by Macedonian troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, 'We'll send you back to the Serbs. Better that they
shoot you than we shoot you,''' recalled Rakip Hajdari, 49, a
farmer who fled with his family.
</P>
<P>
   The massive surge of refugees from Kosovo into Macedonia and
Albania came to an abrupt and alarming halt Sunday night.
Yugoslavia sealed its southern borders early Monday. Macedonia,
fearful that the ethnic Albanians will upset the social and
economic balance here, has been an unwilling host since wave after
wave starting four weeks ago has swelled the numbers here to more
than 130,000.
</P>
<P>
   With the official border crossings closed, small groups of
international journalists set out Monday to remote border areas on
a hunch that refugees would be seeking a route on the footpaths,
not the main roads.
</P>
<P>
   We found what we had come to see -- a group of haggard people on
the move through rough terrain, fleeing the Serbs with heroic will
and desperate ingenuity given the closing of main border points.
</P>
<P>
   What we did not expect were tales from the refugees that the
Macedonian forces were equally as menacing as the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia maintains an official policy as a reluctant host. At
the border, its reputation is far worse.
</P>
<P>
   The Hajdari family said they and hundreds of others thought that
they had found a safe haven in the remote Macedonian border village
of Malina Maala, only to be beaten and harassed by Macedonian
troops.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,500 refugees who streamed into Malina Maala over the
weekend were taken in by local ethnic Albanian families and allowed
to stay. They will be relocated to refugee camps on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hajdari family and scores more were forced out of the
village, they said, by Macedonian police operating with impunity,
swinging gun butts and rubber truncheons.
</P>
<P>
   This border area is thoroughly remote, without the prying eyes
of the United Nations or NATO or other international groups in
Macedonia to look out for the welfare of the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Ostensibly, the Macedonian government maintains its new policy
is to keep the frontier off limits to outsiders and thus prevent
the Kosovo Liberation Army, or KLA, from conducting guerrilla
operations from Macedonian territory.
</P>
<P>
   Others fear it is to prevent the world from learning of the
alleged brutality that may have taken place in these mountains in
recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the United Nations and the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), were denied entry to the
area by Macedonia border guards on Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
   We were, too. Police stopped our car, checked our press
credentials and briefly confiscated the camera of a photojournalist
in our small group. They said we lacked authority to be in the
border area and turned us back.
</P>
<P>
   That's when we caught sight of the Hajdari family as they ended
their three-hour trek up a steep ravine from the small Macedonian
village that had been harboring them. By pre-arrangement, a
dilapidated van was waiting to take them to a host family in
Skopje, Macedonia's capital, only 20 miles to the southeast, but a
two-hour drive.
</P>
<P>
   Their story of brutality at the hands of the Macedonians is one
I and other international correspondents have heard before from
refugees. The allegations are virtually impossible to confirm.
Officially, Macedonian authorities deny wrongdoing and say they are
merely seeking to maintain order in a desperately difficult
situation.
</P>
<P>
   But international aid workers fear that there is a lingering and
potentially dangerous pro-Serb sentiment among the security forces
in this former Yugoslav republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are just Serbs in a different uniform,'' said an
observer for the OSCE.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
