NYT-04-19-99 1823EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4730 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCIENCE-EDUCATION-HNS     04-19 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-EDUCATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHERS WORRY ABOUT QUALITY OF SCIENCE EDUCATION, SURVEY SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A new survey of science teachers shows deep
misgivings about how well American youngsters are learning the
subject, a level of concern that former astronaut Mae Jemison
characterized as a ``wakeup call'' alerting the nation to lagging
student achievement.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 1,712 elementary, middle and high school teachers
found that about half have little confidence in the quality of the
science programs they teach. The figure is 51 percent among
elementary school teachers and 48 percent among their high school
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 2 percent of elementary and middle school teachers
and 4 percent of high school teachers reported being ``very
confident'' about the quality of what they teach.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was sponsored by the Bayer Corporation, based in
Germany, and the National Science Teachers Association. It was
released Monday in New Haven, Conn., at a Bayer-sponsored
conference on ways to improve science education and recruit more
scientists as classroom volunteers and mentors.
</P>
<P>
   Jemison, the conference's keynote speaker, said in a phone
interview that the survey shows ``what science teachers actually
think about how we teach science.'' The message, she added, is that
``science teachers think that U.S. students do have a performance
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Jemison, 42, was the first African-American woman in orbit,
soaring into the heavens aboard the space shuttle Endeavour in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   A physician who served in the Peace Corps in Africa and studied
engineering, she now divides her time between teaching
environmental studies at Dartmouth College in Hanover, N.H., and
her consulting company _ the Jemison Group Inc. _ in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Jemison also runs ``The Earth We Share,'' a camp to enrich
scientific knowledge of 12-to-16-year-old students as well as
science teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The findings dovetail with longstanding concern among educators
over what many of them describe as the low state of achievement in
science among American students. That concern goes back to the
1950s when Congress pumped millions into science education after
the Soviet Union was first in space with the 1957 launching of its
Sputnik satellite.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, an international science test administered to
500,000 students in 41 nations showed that while American fourth
graders compared favorably with their peers overseas, eighth
graders did less well and 12th graders fell significantly below the
international average. The test, the Third International
Mathematics and Science Study (TIMSS), was given during the
1994-1995 school year.
</P>
<P>
   The TIMSS test evoked a huge controversy among educators, with
many calling it an invalid ``apples-to-oranges'' comparison. But
Jemison said the new survey of science educators validates the
TIMSS findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a wakeup call,'' she said. ``It is saying we can't
excuse (low science achievement) and say, `Oh, TIMSS doesn't
reflect reality.' The teachers think it reflects how well their
students work or do not work.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey results also contrast the high value the teachers
place on science education and what they perceive as the low value
the public attaches to it. In the survey, 68 percent say basic
science education is indispensable, but only 2 percent said they
think the general public also views it that way.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The United States, Jemison said, doesn't ``need a million
nuclear physicists, but we do need 100 million folks who are able
to read an article in the newspaper about a science subject and
understand, for example, how to vote on the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Improving science education means enlisting more scientists as
mentors and role models for students, particularly girls and
minorities, Jemison said.
</P>
<P>
   She added that teachers should follow guidelines that encourage
``hands-on'' science and open-ended experimentation ``the way
scientists do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have criticized what many of them call ``cookbook''
experiments, in which students conduct a predictable, recipe-like
scientific test and promptly forget the results.
</P>
<P>
   Given a thought-provoking challenge, ``children will use their
own motivation and creativity,'' Jemison said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 1824EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
