<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ROCKFORD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUESDAY'S `ROCKFORD' CLOSES THE FILE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fair warning, folks. After Tuesday you can pretty much stick a
fork in Jim Rockford. Methinks he's done.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, he was done about two years ago, but CBS has kept the
last ``Rockford Files'' movie on ice since 1997, not wanting to
clutter the airwaves with too many crime solvers. What with
``Martial Law'' and ``Nash Bridges'' and those ``Sons of Thunder''
guys, CBS takes a bigger bite out of crime each week than McGruff
after he's missed a doggie snack.
</P>
<P>
   Rockford re-emerges Tuesday night and, aside from some obviously
creaky joints, he still has the magic that James Garner gave him 25
years ago. The easygoing charm, the big heart, the impatience with
authority are all there _ as comfortable as that old trailer by the
beach, as predictable as Angel Martin's next dodge.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, Angel has only a peripheral presence tonight. Stuart
Margolin, who parlayed the sniveling, self-pitying scammer into two
Emmy Awards in 1979 and '80, spent more hours behind the camera
this time, directing his colleagues in what is billed as the last
of the ``Rockford'' oeuvre.
</P>
<P>
   If so, Margolin and pals went out shouting. Tuesday's film, the
eighth since the series ended nearly 20 years ago, is titled ``If
It Bleeds ... It Leads,'' and it's an all-cannons broadside at the
media's treatment of people who've been charged with serious crimes
but not convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Though ham-fisted in places and unnecessarily preachy at the
end, it's an effective treatment that will find a receptive
audience among a media-wary public and might even get a few
journalists to think about how they do what they do.
</P>
<P>
   With or without a parable, it's always good to see Rockford
again. And Angel and Beth (Gretchen Corbett) and Becker (Joe
Santos), too. Even Lieutenant Diehl (Tom Atkins), still dumber than
a bucket of bolts. ``The Rockford Files'' was always one of the
best things to emerge from the prolific Stephen J. Cannell
production mill. Smarter than most dramas of the late '70s, it also
had one of those perfectly meshed casts that producers dream about
but rarely assemble.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Noah Beery Jr., who died in 1994, the whole gang is
back tonight, augmented crisply by Rita Moreno, who reprises the
role of ex-prostitute Rita Capkovic for which she won an Emmy in
1978. The always solid Hal Linden plays Rita's husband, Ernie, a
dedicated schoolteacher charged with committing a succession of
rapes.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie's guilt or innocence isn't immediately clear, but even
more compelling than the whodunit is a final act that raises
tonight's film above the middling morass of TV movies. If
``Rockford'' is indeed done, it's especially nice that its swan
song was well done.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockford Files: If It Bleeds ... It Leads. Two-hour TV movie
reprising the character of private investigator Jim Rockford.
Starring James Garner, Joe Santos, Gretchen Corbett, Tom Atkins,
Stuart Margolin, Rita Moreno and Hal Linden. Tonight on CBS.
Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
