<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4740 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUNNINGHAM-NOVEL-ART-     04-19 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUNNINGHAM-NOVEL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WRITER HAUNTED BY VIRGINIA WOOLF 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Michael Cunningham was a sophomore in high
school in Pasadena, Calif., he knew hardly anything about world
literature. His cultural life centered on popular music, and he
wrote papers about Bob Dylan's lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   One day, trying to impress a sophisticated young woman in the
senior class, he spoke admiringly about the poetry of Leonard
Cohen. As he recalled in a recent interview, ``She took a deep drag
of her Marlboro and said, `Well, yes, but I wonder if you've ever
heard of T.S. Eliot or Virginia Woolf.'''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of making a joke about liking their record albums, he
went to the school library, where he found no Eliot and only one
Woolf, ``Mrs. Dalloway.'' He read it and was overwhelmed:
``Something about what she was doing in terms of trying to find the
profundity in the most outwardly ordinary experience registered
with me even as a not especially precocious 15-year-old, and it has
stayed with me ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   If the library had had a copy of ``The Waste Land,'' his life
might have gone in a different direction.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 31 years later, Cunningham's novel ``The Hours,'' an
impressionistic response to ``Mrs. Dalloway,'' has been awarded the
Pulitzer Prize for fiction. It was this year's surprise winner over
the other finalists, Russell Banks' ``Cloudsplitter'' and Barbara
Kingsolver's ``Poisonwood Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham was among those most surprised. He was convinced that
Banks would win for his ``wonderful book, a sprawling American
historical saga that was squarely in the Pulitzer tradition.''
Cunningham wondered what chance his ``dark, odd book'' could have.
</P>
<P>
   On the afternoon the Pulitzers were to be announced, he left his
apartment in Manhattan to have lunch with two friends. About five
minutes after 3, he decided to see if he had any telephone
messages. The first was from a reporter, the second from Jonathan
Galassi, his editor at Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, both offering
congratulations.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham started to cry. ``It's slightly embarrassing, but
it's true,'' he said. ``It seemed impossible that this particular
book had been recognized like that.''
</P>
<P>
   His friends looked at him, he said, and they cried. Then he
telephoned his companion, Ken Corbett, who is a clinical
psychologist, and ``everybody else I ever met.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days later when he arrived for a luncheon interview, a
letter from the Pulitzer committee forwarded by his publisher was
waiting for him on the table. For a moment, he considered the
possibility that the letter would inform him that a mistake had
been made. It was of course congratulatory: The letter would be
sent on to his mother in California.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, 46, said he considered ``The Hours'' his ``strongest
book by far'' and ``an act of veneration'' for the original, which
is a day in the life of an Englishwoman. It is his fourth published
novel, and it was a long time in coming.
</P>
<P>
   While studying at Stanford University in the early 1970s, he
thought about becoming a painter; then he took a course in
literature and began writing short stories. After graduation he
wandered around the West for several years, supporting himself by
tending bar while he started, and discarded, novels.
</P>
<P>
   Finally he was accepted at the University of Iowa's writers'
workshop and published stories in The Atlantic Monthly and other
magazines. Then he found himself drifting back into his old bad
habits, tending bar and not finishing novels.
</P>
<P>
   His first book, ``Golden States,'' written hurriedly to beat his
self-imposed deadline of his 30th birthday, was ``a journeyman
effort,'' he said. He moved to New York and was hired as a
secretary at Carnegie Corp., where he worked his way up to a
position writing annual reports and news releases.
</P>
<P>
   When ``A Home at the End of the World,'' a novel about a
friendship of two men and a woman, was published in 1990, he quit
his job. That book was followed five years later by ``Flesh and
Blood,'' a chronicle of three generations of a Greek-American
family. Both books received favorable reviews and sold reasonably
well. The two are, by his own description, ``capacious, traditional
narratives that you could walk right into, unhindered.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he decided to try something different and experimental. His
original idea was to write a modern-day version of ``Mrs.
Dalloway,'' set in New York, with a 52-year-old gay man as the
protagonist, a kind of Dalloway, with the AIDS epidemic as a
backdrop for the story.
</P>
<P>
   After writing about 100 pages and discovering contemporary
parallels for all the characters and events in the Woolf novel, he
realized ``it was just a parlor trick and not a sufficient idea for
a novel,'' he said. ``The world didn't need my take on a great book
_ it already had the original.''
</P>
<P>
   At first he thought about dropping the project, but then he
decided to relax and play around with it. What had at first been
``schematic and precious'' became improvisational, aiming for what
he called ``the loose, riffish quality of `Mrs. Dalloway.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As he said, ``I wanted my book to have its own life, not to be
just an annex to Woolf's.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end it became a triptych, about Clarissa Vaughan, a book
editor living today in New York's Greenwich Village; Laura Brown, a
depressed housewife in Los Angeles reading ``Mrs. Dalloway'' in
1929, and Woolf herself in a suburb of London in 1923.
</P>
<P>
   As with ``Mrs. Dalloway,'' but tripled, events take place on a
single day in the life of each of the women, ``one of whom, not
Woolf, is unambiguously a lesbian,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Each story resonates within the others. Some moments in ``Mrs.
Dalloway'' reappear in ``The Hours'' (which was also the working
title for Woolf's book). Both novels lead to a climactic party, in
each case there is a suicide, and Clarissa is herself a version of
the original title character.
</P>
<P>
   But there are substantial differences between the books. In the
Cunningham book, characters are merged, and they evoke distant
memories of their role models. The writing style, though influenced
by Woolf, is definitely his own.
</P>
<P>
   It is certainly not necessary to know ``Mrs. Dalloway'' to
appreciate ``The Hours,'' but as Michael Wood wrote in The New York
Times Book Review, the connections between the two are ``so rich
and subtle and offbeat that not to read `Mrs. Dalloway' after we've
read `The Hours' seems like a horrible denial of a readily
available pleasure _ as if we were to leave a concert just when the
variations were getting interesting.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham acknowledged the possibility that Laura's reading of
``Mrs. Dalloway'' ``has a subtle but considerable effect on her
life, both in terms of the comfort she receives in reading it and
something darker, a certain sense of Virginia Woolf as a dark angel
who has walked into death ahead of her.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the major challenges of writing the book was to deal with
Woolf as a fictional character, to imagine a day in her life.
Cunningham said that in preparation he read, or reread, her novels,
stories, letters and diaries as well as several biographies, and
then put them all aside to write in his own voice.
</P>
<P>
   At various points in his book, however, he quotes from ``Mrs.
Dalloway,'' and from Woolf herself. Her suicide note appears at the
beginning, and a line from it (``I don't think two people could
have been happier than we've been'') is repeated before the suicide
of one of the characters in ``The Hours.'' That choice he
attributes to the ``ghost of Virginia Woolf, it's a literal
haunting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pulitzer Prize has not drastically changed the author's
life. He is finishing an original screenplay and is thinking about
his next novel, and he continues to teach writing at Columbia
University.
</P>
<P>
   But the publisher printed more copies of ``The Hours,'' and the
book suddenly leaped to the top of Amazon.com's best-seller list,
ahead of Stephen King. Cunningham said he also heard that because
of his book, sales of ``Mrs. Dalloway'' had increased. Both novels
are short, his a few pages longer. They would, he said, ``make a
nice boxed set.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 1833EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4756 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOCKNEY-EXHIBITS-905&AMP;     04-19 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOCKNEY-EXHIBITS-905&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: A MASTER OF THE TREND OF THE DAY, A SLAVE TO
NONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOHN RUSSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Two of the most coveted spaces in the Parisian museum
world are being given over to a 61-year-old English artist whom few
people have known quite what to make of. His name is David Hockney.
</P>
<P>
   On the Rue St.-Merri, in the south gallery of the otherwise
closed Pompidou Center, Hockney has a retrospective exhibition of
164 paintings and photocollages (many of them very large) dated
from 1962 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by Didier Ottinger of the Musee National d'Art
Moderne, it comes with a hefty catalog in which French, German and
English contributors take it in turn to assess a vast body of work
that has been springing surprises, year by year, since January
1960. At the Musee Picasso there is ``David Hockney: Dialogue with
Picasso.''
</P>
<P>
   Between them, the two shows act as a corrective to anyone who
has a one-focus, one-period, one-medium, one-ambition idea of David
Hockney. There is the work that everyone knows: the repertory
company of favorite sitters, the swimming pools (some in
California, others in Connecticut), the panoramic Los Angeles
interiors and the vertiginous up-and-down and in-and-out of the
roads that so often lead up to them.
</P>
<P>
   But there is not one David Hockney. Without ever flaunting it,
he is a true citizen of the world. He has traveled, read, studied
and looked. Between 1973 and 1975, for instance, he spent a lot of
time in Paris. Echoes of France recur throughout his career. When
we look at his deft and affectionate etching of Gustave Flaubert,
for instance, or note what he got from reading Henri Bergson on
memory, or study his monumental photocollage of the Place
Furstenberg in Paris, we know that he knows France from the inside.
</P>
<P>
   When he was living in Paris, he was already being talked about
and written about. In 1975 a then-young French critic, Marc
Fumaroli, who is now an influential member of the Academie
Francaise, got David Hockney exactly right.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played his part,'' Fumaroli wrote at that time, ``in the
empty-headed circles that his allies and protectors frequented. But
he brought to them the graces of a young person who had all the
gifts. Both as Narcissus and as dandy, he had an innate feeling for
what was the trend of the day. But he never got stuck with it.
Though always ready with the right word, he never lost either his
catlike independence or his colossal capacity for work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sang for his supper,'' Fumaroli went on, ``and his gifts as
an actor served him well. But he was neither the prisoner nor the
subordinate of his troupe. He was all the more `in' because he had
made up his mind to stay `out.' What more could be asked of a great
talent at that time?''
</P>
<P>
   Hockney cannot be pinned down. No sooner did his paintings of
boys in the shower take rank as the epitome of early 1960s camp
than he turned to what he called the ``marriage of styles'' as the
motor force in paintings that were large, grand and contradictory
in their idioms.
</P>
<P>
   Those first major American paintings, nobly shown in the
Pompidou, had nothing to do with the laid-back life of Los Angeles.
``Iowa'' (1964), ``Arizona'' (1964) and ``Rocky Mountains and Tired
Indians'' (1965) are monumental in scale.
</P>
<P>
   Inch by inch they are endlessly beguiling to look at. There is
something absolutely right about the imminent electric storms in
``Iowa,'' the minutely defined geological striations in ``Arizona''
and the presence of an up-to-the-minute Knoll chair in the ancient
uncluttered landscape of ``Rocky Mountains and Tired Indians.'' One
and all keep us alert.
</P>
<P>
   As Philippe Starck says in the catalog, the visual elements in
these paintings take us on a long march through the history of art,
one that leads from ancient Egypt to minimal art. Nor can we miss
the fact that the farm buildings in ``Iowa'' hark back to Cezanne's
preoccupation with the cylinder and the cone.
</P>
<P>
   In the Musee Picasso on the Rue de Thorigny, the dialogue with
Picasso is as much a matter of ideas as of actions, and the tone of
Hockney's contributions is not awestruck but conversational.
</P>
<P>
   He first took fire from Picasso in the summer of 1960, when
there was a large Picasso retrospective in London. The lesson was a
general one: that every option should be acted upon. ``There was no
style and no technique that Picasso could not master,'' Hockney
said. ``What was the point of settling down in one little corner of
art and just painting on it over and over?''
</P>
<P>
   Hockney the stage-designer is ideally represented in the Picasso
Museum by the adorable frivolity of his designs for Francis
Poulenc's opera ``Les Mamelles de Tiresias.'' (One of them is
reproduced in miniature, and rare is the visitor who doesn't crack
a smile.)
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the show is a painting dated 1987 that shows how
Hockney can cut deep when the occasion calls for it. One of the
great moments in all opera falls near the end of Wagner's ``Tristan
und Isolde,'' when the dying Tristan hears the approach of Isolde.
``Now I hear the light!'' he cries out with full voice, and in
Hockney's painting we see that in close-up, unforgettably.
</P>
<P>
   For Tristan at that moment, hearing was seeing, and Hockney
brought something rough and raw to the portrayal of his huge
stricken head. Something of that roughness and rawness can be
traced to Picasso's late figure paintings, in which he strove to go
beyond the previous limits of expression in figure painting.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the Pompidou show, Hockney rides high on the limitless
complication and the brash, aggressive color of his high-flying
Californian landscapes of the 1990s. (The paint in those pictures,
as in the ones done last year in his native Yorkshire, does not so
much portray the landscape as couple with it.)
</P>
<P>
   At the Picasso Museum, the plain white spaces and the vibration
of Picasso's own presence encourage a more intimate scale and an
epigrammatic demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   As Hockney sees it, what had been called ``distortion'' in many
of Picasso's portraits of Marie-Therese Walter in 1934 was simply
the plain fact of what we see when we get up very close to another
person and patrol that person's face. At such times, the cubist
vision is the true one and the standard, long-authenticated image
of another human being makes no sense.
</P>
<P>
   Hockney had more than once painted his friend Christopher
Isherwood in a traditional pose, with spectacles gleaming. But in
1984, when he painted ``Christopher Without His Glasses,'' he
toured the familiar head as if he were negotiating Mulholland Drive
on the way to his studio.
</P>
<P>
   Isherwood's features were ``distorted,'' with eyes and nose and
forehead going every which way, but those dislocations rang true.
This was the real Christopher, alive and complete, just as the real
Hockney is alive, if not quite complete, in these two admirably
thought-through exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   The Pompidou show can be seen through April 26, and the one at
the Picasso Museum through May 3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
