<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMDEX-0420-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WINDOWS 98 GETTING HOME COMPUTER NETWORK FEATURE
 &HT;    Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO --- Windows 98, whose introduction at last year's
Comdex/Windows World conference carried some presentation bugs, is
getting an upgrade that includes a home computer networking
feature.
</P>
<P>
   Internet Connection Sharing will allow each user on a network to
share a single Internet link. It is aimed primarily at households
with multiple PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Intel (CQ) announced a network product aimed
at consumers. The chipmaker estimated about 18 million households
have more than one computer, and 28 million will be in that
category by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The Windows 98 upgrade also will include Internet Explorer 5, an
</P>
<P>
   integrated browser.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't Windows 98 that was most on the mind this year of
Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates. It was Windows 2000. And unlike last
year, the viewing screen used by Gates to explain the software
worked. Last year, during Gates' presentation, the audience found
itself staring
</P>
<P>
   at a blank screen.
</P>
<P>
   That embarrassing mishap was on Gates' mind Monday when he
demonstrated an early version of Windows 2000, Microsoft's
</P>
<P>
   business-oriented operating system for personal computers and
network servers.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, when the same Gates aide who in 1998 plugged in
the same scanning device to capture the same photo, the demo came
off without a hitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've asked a lot of people in the last year what happened to
that guy,'' Gates joked.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Microsoft has shipped more than 28 million copies of
Windows 98, many of them installed by computer manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft officials said the company plans to ship two more
versions of Windows 98. The first one, they said, is to go out this
fall and the
</P>
<P>
   next one, to be dubbed ``Second Edition,'' some time next year.
</P>
<P>
   But current Windows 98 users, they said, may not need to buy
either of the new versions. Users can download the new features for
free from the company's Windows update site on the Internet or
order an upgrade CD for $19.95.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Gates said that late this month Microsoft will ship
the third and final test version of Windows 2000 to some 500,000
first-wave customers. This heavy-duty operating system will
eventually replace Windows NT 4.0 and compete with UNIX-based
servers.
</P>
<P>
   Three versions of the last test will be shipped: Windows 2000
Professional, intended for individual users of client servers;
Windows 2000 Server, and Advanced Server. The later two versions
are meant
</P>
<P>
   to run on networks that can support multiple machines.
</P>
<P>
   Gates called Windows 2000 ''the biggest investment we ever made
in a single piece of software.'' He said the Windows 2000 test will
be supported by more than 20 computer makers, 100,000 Microsoft
distribution partners and 140,000 developers.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Allchin, senior vice president of Microsoft's business and
enterprise division, said Windows 2000 will offer major
improvements in reliability and leading-edge networking services.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft expects to ship Windows 2000 in final form by October.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
