<HEADER>
A4761 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-19 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSTESS WITH THE MOSTEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Originally First Lady Hillary Clinton was picked on
for being bossy, brassy and too brainy.
</P>
<P>
   Now she's being scorched for planning to oversee a book about
entertaining at the White House in between touring the tragic
Balkans and New York state, both territories foreign to her.
</P>
<P>
   The book is a subject described by her critics as frivolous and
appropriate only for homebodies with not much else to do. And
certainly not a serious topic for a human rights spokeswoman with
global influence and designs on the U.S. Senate seat from New York.
</P>
<P>
   But this political put-down of official presidential social life
_ with its world-class guests, diplomatic demands, expectations of
elegance and public symbolism of national greatness _ is something
new.
</P>
<P>
   The last I heard, invitations to the White House were greatly
coveted and social events there a product of monumental, detailed
planning which even Martha Stewart could not match. Such elaborate
occasions do not happen by accident. They take work. And the first
lady, no matter her name, inclination or staff size, is ultimately
held responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Yet suddenly the first couple is supposed to demolish gracious
White House traditions and pretend that hospitality consists of
serving fish and chips on paper plates?
</P>
<P>
   Is the idea that no president's wife can be taken seriously if
she pampers her guests? Nancy Reagan would surely take justifiable
umbrage at that!
</P>
<P>
   Or is Hillary Clinton expected to get on a horse and ride out
with the boys to round up some cattle so she can ignore table
settings and write about macho things like heating soup in a can
over a sputtering outdoor campfire?
</P>
<P>
   I immediately heard all this anti-Hillary bilge from female
friends when it was announced that Simon &AMP; Schuster would publish a
book next fall overseen by the first lady, to be called ``An
Invitation to the White House.'' (Males didn't seem to care one way
or the other.) The women recoiled at the concept that Hillary
Clinton was holding forth as a hostess, but they were outraged for
vastly different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Some thought she was demeaning her own gravitas and potential
political future by donning the symbolic apron that female
politicians still fight so hard to avoid. Some thought she was
putting on airs because the Clinton White House has no class, a
refrain reflected in some Washington gossip that Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr is infinitely preferable socially. Some
thought she simply had better things to do, like saving the world.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate jab was delivered by popular New York Times
columnist Maureen Dowd, fresh from winning a Pulitzer Prize. Dowd
declared that ``when she stoops to playing wifey ... it comes
across as counterfeit.'' Because Hillary Clinton does not have a
happy home life, Dowd opined, she is creating a ``Potemkin hearth''
that is ``unsettling and unentertaining.''
</P>
<P>
   Good writing. But since when does producing a book about one of
your most visible public responsibilities deteriorate into playing
wifey? White House entertaining has a political, public and
psychological purpose that is essential to presidential leadership
and the very concept of governing.
</P>
<P>
   These social events are not casual frat-house bashes. This work
is serious signal-sending, network-building and fence-mending. In
the political scheme of things, it matters that it is done, and
done well.
</P>
<P>
   Dolley Madison demonstrated that in the nation's infancy by
presiding over a vigorous social life before and after the War of
1812 with the British. Her parties have gone down in history as a
necessary complement to the dour President James Madison's grip on
official life.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, confusion between the private lives of
presidential couples and their official duties is rampant these
days in the nation's capital, for understandable reasons. Both
President and Mrs. Clinton have a problem convincing voters that
they are capable of carrying on professionally with dispassionate
skill despite the emotional chaos between them.
</P>
<P>
   But it is unrealistic to assume that Hillary Clinton _ or any
first lady for that matter _ is or should be a one-dimensional
figure. Her personality has many facets and she fills many roles,
from public policy adviser to hostess with the mostest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 1843EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
