<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0333 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4762 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HAWKS20-COX     04-19 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks prepare for playoffs on upswing
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ A week ago, the Hawks were sagging. Losers of four
straight. As likely to slip to the bottom of the NBA playoff pool _
or even out _ as they were to get a home-court seed for the first
round.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, their future is bright again. Thank Steve Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smitty makes the offense go,'' Mookie Blaylock said.
</P>
<P>
   Don't underestimate the significance of that statement when a
team has such a difficult time scoring. Not only did he get 20
points in his comeback game from injury Friday against Orlando, he
set up Blaylock for 30 on a lovely 12-for-20 shooting night.
</P>
<P>
   As the Hawks increasingly run their offense through Smith, it
appears all _ well, almost all _ things are possible when they are
healthy. Beset by colds and flu and injuries to Smith, Alan
Henderson and LaPhonso Ellis, who is out for the season, they have
been at least one key player short at almost every turn the past
month.
</P>
<P>
   No contender in the Eastern Conference is a stranger to such
hardship. See the Pacers (Derrick McKey), the Magic (Bo Outlaw),
the Heat (Voshon Lenard and Jamal Mashburn), the Knicks (Patrick
Ewing), the Cavaliers (Zydrunas Ilgauskas) the Pistons (Christian
Laettner). All must muddle through the loss of players.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend past shows how fragile this season is. Atlanta,
mired in sixth place, jumped two spots by beating Boston and
Orlando as the Pacers, the Pistons, the Heat, the Knicks and the
Bucks all suffered stunning setbacks. Today, the Hawks are a full
game better than Detroit, 1 1/2 up on Milwaukee, and they must
remain fourth or better to gain home-court advantage in the first
round. The two closest pursuers hold the tie-breaker edge if they
finish even with the Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   The best part of this stretch run, Hawks coach Lenny Wilkens
said, is that he's getting his players back healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten some nice play out of our bench,'' he said. ``But
when you start changing roles, you create confusion. Guys have to
readjust. What I want going down the stretch is to have each of
them where he belongs and back in a routine because there's very
little turnaround time this year.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Hawks will have only two or three days between
their final regular season game and playoff opener. That they will
play teams they know very well will mitigate that circumstance, but
history shows the post-season is a different game. For recent
evidence, look to last spring's four-game ouster by Charlotte, a
team the Hawks beat six times during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Good health is not the only big plus for this team. There is the
play of Dikembe Mutombo, who has dominated inside, and Grant Long,
who has stepped in twice as a starter for Henderson and acquitted
himself well. A three-day weekend and a relatively light closing
schedule would do wonders for Smith's healing left knee and his
always balky right knee. Ty Corbin and Blaylock have had a chance
to get over their cold and flu problems.
</P>
<P>
   Add to the list of positives the recent play of second-year
forward Chris Crawford, who shot 13-for-21 in games against two
touted rookies, Boston's Paul Pierce and Orlando's rugged Matt
Harpring. The Hawks even got two useful performances from troubled
young guard Ed Gray.
</P>
<P>
   But there are trouble spots that include point guard, where
Blaylock's erratic shooting reflects a huge expenditure of energy
in every game. When Blaylock is neither active nor in rhythm, the
Hawks need a lift from Anthony Johnson. But the young player's
offense has collapsed as well. Over the last nine games, Johnson
has shot 8-for-38. This stretch coincides with the aftermath of his
on-court blow up with teammate Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Wilkens has shown so little confidence in rookie
Roshown McLeod that he left Crawford on the court until he fouled
out against Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks can work around these problems because having Smith in
the lineup means Corbin can swing between big guard and small
forward, giving help where needed. With nine games left in 17 days,
a relatively light pace in this compact season, Blaylock gets his
rest. Long will bring his energy from the bench when Henderson
returns from an injury, perhaps as early as Thursday against
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at this picture, Wilkens says, ``I'm optimistic.'' And
although he is never less than that, he may have good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
