<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4763 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DRAFT-RECAP-COX     04-19 2897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-RECAP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A team-by-team examination of the NFL draft
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writer Len Pasquarelli
analyzes how each team fared in the weekend's NFL draft:
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Cardinals
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: Filled need for speed and big hole at left tackle in
first round with WR David Boston and OT L.J. Shelton, respectively,
then made solid choices throughout. Shelton won't start
immediately, but he'll anchor line for next 10 years. Impact
player: Boston will join talented wideouts Frank Sanders and Rob
Moore. Value picks: LB Johnny Rutledge (No. 2) and CB Coby
Rhinehart (No. 6a) will break in on special teams. Reach: FB Joel
Mackovicka (No. 4) is too stiff. Grade: B+.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Falcons
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: For second year in row, player they most coveted, DE
Patrick Kerney, fell right into their laps. Maybe, to twist the
adage, design is the residue of luck. Rationale for dealing No. 1
in 2000 for TE Reggie Kelly, based on belief incumbent O.J.
Santiago will leave in two years, actually was short-sighted.
Impact player: None. Value picks: SS Johndale Carty (No. 4) might
already be better than all their young safeties, and C Todd McClure
(No. 7a) is tough, but limited, athlete. Reach: FB Jeff Paulk (No.
3). Grade: C.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore Ravens
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: Only came out of draft with four choices, and that's not
enough for team whose offense is being dismantled. CB Chris
McAlister (No. 1) has better mechanics than Champ Bailey, is
bigger, and will team with last year's No. 1, Duane Starks. Impact
player: McAlister. Value picks: SS Anthony Poindexter may be forced
to redshirt because of knee injury, but it was worth a
seventh-rounder just to get his rights, and WR Brandon Stokley (No.
4) is a steal. Reach: None, because they had few picks. Grade: C.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo Bills
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: There are few duets better than GM John Butler and
personnel director Dwight Adams, and they added solid players all
the way through the fifth round. Despite lack of size, CB Antoine
Winfield (No. 1) plays likea 6-footer. RB Shawn Bryson (No. 3) may
be better pro than Tennessee teammate WR Peerless Price (No. 2),
who doesn't have most consistent hands. Impact player: Winfield.
Value pick: TE Bobby Collins (No. 4b) was one of draft's
fastest-rising prospects in the past month. Reach: None. Grade: B-.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina Panthers
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: Still haunted by surrendering pair of first-round
choices as compensation for the '98 signing of underachieving
veteran DE Sean Gilbert. First-year coach George Seifert has lot of
holes to fill, and five choices wasn't enough. Georgia OT Chris
Terry (No. 2a) could challenge for starting left tackle job as a
rookie, but needs bulk and experience. Impact player: None. Value
pick: Only one with chance is LB Hannibal Navies (No. 4), and he
must stay healthy, play like he did at end of '98. Reach: None.
Grade: C-.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Bears
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: No team had more choices (13) and few needed wholesale
influx as much as the Bears. Director of operations Mark Hatley did
nifty job dealing down in the first round, collecting additional
picks, and still getting player he wanted in QB Cade McNown (No.
1). DT Russell Davis (No. 2b) and OG Rex Tucker (No. 3a) are tough
guys on rise, but not everyone is sold on WR D'Wayne Bates (No.
3b). Impact player: McNown. Value picks: LB Khari Samuel (No. 5b)
and RB Jerry Azumah (No. 5c) were heists. Reach: None. Grade: B+.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati Bengals
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: Give ``the Bungles'' credit for not screwing it up when
QB Akili Smith (No. 1), a player they coveted since the combine,
dropped to them. Bengals would have taken him if they had first
overall choice in draft. Landing CB Charles Fisher (No. 2) was a
must, given inability to re-sign incumbent Ashley Ambrose. Impact
players: Smith and Fisher will be starters by mid-October. Value
pick: OG Tony Coats (No. 7a) is a mammoth but developmental
blocker. Reach: Could have gotten WR Craig Yeast (No. 4) later.
Grade: C.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland Browns
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: The quality of the picks certainly doesn't match the
quantity (11), and that's a surprise given how long management
planned this draft. After signing QB Tim Couch (No. 1), the Browns
lost their heads. WR Kevin Johnson (No. 2a) and LB Rahim Abdullah
(No. 2b) both have attitude problems. CB Daylon McCutcheon (No. 3)
is small. Impact player: Couch won't have to start as rookie, but
he's the cornerstone. Value pick: SS Marquis Smith (No. 3b) and LB
Wali Rainer (No. 4). Reach: Abdullah. Grade: C-.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Cowboys
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: Owner Jerry Jones doesn't understand urgency for players
who can immediately contribute to franchise in decline. The top
choices, DE Ebenezer Ekuban (No. 1) and OT Solomon Page (No. 2),
both are formative players who need time to develop. Impact player:
None. Value pick: DE Peppi Zellner (No. 4b) is inexperienced, but
intriguing. Reach: Taking LB Dat Nguyen (No. 3), first player of
Vietnamese ancestry in NFL, was nice public relations move, but
could have gotten him a round later. Grade: D+.
</P>
<P>
   Denver Broncos
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: Except at safety and linebacker, Super Bowl champs
possess no glaring needs and weekend demonstrated they have luxury
of drafting prospects who won't be pressed into playing as rookies.
Best examples are CB Chris Watson (No. 3a), one of few big cover
players in pool but still overlooked by many teams, and DE David
Bowens (No. 5), an undersized pass-rusher. Impact player: None, but
don't need any. Value pick: OG Lennie Friedman (No. 2b) is
late-riser. Reach: WR Travis McGriff (No. 3b). Grade: A-.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit Lions
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: Coach Bobby Ross considered taking OT Aaron Gibson with
eighth overall pick, opted for LB Chris Claiborne (No. 1a), then
dealt for another choice late in first round to get Gibson, who was
still on the board. That gave him two of the 19 blue-chippers in
this draft. Masterful work, indeed. Only question is whether
Claiborne can play outside. Impact player: Gibson will start at
right tackle and maul people. Value pick: No way RB Sedrick Irvin
(No. 4) should have lasted that long. Reach: None. Grade: A.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay Packers
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: Wanted to get bigger at cornerback and did just that
with Antwan Edwards (No. 1) and Mike McKenzie (No. 3a). A third
corner, Fred Vinson (No. 2), adds some speed. Ron Wolf actually
thought about moving up for Edwards but surprisingly got him at
25th spot. DT Cletidus Hunt (No. 3b) is interesting project. Impact
player: Edwards will get chance to start as rookie. Value picks:
Pair of fifth-rounders, RB DeMond Parker and C Craig Heimburger,
were big-time bonuses. Reach: QB Aaron Brooks (No. 4a). Grade: B-.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis Colts
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: GM Bill Polian revels in doing the unexpected and trying
to stick it to so-called experts. But if RB Edgerrin James (No. 1)
falters, no one will let him forget he passed on RB Ricky Williams.
LB Mike Peterson (No. 2) could start right now, and OG Brandon
Burlsworth (No. 3) also could be in lineup by opening day. Impact
player: James seems to be bigger version of the departed Marshall
Faulk. Value pick: DE Brad Scioli (No. 5) will be situational
pass-rusher as rookie. Reach: None. Grade: B.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville Jaguars
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: After ignoring the need for a pure cover corner for
three years, Jags finally got potential starter in CB Fernando
Bryant (No. 1). After that, Tom Couglin settled into the kind of
safe, workmanlike players he prefers. Don't underestimate chances
of Georgia DT Emarlos Leroy (No. 6) to make roster as inside
run-stopper. Impact player: Bryant. Value pick: CB Dee Moronkola
(No. 7a) was second in nation in kickoff returns last year and can
play as ``nickel'' corner. Reach: CB Jason Craft (No. 5) is
undersized. Grade: C+.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Chiefs
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: Left tackle spot has been problem area for Chiefs, and
John Tait (No. 1), premier pass-blocker in draft, should improve
psyche of QB Elvis Grbac. After choice of Tait and RB Mike Cloud
(No. 2), began rolling dice on too many prospects who might turn
out to be suspects. Impact player: Tait could start in '98. Value
pick: Cloud. Reaches: LB Gary Stills (No. 3a) slipped on almost
every team's board because of knee problems. FS Larry Atkins (No.
3b) and WR Larry Parker (No. 4) had past injuries. Grade: C.
</P>
<P>
   Miami Dolphins
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: Still determined to build a running game, Jimmy Johnson
took three backs with his eight choices and hopes to hit on one of
them. Actually, he could strike gold with all three: James Johnson
(No. 2a), Rob Konrad (No. 2b) and Cecil Collins (No. 5a). Impact
player: Konrad is miscast as fullback, actually is big running back
with receiving skill. Value pick: If Collins can stay out of
trouble, and that's a big ``if,'' he will be the steal of this
decade. Reach: P Brent Bartholomew (No. 6) is free agent caliber.
Grade: C-.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Vikings
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: With one of league's best, but most unheralded scouting
staffs, Vikes annually turn in a great job by doing more with less.
This year they had two No. 1 picks and did less than ever with
them. In desperate need of a starting cornerback, Green took QB
Daunte Culpepper (No. 1) instead. Unless he can cover someone, he
won't start until 2001. Impact player: None. Value picks: TE Jim
Kleinsasser (No. 2) and CB Kenny Wright (No. 4a). Reach: DE
Dimitrius Underwood (No. 1b) didn't play a down in '98. Grade: F.
</P>
<P>
   New England Patriots
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: Ended up taking talented underachievers. Got hoodwinked
into believing Giants would take C Damien Woody (No. 1a), a player
New York wasn't even considering, and traded up to get him when he
would have fallen to them. While choice of LB Andy Katenmoyer (No.
1b) was sound, they already have terrific MLB in Ted Johnson.
Impact player: Woody will start. Value pick: SS Tony George (No. 3)
is going to be a solid contributor. Reach: QB Michael Bishop (No.
7a) is free agent type. Grade: F.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans Saints
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: One month after vowing to surrender his entire draft for
RB Ricky Williams (No. 1), coach Mike Ditka did just that. But if
Ditka thinks the Heisman winner is the a guy who can get him to the
playoffs, he must not be looking at the rest of his sorry roster.
Ditka can't get the ball to Williams the promised 30 times per game
if the Saints trail all the time. Plus if Williams' demands are as
steep as his agent claims they will be, Ditka will go ballistic.
Impact player: Williams. Value pick: None. Reach: None. Grade: C+.
</P>
<P>
   New York Giants
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: Including opening choice of OT Luke Pettigout (No. 1),
the club reached for players it could have gotten later. Pettigout
is legit first-rounder, but Giants could have dealt back to get
him. Indicative of approach was selection of a pair of running
backs, Joe Montgomery (No. 2) and Sean Bennett (No. 4), who didn't
start in '98. Impact player: If Pettigout can move to guard, he
might start. Value pick: None. Reach: Bennett was Division II star,
transferred to Northwestern and had 160 yards in '98. Grade: F.
</P>
<P>
   New York Jets
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: Made final installment, first-round pick, on
compensation package to Patriots for signing coach Bill Parcells,
so didn't have choice until 57th pick. Parcells has zero guards
with regular-season experience, so spent three of seven selection
on players at the position. It's not likely any of them will start
as rookie, although Randy Thomas (No. 2) is a mauler. Impact
player: None. Value pick: DT Jason Wiltz (No. 4) is gigantic
run-stopper, must get motivated. Reach: DE J.J. Syvrud (No. 7) free
agent type. Grade: D+.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland Raiders
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: Might look at OT Matt Stinchcomb (No. 1) as guard first,
and selection of former Georgia star gives them future standout on
shaky line. After taking Stinchcomb, they were all over the board
and might as well have been throwing darts. DE Tony Bryant (No. 2)
was much-hyped underachiever during his senior season at FSU.
Impact player: Stinchcomb. Value pick: LB Eric Barton (No. 5a) and
DE Rod Coleman (No. 5b) should be solid down the line. Reach: WR
Dameane Douglas (No. 4) lacks run after catch. Grade: C-.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia Eagles
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: Fans wanted RB Ricky Williams, but credit director of
operations Tom Modrak for realizing you build around a quarterback.
Only problem is, did they take right one? QB Donovan McNabb (No. 1)
didn't play in very sophisticated passing offense. Choices of LB
Barry Gardner (No. 2) and OG Doug Brzezinski (No. 3) were terrific.
Impact players: McNabb and Gardner. Value picks: FS Damon Moore
(No. 4b) and WR Na Brown (No. 4c) are middle-round steals. Reach:
OT John Welbourn (No. 4a) was a bit too high. Grade: B+.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh Steelers
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: As always, solid if unspectacular bounty by one of NFL's
best scouting staffs. That said, free agency defections are
starting to catch up to Steelers, who had to let a few great
prospects pass by to fill huge hole with WR Troy Edwards (No. 1).
FS Scott Shields (No. 2a) is versatile, and maybe team can get
something out of overrated tackle Kris Farris (No. 3b). Impact
player: Edwards. Value pick: LB Joey Porter (No. 3a) is Steelers
kind of edge defender. Reach: They didn't need RB Amos Zeroue (No.
3c). Grade: B-.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis Rams
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: Week that started with acquisition of RB Marshall Faulk
in trade continued to be productive for Rams. Since they can't
count on oft-injured WR Isaac Bruce, choice of WR Torry Holt (No.
1) was a terrific one, even if they passed on some super players.
CB Dre Bly (No. 2) gives team ball-hawking ``nickel'' cover man.
Impact player: Holt. Value picks: QB Joe Germaine (No. 4) will be
solid backup in NFL, and OG Cameron Spikes (No. 5) athletic in-line
player. FS Rich Coady (No. 3a) late-riser. Reach: None. Grade: B.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego Chargers
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: Getting to be a trademark for Bobby Beathard, taking
guys from small schools who don't pan out. This year it included
prospects from South Dakota State, McNeese State and North Alabama.
The guy from the big-name school, FB Jermaine Fazande of Oklahoma,
wasn't even on the draft boards of most teams. Best pick may have
been SS Jason Perry (No. 4), who will be tried at corner. Impact
player: None. Value pick: TE Steve Heiden (No. 3) has great work
ethic. Reach: Fazande and DE Adrian Dingle (No. 5). Grade: D.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco 49ers
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: In his return to the NFL, team president Bill Walsh
didn't get the quarterback he wanted but at least found some
prospects to bolster a dismantled defense. DT Reggie McGrew (No. 1)
has short arms but nice potential, and DE Chike Okeafor (No. 3)
provides some pass-rush speed. Impact player: McGrew. Value picks:
CB Anthony Parker (No. 4a) and FS Pierson Prioleau (No. 4b) both
can run and cover, and FB Terry Jackson (No. 5) is a great special
teams performer. Reach: WR Tai Streets (No. 6) has a torn Achilles.
Grade: C-.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Seahawks
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: New coach Mike Holmgren gave personnel man Randy Mueller
more clout in the draft room, and results were mixed. The Seahawks
twice traded down in the first round and missed all the
blue-chippers, but still got emerging DE Lamar King (No. 1).
Landing QB Brock Huard (No. 3), who threw the ball as well as
anyone at the combine, was grand theft. Impact player: King. Value
pick: Georgia DE Antonio Cochran (No. 4) was a player who came on
late. Reach: OT Floyd Wedderburn (No. 5a) has knee problems. Grade:
B-.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay Buccaneers
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: The streak of sagacious selections by GM Rich McKay and
coach Tony Dungy continued for another year. The Bucs succeed by
drafting productive players and don't worry so much about fitting
molds. DT Anthony McFarland (No. 1) could be super when lined up
next to Warren Sapp. And Dungy loves QB Shaun King (No. 2). Impact
player: McFarland and PK Martin Gramatica (No. 3). Value picks: No
way two seventh-rounders, RB Autry Denson and WR Darnell McDonald,
should have been available. Reach: None. Grade: B.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee Titans
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: The war room battles between coach Jeff Fisher and GM
Floyd Reese became a moot point when DE Jevon Kearse (No. 1)
unexpectedly fell to the Titans. He'll provide the pass rush
Tennessee has lacked. DT John Thornton (No. 2) is an underachiever
who could become a player, if he finds some work ethic. Impact
player: Kearse, who is a defensive rookie of the year candidate.
Value picks: OG Zach Piller (No. 3) and QB Kevin Daft (No. 5).
Reach: WR Darran Hall (No. 6) is swift but has terrible hands.
Grade: C+.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Redskins
</P>
<P>
   Skinny: General manager Charley Casserly could be a lame duck if
the team is sold, so give him credit for putting the good of the
franchise in front of his own good. Moving down to collect picks
from New Orleans didn't cost him a shot at the second-best guy in
the draft, CB Champ Bailey (No. 1). Second-round OT Jon Jansen
could start quickly on a very thin line. Impact player: Bailey.
Value picks: LB Nate Stimson (No. 4) shot up the charts since
January, and PK Jeff Hall (No. 6) is very good. Reach: OT Derek
Smith (No. 5b). Grade: B.
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
