</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARSEATWARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CAR SEAT WARS: THEY'RE BULKY, BEWILDERING AND A BASIC FACT OF
LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by CAR SEAT-FACTS and CAR SEAT-BEST) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The child car seat: at one point or another, the bane of every
parent's existence. Bulky, inconvenient, stinky, the car seat is
nonetheless an essential accouterment of child-rearing. After all,
it saves lives.
</P>
<P>
   But the road to car-seat satisfaction is no easy journey. In
fact, some families never achieve the spiritual plane of car-seat
contentment: wherein a child happily remains in the seat and does
not spill, goober or otherwise despoil the fabric covering the
seat; wherein an adult can properly install the seat without
incurring some minor injury or embarrassment; wherein said seat
does not slide from one end of the vehicle's back seat to the other
during a short trip to the grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be one of my great sources of humor,'' notes Brenda
Hantsche of the car-seat phenomenon. An Arlington, Texas, mother of
six, Hantsche remembers the car seat her little brother rode in
during the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a little metal frame with a cotton piece of fabric
for the seat. And all it did was hook onto the back of the front
seat,'' Hantsche says. ``However, you didn't need an engineering
degree to figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's car seats are far more complex than those primitive
models. They come with 30-page instruction booklets containing
diagrams pointing to lap-belt guides, head-pad straps, adjuster
buttons, release handles, recline bars, tethers, yokes, side slots,
chest-clip harnesses, etc., etc.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is one for every different age and every different
weight,'' complains Loraine Coleman, mom of 3-year-old Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a terrible pain,'' admits Rick Paschall, dad to
3-year-old Conner.
</P>
<P>
   ``They smell up your car,'' claims Julie Wende, 6-year-old
Joey's mom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Along with safety,'' Hantsche adds, ``comes a lot of
frustration and confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Tabitha Williams is pregnant with her first child and, today,
fighting her inaugural battle with a child car seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you do this?'' she asks, struggling to attach a metal
clasp to a blue Buick Park Avenue seat belt. ``Is it that way?''
</P>
<P>
   As part of her prenatal care at John Peter Smith Hospital in
Fort Worth, Williams is attending a 1 1/2-hour class on car-seat
safety. It is her turn to demonstrate proper installation of a car
seat using the demo model at the front of the classroom. It is not
going smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   Williams tries for a few more seconds before instructor Kathy
Owens jumps in and fights the stubborn clasp. Finally, it binds the
lap and shoulder belts properly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an easy thing to use,'' Owens admits of the small
metal gadget called a locking clip.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's this hard,'' Williams says, ``I guarantee I won't go
through all this.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon completing the $7 class, Williams and the other women here
will receive a voucher. After delivering their babies, the women
will turn in their vouchers for a free car seat.
</P>
<P>
   The class consists of a 15-minute video, the hands-on experience
and a short explanation from Owens, the nurse educator. All of it
directly stresses the importance, and indirectly obviates the
headache, of the car seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have an infant backward-facing in the car seat,''
explains harried mom Sandy Raitt. ``But if they reach 20 pounds and
a year, you can have them forward-facing. The problem is, when they
hit 20 pounds before a year, you're supposed to keep them
backward-facing, but they've grown out of the infant seat. So they
make the kind (of car seat) that swivels back and forth. But it's
the hugest thing. If you want to sit in the back seat with them,
you have to smush in. It's a big pain in the butt. ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Petite Julia Decker, mother of four, drives a Ford Explorer, but
placing the car seat in the middle of the back seat blocked her
view of the road, so she moved the car seat directly behind her.
But now when her son asks for his juice, she has to swivel her head
and arm ``Exorcist''-style to reach back to him.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, because Decker transports clients for her work, she is
constantly taking the car seat out and putting it back in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I swear, if they could just make an inflatable one,'' she
fantasizes, ``where you could just push a button and it inflates
and then push it again and it deflates. It would be the easiest
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   As complicated as car seats are for parents, children seem to
have mastered their great mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wants to get out, he's out,'' says Charitta
Bryant-Griffin, mom of 2-year-old Charles.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's only 2,'' notes Bobbie Hickman, Antia Hickman's
grandmother. ``But I'll turn on a spiritual tape and be driving
down the freeway, and I'll look back, and she's standing up
dancing. How she unfastens it, I'll never know. It's hard for
``me'' to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Some parents have learned the hard way how not to place a child
in a car seat. There was the time Lyrtrina Jenkins was leaning over
her baby's car seat and slipped on the car's vinyl upholstery,
sending her face-first into the back seat. ``My mom found that very
hilarious,'' she recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Or the time Hantsche, trying to extract her infant's car seat
from the stroller, smashed her finger so hard she swears she saw
``stars and clouds with little bluebirds flying around them.''
</P>
<P>
   As seemingly innocent as they are, car seats have strained
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband watched everything and read everything about safety
and car seats, and he made us take two back (to the store) before
he got one he felt was safe enough,'' Loraine Coleman says. ``It
was ridiculous. It had to be just so-so.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Bruckner's 3-year-old refuses to sit in her car seat,
except when two other toddler friends ride in the car. Then, all
three clamor for the seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We draw straws every time we get in the car,'' Bruckner notes.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Carithers has the same problem with his 2-year-old
daughter, Sadie, and his girlfriend's 2-year-old. ``They fight over
which car seat is the best,'' he says, sighing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot call it a car seat or they will not sit in it,''
stresses Kathy Steinbrenner, the mom of 5-year-old twins. ``You
have to call it a booster seat or some special name. Car seats are
for babies.''
</P>
<P>
   Car seats and food seem to be in a category all their own.
Jodette Neely's car has built-in car seats for kids. Problem is,
they're impossible to clean. ``Once you get a cookie stuck in 'em,
you can't get it out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They can become a health hazard,'' says Nancy Mackey, whose
4-year-old daughter, Jordan, ``has a cafeteria'' under her car
seat. ``If you don't take (the car seat) out of the car for a
couple months and then you take it out for somebody to sit there,
and there's all that gunk that collects underneath them, old M&AMP;Ms
and crackers that are halfway eaten ... ''
</P>
<P>
   'Nuff said.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to avoid the inconvenience of the car seat? Walk.
Otherwise, suck it up, belt it down and, most importantly, drive
safely.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
