<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4767 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURNER-BROADCASTERS-C     04-19 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURNER-BROADCASTERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Playful Turner addresses audience as broadcaster convention
opens
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS, Nev. _ Only Ted Turner would risk opening an address
to one of the country's most powerful industries like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure I'm probably the only TV station owner who applied
for membership in your group and was turned down.''
</P>
<P>
   And only Turner could get laughs instead of boos for such a
line.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, tens of thousands of broadcasters packed a cavernous
hall Monday to hear Turner poke fun at himself and their trade
group, the National Association of Broadcasters. It represents most
of the radio and TV stations in the country, including all in metro
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The NAB is holding its annual convention here through Wednesday
and invited Turner to come for the first time. He wasn't welcome
when he owned just his cable programming giant Turner Broadcasting
System.
</P>
<P>
   But now Turner has sold his company to and is vice chairman of
Time Warner, one of the largest producers of television programming
and owner of the fledgling WB network.
</P>
<P>
   Turner, though, didn't want to talk much about his new role.
Instead, like a general reminiscing about past battles, he focused
on earlier run-ins with the NAB in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I became a member of the NAB when I bought Channel 17,'' said
Turner. ``But then the NAB opposed me turning Channel 17 into the
SuperStation, a cable network _ so I quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want you to take my $5,000 in membership fees and use
it to beat me over the head,'' said Turner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Later I re-applied and _ can you believe it? _ you turned me
down. Now that must have been a first.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner said he missed those old days, when there were just three
big networks and a handful of independent stations and cable
channels. Now, Turner lamented, there is too much competition, too
many new channels coming with the advent of digital television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want all of you to raise your hands right now and agree with
me not to put any more channels on the air,'' said Turner.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, if there's anyone here from the FCC (Federal
Communications Commission), please don't give out any more
licenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Not many raised their hands, but the audience did give Turner a
big laugh and standing ovation. And that seemed just fine with
Turner, who stepped down from the podium smiling broadly.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
