u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEY-HEROES-COX     04-19 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-HEROES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hero fireman, rescued crane operator treated to Disney parade
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ This had all the makings of a family vacation
photo.
</P>
<P>
   Three kids, husband and wife, flanked by Mickey and Minnie
Mouse. A spring weekday morning, the other coast away from
Woodland, Ala., and about 20 degrees hotter.
</P>
<P>
   But this was not just another trip to Disneyland. As members of
the Ivers Sims family gathered on Main Street USA, their picture
was taken by 20 or so cameras, both still and video. Their visit
included a parade, a firetruck rolling down the street to a slow,
whining siren and a bass drum, which set the beat to a marching
band rendition of the Raiders of the Lost Ark theme. They were
showered in a blizzard of red, white and blue confetti.
</P>
<P>
   All this just a week after the Sims family was very nearly
shattered, when Ivers Sims, a construction worker, clung to a crane
200 feet above a burning Atlanta mill, waiting for the daring
helicopter rescue and ride on a rope with firefighter Matt Moseley.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Sims and Moseley sat side-by-side atop the firetruck
during the cavalcade down Main Street, smiling and waving as they
were greeted like heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not often you get a happy ending like this,'' said
Moseley, whose larger-than-life rescue of Sims was shown on live
television in Atlanta and on CNN. ``A fairy-tale ending in a
fairy-tale land.''
</P>
<P>
   But this one was too real for Hollywood, a raw slice of real
life next to the Super Bowl winners who smile at the TV cameras and
say ``I'm goin' to Disneyland.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like a dream, only in a while reality hits you,''
Ivers Sims said. ``What brought me here was a real experience. I
wish I could have been here under different circumstances. But I'm
glad to be here to talk about living.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariland Sims had told her husband when they married four years
ago, that two places she always wanted to go were Disneyland and to
see the Statue of Liberty. She had no idea it would take nearing
losing her husband _ and an invitation from the folks at Disney _
to bring that dream true.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's turned out to be wonderful,'' said Marilind Sims,
standing with her three children, Chantrius, David and Larry, all
in their Sunday best. ``Sometimes it takes bad things to happen to
get good things.''
</P>
<P>
   A week earlier, she had been trapped in those ever-lasting
moments as her husband hung on for dear life on her television
screen. She circled her sister's house from room-to-room, crying
and praying.
</P>
<P>
   Moseley had been a firefighter for eight years, but never really
got this close to the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It lets you know someone higher than us is taking care of
us,'' Moseley said. ``I've been told by one of the crane engineers,
he couldn't give us a reason that crane was still standing. For all
intents and purposes it should have been down. So somebody else was
there holding that crane up until we could get him off.''
</P>
<P>
   Moseley's mother, Sharon Hembree, was at Disneyland on Monday,
all the way from College Park, Ga., to honor her son and only
child.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was incredible,'' Hembree said. ``I still can't believe it
was him up there.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a belated birthday celebration of sorts for Hembree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last Thursday was my birthday,'' she said. ``Next year for my
birthday, just a card please.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
