<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain calls for 'whatever force necessary' in Kosovo
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One of the first U.S. senators to advocate ground
troops in Kosovo, hawk John McCain (R-Ariz.) swooped into Georgia
Monday and called for the immediate mobilization of U.S.
infantrymen.
</P>
<P>
   The former Vietnam War prisoner of war said timidity among NATO
political leaders has prevented Gen. Wesley Clark, commander of
allied forces, from effectively directing military strikes in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Avoiding casualties_theirs and ours_is not our primary
objective. Winning is. The sooner the better,'' McCain told about
200 people at the Cobb Galleria Centre during a luncheon meeting of
the Georgia Public Policy Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``To that end, we should commence today to mobilize infantry and
armor divisions for a possible _ I emphasize possible _ ground war
in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain has criticized President Clinton for limiting NATO
airstrikes and sidestepping the use of ground forces. A candidate
for the GOP's 2000 presidential nomination, McCain suggested
Congress this week should debate and vote on a resolution
authorizing Clinton to use ``whatever force necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said it was time for Congress and the president to flex
the muscle of a superpower against Yugoslavia President Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best course for us, NATO, Kosovo, Russia _ and even Serbia
_ is to begin fighting this war as if it were a war ... instead of
some strange interlude between peace initiatives,'' said McCain,
who serves on the Senate Armed Service Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Marlon Manuel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
