A4772 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DRAFT-FALCONS20-C     04-19 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-FALCONS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta Falcons draft analysis
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Drafting 30th makes it very tough to wow the world,
but if the current criteria for grading the annual NFL draft
involves how teams address needs, it was an average draft for the
Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   There is room to disagree with coach Dan Reeves' statement a
month ago that draft priorities should be the secondary, defensive
line, tight end and fullback. Many thought the Falcons needed to
add a speedy wide receiver since waiving Tony Martin in February,
and that didn't happen with Chris Calloway, the free agent receiver
they acquired. Calloway is not a burner.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons did add one speed receiver in 5-foot-9, 178-pound
Rondel Menendez. But he came in the seventh round, and played
against few, if any, future NFL defensive backs at Eastern
Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia defensive end Patrick Kerney, the first-round pick, was
a good get. With a great burst, he figures to apply instant
pressure on opposing quarterbacks and likely will be a backup to
right end Chuck Smith.
</P>
<P>
   After that, it was slim pickings.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta traded next year's first-round pick to Baltimore to use
the Raven's 12th pick of the second round to select Mississippi
State tight end Reggie Kelly. Arizona fullback Jeff Paulk was taken
in the third round.
</P>
<P>
   Both satisfied some of Reeves' stated draft goals, but it's
questionable whether those picks will serve the team better than
getting a more talented speed receiver than Menendez or the
moderately quick and super-thin (6-feet, 162 pounds) Eugene Baker
in the fifth round.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves obviously thinks he did the right thing. He wanted a
tight end to complement starter O.J. Santiago in the two-tight end
set and a fullback to spell Bob Christian, whose season ended Dec.
13 with a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Both are blockers.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly caught 12 passes last year, Paulk two in his entire
college career.
</P>
<P>
   Paulk's performance in Arizona State's game against USC sold the
Falcons on that pick. He often got the better of Trojans linebacker
Chris Claiborne, whom the Lions drafted No. 9 overall.
</P>
<P>
   But Atlanta also uses its fullback as a receiver, and Paulk
hasn't shown those skills. He's a very good as a straight-line
blocker, but sometimes struggles in pass protection. He's not
agile.
</P>
<P>
   And Reeves said it is unclear if Kelly can be utilized as a
motion tight end, or H-back, like Brian Kozlowski last year.
</P>
<P>
   The two best picks on paper are Kerney and Utah State safety
Johndale Carty, a fourth-round pick, who is a terrific hitter with
limited instincts who projects to strong safety.
</P>
<P>
   Had he not had a poor senior season when his team changed
defensive schemes, he might have ended up a second-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   Baker consistently got open at Kent, catching a whopping 103
passes as a junior. But it's questionable whether he will have the
strength to beat a jam at the line or whether his 4.54-second speed
in the 40-yard dash will enable him to separate from NFL defensive
backs.
</P>
<P>
   There are possibilities for the Falcons other picks -- Kansas
State middle linebacker Jeff Kelly (6th), Iowa safety Eric Thigpen
(6th) and LSU center Todd McClure (7th). But none are viewed as
impact-type players.
</P>
<P>
   But as always with the NFL draft, only time will tell.
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: The Falcons signed nine undrafted college players Monday,
including former Florida State linebacker Lamont Green, and former
Texas tackle Octavious Bishop, who blocked for Heisman Trophy
winner Ricky Williams. The others were UCLA linebacker Brendon
Ayanbadejo, Charleston Southern offensive tackle John Breeden,
Kansas State punter James Garcia, California cornerback Derrick
Gardner, Ohio University Steve Hoofkin, Colorado guard Ben Nichols,
and Utah State guard Kenny Watts.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
