<HEADER>
A4777 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS20-COX     04-19 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHITE HOUSE SEEKS $6 BILLION FOR BALKAN AIR WAR
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton asked Congress on Monday for
$6.05 billion in emergency money to pay for the air war in the
Balkans and humanitarian assistance to 750,000 refugees forced out
of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The request includes $5.12 billion to replace cruise missiles
and other ordnance and to continue the air war until Oct. 1, the
start of the next fiscal year. However, administration officials
said that does not include potential costs of sending ground
troops, either for a military offensive or for peacekeeping
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the spending package would go for housing, food and
other aid to refugees. Assistant Secretary of State Strobe Talbott
announced that $150 million of that would be aimed at shoring up
neighboring nations, such as Albania and Macedonia, that have been
staggering under the flood of ethnic Albanians fleeing Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that the Congress will act on this,'' Clinton said at
the White House. ``The need for this funding is urgent, immediate,
clearly in the national interest. There are literally lives hanging
in the balance. And so I hope in the spirit of genuine
bipartisanship, the Congress will move the package right away.''
</P>
<P>
   The supplemental spending bill would give Congress its first
formal vote on the 27-day old conflict, which has involved more
than 450 U.S. warplanes at a cost of more than $1 billion. The
United States is providing about 25 percent of the humanitarian aid
for the Kosovo refugees and paying about 60 percent of the cost of
the NATO air war.
</P>
<P>
   However, the spending proposal is not expected to provide a
platform for Congress to debate the U.S. involvement in Yugoslavia.
There have been widespread congressional complaints about the lack
of White House preparation for the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Republican leaders in Congress are criticizing the
proposal for not seeking more money for the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., called the request
``short-sighted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton administration has been downsizing our military
for the last seven years, and the Kosovo crisis has exposed how our
national security is now in real danger,'' the speaker said,
promising that the Republican leadership would seek to add funds to
bolster the Defense Department.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, said in a statement,
``Even $10 billion would be insufficient'' to rebuild the military.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., opposed adding more
funds to this emergency package and said that he would ``probably
encourage the president to veto a bad bill'' and ask Congress to
send him a stripped-down version.
</P>
<P>
   Funding for the Balkan air war, or for any other military
spending added to the measure, would not be subject to
congressional spending caps because it would be labeled
``emergency.''
</P>
<P>
   That means the extra spending would be drawn from the expected
surplus, all of which is coming from Social Security tax
collections, said Susan Tanaka, president of the Committee for a
Responsible Budget, a private watchdog group.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
