<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-MORALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC PANEL ADOPTS MORALS CLAUSE IN SPONSORSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The International Olympic Committee will allow corporate
sponsors to terminate future marketing agreements if the IOC does
anything to harm the image of the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The adoption of a so-called morals clause, a reaction to scandal
revelations of bribery before the awarding of the Winter Games to
Salt Lake City in 2002, is the first by any major sports
organization or league. Until now, sports industry observers said,
morals clauses have been used by businesses in endorsement deals
with athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something we want to do to acknowledge that it is a
two-way street with our sponsors,'' said Michael Payne, marketing
director for the IOC, who said the new policy will apply to any new
sponsorship deals signed for games after the 2000 Olympics in
Sydney. ``We always have had requirements for how the sponsors
could use our Olympic symbols and marks in their marketing. Now, we
want the sponsors to know that there will be some reciprocity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't anticipate having problems like we have had recently
ever again,'' said Payne, speaking from the IOC's offices in
Lausanne, Switzerland. ``But should something like it ever occur
again, heaven forbid, and if we did not fix it right away, there
would be recourse for the sponsors.''
</P>
<P>
   The step by the IOC is a major victory for the corporate
sponsors, who pay an average of $50 million to sponsor the Olympics
for four years. The companies have sought significant reform from
the IOC before signing new sponsorship deals this spring and
summer, observers and officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Businessmen close to recent negotiations with the IOC and its
sponsors say that both the John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co.
and Visa International pushed hard for contractual language that
would allow them to pull out of the sponsorship agreements for just
cause.
</P>
<P>
   David D'Alessandro, Hancock's president and chief operating
officer publicly called for such exit clauses, based on the IOC's
behavior, to be part of the sponsorship agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I brought this up two months ago, Payne told me
personally that there was absolutely no reason for the clause,''
said D'Alessandro, one of the few corporate leaders who have been
willing to publicly argue the need for reforming the IOC. ``We had
a pretty significant argument about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what this is is a reluctant and belated
acknowledgement that indeed the sponsors should have more say in
this,'' D'Alessandro said. ``It's a big deal. It also tells me they
are having a real hard time trying to sign new people up.''
</P>
<P>
   While none of the top Olympic sponsors have announced any
intention to withdraw from negotiations over renewing their
marketing agreements, some have said privately that the scandal has
diminished the allure of the games, and that is having an impact on
their negotiations. And Johnson &AMP; Johnson halted negotiations with
the United States Olympic Committee in February over a prospective
deal to sponsor the games in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   American companies finance a substantial portion of the IOC
budget. Eleven of them, including Hancock and Visa, are currently
paying an average of $50 million each to use the Olympic rings and
other marks as part of their sponsorship deals. Some of the
companies have similar marketing deals with the USOC, and they
spend millions of dollars in advertising on NBC to leverage the
sponsorships.
</P>
<P>
   In total, observers say, the companies represent about $1
billion in revenue for the Olympics. Several of the companies are
currently negotiating new deals with the IOC, to renew their
agreements beyond the Summer Games in 2000 in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Payne said that all of the new sponsorship deals will be covered
by the morals clause. ``It's something I have already approached
the executive committee on, and they have approved,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a first for an organization of that type,'' said Lance
Helgeson, managing editor of the IEG Sponsorship Report, a
Chicago-based newsletter that reports on the sponsorship industry
and just finished hosting an international conference dedicated to
the topic. ``From a standpoint of a property like the Olympics _
which is more of a league product than anything else _ this has
definitely not been seen before, and it's real pioneering.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of stunning, really,'' said Bob Williams, president
of Burns Sports Celebrity Service, a Chicago-based company that
links advertisers with athletes for endorsements. ``We are at the
point of always advising our companies now to ask for really strict
morals language in almost all of their endorsement deals with
individual athletes. But this is like the reverse of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the businesses looking for some assurance from the
sport itself, that it won't do anything to harm their investment''
Williams said
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
