<SLUG> BC-BBA-RAYS-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX SPOIL HOLIDAY MOOD OF HOME CROWD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
Devil Rays 4, Red Sox 1 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- If this is the future, Red Sox fans had better dig in
for a long season. It took only six home games to indicate that the
1999 edition can't depend upon the old magic to ensure success at
Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   A Patriots Day crowd of 33,167 witnessed a lifeless 4-1 loss to
Tampa Bay, as it was evident that the Olde Towne Team lacks the
offensive sock associated with past regimes.
</P>
<P>
   After opening the season 6-1 (including a win in the Fenway
opener), the Sox went 1-4 since on the first homestand. If you
think this is an fluke, than think again.
</P>
<P>
   They Red Sox are losing games to teams like the doormat White
Sox and Devil Rays not only because of a lack of power, but also
because of a lack of consistency throughout the order. This is not
what the Red Sox had in mind when they came home last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We faced one of the best pitchers in the league today in
Rolando Arrojo,'' reminded Jeff Frye, who had two hits Monday. ``At
11 o'clock. In the shadows of Fenway. He was tough. And I'm not
making excuses. The ball I hit in the eighth hit the runner (Jose
Offerman, which thwarted a rally). That's kind of the way our luck
has been going lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last three games we have struggled a bit. The pitchers
are doing a great job. But the rest of us have to do our part. I
wouldn't look for a big turnaround with home runs. We're not a home
run-type of team. We need base hits, two-out RBIs, moving guys
over. That's the type of team we have. That's the type of team we
have to learn to be.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Tampa Bay that used the long ball in this series. Jose
Canseco, who hit three homers in the series, was silent Monday. But
another former Red Sox, John Flaherty picked up the slack with a
run-scoring double in the second in the second and a solo home run
in the sixth to pin Bret Saberhagen (2-1) with his first defeat.
Saberhagen gave up two runs in the second. The Sox got one back in
the fifth on a controversial home run by Offerman (whose shot to
right appeared to have hit the railing).
</P>
<P>
   Offerman's 417 average in 12 games has been a bright spot, but
the rest of the bats have been sporadic at best. Nomar Garciaparra
(.294) can't find daylight, yet. The outfield _ Trot Nixon (.071),
Damon Buford (.250), Troy O'Leary (.267), and Darren Lewis (.167)
has been punchless. Reggie Jefferson, his back problems cured, made
his first start of the season as designated hitter and went 1 for
4.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll snap out of it,'' said Sox manager Jimy Williams.
``There are just too many good hitters in that lineup. Arrojo was
tough. But I still feel good about our hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams couldn't have felt good about what happened in the
eighth, when the Sox put two runners on with two outs, only to see
the rally disintergrate in a matter of seconds. Jason Varitek had
hit two-out double and Offerman walked, setting the stage for a
possible big inning. Frye was at the plate and Tampa countered by
bringing in closer Roberto Hernandez. Frye hit a 3-0 pitch that was
headed toward right field but instead hit Offerman for the third
out. By rule, Frye was credited with a single.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never did see the ball,'' confessed Offerman. ``It's hard to
see the ball in the daylight here. But that's not all to it. We
haven't played the same game that we played on the road. We know
we're going to get it back. Until then, we take one day at a
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Frye said the Sox have to forget about this homestand and get
back to basics Tuesday night in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're not looking for the big inning,'' he said.
``We've got to put together a good solid attack the whole game.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody has to accept some of the blame, added Saberhagen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little frustrating,'' said Saberhagen. ``We hate to
come here and not play in our first homestand the way we had been
playing. (Tampa Bay) played well and deserved to win three of four.
</P>
<P>
   ``What hurt me today was a leadoff walk in the second which led
to two runs., You have to make guys earn their way on. Then we get
a run back at 2-1 and I kind of let them get a run back for 3-1.
They played a very good series against us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
