<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4782 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIRTH-CERTIFICATES-2T     04-19 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIRTH-CERTIFICATES-2TAKES-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIRTHRIGHT DENIED? ADOPTEES SEEK THEIR ORIGINAL CERTIFICATES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CAROL CHRISTIAN 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Cyndi Smith wants her birth certificate.
</P>
<P>
   It may sound like a small matter, but because the Houston woman
was adopted, her original birth certificate is sealed by Texas law.
The document she has, though legal, was filled in months after her
birth to make it appear that her adoptive mother gave literal birth
to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point of getting the original birth certificate is just
that _ to get it and see it, to have the confirmation of oneself,''
said Smith, 35, who was born in Fort Worth and adopted by Bryan
residents through the Gladney Center for Adoption. ``It's not fair
for some people in society to have access to this knowledge and
others to be legally barred from having it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another adoptee, Pamela Hannah of Austin, describes her altered
birth certificate _ which is dated July 1964 but lists an address
that her adoptive parents didn't occupy until spring 1965 _ as
``legal fiction to forever erase the truth of my birth.''
</P>
<P>
   By joining the Texas fight for adoptees' access to original
birth certificates, Smith and Hannah have put themselves in the
middle of an emotional national debate.
</P>
<P>
   On one side is an unknown number of adoptees and birth parents
yearning to connect with each other. On the other side are women
clinging to their privacy, afraid or unwilling to dredge up
memories of what for many was the most painful time of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   A bill to open access to the original documents appears stalled,
for the second straight session, in the Texas Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Under current state law, whenever someone is adopted, the
original birth certificate is sealed and an amended one is issued _
even in cases in which an older child is adopted by a stepfather
and has known his or her birth father for years.
</P>
<P>
   For adult adoptees looking for birth parents, the search is
simpler with an original birth certificate. But Smith and Hannah
have already found their birth mothers. They just want the true
records.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's everyone's right to know where they came from,'' Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
   Though it is impossible to determine how many people in the
United States were adopted and what percentage of birth mothers do
not want contact with their children, one thing is certain:
Proponents of openness get the most exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who want the privacy do not feel comfortable being very
public,'' said Heidi Cox, general counsel for the 112-year-old
Gladney Center, which has the nation's largest maternity home in
Fort Worth for women planning adoption for their babies.
</P>
<P>
   Some birth mothers don't want to be found because nobody in
their family _ including parents, husband and other children _
knows the secret, said Sylvia Franzmeier, program manager for
adoption and post-adoption services at DePelchin Children's Center
in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to tell their current children is especially hard
for some birth mothers, Franzmeier said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel like telling about it would change their children's
opinion of them,'' she said. ``In real life, it doesn't, but that's
what they feel like.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes birth mothers don't want the intrusion in their lives
and think they should not intrude on the adopted person's life,
Franzmeier said. She noted, however, that most birth mothers
contacted by DePelchin at the request of adoptees not only don't
mind the intrusion but are overjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   Other birth mothers don't want contact because they were rape
victims or had hostile relationships with birth fathers, said Paige
Smith, Gladney Center spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or it could be as simple as they are not emotionally prepared
for a meeting with the adopted child at this point and they want to
be able to have some element of control over when that meeting
takes place, if it ever does,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Though the case for open access appears to be losing in Austin,
the debate is far from over.
</P>
<P>
   Cyndi Smith, a computer programmer, is co-founder of the Texas
Coalition for Adoption Resources and Education. The 110-member
group rallied for birth-certificate access in January in Austin and
since then has been lobbying legislators to pass House Bill 13.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which faces an uphill battle, would allow adoptees age
21 or older to get their original birth certificates and would
prevent revision of an original certificate if the court, adoptive
parents or an adoptee age 12 or older requests that it remain
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   House Bill 13 is likely to die in the Juvenile Justice and
Family Issues Committee before being brought to a vote, said
committee chairman Rep. Toby Goodman, R-Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman, who opposes the bill, said the law could drive birth
mothers to place their babies with agencies in other states and
adoptive parents to look for children out of state or out of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have Texas babies going out of state and foreign
babies coming into Texas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's sponsor is Rep. Tony Goolsby, R-Dallas. He is working
on a revised bill that might have a better chance of coming to a
vote in committee, said an aide.
</P>
<P>
   Hannah's birth mother, Joyce Obenhaus of Freeport, has also
lobbied for House Bill 13.
</P>
<P>
   Obenhaus, who was a 27-year-old secretary at Rice University
when she became pregnant by a graduate student, said she had never
looked for her daughter because she was afraid Hannah would be
bitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I know she doesn't hate me,'' Obenhaus said, ``I wish
I had tried to contact her years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that Hannah has met both her birth parents, she said it is
patronizing to be denied her original birth certificate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk, we visit, there's nothing left to hide,'' she said.
``And I still can't get any of the stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas and Alaska are the only states offering all adult
adoptees access to their original birth certificates. Ohio provides
it for any adoptee born before 1964 unless the original record was
sealed by specific request. Tennessee passed an access law in 1996
that survived a challenge in the federal court system but is now
being contested at the state level. In the past year, Oregon and
Delaware have passed access laws that are being challenged in
court.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, state Rep. Debra Danburg, D-Houston, has been a vocal
opponent of adoptees getting original birth certificates against
birth parents' wishes. She said she would oppose House Bill 13 as
long as it amounted to a government edict to expose birth parents
despite promises to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   Danburg said she supports easier access to birth registries
where adult adoptees and birth parents can find each other if both
sign up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that curiosity,'' Danburg said. ``If I were
adopted, I would very much be that kind of person.''
</P>
<P>
   Cyndi Smith said she has spoken to birth mothers and heard of
others who attempted suicide because they feared they would never
know anything about their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are adoptees who attempted suicide because they didn't
know where they came from,'' Cyndi Smith said. ``It's a very
emotional issue on all sides. You can't deny the other person the
right to their own emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of House Bill 13 say existing laws never promised
birth mothers confidentiality in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Wanger, a Fort Worth-area attorney who has researched
Texas adoption law, said she found no statute that guarantees
confidentiality for birth parents. Instead, Wanger said,
confidentiality concerns have focused on adoptees _ on their right
to avoid the stigma of illegitimacy by keeping their birth records
closed.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, Wanger said, adoptions have usually involved both
a hearing to terminate birth parents' rights to the child and an
adoption hearing.
</P>
<P>
   To get their adoption records, adoptees have needed court orders
since 1973, when the Legislature reorganized all types of family
law into the Family Code and created a confidential central record
file. Termination files, by contrast, have never been confidential
unless there was a court order sealing a particular file.
</P>
<P>
   To show that birth mothers have not typically been promised
confidentiality, the Texas coalition has begun collecting copies of
relinquishment affidavits. Of about 25 gathered so far, none
promised the birth mother privacy, Smith said. In fact,
relinquishment affidavits are part of the termination proceeding,
and if the termination proceeding has not been sealed, anybody can
access that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has the birth mother's name loud and clear,'' Smith said of
a typical relinquishment document. ``It points out that it's not
the birth mothers being protected.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 1855EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4784 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARSEAT-FACTS-TEX     04-19 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARSEAT-FACTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE 10 MOST COMMON CAR-SEAT MISTAKES
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies CAR SEAT WARS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. Safety seat is in the car too loose. (You should not be able
to move it side to side or up and down more than 1 inch in any
direction.)
</P>
<P>
   2. Harness does not fit snug around the child. (If more than one
finger can be inserted between the harness belts and the child, it
is not snug enough.)
</P>
<P>
   3. Back-facing seat is not angled properly. (An infant should
ride sitting semi-reclined at a 45-degree angle so that breathing
is not obstructed if his head slumps forward. Place a rolled-up
towel or section of a ``fun noodle'' under the front edge of the
seat to achieve the proper angle.)
</P>
<P>
   4. Baby's head is not properly supported. (Infants may need
extra cushioning pads, rolled-up towels or rolled-up diapers around
their heads for support.)
</P>
<P>
   5. The harness retainer clip is out of place or not threaded
correctly. The clip should be in the middle of the chest, at armpit
level to prevent shoulder straps from slipping off.
</P>
<P>
   6. The locking clip is not used correctly to take up the slack
in seat belts that do not have locking or switchable retractors.
(See details in short accompanying story on locking clips.)
</P>
<P>
   7. Shoulder belts are not worn properly. Children often move
belts under their arms or behind their backs so that they are more
comfortable, but improper placement of belts can cause broken ribs
or internal injuries if there's a crash. Make sure lap belts fit
low and tight across the upper thighs and the shoulder belt crosses
the collarbone and chest _ never the neck or face.
</P>
<P>
   8. A booster seat is used without a shoulder strap. In some
cars, there are only lap straps and no shoulder straps in the back
seat. In most cars, the center seat does not have a shoulder strap.
Booster seats should not be used without shoulder straps, because
they leave the upper body unrestrained.
</P>
<P>
   9. An older child is put into the car's regular lap and shoulder
belts too soon. Booster seats are designed to make lap and shoulder
belts fit small bodies properly. Usually, seat belts will not
properly fit until a child is about 8 years old.
</P>
<P>
   10. Babies are bundled up too much to assure a safe, secure fit
of their car seats. If additional warmth is needed, a blanket can
be placed over the baby and the seat itself after the baby is
secured in the seat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Rear-facing car seats:
</P>
<P>
   Babies should be kept in rear-facing infant or convertible car
seats until they are at least 1 year old and at least 20 pounds.
This offers the best protection for the baby's neck. The
rear-facing seat should be reclined at a 45-degree angle.
</P>
<P>
   Forward-facing seats:
</P>
<P>
   Children from age 1 to 40 pounds may ride in a convertible
safety seat facing forward or a forward-facing-only child seat.
Seats come in three harness styles: five-point, T-shield or
tray-shield. The five-point harness is most often recommended
because it can be adjusted to fit almost all sizes and shapes of
children up to 40 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Booster seats:
</P>
<P>
   Children between 40 and about 60 to 80 pounds (usually 4 to 8
years old) should be in booster seats. Booster seats make safety
belts fit right. Move your child to a booster seat when he outgrows
his forward-facing car seat, and keep him in the booster until your
vehicle's regular lap and shoulder straps fit properly across the
upper thighs and snug over the shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   What the heck is a locking clip (and how does it work)?
</P>
<P>
   First: Don't throw it away.
</P>
<P>
   The locking clip is usually attached to the side or back of most
new child-safety seats, and you need to immediately check your
vehicle owner's manual to see if it's necessary to secure your
safety seat.
</P>
<P>
   Clips are needed to provide tight installation of safety seats
in cars with ``emergency-locking'' retractors _ seat belts that
lock only with a sudden stop or collision (most cars made before
1996) and in newer cars that do not allow you to switch it to
automatic locking.
</P>
<P>
   An ``automatic locking'' retractor locks whenever you stop
pulling it out and will hold a safety seat tightly without a
locking clip. An emergency-locking retractor will not.
</P>
<P>
   If your belts cannot be switched to automatic, the locking clip
must be used to take up the slack in the safety belts.
</P>
<P>
   To install the clip:
</P>
<P>
   _Put the seat belt through the correct path on the safety seat
and buckle it.
</P>
<P>
   _Push down on the safety seat and pull up on the shoulder end of
the belt until the belt is pulled tight.
</P>
<P>
   _Hold the two parts of the belt together at the latchplate and
unbuckle it.
</P>
<P>
   _Thread the belt though the locking clip, close to the
latchplate.
</P>
<P>
   _Buckle the belt again. If you put the clip on correctly, the
belt should stay tight around the safety seat.
</P>
<P>
   _Remove the locking clip when the belt is not holding a safety
seat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget
</P>
<P>
   _The back seat is the safest place for children to ride in a
motor vehicle. Never place a child in the front seat in a vehicle
equipped with passenger-side air bags.
</P>
<P>
   _Read and follow the manufacturer's instructions for installing
and using your particular safety seat.
</P>
<P>
   _Consult your vehicle owner's manual concerning which seats best
fit your vehicle and how to install those seats.
</P>
<P>
   _For a convertible or front-facing seat, secure the car seat
snugly with the seat belt. Then, with the child out of the seat,
press your knee down into the car seat with all your weight while
pulling the seat belt even tighter.
</P>
<P>
   _Never buckle two people _ kids or adults _ into one seat belt.
</P>
<P>
   _Never use a car seat that has been involved in a crash. (They
are designed to withstand one crash.)
</P>
<P>
   _Never use a car seat that does not have a label saying it
conforms to federal standards.
</P>
<P>
   _Don't throw away your car-seat registration form. You need to
send in the registration form so that you can be notified if your
car seat is recalled. If you have any questions or wish to report
any problems, call the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration's Auto Safety Hot Line, (800) 424-9393), or check
the Department of Transportation home page at www.nhtsa.dot.gov.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
