u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-MARATHON-LEDE-COX     04-19 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-MARATHON-LEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ethiopia's Roba wins with over two minutes' lead
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Since wrapping herself in her country's flag after
claiming Olympic victory in Atlanta, Fatuma Roba has become into a
favorite daughter of the Boston Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   Her name is right up there with women from different eras _
Kathrine Switzer, Joan Benoit Samuelson, Rosa Mota and Ingrid
Kristiansen, to name a few. And now she ranks alongside the
grandest of them all, Uta Pippig, the only woman before Monday's
103rd edition of the storied race to win three straight.
</P>
<P>
   Running in a fluid style combining grace and subtle authority,
Roba grabbed the lead at the halfway point from 20-year-old Chinese
upstart Sun Yingjie and spent the rest of the afternoon bolstered
by her Ethiopian supporters who occasionally wandered onto the
course. They would run beside her for short spells, waving their
country's red, yellow and green flag. At 20 miles, she donned a
headband in her country's colors, a gift from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I have run in Boston, I have had great support from
the Ethiopian community,'' said Roba, an officer in her country's
army. ``At one point, in a hilly area, I was tired and the support
gave me a boost and I run with a new pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Roba's time of 2 hours, 23 minutes, 25 seconds was more than two
minutes faster than runner-up Franziska Rochat-Moser of Switzerland
and the fourth fastest ever at Boston. Early on, Roba said, she was
unaware that Yingjie had broken fast, running just off the lead
men's group and clocking five-minutes miles.
</P>
<P>
   Yingjie, who fell back to 11th, and countrywoman Ai Dongmei came
close to missing the race when they ran into visa problems. But
Sen. John Kerry (D-Mass.) intervened, and the two elite Chinese
athletes made it to the starting line.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one took (Yingjie) seriously,'' Rochat-Moser said of the
rapid pace. ``I think it was her first experience running outside
her country.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Boston, and first-timers don't manhandle the rolling
hills.
</P>
<P>
   Except Roba, who was an unknown in 1996 when she entered the
Olympic stadium in Atlanta far in front of her competitors and
became the first black African woman to win marathon gold at the
Games.
</P>
<P>
   The next spring, her first at Boston, she was intent on
validating her Olympic win. She did so and is now 3-for-3 there.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, she has not run well elsewhere. She dropped out of the
1997 world championships in Athens, Greece. The rolling courses of
Atlanta and Boston have suited her well.
</P>
<P>
   Now, her goal is a gold medal at the 2000 Olympics in Sydney,
which would match her late countryman Abebe Bikila, men's marathon
champion in 1960 and 1964. Roba refuses to put herself in the same
category with the Ethiopian hero, though acknowledges that she has
emerged as a role model for her country's children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they want to be like me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fish writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
