<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-MARATHON-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kenyan Chebet no longer second
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Back home in Kenyan, Joseph Chebet had evolved into the
Avis of marathons. Always a bridesmaid, never a bride.
</P>
<P>
   He had been run down at Boston last year and, in his last two
starts of the New York Marathon, lost by a combined six seconds.
That was left to the past Monday when Chebet handled the
come-from-behind business, pulling away from Silvio Guerra of
Ecuador with about four miles to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to be second,'' said a relieved Chebet. ``I like
to be first..''
</P>
<P>
   Chebet came home in 2 hours, 9 minutes, 52 seconds, only the
38th fastest Boston time ever. It helped that two-time champion
Moses Tanui was felled by leg cramps.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Chebet benefitted from the inexperience of Guerra,
starting just his fourth marathon. Guerra proved impatient with the
slow first-half pace and surged up the hills of Newton late on the
course before Chebet easily took back the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I left (the pack), I was thinking I could win,'' said
Guerra, his black hair tied in a ponytail. ``I felt strong and
ready to win. I didn't know how hard the end would be.''
</P>
<P>
   RECORD SHY: Affectionately dubbed ``Boston Billy,'' Bill
Rodgers' run at an American record for over-50 marathoners ended
with him dropping out almost 21 miles. The four-time Boston winner
suffered dehydration and received medical treatment along the
course.
</P>
<P>
   ``My body is telling me it can't run hard any more,'' Rodgers
said. ``I can't push hard for records.''
</P>
<P>
   Another top American, Lynn Jennings, enjoyed an only slightly
better afternoon. Jennings, a nine-time national cross-country
champ and Barcelona Olympic bronze medalist in the 10,000 meters,
finished 12th in her first official marathon.
</P>
<P>
   ROLLING ON: Franz Nietlispach took home to Switzerland his
fourth Boston title, winning the men's wheelchair race in a
personal-best 1:21:36. Louise Sauvage won her third straight title
in the women's wheelchair, outsprinting seven-time champ Jean
Driscoll to the finish line in 1:42:23.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fish writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
