<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4792 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-19 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT OTHER WAR AND THIS WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ Although the room was filled with hard-nosed,
hard-news executives, an air of unreality drizzled on the gilded
ballroom sconces of the Fairmont Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The American Society of Newspaper Editors had asked the White
House to explain the administration's aims in Kosovo. President
Clinton volunteered for the job himself. He spoke for an hour,
including a question-and-answer session. I listened intently.
Unlike many pundits and politicians, I have yet to develop strong
and sure opinions on military action in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Op-ed pages bristle with armchair Eisenhowers, mapping tactics
and strategy on how to stay or when to go. As former doves and
onetime hawks exchange plumage, the missing factor in this
dreamworld debate is speculative, but important.
</P>
<P>
   What happens when American casualties begin to accumulate? After
three weeks, the air war is still a melody played in a video
arcade. Ground troops will be needed in Kosovo if and when, as the
president said in his speech, ``the refugees return under the
protection of an international force.''
</P>
<P>
   Even pilots are not safe. The air of unreality in the
president's speech came not from what he said, but what he did not
say. He began his speech at 12:07. At 12:14 he discussed risk:
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning of the operation, we focused properly on
Serbia's highly developed air defenses to reduce the risks to our
pilots. There are still significant air defenses up, and therefore
there is still risk with every mission.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not return to the subject of risk. His speech was
familiar, cover-all-bases Clintonian tick-tock, an offbrand
Kennedyesque or Sorensenesque syncopation that few can quote or
remember:
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO would be discredited _ yes, because it made promises not
kept, but more important because its values and vision of Europe
would be profoundly damaged. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the stand we have taken, first in Bosnia, now in Kosovo,
against organized ethnic hatred is a moral imperative. But it is
also a strategic imperative. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Now at the end of the 20th century, we face a great battle
between the forces of integration and the forces of disintegration;
the forces of globalism vs. tribalism; of oppression against
empowerment. And the phenomenal explosion of technology, including
that of advanced weaponry, might be the servant of either side or
both.''
</P>
<P>
   An editor asked about the friendly-fire deaths of Kosovar
civilians last week. Stuff happens, the president replied: ``This
is not a business of perfection.''
</P>
<P>
   As tragic as that incident was, the dead were nameless and
faceless to most Americans. The funeral for the first American
casualty, however, is likely to be televised live, igniting debates
in kitchens, church halls, and coffee shops.
</P>
<P>
   At Oxford in 1939, young Englishmen debated defending Poland
against Nazi Germany. ``Die for Danzig?'' they asked. The
silver-haired grandees on the ASNE dais at the Fairmont share a
generational frame of reference. When someone mentions ``the war,''
they and Americans of a similar age think of the war that began in
1939 and ended in 1945. The heroes of that war find their ranks
diminished by time and chance, the debt owed them never fully paid.
</P>
<P>
   For many million more Americans, ``the war'' refers to an
ill-defined military action that began uncertainly in 1959 and
ended in defeat in 1975, a somber episode in what John F. Kennedy
called in his inaugural ``a long twilight struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference between World War II and the war in Vietnam is
the difference between clearly stated goals and rhetorical drift.
It is the difference between a formal declaration of war and
``mission creep.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Die for Danzig?'' Such a question will not be asked while this
war remains antiseptic and undeclared. If body bags arrive at
American air bases, an answer will be required, an answer we have
not heard yet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
