<HEADER>
A4795 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-19 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASHING TOWARD 2000, STEERING CLEAR OF TROUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How the electorate views the Clinton presidency in the coming
months may well determine his successor in the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   After years of Monica Lewinsky, Kenneth Starr, Whitewater, and
various scandals and controversies in Bill Clinton's tenure, the
American voters, though strongly supportive throughout Clinton's
ordeal, may be looking for a candidate less likely to generate
controversy. Voters don't want to hear, read, or watch reports on
one scandal or investigation after another generated by the
nation's leader.
</P>
<P>
   While some Republican presidential hopefuls, such as Lamar
Alexander and Dan Quayle, are attempting to come across as
occupants of the highest moral ground, they do not exactly incite
enthusiasm among many voters.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the populace is looking for something beyond
moral standards; they are also looking for someone who can, like
Clinton, do his job well and maintain the healthy economy.
</P>
<P>
   Early signs point to a presidential election battle between the
Republican with the money and the Democrat with the numbers.
Republican hopeful George W. Bush is raising money faster than any
other potential candidate. Vice President Al Gore is receiving
endorsements from large organizations, including organized labor.
He has already received the endorsement of the 600,000-member
Communications Workers of America, and is expected to receive many
more such endorsements as he makes his pitch to be labor's friend
and a friend of working families.
</P>
<P>
   Although some polls show that Republican Elizabeth Dole is
currently the front-runner in the New Hampshire primary, other
polls show Bush, the son of former President George Herbert Walker
Bush, defeating all potential candidates, including Gore, by
substantial margins.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the cerebral Bill Bradley, the former professional
basketball player and US senator from New Jersey, somehow catches
on during the Democratic primaries, Gore appears to be the
candidate who can offer voters both substance and personal
morality, if he is able to withstand controversy about his
fundraising efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, too, comes with potential vulnerability. He acknowledges
without elaboration his earlier and wilder days _ ``when I was
young and irresponsible, I was young and irresponsible,'' he says
simply _ apparently hoping that by not elaborating, further
questions will go away. But in a presidental campaign, as Clinton
and former Democratic presidential hopeful Gary Hart know all too
well, such questions rarely disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that is why it might be better for Bush and others to
explain their pasts, in context, early in the campaign. Not to do
so allows their opponents, or the media, to give these issues a lot
of exposure that could do more harm than an honest acknowledgment
of past misdeeds. That also protects a candidate from being on the
front pages in the final, and most dangerous, weeks of an election;
candidates who have been there would give both Gore and Bush that
advice.
</P>
<P>
   There is one thing voters do not want any candidate to be:
boring. And that means that Gore has some work to do. He needs to
rid himself of the wooden style that, for the moment, is a staple
for comedians.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he has two things in his favor: his good humor about the
jokes, and the distinct possibility that his Republican rival,
while generally perceived as a nice guy, may actually be more
boring than Gore appears.
</P>
<P>
   Gore must, in the coming months, portray himself as the
candidate who will continue Clinton's job of keeping the economy
strong, while separating himself from the scandal side of Clinton's
legacy. The Republicans, of course, will attempt to do just the
opposite _ link Gore to the negative side of the Clinton presidency
and stress that it is time for an entirely new team.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bush and Gore know the task ahead of them. When the polls
open in November 2000, voters will decide which of the candidates
has best managed to be like Clinton in substance and job skills,
but bears no resemblance to the man who managed to get into enough
legal and political trouble to last voters a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
