<HEADER>
A4796 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r n &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RESTOREDCOURTHOUSE-TE     04-19 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESTOREDCOURTHOUSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILL COUNTY GEM: DEDICATION SET FOR REBUILT COURTHOUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL HANNA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HILLSBORO, Texas _ When the Hill County Courthouse burned on
Jan. 1, 1993, a few distraught residents wondered whether the
historic structure should be torn down.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the clock tower had fallen to the courthouse's ground
floor and there were questions about whether the limestone exterior
was structurally sound.
</P>
<P>
   But that vocal minority was quickly drowned out. For most
residents, giving up on the old building was unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I would see my wife shed tears over a
building,'' said Hillsboro attorney Jim Showers. ``But the night of
the fire she stood there and cried. Like every Hill County native,
that courthouse meant so much to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Within days, Showers was planning a benefit concert with Hill
County native Willie Nelson. The long, costly road to bringing the
courthouse back had begun.
</P>
<P>
   Six years and approximately $10 million later, Hill County is
celebrating that perseverance. On Saturday, the structure, restored
to its original splendor, will be dedicated by Gov. George W. Bush,
and Nelson will perform again to celebrate its completion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody said they never dreamed it would take six years.
Everybody thought it would be three,'' said Hill County Judge
Kenneth Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we owed it to this 102-year-old building to try and
rebuild it, and with the help of everyone in this county and just
about everyone who ever lived here, we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who lives between Hillsboro and Itasca, said many
residents didn't appreciate the building until it was nearly gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know every time I came into town, just by habit, I would
look up there to see that clock and see what time it was,'' Davis
said. ``It really took me a year after the fire to stop looking up
and see nothing but sky.''
</P>
<P>
   In rebuilding the courthouse and the 70-foot clock tower,
project architect Larry Irsik tried to return the courthouse to the
way it looked when it opened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty difficult,'' Irsik said. ``There's not any
original drawings. Surprisingly, very few original photographs
exist. There's not a single historic photograph of the district
courtroom. So what we did in some areas is totally interpretive.''
</P>
<P>
   But sorting through the burned debris of the fire, Irsik, who
works for the Dallas firm ArchiTexas, tried to account for every
piece of molding, tile and wood and its location in the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   The exterior of the building, which incorporates Classical
Revival and Italianate influences, was well known. But oral
histories from elderly Hill County residents were needed to tell
architects about the courthouse's interior before it was modernized
in the 1950s and 1960s, Irsik said.
</P>
<P>
   The two spaces that spark the most conversation inside the
renovated courthouse are the district courtroom and the basement.
</P>
<P>
   Before the fire, the courtroom's balcony had been sealed off,
the ceiling lowered, and it looked like many other old courtrooms
across Texas, Showers said. Now, it looks ready for a remake of
``To Kill a Mockingbird.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking up portions of the second and third floors, the courtroom
_ which is still smaller than the original _ includes a sweeping
balcony, a pressed metal ceiling and long-leaf pine floors that
were recycled from the renovation of the Texas Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coincidentally, much of interior is from the same era as the
Texas Capitol,'' Irsik said. ``A lot of the moldings were from
stock materials. I don't know much in the building that was custom
made. Most of the moldings were readily available in that time.''
</P>
<P>
   County officials say two weddings have been scheduled in the
courtroom, the first one on May 15, two days before the county will
begin moving its offices from a converted grocery store back into
the building.
</P>
<P>
   The cavelike basement has surprisingly drawn the most comments
from visitors, Irsik said. Workers excavated around the structure,
waterproofed it and left the natural limestone walls unadorned.
</P>
<P>
   The fire has also stirred interest in renovating other Texas
courthouses _ not just for fire safety but also to restore their
original grandeur. No longer are officials satisfied with makeshift
repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Some Texas counties, such as Ellis and Hood, already have made
improvements. Others are not far behind.
</P>
<P>
   The Hood County Courthouse, which, like Hill County's, was
designed by W.C. Dodson and opened in 1891, was used as a reference
for hinges and other details in the Hill County Courthouse. The
interior of the Ellis County Courthouse, which is being renovated,
will rival the inside of Hill County's courthouse when complete,
Irsik said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also has jumped into the restoration trend, proposing a
$100 million fund to renovate Texas courthouses. Officials in many
counties, such as those in Johnson County where Irsik's firm has
been hired, are eagerly waiting to see whether the Legislature
passes the bill.
</P>
<P>
   But Hill County residents are thinking about the present. After
six long years, it's a point of pride that the old courthouse is
not only back, but vastly improved over the one that burned.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably going to be the finest restored courthouse in
the state of Texas,'' said Showers, the Hillsboro attorney. ``It
rivals the state Capitol in restoration quality. For those of us
who live here, it's awe-inspiring.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   What _ Hill County Courthouse dedication with Gov. George W.
Bush
</P>
<P>
   When _ 1:30 p.m. Saturday
</P>
<P>
   Where _ north side of the courthouse square in Hillsboro, 55
miles south of Fort Worth. Take Interstate 35W, exit at Texas 22,
go west to downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Cost _ dedication ceremony is free.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Nelson concert _ 2:30 p.m. on the south side of the
square. Cost is $25. Fences will prevent those without tickets from
seeing the show.
</P>
<P>
   Information _ (800) HILLSBORO
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
