<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Tuesday, April 20, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Stewart Slavin at the Daily News, (818) 713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-NAME (Los Angeles) _ Besmirched by Blythe Street's
notorious reputation as a haven for gangs and drug dealers, Blythe
Street Elementary School wants to change its name. By David Baker.
(Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   LA-BUDGET (Los Angeles) _ Shifting his top priority to improving
neighborhoods' quality of life, Mayor Richard Riordan said Monday
he would ask the City Council to approve a $4.2 billion budget for
1999-2000 that increases tree trimming, street resurfacing, alley
closures and abandoned buildings. By Rick Orlov. (Will move in the
``a'' national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   HOTRODDER-SAVED (Los Angeles) _ Louis Senter has been on the
cover of Hot Rod magazine, but he ended up under his rod, being
dragged. Three teen-agers saved Senter's life when the yellow
street rod suddenly rolled over him while he was working on the
car. By Lisa Van Proyen. (Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n''
California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   LUCKYFISH (Los Angeles) _ Hoe Jin Soon tried to bring $150,000
worth of ``Lucky'' fish into the United States from Malaysia, but
none of the good fortune rubbed off on him. After getting nabbed
with plastic bags filled with the prehistoric-looking endangered
species by U.S. Customs officials last month, he pleaded guilty
Monday and faces up to a year in jail. By Peter Hartlaub. (Will
move in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
