<HEADER>
A4807 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-PREPAREDNESS-960(     04-19 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-PREPAREDNESS-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALES HEAT UP FOR YEAR-END PREPAREDNESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN AUSTIN 
and JAN JARVIS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Nobody can predict whether the Y2K bug will cripple or
inconvenience the civilized, computer-dependent world, but this
much is sure: Preparedness won't be cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Some opportunists have found in the Y2K craze the chance to cash
in on customers' escalating fears. Others who are concerned about
chaos spilling into the streets in 2000 have turned their living
rooms into mini grocery stores. Driving this booming cottage
industry are plenty of people eager to buy preparedness products,
even if it means a hefty investment.
</P>
<P>
   Stocking up on enough dehydrated foods for a family of four for
a year will cost about $3,000. Stash enough ready-to-eat meals to
keep that same nuclear family on three squares a day and the cost
can climb to around $14,000.
</P>
<P>
   Add a tent that sleeps six ($122), solar-powered shower ($295),
charcoal-burning stove ($280), grain mill ($116), a generator
($269) and water filter ($170) to the ammunition, weapons and
getaway survival ranch and it's easy to see that there's no limit
to how much people can _ and do _ spend. For some, the built-in
computer bug means war.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't want to wait,'' said Phyllis Hopkins,
owner of Best Prices Storable Foods in Mesquite. ``They want to
make sure they've got it now so they're not caught in the wheel
when it stops.''
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Jenkins of Garland has been stocking up on canned goods,
seeds and sprouts since last year. Now, with only canned eggs left
on her shopping list, she's confident that she'll be prepared for
any emergency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at it as insurance,'' she said. ``I know the kids will
have plenty of food next year, and if I don't use everything I
don't have to buy groceries.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Y2K bug will spur a crisis, Jenkins can't be
certain, but she's worried about the civil unrest that could occur
when people realize they are not as prepared as they need to be.
</P>
<P>
   All this angst stems from the so-called Y2K problem, which
arises from the inability of many computers to distinguish dates
correctly. Unmodified computers, for example, could read 2000 as
1900. The fear is that the miscalculations could lead to widespread
disruptions in a world that is increasingly dependent on
microchips.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Emergency Management Agency has said that forecasts
of cataclysmic collapse from the year 2000 computer problems are
greatly exaggerated, but many people are not buying it.
</P>
<P>
   What they are buying, many retailers insist, are products that
will function regardless of what the year is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every gun I have is Y2K compliant,'' said Dale DeGroote, sales
manager at Bob's Discount Firearms in Hurst. ``We're seeing a lot
of people buying the politically incorrect weapons. A lot of stuff
that holds 30 or more rounds.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``politically incorrect'' hardware includes the AR-15
semiautomatic rifles he recently sold a 65-year-old woman. She
bought three rifles, 10 magazines and 3,000 rounds of ammunition.
Her tab for preparedness was $3,600.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never owned a gun in her life,'' DeGroote said, adding that he
has seen a big influx of new customers bitten by Y2K-bug phobia.
``She was going to the hills.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no average expenditure.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins' customers spend anywhere from $200 to $50,000 on
preparedness products ranging from powdered kelp to hand-cranked
grain mills. She sells $10,000 to $14,000 worth of grain mills
weekly.
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt that people are buying into the Y2K concept. At
Preparedness Expo '99 in Mesquite this month, about 2,000 people
showed up during the first hour it was open, said Angie Benson, who
works for the organizers of the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last year, we have seen an increase of about 30 percent
in attendance,'' she said. ``Dallas is traditionally one of our
best shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Food and water are at the top of shopping lists, but buyers are
also investing in $269 PowerPony generators from California and
$219 water filters guaranteed to eliminate 99.99 percent of E. coli
bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   At Cheaper than Dirt in Fort Worth, ready-to-eat meals are
selling like hot cakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are buying meals like crazy,'' said Dan Grant, manager
at Cheaper Than Dirt, a Fort Worth store that sells camping and
outdoor survival supplies. ``We've had orders from people buying it
by the truckloads _ that's $104,000 worth of ready-to-eat meals.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Anderson, a Hurst woman who has written a book called
``Y2K For Women,'' said that if consumers spend an extra $10 a week
on basics they'll have six months' worth of food stored by Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   She suggests buying beans, rice, oil, sugar, pasta, unscented
bleach and maybe some chocolate along with a gallon of water a
week. Even if Y2K turns out to be nothing, the food can be eaten or
given away. If the worst happens people will be ready, she said.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   Katie Moore, of Carrollton, has been storing seeds, beans,
greens and other supplies over the past year. She has also
purchased a solar oven and generator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started in October,'' she said. ``I wish I had started
sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   The demand for generators is revving up to an unprecedented
pitch at Lawn &AMP; Garden Warehouse of Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big generators are on national back order,'' said Milton
Banks, spokesman for the store. ``These are all Y2K people, 'cause
we never used to have calls for these. It all started around New
Year's. People are frightened.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost for a 6,500-watt Honda generator that will provide
electricity for a large house is $3,400. A 1,000-watt generator
that would run a television and VCR costs $780. The little ones are
still available, but Banks said he's got 15 big ones back-ordered
and he could sell them immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Other items that are fast disappearing are radios and
flashlights that don't depend on batteries.
</P>
<P>
   A $99.95 wind-up radio from South Africa that has been on order
since January is not expected to be shipped until May, Hopkins
said.
</P>
<P>
   This minor inconvenience is just a warm-up for what some believe
lies ahead. The doomsayers predict food and fuel shortages, power
disruptions and possibly looting in the streets as those who didn't
prepare try to take advantage of those who did.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, only a fraction of the public is buying into the
idea of any kind of Y2K catastrophe. The majority of Americans are
ignoring or denying it, Hopkins said. In her opinion, the rush to
get last-minute supplies on New Year's Eve will resemble a scene
from a disaster movie.
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate the demand, Cheaper than Dirt has 78 telephone
operators to take orders. Once a business that catered to campers
and survivalists, Cheaper than Dirt has seen its business grow
since last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get three to six truckloads of ready-to-eat meals a week
now, compared to maybe a truckload every two weeks in the past,''
Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce and Phyllis Hopkins moved their home-based side business
out of their living room and into a 17,000-square-foot warehouse
when sales rocketed from $120,000 in 1997 to $3 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last January it started going crazy, and by May I had to quit
my job,'' Phyllis Hopkins said. ``I didn't get any sleep all night
because people were faxing things.''
</P>
<P>
   Their customers include programmers, church groups and lots of
grandmothers ordering for their families. Orders come from as far
away as Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicken Little syndrome has apparently hit hardest in
California, Washington and Texas, where many of Hopkins' customers
live.
</P>
<P>
   Most people adhere to the philosophy that the problem will be
solved by somebody.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of the world is in denial on this,'' Hopkins said.
``Life is going to be real interesting for a while. The people who
don't do anything are going to go nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Big businesses have started to address the Y2K bug, but many
small businesses and doctors' offices are far from solving it,
Anderson said. An estimated 90 percent of doctor's offices and half
of small- to medium-sized businesses have yet to address the
computer problem, according to a U.S. Senate committee report on
compliance. And 64 percent of hospitals, most of them small, have
no plans to test their Y2K efforts simply because they can't afford
to, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fears of lack of access to medical facilities has led some
proponents to push people to stock up on prescription and
over-the-counter drugs and other emergency supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials have said the best way to prepare is to
have enough food on hand to last several days, enough cash to last
the holiday weekend and at least a half-tank of gas in the car.
Fortunately, the technology in most cars is not sensitive to the
Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
   In the event that someone has to go without food for a while,
there are survival tabs available that provide protein to sustain
essential body tissues. They cost $27 for 180, enough to last two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Just how long the Y2K crisis might last is debatable. While many
predict it will never happen, others are stocking up for an entire
year.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is among those who believe that people have nothing to
lose by hoarding food that they can always eat or share with
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not a downside to preparing for emergencies,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
