<HEADER>
A4810 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRADLEY-PROFILE-ART-2     04-19 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-PROFILE-ART-2TAKES(1,235)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY EMERGES AS NO. 1 ALTERNATIVE TO GORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Bradley is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey likes to
tell audiences that in 1988 he looked at himself in the mirror and
said, ``You're not ready.'' He decided not to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, he says, ``there was something inside me that
said, `No. Don't do this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But by last fall, he recalls, he looked in the mirror again and
told himself: ``I'm at the top of my game. I'm going to run for
president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Only months ago, many Democrats questioned Bradley's timing.
They argued that he passed up his best chance in 1992 _ and that
trying to triumph over an incumbent vice president was a quixotic,
even foolhardy, exercise.
</P>
<P>
   But now, largely because of circumstances that Bradley had
nothing to do with, few political professionals dismiss his
prospects outright, even as they concede that Vice President Al
Gore remains the clear favorite for the nomination. That is because
Bradley has already captured the prize for which nearly a dozen
contenders on the Republican side are arduously competing: to
emerge as the alternative should Gore falter.
</P>
<P>
   The parade of other Democrats who had planned to take on Gore
has evaporated, leaving a simple dynamic. If Gore does not get the
nomination, Bradley does. Never before in a modern-day contest for
an open White House has the competition been distilled to two
people so early.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Al Gore and I, one-on-one, for 11 months,'' said Bradley,
who is as much known as a basketball star at Princeton University
and for the New York Knicks as for his 18 years in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   As the only alternative to Gore, Bradley is in a much stronger
position than he would have been had other Democrats, including
Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the House minority leader, Sen.
Paul Wellstone of Minnesota, and Jesse Jackson, not bailed out. He
will automatically draw all of the negative vote from those people
who dislike Gore or President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   And Bradley will command far more attention from the press, and
from voters. On Tuesday, for instance, he plans to highlight his
long interest in race relations with a speech in New York that will
in part address the case of Amadou Diallo, the unarmed West African
immigrant who was shot and killed by city police officers. It is
the latest attempt by Bradley to promote so-called ``big ideas'' to
contrast himself with small-bore initiatives advanced by Gore, like
combating local traffic congestion.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., who decided not to challenge Gore, said
Bradley has the potential to win the nomination. ``Any time there's
only two people in the race there's a possibility,'' he said.
``Bradley has two things people like: He was a good basketball
player and he's smart. If he adds a third one, that he's a leader,
he'll be tough.''
</P>
<P>
   It is an enviable political perch: As the early favorite, Gore
faces pressure not only to prevail in the early contests, but also
to win overwhelmingly. Even if Bradley gains a respectable
percentage of the vote but ultimately loses, he can still win
plaudits as a dragon slayer who came close to toppling an incumbent
vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bradley has yet to prove that he is the best candidate to
make the most of the one-on-one dynamic. The reality is that Gore's
weaknesses are not necessarily Bradley's strengths. Both are known
as more cerebral, even shy, than back-slapping politicians. Both
are often less-than-compelling orators. And it is difficult to
decipher any momentous issue differences between the two, beyond
that Bradley opposed the administration's welfare reform measure.
He feared that it would force mothers to abandon their children for
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's reputation as somewhat plodding is sometimes evident
in his campaign speeches. In a talk to contributors in Palm Beach,
Fla., recently, he hardly sounded convincing when he said, ``Now,
the question is, `Can you win?' And the answer is, `Absolutely.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he came alive at a Democratic Party convention in
Manchester, N.H., earlier this month when he delighted the
audience, and underscored his appeal as a celebrity, with tales
from his basketball days. He also puts forth a personal side.
Everywhere he goes, he says he is thankful that he did not run in
1992 because his wife, Ernestine, was diagnosed that year with
breast cancer and has since recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Though at 6-foot-5 Bradley looks a bit awkward loping about,
mingling with voters, his admirers often walk away from him with
the same response: He is more charming than they expected, and
would be a clean break from the scandalous Clinton years.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Bradley said he doubted that those who
questioned his campaigning skills ``have ever been out with me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on the road for 30 years,'' he said, ``and all those
years I've either been performing in short pants, campaigning for
people or earning money on the road. Now I'm out campaigning for
the presidency, and it's the ultimate exhilaration.''
</P>
<P>
   Insisting that the contest was serious business for him, Bradley
said, ``I don't get into it unless I can see my way through to 270,
which are the electoral votes needed to be president.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's biggest arguments for why voters should turn to him
are that he has had a more varied life experience than Gore, who
was the son of a senator, and more ambitious ideas. ``I had a life
before I got into politics,'' he tells audiences.
</P>
<P>
   His supporters also emphasize that Bradley has a
long-established reputation as championing campaign reform, and
that his ethics have never been questioned. That, they say, would
make a pointed contrast to the Clinton years and the questions that
have been raised about Gore's efforts to raise money in the 1996
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Bradley, who retired from the Senate in 1996, has yet
to put forward many specifics about what he would do as president.
He has been reluctant, for example, to spell out how the
administration should be handling the most pressing matter of the
day: the crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's advisers, already devising arguments to undermine their
competitor, say that it is disingenuous for Bradley, who is 55, to
cast himself as a Washington outsider because he was a senator a
decade longer than the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore advisers were clearly unnerved that Bradley collected
$4.3 million in the first three months of the year, an impressive
sum even though it did not approach the $8.9 million amassed by
Gore in the same period. The fact that Gore has an opponent has
also prompted him to display his political might by taking steps
like staging a formal endorsement with Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has nowhere near the endorsements or the vast staff of
the Gore organization. Not one member of Congress, not even from
New Jersey, has publicly signed on to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bradley has assembled a skilled staff, including many
longtime advisers, although they still seem to be struggling with
the unexpected demands placed upon the second candidate in a
two-person matchup.
</P>
<P>
   Insisting that he was well aware of, but unfazed by Gore's
institutional advantages, Bradley offers a sweeping, yet rather
vague, explanation for how he can prevail: ``Ultimately, the people
decide these elections and they decide them on the basis of who's
speaking to their lives and who do they feel is speaking most
clearly about the future of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's unexpected position as an underdog to be reckoned with
is in part an outgrowth of Gore's miscalculations. Though the vice
president shrewdly scared off potential rivals who were intimidated
by his seeming invincibility, he did not take Bradley's intentions
as seriously as he did the others.
</P>
<P>
   Early polls show that Gore's support is quite shallow and that
Bradley has gained significant ground in the polls in recent weeks,
though he remains far behind Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley strategy is founded on the premise that voters in
the two most pivotal early contests, the Iowa caucuses and the New
Hampshire primary, sometimes pride themselves on being contrary and
do not always reward the expected winner. Bradley hopes he will
emerge in one or both of those early contests. He is also wooing
independent voters and even Republicans, with some success, judging
by the turnout at various events.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Schnitzer, a New Jersey resident who calls himself ``a
snowbird'' because he spends his winters in Florida, said at a
Bradley event in Palm Beach that he opposes Gore because ``he's a
little too much in the Clinton image.'' But, he said, he is worried
that beyond the mid-Atlantic states, Bradley may strike voters as
``too Eastern, too liberal, too intellectual.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's advisers dismiss Bradley as the Gary Hart of 2000. In the
1984 Democratic primaries, Hart, at the time a Colorado senator,
emerged as the alternative to former Vice President Walter F.
Mondale, and, like Bradley, portrayed himself as the thoughtful
candidate with big ideas. Hart jolted the Democratic Party by
winning the New Hampshire primary, but his candidacy imploded when
he was accused of adultery. Mondale recovered the momentum with a
heavy advertising campaign and by posing this question about Hart's
vaunted ideas: ``Where's the beef?''
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley's advisers contend that because of the newly
compressed primary schedule in 2000, a victory in Iowa or New
Hampshire will make him unstoppable as the race turns quickly to
big states like California and New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Gore maintains his standing, Bradley probably can't do
anything,'' said John Haskell, a professor of political science at
Drake University in Des Moines. ``But if the economy went bad, or
if you get lucky in some primary _ Gore makes a stupid mistake _ it
can really snowball because of the front-loaded primaries.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Though Gore has established far more extensive organizations,
Bradley has the advantage of being able to campaign full time _ and
without being captive to Air Force 2 and other trappings _ which
can be important in early states where one-on-one contact with
voters is crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difficulty Gore faces now in Iowa and New Hampshire is
that these are both states where he has never really campaigned on
his own behalf before and there's an inherent need in those
constituencies to see him up closer in a more retail way,'' said
William Carrick, a veteran Democratic strategist. ``Obviously,
that's easier for Bradley to do than for Gore. You're hearing
rumblings that Bradley's doing well _ but it's easier for him to
get out and touch people.''
</P>
<P>
   The hard part, Carrick noted, is advancing from No. 1
alternative to the nominee. ``We have a history of the process
producing significant and serious challenges to the established
front-runner,'' he said. ``But it's a 50-50 thing whether they win
or not.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, over lunch in Palo Alto, Calif., where Bradley was a
fellow at Stanford University, he recalled what he did not miss
about his old job: ``Who needed to be stroked? Who needed to be
called? Who needed to be reasoned with? Who in the press were our
allies? Who were our enemies? How do we convince four or five
people on the other side you need to have to make something really
go. It's just a different time.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked then whether he had the stomach or endurance to dive back
into the most competitive political arena of all, he shrugged and
said, ``Who knows? Who knows?''
</P>
</TEXT>
