<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIA-MARKETPLACE-805&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIA'S STOCK MARKETS ARE RISING AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Stock markets from Seoul to Singapore soared Monday,
extending a rally that many analysts here say is proof that foreign
investors are returning in large numbers to the recession-ravaged
economies of Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something fundamental is happening,'' said Miron Mushkat, the
head of global economics and strategy at Indocam Asia Asset
Management in Hong Kong. ``The markets are telling us that the
Asian crisis is over. We are moving from deeply dark territory into
the land of the light.''
</P>
<P>
   The euphoria was most pronounced on the Jakarta Stock Exchange
in Indonesia, where shares jumped 6 percent. But the gains were
impressive throughout the region: 5.7 percent in Seoul, South
Korea; 5.5 percent in Manila, the Philippines; 4.1 percent in
Singapore; 2.7 percent in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia; and 2.2 percent
in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   The Nikkei index in Tokyo was the only exception, falling 1.1
percent after a string of powerful gains last week.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the general sense of a better tomorrow, analysts said
several factors were driving the rally. Asian governments have
aggressively cut interest rates; on Monday the Philippines cut
rates for the 10th time this year. Foreign-fund managers are
steering more money to the region, in part because technology
stocks in the United States have lost some of their appeal after
troubles at Compaq Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people shift out of technology stocks, they tend to look
at cyclical stocks and overseas opportunities,'' said Marc Faber,
managing director of Marc Faber Ltd., an investment firm in Hong
Kong. ``People do feel that the crisis in emerging economies
worldwide is over.''
</P>
<P>
   The rally in Asian stock markets is all the more remarkable
because it bears no relation to the underlying health of the
economies. In Hong Kong, for example, the government announced
Monday that unemployment reached a record rate of 6.2 percent in
the three months from January through March.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted, the Hang Seng index roared past the 13,000 level
before closing at 12,766. The Hang Seng, which has risen 17 percent
just this month, has regained all the ground lost since it crashed
in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors said they were alarmed by this performance
because it could lull government officials and business executives
into thinking the hard times were over. With money pouring into
Asia, some analysts predict that efforts toward fundamental
economic changes could bog down in Indonesia, Thailand and
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a once-in-a-blue-moon opportunity to sort out Asia,''
said Bill Kaye, the senior managing director of the Pacific Group,
an asset-management firm in Hong Kong. ``But here we are, back to
the races.''
</P>
<P>
   Faber said, ``The big problem with falling interest rates and
surging liquidity is that it lessens the incentives to pursue deep
reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Indonesia recently took steps to clean up its insolvent
banking system, the restructuring process has been extremely slow
in Malaysia and Thailand. In Hong Kong, the robust market belies an
economy that has failed to reduce costs, despite a reduction in
costs of rival economies like Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that shares in Seoul rose Monday because of hopes
that South Korea's largest conglomerates were finally reducing
their bloated operations. The leaders of LG Group and Hyundai
Group, for example, met Monday to discuss plans for a subsidiary of
Hyundai to acquire LG's electronics unit, LG Semicon.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are not the only people expressing a belief that the
worst is over in Asia. The Asian Development Bank said Monday that
the economic downturn had hit bottom, and it predicted that the
region would return to economic growth this year.
</P>
<P>
   In its annual report issued in Manila, the president of the
bank, Tadao Chino, said: ``I believe the worst of the financial
crisis is over. This gives us reason to expect that 1999 will see
notable improvements in economic performance.''
</P>
<P>
   The development bank predicted that Asia, excluding Japan, would
grow at an average annual rate of 4.4 percent in 1999 and 5.1
percent in 2000. That compares with 2.6 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Though the performance of Asian stock markets is impressive,
analysts pointed out two caveats.
</P>
<P>
   First, the volume of trading on some markets _ notably Jakarta _
is much smaller than it was before the crisis. So a relatively
small infusion of capital can cause a large percentage increase.
</P>
<P>
   Second, investors are aggressively buying shares in major public
companies like HSBC Holdings, the parent of Hong Kong and Shanghai
Banking Corp., which hit an all-time high of $284 (Hong Kong), or
$36.64 (U.S.), before closing at $280 (Hong Kong), or $36.12
(U.S.). But that does not mean that money is flowing to the small
and medium-size companies, the backbone of many Asian countries.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``There is this disconnect between the large-cap stocks and the
carnage of small companies down below,'' said John Pinkel, a
partner at Shaw, Kwei &AMP; Partners Ltd., a Hong Kong fund that
invests in smaller companies.
</P>
<P>
   For all the caveats, however, forecasters do not see an end to
the rally soon. As the sentiment about Asia improves, more fund
managers in the United States and Europe are expected to divert
capital to these markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to predict anything when we make these
qualitative leaps,'' Mushkat said. ``Our year-end target for the
Hang Seng was 12,000, which seems rather irrelevant right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
