<SLUG> BC-DOGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPLE SUES CITY OF HOUSTON AFTER DOGS MISTAKENLY PUT TO SLEEP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RON NISSIMOV 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A couple whose two pedigree golden retrievers were
mistakenly euthanized by the city's animal control department in
September has sued the city for an unspecified amount.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about money,'' said Pam Beckert, who filed the
state district lawsuit late last week with her husband, Donald
Beckert.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never got an apology from anybody, and they never answered
our questions as to how this happened,'' she said Monday. ``We hope
this will make some difference and hopefully it won't happen to
anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   The Beckerts claim in their lawsuit that the city's Bureau of
Animal Regulation and Care violated its policy by putting the dogs
to sleep within hours after they were picked up in the Kingwood
area of Houston on Sept. 4. According to city guidelines, stray
dogs are supposed to be kept for at least three days before being
euthanized.
</P>
<P>
   The Beckerts also assert in the lawsuit that they repeatedly
called the animal control department from Sept. 4-8 and were
wrongly told the dogs had not been picked up.
</P>
<P>
   The Beckerts' attorney, Gary Polland, said he doesn't know the
monetary amount his clients will seek, but under state law the
maximum they could get by suing the city is $250,000,
</P>
<P>
   City officials declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The dogs, 8-year-old Christi and 6-year-old Duncan, 6, slipped
out of the Beckerts' yard on Sept. 4 shortly after receiving a
bath. Their collars had not been put back on since they were still
wet.
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor spotted the dogs and placed them in her yard and then
called the animal control department to have them picked up because
she did not have time to look for the owners, the lawsuit said. The
neighbor, who was leaving for the Labor Day Weekend, could not wait
for animal control officials to arrive at her house, so she faxed
them permission to enter her yard and retrieve the dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Animal control officials apparently thought the woman who called
them was the owner and that she wanted them euthanized. Since the
dogs were not considered strays, animal control officials did not
have to wait three days before euthanizing them.
</P>
<P>
   Under city guidelines, people who request that their dogs be
euthanized must sign affidavits of ownership. The neighbor never
signed such an affidavit, Kathy Barton, spokeswoman for the city
Health and Human Services Department, which oversees animal
control, said in September. This requirement is sometimes waived if
the owner is under duress.
</P>
<P>
   Barton said at the time she doubted that the animal control
department would continue to allow such waivers in light of what
happened to the Beckerts' dogs.
</P>
<P>
   But the couple's attorney said Monday he doesn't think the city
has changed any euthanization procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Beckert said the dogs _ which she calls her ``first
children'' because she and her husband acquired them before any of
their three children were born _ are greatly missed.
</P>
<P>
   She said her 5-year-old daughter constantly asks about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell her they went to doggy heaven,'' Pam Beckert said.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
