<SLUG> BC-BANANA-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE GROUP APPROVES A PENALTY IN BANANA WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ The United States received the World Trade
Organization's formal approval on Monday to impose $191.4 million
in punitive tariffs on European goods in a protracted fight over
European banana imports. But the effective date of the sanctions
was still in dispute.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first time in the four years the world trade group
has been in existence that such retaliation had been approved, and
only the second such retaliatory step going back to its
predecessor, the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has maintained for six years that the European
Union unfairly discriminates against bananas from Latin American
countries, which are exported by U.S. companies, in favor of those
grown and exported from former European colonies, mostly in the
Caribbean. The trade group agreed with the U.S. complaint earlier
this month, although it reduced the amount of damages sought from
an original $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the European trade commissioner, Sir Leon Brittan,
said that the European Union would not appeal. But on Monday, the
Europeans' delegate here, Roderick Abbott disputed the effective
date of the sanctions, arguing that they were not retroactive to
March 3, the date the United States contended. ``It is normal that
a decision applies from the day that it was taken,'' Abbott said.
</P>
<P>
   Rita Hayes, the U.S. representative to the World Trade
Organization, disagreed and said that notice of the tariffs was to
be posted in Monday's Federal Register.
</P>
<P>
   Tariffs of 100 percent will be levied on a range of products
that includes lithographs, bed linens, German coffee makers, French
plastic handbags, cardboard packing material and lead-acid storage
batteries. The sanctions effectively double the price of the
imports and make them much harder, if not impossible, to sell in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   European and U.S. officials will meet Wednesday in an attempt to
negotiate an effective date for the sanctions, but a compromise
could be difficult. Abbott noted that the interests of the two
sides ``are diametrically opposed.''
</P>
<P>
   If the two sides cannot agree on a date, the matter would be
referred to the WTO's dispute-resolution process. But Mrs. Hayes
said the United States and the Europeans could settle the matter
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The retaliatory sanctions were the first to be imposed since
1952, when the Netherlands acted against the United States in a
dispute over dairy products. The victorious Dutch got approval to
reduce the number of metric tons of U.S. ground wheat flour they
imported.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to approving the U.S. sanctions on Monday, a
three-member arbitration panel reaffirmed the illegality of the
European Union's banana-import policy.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how or even when the Europeans will amend that
policy, but Abbott said Monday that any changes soon were unlikely,
because of European Parliament elections in June and the likelihood
that a new executive agency would not be in place in Brussels,
Belgium, until the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hayes said the ``only deadline is compliance,'' leaving the
European Union presumably in the position of paying the tariffs
until it makes its import policy acceptable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
