<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ADRIATIC-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVA CASTS A SHADOW OVER ADRIATIC RESORTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 25) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The bombing and the refugee crisis in Yugoslavia are
affecting vacation travel in some areas on the Adriatic Sea, and
not others _ so far. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Resorts on the Dalmatian coast, on the eastern shore of the
Adriatic, report dwindling numbers of visitors, and tourists have
largely abandoned Apulia, across the Adriatic on the heel of
Italy's boot.
</P>
<P>
   But in Venice tour operators and hotel owners are holding their
breath. The war has not affected tourism there, and indeed, the
Easter season was one of Venice's brightest ever _ perhaps, tourism
officials say, even buoyed by the decision of major cruise ship
operators to reroute their vessels from Croatian ports like
Dubrovnik to ports in Italy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than any other region, the Dalmatian coast of Croatia is
hurting. ``Tourism is suffering, even though it is peaceful and
quiet here,'' said Mives Milos, spokeswoman for the tourism board
of Dubrovnik, the ancient seaport that is the area's principal
attraction. ``People think we are too close to the war, and the
name Dubrovnik is associated with Yugoslavia.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tourism had begun to revive from the shaking it took during the
brutal three-year Bosnian war. When that conflict ended in 1995,
tourists began trickling back to Dalmatia, the narrow finger of
Croatian territory that inches down the Adriatic's eastern shore _
albeit in numbers far below what they had been before the fighting
began.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 tourist arrivals in Croatia rose 9.5 percent, to 4.2
million. Martin Brackenbury, chairman of the World Tourism
Organization's business council, said that travel bookings to
Dalmatia were ``not looking as good as we would like.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last April, Ms. Milos said, Dubrovnik counted 13,526 visitors to
its narrow lanes and medieval ramparts. In the first 12 days of
this April, only 1,307 visitors came, more than 80 percent of them
from Croatia and neighboring Bosnia-Herzegovina. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dubrovnik's airport, on the bluffs above the Adriatic, was
closed for several days at the outset of the NATO air strikes; it
has reopened, but only for flights to and from the Croatian capital
of Zagreb. Other connections, like Alitalia's scheduled
twice-weekly flight between Rome and Dubrovnik, have been suspended
indefinitely. Dubrovnik's hotels, which have 7,000 beds, remain
open, Ms. Milos said, yet only about 200 visitors a day are
arriving.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dubrovnik and other Croatian ports have also been hurt by the
caution of major cruise lines, including Windstar Cruises, Holland
America, Silversea, and the Carnival Corp.'s Seabourn Cruise Lines
and Cunard Line, which have replaced stops there with stops in
Italy and Greece. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dalmatia's plight is in marked contrast to the exuberance in
most Italian cities on the Adriatic, including Venice, though some
regions of Italy, like Apulia, are suffering a flight of visitors
similar to Dubrovnik's. Ferry operators in Italian Adriatic ports
like Ancona have seen travelers eastward dwindle, and elsewhere
Italian officials fear that if the fighting continues or escalates,
they too may be affected. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had any signs of cancellations,'' said Pierluigi
Bolla, commissioner for tourism in the Veneto region, of which
Venice is a principal attraction. In resorts like Jesolo, he said,
hotels just reopened for the season were not sufficient to absorb
the tourist invasion.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But farther down Italy's Adriatic coast, in Ancona, the
principal port for embarkation to Dalmatia, ferry operators report
a sharp drop in travelers that reminds them of the dark years of
the Bosnian conflict. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the tourism research group of Confcommercio,
the Italian retailers' association, said that statistics were not
yet available, but that anecdotal evidence indicated that Easter
was a problem in Apulia. In March, after the bombing began, Italy
declared a state of emergency in the region, both for its proximity
to the Yugoslav republic of Montenegro, 120 miles across the
Adriatic, and the possibility of large numbers of refugees from
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   At Brindisi and Bari, Apulia's major cities, the commercial
airports remain closed, forcing travelers to use the Naples
airport, a 120-mile bus ride to the west. Three NATO bases from
which warplanes are launched toward Kosovo _ in Brindisi, Gioia del
Colle and Amendola _ are there, and anti-aircraft missile launchers
and mobile radar units have been deployed along the region's broad
white beaches, frightening tourists away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Florentine schoolchildren on a recent outing to Torre
Cintola, an Apulian resort, telephoned home with excited reports of
missile emplacements near their hotel, so many calls were made to
the school by concerned parents that the trip was curtailed. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
