<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4833 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-MONTENEGRO     04-19 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-MONTENEGRO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERB DRAFT CALL TO MONTENEGRIN MEN CAUSES FRICTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA, Yugoslavia _ With his aviator sunglasses, bomber
lapel pin and Bruce Willis-style attitude and haircut, Velko
Vlahovic looks every part the fighter pilot. But like so many men
here facing conscription by the Yugoslav military to fight,
Vlahovic doesn't know what he would do if Slobodan Milosevic's
forces demanded that he fight in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As a Yugoslav Air Force reservist, Vlahovic has dedicated much
of his life to aviation _ flying for the air fleet, painting
picture-perfect images of military aircraft, and participating in
air shows with his many friends in the US Air Force and British
Royal Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   His photo albums are filled with pictures of smiling American
military pilots, their arms slung around Vlahovic's broad
shoulders. The 31-year-old half-Serb, half-Montenegrin pilot still
e-mails a US Air Force buddy in Aviano, Italy, where NATO planes
are stationed for the attack on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Vlahovic considers himself what he calls a
``Yugoslav Hamlet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to fly, but I don't want to kill anyone, especially my
friends,'' said Vlahovic. He has received a draft notice, but
convinced the Army that it was a mistake, since he is an Air Force
reservist and pilots have not yet been called up.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro, which, with Serbia, makes up Yugoslavia, is
determined to stay out of the war in Kosovo. Part of its civil
disobediance has been a defiance of the Yugoslav Army's aggressive
effort to conscript Montenegrin men between 18 and 65.
</P>
<P>
   Even the 42-year-old Justice Minister, Dragan Soc, has received
three draft notices _ all of which he has defied. ``I think it's
politically provoked,'' said Soc, whose Montenegrin government
opposes Milosevic and the Yugoslav President's policies in Kosovo.
``There is no army in the world which calls up a minister in the
government into service in the infantry with a gun _ except mine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Milosevic regime also renewed its demand that Montenegro's
deputy prime minister, Novak Kilibarda, be arrested and tried in a
military court for his anti-conscription statements.
</P>
<P>
   ``They chose me as an example,'' said Kilibarda in an interview.
``I feel proud they are prosecuting me. It's like they are giving
me a medal against Milosevic's policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Kilibarda is heavily guarded, spending his nights at a local
hotel. Two Montenegrin police officers stand at the entrance of the
floor, wielding assault weapons. Bodyguards shadow him as he
attends sessions of Parliament and teaches at a local university.
Soc doesn't bother with extra protection. His house is directly
across the street from the military court, which could try him if
he continues to defy the Army. Soc salutes them as he walks past.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just part of the special psychological war between civil
authorities and Milosevic's military authorities,'' Soc said.
</P>
<P>
   Soc's open and confident defiance is typical of people here.
Vastly outnumbered in population (a half million in Montenegro
against 10 million in Serbia) and in military capability (a maximum
10,000 Montenegrin police versus 20,000 Yugoslav Army troops
already stationed in Kosovo), Montenegrins say they would take up
arms to fight for their own republic _ be it against Serbia or
against NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a pacifist,'' and so refused the Yugoslav Army's
conscription effort, said 24-year-old Alem Mlatisuma. But he said
he would fight if Montenegro were attacked. ``The line between a
war criminal and a pacifist is very thin,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Soc said he did not know how many men had dodged the draft; the
estimated 25,000 Montenegrins who did answer the call are either
loyal to Serbia or felt obligated to follow the Yugoslav order, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Montenegrin government does not recognize Milosevic's
declaration of war, and so says the aggressive conscription and
attempt to arrest Kilibarda are illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Local Montenegrin authorities are trying to protect men from the
draft by declaring that their civilian work is critical to hold
together the already-dismal Montenegrin and Yugoslav economies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly don't do anything as a government to forbid
people from being conscripted,'' said Radomir Sekulovic, a senior
advisor to the Montenegrin government. The local authorities simply
told business owners that they should draw up a list of the
indispensable employees _ and ``you can guess'' that the list
includes draft-age men, Sekulovic said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Milosevic regime hasn't made the final push _
arresting government ministers, or imposing martial law here. But
locals fear the day is coming. Montenegrin political leaders and
residents alike display a remarkable willingness to take on a
stronger enemy. Sekulovic insisted that the local police force _
combined with police reservists, could wipe out the Yugoslav
National Army.
</P>
<P>
   He ridicules the Yugoslav Army troops, which are now spread out
through Montenegro, reportedly having abandoned their barracks
because they are afraid they will be bombed by NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is their level of courage, their bravery, go ahead _
they can hide under the skirts of women here,'' Sekulovic said.
``We see it as a sign of weakness'' of the Yugoslav Army, he said.
But Montenegrins, caught in the middle between NATO and the
Yugoslav federation _ a country they love, led by a regime they
despise _ aren't picking a fight.
</P>
<P>
   Many Montenegrins have fond remembrances of the days when
Yugoslavia, then made up of six republics, was in the globally
unusual position of being accepted by both the Western capitalist
world and the Eastern communist one.
</P>
<P>
   Under the rule of Josep ``Tito'' Broz, from the 1940s to the
1980s, Yugoslavs could go virtually anywhere with their passports.
Yugoslavia sided with the Americans in both world wars.
</P>
<P>
   Since the brutal Balkan wars of this decade and under the
leadership of Milosevic, Serbia has become a closed state. It's
difficult for foreigners to get in, difficult for locals to travel
out, and the republic is suffering from both air strikes and
international economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegrins, meanwhile, still look to the West, even as they
cry for a halt to the air strikes against both Montenegro and
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The office wall of the Information Secretariat here has a
portrait, not of Milosevic or even of Montenegrin President Milo
Djukanovic, but one of a smiling, young Tito. Vlahovic's photo
album shows the odd contradiction: There are photos of him standing
alongside a Yugoslav fighter plane, armed with American-made
Stinger missiles. In another, he is in a cockpit with the chief
flight tester for a major US aerospace company.
</P>
<P>
   A picture of his mother shows her, in typical 1960's style
bouffant hair and minidress, standing proudly by the family's
then-fashionably pink 1966 Ford.
</P>
<P>
   One of his recent e-mails from his US Air Force friend said the
American pilot had just returned from a bombing mission in Iraq,
and noted wryly that ``we almost came by to drop bombs on you at
Christmas and New Year's.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea that Vlahovic could end up on the other side in an air
war against his e-mail pal is something he can't contemplate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have got so many friends among US Air Force pilots,''
Vlahovic said, closing his photo album. ``I do not know what I
would do in that situation, if they called me up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
