<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ WOES: POOR STRATEGY OR MANAGEMENT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The abrupt ouster of Compaq Computer Corp.'s chief executive
this weekend revealed a fundamental debate about the world's
largest PC maker: are its recent financial woes the result of a
flawed strategy, or simply poor management?
</P>
<P>
   In his eight years at the helm of Compaq, CEO Eckhard Pfeiffer
built the company from a troubled manufacturing operation into a
broad technology competitor. His purchase of Digital Equipment
Corp. last year for $9.1 billion symbolized Compaq's transformation
into a full-service firm able to sell everything from handheld
digital assistants to systems that power stock exchanges and banks.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue from Digital's former services line has grown 10 percent
in the past year, analysts estimate, and Compaq also hopes to
profit from AltaVista, Digital's innovative Internet search-engine
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the effort to diversify hasn't eliminated Compaq's exposure
to competition in its chief line of business: building personal
computers for consumers and corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Compaq said first-quarter profits would be half of
what was expected, sending its stock down 22 percent. Shares fell
3/4 to close at 22 7/8 in New York Stock Exchange trading Monday,
about half the level they traded at in January.
</P>
<P>
   Now critics worry the company has failed to integrate Digital
and other disparate pieces into a cohesive whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not clear what Compaq is or what it stands for in the
market,'' said Merrill Lynch analyst Steve Milunovich. ``They're
not blowing the cover off the ball,'' said BT Alex Brown analyst
Phil Rueppel.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts Monday, Compaq Chairman
Benjamin Rosen rejected those opinions and said the Digital deal
and others mean the company ``can offer more complete solutions''
to customers than specialized competitors like Dell Computer Corp.,
which sells computers directly over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The main problem lies in putting the broader strategy into
practice, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've fully exploited the potential of Digital
but I think we're well on our way,'' said Rosen, who now shares
Pfeiffer's duties with other board members pending a search for a
permanent replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq says it has completed the bulk of the work needed to
integrate Digital with the rest of its operations, centered in
Texas. To profit from the boom in Internet stocks, Compaq plans to
sell shares in AltaVista to the public. Compaq also recently
purchased Shopping.com, an electronic commerce service, for $220
million to bolster AltaVista, which has lagged behind Yahoo Inc.
and Lycos Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq also has moved AltaVista to offices on the West Coast,
part of a broad reorganization of Digital assets.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak in the late 1980s Digital, based in Maynard, Mass.,
employed 30,000 workers in Massachusetts and New Hampshire,
including large operations where it assembled minicomputers and
PCs.
</P>
<P>
   But Digital was late to the personal-computer boom, and by the
time of its takeover was attractive mainly for its services unit,
which sets up and runs large corporate computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   With headquarters in Stow, Mass. and headed by former Digital
executive John Rando, Compaq Services now employs 27,000 workers
worldwide, including much of a staff of 7,000 in Massachusetts and
about 2,000 people at offices in Nashua, N.H. Another 2,000 people
assemble high-end server computers at a plant in Salem, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, Compaq also has service staffs in Shrewsbury,
Lexington, and Littleton and keeps an engineering office in
Marlborough. Shrewsbury is also the location for a unit that
develops information-storage systems.
</P>
<P>
   After the Digital deal, revenue from Compaq's services division
climbed to $3.7 billion last year from $462 million in 1997. Gross
profit margins for services were 32 percent, compared with 23
percent for the company as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't been enough to offset falling margins in Compaq's
main business segment, computer products, which fell to 22 percent
last year from 28 percent in 1997 amid stiffer competition from
rivals like IBM and Dell. Still, the 12.8 million PCs Compaq
shipped last year still made it the world's largest producer.
</P>
<P>
   IBM shipped 7.6 million and Dell shipped 7.3 million machines,
out of a total world market of 92.9 million, according to Gartner
Group's Dataquest unit.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to Rosen Monday, some analysts asked if the company
might abandon Pfeiffer's focus on building market share and
concentrate on increasing profits. Rosen declined to discuss the
tradeoff. ``We're not ready to answer that question, but it's an
excellent question and we're looking into it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Pfeiffer's removal, Compaq on Sunday said its former
chief financial officer, Earl Mason, had also departed to become
chief executive of another company. Rosen said Compaq plans to
allow the person it eventually selects for the top job to choose
the new chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq is due for several more days of scrutiny. Its
first-quarter results are due out Wednesday and the company's
annual meeting is set for Thursday in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Hiawatha Bray of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
