<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH DEFENDS SECURITY MEASURES IN TEXAS CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush said he had nothing to do
with a new policy that resulted in the arrests of four protesters
Monday outside the Governor's Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Some protesters complained the new rule was designed to squash
negative publicity about the governor as he considers a bid for the
Republican presidential nomination, but Bush and Texas Department
of Public Safety officials insisted that ongoing construction at
the mansion prompted the new policy.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush said it was solely the safety agency's call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't set the rules here,'' Bush told a news conference.
``They make the determination as to what's fair and what's not
fair.''
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Public Safety decided last month that
protesters will have to restrict their activities to an area across
the street from the front of the mansion. Previously, they could
protest on the same side of the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a crackdown at all. As I understand it, there are a
set of rules. People are given a chance to come and express
themselves. If they block passageway into our mansion, they're
given a warning,'' Bush said. ``If they continue to do it, the only
recourse is to move them off ... Some people don't mind busting the
rules, and there's a consequence.''
</P>
<P>
   The consequences were demonstrated Monday when four people
protesting a bill that would allow certain industries to cut
pollutants voluntarily were arrested because they refused to stay
in the designated area, according to the DPS.
</P>
<P>
   DPS spokesman Tom Vinger said the four were arrested on charges
of obstructing a passageway, a misdemeanor punishable by up to six
months in jail and a maximum $2,000 fine. About 25 people were
protesting when the arrests were made Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``DPS Capitol Police asked them three times to disband and go to
the designated area. Those who did not comply were placed under
arrest,'' Vinger said.
</P>
<P>
   He said DPS officials decided to designate the protest area
because they were concerned about public safety when large groups
assemble outside the Governor's Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a large group is on the sidewalk, other people are going
to have to walk into the street to walk around them,'' he noted.
``For everybody's safety, we decided to establish a protest area,
so that people can protest, but it won't hinder anyone's access.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has nothing to do with him running for president,'' Vigner
said, referring to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But protester James Scott, who works for the consumer group
Public Citizen, said he and the other picketers were only
exercising their right to free speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely think the Capitol Police were way out of line,
because this was just a peaceful protest,'' Scott said. ``They
weren't blocking anything at all. If anything was blocking the
entrance to the Governor's Mansion, it was the seven or eight cops
standing there looking ominous.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, there have been protests at the same location
with no problems,'' Scott said. ``They may have a heightened sense
of security because he's running for president ... and I would
understand that except he wasn't even there when we were
protesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush formed an exploratory presidential committee in March, but
he has said repeatedly he doesn't plan to make an official decision
on whether to run for president until after the state legislative
session ends on May 31.
</P>
<P>
   However, New York Times columnist William Safire on Monday
quoted Bush as saying: ``I am a candidate and I am going to be the
nominee. I think I am going to be the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he misspoke in the interview with Safire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot remember what the exact words were, but I have not
formally declared my candidacy, as you know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't actually seen the words'' in the column, he said.
``It should have been, `I'm still exploring.'
</P>
<P>
   ``If I run, I believe I have a very good chance to be the
nominee,'' Bush replied when pressed on the Safire interview. ``I
believe I'll be the nominee should I decide to run, but I've got a
lot of work to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if I run, I have a good chance to be nominated. If I'm
nominated, I've got a good chance to win, but I haven't formally
declared my candidacy,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
