<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-DECENCY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT UPHOLDS LAW BANNING OBSCENE E-MAIL SENT AS ANNOYANCE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Monday upheld a federal law
prohibiting computer users from sending obscene e-mail messages
intended to annoy their recipients.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual move, the justices affirmed without comment a
lower court's decision that ApolloMedia Corp. violated the 1996
Communications Decency Act with its ``www.annoy.com'' Web site, on
which people can send anonymous e-mail messages to public
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The lower court, a panel of three federal district court judges
in California, said the San Francisco-based company violated a
provision of the law that prohibits the transmission of a
``communication which is obscene, lewd, lascivious, filthy or
indecent with intent to annoy, abuse, threaten or harass another
person.''
</P>
<P>
   The messages ApolloMedia transmits to public officials via its
Web site are often laced with profanities and, some might say,
obscenities. In ruling against the company, the three-judge panel
said the law was valid, citing Supreme Court decisions that
obscenity is not protected under the First Amendment right to free
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, people who send obscene e-mail messages with the
intent to annoy can be sentenced to prison for up to two years.
</P>
<P>
   In its unsuccessful appeal to the high court, ApolloMedia argued
for a broad interpretation of the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``At stake ... is the right of ... all Internet users not to
have to live under the uncertain cloud of a statute that on its
face makes an indecent communication a felony,'' the company
argued.
</P>
<P>
   ApolloMedia President Clinton Fein, in a message on his
company's Web page, said that the free-speech rights of all people
were at stake in the Supreme Court appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This endeavor is not expedient, it is not politic and, indeed,
it more often than not, is not particularly popular,'' he said of
his company's legal challenge. ``Real free speech seldom is, but
fighting this battle is the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department had urged the justices to reject the
appeal, saying the federal government would not prosecute violators
of the law, such as ApolloMedia, unless their e-mail messages were
obscene.
</P>
<P>
   The decency act allows challenges to its constitutionality to be
appealed directly from a federal district court to the Supreme
Court without having to be considered first by an intermediate
appeals panel.
</P>
<P>
   The justices' unsigned, one-line decision in ApolloMedia vs.
Reno followed a 1997 ruling in which they struck down as
unconstitutionally broad a different provision of the decency law.
That provision had made it illegal for anybody to send ``obscene or
indecent'' material on the Internet that they knew could be seen by
someone under 18.
</P>
<P>
   While obscenity enjoys no constitutional safeguards, material
that is merely indecent is constitutionally protected, the court
said in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
