<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Washington) _ Yugoslav forces close the main
refugee crossing point into Albania, and White House officials work
through objections from NATO partners to the Clinton
administration's call for an oil blockade of Yugoslavia. By CRAGG
HINES.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-FUNDS (Washington) _ President Clinton asks Congress for
$6 billion for the Balkan conflict and for the refugee crisis in
the region, prompting a Republican pledge of a full debate on
Clinton's overall strategy. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-LEVIN (Washington) _ Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., just back
from a weekend in Albania and Macedonia, says Americans should be
prepared for a long air war, one lasting ``many months,'' in the
fight over Kosovo. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-EDUCATION (Washington) _ A new survey of science
teachers shows deep misgivings about how well American youngsters
are learning the subject, a level of concern that former astronaut
Mae Jemison characterized as a ``wakeup call'' alerting the nation
to lagging student achievement. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-DECENCY (Washington) _ The Supreme Court rules that a
federal law against obscene and lewd electronic mail is
constitutional. Critics argued that the law threatens free speech
on the Internet. By STEVE LASH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Austin, Texas) _ Gov. George W. Bush says he has
nothing to do with a new policy that resulted in the arrests of
four protesters outside the Governor's Mansion. Public safety
officials have imposed new security restrictions that restrict
protesters to an area across from the Governor's Mansion. By LAURA
TOLLEY. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BIRTH-CERTIFICATES (Houston) _ An emotional debate has flared
between adoptees who want access to their original birth
certificates and women clinging to their privacy, afraid or
unwilling to dredge up memories of what for many was the most
painful time of their lives. By CAROL CHRISTIAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   DOGS (Houston) _ A couple whose two pedigree golden retrievers
were mistakenly euthanized by the animal control department have
sued the city. ``This isn't about money,'' says Pam Beckert, who
filed the lawsuit with her husband, Donald Beckert. ``We never got
an apology from anybody and the never answered our questions as to
how this happened.'' By RON NISSIMOV. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPAQ-ANALYSIS (Houston) _ Eckhard Pfeiffer pulled Compaq out
of the ditch in 1991 and turned a $3 billion computer maker into a
$40 billion computer powerhouse. We take a look at what
precipitated the sudden departure of the chief executive. By DWIGHT
SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPAQ (Houston) _ We look at potential successors to Eckhard
Pfeiffer, the ousted chief executive of Compaq Computer Corp. By
TRICIA SERJU-HARRIS.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Houston) _ Companies typically will reveal only
the dates of employment and the position held by a former employee,
commonly known as ``name, rank and serial number'' in human
resource circles. But that means another company gets stuck with
the same problem employee. By L.M. SIXEL. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Originally First Lady Hillary
Clinton was picked on for being bossy, brassy and too brainy. Now
she's being scoffed at for planning to write a book about
entertaining at the White House, supposedly a homebody subject
inappropriate for a putative U.S. Senate candidate. This is silly.
The female Clinton has never been one-dimensional. By MARIANNE
MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ These are taxing times for
would-be presidents, including Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who paid
$3.77 million in federal income taxes on income of $18.4 million.
No wonder he is always crying out for tax relief. By CLAY ROBISON.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Houston) _ Coming off one of their most
demoralizing defeats of the season, the Houston Rockets try to
bounce back tonight with a home game against Seattle at the Compaq
Center. By JONATHAN FEIGEN. With: BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Houston) _ The Houston Astros have struggled so far
this season even though they have played mostly at home. Now as the
team heads into a stretch where it plays 12 of its next 16 games on
the road, the Astros feel the need to make up for lost time
starting Tuesday in Chicago against the division-rival Cubs. By
JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
