<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Tuesday, April 20, on the New York Times
wire. For questions, please call Marcus Chan at 415-777-8443 or the
business desk at 415-536-5172. For business stories running on Page
A1, call the news desk at 415-777-7074.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SALON _  &LR; Salon, an Internet media company, registers to sell 2.5
million shares at $10.50 to $13.50 a share. By Dan Fost
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNWIRED20 _  &LR; Unwired Planet, the Redwood City company that
provides information from the Internet to cell phones, is cashing
in on the Dot Com trend. The company, which plans to go public
later this month, will change its name to Phone.Com. By Deborah
Solomon
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STREET _  &LR; (column) Mark Veverka looks at the undervalued stocks
as the market shifts from tech to smokestack stocks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; MONEY BUDGET &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; PRIVACY _ &LR;  California may become the first state to give consumers
control over how information is used that's gleaned from
supermarket frequent-shopper programs like Safeway's Club card and
Lucky's Reward card. The chains use the programs to funnel
promotional dollars to the most loyal shoppers. But some
legislators are afraid that detailed information on shopping habits
and personal tastes could be used in nefarious ways, such as to
deny health benefits to heavy tobacco or liquor purchasers. Four
privacy rights bills are pending that seek to set controls over
this new goldmine of data collection. By Rebecca Smith
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONEYBAG _  &LR; Arthur Louis' money mailbag column.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
