<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-SPIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO SEES LOSSES ON THE PROPAGANDA FRONT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ NATO confirmed Monday it had probably killed fleeing
Kosovo refugees by mistake and at the same time began discreetly
beefing up its public relations apparatus, apparently worried that
it is in danger of losing the propaganda war even as it insists it
is winning the military one.
</P>
<P>
   While Europe's most prominent spin doctor worked behind the
scenes to bolster NATO's small, inexperienced publicity arm, the
alliance brought forward a commander leading the air war to admit
that his pilots may have inadvertently killed refugees.
</P>
<P>
   US Air Force Brigadier General Daniel Leaf stood in the briefing
room at NATO headquarters in Brussels, admitting his pilots bombed
vehicles in a convoy last week in which dozens of ethnic Albanian
refugees were killed, while Alastair Campbell, British Prime
Minister Tony Blair's press secretary, settled into an office just
down the corridor.
</P>
<P>
   Blair's office confirmed that Campbell had been asked by NATO
general secretary Javier Solana and NATO chief spokesman Jamie Shea
to advise them how to improve NATO's public relations strategy. A
Downing Street spokesman said Campbell would remain in Brussels
overseeing a revamping of NATO's public information office ``as
long as it would be helpful.'' Other NATO countries are also
expected to send in public information officers to help Shea, who
has a staff of just three despite representing the world's biggest
military alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell was invited in after last week's debacle in which NATO
admitted its forces had inadvertantly bombed a column of refugees,
released a tape recording of a pilot purportedly talking about why
he mistakenly bombed the refugees, then insisted the recording was
of a pilot who had actually bombed Yugoslav forces, not civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Among the press secretaries of the various European leaders,
Campbell is widely considered the most powerful, making policy as
often as he articulates it. He is credited with devising the
campaign strategy that Blair used to move the British Labor Party
away from its dogmatic left-wing policies, end 18 years of
Conservative rule, and win the biggest parliamentary majority in
nearly two centuries.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Blair is willing to dispatch indefinitely to NATO
the man widely regarded as his closest adviser underscores how much
importance the western allies attach to the propaganda war, in
which Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic gained a leg up last
week after the embarrassing slaughter of the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's appearance by Leaf, meanwhile, created as many
questions as it answered. The general, who is in charge of the
pilots based at Aviano, the main NATO airbase in Italy, said his
pilots had bombed two separate convoys near Djakovica over a
two-hour period last Wednesday. Serb authorities claimed up to 80
refugees were killed by NATO bombs, but reporters brought to the
scene by Serb military minders a day later counted about two dozen
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf said a reconstruction of the bombings, based on interviews
with the pilots, video imaging of the attacks, and press accounts,
led him to conclude that the first bombing run destroyed a military
target, but that the second convoy included civilian vehicles and
``unforseen casualties.''
</P>
<P>
   He said a review of the first bombing showed that the pilot had
hit a vehicle carrying Serb troops who had been torching homes, an
integral feature of the Serb effort to drive ethnic Albanians out
of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf said the pilots who dropped bombs on the second convoy,
after watching enhanced pictures of what they saw through their
four-inch targeting screens, acknowledged that the vehicles they
bombed could have been tractors used by fleeing refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The general said NATO could not be sure how many of the refugees
were killed by bombs because its investigators could not visit the
scene. He suggested Serb troops had opened fire on the refugees,
and dropped grenades on them from helicopters, after the NATO
bombing. He said other refugees had told journalists that some of
the bombs were dropped by low-flying jets, while the NATO planes
were flying at high altitude. Reporters who saw the bodies,
meanwhile, said some appeared to have been machine-gunned.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf said British pilots flying in the same area had tried to
warn their American colleagues that the convoy they were targeting
included civilians, but the attack ended before the Americans got
the warning. He also acknowledged that the American pilots decided
that the second convoy was a military one even though it included
far more vehicles than Yugoslav forces are known to travel in.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as there was any doubt, they stopped attacking,'' Leaf
said, adding, ``We don't jump to hasty decisions in these life and
death'' situations.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf declined to detail what information, besides their
eyesight, the pilots used to decide that the second convoy was
military. Last week, NATO officials said they were flying at 15,000
feet, but Leaf said that specifying how high NATO fighters were
flying would help Serb forces shoot them down.
</P>
<P>
   That information deemed crucial to the security of NATO pilots
Monday had been freely disclosed last week underscored attempts by
NATO to put its information office in order.
</P>
<P>
   A British government spokesman said Campbell was shocked when he
found out how small the NATO press operation was.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was designed for peacetime,'' said the spokesman. ``This is
a unique situation, and clear support was needed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
