u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ARROJO-BOS &LR;      04-19 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ARROJO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARROJO FINALLY GAINS FIRST VICTORY OVER BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Whenever he had faced the Red Sox in the past, Rolando
Arrojo might have been tempted to wonder: You call this freedom?
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old _ that's what he says he is, anyway, though some
archivists believe he may have forgotten to count four birthdays or
so _ defected from Communist Cuba on July 9, 1996. And after a
bidding war for his devilish sidearm services, the righthander
burst upon the US baseball scene last season, winning 14 games for
the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, a record for an expansion pitcher, and
being acclaimed as the American League Rookie Pitcher of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Except against the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   In Tampa's maiden game at Fenway Park last June 12, he dropped a
5-1 decision, though he allowed only two runs and struck out nine
in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   In his first start of 1999, Tampa's home opener April 9, Boston
oppression continued as Arrojo lasted just 5 1/3 innings in a 4-1
loss.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday the refugee celebrated Patriots Day spectacularly,
shackling the Red Sox for seven innings in a 4-1 victory, his first
of the season. Rationing his pitches like Castro does essentials,
Arrojo threw the ball only 79 times _ 53 for strikes _ struck out
six, walked none, and allowed only three hits, including Jose
Offerman's tainted home run to right field in the fourth that
appeared to hit the railing but was ruled to have gone into the
stands.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when everything seemed to go right for him, experts in
the visitors' clubhouse were asked what had worked best for Arrojo.
</P>
<P>
   ``His breaking ball for strikes from down under,'' said manager
Larry Rothschild. ``And he was pinpointing his fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A great slider,'' said former Boston catcher John Flaherty,
who assisted his batterymate with a run-scoring double in the
second and a sixth-inning homer, his first ever at his former
address.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Arrojo figured he had a couple of more important
items working _ his back and his head.
</P>
<P>
   Both had been betraying him all season. A sore lower back
rendered spring training a wasted exercise for him, and the
distraction of the pain weighed heavily on his mind. That was
reflected in his first two outings: the loss to the Sox and a
no-decision against Toronto in which he couldn't hold a 6-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lost his concentration or something in that game,'' said
Flaherty. ``Today I thought he had his concentration throughout.''
</P>
<P>
   That, Arrojo theorized, was because he had his health throughout
_ well, almost. Until a stiff neck prompted Rothschild to lift him
for precautionary reasons, Arrojo was a portrait of physical
fitness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt really good for the first time,'' he said through his
interpreter, bullpen coach Orlando Gomez. ``I felt I didn't have a
real good spring because I couldn't throw the ball hard. But after
my last start, I could finally do my normal training _ running,
working on my legs. This was the first time my back hadn't bothered
me.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he said, ``my head was never out of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   That was most evident in his one suspenseful inning, the fourth,
when Jeff Frye followed Offerman's leadoff homer with a single,
putting the tying run on base. After retiring Reggie Jefferson on a
fly to center, Arrojo faced his most crucial duel of the day. And
he won it by getting Nomar Garciaparra on a pop to second.
</P>
<P>
   ``He set the whole thing up with breaking balls,'' marveled
Rothschild. ``Nomar, being one of the best hitters in baseball,
fought him off on a few. Then he threw a fastball that he really
let go.''
</P>
<P>
   That handcuffed Garciaparra, and after Arrojo ended the threat
by getting Troy O'Leary on a dribbler in front of the plate, he was
in command.
</P>
<P>
   Given his recent medical history, the stiff neck may have been
alarming. But Rothschild attributed it to nothing more than fatigue
_ ``This was the first time he'd gone seven innings'' _ and Arrojo
considered it a nuisance, not a concern.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he could have finished had it not been for Rothschild's
caution, Arrojo spoke emphatically a word that required no
translation:
</P>
<P>
   ``Easy.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just what his workday was against the Red Sox. Finally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
