<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4878 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-CNN-ARNETT20     04-19 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-CNN-ARNETT20 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Star reporter was tainted by story about Tailwind
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ CNN severed relations Monday with Peter Arnett, one of
the network's brightest stars during the Persian Gulf War and later
its most controversial for his role in the Operation Tailwind
fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   Arnett, who won a Pulitzer Prize in 1966 for his reporting for
The Associated Press in Vietnam and who is recognized by his
colleagues as one of the greatest war correspondents of the
television age, was tarnished when he reported the Operation
Tailwind story, charging that the United States used nerve gas in
Laos in 1970. CNN then retracted the story in the biggest
embarrassment in its history.
</P>
<P>
   Arnett, 64, did not return telephone calls seeking comment
Monday. He was quoted in USA Today, before his departure was
announced, as calling CNN's treatment of him ``pretty shabby.''
Later on Monday, Arnett was quoted in a CNN statement as saying,
``I've had a long and wonderful relationship with CNN and have been
proud to be part of this great news organization.''
</P>
<P>
   The terse news release stated that CNN and Arnett had ``reached
an understanding that will bring Arnett's 18-year service to an
amicable conclusion.'' He had been in the middle of a five-year
contract, with a window of negotiation coming in July.
</P>
<P>
   CNN International President Eason Jordan, to whom Arnett
reported, declined to comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   While Tailwind may not have been the only cause of Arnett's
dismissal _ there were indications from within CNN Monday that
salary and other issues were involved _ it's unthinkable that the
network would have ended his contract now had it not been for
Tailwind.
</P>
<P>
   Arnett was reprimanded by the network for his role as reporter
of the Tailwind story, which aired last June as the first
installment of the TV newsmagazine ``NewsStand.'' The report,
stating that U.S. military personnel used nerve gas in Laos in
1970, was soon attacked by the military.
</P>
<P>
   Besides retracting the story and reprimanding Arnett, CNN fired
two producers and allowed one executive to resign. The network has
since settled, for hundreds of thousands of dollars, at least two
lawsuits by veterans involved in Tailwind alleging defamation of
character, and at least two more suits are pending.
</P>
<P>
   Just how much Arnett contributed to the Tailwind story became a
source of controversy. He said at the time that he was responsible
for ``not one comma,'' and producers April Oliver and Jack Smith
acknowledged that they were the prime movers of the story, which
they maintain is true.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a gutsy reporter who has an incredible track record,''
Oliver said Monday from her home in Virginia. ``The military made
it clear that they wanted his head and it appears now CNN has given
it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one military man was glad at the news about Arnett:
Maj. Gen. Perry Smith, the former CNN military analyst (now with
NBC) who resigned over Tailwind and pushed the network to
apologize.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have any credibility left,'' Smith said Monday,
from Augusta, where he lives. ``Why he was not fired last summer
amazes me. It's taken awhile, but at least it's finally
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People looked at me as a role model,'' Arnett said last year,
shortly after being reprimanded by CNN. ``They couldn't understand
how a role model could be involved in such a sorry episode as this.
My journalistic principles were bent, but they're intact.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnett's role in Tailwind eventually came to overshadow the rest
of his career as a war correspondent. After he said he had narrated
the piece as a good ``company man'' but had not researched it, CNN
correspondent Christiane Amanpour, wrote a blistering op-ed piece
for The New York Times, attacking Arnett.
</P>
<P>
   But the incident displayed a key part of the TV newsmagazine
culture: that producers and researchers generally do all the
legwork, and the ``name'' correspondent usually comes in at the
last minute to do some interviews and narrate. After Tailwind, the
broadcast networks all went on record as saying that never again
would a correspondent on a challenged report be able to say he or
she was just a narrator.
</P>
<P>
   And some of Arnett's colleagues, aware that he had been caught
in a bad situation not entirely of his own making, stuck up for
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never met anybody who had more respect for Peter Arnett
and his lifetime achievement as a reporter,'' CBS News anchor Dan
Rather said at a meeting with TV critics earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Arnett was hired by CNN in 1981 when the network was still
disparaged by most professional journalists. ``Not only was he a
solid reporter, but he was valuable in terms of showing we were
serious about what we were doing,'' said Ed Turner, a former key
vice president at CNN.
</P>
<P>
   There was no doubt that the 18-year CNN veteran was
conspicuously absent from his network's coverage of the war in
Yugoslavia, though he had covered Yugoslav conflicts several times
from 1994 to 1997. Arnett told The New York Times he had asked CNN
to send him to Yugoslavia, but some CNN executives reportedly
believed that he continued to be tainted by Tailwind.
</P>
<P>
   ``His work will stand in the hall of great reporters. I think
the body of his work will survive the unfortunate concllusion that
occurred here,'' said Turner, now president of the Forum Network, a
public affairs cable network.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
