<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES0420-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves notes: Braves bats and Baylor make for explosive lineup
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Consider the Braves offense of late.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-record 20 runs they scored on Sunday is a little
inflated to read much into, but why not? Underneath the light-air
advantage of Coors Field appeared some major forces at work, some
forces that re-shape the kind of offense the Braves will be putting
on this year.
</P>
<P>
   Some new trends developing _ some that were set by new hitting
coach Don Baylor _ that may re-define this lineup:
</P>
<P>
   _ A newfound patience in Andruw Jones.
</P>
<P>
   He struggled in spring training and struggled in the first week,
hitting the same way he hit the first half of last season - in a
hurry. Swinging at breaking balls in the dirt, missing fastballs
over the plate, falling behind pitchers and having little chance to
catch up.
</P>
<P>
   But ever since he came back from three consecutive strikeouts to
take a walk, score a run and eventually drive in the winning run in
a 3-2 win over the Diamondbacks, Jones has been a new hitter.
</P>
<P>
   He has struck out only three times in the six games since, none
in the last four games. He drew three walks on Saturday against
Colorado, bringing his season total to eight, which leads the team.
His patience paid off a day later on Sunday - when he doubled his
hit production this season in one game with a career-high five hits
and watching his batting average climb from .156 to .265.
</P>
<P>
   And he talks like a new hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day you go out, you can learn something,'' Jones said.
``I'm looking for a good pitch to hit, if I don't get it, I ain't
going to swing. They're going to get tired of seeing you walking
and they'll give you a pitch to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Continued quiet success of cleanup hitter Brian Jordan if it's
possible to get a quiet 13 RBI in the first 11 games. He lacks the
pop of Andres Galarraga but who doesn't? He's scored runs in nine
of the first 11 Braves games, driven in runs in seven of the 11,
scored a pair of winning runs and leads the team with four home
runs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chipper Jones has already matched his home run total from the
right side from a year ago, in only 11 games this season. That was
the first item of business when he first met with Baylor this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Braves are scoring some runs without waiting on the long
ball. They are 3-1 this season when they haven't hit a home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not relying on the three-run homer,'' Chipper Jones
said. ``We've got some guys who can run a little bit. we're doing a
good job of hitting behind runners, moving guys over, hitting a
harmless groundball to get a run in. When you execute, good things
happen, and we executed well (Sunday).''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
