</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO ACKNOWLEDGES IT MAY HAVE KILLED CIVILIANS IN BOMBING RAIDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ NATO acknowledged for the first time on
Monday that it bombed two entirely separate groups of vehicles near
the Kosovo town of Djakovica last Wednesday and might have killed
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, NATO has only acknowledged that its planes
accidentally bombed a civilian tractor north of Djakovica on that
day. But Serbian authorities and Kosovar refugees have insistently
reported allied hits along the road south of Djakovica, putting
NATO credibility to a severe test. The Serbs claimed that 60
civilians were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Providing its first comprehensive briefing on the disputed
attacks, NATO officers said that their pilots, flying at high
altitude, had been convinced that they were striking only military
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   But as the raids proceeded, allied officers at a command post in
Italy became concerned that fleeing refugees might be in the second
group, a huge convoy of more than 100 vehicles southeast of the
town.
</P>
<P>
   Their suspicions were aroused after NATO intelligence experts
warned that Serbian military forces do not generally travel in such
long columns.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of OA-10 observation planes were quickly dispatched to
the area. Using binoculars, their pilots reported that civilian
vehicles appeared to be interspersed with the military ones, and
the NATO attacks were broken off.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we know from the debris that the Serbs showed is that
some civilians died there and that there is the possibility that
NATO aircraft were the cause,'' said Brig. Gen. Daniel Leaf, the
American commander of an air wing at Aviano, Italy, who led the
official NATO inquiry into the episode.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's briefing demonstrated the difficulties of identifying
targets from high altitude over a region where Serb army and police
forces have been driving civilians from their homes and often
herding them down roads. Allied planes have spotted Serb tanks
concealed next to ruined homes and even churches, and Serbian
soldiers have been reported using tractors and other vehicles as
well as military equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's assessment was also an important political test for the
alliance. Since NATO's April 14 air strikes against convoys near
Djakovica spurred allegations of civilian casualties, NATO
spokesmen have been on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   That was the result not only of the insistent Yugoslav charges,
which were buttressed by reporters taken to the scene by Belgrade
authorities. It was also the result of contradictory statements by
NATO's supreme commander, Gen. Wesley K. Clark, and conflicting
accounts of the raid by the Pentagon and the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   NATO sought to explain its error on Monday by releasing a flood
of information about aircraft patrols, laser-guided bombs and even
conversations between the pilots and airborne controllers.
</P>
<P>
   One such excerpt was drawn from a conversation between an
airborne command post, referred to in military parlance as ABCCC,
and an F-16 pilot attacking the convoy south of Djakovica.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just received word that this is a VJ convoy,'' the ABCCC
told the F-16 patrols, using the acronym for the Yugoslav military.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of bad weather and frustrating attempts to uncover
hidden Serbian armor, the pilots thought they had stumbled on a
bonanza.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great,'' responded one of the F-16 pilots. ``ABCCC, I want as
many fighters as I can get, now.''
</P>
<P>
   Important questions still remain, however, some of which may
never be answered. One is how many civilians were killed in the
convoy on that Wednesday, and were they all killed by allied
planes. Another is whether NATO can reduce the risk of hitting
civilians without hampering its attacks on Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   Another question is whether it is really possible to dependably
distinguish civilian from military targets at the altitude at which
NATO planes customarily operate, 15,000 feet, though they sometimes
fly somewhat lower.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
