<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-DRUGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICARE WOULD PAY $1,700 A YEAR FOR PRESCRIPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Congressional Democrats are expected to unveil legislation
Tuesday calling for Medicare to cover prescription drugs for 39
million elderly and disabled citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by Senator Edward M. Kennedy, the bill calls for Medicare
to pay $1,700 a year towards outpatient prescription drugs for each
Medicare beneficiary, according to sources familiar with the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the program, which Republicans have warned would be
prohibitive, would be funded partly by the premiums paid by
seniors, a new tobacco tax, and money allocated from the federal
budget surplus. No exact figures on the cost of the proposal were
available.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy bill is the broadest proposal in Washington so far
to address what is increasingly perceived as Medicare's biggest
omission, the failure to cover outpatient medications.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill being cosponsored by Democratic Representative
Fortney ``Pete'' Stark of California, beneficiaries would chip in
20 percent of the cost of their prescriptions after meeting a $200
deductible. The benefit would be offered under Medicare's Part B
program, which pays for doctor's bills, home health care, and other
outpatient services. Seniors pay a monthly premium to cover 25
percent of Part B expenses.
</P>
<P>
   For seniors whose incomes are at or below 130 percent of
poverty, the bill calls for subsidies to help meet the deductible
and copayments.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the bill would cover 100 percent of the cost of
prescription drugs once a senior citizen spends $3,000 a year
out-of-pocket on medications. This benefit would be available to
all beneficiaries regardless of their income.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the bill would require all private insurance policies
that cover the bills not paid by Medicare _ so-called ``Medigap''
supplemental insurance policies purchased by seniors _ to offer
limited prescription drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to be delivered Tuesday, Kennedy wrote, ``This
legislation is a lifeline for every senior citizen who needs
prescription drugs to treat an illness or maintain their health.''
</P>
<P>
   Seniors on average fill 18 prescriptions a year and take four to
six drugs a day, according to the Kennedy script.
</P>
<P>
   The growing importance of prescription drugs in the arsenal of
modern medicine and the rapidly escalating cost of those drugs have
boosted the argument for drug coverage under Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Fiscally conservative Republicans, however, have opposed adding
an expensive new benefit when the Medicare program is estimated to
run out of money as early as 2015.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fiscally fragile program,'' said Gail Wilensky, who
ran the Medicare program under the Republican Bush administration
and is chairwoman of the Medicare Payment Advisory Commission,
which advises Congress on Medicare matters.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's proposal is also likely to run into stiff opposition
from the pharmaceutical industry, which fears that a broad benefit
under a government program would lead to price controls.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we understand it, the Kennedy proposal would. . . rely on
federal government controls for access, choice, scope of benefits,
and quality of care for seniors,'' said Alan Holmer, president of
the Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of America, an
industry group in Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 2026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
