<HEADER>
A4886 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLANE-CRASH-COX     04-19 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANE-CRASH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pilot performed dogfight maneuvers before fatal crash
 &HT;    By Chris Reinolds
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARTERSVILLE, Ga. _ Two people killed in a small plane crash
Monday in Bartow County, Ga. were apparently engaged in dogfighting
maneuvers with another plane.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Powell, National Transportation Safety Board air safety
investigator, said another aircraft was flying with the T-34 model
A plane that crashed at 12:51 p.m. The single-engine plane smashed
into a clump of pine trees in a field about 10 miles northeast of
Cartersville.
</P>
<P>
   The sky-blue plane's wing was found a mile from the crash site
south of Ga. 140. Powell said the two planes were ``performing a
mission.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They do dogfight simulations, from what I'm told,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The planes departed from Atlanta's Fulton County/Charlie Brown
Airport. The other plane returned to the airport following the
crash, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Bartow County Sheriff Don Thurman said witnesses saw the plane
spiral down into the stand of trees.
</P>
<P>
   Both planes apparently belong to Sky Warriors, which sells
flight combat fantasy experiences for $695.
</P>
<P>
   Sky Warriors' combat-trained pilots fly the T-34 military-style
trainers from the airport to the skies over Lake Allatoona. Once
there, the pilot, who sits in the back of the two-seat cockpit,
turns the controls over to the customer, the company's president
Earl ``Stinger'' Arrowood said in a 1996 interview.
</P>
<P>
   The plane came down about 100 yards from Shirley Trautwein's
barn in a neighborhood of homes on large lots widely scattered
around a valley surrounded by rolling hills.
</P>
<P>
   Trautwein wasn't at home when the crashed occurred, but arrived
later to find television news satellite trucks camped near her
house.
</P>
<P>
   After surveying the wreckage, Trautwein said the plane's
crumbled shell was no more than eight feet long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear them flying on the weekends and hear them
dogfighting,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Renate Kline, who lives across the valley near the crash, said
she and her husband heard a very loud boom but didn't see the
plane. Olive Waldorf, another neighbor, said she heard the
dogfighting, but didn't know the plane had crashed until she saw
the firetrucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like a movie about World War I,'' Waldorf said.
``We're so used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the second fatal plane crash in Bartow this year. In
February, an airplane slammed into the ground in Cartersville,
killing the pilot. That plane, a Piper Lance PA-32 RT, broke apart
about 20 yards from a 45-home subdivision.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators and witnesses said the Piper barely missed
crashing into the subdivision and into Cartersville Middle School,
about 150 yards from where deputies strung yellow police tape.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Reinolds writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
