<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-FUNDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ASKS CONGRESS FOR $6 BILLION TO PAY FOR KOSOVO
INTERVENTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton sent Congress a $6.05 billion
request Monday for emergency Pentagon spending to help prosecute
the NATO air campaign against Yugoslavia and provide humanitarian
assistance to the Kosovar refugees.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of promising quick approval, Republican leaders
threatened to turn the request into a platform for a debate over
U.S. military readiness, which they said has declined precipitously
under the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., issued a statement
labeling the request for funding ``shortsighted,'' saying that all
it would do is ``replace bullets for bullets and bombs for bombs
spent in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert said he favors an ``open debate'' on the request that
would allow members to vent their frustrations about a U.S.
military he contends is spread so thin around the world that the
nation's defense is in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton administration has been downsizing the military
for the last seven years, and the Kosovo crisis has exposed how our
national security is now in real danger,'' Hastert said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton agreed with Hastert that a debate on military readiness
is a good idea. But he asked the Republicans to hold off on airing
their grievances about it until Congress takes up the Defense
Department appropriations bill later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The need for this funding is urgent, immediate, clearly in the
national interest,'' Clinton said at a White House ceremony
honoring the national teacher of the year. ``There are literally
lives hanging in the balance. And so I hope, in the spirit of
genuine bipartisanship, the Congress will move the package right
away.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's request, based on the recommendation of Pentagon
officials, includes about $5.1 billion for military spending, $360
million for Defense Department humanitarian efforts, and $591
million in direct assistance to the Kosovar refugees and the
frontline states of Albania and Macedonia, where more than half a
million of them are living in camps.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the military-related funds, $3.6 billion would be used to
fund the U.S. portion of the ongoing NATO air campaign for the rest
of the fiscal year if necessary, while another $700 million would
be used to replenish munitions used in the attacks so far. The
remaining $800 million would be held in reserve and used as the
need arises.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Lew, director of the Office of Management and Budget, told
reporters in a briefing that the emergency supplemental request
would ensure that the country maintains its military readiness
while providing ``the resources necessary to continue the current
operations as long as necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the humanitarian assistance will be enough to take care
of current refugee needs as well as ``additional refugee problems
as they emerge.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the administration request was about $3 billion more
than Pentagon officials had hinted at last week, it was not enough
to Republican lawmakers who would like to use the supplemental
funding request to beef up other Defense Department operations and
provide a 4.8 percent pay raise for military personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't just a matter of replacing spent bullets and bombs.
We must urgently improve our military capabilities across the
board. That means looking at weapons procurement, readiness,
personnel and other areas,'' said House Majority Leader Dick Armey,
R-Irving.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Clinton has created ``this national security
emergency by squeezing the defense budget while expanding military
commitments, first in Iraq and Bosnia, and now in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Senate side, Republicans are looking to use the emergency
funding request as a vehicle for debate over Clinton's entire
policy toward the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison cautioned against a protracted
debate over military matters Monday that would end up delaying
approval of the funding request. But she said it was important for
the Senate to at least give members a chance to share their views
on U.S. policy in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be bipartisan support for the funding request, but
there will also be debate on the policy,'' Hutchison said. ``People
are concerned about the way this operation is being conducted and a
lot of us are looking for more diplomacy and outreach to have a
chance for a long-term peace, not just in Kosovo but for all the
Balkans.''
</P>
<P>
   While expressing support for the funding request, Hutchison said
Congress must ensure that the money does not come from ``other
defense appropriations.''
</P>
<P>
   As an emergency spending bill, however, the request is likely to
be paid for out of current budget surpluses and not by raiding
other programs or accounts.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The threat by Republicans to turn the request into a platform
for criticizing Clinton administration policies came as no surprise
to White House officials who bristled last week when House Majority
Whip Tom DeLay, R-Sugar Land, referred to the allied operation as
``the Clinton war.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Republican leaders have taken to calling the Kosovo
conflict ``the Democratic war,'' and Hastert has even referred to
U.S. military personnel involved in the NATO operation as ``his
(Clinton's) forces.''
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart told reporters Monday
that he hopes the Republican-controlled Congress will try to resist
the temptation ``to get bogged down'' in a bitter debate over
defense matters.
</P>
<P>
   He disputed claims by Hastert and others that the nation's
military readiness has eroded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our military readiness is top-notch. The president has worked
with the Pentagon over the last few years. We've reprogrammed some
money. There has been some ... additional readiness money
appropriated,'' Lockhart said, adding that Clinton included a
recommendation for a $100 billion increase in defense spending over
the next five years in his 2000 budget proposal.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
