<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4893 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      04-19 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US SUSPECTS HALF-MILLION ALBANIANS MAY BE MISSING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER AND ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As many as 500,000 ethnic Albanian men are missing
and may be victims of Serb genocide, the State Department reported
Monday, igniting new fears about the breadth of Slobodan
Milosevic's brutal siege in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Amid allied reports of mass executions by Serb forces in more
than 60 Kosovo villages, State Department officials said no fewer
than 100,000 ethnic Albanian men are unaccounted for and may be
lying in mass graves throughout the separatist province. ``Based on
past practice, it is chilling to think where those 100,000 men
are,'' said State Department spokesman James Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   The number of missing men could be as high as 500,000, the State
Department said, ``if reports of widespread separation of men among
internally displaced persons within Kosovo are true.''
</P>
<P>
   With the chaos in Kosovo, and the lack of international
observers in the province, State Department officials said, the
actual dimensions of the refugee crisis may not be known until
peacekeeping forces enter the territory.
</P>
<P>
   The report was issued as concern grew over the fate of an
estimated 35,000 ethnic Albanians who were trapped in Kosovo Monday
when Yugoslavia suddenly closed the main border crossing to
northern Albania. A top Albanian official said there is no trace of
the 35,000 refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of them disappeared,'' said Prec Zogoj, a top adviser to
Albanian President Rexhap Meidan. ``Where are they?''
</P>
<P>
   There were these other developments on the 27th day of the
allied airstrikes against Yugoslavia:
</P>
<P>
   _ President Clinton asked Congress for $6 billion in emergency
spending to fund the US military role in Kosovo through September
and increase aid to refugees. More than 600,000 ethnic Albanians
have fled Kosovo since the NATO airstrikes began.
</P>
<P>
   _ Russian President Boris Yeltsin directly appealed to Clinton
to end the NATO bombing and discussed the possibility of Russian
troops joining an international peacekeeping force in Kosovo when
the military conflict ends.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, in his first conversation with Clinton since the
bombing began, also vowed that the Russia military will not
intervene in the crisis and will not supplement the one spy ship
that is currently operating in the region.
</P>
<P>
   _ United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan announced he will
travel to Moscow next week to discuss Kosovo, including Yelstin's
offer for Russia to help mediate a possible truce.
</P>
<P>
   _ NATO formally acknowledged that two bombing raids in Kosovo
last week, including an attack on a refugee convoy, probably killed
dozens of ethnic Albanian refugees. ``It is possible there were
civilian casualties at both locations,'' said US Air Force
Brigadier General Daniel Leaf said.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Pentagon did not rule out the possibility that the United
States would try to exchange a captive Yugoslav army officer for
three American soldiers being held by Milosevic. ``We will pursue
any reasonable means to get them out,'' said Pentagon spokesman
Kenneth H. Bacon, when asked about a possible exchange.
</P>
<P>
   _ NATO officials, responding to concerns about the allies
launching a second month of air strikes Wednesday despite marginal
progress to date, appealed for patience. ``Since when was a
dictator defeated in 24 hours?'' said NATO spokesman Jamie Shea.
``It took six years to defeat fascism in Europe in the middle of
the 20th century. I think we can take two or three months to defeat
President Milosevic, quite frankly.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Many of the allied nations, led by the United States, sought
consensus among the 19 NATO partners to prevent Yugoslavia from
importing oil. The strategy could include a naval blockade of
Yugoslav ports.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two American relief workers died when the car in which they
were riding veered off a slippery road and plunged about 1,300 feet
off a cliff in Albania as they headed for a refugee camp in Kukes.
They were identified as David McCall, 71, and his wife, Penny
McCall, 57, of New York City. The couple had played a pivotal role
in building Refugees International, a disaster relief group. Also
killed in the accident were Refugees International's European
representative, Yvette Pierpaoli, of Serviers, France, and the
car's Albanian driver.
</P>
<P>
   The developments occurred against a backdrop of fear and misery
on the roads leaving Kosovo and in the refugee camps in neighboring
countries. After 4,500 refugees trudged through the main crossing
point to northern Albania on Sunday, only 28 made it across Monday
before Yugoslavia shut down the border without explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian officials said the additional 35,000 refugees were seen
headed for the border checkpoint at about 3 a.m. Monday. ``But
nobody arrived,'' Zogoj said.
</P>
<P>
   The 28 ethnic Albanians who did arrive told authorities they saw
rows of tractors and other vehicles abandoned by the roadside.
``They fear the vehicles may belong to the people who
disappeared,'' a relief official said in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Undersecretary of State Thomas Pickering said the
United States has obtained ``numerous refugee reports of Serb
police now assembling Kosovar Albanians into grave-digging chain
gangs.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the refugees reportedly are being clad ``in red jackets
and forced to dig graves for their countrymen killed by Serbian
ethnic cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations World Food Program estimated Monday that
840,000 displaced Kosavars are on the move in the province, with
many facing grave risks. About a third of the homeless are bunched
near the borders with Montenegro and Macedonia. An additional
565,000 are believed to be divided into three separate groups
hiding in forests and on hills as they are shelled by Serb
artillery.
</P>
<P>
   As the UN agency issued an urgent appeal for food to feed the
840,000 homeless Kosovars, NATO vowed to press forward with the air
campaign and plans to commemorate the organization's 50th
anniversary with a three-day summit in Washington, beginning
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of determination is total,'' said NATO Secretary
General Javier Solana. ``This is not a conflict over territory or
raw materials or strategic routes. Only values are at stake here.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is expected to meet in Washington before the summit with
Prime Minister Tony Blair of England, the major partner with the
United States in providing military support for the NATO campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In air strikes Monday night, NATO fired four missiles in two
separate attacks on a Serb satellite ground station that supports
telephone and television communications, according to the Yusolav
news agency Tanjug.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the relentless pounding for nearly a month, Milosevic
continues to send additional forces into Kosovo, where more than
43,000 Serb troops are believed to be carrying out his campaign of
``ethnic cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   The first of 24 US Apache helicopters are scheduled to arrive in
Albania this week for possible attacks on the Serb forces. The
Apaches, whose crews will face among the greatest risks yet among
the allied forces in the Balkans, are one of the Army's most
effective antitank weapons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
