<HEADER>
A4899 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELLSOUTH-COX     04-19 1918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth adds Qwest to its puzzle
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving to (a) General news and (f) Financial categories.)
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth Corp. has agreed to pay $3.5 billion for 10
percent of Denver-based Qwest Communications, taking a large _ and
long-awaited _ stride toward becoming a complete telecommunications
company.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth, which has made no acquisitions since purchase of a
paging unit in 1992, has watched from the sidelines while the
industry has been rocked by a series of mega-mergers. Increasingly,
BellSouth has been under pressure from analysts and investors to
respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``This brings BellSouth back into the game,'' said Phil
Asmundson, director of telecommunications for Deloitte &AMP; Touche.
``That 10 percent at the end of the day is also a really
inexpensive way to practically guarantee exclusivity. As good as it
is to have Qwest, it's even better to make sure nobody else gets
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The alliance might have been an all-out merger, but for the
limits of the law. Until BellSouth wins federal approval to offer
long-distance service, it is permitted only 10 percent ownership of
a long-distance company. Qwest, which last year bought LCI
International, is now the nation's fourth-largest long-distance
company. Qwest also has 18,500 miles of high-speed cables
crisscrossing the country.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth dearly wants entry into long-distance. But even more,
the Qwest alliance signals a vision of survival in a rapidly
shifting industry, and it is a different view than some others have
taken, said F. Duane Ackerman, company chairman and chief
executive. ``From my perspective, this is all about data. It is
about electronic commerce, Web hosting, Internet access and
video-streaming.''
</P>
<P>
   If the future belongs to data, profits from old-style voice
transmission are bound to fall, said Ford Cavallari, executive vice
president of Renaissance Worldwide, a Boston-based management
consulting company. Having access to Qwest's vast network should
let BellSouth exploit the transition to that new world, he said.
``This is very important and very impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Where the deal is most vulnerable is, ironically, the same place
it is strong: so many lines for high-speed data are being installed
that demand may take some time to catch up, slashing the immediate
profit from owning the networks, Cavallari said. There simply
aren't enough customers to use all the capacity _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   But prospects are generally good, said Marc Bacurin, analyst at
J.C. Bradford.
</P>
<P>
   Qwest should finish this year with revenue of $3.6 billion,
representing 60 percent growth, he said. ``This gives them access
to all of BellSouth's customers. It is a pretty good match.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gantt, economist and president of the Ansley Group, said
the deal is evidence of a shift inside BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are looking into the future and they know that the future
will be different from an old-line phone company. People will want
a company that will deliver a panoply of services to wherever they
are.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth officials for months resisted the tide of mega-mergers
by saying the company was open to any negotiation, while expressing
confidence in its ability to succeed without a merger.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent months, Wall Street analysts have obviously become
more impatient with BellSouth's apparent determination to avoid a
merger.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth stock began to drift slowly downward from all-time
highs. In recent months, company executives have been increasingly
emphatic that there was no ``go it alone strategy,'' and rumors
began to swirl that a deal was in the works.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, talk of a Sprint deal dogged BellSouth for months.
But Sprint's cost would be formidable, and its management is
notoriously independent-minded. Moreover, Sprint already has
everything from local to long-distance and can play hard to get.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the most valuable part of an alliance is not the
network, said Michele Wolf, Bear Stearns analyst. ``The network is
the easy part. It is the distribution channels, the customer
support and the back-office that really makes a long-distance
company. You buy Qwest and you get a robust, solid long-distance
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch analyst Daniel Reingold too called it a positive
move. ``This deal gives BLS access to one of the premier fiber
optic networks in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   The pact benefits both sides. BellSouth gets access to 18,500
miles of high-speed lines, the expertise to manage those data
transmissions and the far-flung customers who use them. The two
companies can now market services jointly.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth now has a route to a full-tilt, national long-distance
effort _ and the only thing in the way is federal permission to
enter that market, which BellSouth expects soon. The deal gives
Qwest a local service presence that it has lacked, as well as much
deeper pockets and connection to a brand name that is good as gold
_ at least in the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also meshes internationally. Qwest has a growing
business in Europe and is in talks toward a Japanese partnership.
BellSouth is the largest outside investor in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Geographically, this is very complementary,'' Gantt said.
</P>
<P>
   But in terms of sheer size, BellSouth _ even with Qwest _ still
falls far short of rivals like AT&AMP;T and MCI WorldCom. And in terms
of services too, BellSouth still lacks some firepower.
</P>
<P>
   Most obviously missing from the BellSouth arsenal is
long-distance. But as the market for telecommunications becomes
national and even global, BellSouth is still mostly a regional
player drawing the lion's share of its business from phone service
in the Southeast. The combination has no local service component
outside the BellSouth region, no national wireless phone service
and only token international presence outside Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Nacchio shrugged off comparisons to larger rivals. ``I think we
match up quite well in high-speed Internet and broadband. I think
we are at the scale and scope to compete globally.''
</P>
<P>
   But BellSouth and Qwest may find themselves at a disadvantage to
companies that can offer one-stop shopping. That's why BellSouth
needs to win the right to offer long-distance, and it could be an
argument for adding other pieces as well, Cavallari said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, a telecom company should be able to offer voice,
video and data anywhere,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, BellSouth had decided it needed to dramatically bolster
its high-speed and long-distance capabilities. That is why the
company approached Qwest, Ackerman said. ``It came out of our data
strategy, to pursue a good partner.''
</P>
<P>
   Talks started six months ago with Keith Cowan, vice president of
corporate development, serving as BellSouth's lead negotiator,
reporting to Senior VP Sidney Boren.
</P>
<P>
   As negotiations grew serious, Ackerman took to the air, flying
to Denver to meet with Nacchio. By this past weekend, with Nacchio
in Atlanta to close the deal, only details remained. Sunday, the
BellSouth board met via conference call and gave a thumbs up. A few
hours later, the Qwest board did the same. Another teleconference,
this one in the evening, was convened to inform various officers
and vice presidents of BellSouth and at 6 a.m. Monday, the word
went out to the news wires.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty minutes later, Ackerman and Nacchio shared the spotlight
on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   One way to measure success of the Qwest deal would be
BellSouth's successful entry into long-distance. Ackerman has
predicted that BellSouth can collect about 25 percent of the
approximately $10 billion a year in long-distance business within
its region. Qwest offers a route to those revenues, but not without
approval to enter the market.
</P>
<P>
   Approval is no slam dunk. Three years after the
Telecommunications Act set out the rules for entering
long-distance, BellSouth has been rejected by regulators three
times _ twice for Louisiana and once for South Carolina. Rivals
like AT&AMP;T and WorldCom still bitterly oppose BellSouth's
application, arguing that the company has not opened its local
market up to competition as required.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ackerman predicted that BellSouth will be in long-distance
within the year, possibly within a few months. ``We are quite
optimistic about the outlook for Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the deal announced Monday provides that once BellSouth
has won approval for long-distance it can buy an additional 10
percent of Qwest and be given one of the seats on the 11-member
Qwest board. For two more years, the deal would limit BellSouth to
a 20 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman said he is not frustrated by the restrictions of law
and contract that will keep BellSouth from buying Qwest outright _
at least for now. ``We've always had the view that you can create
an alliance where you do not have to own everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Some commentators were quick to note that even with a only a 10
percent stake BellSouth was still paying far more for Qwest shares
than it would have a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman defended the price. ``The price reflects the great
potential we put on this aggressive young company. It gives us
access to a national network without having to build it
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Michael Balhoff of Legg Mason Wood Walker agreed that to
justify the deal, BellSouth must show its arrangement with Qwest
saves them from building $3.5 billion worth of network and
high-speed lines. ``And it appears that this is a reasonable
expectation.''
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, Qwest seems vastly different from BellSouth,
which is often still seen as the stodgy successor to AT&AMP;T, enjoying
the monopoly bequeathed by Ma Bell.
</P>
<P>
   But through the 1990s, BellSouth has drifted through a long,
slow and sometimes painful transition that has reshaped its
identity. Tens of thousands of jobs have been cut, mostly from the
local phone unit. Other units _ wireless, Internet, cable
television _ have grown, often in businesses where cut-throat
competition is a given.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman said the two companies have worked together on a small
group of critical customers. ``We are not total strangers.''
</P>
<P>
   Nacchio is, like much of BellSouth's top management, a veteran
of AT&AMP;T. Nacchio stayed with the giant after a federal consent
decree set off its 1984 divestiture of seven regional companies
known as the Baby Bells.
</P>
<P>
   At AT&AMP;T, Nacchio said he had not known Ackerman, but had been
friends with William Redderson, who is now vice president at
BellSouth. After divestiture, he fell out of touch.
</P>
<P>
   Called ``Machine Gun Joe'' by others inside AT&AMP;T, Nacchio was
known for his greater New York diction and his rapid-fire
conversational style. He was also known for turning around stagnant
units. By the mid-1990s, Nacchio was running the long-distance
consumer unit, a 40-something executive with a shot at succeeding
whoever was picked to run the company at the expected retirement of
Robert Allen.
</P>
<P>
   But another youngish executive _ John Walters _ was recruited
from the outside and named Allen's heir. Walters eventually was
sent packing, but not before the departure of many potential rivals
for the throne _ including Nacchio, who landed at Qwest.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth stock Monday rose 68.75 cents to $41.875. Qwest stock
soared $10.125 a share in early trading, before falling back to
close unchanged at $82.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
