<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0410 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4902 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRLINE-REPORT-NYT &LR;      04-19 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY SHOWS AIRLINES DOING WORSE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Neb., Kan.)  (af)  
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The major airlines are getting worse at many of the
parts of their jobs that passengers care about the most: being on
time, handling baggage and treating travelers decently.
</P>
<P>
   The findings come from the National Airline Quality Rating, a
study of statistics reported to the government conducted by
business professors at the University of Nebraska and Wichita State
University. The study also found that complaints to the
Transportation Department were up 26 percent in 1998, after rising
20 percent in 1997. The most frequent complaint was ``flight
problems,'' including cancellations and delays.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which made assumptions about the relative importance
of several factors, ranked USAirways as the best airline and United
Airlines, whose parent company the UAL Corp., as the worst. But the
authors acknowledged that few people have a choice between those
two, and that many have no choice at all.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, said Dean E. Headley, an associate professor of
marketing at Wichita State who is one of the two authors, of the
1,000 most popular routes in this country, only about half are
served by more than one airline.
</P>
<P>
   Headley said, though, that ``if you still have some choice, this
may be useful to help you make a further choice.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey found enormous differences among the airlines for
each category.
</P>
<P>
   Ranked by the number of complaints, Northwest Airlines, which
left thousands of passengers stranded at the Detroit airport during
a snowstorm a year ago, had the worst record, 2.21 letters per
100,000 passengers. America West, whose parent is America West
Holdings Corp., was not far behind, with 2.11. Best was Southwest,
with 0.25 letters per 100,000 passengers, a rate one-tenth that of
Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of planes arriving on time in 1998 was 77.2, down
from 77.9 the year before; Southwest Airlines was best, at 80.8,
and America West was worst, at 68.5.
</P>
<P>
   There were 5.16 mishandled bags per 1,000 passengers in 1998, up
from 4.96 the previous year. United was worst with 7.79 bags;
America West was best with 3.88.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints to the Transportation Department rose to 1.08 per
100,000 passengers, from .86 the year before.
</P>
<P>
   At the Air Transport Association, the trade group of the major
airlines, Edward A. Merlis, the senior vice president for
legislative and international affairs, said that some of the
problems were a byproduct of prosperity. Sitting in a full
airplane, he said, ``shorter tempers arise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The more congested the system is, the lower your threshhold
for being disturbed,'' Merlis said. But a positive effect of fuller
flights is lower fares, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Merlis said the airlines had good reason to want to decrease the
number of misdirected bags, because it costs an airline an average
of $25 to return each lost bag to a passenger, a figure that is
about double the average profit per passenger.
</P>
<P>
   As for the number of complaints, he said that at about 8,000 a
year directed at United States airlines, ``out of 600 million
passengers, yes, a 25 percent increase is a lot and maybe it's
indicative of something, but I don't think as an absolute value
it's indicative.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates had other theories.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're seeing is the net result of lack of competition,''
said Laurie Berger, editor of Consumer Reports Travel Letter.
``When there's no competition, there's no incentive for airlines to
provide better service.''
</P>
<P>
   Planes are dirtier and food is worse on domestic flights, Ms.
Berger added, because airlines are concentrating on their overseas
routes instead.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Berger said that episodes like Northwest's mishandling of a
snowstorm in Detroit last winter, with thousands of people stuck in
planes for hours, had become ``the poster-child example of
passenger rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hudson, the executive director of the Aviation Consumer
Action Project, which is affiliated with Ralph Nader, the consumer
advocate, said ``the intensity of the complaints we get, I've never
seen it higher.''
</P>
<P>
   But in one category in the survey, the airlines did better.
Involuntary denied boardings, or ``bumping'' of passengers who had
reserved seats, fell to .87 per 10,000 passengers, from 1.06 the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Merlis said the reason was that ``yield management programs''
were improving. These are the same programs the airlines use to
decide how to price their seats, including when to raise the price
because only a few are left, and when to cut the price because
otherwise the plane will fly with empty seats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
