<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE GLOBALUTION GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few years ago I was interviewing a dissident Indonesian news
editor who was telling me about how he managed to get critical
things about the corrupt Suharto family into the heavily controlled
Indonesian press. He said that when President Suharto's son was
being given government subsidies for a wacky idea he had for
building an Indonesian car industry, the local press was reluctant
to come out openly against this nepotism. What the Indonesian press
did instead was wait for the World Trade Organization to bring a
case against Suharto's son for unfair trade practices and then
splash that on the front pages. The message was, ``Gosh, we would
never say anything bad about the president's son, but these folks
at the WTO sure think he's up to no good.''
</P>
<P>
   This Indonesian use of the WTO is not an isolated case.
Actually, it is an example of a new political phenomenon you can
see in many developing countries today, which I call
``globalution.'' Globalution happens when reformers understand that
revolution from below may be too explosive, and revolution from
above is never going to happen, so they choose revolution from
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Their strategy is to plug their country into every possible
global rules-based organization they can find _ from the World
Trade Organization to the PriceWaterhouseCoopers accounting firm to
Conservation International _ in hopes of importing rule-of-law
systems from beyond.
</P>
<P>
   This is how one should look at the issue of whether the United
States should support China's entry into the WTO _ something that
President Clinton balked at when China's prime minister, Zhu
Rongji, visited last week, but that Clinton is reconsidering and
renegotiating with the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   That China's joining the WTO _ on American terms _ is so
manifestly in our economic interest is not even worth debating.
America's markets are largely open. China's joining the WTO will
not have much impact on China's exports to the United States. But
it will have a huge impact on American access to China's market,
because it will force China to open up to foreigners on a defined
schedule with set rules overseen by a multinational organization _
replacing the arbitrary, closed system the Chinese have now. There
is this notion out there that letting China into the WTO is somehow
a giveaway. Well, it is, sort of. It's a giveaway to the U.S.
economy.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more going on here. Zhu Rongji is a closet
globalutionary. He knows that this deal would help force more
transparency, global standards and outside reviews on what is now a
highly secretive system of trade laws in China, in which individual
bureaucrats have huge discretion and therefore huge opportunities
to rip off both foreigners and Chinese. China's entry into the WTO
would also help open the interior of China to foreign investors in
the fields of Internet service, telephones, faxes and banking,
which in turn would help to raise living standards and to develop
parts of China that China itself cannot afford to develop. Right
now foreign companies cannot own telecommunications companies in
China. If China enters the WTO, Sprint, AOL and AT&AMP;T will all be
able to buy into companies there, and that can only contribute to
China's being more wired into the world. Lastly, Chinese
entrepreneurs, who today have to do their importing through state
trading companies, will now be able to import and export directly,
which can only help strengthen the private sector in China.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Zhu clearly sees the WTO as a way to force his
own economic and political reforms on the bloated, inert and
corrupt Chinese system. But we should have no illusions. Opponents
of this deal within China will fight an intense rearguard action
against it if China signs. Implementation will not be easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that the biggest opposition in China is coming
from elements in China's national defense area who are saying to
Zhu, `You are putting us into a globalized world and we are going
to lose control,' '' says Michael Oksenberg, a Stanford University
China scholar.
</P>
<P>
   China is not going to be remade overnight, by this or any other
globalution deal. But China's joining the WTO would be a huge step
in the protracted process of opening up the Middle Kingdom and
easing its wrenching transition from Communism. It would be a
grievous error to miss this opportunity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
