<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-MOSQUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL ADOPTS COMPROMISE PLAN ON NAZARETH MOSQUE DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israel has adopted a compromise plan to resolve a
violent dispute in Nazareth between Muslims and Christians. The
plan would allow a small mosque to be built next to a planned plaza
for millennium pilgrims.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict over Muslim plans to build a large mosque on the
site of the plaza set off clashes for several days this month in
the Israeli Arab town, which is revered by Christians as the
boyhood home of Jesus. The Vatican and church leaders warned that
millennial celebrations there, including an expected visit by Pope
John Paul II, could be jeopardized.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to avert further unrest and friction with the
Christian authorities, a committee of senior Israeli officials
decided on the compromise on Sunday after several unsuccessful
mediation efforts. Officials said that if the plan was rejected,
the government would press its case in court, where the dispute is
already being heard.
</P>
<P>
   The office of the Vatican's envoy to Israel declined to comment
on the plan Monday, but Muslim leaders in Nazareth rejected it,
setting the stage for perhaps weeks or even months of further
litigation before the government takes action.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a decision, not a proposal for negotiation,'' said
Motti Zaken, the prime minister's Arab affairs adviser. ``I'm happy
that the parties are not satisfied, because this is a compromise,
where no one is pleased but everyone can live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tourism Minister Moshe Katzav, the cabinet official responsible
for Arab affairs, predicted that ultimately ``both sides will
accept the solution, because the government has no other
proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   The dispute focuses on a half-acre of state-owned land near the
Basilica of the Annunciation, hallowed to Christians as the site
where the angel Gabriel told Mary that she was pregnant with a son.
The Nazareth municipality cleared the area 18 months ago for a
plaza to accommodate pilgrims expected for the celebrations of the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Muslims set up a protest tent and held prayers at the site, next
to a structure revered as the tomb of Shihab a-Din, a 12th-century
Muslim leader who died in a Crusade battle. Asserting that the land
is the property of an Islamic trust, Muslim leaders announced plans
to build a sprawling mosque there.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute, which reflected a struggle between Nazareth's
Muslim majority and Christian minority over the character of the
city, erupted beginning on Easter Sunday. More than 20 people were
hurt, stones were thrown at Christian motorists and shops, and
stores were attacked with firebombs. Churches closed for two days
in protest, and the Vatican criticized the mosque scheme, calling
it a provocation.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli government tried to mediate the dispute, offering
several solutions that were rejected.
</P>
<P>
   The plan presented Monday provides for a modest mosque at the
disputed site, while promising an alternative site in Nazareth for
a large mosque. The rest of the area will serve as a plaza for
millennium pilgrims, and will be vacated by the Muslim protesters,
according to the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Although it has the support of Nazareth's Christian mayor, Ramez
Jeraysi, it was promptly rejected by local Muslim leaders, who hold
a one-vote majority in the city council.
</P>
<P>
   Salman Abu Ahmad, a leader of the Islamic Movement, which has
the majority in the council, denounced the government plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot give up sacred land that is an Islamic trust,'' Abu
Ahmad said. ``We will not leave this land. We will stay there and
continue our prayers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
