<SLUG> BC-TELECOM-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO EUROPEAN TELEPHONE GIANTS EXPECTED TO ANNOUNCE MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Telecom Italia and Deutsche Telekom, two formerly
state-owned telephone giants of Europe, are expected to announce an
agreement as early as Tuesday to merge in a deal valued at about
$95.4 billion, creating the world's largest telecommunications
company.
</P>
<P>
   The combination, which the boards of the Italian and German
companies were still discussing on Monday night, would rank as the
biggest corporate deal in history. It also is the most stunning
example to date of corporate merger frenzies that are remaking
European businesses and the global telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
   The companies had scheduled a news conference for Tuesday in
London to present the plan for a merger, then postponed it for what
they called organizational reasons. But their boards were planning
to meet Tuesday and people close to the talks said approval of the
deal was expected.
</P>
<P>
   Although the merger would face formidable obstacles, including
possible antimonopoly challenges by European Union regulators, it
is expected to set off a scramble by smaller telephone companies to
find partners.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts said the combined companies could develop a
serious challenge to the overseas ambitions of some of America's
biggest phone companies trying to crack the European market.
</P>
<P>
   It also could presage a possible Deutsche Telekom takeover of
Sprint, the No. 3 long-distance company in the United States, the
one key market uncovered by the German-Italian merger plan.
Deutsche Telekom owns a 10 percent stake in Sprint and there was
speculation Tuesday that it might try to buy the rest.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the Telecom Italia board said it had examined
``substantially, a merger of equals between Telecom Italia and
Deutsche Telekom, from which would emerge the second-largest global
telecommunications group'' by revenue. The board said it would
reconvene Tuesday ``to conclude its evaluations and to make
definitive decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed merger, if approved, would mark the first time that
two of Europe's formerly government-owned phone companies have come
together. Phone companies in Europe, like those in the United
States, have been joining forces to expand their markets and
increase their ability to compete around the world while cutting
costs.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
