<P>
   WASHINGTON-PRIMARY (Seattle) _ Washington state leaders decide
to schedule the presidential primary on Feb. 29 next year, a week
ahead of ``Super Tuesday,'' March 7, when California, New York and
a dozen other states will hold primaries.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   DAMS-BREACHING (WASHTUCNA, Wash.) _ Here in wheat country, fear
and anger flow from rural roads into the towns and cities that line
the Snake River. Federal officials are seriously considering
breaching the four dams of the Lower Snake River. And while the
biggest cost will be replacing electricity from the dams, the
region's struggling farmers fear that the loss of barge
transportation will drive them to their knees. With art. With
sidebars slugged COST-DAMS, FISH-DAMS, EXPLAINER-DAMS. Photos
available through wieck date base.
</P>
<P>
   By Rob Taylor. (Story has moved in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   COST-DAMS (PASCO, Wash.) _ Ron Reimann grows fruit trees,
potatoes and other crops on 1,300 acres that may get put out of
business to save fish. Reimann's land is irrigated by pumps in the
river, but if Ice Harbor Dam is opened, his pumps will be sucking
air.
</P>
<P>
   By Rob Taylor. (Story has moved in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FISH-DAMS (Undated) _ Though study and debate continue, key
scientists have portrayed dam removal as the only strategy that
offers a good chance of restoring Snake River salmon runs to
healthy levels.
</P>
<P>
   By Rob Taylor. (Story has moved in the ``a'' category.)
