<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. PUSHES FOR ALLIED AGREEMENT ON CUTTING OFF FUEL TO SERBS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States, eager to cut off fuel supplies
to Serb military forces, pressed NATO allies Monday to agree on
inspection and enforcement procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's important that, working through the alliance,
that we choke off any efforts of oil being brought in from the
outside,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. diplomatic and defense officials proposed boarding and
searching ships in the Adriatic Sea for cargo that might buttress
the war effort of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic against
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department did not rule out a naval blockade, but
Clinton administration officials indicated they hoped to stop short
of that formal step, which is an act of war under international
law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within the NATO alliance we are looking at a variety of things
to try to take steps to increase the pressure on Milosevic's
military supplies and try to get at the grip by which he represses
Kosovo,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. diplomats were reluctant to discuss resistance to the plan
within NATO, but administration officials indicated problems
remained with the French, Italians and Greeks.
</P>
<P>
   In the Balkans, Milosevic's military forces, who had been
herding Kosovar refugees toward Albania and Macedonia, closed
border crossing points without warning or explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of allied governments were at a loss to explain where
the long line of refugees, who had been waiting just inside Kosovo
over the weekend, had gone but said it was yet another ominous
sign.
</P>
<P>
   On the diplomatic front, President Clinton talked with President
Boris Yeltsin of Russia by telephone for 45 minutes, their first
conversation since the bombing started 28 days ago Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman said the leaders' discussion included the prospect
that Russian troops would join an international peacekeeping force
in Kosovo after a cease-fire and withdrawal of Serb forces.
Russians are already part of a similar multinational force in
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan said he will soon go to Moscow
for consultations with Russian leaders, who have strongly condemned
NATO's assault on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Annan said he would not be carrying any specific new peace
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said Yeltsin reaffirmed his public statements that
Russia ``won't be drawn into this conflict.'' Yeltsin had announced
earlier Monday that additional Russian Navy vessels would not be
sent to the Adriatic Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also asked Congress for $6 billion in emergency spending
for the Balkans conflict, most of it for the U.S.-led NATO military
operations but with some humanitarian funding for ethnic Albanian
refugees who have fled Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are literally lives hanging in the balance,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke over the weekend with French President Jacques
Chirac, and apparently they discussed cutting off Milosevic's oil
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Reuters news agency quoted a French foreign ministry official in
Paris as saying that France was well aware it was crucial to stop
the flow of oil to Yugoslavia but said that a legal basis had to be
found.
</P>
<P>
   Halting oil tankers could require a new U.N. resolution, the
French government sources said, but the Clinton administration
contended no new U.N. authorization was needed to crack down on oil
shipments that could benefit Serb troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our basis is that there already is a United Nations'
resolution banning any importing of military supplies,'' Lockhart
said.
</P>
<P>
   The issue was complicated by the fact that Milosevic's only
seaport is in Montenegro, Yugoslavia's nominally pro-Western
republic.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said allied airstrikes ``have taken
out about 70 percent of the (Yugoslav) military supplies of fuel.''
He said Milosevic's army ``is hurting now because of a lack of oil,
both of supplies and the ability to distribute it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's state-run Tanjug news agency said air raid sirens
sounded Monday night in the capital of Belgrade and that airstrikes
were reported in other regions, including Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by a reporter at the alliance daily briefing at
headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, to reflect on what will soon be
a monthlong air campaign, NATO spokesman Shea said the operation
would not be judged by the calendar.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more just your cause is, the longer you're justified in
pursuing that cause, obviously,'' Shea said. ``The strategy is
going to work. It's working at the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
