<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NERVOUS JASPER, A THIRD OF STUDENTS ARE KEPT OUT OF SCHOOL 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ There were no bombs in Jasper on Monday. No
rallies, no marches, no threats, nothing. A handwritten sign taped
inside the front door of the Jasper County Courthouse casually
reminded the last person out to lock up.
</P>
<P>
   But in this East Texas town made famous by last summer's
dragging death of a black man, nerves are still jangled. On top of
that, Monday was the anniversary of the Oklahoma City bombing and
the Branch Davidian fire in Waco, and Tuesday is a pretrial hearing
for the second of three white men accused in the murder of James
Byrd Jr.
</P>
<P>
   For many, it was just too much. So they kept their kids home
from school.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 1,080 students, or 32 percent of those enrolled in
Jasper's two elementary schools, the middle school and the high
school, were absent when the bell rang Monday morning, or were
picked up by parents shortly after classes started, said Doug
Koebernick, superintendent of the Jasper Independent School
District.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand parents hold their children very dearly,''
Koebernick said. ``But there have been no threats, no problems at
all. The weather is beautiful, and we are having a great day at
school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted the peace of mind,'' said Shannan Holmes, who
sent her 8-year-old daughter, Meagan, to the baby sitter with her
little brother instead of to second grade at Parnell Elementary.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's all kinds of nasty rumors going around, but I just
thought it was better to be safe. It's just one day. She can go
back tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The rumors started circulating several weeks ago after officials
at the Texas Department of Criminal Justice intercepted two letters
from a prison inmate who is a member of the Aryan Circle, a racist
prison gang. The inmate was once imprisoned with John William
``Bill'' King, a 24-year-old white supremacist who was convicted in
Byrd's dragging murder and sentenced to death earlier this year,
and with King's co-defendant, Lawrence Russell Brewer Jr., 32,
whose pretrial hearing is scheduled for this morning.
</P>
<P>
   The letters, intended for two other inmates, discussed a
``family reunion and annual Jasper tractor pull and drag racing
event'' that was to take place on April 19.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper County District Attorney Guy James Gray earlier had cited
the date of the Oklahoma City bombing and the Waco fire in
rescheduling Brewer's change of venue hearing from Monday to
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI investigated the letter-writing inmate and alerted
Jasper authorities, who added more patrols as a precaution, Jasper
Police Chief Stanley Christopher said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But Christopher insisted he had not received any other threats
of violence and urged parents to send their children back to
school. His own son went to high school Monday, and his grandson
was in day care, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all rumor,'' he said, clearly exasperated. ``There are
no threats. There are no bombs. We have not received any word of
any rallies or demonstrations by the KKK or the Black Panthers or
anybody. There is nothing to substantiate any of these rumors.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Superintendent Koebernick said parents started calling him at
home Sunday night, and he and other administrators tried to assure
them that the schools had not been threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Lout, owner of local radio station KJAS 107.3, said several
parents called him Sunday night, asking about rumors of bomb
threats at the schools and at Wal-Mart. None was true, he told
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had one call at 2:30 this morning, and another at 4 a.m.,
parents wanting to know if the schools were going to be open, and
if I thought it would be safe to send their kids,'' Lout said. ``I
told them I didn't see any reason why it wouldn't be.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after several assuring radio reports on Monday morning,
worried parents continued to call the station, he said, asking
whether they should go pick up their kids.
</P>
<P>
   Koebernick said he was hopeful that the students would return to
school Tuesday, even though Brewer, who goes on trial May 17, will
make an appearance at the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only one anniversary, and the anniversary is today,''
the superintendent said. ``We expect that all the kids will be back
in school tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
