<HEADER>
A4924 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-ART-5     04-19 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-ART-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEES' REPORTS OF RAPES AND KILLINGS ON INCREASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ Refugees arriving in Macedonia from Kosovo
are increasingly reporting rapes and killings by Yugoslav forces,
international observers said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees arriving in recent days from the area around Gnijlane
in southeastern Kosovo have related stories of summary executions
and of a mass grave in the area they passed through, said an
official of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the European group have been interviewing
refugees to try to document reports of atrocities against the
Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   The reports, if true, would represent a worsening of the
situation for civilians fleeing to Macedonia, the official said.
``In particular in the last three to four days, we have had stories
of summary executions,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Albanian refugees have flooded in from Kosovo over
the last few days, in a second wave of mass expulsions conducted by
Yugoslav forces. This wave appears to be slower than the first, in
which 50,000 refugees were forced out in 48 hours, but may prove
more deadly, the European official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is slower, and more systematic,'' he said. ``We are now
getting reports of mass graves, which is an indication that it is
getting worse.''
</P>
<P>
   After surging over the weekend, the flow of refugees out of
Kosovo slowed dramatically Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In the first wave of refugees here, largely from Pristina, the
Kosovo capital, and the city of Urosevac, there was only one report
of young men being separated and taken away, a European official
said, and most of the young men from Pristina were allowed to
leave. But reports that men are being separated from their families
and not allowed to leave with them are increasing.
</P>
<P>
   The early refugees had reported killings by Serbian security
forces, but in small numbers. ``I had the impression that in the
first wave they did not have time'' to commit systematic killing,
the European official said of the Serbian security forces.
</P>
<P>
   European officials said that in seven interviews recently,
including one with an alleged victim, refugees had reported rapes
by Yugoslav troops or police personnel.
</P>
<P>
   In the other six cases, the refugees said they had witnessed
rapes. One described a rape and the brutal killing of the victim.
Another described seeing the rapes of several women by soldiers or
members of the Serbian police.
</P>
<P>
   The European group has a team of 50 observers working in refugee
camps and villages in Macedonia, interviewing and trying to
document reports of human rights abuses. Another 77 are working in
Albania. The officials said the team members are being meticulous
in gathering documentation and trying to double-check the reports.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence will be offered to the tribunal at The Hague,
Netherlands, that is prosecuting Balkan war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   One European official, who is preparing an internal report
documenting the level of atrocities, described the situation in
Kosovo as ``absolutely lawless,'' with reports of abuses by
Yugoslav civilians as well as soldiers and police personnel. The
official said there were very few reports of police or army
personnel or Serbian friends offering help or protection to Kosovo
Albanians who were threatened with violence.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In one report, a person was reported to have been killed for
refusing to leave for the border, the European officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the office of the U.N. high commissioner for
refugees said Monday that they feared that Yugoslav forces were
again preventing tens of thousands of ethnic Albanians from fleeing
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   After a wave of 30,000 refugees poured out of Kosovo during one
24-hour period last weekend, only several hundred refugees from
Kosovo crossed into Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro on Monday,
the refugee agency officials reported.
</P>
<P>
   ''It all seems very ominous,'' said Kris Janowski, a spokesman
for the office of the high commissioner. ``Before there were tens
of thousands of people who were terrified and fleeing, and now
you've got this invisible curtain that has descended where no one
crosses.''
</P>
<P>
   The few refugees who did manage to arrive in Macedonia reported
seeing Yugoslav forces blocking Albanians from leaving Kosovo.
Systematic attacks on Albanian villages, which refugees said were
intensifying last week in southeastern Kosovo, were now being
carried out against Albanian villages near Pristina, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Adem Kacori, a bus driver who arrived here Monday with his
8-year-old son, said five villages north of Pristina _ Barilevo,
Milevc, Leban, Pugovc and Ovenovac _ had been burned by Yugoslav
forces in the last three days.
</P>
<P>
   Two refugees from the Pristina area reported seeing villages
burning around Pristina during the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees continued to describe nightmarish scenes inside Kosovo.
One of the refugees said the body of a man who was shot dead in
front of her home in Pristina lay in the street for four days
because no one dared venture outside to retrieve it. Her sons, she
said, were terrified by the thunderous concussions of NATO bombs
and the endless rifle fire from Serbian paramilitaries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
