<SLUG> BC-RUN-MARATHON-MMASTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFRESHED KUZNETSOV TAKES MEN'S MASTERS HONORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- This time, unlike last year, Andrey Kuznetsov was much
more comfortable with his hotel arrangements. He didn't have to
sleep in the lobby of the hotel _ the Fairmont Copley Plaza _ for a
night, Saturday evening, upon finally getting his visa to come to
Boston to run the Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he had his own bed, telephone, shower area throughout
his stay. Life was much more comfortable this time.
</P>
<P>
   There was no difference in the result, though. Kuznetsov won the
masters for the second consecutive year. Monday, in seven place
overall, Kuznetsov _ from Havarovsk, Russia and living in
Gainesville, Fla. the last three months _ had a 2:14.20 time.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Kuznetsov, 41, has beefed up his bank account a
bunch, with $19,000 _ $10,000 for his masters crown and $9,000 for
the place. He is considered the world's best masters runner.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in his first year as a masters, he won five masters
marathons _ in Houston, Grandma's, Twin Cities, Ocean State as well
as Boston _ his total prize money $51,150. He was 15th overall in
Boston with the third best time at 2:15.27.
</P>
<P>
   This year's time is better, a new third best at the Boston
marathon. Kuznetsov's best marathon was at 2:12.31, that in Monaco
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first half of the race was easy for me, but in the second
half, I tried to run faster to get better results, but with the
mountains and the hills, my legs were heavy,'' Kuznetsov said. ``I
was happy with my results. This year, though, the wind with a
little more to my face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going into the race, I felt very well, very confident. I was
ready to run, figuring that I would run about 2:12 or 2:14,
depending on the weather conditions. Every mile was faster, about
five minutes or so in the second half. I could catchup, but it was
a little too fast. I started to feel the tiredness.''
</P>
<P>
   In his last marathon, in Houston in mid-January, Kuznetsov won
with a 2:19.56. ``I wanted to get closer to my personal record,
that was one of my goals,'' he stated of Monday's run. ``I love the
track here, and the people are very nice. The general environment
is very welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuznetsov has been a serious runner since age 26. Before that,
he preferred cross country skiing. And now he runs six marathons a
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the only running I do, though,'' added Kuznetsov,
who lives in Florida with his wife, Olga, and two daughters. ``I
run different races between them, about three or four other runs,
just not as long.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerning last year's hotel difficulty, it wasn't Kuznwetsov's
fault. ``It was the decision of the people who work in the American
Embassy,'' said Kuznetsov, who continues to coach youngsters in his
Russian hometown. ``They gave me a hard time. I went to Jamaica and
won overall there, with the course record. And then the American
Embassy didn't give me a visa.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I was forced to go from Jamaica in my shorts and t-shirt in
February in the freezing wind. I couldn't go back home, though,
because it's seven times zones different, can you imagine now many
thousands of miles that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I fought for my visa and rather than trying to go back and
training in Russia in the snow and ice. I got my visa to come here
very late, two days before the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year, Kuznetsov will go for his third consecutive Boston
Marathon in the masters division. Room service in his hotel
throughout his stay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
