<HEADLINE>
CHOW: GO ON, HAVE ANOTHER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; _ Dean Edell &LR;  writes in ``Eat, Drink &AMP; Be Merry''
(HarperCollins; $25) that if over your whole lifetime (it's
probably too late already) only 30 percent of the calories you
consumed came from fat, your life expectancy would increase by
three months if you're a woman and four months if you're a man.
Pass the fries, please.
</P>
<P>
   _ East Bay physician  &UR; Oscar London &LR; , whose online essays are
available at HealthCentral.com, says calorie counting is futile.
``The five-year cure rate for lung cancer is 5 percent, versus 2
percent for obesity. ... In other words, you're more than twice as
likely to be cured of lung cancer than of obesity. The 2 percent
who manage this rare feat transform themselves from overweight
lovely people into the biggest bores on the planet. But thin. Far
into their nursing home years, they wheel swiftly up and down the
corridors searching for someone to be amazed at how little they had
for breakfast.''
</P>
<P>
   _ In ``American Appetite, the Coming of Age of a Cuisine''
(Bard; $25),  &UR; Leslie Brenner &LR;  explores the difference between the
north and the south, at least in Mexican cuisine. ``If San
Francisco and the rest of Northern California distinguished itself
with burritos,'' she writes, ``Los Angeles' Mexican cooks made
their statement with tacos.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Ken Maley  &LR; forwards ``The Making of a Home,'' a Life magazine
story from May 1953 about home-economics majors at Cornell
University:
</P>
<P>
   ``Critics belittle Cornell's approach by saying that a girl need
only know how to read labels in order to run a home; her college
years would be better spent taking broader educational courses. To
this Cornell replies that making a home is likely to be the biggest
part of a woman's life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SEEKING THE CURRYS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If you're an actor who wants to spend the summer at Camp Curry,
the administration at Yosemite is looking for two ``centennial
interpreters'' to play  &UR; David &LR;  and  &UR; Jennie (Mother) &LR; 
 &UR; Curry &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The Currys, who were schoolteachers in Redwood City, founded
Camp Curry in Yosemite on June 1, 1899. He is remembered for
``stentorian'' _ ``generous in voice, generous in build'' _ shouts;
she is remembered as being ``attentive to guest and employee
needs.''
</P>
<P>
   David and Mother will stroll through Curry Village ``while in
costume and character,'' give daily tours, host evening programs
and organize children's activities. Candidates should fax their
qualifications to (209) 372-1135.cq &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
