<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0426 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4930 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-2NDTAKE-N     04-19 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BRUSSELS, Belgium: somewhat lower.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wearing his flight suit, Leaf explained that the episode began
about 12:30 p.m. local time, when a pair of U.S. F-16s observed
ethnic Albanian villages being set on fire north of Djakovica.
Their call sign was ``Bear 21.'' The episode was first documented
last week at NATO when alliance officials took the unusual step of
playing a taped interview with one of these F-16 pilots.
</P>
<P>
   A F-16 pilots in ``Bear 21'' saw people running from a house
that burst into flames and jumping onto a vehicle, which NATO
officials said may have been a tractor. Believing that they had set
the house on fire, he attacked the vehicle with a laser-guided
bomb, destroying it.
</P>
<P>
   Another bomb was later dropped north of the town in an attack by
a different group of F-16s. Serb television later showed destroyed
tractors at that site, raising the possibility of civilian
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's principal disclosure, however, was of the attack later in
the day south of the town on a large convoy of more than 100
vehicles. That raid involved several sets of aircraft, including
F-16s, French Jaguars, OA-10 observers, as well as a flying
airborne command and control aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Another important link was NATO's command center in Vicenza,
Italy _ known at the Combined Air Operations Center- which is
coordinating the air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The raids on this column began when two F-16s, code-named ``Bear
31,'' saw the convoy. From the start, the F-16 pilots were worried
about the possibility of civilian casualties. With many villages
aflame, there was reason to think that many refugees might be on
the road.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf said the pilots in ``Bear 31'' had an ``extensive
discussion'' with the ABCCC command plane about whether the convoy
was a civilian or military target. It was not easy for the pilots
to identify the vehicles from the high altitude they generally fly
at to avoid Serbian anti-aircraft artillery.
</P>
<P>
   And while F-16s incorporate advanced military technology, these
systems have their limits. Potential targets are shown in the F-16
cockpit on a special display, which is about 4.5 inches wide and
4.5 inches long. The targets are not shown in color, but in shades
of green.
</P>
<P>
   An F-16 pilot has to look out the cockpit to see the color of
the vehicles below him, an important factor since military vehicles
are often painted dark green. He cannot use binoculars because the
cockpit is too small, a military official said.
</P>
<P>
   As was the case of the ``Bear 21'' F-16 patrol north of
Djakovica, the ``Bear 31'' F-16s were flying air controllers, whose
mission was not only to carry out strikes but to coordinate attacks
by other allied planes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite worries about refugees on the road, a number of factors
led ``Bear 31'' to conclude they were observing a military column.
The 20 or so vehicles at the front appeared to be traveling in
formation, with a set distance between them. They were moving
quickly, leading the pilots to believe they were not tractors.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the ABCCC command and control alerted the planes that
the convoy was made up of Yugoslav military vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The two F-16s attacked the convoy, destroying one vehicle. They
called in strikes by two French Jacquar planes, which missed the
convoy.
</P>
<P>
   The F-16s ran low on fuel and were replaced by another pair of
F-16 planes, codenamed ``Bear 41,'' which came under Serb
anti-aircraft fire.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, there was an ominous warning. After twenty minutes of
bombing against the convoy, the command center in Italy wanted the
planes to check the targets again and make sure that they were
military.
</P>
<P>
   Military intelligence experts at the command center were dubious
that Serbian forces would be driving down an open road in such a
long convoy. They had been hiding and hunkering down for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   To get a better look ``Bear 41'' asked for help from a pair of
OA-10s, code-named ``Cub,'' which had been flying over eastern
Kosovo. The plane is slower and its pilot use binoculars to pick
out targets.
</P>
<P>
   The OA-10s reported that military vehicles had been struck, but
that civilian vehicles also seemed to be present. By then seven
laser-guided bombs had been aimed at a convoy south of Djakovica,
though not all of them hit their mark.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf still insists that some military vehicles were hit. Others
appear to have been tractors.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we watch these videos in the comfort of this room and on a
large display it appears possible the vehicles are tractors _ or
tractor-type vehicles,'' he said. ``As I reviewed the tapes with
the pilots, they agreed. However, they were emphatic that from the
attack altitude, to the naked eye, they appeared to be military
vehicles.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaf acknowledged that British Harrier pilots had seen a convoy
and identified it as containing refugees. This happened at about
the same time as the attacks on the convoy were being carried out,
but Leaf said the Harriers were ``not in communication with the
aircraft in question.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior allied officer said the episode had NATO commanders
order a re-examination of procedures for finding and identifying
targets. But worried about Serbian anti-aircraft fire, the alliance
appears intent on continuing high-altitude strikes for now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
