<HEADER>
A4935 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-ART-2TAKES(1     04-19 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-ART-2TAKES(1,050)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK MARKET HIT AS INVESTORS FLEE TECHNOLOGY AREA
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Two graphics on Monday's sell-off are is being sent to
NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON and KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; NEW YORK _ In a stunning reversal, investors piled out of
technology stocks and other market darlings on Monday, pummeling
the very shares that propelled the broad market averages to records
last week.
</P>
<P>
   After rising 271.8 points, or 2.6 percent, during the morning,
the Dow Jones industrial average ran out of steam shortly after
noon and ended the day down 53.4 points on the day, or a
half-percent, at 10,440.53.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq market started the day in negative territory and
never climbed out as investors fled the computer, Internet and
telecommunications stocks that they had favored. The Nasdaq
Composite, home to most of the nation's technology companies, fell
138 points, or 5.6 percent, to close at 2,345.61. That was the
composite's second steepest fall in points but only its seventh in
percentage terms. Its largest point decline took place on Aug. 31,
at the height of the Russian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Volume on the New York Stock Exchange exceeded 1.2 billion
shares, the second-heaviest trading day in exchange history. Nasdaq
trading volume was also brisk, at 1.198 billion shares.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the day, investors took refuge in stocks whose fortunes
rise and fall with the economy, but even those shares began to
sputter at the close. ``This kind of a sharp and dramatic reversal
is not just business as usual,'' said Byron R. Wien, an investment
strategist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``There's a message here.
The message is everything finally began to sell off from sheer
exhaustion.''
</P>
<P>
   Though oil prices rose in the morning, there was no fundamental
event that caused the noontime reversal in the Dow average.
Instead, the shift from the glamour stocks of technology, health
care, Internet and telecommunications companies _ a phenomenon that
began last week _ simply gained momentum on Monday. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's/Barra Growth stock index _ a collection of companies with
high growth rates and lofty stock valuations _ has fallen 10
percent in the past five trading days.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the biggest losers Monday were stocks that had
previously seemed to levitate. Even after Monday's collapse, these
shares are trading at high prices based on their earnings and are
well above their lows. America Online, for example, fell $26.9375
to close at $115.875. Although that is down more than 30 percent
from its high of April 6, the shares are now where they were just
about a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   And Charles Schwab Corp., a brokerage concern that is a favorite
Internet play because of its online trading services, closed down
32 percent from its high of one week ago. Still, it is up 81
percent since the start of the year. Reflecting the overall damage
done to Internet stocks, the American Stock Exchange's Internet
index is down 18 percent from its high of last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Proving once again that the market's leadership can change on a
dime, investors last week began to realize that excessive
valuations in stocks posed more risk than they could comfortably
accept. Rather than flee stocks entirely, they shifted to shares of
some companies that had been left for dead. Previously unglamourous
companies such as United Technologies Corp, a maker of heating and
air conditioning systems, elevators and jet engines; 3M, an
industrial products maker, and Smurfit-Stone Container, a paper
manufacturer, registered impressive gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors had the idea that it's a new economy and a new stock
market and that meant you don't have to worry about the old rules
of diversification and quality,'' said Alan F. Skrainka, chief
market strategist at Edward Jones in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   No longer.
</P>
<P>
   The move away from growth stocks with high valuations and into
companies that are viewed as cheaper began last week. Market
strategists pointed to two events that gave investors pause. The
first was the European Central Bank's move on April 8 to cut
interest rates, a signal that policymakers are committed to keeping
the world on a path to economic growth by jumpstarting Europe's
economies.
</P>
<P>
   Why would this send growth stock investors running for cover?
``When growth is scarce, investors don't want to own stocks whose
fortunes are hostage to the economy,'' explained Skrainka. ``But
when growth is plentiful, the tide lifts all boats, and that may be
what we're facing as global economies start to pick up.''
</P>
<P>
   The second scare for growth stock investors came last Monday
when Compaq Computer warned that its quarterly earnings would be
half what Wall Street analysts had been expecting. This reminded
traders that technology, for all its promise, can also disappoint.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to investor concern about growth stocks in general and
technology stocks in particular, was the news on Friday that Robert
Stansky, the manager of Fidelity's Magellan fund, had sold large
positions in many of the hot technology stocks that had been his
biggest holdings. Stansky moved into more mundane stocks that were
trading at lower premiums to their earnings growth rates, so-called
value shares.
</P>
<P>
   Stock traders noted Monday that there were so few buyers for
most stocks that sellers could get out only if they accepted prices
well below the prevailing market. Some stocks fell sharply even
though a relatively few shares exchanged hands.
</P>
<P>
   Companies waiting in the wings to offer their shares to the
public for the first time were likely losers in Monday's market
decline as well. Three internet concerns, Net Perceptions Inc.,
Proxicom Inc., and Launch Media Inc., had planned initial public
offerings this week. Until investors become more hospitable to
companies like these, such offerings will remain on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Market strategists pointed to the hordes of rapid-fire
daytraders, many of whom are relative newcomers to stocks but who
have yet to experience a severe decline in stock prices. In recent
months, these traders have created significant momentum and profits
as they piled into stocks. Now that they are piling out, they are
likely to create tidal waves of selling.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a case where a lot of these stocks have some
unreasonable gains,'' said Lazslo Birinyi, who heads his own stock
research company in Greenwich, Conn. ``Now people are starting to
lock in the gains when they can. As these stocks decline from their
highs, the movement feeds on itself.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Longtime traders worry that a flood of calls from brokerage
companies will go out to stock investors on Tuesday for more funds
to prop up diminished portfolios that they have borrowed against to
buy more stocks. Customers must meet these requests, known as
margin calls, with fresh money or with cash raised by selling
stocks. If shares are sold, the market decline could accelerate.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Ameritrade, a large discount brokerage firm,
acknowledged that it had slightly higher margin calls than normal
on Monday, adding that it had no discernible problems with trading.
She also noted that the brokerage firm had previously imposed
higher borrowing limits, presumably lessening the number of margin
calls that would go out to customers.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, investors could jump back into their former stock
market darlings if they judge the selling to be overdone. Such a
strategy has served them well over the last five years and was
especially shrewd when the market rebounded from its correction
last October. Microsoft, for example, which was down 6.5 percent
Monday, announces its earnings Tuesday. Investors may like what
they see and bid the stock back up again.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Wien, of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, said that the
United States stock market remained overvalued and that the broad
market averages would experience a correction, defined by traders
as a decline of 20 percent. ``What you're seeing is a resolution of
excessive valuation in the market. I expect the indexes to decline
further, but I don't think we're in a bear market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
