<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0433 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4946 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELECOM-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;      04-19 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELECOM-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ROME: cutting costs.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the agreement were announced, it would pose what appears to
be an insurmountable obstacle to a $65 billion hostile bid for
Telecom Italia by Olivetti SpA, the No. 2 Italian phone company.
</P>
<P>
   It was Olivetti's bid for Telecom Italia last month that forced
the bigger company's chief executive, Franco Bernabe, into an
urgent search for a savior and discussions with his Deutsche
Telekom counterpart, Ron Summer.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Colaninno, Olivetti's chief executive, was the most
prominent skeptic about the proposed German-Italian deal on Monday,
suggesting that the postponement of the news conference in London
signaled broader problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had to cancel the press conference?'' he said to
reporters. `'Why? Aren't the planes flying?''
</P>
<P>
   But advisers to the companies said they were confident the
boards would reach agreement. `'They will pull it off,'' an adviser
to Deutsche Telekom said.
</P>
<P>
   A merger of the two companies would create the world's largest
phone company ranked by stock market value, at about $212 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Its revenue, of about $63 billion, would be surpassed only by
that of the Japanese phone giant, NTT.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dramatic move,'' said Christopher Tucker, director of
telecommunications research at the West LB Panmure brokerage in
London. `'It's a wakeup call to the sector.''
</P>
<P>
   Although details of the merger remained unclear on Monday night,
the chief executives of both companies were expected to share
responsibilities for a period of time.
</P>
<P>
   According to advisers to the companies, the deal could involve
the creation of a new company in which Deutsche Telekom
shareholders would own the majority stake. They said the new
company would pay as much as 12 euros, or about $12.72, for each
Telecom Italia share. Based on Telecom Italia's 7.43 billion shares
outstanding, the total value of the deal would be about $95.4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Though the companies appeared at pains on Monday night to
describe the deal as a merger of equals, it was clear that Deutsche
Telekom would likely emerge the stronger partner.
</P>
<P>
   Trading in the shares of Telecom Italia on the Milan exchange
and in the company's American depository receipts on Wall Street
were suspended on Monday. The Milan authorities said they would
decide before the start of trading Tuesday whether to continue the
suspension. In Frankfurt, the share price of Deutsche Telekom
closed down 0.7 percent, at 37.90 euros.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the listless performance of Deutsche Telekom
reflected some investor skepticism at the deal. Given earlier
assurances by the government of Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema that
Telecom Italia should not be sold to foreign buyers, analysts said
it would be difficult to frame conditions that would make it appear
the deal was a full merger of equals. Moreover, given the powerful
market positions of both companies in their domestic markets, the
deal can be expected to come under close scrutiny by European
antitrust authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Karel Van Miert, the chief European antitrust official, said on
Monday that any such deal could not go ahead ``without substantial
concessions'' from both companies. Speaking to reporters in Geneva,
Switzerland, Van Miert said the proposed deal ``will be a
complicated case,'' but that `'one cannot be against a large merger
in principle,'' particularly given the trend to large combinations
in the global industry.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Olivetti advisers were quick to criticize the proposed deal.
``These are two not too efficient giants getting together, and they
think they are creating a Ferrari,'' said an investment banker
advising Olivetti.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while officials close to both companies sought to
project an air of certainty, differences appear to have arisen
among the members of the Telecom Italia board over the planned 40
percent control that would be left to Telecom Italia shareholders,
which would require substantial legal maneuvering to assure that a
merger of equals would in fact emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the German government, which now holds a 72 percent
share in Deutsche Telekom, would wind up with a diluted 40 percent
share after the proposed merger. But this too remains a problem for
Italian leaders. Telecom Italia, the formerly national phone
company, was taken public by the government in recent years, and
the Rome government now holds a residual 3.4 percent share, which
gives it veto rights over major decisions.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alema, the Italian prime minister, reiterated Italy's interest
that the proposed company be controlled equally by German and
Italian interest. `'The agreement has to be of equals,'' he told a
weekly briefing.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said, German government ownership could be an
obstacle. `'We cannot allow ourselves to think that, having now
privatized Telecom Italia, it could become a company in which the
prime owner is the German state,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A working group of cabinet and Treasury ministry officials is
expected to meet on Wednesday to set criteria under which the Rome
government may exercise its veto right, D'Alema's office said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Criticism of the deal came also from France Telecom, which
appeared to be one of the big losers in the arrangement. France
Telecom is linked with Deutsche Telekom in two major alliances, and
the companies have reciprocal 2 percent shareholdings.
</P>
<P>
   France Telecom, in a statement, said it was `'premature to
measure all the consequences for the French-German partnership.''
</P>
<P>
   But the share price of France Telecom was hit hard on the Paris
bourse, falling 5.4 percent to close at 76.50 euros.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the merger was substantially worked out in recent
weeks in discussions between Telecom Italia's Bernabe and Deutsche
Telekom's Sommer. Deutsche Telekom hired Goldman Sachs to advise it
on the shape such a merger could take; Bernabe has been using
Credit Suisse First Boston and J.P. Morgan as advisers.
</P>
</TEXT>
