<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4949 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBC-BRANAM-COLUMN-LAD     04-19 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-BRANAM-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CAN'T-LOSE DECISION FOR TUCKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It seemed like the perfect fit: A local player
chooses to play baseball at the local university. For Brad Tucker,
though, it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   After three seasons at Fresno State, Tucker decided he needed to
go pitch for a team where he felt wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a time where I needed to make a decision for my
baseball career,'' Tucker said. ``What I felt was the best decision
for me was to get out of there. I felt I wasn't getting the best
out of myself. I needed a change of scenery.''
</P>
<P>
   The right-handed Tucker went from a pitcher without an identity
at Fresno State to a player who seemingly can't lose at Pepperdine.
His record with the Waves over the past 1{ seasons is 15-1,
including 7-0 this season.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker has helped the Waves to a 32-7 record and a ranking as
high as third in the nation. Even after two mediocre outings this
past weekend at Loyola Marymount _ Saturday he lasted just 11/3
innings and gave up five earned runs _ Tucker leads the Waves
starters with a 2.73 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   In three outings before the LMU series, he was 2-0 with a 0.76
ERA. The Pepperdine staff entered last week fifth in the nation
with a 3.25 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really happy for Brad,'' Pepperdine coach Frank Sanchez
said. ``Brad has been able to establish himself here.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't at Fresno State, even after coming in as a heralded
freshman from Bullard High, a local baseball powerhouse. He
appeared in 28 games as a Bulldog, 19 starts, and had a combined
record of 7-5. He was 4-2 as a freshman, redshirted his sophomore
year after suffering a lower back injury, then went 3-3 with a 4.42
ERA in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The local media labeled Tucker a disappointment, especially
after the success his older brother Ben had as a pitcher at USC.
Still, he said it was tough to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of people that followed me up there and who were
supportive,'' he said. ``But I kind of got myself into a rut.''
</P>
<P>
   Riordan rallying: Outfielder Matt Riordan developed into a solid
college player _ and pro prospect _ in his first two seasons at
Loyola Marymount.
</P>
<P>
   This year has been more of a struggle for Riordan, who was the
Daily News' Player of the Year in 1995 at Westlake High. After
getting the game-winning single in the Lions' 6-5 win over
Pepperdine on Sunday, Riordan's season batting average stood at
.315. His career average at LMU was .352 entering the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been unlucky in a lot of things,'' Riordan said. ``Bad
calls by umpires, line drives hit right at people.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he hit safely in a team-high 14 games earlier this
season and is 16 for 19 in stolen-base attempts, Riordan said he
thinks he's pressed at the plate. He will be eligible for the
major-league draft in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to play pro ball,'' he said. ``We'll see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Angelic touch: It's no surprise LMU's three-game sweep of
Pepperdine coincided with the return of junior second baseman
Anthony Angel to the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Angel sprained his ankle in the first game of a doubleheader
against San Francisco three weeks ago. He missed the Lions'
nonconference game at USC and two games at Portland. LMU was 1-3 in
that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough to sit on the bench,'' said Angel, who is LMU
head coach Frank Cruz's nephew. ``It was definitely tough. (But) I
saw a lot of things I can work on.''
</P>
<P>
   Angel used his new-found knowledge to bat .533 (8 for 15) in the
three games against the Waves. He had seven RBI in the series and
hit his third homer of the season in Saturday's 19-10 win.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Angel) is such a magnet,'' Cruz said. ``He's a leader. It's
good to have him back, no doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Tie at the top: USC, all but out of the postseason six weeks
ago, is tied for the Pacific-10 lead with Stanford after taking two
of three against the host Cardinal this past weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans (26-18 overall, 12-3 in the Pac-10) beat Stanford
17-15 on Sunday despite a career-high five hits and seven RBI by
former Camarillo standout Joe Borchard, who leads the Cardinal with
a .399 average and eight home runs.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the Trojans were down 9-2. The best pitching
performance by USC came from Dominic Correa, normally a utility
infielder. He pitched the last three innings and didn't give up an
earned run to earn his first career win.
</P>
<P>
   Great Scott: Bill Scott, a sophomore outfielder at UCLA,
continued his impressive season with a three-run homer and four RBI
in the Bruins' 9-3 win Saturday over Arizona State. Scott leads
UCLA with 15 homers and 60 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA got a game-winning grand slam in the bottom of the ninth
from second baseman Chase Utley to beat the 14th-ranked Sun Devils
8-6 Sunday and complete a three-game sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, who had never hit more than two homers in a game at
Alemany High, set Pac-10 records with four homers and 11 RBI
against Washington on March 30. He leads the Bruins (20-23) in nine
offensive categories. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
