<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Stock Splits And Your Tax Bill
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Arthur M. Louis &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I am holding some common stock that I purchased in 1987
at $72 per share. The original holding was 100 shares, but the
stock has split 2-for-1 three times since then, and now I have 800
shares, recently selling at $55 per share. If I sell only the
original 100 shares, can I use the $72-per-share cost basis in
figuring my capital gain?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; Answer: &LR;  Boy, don't you wish!
</P>
<P>
   If you could do that, you could reduce your tax bill by
declaring a capital loss to offset your capital gains or other
income. You would be selling $5,500 worth of stock while figuring
your cost basis at $7,200.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, you can't do that. Because the stock splits have
left you with eight times as many shares as you started, you must
divide your original cost per share by eight to determine your
present per-share cost basis.
</P>
<P>
   Eight divided into 72 equals 9, so your cost per current share
is $9. If you were to sell 100 shares at $55 per share, you would
have to report a $4,600 long-term capital gain ($5,500 minus $900).
The gain would be long term because you have held the shares for
more than one year.
</P>
<P>
   What you have in mind is not, as you suggest, selling your
``original 100 shares.'' Your original 100 shares have become 800
shares, so selling 100 now is the same as selling only 12-1/2 of
your original shares.
</P>
<P>
   Value of Old Stocks
</P>
<P>
   Q: From 1969 to 1975 I was employed with General Electric and
picked up some stock through my retirement fund. I have the
certificates in my possession, and want to know how I can contact
GE to determine their worth. I believe the stock has split over the
past 20 years and also has been accumulating dividends. Can you
give me some direction?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Something doesn't add up. If you have held the
certificates all those years, then GE should have sent you new
shares every time it split the stock. It also should have mailed
you dividends every three months.
</P>
<P>
   It may be that the bureaucracy fouled up your account somehow,
but I doubt it. The more likely explanation is that you changed
addresses without informing GE. If you did, the post office would
have bounced your split shares and dividends back to GE's transfer
agent.
</P>
<P>
   If that happened, then GE was legally required to turn your
property over to the government of the state in which you lived
just before the company lost track of you. The states hold
unclaimed property indefinitely. If that's what happened, you will
have to file a detailed claim with the state, establishing your
identity and your rights to the property.
</P>
<P>
   But your first move should be to telephone GE headquarters and
ask if the company has any records indicating what became of your
stock and your dividends. The headquarters number is (203)
373-2211. Ask for either the investor relations department or _
since you are a former employee _ the human resources department.
</P>
<P>
   Dividend Reinvestment
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have about 30 shares of PG&AMP;E stock and am participating in
the company's dividend reinvestment program. PG&AMP;E reinvests the
full amount of my cash dividends in the company's stock, but at the
end of the year it sends me a 1099 form indicating the amount of
dividends it paid me. Do I have to report that amount as income or
can I wait until I sell the stock and report it as a capital gain?
</P>
<P>
   A: Internal Revenue Service spokesman Larry Wright says you have
to report the dividends as ordinary income for the year in which
they are paid, even though you didn't actually lay hands on the
cash.
</P>
<P>
   When you sell the shares, the amount you paid through the
dividend-reinvestment program will constitute your cost basis in
calculating your capital gain.
</P>
<P>
   With most dividend-reinvestment programs, you get a detailed
year-end statement indicating how many shares you bought, when you
bought them and how much you paid. Save those statements, because
you will need them when you figure the tax on the shares you sell.
</P>
<P>
   The nice thing about these statements is that they enable you to
single out particular shares for sale _ assuming that you don't
sell them all at once. If you want to sell part of your holdings,
you should tell PG&AMP;E exactly which ones. You will want to sell
those on which you have the smallest capital gain _ or even a loss
_ to minimize your taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Before selling, you also should consider how long you have held
each of your shares. If you wait to sell until more than a year
after the purchase date, you can treat any profit on the sale as a
long-term capital gain, which will be taxed at a lower rate than a
short-term gain.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you are in the 28 percent federal tax bracket,
your short-term capital gains will be taxed at the 28 percent rate,
while your long-term gains will be taxed at only 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to moneybag(at
sign)sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
