<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNWIRED-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Firm Hopes `Dot Com' Helps IPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Deborah Solomon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Unwired Planet, the Redwood City company whose technology lets cell
phones access the Internet, is jumping in on the ``dot com'' trend.
</P>
<P>
   Just three weeks after filing to become a public company,
Unwired Planet plans to announce today that it will change its name
to Phone.com.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also adding a telecommunications heavy hitter to
its board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Reed Hundt, the former chairman of the Federal Communications
Commission, will join Unwired's board effective today.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the company's impending initial public offering,
officials are in a ``quiet period'' and could not comment on the
name change or Hundt's appointment.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which was founded in 1994, provides technology that
enables the delivery of Internet-based services to wireless
telephones.
</P>
<P>
   Using Unwired's Web-browsing technology, wireless carriers can
give customers the ability to get news alerts, check stock quotes
or find directions from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The information is displayed on a screen on the cell phone
instead of a computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   Unwired, which plans to go public in the next few months, will
also change its Web site address today to &LR;  www.phone.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Industry watchers familiar with Unwired said the company may
benefit from the dot com trend, in which dozens of Internet
companies have made millions _ at least on paper _ after going
public.
</P>
<P>
   However, several questioned whether the name Phone.Com is
actually a misnomer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they are trying to cash in on the cachet of the
Internet, but the name Unwired Planet spoke much more toward what
they did,'' said Albert Lin, who follows the wireless industry for
the Abernathy Group in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people will always associate them with phones.''
</P>
<P>
   Lin said the company's technology is universal enough that it
could be used in other devices, such as electronic organizers and
personal digital assistants.
</P>
<P>
   Hundt, who will join Unwired today, serves on the boards of
several Bay Area companies, including Alameda's Ascend
Communications and San Francisco's NorthPoint Communications.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
