A4952 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-ARRESTS-BUSH-COX     04-19 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-ARRESTS-BUSH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Protesters arrested at Governor's Mansion
 &HT;    By Ralph K.M. Haurwitz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A prudent measure intended to protect public
safety? Or an unconstitutional muzzling of free speech to suppress
criticism of Gov. George W. Bush's policy on air pollution?
</P>
<P>
   Those were the explanations offered by authorities and activists
after four protesters were arrested outside the Governor's Mansion
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a safety issue,'' said Tela Mange, a spokeswoman for
the Texas Department of Public Safety. ``If there are protesters on
the sidewalk, other people have to walk into the street to get
around them. They were asked at least twice to move out of the way,
and they refused and were arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   The protesters were handcuffed and taken to the Travis Central
Booking Facility on a charge of obstructing a passageway, a Class B
misdemeanor with a maximum penalty of six months in jail and a
$2,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of several environmental and consumer groups
participating in the protest said it appears that Bush, who is
considering a run for the White House, wants to stifle critics. The
groups _ including Public Citizen, Texans United, the Texas
Campaign for the Environment and the Sustainable Energy and
Economic Development Coalition, among others _ oppose a Bush-backed
bill that would encourage, but not require, older industrial plants
to reduce emissions.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Jacobson, executive director of the American Civil Liberties
Union, which is representing the arrested protesters, said he stood
on the sidewalk in front of the mansion for 35 to 40 minutes,
without holding a protest sign, and was not told to move. Only
people with signs were arrested, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The motive is so clearly to stop their speech,'' Jacobson
said. ``It is certainly sad that in Texas, in front of the
Governor's Mansion, you cannot exercise your free-speech rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Those arrested were identified as Richard C. Abraham, 49, of
Houston; Roger C. Baker Jr., 56, of Austin; Michael R. Covington,
51, of Houston; and Karen N. Sloan, 47, of Webster, a Houston
suburb.
</P>
<P>
   The activists knew they were risking arrest and even sent out a
news release in advance announcing the possibility. Abraham was
arrested outside the mansion last month at a protest.
</P>
<P>
   DPS officers had instructed the activists to confine their
protest to an area just across Colorado Street, which borders the
mansion. But the activists marched from that side of Colorado to
the mansion side and began walking along a sidewalk at the edge of
the grounds.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, protests took place on the sidewalk without
incident, the activists said. Tom Vinger, a DPS spokesman, said a
new policy was initiated by Lt. Mike Escalante, head of the
governor's protective detail. Escalante consulted with DPS lawyers
on March 12 and notified the governor's office of the new rules,
Vinger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was concerned about safety and decided to establish a
designated protest area,'' Vinger said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush defended the policy and the arrests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the rules are fair,'' he said. ``Everybody is given
the opportunity to come and express their pleasure or displeasure
with the governor. Everybody was given ample warning as to what
would happen if the rules were broken. As I understand it there
were several warnings given, and the person evidently wanted to
challenge the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   A bill supported by Bush and working its way through the
Legislature would allow older industrial plants to obtain air
pollution permits by complying with 10-year-old emission standards.
Participation in the program would be voluntary. Critics want the
Legislature to mandate compliance with current standards, which
would produce more cleanup but at higher costs.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph K.M. Haurwitz writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
