<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ HAS ITS JOB CUT OUT FOR IT IN SEARCH FOR NEW CEO 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By TRICIA SERJU-HARRIS 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Finding a replacement for Compaq Computer Corp.'s
ousted Chief Executive Eckhard Pfeiffer won't be easy, industry
analysts said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The talent pool of qualified replacements is too small,
Hewlett-Packard Co. is already on the hunt for a new CEO to take
Lewis Platt's place, and board members will have to please both
themselves and shareholders _ a difficult chore in any search,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any CEO search is difficult because you have various
constituencies _ both at the board of directors level and with
shareholders _ that make it a challenge,'' said Jane Howze,
managing director of Houston-based executive search firm The
Alexander Group.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation on Monday as to where Compaq would go for its
candidates ran the gamut of the nation's top technology executives.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg News quoted industry analysts &UR;  &LR; as saying several
executives would be good choices. Among them: Rick Belluzzo,
chairman and CEO of SGI; Eric Schmidt, chairman and CEO of Novell;
Robert Pittman, president and chief operating officer of America
Online; and Sam Palmisano or John Thompson, senior vice presidents
of International Business Machines Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Until a successor is named, Compaq chairman and co-founder Ben
Rosen will run the company with vice chairmen Frank Doyle and
Robert Enloe until a new CEO is found.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq must also find a replacement for Earl Mason, its chief
financial officer, who resigned Saturday to become president and
chief executive of Alliant Foodservice, a fast-growing
Chicago-based food service distributor.
</P>
<P>
   He had been in discussions with the firm since January and
notified the Compaq board of his intentions to leave in March.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq Treasurer Ben Wells will be acting CFO.
</P>
<P>
   Mason didn't want to discuss whether Compaq would have kept him
as CFO if he hadn't resigned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. You'd have to ask Compaq,'' he said. ``I left on
very good terms with all of them. Ben and I are very good
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Howze expects it will take several months for Compaq to find a
replacement for Mason and Pfeiffer, who joined the company in 1983.
The search is being led by the search firm Heidrick &AMP; Struggles.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates must have a breadth of capability and would probably
be a CEO or have CEO potential, Rosen said during a conference call
Monday morning with analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The candidate should have a minimum comfort level with
technology,'' Rosen said. ``It requires someone in general who can
manage an extremely complex multinational company.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis Mazzucchelli, a senior vice president at Gerard Klauer
Mattison, was not excited about the idea of a board running the PC
maker.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market has a rational perspective on this,'' he said. ``In
my view, the stock shouldn't do anything until we get a better
sense of where they're going.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Dzialo, director of research at Olde Discount Corp. in
Detroit, said a three-member executive panel is acceptable for the
short term.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compaq needs to have a person at the helm who has a good
working rapport with the management team and with the board of
directors,'' Dzialo said. ``The company has a lot of potential, but
they need help with the execution.''
</P>
<P>
   The departures of Pfeiffer and Mason came nine days after the
company warned first-quarter profits would be less than half what
analysts had expected.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq fell 7/8 to 22 3/4 in trading of 38.6 million shares,
making it the second-most active U.S. stock. The stock rose as much
as 4.2 percent earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   That's a far cry from last week's 24 percent tumble. Compaq
shares have lost more than half their value since reaching a record
high of 49 1/4 on Jan. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq has struggled for much of the past year to become more
competitive with companies like Dell Computer Corp., the No. 1
direct PC seller. At the same time, it is trying to meld with the
services and sophisticated computers gained from its $9 billion
purchase of Digital Equipment Corp.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
