<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
(HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASDAQ PLUMMETS 5.6 PERCENT AS INVESTORS SHIFT FOCUS
</P>
<P>
   In a stunning about-face, investors piled out of technology
stocks and other market darlings, pummeling the very shares that
propelled the broad market averages to records last week. The
Nasdaq composite index, home to many of the nation's technology
companies, fell 138.43 points, or 5.57 percent, to 2,345.61. That
was its second-biggest point fall and seventh largest in percentage
terms.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 53.36 points, or
five-tenths of a percent, to 10,440.53, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index fell 29.52 points, or 2.24 percent, to 1,289.48.
Volume on the New York Stock Exchange exceeded 1.2 billion shares,
the second-heaviest trading day in exchange history.
</P>
<P>
   Stock markets from Seoul to Singapore soared, extending a rally
that many analysts say is proof that foreign investors are
returning in large numbers to the recession-ravaged economies of
Asia. Market Place.
</P>
<P>
   PHONE GIANTS EXPECTED TO MERGE
</P>
<P>
   Telecom Italia and Deutsche Telekom, two formerly state-owned
telephone giants of Europe, are expected to announce an agreement
as early as today to merge in a deal valued at about $95.4 billion,
creating the world's largest telecommunications company.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. AND CHINA PREPARE FOR TALKS
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's negotiators leave for Beijing Tuesday to try
to clinch a sweeping market-opening deal with China. But some of
the most intensive talks are going to take place with a skeptical
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The United States received the World Trade Organization's formal
approval to impose $191.4 million in punitive tariffs on European
goods in a protracted fight over European banana imports. But the
effective date of the sanctions was still in dispute.
</P>
<P>
   APPLE JOINS INTERNET-AUDIO FRAY
</P>
<P>
   In a challenge to Microsoft and Real Networks, Apple Computer
introduced a new version of its Quicktime multimedia software
designed to permit computer users to receive video and audio
programming over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL RETURNING TO BOND MARKET
</P>
<P>
   When Brazil devalued its currency in January, the nation was
faced with rising inflation, soaring interest rates, the threat of
default and a recession; most foreign investors crossed Brazil off
their dance cards. Three months later, Brazil is offering $1
billion in five-year notes for sale this week. The remarkable
turnaround is a reminder of how fast things can change in volatile
emerging markets. The planned sale is also a tribute to the skill
of the new head of Brazil's central bank, Arminio Fraga.
</P>
<P>
   ELI LILLY PROFIT INCREASES 12 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Eli Lilly said that its first-quarter profit rose more than 12
percent even as sales fell for its biggest drug, the antidepressant
Prozac.
</P>
<P>
   Case, the maker of farm equipment, said that it had a
first-quarter loss as slumping crop prices forced farmers to curb
spending on tractors and machinery.
</P>
<P>
   CNN AND ARNETT REACH SETTLEMENT
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of steadfastly refusing to comment on the status of
Peter Arnett, its onetime leading foreign correspondent, the Cable
News Network said that it had reached a financial settlement with
Arnett that would end his 18-year career at CNN. No specific terms
of the deal were disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   IMPLANT REPORT STAYS IN COURT
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge refused to dismiss a report by an expert panel
that found no evidence that breast implants cause disease, despite
complaints that a member received money from an implant maker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
