<SLUG> BC-HKN-ROENICK-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIDELINED ROENICK SEES A DIFFERENT COYOTE TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. - He is sitting near his pool, hand
immobilized by a cast, eyes floating from a breakfast of
painkillers, face inflated from surgery, his jigsaw jaw fused in
three places.
</P>
<P>
   If you're wondering how Jeremy Roenick is doing, well, you try
waking up every morning with a mouthful of screaming teeth. Other
than that, he feels great.
</P>
<P>
   Not about himself. About a hockey team that must cross the
bridge without him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to beat St. Louis, no question,'' Roenick
said. ``And I'm looking forward to watching it.''
</P>
<P>
   Intuition? Or wishful thinking?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just see a different look in their faces,'' he said. ``A
different mood. Keith (Tkachuk) is really prepared. I think he
wants to bring this team to a new level, and he's just the guy who
can do it. I have all the confidence in the world that they're
going to have a great playoff.''
</P>
<P>
   Words. You could freeze Roenick's vocal chords and they'd still
find a way out, full of swagger, destined for somebody's bulletin
board.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the door opens to another postseason. For the
Coyotes, the playoffs are like the kind of relative who stays a few
days, leaves the place a mess and takes off for someone else's
house. They are trying to break a long-standing jinx, trying to win
a series with long-term ramifications. And they must do so without
their leading scorer, their top-line center, their prime-time
player.
</P>
<P>
   You are tempted to smirk at Roenick's confidence, eager to
recall his gold-medal guarantee at the 1998 Olympic Games in
Nagano. That prediction went up in flames, and when someone reached
for the fire extinguisher, it was too late. Someone else had
already thrown it out of the dormitory window. &QL; 
Fed up with losing &QL; 
But this might be a little different. What Roenick senses could be
the natural evolution of a team weaned on first-round exits. A team
so sick of losing that it's not going to happen again, regardless
of injuries, excuses and opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``As athletes, a lot of times we learn the hard way,'' Roenick
said. ``But there's a whole different feeling about this team.
Shoney (head coach Jim Schoenfeld) has done a great job at staying
in tune with the pulse of the team. Keith has matured tremendously
as a leader. He knows that everyone in that dressing room wants the
same thing _ to win a Stanley Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   And for those who still cling to notions of a feud between the
two stars, Tkachuk was one of the first to call Roenick when he
returned from the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an arrogant (mild expletive). So am I, and so are a lot
of hockey players,'' Roenick said. ``But he does care. A lot of
people say he just cares about himself. But Keith cares a lot about
this hockey team, and he does want to win. And I'm telling you,
he's got that look in his eye. The look where you know he wants to
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Proof: When Tkachuk was asked about overcoming Roenick's injury,
he barked out the following response: ``No excuses. This is where
it starts. I don't care if you have 10 guys out of the lineup, you
have to find a way to win.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a shame this kind of determination is saddled by injury,
especially when the another first-round flop could mean significant
changes in the organization. If the Coyotes fall to the Blues, the
head coach is gone. Roenick and a few others could be traded. The
chemistry might be altered. And pending the outcome of the Los
Arcos project, payroll might be slashed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot depends on that new building,'' Roenick said. &QL; 
`A job to do' &QL; 
For now, all of that is out of Roenick's control. He can't play
hockey without risk of shattering his face. He can't chew for five
weeks. Because of his injured hand, he can't even use the
world-class putting green over in the corner of his yard. But one
thing is certain: Although his wife is concerned over his battered
body, Roenick will not retire any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wants me to be healthy, wants me to be able to play with
my kids,'' he said. ``But she would never ask me to retire from the
game. She knows I want to win a Stanley Cup. She knows that's my
dream, to carry that Cup. She would never take that away from me.''
</P>
<P>
   But the chase only gets tougher. In 1992, Roenick reached the
Stanley Cup Finals with the Blackhawks. They lost in a sweep. Since
then, he has missed two postseasons due to injury _ both courtesy
of Dallas' Derian Hatcher _ and found success wildly fleeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we lost in the Finals to Pittsburgh, I said, `It's OK.
I'll be back here some day,' '' Roenick said. ``I haven't had a
sniff since.''
</P>
<P>
   Now this. Ironic for a guy who lives next door to owner Richard
Burke, but Roenick has never felt so removed. He is powerless,
aching to be needed, lusting to be part of the quest. But as they
get ready to hoist the curtain and get on with a defining
postseason in the life of the Phoenix Coyotes, Roenick has one last
message to his teammates:
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget about me,'' he said. ``That would be perfect. Don't
think about me for one moment. The emphasis has to be on Keith
Tkachuk, Rick Tocchet, Nikolai Khabibulin. They're the ones who
have to do this. I'm not part of it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm behind them 100 percent, but this has to be about the
Phoenix Coyotes. Not about Jeremy Roenick's injury. This is the
playoffs, and they have a job to do.'' &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
