<HEADER>
A4969 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-BOSTON-MARATHON-A     04-19 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-BOSTON-MARATHON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A SINGLE FOR CHEBET AND A TRIPLE FOR ROBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Joseph Chebet of Kenya enjoyed his trips to the United
States, even if he was always second best. He ran second in the
1997 New York City Marathon, second in last year's Boston Marathon
and second in last year's New York City Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to be second,'' he said Monday, and he is second
no more. Monday afternoon, in the 103th annual Boston Marathon, the
28-year-old Chebet took the lead with four miles to go and won by
200 yards over Silvio Guerra of Ecuador. Chebet ran the 26 miles
385 yards from suburban Hopkinton to the Back Bay section of Boston
in 2 hours 9 minutes 52 seconds, not quite pedestrian time, but not
exceptional either.
</P>
<P>
   While Chebet was piling up those second places, Fatuma Roba was
winning. The 27-year-old Ethiopian won the 1996 Olympic marathon in
Atlanta and the 1997 and 1998 races here. Monday, she made it three
consecutive Boston victories, a feat achieved officially only by
Uta Pippig of Germany from 1994 through 1996.
</P>
<P>
   For half the women's race, Sun Yingjie of China, who at age 20
was running her fifth marathon, set a suicidal pace close to that
of the men's leaders. But when Roba stepped up her pace, she passed
the fading Sun, shook off Catherine Ndereba of Kenya and won
comfortably.
</P>
<P>
   Roba finished 700 yards ahead of Franziska Rochat-Moser of
Switzerland in 2:23:25, the 15th fastest time in history. She
dismissed that, saying, ``I was expecting a better time _ 2:21 or
2:22.''
</P>
<P>
   The race sponsors, led by John Hancock, put up $525,000 in prize
money. Chebet and Roba collected $80,000 each. In addition, Roba
received an appearance fee of perhaps $80,000 and Chebet a lesser
amount.
</P>
<P>
   This was Patriots Day, a Massachusetts holiday that commemorates
the skirmishes in suburban Lexington and Concord that touched off
the Revolutionary War. There were 12,797 men and women running in
this, the world's oldest and most storied marathon. With the
starting-time temperature at 60 degrees and a westerly breeze to
the runners' backs, it was a nice day for a marathon.
</P>
<P>
   A Kenyan man won for the ninth year in a row. Nine Kenyan men
ran, and the best of them finished first, fifth, sixth, 10th, 12th
and 15th, their weakest performance in years. Moses Tanui, the
Kenyan who won the last two years and three of the last four, was
running eighth when he dropped out after 22 miles.
</P>
<P>
   For the first half of the men's race, no one was brave or
foolhardy enough to force the pace. After 16 miles, Guerra had
enough of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was feeling great and strong,'' he said. ``I'm still trying
to learn how to run a marathon. I go out to try and win the race,
but with a marathon you never know. I tried to win it, and to win a
race you have to take risks.''
</P>
<P>
   Guerra took the lead and stepped up the pace, and in Newton, on
the first of four hills that end with Heartbreak Hill, he ran an
uphill mile in 4 minutes 50 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   That shook off many contenders. It also left Guerra with big
foot blisters that forced him to back off a bit. Chebet, always
close, passed Guerra after 22 miles, and Chebet, although he tired
noticeably toward the finish, was never threatened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was worried about Guerra,'' Chebet said. ``After I passed
him, I was worried about someone else catching me, so I pushed very
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the women's race, Roba had every reason to worry. Sun,
the Chinese upstart, was running either the fastest race in history
or one of the most indiscreet.
</P>
<P>
   With a stiff, upright stride, arms hardly bent, she looked as if
she were trying to run through a bad case of arthritis. But she was
running comfortably alongside John Campbell of New Zealand,
history's fastest over-40 male runner, and after three miles she
was 300 yards ahead of Roba.
</P>
<P>
   Roba treated the situation as a distraction rather than a
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first,'' she said, ``I didn't realize that there was
somebody out in front of me. When I did, I picked up my pace
some.''
</P>
<P>
   Sun drifted back and finished 11th in 2:37:11. She left Roba to
battle it out with Ndereba, who dominated the American road-race
circuit last year.
</P>
<P>
   Kenyan women won major marathons Sunday in London and Rotterdam,
but there would be no weekend trifecta. For four miles, Roba and
Ndereba ran together. When Roba decided to take off after 17 miles,
they bumped slightly and muttered apologies. Then Roba left, and
Ndereba retreated to sixth place in 2:28:27.
</P>
<P>
   There were cheers for Roba all along the course from the large
Ethiopian community here. After 20 miles, two spectators waving an
Ethiopian flag started running behind her. They handed her a
headband in the green, yellow and red of the Ethiopian flag. She
put it on her wrist and then on her head.
</P>
<P>
   She was struggling slightly at the end and Rochat-Moser was
closing strongly, but too far back. Still, there was redemption of
sorts for Rochat-Moser. She has struggled since she won the New
York City Marathon in 1997, partly because she spends so much time
running her Michelin three-star restaurant, Girardet, in Crissier,
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   ``My aim was to run my personal record,'' she said. And she did,
finishing in 2:25:51.
</P>
<P>
   For Roba and Chebet, there was big prize money and glory. For
Guerra, second in the men's race, there was less prize money
($40,000), less glory and a lesson for someone who started running
marathons only two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no regrets,'' he said. ``During a race, you do not have
too much time to think, so whenever you feel good you have to go
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Would he do anything differently?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he said. ``I would have won the race.''
</P>
<P>
   FINISHING KICKS
</P>
<P>
   The leading American finishers were 38-year-old Lynn Jennings of
Newmarket, N.H., 12th among the women in 2:38:37, and 32-year-old
Joe LeMay of Danbury, Conn., 13th among the men in 2:16:11. This
was the first official marathon for the 38-year-old Jennings, one
of the world's leading distance runners.
</P>
<P>
   At 51, Bill Rodgers, a four-time Boston and four-time New York
winner, was running his first serious marathon in seven years. He
dropped out atop Heartbreak Hill, almost 21 miles into the race,
because of dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   The wheelchair winners were Franz Neitlispach of Switzerland
(1:21:36) and Louise Sauvage of Australia (1:42:23), each for the
third consecutive year. For the second year in a row, Jean Driscoll
of Champaign, Ill., finished second in the same time as Sauvage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 2136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
