r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-PLAYOFFS-MIND-GAM     04-19 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PLAYOFFS-MIND-GAMES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANLEY CUP PLAYOFFS CAN BE BEST-OF-SEVEN MIND GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They stand behind the benches in fine suits, regally overlooking
the mayhem occurring before them, acting as if they are above it
all.
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe it. Come playoff time, NHL head coaches are
nothing more than well-dressed Eddie Haskells, willing to try
anything to give their teams an edge in pursuit of the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   They will have players sport fake casts and arrange for
opponents to gag on paint fumes before a game. They even have been
known to throw change on the ice and then, with the feigned
innocence of a professional wrestler who has just placed brass
knuckles back in his trunks, blame it on unruly fans.
</P>
<P>
   Practically anything goes in the NHL playoffs, and it's all
passed off under the title of gamesmanship, a time-honored
tradition that helps make hockey's playoffs more intriguing than
any other professional sport's.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are trying to find that one little edge, someplace,
somewhere,'' said Mike Keenan, a former NHL coach who has coached
in four Stanley Cup finals, winning once. ``Sometimes, it takes on
its own drama and that's what makes it fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Emotion plays a bigger role in hockey than perhaps any other
sport. The game is so fast that strategy can be quickly rendered
useless, leaving emotion and effort as the only constants.
Preparing a team mentally during a long series can be as important
as any game-planning a coach does.
</P>
<P>
   That's why you will see coaches go to odd lengths in attempts to
inspire their teams, relieve the pressure on their players,
influence officials and rattle opponents.
</P>
<P>
   That's what makes the NHL playoffs, which begin Wednesday, not
only about delivering hits, but about pitching fits. It's a time
for stingy goaltending and creative mindbending.
</P>
<P>
   The current master of mental gymnastics is Detroit Coach Scotty
Bowman, who has coached eight Stanley Cup champions, including the
Red Wings, who have won two straight.
</P>
<P>
   When St. Louis, the Coyotes' first-round opponent beginning
Thursday, played Detroit in the playoffs in 1996 and 1997, the
Blues were greeted by a freshly painted locker room in Joe Louis
Arena. The fumes were overwhelming even after the Blues tried to
clear the air by running floor fans around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably coincidental but Detroit went on to win each
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``That room has had eight coats of paint the last two years,''
St. Louis defenseman Marc Bergevin told reporters last year. ``It
looks nice, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Few hockey coaches can match Keenan's love of gamesmanship. His
plans usually were as orchestrated as a symphony and accompanied by
media anxious for an interesting angle.
</P>
<P>
   There is an art to gamesmanship, said Keenan, fired this year by
Vancouver and now living in Florida. The best practitioners are
those who are in tune with their surroundings and intuitively know
what's needed in different situations.
</P>
<P>
   It's Zen mixed with a dash of used car salesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be able to read the situation, read the team, read
the needs and know what might be sellable with officials, the
league and . . .the fans,'' Keenan said.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in 1992 Keenan's team, the Chicago Blackhawks,
were playing Pittsburgh in the Stanley Cup finals. One of Keenan's
best players, Jeremy Roenick, now with the Coyotes, was nursing a
sprained thumb, and Keenan was concerned the Penguins might go
after Roenick's injury.
</P>
<P>
   So rather than hide Roenick's wounded digit, Keenan made the
thumb a central part of the finals. He had Roenick show up to
practice in a cast. Roenick, normally friendly to the media, then
declined to answer questions about it.
</P>
<P>
   Keenan accused the Penguins of going after Roenick's thumb,
although he produced no videotape to prove it. But for a few days,
Roenick's thumb stood as tall in Chicago as the Sears Tower.
</P>
<P>
   The Blackhawks lost the series, 4-0, but not because Pittsburgh
went after Roenick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly drew it to the attention of the officials,''
Keenan said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, the mind games become laughable as coaches try
anything to gain an edge. Players are accustomed to skating on bad
ice in practice sessions on the road, or having a Zamboni blocking
the entrance to the rink. The fact that grown, well-paid men dream
up these schemes is amusing to some.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called overthinking,'' said Charlie Simmer, a former NHL
player and color broadcaster for the Coyotes. ``There are only so
many ways you can cut a board. Some just do it better than
others.''
</P>
<P>
   The Valley received its first taste of NHL gamesmanship two
years ago in the Coyotes' first season here, when they met the
Mighty Ducks of Anaheim in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Ducks Coach Ron Wilson, unhappy with the way his star, Paul
Kariya, was being slapped around by Phoenix, warned the Coyotes
that Roenick and Keith Tkachuk had better have their helmets on
tight.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson wasn't serious about going after the Coyotes' stars. He
just wanted the referees to protect Kariya as much as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember the series changing any,'' said Bobby Smith,
the Coyotes general manager, whose team ended up losing in seven
games. ``But Tkachuk and Roenick spent two days answering questions
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   One purpose of gamesmanship is to reach the referees through the
media, thus influencing a series.
</P>
<P>
   Smith doesn't think referees pay attention to what's written or
broadcast but Keenan disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (referees) tell you they don't read anything, but they
read everything,'' Keenan said. ``And if they don't read, someone
tells them about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The media are often used as tools, and coaches like Keenan and
Bowman know their audiences. In a seven-game series, reporters are
eager for new and different angles. Keenan, Bowman and others have
masterfully provided them, lobbying referees and deflecting
attention and pressure from their teams in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus of the media is so much more intense as you go from
16 teams to eight teams to four teams,'' Smith said. ``It can be
used . . . to get a distraction. If you want to take the focus off
your goaltender for a couple days, you create something.''
</P>
<P>
   When Keenan was with the Blues in '96, he made a big deal out of
the size of the visiting bench area in Detroit's Joe Louis Arena.
Too small, Keenan said. Visiting teams didn't have enough room for
line changes.
</P>
<P>
   Keenan's charges were proven correct and changes were made. But
his main objective was not in securing larger bench accommodations.
It was deflecting attention from goalie Jon Casey, who was playing
in place of an injured Grant Fuhr.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about hockey gamesmanship is that the masters of
it admit it, as least after the statute of limitations has expired.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, St. Louis Coach Jacques Demers twice dropped pennies on
the ice to delay play in a playoff game against the Minnesota North
Stars. The joke was that he chose pennies because, as the league's
lowest paid coach, he couldn't afford more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had killed four penalties in a row and I did it to rest our
guys,'' he said a year later. ``I'll never do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds a little like Dennis the Menace promising to stay
out of Mr. Wilson's flower bed, hockey people understand. At
playoff time, almost everything said and done comes with an implied
wink.
</P>
<P>
   The purists hope that it stays that way, that television,
corporate sponsors and the league office don't pour antiseptic over
the game and try to sanitize it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have some bacteria somewhere,'' Keenan said.
``It's the last frontier, isn't it?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
