</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-MARATHON-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD TO WIN A MARATHON ON THE COUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - I woke up Monday morning and turned on my TV. A guy on
ESPN2 said ``And ``off'' they go!''
</P>
<P>
   I read Dear Abby. Had breakfast. Shaved. Showered. Dressed.
Drove to work.
</P>
<P>
   When I arrived at the office, the TV announcer was interviewing
a small man wearing a medal that weighed more than he does.
</P>
<P>
   His gold laurel wreath brought to mind Caesar in ``The Ten''
``Commandments''.``''
</P>
<P>
   It was over.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Chebet already had won the Boston Marathon. The man ran
26.2 miles in 2 hours, 9 minutes and 52 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   When he broke the tape, he wasn't even breathing hard.
</P>
<P>
   They just keep going and going . . . &QL; 
Marathon runners are put on this earth for one reason. To make the
rest of us feel inferior and guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Human beings who run 26 miles in the time one can play nine
holes in a cart are almost as amazing as those bicyclists in the
Tour de France. The race starts in June. As the contestants depart,
the French people blow kisses and shower them with crepes. Here in
the States, we shrug and forget about them.
</P>
<P>
   Time passes.
</P>
<P>
   We celebrate the Fourth of July. Take family vacations. When we
return home two weeks later, tanned and rested, these guys are
still at it, hunched over their handlebars, legs churning
furiously, pedaling up the Alps.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know what the TV ratings were for the Boston Marathon.
Probably not good.
</P>
<P>
   The race began at 9 a.m. Arizona time and went head-to-head with
Sally Jessy Raphael. Monday's show: unfaithful men are confronted
with proof.
</P>
<P>
   A good reason to ``start'' running _ and not stop.
</P>
<P>
   There's not much to watch, really. A river of humanity flows
away from the starting line. Spectators lining the streets cheer
and wave. Soon the contenders _ who measure .00013 percent body fat
_ separate themselves from the pack. They run uphill. Downhill.
Heartbreak Hill doesn't faze them.
</P>
<P>
   Eyes straight ahead.
</P>
<P>
   One foot in front of the other.
</P>
<P>
   Determined.
</P>
<P>
   Relentless.
</P>
<P>
   Marathon runners are like Buck Showalter. Their expression never
changes.
</P>
<P>
   How can they endure? Do they run on batteries? Or do you wind
them up, like a toy with a key?
</P>
<P>
   To win the Boston Marathon, the first thing you do is move to
Kenya. Actually, that's the second thing. The first thing is to
change your diet. No more pizza and cheesecake. It's bird seed from
now on.
</P>
<P>
   Then you move to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   Chebet is a Kenyan. A Kenya runner has won the last nine Boston
Marathons. Opinion is divided over why athletes from that land now
dominate long-distance running. Is it genetics? Altitude? Training
techniques? Lifestyle?
</P>
<P>
   The book ``Kenyan Running'' alludes to the ``romantic myth'' of
a simple essential Africa in which young children run endlessly
across the plains to school.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Kenyans are just more dedicated. Perhaps they win because
they work harder. That's usually how it goes in life.
</P>
<P>
   Life, liberty, pursuit of laziness &QL; 
Americans once dominated the Boston Marathon. But an American male
hasn't won since 1983, an American woman since '85.
</P>
<P>
   I was hoping Bill Rodgers might win again until I read he is 50
years old.
</P>
<P>
   Although many Americans exercise, even more don't, choosing
instead to lie on the couch and watch TV or read paperbacks such as
the one called ``The Non-Runner's Book,'' advertised as a manual of
tips for the listless majority and advice for the preferably prone.
</P>
<P>
   The book suggests that non-running can be enjoyed by anyone, at
any time. It points out that once a person starts to not run it is
hard to stop.
</P>
<P>
   I have my own theory why Americans don't win the Boston Marathon
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   In this country most of us ask ourselves, ``Why run when I can
ride?''
</P>
<P>
   That's why NASCAR is so popular. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at (602) 444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
