<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER DOBSON QB LEIGH SIGNS AS FREE AGENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quarterback  &UR; Graham Leigh is glad there is film of his junior
season at New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put on the games, and he's throwing the ball on rhythm,''
Cardinals scout  &UR; Cole Proctor said of the Mesa Dobson High School
product. ``He's moving the football team. He was an exciting
quarterback making plays on his own.''
</P>
<P>
   Leigh, who agreed to terms on a rookie free-agent deal with the
Cardinals on Monday, was the Western Athletic Conference Mountain
Division Offensive Player of the Year in 1997. He threw for 2,318
yards and 24 touchdowns and eas intercepted only eight times. He
also rushed for 528 yards.
</P>
<P>
   But following the season, Lobos Coach  &UR; Dennis Franchione left
for Texas Christian University and was replaced by  &UR; Rocky
Long. &UR; Leigh had a poor senior year and was intercepted 17 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The change in coaching staff really hurt him,'' said Proctor,
the Cardinals' West Coast scout. ``In 1997, it was a completely
different picture. He has a great opportunity to redeem himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Leigh, who grew up in Chandler, three miles from the team's
Tempe training facility, will compete with seventh-round draft pick
 &UR; Chris
 &UR; Greisen for the No. 3 quarterback job.
</P>
<P>
   He chose the Cardinals over the San Francisco 49ers, the Oakland
Raiders and the Cleveland Browns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where else could he go and he have a 50 percent chance of
making the team?'' Cardinals offensive coordinator  &UR; Marc Trestman
said.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of last year, Leigh was projected as a 1999
third-round draft pick. A year later, he wasn't selected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through a lot (Sunday), having to sit through the whole
draft,'' said Leigh, who will graduate with an engineering degree
in May. ``I know I ranked a lot higher after my junior year. My
senior year, hurt me a lot _ new coaches, new system, a really
young team. I'm confident I'm the quarterback people saw in the '97
film.'' &QL; 
Recent additions
</P>
<P>
   Leigh was the only rookie free agent signing confirmed by the
Cardinals, with the rest of the list announced today.
</P>
<P>
   Three other rookie free agents apparently have agreed to terms _
offensive linemen  &UR; Kevin Swillis of California and  &UR; John Feugill of
Maryland and punter  &UR; Jeff Roberts of Fresno State.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, 6-foot-3, 207 pounds, will compete with veteran  &UR; Scott
Player for the punting job. &QL; 
Good humor guys
</P>
<P>
   First-round draft picks  &UR; David Boston, wide receiver from Ohio
State, and  &UR; L.J. Shelton, offensive tackle from Eastern Michigan,
and fifth-round pick  &UR; Yusuf Scott, offensive guard from Arizona,
met the Valley's media on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Boston couldn't stop laughing at the one-liners from Shelton and
Scott, who offered to bring his homemade barbecue sauce to the
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the best barbecue sauce in town,'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton was asked about the possibility of replacing seven-time
Pro Bowler  &UR; Lomas Brown at left offensive tackle. ``More than I've
heard about replacing Lomas, I've heard about protecting our
big-money quarterback,'' Shelton said of starter  &UR; Jake Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, who weighs 320 pounds, also had Plummer on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to work out a deal because my running back in Arizona,
 &UR; Trung Canidate, took me out to eat dinner after each game,'' Scott
said. ``So, Jake will have to take me out, and I'll take care of
him, too.'' &QL; 
On the mend
</P>
<P>
   Starting running back  &UR; Adrian Murrell likely will not
participate in drills at next week's three-day minicamp after
undergoing arthroscopic surgery on his left knee two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Murrell, who suffered a slight tear of his meniscus ligament, is
expected to be at full strength for training camp in July. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
