<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-KIDD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDD MAKING NAME AS SHOOTING STAR  
 DEDICATION, CONFIDENCE ARE DIFFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ When Jason Kidd entered the NBA as a 21-year-old rookie
in 1994, it was apparent that only one thing would determine
whether Kidd became a great player or just another good one.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd shot just 38.5 percent that first season with the Dallas
Mavericks, yet he still shared the NBA's Rookie of the Year award
with Detroit's Grant Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The book on Kidd was that if he could improve enough as a
shooter to hit 45 percent of his shots, he would be an unstoppable
force with his ball-handling, strength, vision and passing skills.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd admits he wasn't dedicated enough early in his career to
improve his shooting. That is one of the reasons the Mavericks
traded Kidd to Phoenix the day after Christmas in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   There were those in the Dallas franchise who didn't believe Kidd
would develop the ability to shoot, and thus shouldn't be the
centerpiece of a franchise.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks, who play host to the Suns tonight, have lived to
regret that decision. The Suns have lost only one game to the
Mavericks since the trade. And Kidd has improved his shooting each
season he has been in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed to build a base to work from, and I've done that
since I came here (to the Suns),'' Kidd said. ``I think it just
comes from not being satisfied, and building some confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to be a guy, when my career is over, who was
considered a good player that could have been a great player if I
could shoot it better,'' Kidd said.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd is shooting the ball this season better than he has at
anytime in his career _ 44 percent going into tonight's game. He
set a goal of shooting 45 percent this season, 35 percent from
three-point range and 82 percent from the free throw line.
</P>
<P>
   Those were ambitious marks considering Kidd's 41.3 percent last
season was a career best, and that his career mark from three-point
range was 32.1 and from the free-throw line was 71.4.
</P>
<P>
   But Kidd has come close. He's ahead of the three-point goal,
hitting 39.1 percent, and is making 76.2 percent of his free
throws.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd was named the NBA's Player of the Week on Monday for
averaging 22.8 points, 10.5 assists and 5.0 rebounds last week.
It's the first time this season Kidd has won the honor, the fifth
time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason is learning the game all the time,'' Suns Coach Danny
Ainge said. ``I think he's a lot better player this season than
he's ever been, and one of the areas he has improved the most is in
his shooting. He's more aggressive in looking for his shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a lot less hesitation than I've seen in the past. Jason
is about winning, and he knows his shooting is an important part of
uf winning.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean Kidd has become selfish. In fact, he leads the
NBA in assists with 10.8 a game.
</P>
<P>
   And he said he'll probably never have the no-conscience approach
of pure shooters. But for the first time in his career, Kidd sees
opponents respecting his shot. Throughout his previous four NBA
years, virtually every team would defend Kidd on pick-and-roll
players by having his defender slide below the pick.
</P>
<P>
   It is conceding an open jump shot. But now many teams are coming
over the pick to defend Kidd, a sign that he can't be counted on to
miss. And that creates opportunities for others from the
pick-and-roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can continue to knock down shots, it makes everyone else
get easier shots,'' Kidd said.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd has taken his shooting to a new level in April, making 56.4
percent of his shots and 16 of 32 three-pointers. It's not a
coincidence that the Suns are having their best month as a team
with a 7-3 mark in April.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd credits his wife, Joumana, for encouraging him to work on
his marksmanship, and assistant coach Frank Johnson and strength
coach Robin Pound, who work with him daily.
</P>
<P>
   He's even starting to make a little pocket change occasionally
in shooting games with his teammates and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never used to get in those games when I was in my first
couple of years in the league,'' he said. ``I usually just went
home after practice. Now I try to get in games with our better
shooters. You don't want to be considered one of your team's best
players if you can't even win any of the shooting games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to win them all, but I can win two or three
times a week. That's a lot better than in the past.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
