<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-715&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT TO DECIDE ON SELF-REPRESENTATION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (nk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court agreed Monday to decide whether
people convicted of crimes have a constitutional right to represent
themselves on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   A California inmate _ representing himself _ persuaded the court
to hear the case. The justices will decide whether to extend to
appeals the right of self-representation the court established for
criminal trials nearly 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In Faretta vs. California, in 1975, the court ruled that the
right to dispense with a lawyer and defend oneself at trial was an
inherent part of the Sixth Amendment right to present a legal
defense in a criminal case.
</P>
<P>
   While that amendment is best known for guaranteeing ``the
assistance of counsel,'' the court emphasized in the 1975 ruling
that a lawyer ``shall be an aid to a willing defendant _ not an
organ of the state interposed between an unwilling defendant and
his right to defend himself personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that most defendants are not likely to do as well
in court as most lawyers, the court said then, ``Personal liberties
are not rooted in the law of averages.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, there has been disagreement among state and lower
federal courts over whether the principle of self-representation
also applies to appeals. The case the justices accepted Monday is
both an unlikely vehicle for a Supreme Court ruling and at the same
time a telling example of the dilemma for the legal system posed by
a defendant whose desire to tell his own story is not matched by
his legal training or acumen.
</P>
<P>
   Inexpertly typed in all capital letters, the petition was filed
by Salvador Martinez, a California man who was convicted of
embezzlement after representing himself at trial last year.
Applying longstanding state precedents, the California appellate
courts refused to let Martinez represent himself in his appeal.
</P>
<P>
   A state agency in California provides appellate lawyers for
indigent defendants and requires the lawyers to meet specific
standards in preparing their cases. Martinez did not explain to the
justices why he had not chosen to accept the state's help. In fact,
he offered no legal argument at all, simply listing the lower court
rulings that demonstrated the existence of conflicting judicial
views.
</P>
<P>
   His success in getting the justices' attention was nonetheless
notable; fewer than 2 percent of all cases filed at the court are
ever granted. But having brought his case this far, Martinez may be
disappointed to learn that he will not be able to argue it himself
when the court hears it next fall; he is not a member of the
Supreme Court's bar, and the justices, following their normal
practice, will appoint someone who is.
</P>
<P>
   The answer to the question presented by the case, Martinez vs.
California, No. 98-7809, is not obvious because appeals stand on a
very different footing than trials. While the right to a trial is
guaranteed, the court has long made it clear that there is no
constitutional right to an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   All states do provide for appeals, and the court ruled in 1963
that when they do so, they must provide lawyers for indigent
defendants so as not to make the appeal a ``meaningless ritual.''
Nonetheless, a defendant does not necessarily have the right to be
in the courtroom during an appellate argument, while a defendant's
presence at trial is guaranteed by the Sixth Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   In opposing Martinez's appeal, California Attorney General Bill
Lockyer told the court that nothing in the Constitution's text
guaranteed the right to self-representation on appeal and that
``there is simply no good reason to alter years of fundamental
understanding'' by creating such a right.
</P>
<P>
   Lockyer said defendants who represent themselves on appeal could
be expected to place new burdens on the legal system, requiring
judges and prosecutors to decipher poorly written material.
</P>
<P>
   The court may find that argument to be a weighty one. Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist, the only current justice who was on
the court when the Faretta decision established the right to
self-representation at trial, was one of three dissenters from that
decision. He joined a dissent by Warren E. Burger, then the chief
justice, who objected that the ruling ``can only add to the
problems of an already malfunctioning criminal justice system.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   These were among the other developments at the court Monday:
</P>
<P>
   Obscene e-mail
</P>
<P>
   Without comment, the court upheld a ruling by a special
three-judge federal District Court here last year that a federal
law outlawing the transmission of obscene e-mail or faxes does not
violate the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The challenged provision of the Telecommunications Act of 1996
refers not only to obscene messages but also to those that are
``lewd, lascivious, filthy, or indecent'' _ all types of speech
that enjoy constitutional protection. However, the District Court
accepted the government's position that the law should be
interpreted to apply only to obscenity, which has no constitutional
protection.
</P>
<P>
   The case, Appollomedia Corp. vs. Reno, No. 98-933, was brought
by a San Francisco company that maintains a Web site through which
users can send indecent messages to public officials and others.
</P>
<P>
   Deportation Case
</P>
<P>
   Also without comment, the court turned down a request to
reconsider its 6-to-3 ruling last month that foreigners facing
deportation for their political activities cannot raise a First
Amendment challenge claiming that they were unconstitutionally
selected for deportation.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers representing eight Palestinians facing deportation for
their activities on behalf of the Popular Front for the Liberation
of Palestine argued that the decision last month, Reno vs.
American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee, No. 97-1252, was
procedurally unfair because the court had told the parties that it
would not decide the free speech issue.
</P>
<P>
   Because the court's focus appeared to be only on procedural
issues, the Palestinians' lawyers did not file a brief on the First
Amendment question. ``The court reached its result without even
hearing from the people it has now effectively silenced,'' the
lawyers told the justices in their petition for a rehearing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
