<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-COMPAQ CHIEF PFEIFFER SAYS OUSTER WAS DESIGNED TO PLACATE WALL
STREET 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Although he hesitates to use the word ``scapegoat,''
Eckhard Pfeiffer said Monday that his abrupt weekend ouster as
leader of Compaq Computer Corp. was designed to mollify Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   An unbowed Pfeiffer also said that his controversial statements
that the entire PC industry is slowing ultimately will be proved
correct.
</P>
<P>
   The 57-year-old German native lost his job Sunday because, key
board members said, the company had not been executing well on its
strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to appease the financial community, you create a
shakeup,'' Pfeiffer said. ``That, at least, seems to wipe the page
clean and you start from there.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that is subject to execution, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Earl Mason, Compaq's chief financial officer, also resigned
Sunday to become the chief executive at Chicago-based Alliant
Foodservice. Mason insists his departure was coincidental and not
related to Pfeiffer's ouster.
</P>
<P>
   The departures capped a tumultuous nine days for the computer
maker, which is Houston's largest company in terms of revenues.
</P>
<P>
   On April 9, Pfeiffer and Mason warned that Compaq's
first-quarter profits would be half what analysts were expecting,
citing dropping prices, cutthroat competition and softening demand
for business PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer said the conditions were industrywide, but when the
leaders of other computer makers began saying otherwise, analysts
and investors started questioning Pfeiffer's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``That created, let me say, frustration and a lack of
credibility with the financial community,'' Pfeiffer said.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Rosen, the venture capitalist who loaned Compaq's founders
$20,000 to start the company, is now running Compaq along with two
other board members, Frank Doyle and Ted Enloe. The three are
overseeing the computer maker's day-to-day operations in an
``office of the chief executive.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the second time Rosen has engineered the departure of a
chief executive. In October 1991, Rosen moved to fire co-founder
Rod Canion, who seemed unable to adapt to a growing demand for
low-cost PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in somber tones and without bitterness, Pfeiffer urged
the triumvirate to quickly hire a new chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had better hurry,'' he said. ``I don't think the current
team is the solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Sunday announcement came as a surprise, Pfeiffer
said he had been negotiating his possible departure over a period
of weeks _ even as he appeared poised and confident hosting
Compaq's biennial Innovate Forum 99 trade show last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``That discussion went on for quite a while,'' he said. ``We
talked about management structure and potential variations.''
</P>
<P>
   During Monday's interview, Pfeiffer frequently used the word
``we'' when referring to his former employer. At one point, he
laughed and apologized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry, it doesn't go away that fast,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Sunday and again in a conference call with
analysts on Monday morning, Rosen said that the board had become
concerned that Compaq was not keeping ahead of industry trends and
not moving fast enough with regard to its Internet strategy.
</P>
<P>
   But Pfeiffer asserted that Compaq ``had already been moving at
Internet speed _ plus a lot,'' and that its initiatives had already
made it No. 1 in many Internet-related areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we are one of the strongest Internet players, while
the perception is not as strong as the hard fact,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of speed, what people are confusing is what it takes
to integrate companies like Digital and Tandem in a matter of two
years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq bought Tandem Computer, which makes large computers used
in big businesses, and Digital Equipment Corp., over a two-year
period. Compaq is still in the process of integrating Digital.
</P>
<P>
   During the Innovate trade show, Pfeiffer unveiled a new strategy
to make Compaq the leader in supplying Internet-related hardware
and services to businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take credit for pointing it in this direction,'' he said.
``We are the only major company in the industry that has a 100
percent focus on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Rosen has embraced the Internet strategy but said he wants to
see Compaq move faster on it.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer also stuck to his guns regarding an overall PC industry
slowdown. He pointed to a comment from Intel Corp. that sales of
processors during the second quarter appear to be slowing.
</P>
<P>
   And he said that archrival Dell Computer Corp. actually came in
below expectations on its quarter. But because its fiscal year is
different from the rest of the industry, its slowdown was masked by
the timing of its quarterly report.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer said that, for the foreseeable future, he will remain
in Houston but will ``go where the next opportunity takes me.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer's separation agreement with Compaq, according to
documents filed with the Securities Exchange Commission, includes a
provision that he not work for a competitor for two years.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that does not stop him from working for another
high-tech company that does not compete with Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   ``But after you've run a $40 billion company, where do you go?''
he asked.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
