<HEADER>
A5000 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN     04-19 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER PLAY IS KEY FOR DUCKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- If the Mighty Ducks have one advantage against the
Detroit Red Wings in their upcoming playoff series, it figures to
be on the power play. Anaheim finished the season with the NHL's
No. 1-ranked power play unit (22 percent).
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks scored 83 power play goals, 18 more than the Red
Wings, who finished 10th (16.8 percent). The team's power play had
struggled through a 1-of-19 slump before scoring twice early in the
Ducks' 3-3 tie in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   That was a sight for the sore eyes of Anaheim coach Craig
Hartsburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power play is important to us,'' said Hartsburg, whose
team opens the playoffs in Detroit on Wednesday. ``Early in the
games, the power play can get you some momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg said he wasn't overly concerned about the power play,
however.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have lots of confidence in the guys on that unit,'' he said.
``Power plays can be hot and cold. You just have to stick with what
has had success and stay with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings certainly know how dangerous Anaheim is when it
gets the man advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't take a lot of penalties,'' winger Brendan Shanahan
told Detroit reporters. ``We're going to preach a lot of
discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   -- On paper, the Anaheim-Detroit series appears to be an
open-and-shut case. It would seem to be a mere formality for the
Red Wings as they begin their quest for a third consecutive Stanley
Cup title.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the Ducks are 4-15-5 all-time versus the Red Wings in
the regular season and are 1-8-3 in Detroit. Those numbers don't
include the Red Wings' four-game sweep of the Ducks in the second
round of the 1997 playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's players and coaches are saying the right things.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a good test for us,'' said Detroit assistant
coach Barry Smith. ``They've played much better as a team this year
than previously. It's not just a two-man team.''
</P>
<P>
   One newspaper columnist in Detroit thinks Anaheim is little more
than a bunch of sitting Ducks. He suggested the Red Wings would
much rather face them than San Jose or St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   He cited Detroit's superior depth, Guy Hebert's inexperience in
the playoffs, the Ducks' young defensemen, their dependence on
Kariya and Teemu Selanne and Chris Chelios' ability to intimidate
Kariya.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim winger Jim McKenzie knows a lot of stock shouldn't be
put in one writer's opinion, but also added such an article
``should'' motivate the Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You use whatever you can,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   -- Right wing Teemu Selanne won the inaugural Rocket Richard
Trophy as the National Hockey League's top goal scorer. Selanne
scored 47 goals and had 60 assists in 75 games.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL introduced the trophy last June to honor Maurice
Richard, who was the first player in league history to score 50
goals in 50 games. Ironically, this was the first full season since
1969-70 that no player scored at least 50 goals.
</P>
<P>
   -- While the Ducks played before only nine sellout crowds at the
Pond this season, hockey fever is alive and well in Hockeytown. The
Red Wings sold out all 41 games at Joe Louis Arena. Detroit also
played before sellout crowds in 35 of 41 road games.
</P>
<P>
   -- Both the Ducks and Red Wings are relatively healthy as the
playoffs begin. Defensemen Uwe Krupp, who signed a four-year,
$16-million free-agent contract in the offseason, is out with a
herniated disk after playing only 22 games this season. His absence
was a big reason the Red Wings were forced to trade for defensemen
Chelios and Ulf Sammuelsson at the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings will also likely be without tough-guy winger Joey
Kocur due to a groin injury.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Pascal Trepanier, who was providing much-needed depth
for the Ducks on defense, is out after undergoing surgery for a
torn ACL in his right knee. He was hurt playing basketball during
an off-day on the team's last East Coast road trip.
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie did not practice on Monday after being hitting in the
neck and jaw with a high stick by San Jose's Andrei Zyuzin on
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel fine. I want to play, no question,'' said McKenzie, who
has a large welt on his neck. ``But it's going to be a trainer's
and doctor's decision.''
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie wasn't exactly thrilled with the stickwork Zyuzin
displayed in what should have been a meaningless game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a four-year-old playing hockey and that's one of the
first things you teach -- keep your stick down,'' said McKenzie.
``Maybe he thought he was Luke Skywalker and I was Darth Vader.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Jason Marshall, Pavel Trnka and Marty McInnis all sat out the
final game in San Jose due to undisclosed injuries, but all are
expected to play against Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   -- Who knows if Kings president Tim Leiweke will be rooting for
the rival Ducks to beat the Red Wings in the opening round, but
there's little question he hopes Detroit takes a fall somewhere
along the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Ottawa wins it all,'' Leiweke told reporters recently.
``They've done it the right way, building through the draft.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiweke obviously has a hard time dealing with the approach
Detroit took at the trading deadline when the Red Wings traded for
high-piced veterans Chelios, Samuelsson, Wendel Clark and Bill
Ranford.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm (understand) Detroit did, but at some point, everybody has
to look themselves in the mirror and ask whether it's all about
buying a Stanley Cup,'' said Leiweke, whose team will lose millions
this season. ``To go out and write checks for the Stanley Cup
destroys the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Ottawa, Leiweke's sentimental pick, was molded by current
Anaheim general manager Pierre Gauthier and is run by ex-Kings
excutive Roy Mlakar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 2149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
