<HEADLINE>
PHOTO FULL UPDATE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 04/19/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- April 19, 1999 -- MRSCLINTON, 4-19 --
Hillary Clinton speaking at the Boathouse in Central Park on
Monday. Presenting herself as a New Yorker in spirit and in
politics, Hillary Rodham Clinton began a two-day tour through
Manhattan and Long Island on Monday, praising the state's history
and culture as she expounded for the first time on why she might
want to be the senator from a state she has never called home. ``I
love New York,'' she says. ``I always have.'' (Ruby Washington/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) BUDAPEST, Hungary -- April 19, 1999 --
HOLBROOKE-CONFIRM, 4-19 -- Richard Holbrooke, President Clinton's
special envoy to Yugoslavia, walks along the banks of the Danube
River last month hours after arriving from Belgrade where he
unsuccessfully tried to pursuade Yugoslav leader Slobodan Milosevic
to accept a peace plan in Kosovo and avoid NATO air strikes. Senate
leaders and the State Department say they are close to a deal that
could rescue Holbrooke's long-delayed nomination to lead the
American delegation to the United Nations. (Edward Keating/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) MILWAUKEE -- April 19, 1999 -- WIS-WELFARE-3, 4-19 --
Michelle Crawford, at home in Milwaukee with daughter Yolanda Reed,
7, remains off welfare and on the job at a nearby plastics factory.
Initially she resented being forced to work for her welfare check,
of $673 a month. ``To me, it was just like slavery,'' she says. ``I
couldn't be with my kids.'' (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) MILWAUKEE -- April 19, 1999 -- WIS-WELFARE-2, 4-19 --
``I like getting up in the morning, going to my job,'' says
Michelle Crawford, at work at a plastics factory near Milwaukee.
``I want to tell other girls, 'Hey, if you're going through
something, I've been there,' `` she says. ``I've had those things
thrown in my face: 'You'll never be nothing.' There's women out
there scared.'' (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) BOSTON -- April 19, 1999 -- BOSTON-MARATHON, 4-19 --
Joseph Chebet of Kenya, left, and Fatuma Roba of Ethiopia, cross
the finish line to win the Boston Marathon on Monday. Chebet came
in at 2 hours, 9 minutes, 52 seconds while Roba's time was 2:23:25.
(Jim Davis/Boston Globe Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) PRINCETON, N.J. -- April 19, 1999 --
EMPIRICAL-ECONOMISTS, 4-19 -- Alan B. Krueger with daughter Sydney,
6, and son Ben, 8, in the backyard of their New Jersey home. No
group in the profession of economics is challenging accepted wisdom
more vigorously than empirical economists like Krueger. But he does
so rather cautiously, and there is a reason for his hesitation:
Abstract thinkers still dominate academic economics with their
explanations of how people and markets behave. (Laura Pedrick/New
York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) HAT CREEK, Calif. -- April 19, 1999 -- ALIEN-LIFE, 4-19
-- Dr. William Welch, professor of Astronomy and Electrical
Engineering at U.C. Berkley, stands among the radio telescopes that
he is working with at Hat Creek Radio Observatory near Redding,
Calif. As the first professor to hold the university's Watson and
Marilyn Alberts' chair for the Search for Extraterrestrial
Intelligence, the first academic chair of its kind anywhere,
Welch's job is to scour the universe to find humanity's neighbors
out there, somewhere, light years away. (Monica Almeida/New York
Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) MADISON, Wisc. -- April 19, 1999 -- WIS-WELFARE, 4-19 --
Michelle Crawford addresses a joint session of the Wisconsin State
Legislature last January as Gov. Tommy Thompson, right, looks on.
Crawford outlined to the legislature how Thompson's showcase
welfare program had transformed her life.
</P>
<P>
   (Andy Manis/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) BRAZDA, Macedonia -- April 19, 1999 --
KOSOVO-CHILDREN-BOS, 4-19 -- Jeton, 5, is comforted by his mother,
Aimonie Hasani, inside their tent in Brazda. Jeton saw his
grandmother die in her garden at the hands of the Serbs. The damage
from this war is both psychological and physical to the
quarter-million children displaced from their homes. (Bill
Greene/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) CLAREMONT, N.H. -- April 19, 1999 -- BRADLEY-PROFILE,
4-19 -- Bill Bradley, former U.S. senator from New Jersey, at a
campaign stop in a donut shop recently. The parade of Democrats who
had planned to take on Vice President Al Gore for the presidency
has evaporated, leaving a simple dynamic. If Gore does not get the
nomination, Bradley does. Never before in modern American politics,
in a contest for an open White House, has the competition for a
nomination been distilled to two people so early. (Herb Swanson/New
York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) AVIANO AIR BASE, Italy -- April 19, 1999 --
KOSOVO-PILOTS, 4-19 -- A pilot of an F-16 waits for the signal to
shut down his engines after arriving from a mission over Kosovo
last Friday. Peering down at the ground from 15,000 feet or higher,
NATO pilots like those who apparently attacked civilians in Kosovo
last week by mistake rely on a combination of technology and their
own eyesight to identify what they are seeing. (Senior Airman
Jeffrey Allen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- April 19, 1999 -- MET-GREEK-CORRIDOR-2, 4-19
-- Dorothy H. Abramitis, a conservator, removing the last bit of
resin from a statue before the reopening of the Met's Greek and
Roman gallery. One of the first parts of the museum to be put
together, the antiquities collection is the last major department
to be overhauled. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- April 19, 1999 -- MET-GREEK-CORRIDOR-1, 4-19
-- The newly renovated 140-foot-long central gallery at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art. It is being reopened as the centerpiece
of the second phase of a three-part campaign to overhaul all the
Met's galleries of Greek and Roman art. (Fred R. Conrad/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- April 19, 1999 -- CUNNINGHAM-NOVEL, 4-19 --
Michael Cunningham, Pulitzer Prize winner for fiction, in his
apartment in Chelsea. Cunningham, 46, says he considers ``The
Hours,'' his ``strongest book by far,'' and ``an act of
veneration'' for the original - Virgninia Woolf's ``Mrs. Dalloway''
- which is a day in the life of an Englishwoman. It is his fourth
published novel, and it was a long time in coming. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- April 19, 1999 -- SCI-GOD-DEBATE, 4-19 --
Reprising their ``God vs. Science'' debate at the National Museum
of Natural History in Washington, the nonbeliever, Dr. Steven
Weinberg, left, and the believer, the Rev. Dr. John Polkinghorne.
Propelled by intriguing advances in cosmology and by millions of
dollars from the Templeton Foundation, efforts to build a
``constructive dialogue'' between science and religion have
proliferated of late. (Carol T. Powers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) MARTINSBURG, W.Va. -- April 19, 1999 --
SCI-PARKINSONS-FETAL, 4-19 -- Steve Ashworth of Martinsburg says
his life is on hold until he learns the result of a study of fetal
brain-cell transplants for Parkinson's. On Wednesday, the wait will
be over. At a conference in Toronto, Dr. Curt Freed, the University
of Colorado neuroscientist who led the study, will announce his
results, 11 years after President Reagan first banned the use of
tax money for such research. (Scott Robinson/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) PITTSBURGH -- April 19, 1999 -- SCI-BRAIN-PLASTICITY,
4-19 -- Dr. Jay McClelland, a leader of the Pittsburgh team that is
discovering ways to overcome mechanisms in the brain that are
resistant to change. In a fascinating set of experiments,
researchers at the Center for the Neural Basis of Cognition here
have found a way to teach native speakers of Japanese to hear the
difference between L and R reliably after just one hour of
training. (Terry Clark/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) SANTA BARBARA, Calif. -- April 19, 1999 --
SCI-ASHTEKAR-PHYSICS-2, 4-19 -- Dr. Abhay Ashtekar caused a
sensation among theoretical physicists by redefining the variables
in Einstein's equations. ``I have never been able to follow a
recipe,'' he says. ``I just add what seems right.'' (Michael
Tweed/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) SANTA BARBARA, Calif. -- April 19, 1999 --
SCI-ASHTEKAR-PHYSICS-1, 4-19 -- Dr. Abhay Ashtekar is nonchalant
about the implications of his work. Physics, he says, ``is only a
part of the whole mystery of nature, of existence and ourselves.''
(Michael Tweed/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- April 19, 1999 -- MIND-HEALTH-REVIEW, 4-17 --
Medical science, focused on curing the ills of the body, has often
treated the mind like an annoying younger brother: a presence to be
ignored whenever possible, humored when unavoidable and used as a
scapegoat when the need arises. This philosophy is now changing.
Researchers have found that after writing about traumatic effects
in their lives, some patients in their study found their condition
improved . (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) MORINA BORDER POINT, Albania -- April 19, 1999 --
KOSOVO-REFUGEES-COX, 4-19 -- Haxhi Nimani, 50, who claims Yugoslav
security forces broke the windows of his car, waits at a border
crossing on Monday for relatives who were separated as they fled
Kosovo. Nimani transported eight members of his family out of the
embattled region and fears the others were killed or injured.
(Marcia Kunstel/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- April 19, 1999 -- CLINTON-TEACHER-FLOATER,
4-19 -- President Clinton congratulates Andrew Baumgartner, a
kindergarten teacher from Augusta, Ga., winner of the National
Teacher of the Year award, during a ceremony at the White House on
Monday. Clinton used the occasion to urge Congress to act on his
proposals to subsidize the hiring of 100,00 new teachers and to
modernize schools throughout the nation. (Paul Hosefros/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- April 19, 1999 -- ISRAEL-POLITICS-2-B&AMP;W, 4-19
-- Benjamin Netanyahu, right, in 1973, as a young soldier in an
elite commando unit led by Ehud Barak, far left. Barak is seen
looking on at hostage freed after his unit stormed a Sabena
airliner in 1973. The long, tangled relationship between Netanyahu,
now Israel's prime minister, and Barak, Netanyahu's chief rival in
May 17 elections, provides an odd backdrop to the campaign.
(Israeli Defense Forces/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) JERUSALEM -- April 19, 1999 -- ISRAEL-POLITICS, 4-19 --
The long, tangled relationship between Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu, bottom, and Labor's Ehud Barak, Netanyahu's
chief rival in upcoming elections, provides an odd backdrop to the
campaign. Israelis go to the polls on May 17. (Rina Castelnuovo/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ELBASAN, Albania -- April 19, 1999 -- KOSOVO-REFUGEES-2,
4-19 -- Young refugees from Kosovo draw on pads provided by a
Norwegian relief group on Monday in a camp set up just south of the
Albanian capital of Tirana. The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees
estimates that more than 600,000 people, the vast majority of them
ethnic Albanians, have left Kosovo since NATO began its air assault
March 24. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) ELBASAN, Albania -- April 19, 1999 -- KOSOVO-REFUGEES-1,
4-19 -- Refugees from Kosovo gather around a television to watch
the latest news on Monday in a camp set up just south of the
Albanian capital of Tirana. The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees
estimates that more than 600,000 people, the vast majority of them
ethnic Albanians, have left Kosovo since NATO began its air assault
March 24. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- April 19, 1999 -- HKN-GRETZKY, 04-18 -- Wayne
Gretzky of the New York Rangers, the NHL's leading scorer, thanks
his fans Sunday after playing in his final game in sold-out Madison
Square Garden. ``I love this game so much, it's treated me well,''
Gretzky told reporters after the game. ``It's a great game and I'm
going to miss it so much.'' (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
