<HEADER>
A5005 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPAQ-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      04-19 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: NEXT CHIEF OF COMPAQ MAY HAVE TO REINVENT IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Compaq Computer Corp. begins its search for a new chief
executive, it is clear that the prospective leader's first
challenge will be to chart a course from the brick-and-mortar
retailers that have been the company's lifeblood to the
direct-sales model that is increasingly defining the industry's
future, analysts and consultants said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Eckhard Pfeiffer, 57, was dismissed over the weekend by Compaq's
board, led by a company co-founder, Benjamin Rosen. Earl Mason,
Compaq's chief financial officer, also resigned to become chief
executive at an unidentified company. The announcement came nine
days after Compaq warned that its first-quarter income would be
about half what analysts expected.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq's problems stem from a strategy that has appeared to pull
the company in opposite directions at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, it has struggled to compete in the
personal-computer market with Dell Computer Corp., which sells
directly to buyers, avoiding the dealer channel and its markup, and
builds each machine to order, keeping inventories and costs at a
minimum.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Compaq, though its acquisitions of Digital
Equipment Corp. last year and Tandem Computer in 1997, has tried to
become a major systems company, like IBM Corp. and Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that Compaq's strategy has been unraveling for
quite a few years now,'' said Regis McKenna, president of McKenna
Group, a management consulting firm based in Palo Alto, Calif.
``They're caught between the low end and the high end, and that's
why you see them constantly changing their mind. The first thing
they have to do is figure out what they want to be when they grow
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer succeeded Compaq's first chief executive, another
co-founder, Rod Canion, in 1991, in a coup also led by Rosen. He
aggressively lowered Compaq's cost structure to meet the challenge
of new competition, and the reduced costs allowed the Houston-based
company to gain the computer industry's leading market share while
maintaining decent profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   But by the late 1990s, as Compaq embraced the sub-$1,000 PC, its
growth came at the expense of profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   About 18 months ago, Compaq announced that it was moving to a
build-to-order business model, similar to Dell's, but that it would
retain its traditional distribution through the dealer channel, as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Although Compaq did reduce internal inventory levels, it has
never matched Dell's operating efficiency, and it has continued to
lag behind Dell in growth. Dell has systematically sought out
Compaq's strongest markets, first in laptops and then in servers
and work stations, and has gained market share in each.
</P>
<P>
   Like Canion, who made an unsuccessful attempt to acquire Silicon
Graphics in the late 1980s, Pfeiffer looked to the high end of the
market to differentiate Compaq. The Tandem and Digital acquisitions
were meant to transform Compaq from the world's largest PC company
into a fully integrated computer systems company. Just as it had
passed IBM in personal-computer sales, so Compaq would come to lead
the systems business, Pfeiffer predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kind of goals he had sounded good to shareholders _ like
being a $50 billion company by the year 2000, or to beat IBM _ but
they didn't have anything to do with customers,'' said Mark
Anderson, president of Strategic News Service, a research firm
based in Friday Harbor, Wash. ``The new CEO should look at
everything Eckhard acquired and ask: Did the customer benefit from
that? If the answer isn't yes, they should get rid of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said he was not necessarily advocating the sale of
Digital, Tandem or any of the smaller companies Compaq acquired in
recent years, only their integration into a coherent strategy. ``If
you think of the Internet as the all-embracing future, as Ben Rosen
seems to suggest from his statements, it's not hard to see how the
parts of Compaq fit into that,'' he said. ``The new CEO should have
a clear focus on a single business plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest challenge facing Compaq's next leader is how
to differentiate the company's products at a time when the value of
brands has been diminished and personal computers sell almost
exclusively on the basis of price. While Apple Computer can command
a small premium based on the ease of use or on the attractive
design of its products, and Sun Microsystems flourishes as a
high-end technology company identified with the Internet, most
computer makers struggle to add value to a commodity product.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business has been assiduously destroying pricing and
profitability, bent on self-immolation,'' said Seymour Merrin,
president of Merrin Information Services, a consulting firm based
in Palo Alto. ``Compaq, more than any other vendor, has the
opportunity to do what Robert Crandall at American Airlines did
when he said, `The time has come to stop killing ourselves.' The
customer, if he perceives value, is willing to pay. What all the
companies have failed to do, with Compaq right at the front, is to
differentiate.''
</P>
<P>
   Dell prospers by offering performance at a price, rather than
just a low price, and by making the purchasing process more
pleasant, Merrin said. But he said he did not believe that Compaq
should emulate Dell by eliminating the dealer channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compaq can't do that,'' Merrin said. ``They have better
distribution than anyone else. A good percentage of their customers
are buying through dealers because they want to. What they should
do is set up a totally separate business unit'' for direct sales.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Bajarin, president of Creative Strategies, a consulting firm
in Cupertino, Calif., agreed. ``I don't think you can cut the
channel off, but what you have to do is take off the price
protection you give dealers,'' he said, referring to the common
practice of reimbursing dealers for price cuts affecting current
inventory. ``It's a new world and a new economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The new chief executive Bajarin said, ``has to build a model
that says no matter what the customer wants to buy, no matter where
they want to buy it _ on the Internet, by telephone, in a
superstore _ Compaq has to make it available.''
</P>
<P>
   On a day of widespread losses among technology stocks, Compaq's
shares closed Monday at $22.75, down 87.5 cents, on trading of more
than 38 million shares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
