A5013 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLIGHT-GLENN-COX     04-19 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLIGHT-GLENN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glenn leads 2003 Committee into action
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ He wasn't sitting on a rocket, but John Glenn got
the crowd chanting ``Ten, nine, eight. . .'' Monday afternoon in
the U.S. Air Force Museum, where he helped the 2003 Committee
launch its campaign to celebrate the centennial anniversary of
powered flight.
</P>
<P>
   When the crowd of about 100 people got to ``zero,'' the space
pioneer flipped a switch that started the committee's digital
``countdown clock'' to Dec. 17, 2003, the 100th anniversary of the
Wright brothers' first flights in a powered airplane.
</P>
<P>
   It was Glenn's first public act as secretary general of the 2003
Committee, which also started operating under the new name
``Inventing Flight.''
</P>
<P>
   The event preceded an invitation-only gala at the museum, where
Inventing Flight officials offered the latest plans for a year-long
series of events to celebrate the first flight centennial.
</P>
<P>
   J. Bradford Tillson, chairman of Inventing Flight's board of
trustees, highlighted the main activities:
</P>
<P>
   Preparation of educational programs and materials, among them a
school curriculum plan dubbed ``From Kites to the Wrights'' and a
Digistar planetarium show.
</P>
<P>
   A variety of sports events, including bicycle races reminiscent
of the Wright brothers' days as bicycle makers.
</P>
<P>
   An international arts festival dedicated to conflict resolution,
starting with a week-long festival in May or June 2001, with the
aim of making it an annual event by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   A series of aviation-related events, culminating in what
Tillson, who is also publisher of the Dayton Daily News, called
``an air show for the ages.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn said the 100th anniversary of powered flight deserves ``a
celebration of mammoth proportions'' because the airplane was a
revolutionary development that changed the world.
</P>
<P>
   And he said Dayton is an appropriate place to celebrate Orville
and Wilbur Wright's accomplishments: ``They lived, they worked and
they invented flight right here in Dayton.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn himself helped pioneer space flight in 1962 when he became
the first American to orbit the earth. Last October, he became the
oldest person to orbit the planet when he flew on a space shuttle
at age 77.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, whose titles have included Marine Corps colonel,
astronaut and U.S. senator, poked a little self-conscious fun at
his latest salutation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never a secretary and I never made general,'' he
quipped.
</P>
<P>
   The countdown clock is one of several that will be on display
around the Dayton area. The first will remain in the museum, with
others at Dayton International Airport and downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy R. Gaffney writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
