<SLUG> BC-GORE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore visits Ohio, visits tornado sites
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Vice President Al Gore helped his 2000 presidential
prospects during a visit to Cincinnati on Monday by winning
endorsements from U.S. Rep. Tony Hall and other Democrats and by
adding $150,000 in pledges to his campaign treasury.
</P>
<P>
   During his six-hour visit, Gore also visited Blue Ash and
Montgomery, Cincinnati suburbs hit by an April 9 tornado, and made
a vigorous defense of the air war being waged by the United States
and its NATO allies against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   It was the vice president's second visit to Ohio in less than a
week, pointing up the state's importance in next year's
presidential elections, Gore backers said. Last Wednesday, the vice
president, who once raised tobacco on his Tennessee farm, visited
Akron for an anti-smoking event.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 people attended a fund-raising luncheon at the downtown
Westin Cincinnati Hotel and either made contributions to Gore's
campaign or promised to raise funds. A campaign aide said the event
is expected to net at least $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Hall's endorsement came at the luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the easiest endorsement I've ever made,'' said Hall,
D-Dayton, who served in the U.S. House with Gore. ``He's my friend
and I like him a lot. I think he's a good and decent man.''
</P>
<P>
   Little mention was made of President Clinton, whose tenure had
been tainted by his impeachment and related allegations of
misconduct. Hall's reference to Gore as a ``good and decent man''
was echoed by Cincinnati Mayor Roxanne Qualls in her endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has made it clear he is ``absolutely committed'' to his
wife, their three daughters and their son, Qualls said. Qualls also
announced that the Gores will become grandparents for the first
time in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's such a young man to be a grandfather, wouldn't you say?''
she asked. The vice president turned 51 on March 31.
</P>
<P>
   At the event, the Gore campaign also announced that the vice
president has been endorsed by state Sen. Mark Mallory, former U.S.
Rep. David Mann and other Cincinnati-area Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery County Democratic Chairman Dennis Lieberman, who
attended the fund-raiser, said he personally has endorsed Gore but
the county party has not.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's extremely intelligent. If people take the time to listen
to him, he'll be elected,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who attended private schools as a boy, told supporters
that if he's elected he will make ``revolutionary changes in our
public schools.'' He said he wants to reduce class sizes so no
teacher _ in all grades up to the 12th _ has more than 20 students.
Also, Gore said he wants to make early childhood education
available to every child in the country who wants it
</P>
<P>
   Such changes are necessary to help the United States maintain
world leadership in an information age, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president also urged the friendly crowd to back the
American and NATO war effort in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It confronted us with a situation where there were no good
options,'' he said. ``I'm proud we did respond.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he does not want the 21st century to be molded by
``thugs in ski masks with hatred in their hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in Ohio and nationally have criticized Clinton and
Gore for raising money while the war rages, and that continued on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Clinton on the golf course and Gore on the road, you
wonder who is watching the store . . . It's shameless,'' said Gary
Abernathy, spokesman for the Ohio Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, however, said such charges are ``nothing more than
political accusations.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that both Gore and Clinton have been willing to discuss
the war and the reasons for American involvement, as Gore did
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what he's doing is commendable, bringing it to the
people,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   During the visit to Blue Ash and Montgomery, Gore sympathized
with those cleaning up from the tornado that killed four people and
destroyed hundreds of homes.
</P>
<P>
   He was not able to tell them, however, that Gov. Bob Taft's
request for assistance from the Federal Emergency Management Agency
for families, businesses and local governments had been approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is under intensive review right now at FEMA. There should
be some kind of word on that early this week,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   William Hershey writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
