<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5015 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-ART-NYT     04-19 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON BEGINS NONCAMPAIGN OFFENSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Presenting herself as a New Yorker in spirit and in
politics, Hillary Rodham Clinton began a two-day tour through
Manhattan and Long Island on Monday, praising the state's history
and culture as she expounded for the first time on why she might
want to be the senator from a state she has never called home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love New York,'' she proclaimed. ``I always have.''
</P>
<P>
   In the course of a rigorous 12-hour day of speeches, dinners,
photo sessions and a news conference, the first lady also strongly
assailed the idea of private school vouchers as a threat to the
nation's public education system. In so doing, Mrs. Clinton drew a
strong, though unstated, contrast to Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who is
also considering running for Senate, and has enthusiastically
embraced the idea of private school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady, who will be spending three days in New York this
week, said that her visits were all part of official White House
business. As such, they are being financed almost entirely by
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mrs. Clinton kept to a schedule that would have been
considered heavy even for a declared candidate entering the final
week of a difficult contest. Her choice of stops was reminiscent of
a typical Democratic candidate's campaign itinerary, from an
environmental event in Central Park in the morning to a fund-raiser
for Rep. Jerrold Nadler, where she praised the Manhattan Democrat's
``vigor, intelligence and energy'' in defending her husband during
impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton seemed to take pains to reply to a criticism that
Giuliani has repeatedly raised about her potential candidacy: that
if she ran, she would be a political opportunist, because she has
never lived in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton declared her affection for the state, instructing a
roomful of reporters about the diversity of the state's
agricultural crops and, by using the word ``we'' in discussing the
state, all but implying that she was a New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is truly a microcosm of America,'' she said, adding
that it had ``everything from our biggest, most dynamic city to
rural areas that produce some of the crops that you might be
surprised to know are actually grown right here in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So we have everything in New York that we have in America,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, who grew up in Illinois, recounted her frequent
visits to New York as first lady, and said that she felt
politically comfortable in the state. She suggested that
representing New York would allow her to work on issues she had
hoped to tackle as first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way that New York handles a lot of issues, and the
challenges that are going to be facing America in the next century,
are ones that are of deep interest to me,'' Mrs. Clinton said. ``So
in my many visits to New York, I have always been very excited by
the dynamism of the people here and the real cutting-edge approach
to a lot of what I consider to be the important issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's trip marked another chapter in what has become
a very active if not-quite-declared campaign between two
not-quite-declared candidates to succeed Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, the Democrat who is retiring next year. For all the
tentativeness of Mrs. Clinton's intentions, her mere arrival drew a
huge press contingent, including eight television cameras and a
pack of reporters from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In this campaign netherworld, Mrs. Clinton and her staff seemed
unsure whether she was a potential candidate or just a first lady.
They seemed flummoxed by questions about the appropriateness of
taxpayers financing the trip; the first lady's press secretary,
Marsha Berry, wearily suggested that a reporter who pressed her on
who was paying for the travel was ``a pinhead,'' though she said
that the first lady would address the question if and when her
candidacy became more concrete.
</P>
<P>
   While the schedule seemed designed to encourage press attention,
the first lady declined to provide routine transportation for her
sizable press corps, apparently concerned that such a gesture might
undercut her portrayal of the trip as business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani was anything but tentative in his treatment of a
Democrat who even his aides acknowledge would be a formidable
rival. Outside of New York City, ``I do note, as I travel around
the state, a very strong reaction against her running,'' he said.
``I have people coming up to me, saying to me, and not just
Republicans, `Why don't you go run in Arkansas?' ''
</P>
<P>
   He also criticized Clinton's handling of Kosovo. ``From the very
beginning, this should have been thought out better and the purpose
should have been stated better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday marked the first time that the first lady had publicly
discussed a Senate race, at least on American soil. (She had
answered questions about it during a visit to Cairo.) The first
lady did nothing to discourage the speculation; her remarks, in
fact, suggested that she is exploring ways to deal with problems
she might confront as someone who does not live in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
