A5017 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-NYT &LR;      04-19 0428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO UPDATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; COMBAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ On the 27th day of the air assault on Yugoslavia, NATO struck
a communications transmitter near the Kosovo capital, Pristina, and
an airport near Urosevac in southern Kosovo. During the preceding
night, NATO planes bombed Pristina and Novi Sad, Serbia's second
city.
</P>
<P>
   _ NATO acknowledged for the first time that its aircraft had hit
two separate convoys in southwestern Kosovo last week and might
have killed civilians.
</P>
<P>
   _ Separatist rebels of the Kosovo Liberation Army said they had
captured three members of the Yugoslav army.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REFUGEES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The flow of Kosovo Albanians into Albania and Macedonia dried
up, raising fears among aid workers for the safety of tens of
thousands of refugees. The U.N. high commissioner for refugees said
Yugoslav forces appeared to be turning back Albanians trying to
leave the country.
</P>
<P>
   _ The U.N. refugee agency estimated that more than 619,000
refugees had fled to neighboring countries since conflict broke out
in Kosovo more than a year ago.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ NATO was considering parachuting relief aid to displaced
Albanians within Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DIPLOMACY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ President Clinton called President Boris Yeltsin of Russia to
press for Russian involvement in a resolution that would involve
Russian troops in an international force in Kosovo. It was their
first conversation on the conflict since the bombing began on March
24.
</P>
<P>
   _ U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said he would visit Moscow
on April 29 to discuss the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER DEVELOPMENTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The Clinton administration asked Congress for $6 billion in
emergency money for the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the Yugoslav republic of Montenegro, residents of three
Muslim villages near the border with Kosovo said the Yugoslav army
had expelled them to turn their communities into a second front
line.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bulgaria agreed to allow NATO to freely cross its airspace.
The Czech Republic, which joined NATO last month, authorized NATO
planes on missions over Yugoslavia to use its airfields, and
alliance ground troops and military supplies to pass through its
territory, though the decision must be ratified by Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   _ NATO leaders will curtail the opening ceremony of their summit
meeting in Washington on Friday to discuss the Kosovo conflict,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ON THE WEB  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Continuous coverage of the conflict in Yugoslavia is available
from The New York Times on the Web: http://www.nytimes.com
</P>
</TEXT>
