<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OBSTACLES REMAIN IN L.A. BID FOR NFL TEAM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN WILLIAMS 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One thing is clear in this city's pursuit of a
National Football League expansion team _ it won't use tax dollars
to build the kind of stadium the NFL demands.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the only thing that's clear.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL picture here remains as hazy as the smog hanging over
the only U.S. city to lose two professional football teams in the
same year.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are there no plans to use tax dollars _ which the NFL
wanted _ but there are no plans for a state-of-the-art stadium.
There is no clear-cut location for it. There is no ownership group
with enough support from league owners to get the 24 votes needed
to join their elite club.
</P>
<P>
   To sort out some of the confusion, NFL officials flew here for
meetings Monday and Tuesday with business, civic and political
leaders to get a sharper image of what must occur to meet the
league's Sept. 15 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   If the answers aren't found by then, it is very likely Houston
and businessman Bob McNair will be get the league's 32nd franchise.
They have what Los Angeles doesn't: a ready-to-go $310 million
stadium deal backed by $195 million in local tax dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very confusing situation here,'' NFL Expansion
Committee Co-Chairman Jerry Richardson said in the Century Plaza
Hotel, where NFL officials are meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, owner of the Carolina Panthers, said that despite
the confusion he thinks Los Angeles can take a major step toward
getting pro football for the first time since the Raiders and Rams
left in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Richardson and other NFL officials attended a
cocktail party held by the Los Angeles Business Advisers, a group
of top business executives. Today, the owners will tour the
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we met in Phoenix last month, Los Angeles was standing
still,'' Richardson said. ``But in the last month, we have gotten
overwhelming support from almost everyone in the community. Every
business leader, religious leader, academic leader and political
leader seem to have a genuine interest to do what they can to get a
team.''
</P>
<P>
   What they have not done, however, is put together a solid deal.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said the league has list of general goals the city
must meet, including a better understanding of how much parking a
Los Angeles deal can include and, specifically, who will pay for
it.
</P>
<P>
   If the owners agree to let a renovated Coliseum become the
stadium for the next team, they want assurances there is enough
parking close so fans don't have to walk through the rowdy
neighborhood around it.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson also said there are issues about control of the
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But utmost among the goals is creating a situation here where
the league can up the ante for an expansion fee by pitting
ownership bidders against one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Owners don't want to be dictated to about who the Los Angeles
owner will be,'' Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   That creates a dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   Developer Ed Roski holds the right to make a new stadium out of
the old Coliseum. Though someone can buy that right from him _ for
the $5 million in costs he has incurred to date _ no one seems
willing to do it
</P>
<P>
   because it would also shoulder aside his partner, Eli Broad, one
of the most politically connected people in the city.
</P>
<P>
   A series of events unfolded last week that could lead to a
bidding war in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   First, Richardson bluntly told the Los Angeles Times that he
wanted Roski's deal terminated by the time NFL owners meet this
week.
</P>
<P>
   That coincided with an announcement by Hollywood deal-maker
Michael Ovitz that he was backing out of a competing proposal to
build a new stadium, called The Hacienda, atop a former landfill in
nearby Carson.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz said he would focus on the Coliseum project.
</P>
<P>
   But representatives for both Broad-Roski and Ovitz have said
they will not share control with each other. It's a winner-take-all
game.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And the game has a wild card, pushed by the NFL and supported by
Ovitz _ move the Los Angeles Dodgers from Chavez Ravine to a new
stadium next to the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were bought last year by Rupert Murdoch, who also
owns Fox Sports _ which televises NFL games. Last week, team
officials scoffed at the suggestion, saying they are working on a
$30 million to $50 million renovation of Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox officials have not dismissed the idea.
</P>
<P>
   The confusion means little news is likely to come out of the
meetings, which will end with a Coliseum press conference attended
by Mayor Richard Riordan and City Councilman Mark Ridley-Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   All this means is that Los Angeles has less than five months to
work out a deal it has been unable to cobble together for more than
a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't done much so far,'' said one NFL official.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
