<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ZONING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIMITS PLANNED ON BUILDING HEIGHTS IN NEW YORK CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Moving to overhaul New York City's zoning laws for
the first time in 40 years, the Giuliani administration on Tuesday
will propose the city's first broad limits on the height of
skyscrapers. The rules would curtail a longstanding practice that
permits developers to build higher buildings in exchange for
creating plazas or other public amenities at ground level.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are among several in the planned zoning revisions.
Some changes would open manufacturing areas to more medical and
social service complexes. Others would greatly increase the number
of parking spaces allowed in new residential buildings and impose
more restrictions on the large billboard-type signs that are common
across the city.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most significant changes involve building size,
with the new proposals aimed at setting maximum heights for
buildings in most parts of a city that is synonymous with its
skyscrapers. City officials say the height limits have yet to be
determined, but added that the permissible height of new buildings
would probably be similar to that of the tallest existing structure
in any particular neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The most congested parts of midtown and downtown would be
excluded from the new height rules, Joseph Rose, the chairman of
the City Planning Commission, said in an interview. The idea, Rose
explained, is not to protect those two most densely developed parts
of Manhattan from more dense development, but to prevent other
areas of the city from being overdeveloped.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed restrictions are intended to address the challenges
posed by a strong economy and a resulting building boom that has
tested limits on the height and scale of new construction.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Donald Trump is proceeding with plans for a
90-story apartment building on a residential East Side block, a
project he has been able to push by obtaining development rights
from several nearby properties.
</P>
<P>
   The Trump plan would have been blocked if the proposed zoning
changes had been in effect when it was awaiting city approval, Rose
said. He would not give other examples of buildings, either
existing or proposed, that would be disqualified.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the existing rules that allowed for such projects
cumbersome and obsolete, city officials say developers should no
longer be allowed to exploit such development rights _ and use
outdated city incentives _ to build ever-higher towers.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, they said, the city should find ways to
accommodate projects that meet the needs of its growing economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a city that has been built to its borders, but is
still growing and changing as rapidly as any other,'' said Rose,
who is scheduled to describe the proposed zoning changes to an
invited group of planners, community advocates and elective
officials in a City Hall address Tuesday. He said the height limits
would vary according to the existing scale of city neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the city's complex 900-page zoning law that was
first written in 1916 and last amended in 1961, Rose said he feared
what he called ``a Pandora's box'' of conflicting demands from
developers, environmentalists and others if the entire zoning
statute were opened for revision.
</P>
<P>
   The solution, he said, was to institute a limited number of
``dramatic modifications.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed changes face a battery of tests, including public
hearings, environmental review and a City Council vote. The
administration hopes to have the rules in place by the time
Giuliani leaves office; the last time such major changes were
proposed, in the 1950s, the revisions were not enacted for nearly a
decade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
