<SLUG> BC-MARKET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK MARKET HIT AS INVESTORS FLEE TECHNOLOGY AREA
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for inserts, rewriting throughout)   (mb) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON and    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a stunning reversal, investors piled out of
technology stocks and other market darlings on Monday, pummeling
the very shares that propelled the broad market averages to records
last week.
</P>
<P>
   After rising 271.8 points, or 2.6 percent, during the morning,
the Dow Jones industrial average ran out of steam shortly after
noon and ended the day down 53.36 points, or 0.5 percent, at
10,440.53.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq market started the day in negative territory and
never climbed out as investors fled the computer, Internet and
telecommunications stocks they had been favoring. Amazon.com lost
16 percent, Dell Computer declined 7.3 percent, and Microsoft fell
6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index, home to most of the nation's
technology companies, fell 138.43 points, or about 5.6 percent, to
close at 2,345.61.
</P>
<P>
   That was the composite's second- biggest fall in points but only
its seventh in percentage terms. Its largest point decline took
place on Aug. 31, at the height of the Russian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Volume on the New York Stock Exchange exceeded 1.21 billion
shares, the second-heaviest trading day in the exchange's history.
Nasdaq trading volume was also brisk, at 1.198 billion shares.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the day, investors took refuge in stocks whose fortunes
closely track the performance of the economy, but even those shares
began to sputter at the close. ``This kind of a sharp and dramatic
reversal is not just business as usual,'' said Byron R. Wien, U.S.
investment strategist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``There's a
message here. The message is everything finally began to sell off
from sheer exhaustion.''
</P>
<P>
   Though oil prices rose in the morning, traders said this alone
was not enough to kill the rally in the Dow. The shift away from
the glamour stocks of technology, health care, Internet and
telecommunications companies began last week and it simply gained
momentum. The Standard &AMP; Poor's/Barra Growth stock index _ a
collection of companies with high growth rates and lofty stock
valuations _ has fallen 10 percent in the last five trading
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the biggest losers on Monday were stocks that had
previously seemed to levitate. Even after Monday's collapse, these
shares are trading at high prices based on their earnings and are
well above their lows. America Online, for example, fell 23~ a
share, to 115~. That is down more than 30 percent from its high of
April 6, but the shares are now where they were just about a month
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the Charles Schwab Corp., a brokerage concern that is
a favorite Internet play because of its on-line trading services,
closed down 32 percent from its high of one week ago. Still, it is
up 81 percent since the start of the year. Reflecting the damage
done to Internet stocks, the American Stock Exchange's Internet
index is down 18 percent from its high set last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Proving once again that the market's leadership can change on a
dime, investors last week began to realize that excessive
valuations in stocks posed more risk than they could comfortably
accept. Rather than flee stocks entirely, they shifted to shares of
some companies that had been left for dead. Previously unglamorous
companies such as Allied Signal, Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing
and Smurfit-Stone Container registered impressive gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors had the idea that it's a new economy and a new stock
market and that meant you don't have to worry about the old rules
of diversification and quality,'' said Alan F. Skrainka, chief
market strageist at Edward Jones in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   No longer.
</P>
<P>
   The move away from growth stocks with high valuations and into
companies that are viewed as cheaper began last week. Market
strategists pointed to two events that gave investors pause. The
first was the European Central Bank's move on April 8 to cut
interest rates, a signal that policy makers are committed to
keeping the world on a path to economic growth by jumpstarting
Europe's economies.
</P>
<P>
   When economic growth around the world is scarce, as it has been
recently, investors retreat to stocks they know can produce good
earnings in spite of any malaise _ these are shares with hefty and
reliable profits, so-called growth stocks. Indeed, these investors
are willing to pay premiums for these profits. But when growth is
plentiful, a broader group of companies benefits and investors can
find improving profits in less expensive stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The second scare for growth-stock investors came last Monday
when Compaq Computer warned that its quarterly earnings would be
half what analysts had been expecting. This reminded traders that
technology, for all its promise, can also disappoint.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to investor concern about growth stocks in general, and
technology stocks in particular, was the news on Friday that Robert
Stansky, the manager of Fidelity Investments' Magellan fund, had
sold large positions in many hot technology stocks that had been
among his biggest holdings. Stansky moved into ``value stocks,''
more mundane shares that were trading at lower premiums to their
earnings growth rates.
</P>
<P>
   Traders noted on Monday that there were so few buyers for many
falling stocks that sellers could get out only if they accepted
prices well below the prevailing market. Some fell sharply even
though relatively few shares exchanged hands.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Companies waiting in the wings to offer their shares to the
public for the first time were likely losers in Monday's market
decline as well. Three Internet concerns, Net Perceptions Inc.,
Proxicom Inc. and Launch Media Inc., had planned initial public
offerings this week. Until investors become more hospitable to
companies like these, such offerings are likely to remain on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Strategists pointed to the effect that hordes of rapid-fire day
traders _ many of whom are relative newcomers to stocks and have
yet to experience a severe, protracted decline in stock prices _
could have on the market. In recent months, these traders have
created momentum and profits as they piled into stocks. If they are
now piling out, they may create tidal waves of selling.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a case where a lot of these stocks have some
unreasonable gains,'' said Laszlo Birinyi, who heads his own stock
research firm in Greenwich, Conn. ``Now people are starting to lock
in the gains when they can. As these stocks decline from their
highs, the movement feeds on itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime traders worry that a flood of calls from brokerage
firms will go out to stock investors on Tuesday for more funds to
prop up diminished portfolios that they have borrowed against to
buy more stocks. Customers must meet these requests, known as
margin calls, with fresh money or with cash raised by selling
stocks. If shares are sold, the market decline could accelerate.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Ameritrade, a large discount brokerage firm,
said that it had slightly higher margin calls than normal, adding
that it had no discernible problems with trading. She also said
that the brokerage firm had previously imposed higher borrowing
limits, presumably lessening the number of margin calls that would
go out to customers.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, investors could jump back into their former stock
darlings if they judge the selling to be overdone. Such a strategy
has served them well in the last five years and was especially
shrewd when the market rebounded from its correction in October.
Microsoft, for example announces its earnings on Monday. Investors
may like what they see and bid the stock back up again.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wien of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter said that the United
States stock market remains overvalued and that the broad market
averages will experience a correction, defined by traders as a
decline of 20 percent. ``What you're seeing is a resolution of
excessive valuation in the market. I expect the indexes to decline
further, but I don't think we're in a bear market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
