<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5033 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-ECON-NYT &LR;      04-19 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL BOUNCES BACK, OFFERING $1 BILLION IN DEBT FOR SALE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Brazil devalued its currency in January, the nation was
faced with rising inflation, soaring interest rates, the threat of
default and a recession. Most foreign investors crossed Brazil off
their dance cards.
</P>
<P>
   Three months later, Brazil is offering $1 billion in five-year
notes for sale this week to global investors.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians' remarkable turnaround, which caught many
investors by surprise, is a reminder of how fast things can change
in volatile emerging markets. The planned sale is also a tribute to
the skill of the new head of Brazil's central bank, Arminio Fraga,
who took over in February and helped produce the sharp drop in
interest rates and the rally in Brazil's currency that has made a
return to the global capital markets possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty amazing,'' said David Sekiguchi, head of Latin
American Strategy at J.P. Morgan Securities. ``Brazil beat the most
optimistic expectation.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it is not yet clear how strong the demand for the new
debt issue will be, the talk Monday in the corporate bond market
was positive. Early indications, though, are that prospective
investors want to be offered a premium over current yields on
existing Brazilian bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the closest maturity to the new debt _ the Brazilian
note due in 2008 _ was trading at a yield of 11.58 percent, or
almost 6.5 percentage points over the comparable U.S. States
Treasury obligation. Given that a five-year note would have a
slightly lower yield, a spread over the five-year Treasury note of
more than six percentage points would seem to provide the premium
that many investors want. That would put the yield just under 12
percent, which is high but well below where Brazilian interest
rates were at the end of February.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are comfortable with the credit,'' said Barbara Kenworthy,
portfolio manager at Prudential mutual funds. But, she added, ``we
want to see if this will come at yields higher than outstanding
paper.''
</P>
<P>
   The success of the issue is important in several ways. For one
thing, the government wants to prove to domestic investors that
foreign buyers are again interested in Brazil. Such a show of
foreign support would help lower the cost of Brazil's domestic
borrowing, which is one of the government's biggest burdens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a way to signal to the local market that the foreign
market is there once again for Brazil,'' said Jose Barrionuevo,
director of global market strategy at Lehman Brothers. ``It makes
local investors more confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Another purpose is to set up a benchmark for other Brazilian
debt. A successful sale of this government note would make it
easier for Brazilian corporations to come to market.
</P>
<P>
   The debt issue, which is being led by underwriters from Salomon
Smith Barney, a part of Citigroup, and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter,
offers investors a choice in how to buy the new five-year notes.
They can pay cash or they can exchange existing shorter-term Brady
bond issues. For Brazil, the exchange would retire some
higher-yielding debt. For example, the so-called IDU issue that
matures in 2001 was yielding about seven percentage points over
comparable Treasuries Monday, higher than the spread investors may
get on the new bond.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Swanson, portfolio manager of the Strategic Income Fund at
MFS in Boston, said he was considering buying the new five-year
notes because he thinks Brazil is ``an improving story.'' But he
said he would probably not exchange the eligible Brady bonds
because they offered a better yield.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians, according to Michael Corbat, head of Latin
American debt origination and emerging-market sales at Salomon
Smith Barney, will have a lunch in New York Wednesday for investors
where Fraga will speak. There will also be an investor conference
call and a separate meeting in Boston. The cash sale will be priced
on Thursday, and then the exchange will be set on Friday, based on
the cash price.
</P>
<P>
   There are many signs of improvement in the outlook for Brazil,
although the economy is not out of the woods. Official interest
rates were cut to 34 percent last week, the third reduction since
Fraga took over. The interest rate on Brazil's bond due in 2027
fell to 12.45 percent Monday from a high of 18.7 percent in
January. Stocks have rallied sharply, even in dollar terms. And the
nation's currency, the real, has rallied back to an exchange rate
of 1.6775 to the dollar. That is still down 28 percent from its
rate before devaluation, but it is a nice rebound from the 44
percent plunge at the currency's low point early in March.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of the bond sale Monday gave an immediate boost
to Brazilian foreign debt, with many issues rallying. But by the
end of the day, many of those had given up their gains and were
down somewhat. Traders suggested that some selling may have come in
the wake of a selloff in United States stocks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 2222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
