r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-DRAFT-SIGN-     04-19 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-DRAFT-SIGN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS TAKE TWO IN FIRST _ BUT CAN THEY SIGN THEM? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Cardinals top draft pick David Boston guaranteed
Monday he wouldn't be a holdout.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad wouldn't let me hold out,'' said Boston, of his father,
Byron, an NFL game official.
</P>
<P>
   Boston, the Ohio State wide receiver picked eighth overall,
didn't put his pledge in writing.
</P>
<P>
   Eastern Michigan offensive tackle Lonnie Shelton, the team's
other first-round pick, also said he planned on being signed before
the July 30 opening of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   History isn't on their side. Two of the team's last three
first-round picks _ Defensive ends Simeon Rice and Andre Wadsworth
_ missed all of camp and didn't sign until right before the start
of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   There are indications, however, this year will be different for
the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Team Vice President Bill Bidwill Jr. talked to Boston and
Shelton and their agents about their chances of holding out before
drafting them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're going to have problems signing those
guys,'' Bidwill Jr. said. ``Both of those kids expressed desire to
be in on time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have had success getting players signed on time
when they don't have a pick in the top five of the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, cornerback Tom Knight was picked ninth overall
and signed before training camp opened. In fact, the Cardinals were
one of the first teams to have all of their players signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knight wanted to be in on time and got in on time and got a
fair deal,'' Bidwill Jr. said.
</P>
<P>
   Also helping the Cardinals' chances of getting the players
signed before the start of camp is that Kentucky quarterback Tim
Couch, the first overall pick, already has agreed to terms with
Cleveland on a seven-year, $48 million deal.
</P>
<P>
   Couch and the Browns reached agreement before the draft, the
first time that has happened in the NFL since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, hurting Wadsworth's negotiations with the Cardinals is
that last year's No. 1 pick, Tennessee quarterback Peyton Manning,
didn't even start negotiating with Indianapolis until mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably will affect the first three picks because all are
quarterbacks,'' said Boston's agent Mitch Frankel, who accompanied
him to Tempe Monday for a news conference to introduce the top
picks.
</P>
<P>
   There could be a trickle-down effect. With Couch signed, other
players picked in the top 10 might start negotiating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Torry Holt will get done pretty quickly because St.
Louis is reasonable and is motivated to get him into camp as soon
as possible,'' said Frankel of the North Carolina State wide
receiver drafted sixth overall by the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel's last No. 1 pick, Miami of Florida defensive end Kenny
Holmes, was in Tennessee's training camp on time two years ago. But
the previous year, another of his clients, controversial running
back Lawrence Phillips of Nebraska, was late for the Rams' camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a unique situation,'' Frankel said of a complicated
contract in which Phillips' contract was tied to him staying out of
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel said he didn't have a problem with Bidwill Jr. asking
pre-draft questions about the team's ability to sign Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made it clear to us that he didn't want to see a holdout
and said, `Do you forsee that happening?' '' Frankel said. ``We
told him we don't want that to happen, and I would have asked the
same question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always prided myself on being reasonable. . . . As long
as the Cardinals (are) the same way, I don't forsee any problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelton, taken 21st overall, likely can't afford to be a holdout
if he wants to compete for the starting left tackle job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts an offensive lineman more than any other position to
miss training camp,'' Bidwill Jr. said. ``Look at what happened to
Orlando Pace (of the Rams) two years ago. There are tons of
examples.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelton's agent, Lamont Smith, who also represented former
Cardinals offensive tackle Lomas Brown, said he understands how
important it is for rookie offensive linemen to be in camp on time.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, his client, offensive tackle Tra Thomas of Florida
State, picked 11th overall by the Eagles, signed well before camp
opened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to get tackles in on time because of the
cohesiveness of the offensive line,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Also helping the Cardinals' negotiating position with Shelton is
that Oakland and the New York Giants drafted offensive tackles 18th
and 19th overall, respectively. As a result, Shelton's contract
will be slotted after those tackles.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said when he talked to the Cardinals before the draft,
they inquired about ``taking certain things off the negotiating
table. We took the positon that we thought we could get (the deal)
done, but we didn't want to take the things off the table.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the player picked 21st overall, wide receiver Randy
Moss of Minnesota, received a signing bonus of $2 million and an
average salary of $1.092.5 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   The eighth-pick overall, defensive end Greg Ellis of North
Carolina, received a six-year, $11.5 million deal, including a $5.4
million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Contracts are expected to increase 8 percent from a year ago. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
