<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MARTONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CONGO OR KOSOVO, A COMPULSION TO HELP 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They tell each other it's because of the ``3Ms'' _ in
other words, they're convinced they have the characteristics of
martyrs, misfits and masochists. They see each other at the world's
most horrific disasters. They dig wells, rehydrate children with
intravenous fluid and live on adrenaline. Kosovo (and Rwanda and
Uganda and Congo) are how they make their living.
</P>
<P>
   So when Gerald Martone, a registered nurse, was talking to
refugees over the weekend in northern Albania, he wasn't all that
stunned when a fellow rescue worker ran up behind him and engulfed
him in a bear hug. ``And you try to remember, where did I last see
him?'' Martone said Monday by phone from Tirana. ``Was that
Liberia? Was that Sierra Leone?''
</P>
<P>
   Martone, who considers himself a masochist and a martyr but not
a misfit, is the emergency response director of the International
Rescue Committee, the world's largest nonsectarian refugee agency.
The committee was Albert Einstein's idea, to help people escape
from the Nazis; the theologian Reinhold Niebuhr helped found it.
</P>
<P>
   When things are calm, Martone lives in the Murray Hill section
of Manhattan and works out of the committee's headquarters there,
where he fidgeted through an interview two weeks ago. (Too much to
do, and he wanted to get to Albania.) When things are not calm, and
they usually aren't, Martone, 42, is in a satisfied frenzy, a
leader of a band of people who move from crisis to international
crisis. Right now Kosovo is the center of his world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm compelled by it,'' Martone said. ``For the lay person who
sees these images of Kosovo, it must evoke tremendous frustration
and a sense of guilt. For me, I just see, `Wow, we can make a
difference here.' I know what to do in this situation. People don't
have to die.''
</P>
<P>
   Martone has worked in a dozen war zones over the past 20 years,
and becomes excited about things like latrines. In fact, a snapshot
of one he built in Congo hangs on his office wall. ``Best thing in
the world to do to save lives,'' he said. ``Very unphotogenic.''
</P>
<P>
   But he has learned how quickly latrines can turn around a
cholera outbreak, like the one he saw in the Goma region of Zaire
in August 1994, when 2,000 people were dying each day. ``I remember
walking along with people pulling at your pants, saying, `Help
me,''' Martone said.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing Martone has seen in Albania is as bad, which does
nothing to diminish the horror stories from refugees who have
flooded across the border. He has heard of children who suffocated
in the packed trucks and trailers, and has seen pictures they've
drawn of their burning homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a horrible story of one family who had their injured
father hidden under a pile of clothing, with a kind of snorkel for
air,'' Martone said. ``It took so long to get to the checkpoint
that by the time they finally did pass through, they unburied him
and he had died.''
</P>
<P>
   Martone arrived in Tirana late last week to oversee his staff of
150, locals and expatriates, who are building dormitory-style
housing for refugees in towns throughout Albania. He lives in an
apartment with friends, but spends most of his time at the office,
a couple of fifth-floor rooms in a back alley of Tirana. The
weather is wet and cold, yet his spirits are good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on a bit of a high, I guess,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What turns someone into a 20-year relief worker? Martone said
that for him, it was his father, who designed uniforms for the Army
and who went to Vietnam when Martone was 10. ``I think he managed
logistics or something,'' Martone said. The elder Martone sent back
Super-8 film of primitive living conditions, which made an
impression on his son. ``I was appalled at the disparity,'' Martone
said.
</P>
<P>
   Right after graduating from the University of Massachusetts at
Lowell, in 1979, Martone went into the Peace Corps, to Liberia,
where he built latrines and worked in a clinic. Five months after
arriving, he was held up at gunpoint in a coup, thrown into the
back of a truck, then driven around a chaotic Monrovia, the
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Martone can still remember the bloodshot eyes of his captors.
``It was the most frightening thing that's ever happened to me,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Martone was eventually freed, and got right back on the horse _
if anything, the incident propelled him with even more purpose into
dangerous relief work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freud would say it's repetition compulsion, that people feel
compelled to repeat powerful emotional experiences,'' Martone said.
He passed up medical school _ he says his parents think he's ``a
little quirky'' _ and decided to become a nurse. ``In the Peace
Corps, I saw what nurses were able to do,'' Martone said. ``It was
nothing less than dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Martone is divorced (a sign in his office says ``Get a Life
Gerry''), and has a 7-year-old son who lives in Boston. He also has
a specialty in clinical hypnosis and is, in fact, a compelling and
slightly hypnotic personality. He does excellent magic tricks, like
taking out the little ball in his computer mouse and making it
disappear if you ask.
</P>
<P>
   He is clear-eyed about the impact of his work: ``A lot of people
reflect back on the futility of it, that we're making such a small
dent in such an enormous problem,'' he said. ``That's why so many
people in this field find one person they can grab on to, the one
refugee child who they go and bring an apple to. You measure your
success in very small increments.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
