<HEADLINE>
VAN BREDA KOLFF HAS BIG PLANS FOR WAVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU _ The standard for men's basketball in the West Coast
Conference used to be Pepperdine. Now it is Gonzaga.
</P>
<P>
   Jan van Breda Kolff, introduced as Pepperdine's new head men's
basketball coach Monday morning, said he wants the bar back.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a unique situation,'' van Breda Kolff said. ``(We
have) a very good basketball team coming back.If the work ethic is
there and the determination is there, now it's just getting to that
next step: getting past Gonzaga and winning the league
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga won the WCC title this season, upset Stanford and
Florida in the NCAA Tournament and was one win away from the Final
Four before its run ended against eventual national champion
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine went 19-13 last season and finished second in the WCC
under head coach Lorenzo Romar, who resigned in March to take the
head position at Saint Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Van Breda Kolff said he wants to return the program to the
prominence it had from 1981-93, when coaches Jim Harrick and Tom
Asbury guided the Waves to a combined eight conference titles. The
Waves were selected to play in the NIT this season, marking their
first postseason appearance in five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's right on the cusp of being back where it was, back in the
days when Jim and Tom were here,'' van Breda Kolff said. ``That's
our goal. Other teams in our conference will use Pepperdine as a
barometer.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine athletic director John Watson, who was in charge of
the search committee, said van Breda Kolff was selected because of
his experience, his background and his character.
</P>
<P>
   Van Breda Kolff is the first coach Watson has hired since he was
named AD last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a man, in my judgment, who met all the standards we were
looking for,'' Watson said. ``A man who is committed to the mission
of this university, a strong Christian individual, a man of
character and integrity and a man who knows the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Pepperdine, van Breda Kolff was the head coach at
Vanderbilt for six seasons and Cornell for two.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt had six new players last year, and the Commodores
struggled to a 14-15 record. Lack of chemistry or experience isn't
the case at Pepperdine _ the Waves return four starters and have
top recruit Kevin Bradley projected as the starting point guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do a lot of damage with the team we have,'' said Kelvin
Gibbs, a sophomore forward and the team's leading returning scorer.
</P>
<P>
   Van Breda Kolff said he uses a system that features an up-tempo
offense and a pressing and trapping defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to create offense off our defense,'' he said.
``Watching the film from last year, I think there is a lot of
athleticism here. I think we can be a team that can score more than
last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs said he played van Breda Kolff's style in high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will bring back a lot of memories,'' Gibbs said.
</P>
<P>
   Van Breda Kolff said he is going to use the next few days to
meet with returning players, contact the incoming recruits and form
a staff. He said he wants to have at least one assistant with ties
to the Los Angeles area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
