<HEADER>
A5057 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEECEE-CONGRESS-NYT &LR;      04-19 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEECEE-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPITAL INVOKES FRAMERS IN VOTING-RIGHTS SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``Relief, 200 years late, can be ordered,'' the
lawyer for the District of Columbia told a special three-judge
court Monday in arguing in its lawsuit against the federal
government that residents of the city should be allowed to vote for
members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, John M. Ferren, the city's corporation counsel,
invoked the founding fathers, saying that Patrick Henry, Alexander
Hamilton and James Madison all spoke, in the convention that drew
up the Constitution, in favor of such voting rights for residents
of the capital.
</P>
<P>
   When the presiding judge, Louis F. Oberdorfer of the federal
district court here, noted Monday that no less an eminence than
Chief Justice John Marshall had disagreed with that position,
Ferren conceded the point but argued that Marshall had not been at
the Constitutional Convention.
</P>
<P>
   The 23rd Amendment gave the city's residents the right to vote
for president, and federal laws have established local elections.
But lawyers for the city argued Monday that its 500,000 residents
were being unconstitutionally deprived of their right to vote for
congressional representation, a right residents had for 11 years
until Maryland and Virginia, the states from which the District of
Columbia was carved, took it away in 1800.
</P>
<P>
   The District of Columbia is represented by a nonvoting delegate
in the House of Representatives, Eleanor Holmes Norton.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge panel was appointed to hear the case because of
the complex nature of the issues. Whatever it rules, it is certain
to be appealed to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The status quo is being defended by the Justice Department,
although Attorney General Janet Reno has said that she supports
voting rights. Because President Clinton and other federal
officials are defendants in the case, Justice Department lawyers
are defending them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Constitution leaves us no choice,'' John R. Tyler, the
senior trial counsel in the civil division of the Justice
Department, argued in court Monday. ``The framers intended that
representation in Congress be reserved to the people of the several
states.''
</P>
<P>
   The city contends that while it is not a state, its residents
enjoy virtually all other constitutional rights, like trial by
jury.
</P>
<P>
   The government said it was opposing the suit only on
constitutional grounds, because Article 1 says congressional
representatives would be elected ``by the people of the several
states'' and it was not taking a stand on a political solution to
the question.
</P>
<P>
   The government contends that the right for District of Columbia
residents to vote for congressional representation must be won
through constitutional amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Another member of the panel, Judge Merrick B. Garland of the
U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit, raised
political questions about the case.
</P>
<P>
   If the District of Columbia sent one person to the House and two
to the Senate, Garland asked Ferren, would that not dilute the
power of the congressional delegations from the states and lead
them to oppose it?
</P>
<P>
   Ferren said the nation dealt with such dilutions each time it
expanded, from 13 to 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   The third member of the panel is Judge Colleen Kollar-Kotelly of
the federal district court.
</P>
<P>
   In his summation, Ferren said: ``We are talking about the most
precious, the most fundamental right that any of us can have, the
right to vote. This right is at the very heart of a government we
fought a Revolutionary War to gain, a Civil War to protect, and
world wars in which men and women of the District of Columbia, like
men and women from all over this country, died to keep.
</P>
<P>
   ``But unlike every other adult citizen of the 50 states _
indeed, unlike men and women with whom we work side by side every
day, who live in Maryland and Virginia _ we don't have the right to
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   The ceremonial courtroom in the federal courthouse was jammed
with supporters of the voting rights suit, many of them voicing
their agreement as the lawyers spoke.
</P>
<P>
   When one of the principal lawyers bringing the suit, George
LaRoche, made a popular point, there was applause from the
spectators. Oberdorfer pounded his desk twice for order, using his
fist instead of a gavel.
</P>
<P>
   Ferren concluded his argument by declaring: ``If the framers
were here today, I believe they would be astonished that the
half-million citizens of our nation's capital _ unlike any other
capital of a democracy in the world _ do not have the right to vote
for those who govern them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
