<DOCNO> NYT19990419.0495 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5061 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALON-SFCHRON &LR;      04-19 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Salon Caps Changes With IPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Dan Fost &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Salon.com will soon see if a literary reputation and online cachet
lead to stock market riches.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Web publisher of literature, commentary and
news filed yesterday to sell stock to the public. It hopes to raise
at least $26 million by offering 24 percent of the company.
</P>
<P>
   The move caps a rush of news out of Salon in recent weeks _ new
financial backing, a national advertising campaign, a redesigned
Web site, the acquisition of the online community the WELL and,
most notably, the changing of its name from Salon Magazine to
Salon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, companies with a ``.com'' at the end of their name
are commanding high stock market valuations, even if they don't
generate any profits.
</P>
<P>
   Salon certainly fits that model. According to the filing, the
company has lost $10.5 million since its inception in July 1995,
and expects continued losses in the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   In the last nine months of last year, Salon brought in $2.1
million in revenue _ nearly triple the revenues for the same period
in 1997 _ but it lost $4.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials declined to comment, citing the ``quiet
period'' mandated by the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The company relies on banner ads and sponsorships for 93 percent
of its revenue, and it has a relatively small number of
advertisers. For instance, just one advertiser, Borders bookstores,
accounted for 18 percent of Salon's revenues in the nine-month
period. Salon plans to develop electronic commerce sponsorships, as
well as add shopping capabilities to its site.
</P>
<P>
   The filing also noted that Salon may publish controversial
content that could irritate advertisers. The site gained wide
notoriety for its decision last year to break the news that U.S.
Representative Henry Hyde, R-Ohio, _ a leader in the movement to
impeach President Clinton _ had an extramarital affair 30 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Many money-losing Internet firms have been able to generate huge
valuations under the theory that more people will be online as the
Internet becomes easier to use, and the companies that establish
Internet brands early will be poised to make significant profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time will have to tell if this is all insanity or if spending
money to build a brand is money well spent,'' said Ben Holmes,
president of IPOPros.com, an independent research firm in Boulder,
Colo.
</P>
<P>
   In an online world in which stories are short and news breaks
fast, Salon is almost an anomaly: A site that publishes thoughtful
commentary and well-known writers. It's been compared to the New
Yorker or the Atlantic Monthly, neither of which has a significant
online presence. Salon's only real online competition comes from
Slate, which is published by Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Salon was founded by a group of former San Francisco Examiner
editors. David Talbot, the Examiner's former arts and entertainment
editor, is chairman and editor in chief, overseeing a site that
publishes writing on travel, technology, arts, media, books,
politics and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Salon announced it had raised $15 million from a
variety of private investors. It also announced the hiring of achief financial officer and a vice president of sales, and it named
legendary television producer Norman Lear, the creator of ``All in
the Family,'' to its board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Salon plans to sell 2.5 million shares for between $10.50 and
$13.50 per share, which would raise between $26.25 million and
$33.75 million. A price of $10.50 per share would value the company
at $112.35 million, while the higher valuation would make it worth
$144.45 million.
</P>
<P>
   Salon's underwriters are W.R. Hambrecht + Co. and Daiwa
Securities America Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The initial public offering will provide a major test of
Hambrecht's new OpenIPO format, in which average investors get to
bid on shares before the offering price is set. While many hot
Internet offerings open at low prices but then soar when trading
begins, the OpenIPO system theoretically should bring offering
prices in line with the actual trading prices.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only Ravenswood Winery has used the system and that
company, which went public this month, has held far steadier than
the more volatile Internet offerings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
