r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      04-19 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Why the Time Could Be Right for Considering Sector Rotation
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Mark Veverka &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Isn't it about time that you finally have that discussion with your
teenage kids about, you know, um, sector rotation?
</P>
<P>
   Better that you do this before they learn about it on the
streets. It's time for tough love. Somebody has to tell junior to
log off and listen up: Not all overpriced technology stocks can go
up forever. Sooner or later, cheap stocks with wads of cash and
smart management are eventually going to lead the market.
</P>
<P>
   It is the unpleasant obligation of parents to deliver this
painful message to the ones they love. Sector rotation, of course,
is one of those $2 Wharton phrases that means investors are
shifting their preferences from certain groups of stocks that were
once on fire to others that had been sucking wind.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, when institutions start pulling their money out of
Microsoft and Merck and begin plunking it down on Boeing, Allied
Signal and Minnesota, Mining and Manufacturing _ as they have been
over the past couple of days _ time may be of the essence to talk
to the kids.
</P>
<P>
   As noted last week in this column, cyclical stocks _ those that
are sensitive to economic factors such as interest rates _ caught
an updraft last week. And they continued to surge northward
yesterday into the teeth of a fierce Nasdaq sell-off as the
tech-heavy index suffered its second-biggest point drop in history.
</P>
<P>
   The abrupt shift from sexy growth stocks to boring value plays
is definitely real, but will it be a long-term relationship or just
a tease?
</P>
<P>
   Byron Wien, the chief investment strategist at Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter, thinks the ``big move'' to cyclical stocks isn't over.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that's just one expert's opinion. Wall Street
strategists and money managers are divided on this one. Many are
still picking up the pieces from yesterday's avalanche on the
Nasdaq Stock Market, wondering if their favorite names in
technology won't rebound faster than a mediocre Web site can go
public.
</P>
<P>
   There is some concern that the shift had been so quick and
pronounced that cyclicals might peak early and technology would
recover as nicely as it did after last August's ruble ruse. But
Wien doesn't buy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (cyclicals) have a ways to go, (and) I think the
upward trend will broaden to include small- and mid-cap stocks,''
Wien stated in a research note yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   So, what are you gonna do? Buy a little America Online on the
dip or take the value plunge and buy cheap manufacturing stocks?
</P>
<P>
   Wien is telling his clients to start looking for attractive
small- and mid-size stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the U.S. economy turns in another strong quarter, it should
be favorable for cyclicals and smaller stocks. Managements of
cyclical companies focus on revenues and therefore benefit from a
strong economic environment. Since these stocks trade relatively
thinly, a little money flowing into them tends to make a big
impact,'' Wien says.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the strategist points out that the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index remains about 25 percent ``overvalued'' according
to Morgan Stanley Dean Witter's economic models.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, he ``still expects a correction in the
not-too-distant future, (and) this may become the firm foundation
for a change in (sector) leadership,'' Wien says.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, nobody said that sector rotation would be pretty. As loyal
Street Smart readers may recall, Wien's counterpart at PaineWebber,
Ed Kerschner, also predicted a market correction for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   One of the scenarios is that the shift into cyclicals might
precede a minor correction of about 5 percent, setting the table
for another bull run fueled, this time, by small- and mid-cap
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   But the small-cap bulls aren't holding their breath. They
desperately want to believe. For more than four years, the
Lilliputians have been getting trampled in the land of the giants,
says William Edwards, president of Palo Alto Investors, a $60
million small-cap hedge fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are pleasant things for us to hear, but we haven't seen
any evidence of it yet,'' Edwards says.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the undervalued stocks discovered in recent days have
been large-cap cyclicals. Meantime, small caps have been on the
sidelines for so long that even their most ardent fans are reticent
to declare that the tide is turning. (Small caps are widely
considered to be stocks with valuations under $1 billion.)
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index, a primary benchmark for small-cap
stocks, has seen about a 10 percent annualized return since April
1994, compared to about a 26 percent yearly return for the Dow
Jones industrials and a 27 percent performance by the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a staggering period of underperformance (for small
stocks). I`ve never experienced anything like this in my career,''
Edwards says.
</P>
<P>
   With the nudge of a stronger global economy, that's nothing that
a little sector rotation couldn't fix.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
