<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-CHALLENGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLE MEDIA SOFTWARE CHALLENGES 2 RIVALS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CUPERTINO, Calif. _ In a direct challenge to both the Microsoft
Corp. and Real Networks Inc., Apple Computer on Monday introduced a
new version of its Quicktime multimedia software designed to permit
computer users to receive video and audio programming over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The distribution of multimedia content is emerging as one of the
hottest businesses on the Internet. Last week in Hollywood,
Microsoft announced its own technology in the field, known as MS
Audio 4.0, and the International Business Machines Corp. and Sony
Inc. announced an agreement to make their competing systems
compatible with each other.
</P>
<P>
   All three companies, plus a handful of other developers, large
and small, are vying to produce the technology that will ultimately
be adopted as the standard by the recording industry. That industry
is deeply concerned about the rapid growth of a vibrant cottage
industry around the MP3 audio standard, a format for storing audio
files.
</P>
<P>
   Because MP3 has no built-in copyright protection schemes, the
recording industry views it as a serious threat; hundreds of
thousands of MP3 users are already exchanging music over the
Internet without paying musicians or record companies.
</P>
<P>
   Multimedia programs _ incorporating audio, video, and computer
graphics _ can be played on computers in two basic ways: streaming
media, which delivers the program as the user watches or listens,
and downloaded media, which is delivered in its entirety to the
user's hard drive and then viewed or heard. Programming can
originate from television or radio broadcasts or from recorded
music.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the battle over the market for Internet viewing of
multimedia presentations has largely been between Microsoft, which
has built many of the most popular formats into its Windows Media
Player, and Real Networks, maker of the Realplayer streaming
software. However, analysts said Monday that Apple's strategy would
probably make it a three-way race.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to announcing an initial public test, or beta, for
Quicktime 4, Apple said it would offer software that would make it
possible for server computers using its Mac OS X operating system
to distribute multimedia content over the Internet. They said the
server software would support a streaming technology that has been
defined as a standard by an Internet engineering task force backed
by many companies.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, at the National Association of Broadcasters meeting
in Las Vegas, Apple executives said Monday that its new server
software would have the support of several key hardware
manufacturers, including Cisco Systems, IBM, Silicon Graphics Inc.
and Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   The result will be relatively inexpensive server computers that
will allow independent artists or small businesses to offer
programming to large audiences over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts said Monday that Apple should have a
significant advantage in the market for Internet multimedia
software since much of the multimedia material already offered on
line was originally created in the Quicktime format.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on the media,'' said Andrew Gore, editor in chief
of Macworld magazine. ``For movies, they have a tremendous
advantage. However, for live video, Microsoft has made a
significant inroad.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple officials said Monday that the company's strategy was
different from those of both Real Networks, which charges a
licensing fee for its server software, and Microsoft, which offers
its server technology only on the proprietary Windows NT operating
system. Because Apple is releasing the source code for its server
software, it will be simple for organizations that want to transmit
multimedia material to adapt their own systems. Phil Schiller,
Apple's vice president for worldwide marketing, said the company
would make an effort to insure that the new Quicktime software
incorporates a wide variety of different media formats known as
``codecs'' (for compression-decompression), bodies of software
coding that transform audio and video programming into digital
format for transmission and translate it back on the user's
computer. ``We support more codecs than anyone in the world,''
Schiller said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in recent months the competition in the streaming media
market has shifted to a battle to demonstrate the highest quality
in codecs. While it is hard to tell the differences when one is
using a modem that delivers speeds of 56,000 bits a second,
Schiller said, the rapid shift among consumers to high-speed cable
modems and digital subscriber lines, is making distinctions more
apparent.
</P>
<P>
   The Quicktime 4 viewer can be downloaded free by both Windows
and Macintosh users from Apple's Web site. A $29.95 version lets
users create and edit digital content. And separately, Apple said
Monday that it had begun shipping professional video authoring
software.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
