<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5065 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     04-19 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: 2 RUNNERS, 2 MIND-SETS, 2 LETDOWNS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., N.J.)  (mk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ By the time Bill Rodgers reached the top of Heartbreak
Hill, his legs were fading and, much worse, his eyes were lying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started seeing flashing lights,'' he said. ``That's the sure
sign of dehydration.''
</P>
<P>
   That was also his cue to exit the Boston Marathon on Monday,
stage left, into a Red Cross tent that just happened to be
stationed there, like the last exit on the highway to Hades. It
wasn't quite the Eliot Lounge on Commonwealth Ave. _ a bygone
establishment on whose premises Rodgers once quit this famous race
_ but when those body alarms start sounding at the advanced
runner's age of 51, the judicious choice would seem to be the bed
over the beer.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers, knowing what awaited him if he insisted on finishing
the last five miles, told himself, ``I've dropped out here
before,'' and so it was that he did once more.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, he had not returned to Boston just to run
recreationally, any more than Wayne Gretzky played hockey to glide
around the ice. Rodgers did jog and wave to the crowd in 1996, the
centennial race, and that was fun but that gets old. He could do
that when he's 61. They call the contenders elite runners in this
grueling sport. When the legs go, the self-image does not.
</P>
<P>
   This time, having not run a competitive marathon since 1992, the
patriarch of American marathoners came with a stopwatch and a
dream.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers was aiming for a 2-hour-30-minute finish, an over-50
record and a rare yelp of Yankee exultation in a sport he owned
long before it became the national pastime of Kenya. He won here
for the first time in 1975, when Monday's winner, Joseph Chebet,
was jogging to nursery school in the Kenyan bush. Rodgers won four
Boston Marathons, four more in New York, and Monday's was his 52nd
overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the good over 40 and over 50 runners come to it
late,'' he said. ``My body was trying to tell me something, that
those 52 marathons have taken a toll. So maybe trying to set a
record on a sunny day on this particular course wasn't a good
idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe LeMay could've told him that and saved him the pain. Then
again, LeMay, 32, represents the contemporary American marathoner,
whose objectives are more associated with surviving such a course
than actually defeating it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you get through Boston without crashing and burning,
that's a good day,'' he said, perhaps coining a modern American
mantra.
</P>
<P>
   Out of Danbury, Conn., by way of Ridgewood High School in New
Jersey and Princeton University, LeMay took the early-morning ride
to the start in Hopkinton, Mass., hoping to run his fifth marathon
in the vicinity of 2:13 or 2:14. He thought that a little
cooperation from his cranky back combined with one lucky break _
like the disappearance of the Kenyan bus _ might have put him in
the run for the prize money.
</P>
<P>
   Those aspirations went awry with the weather. ``I made a promise
to myself that if it got close to 70 degrees, I would shoot for
2:16,'' LeMay said. He finished at 2:16:11, in 13th place, the
first American to cross. In Chicago last October, they awarded
prize money for this distinction, but, as LeMay said, ``Two-sixteen
is not bad but not very good considering the rest of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not exactly a fair fight, for several reasons, one of
them being that the Kenyans train together and don't spend their
weekdays in the employ of a computer company, as does LeMay. He
fiddles with a mouse for 40 hours, runs 120 miles and, in his spare
time, takes an honest look in the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to say the only reason they're so much better is that
we work, but it's not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Having concentrated on the 10,000 meters for much of his career,
LeMay said he always wanted to try marathons after watching Rodgers
as a kid. ``Most kids were looking at football and baseball
players,'' he said. ``For me, it was Bill. I've always wanted to
shoot for 2:10 because that's what he was running when he was
winning. For me, he's the man who set the standard.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers once gave LeMay a pep talk after a disastrous 1993
marathon debut in New York. The next piece of counsel could be that
standards are not set by playing it safe. LeMay held back and wound
up admitting his result was ``not very good.'' A smiling Rodgers
was helped into the interview room by a Red Cross volunteer and
made it clear there was no other way.
</P>
<P>
   They were 20 years and a generational mind-set apart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
