<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shades of Anna Sui
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lots of designers have fragrances, but how many have
a full line of color cosmetics? There's Yves Saint Laurent. There's
Versace. And now there is Anna Sui, who is introducing her
collection of lipstick, nail polish, eyeshadow, mascara and more
Wednesday at Saks Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   She will be there at 12:30 p.m. to show customers her wide range
of colors (51 for nails alone, including 21 shades of purple, her
favorite color). The products are scented with tea rose, one of Ms.
Sui's favorite flowers. In keeping with her rock-and-roll attitude,
the powder puffs are purple.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I really wanted to do was bring fun back into makeup,''
Ms. Sui said. ``I have an obsession with buying makeup. I'll buy
something because it's an unusual color or because I like the
packaging. And I reuse the containers for jewelry.''
</P>
<P>
   The line, which has been sold in Japan since last fall, is one
of the three best-selling brands at Isetan, the department store.
</P>
<P>
   There is also an Anna Sui fragrance, which she describes as ``a
floral with an incense-y powder base, what they call a floriental
in the fragrance world.'' It, too, is purple and comes in a bottle
with a black lacquerlike frame. Fragrance prices range from $35 to
$145; makeup, from $13 to $35.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed to Paper
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sotheby's May 3 fashion sale is called ``Pulp
Fashion,'' a quizzical name until you stop to realize that paper is
made from pulp. ``The idea is anything related to paper and
fashion,'' said Tiffany Dubin, the head of the auction house's
fashion department. ``We originally called it `Paper Fashion,' but
`Pulp' gave us a little more leeway. One of the things we try to do
in each sale is have a sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   So, in addition to books, photographs and illustrations, the
auction will include items like a dress made of Bergdorf Goodman
gift cards, a jeweled shoe made of paper, a pair of Calvin Klein
briefs mounted on cardboard by Andy Warhol, cardboard replicas of
the Hermes Kelly bag, colorful paper dresses from the 1960s, men's
``chinos'' made of manila envelopes, and vintage luggage covered
with paper travel stickers.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the surprising lots I expect to be a killer,'' Ms.
Dubin said, ``is No. 129, a rough print of Marilyn Monroe in a
Jackie wig photographed by Bert Stern. Some negatives from the
shoot turned up a few weeks ago at the 26th Street flea market, and
everyone went wild.''
</P>
<P>
   The picture is expected to go for $2,500 to $3,500.
</P>
<P>
   Intermix Branches Out
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Intermix, the trendy boutique that started in
Manhattan's Flatiron district in 1993, attracting a customer base
of models and young career women, and branched out to upper Madison
Avenue last winter, plans to go national. Khajak Keledjian, who
owns the stores with Haro Kaldjian (they're brothers, but spell
their surnames differently), said Monday that they were planning to
open five more stores in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   The first three will be in South Miami Beach, Seattle and
Dallas. ``There will definitely be a store this fall in one of
those cities, though I can't say which,'' Keledjian said.
</P>
<P>
   As might be expected, the Intermix at 1003 Madison Ave. (77th
Street) gets a more sophisticated, more demanding customer than the
one at 125 Fifth Ave. (19th Street), Keledjian said. ``We get a lot
of mothers and daughters shopping together,'' he said of the uptown
location, ``and a lot of customers coming from other states. We
have a broader range of designers uptown, more higher end. There's
more attention to accessories, and the shoe area is a store within
a store.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the designers carried uptown are John Bartlett, Alberta
Ferretti, Rebecca Danenberg, Tracy Feith, Paul &AMP; Joe, and Isabel
Marant. There are accessories by Kate Spade and shoes by Jimmy Choo
and Tony Valentine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
