<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-QWEST-610&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELLSOUTH AGREES TO ACQUIRE 10 PERCENT OF QWEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeking to expand into data communications, BellSouth Corp. said
Monday that it had agreed to acquire 10 percent of Qwest
Communications International Inc., the No. 4 long-distance carrier,
for about $3.5 billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is perhaps the most important strategic move for
BellSouth, one of the biggest local telephone companies in the
United States, since it split from AT&AMP;T Corp. in 1984. It is also
BellSouth's first major response to the wave of deal-making that
has swept the communications industry since passage of the
Telecommunications Act of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth agreed to the investment as part of a broad
partnership that would give it access to Qwest's nationwide
fiber-optic network and that would give Qwest better access to
BellSouth's client base in the Southeast. In BellSouth, Qwest is
also set to gain perhaps the largest customer for its long-distance
network, while BellSouth is set to exploit Qwest's growing
expertise in offering advanced data services.
</P>
<P>
   The deal could help BellSouth retain big corporate customers
that are looking for integrated packages of local, long-distance
and data services _ packages that local carriers like BellSouth
have had difficulty providing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a significant step in our objective of becoming the
premier data communications provider to our customers,'' Duane
Ackerman, the BellSouth chairman, said in a statement. ``This
relationship allows our customers to enjoy the range of benefits
from a comprehensive set of Internet and broad-band digital
solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal is the second this year between a Bell local phone
company and a long-distance carrier. In February, SBC
Communications, which has agreed to buy Ameritech Corp., said it
would acquire up to 10 percent of the communications unit of
Williams Cos. for as much as $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the Qwest-BellSouth pact may have broader implications, and
not just because of the larger financial value. BellSouth has long
been thought of as a potential acquirer of Sprint Corp., the No. 3
long-distance carrier, and though the agreement announced Monday
does not explicitly preclude such a move, Ackerman said that his
main priority was making the alliance with Qwest a success.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Nacchio, chief executive of Qwest, said in an interview
that it was reasonable to think that BellSouth's investing in a
competing long-distance company would not help the BellSouth-Qwest
venture succeed.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the agreement, Daniel Reingold, the chief
telecommunications analyst at Merrill Lynch, released a short
report on the implications for Sprint titled ``Left Out in the
Cold?''
</P>
<P>
   Sprint shares fell $2.5625, to $97.4375. Shares of IXC
Communications Inc., another long-distance carrier that had been
considered a potential acquisition candidate for BellSouth, fell
$3.375, to $40.875.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, BellSouth shares rose 68.75 cents, to $41.875.
Qwest shares traded as high as $92.125 in the morning before
closing unchanged at $82.
</P>
<P>
   The early move in Qwest's stock appeared to reflect BellSouth's
agreement to pay $94.50 a share for its 10 percent investment in
Qwest, a premium of roughly 15 percent over Qwest's closing price
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   About 55 percent of the shares BellSouth agreed to buy, worth
about $1.93 billion, would be newly issued by Qwest. The remaining
45 percent, worth about $1.57 billion, would be sold by Anschutz
Co., Qwest's principal owner.
</P>
<P>
   That would leave Philip Anschutz, the reclusive oil and railroad
magnate, in control of about 40 percent of Qwest. Nacchio said
Anschutz had agreed to sell some of his shares partly out of a
desire to turn his paper profits into cash.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As with the other Bells, federal rules prohibit BellSouth from
selling long-distance service to its core customers until the
company convinces regulators that its local markets are open to
competitors _ a test that no Bell company has yet passed. The rules
cap Bell investments in long-distance operators at 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with Qwest provides that once BellSouth wins entry to
the long-distance market, it will get a seat on the Qwest board and
the right to increase its stake in the company to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this deal, Duane Ackerman has said, `We're here to stay;
we're here to play, and we are going to be a force, not only
domestically but internationally,''' said Phil Asmundson, head of
communications and media accounting practice at Deloitte &AMP; Touche.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has invested heavily in Latin America, while Qwest has
formed a joint venture with the Dutch telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   Asmundson said he saw the deal Monday as just a prelude to a
full-blown merger between BellSouth and Qwest once BellSouth is
allowed into the long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe by any stretch of the imagination that this is
it; this is just the beginning of the dance,'' he said. Qwest, he
added, ``is a company that was born and bred to be bought.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal leaves U S West as the only Baby Bell without an equity
alliance with a long-distance operation. Bell Atlantic Corp. has
agreed to merge with GTE Corp., which itself owns part of the Qwest
network.
</P>
<P>
   The Bells are allowed to sell long-distance service in
connection with new businesses like wireless phone service.
BellSouth currently uses AT&AMP;T for many of its long-distance needs,
but BellSouth said Monday that it would begin to move as much of
its traffic as was feasible onto Qwest systems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
