<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SIXERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE AGAIN, EWING MISSES AND KNICKS LOSE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ In a very physical game against the Philadelphia
76ers, the Knicks were bumped and pushed three spots out of the
playoff standing Monday night with a 72-67 loss at First Union
Center.
</P>
<P>
   It was their fourth loss in a row and dropped them to .500 with
a 21-21 record. The Knicks had a chance to tie the game after
making up an 8-point, fourth-quarter deficit. But with his team
trailing by 69-67, Patrick Ewing's jumper landed off the mark with
21.8 seconds left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was hope when Theo Ratliff missed two free throws
with 21 seconds left. But on his second miss, the rebound slipped
past Larry Johnson and made its way into the hands of Allen
Iverson, who was fouled and made 1 of 2 free throws with 16.6
seconds remaining to provide a 3-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   After a chaotic possession, Allan Houston rushed a 3-pointer
with 4.4 seconds to go. It missed badly and bounced over the
backboard. The 76ers' Eric Snow then hit two free throws to put the
game away.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, who did not score in the second half, finished 4 for 13
for 12 points. Latrell Sprewell scored 16 points and Ewing had 11
on 3-for-8 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Geiger led the 76ers with 22 points and Iverson added 20.
</P>
<P>
   The 76ers were not the easy prey they had been in their two
previous games against the Knicks. Instead of falling apart every
time Iverson shimmied and shook and missed a jumper, the 76ers used
a very active and agile defense, led by the shot-blocking efforts
of Ratliff, and blended Geiger into the offense.
</P>
<P>
   The twosome propelled the 76ers to a lead in the opening minutes
of the game that they would not relinquish in the first half. To
punctuate the first half, the Knicks' defense left Iverson wide
open for a 3-pointer at the buzzer that gave the 76ers a 44-39
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The 76ers came out in the third quarter and hit the Knicks with
a couple of quick baskets to take a 48-41 lead. But then, on the
effort of two steals, a 3-pointer and a layin on the break by
Charlie Ward, the Knicks were able to make up some ground and tied
the game at 50-50 with 4:25 left in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   After watching the 76ers block shots, Chris Dudley sprang up in
the paint and swatted away a runner by Larry Hughes, who had gotten
away with that shot twice before. The Knicks looked energized by
that play, but were unable to harness their energy and get off a
smart shot on their next two trips down the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Off a turnover by Sprewell, Snow launched an alley-oop from just
inside midcourt to Hughes, who fielded it in the air and turned it
into a hair-raising layup to give the 76ers a 54-50 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Then off back-to-back blocks by Ratliff, one on Marcus Camby and
one on Sprewell, the 76ers were able to parlay his defense into a
56-50 lead at the end of the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   This was a stark departure from the way the Knicks had
manhandled the 76ers in their first two meetings. In those games,
the Knicks compiled a combined halftime edge of 88-57 and went on
to comfortable victories.
</P>
<P>
   Just a week ago, when the Knicks were completing a three-game
winning streak with a 91-72 victory against the 76ers, Chris Childs
and Ward alternated intense defense on Iverson and held him to 4
for 16 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Iverson started the first half 5 for 11 with 14
points. Although the defense was tight on him, he was able to flash
his crossover moves and head fakes to create just enough space to
deliver.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were struggling just to breathe in the face to the
physical 76ers. They shot 35.7 percent from the field in the first
half, with Ewing (1 for 4) hurting more than helping. After a
2-for-7 beginning, Houston hit his last two shots of the half for
12 points and Sprewell came up with 8 points off the bench. The
efforts by Sprewell and Houston, plus some silly fouls by the 76ers
to put the Knicks to the line 15 times in the first half, allowed
them to stay closer than their off-kilter play would have
indicated.
</P>
<P>
   They were within 5 points at the half despite the exasperation
caused by the three blocked shots apiece by Geiger and Ratliff in
the first half. They made every layup an adventure for the Knicks,
which was part of the reason Ewing and Camby, who missed all three
of his first-half shots, were having such a difficult time
underneath the basket. The last time the Knicks played the 76ers,
Camby scored 15 off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Knicks played the 76ers, everything was going
so smoothly for them. They were riding a winning streak and feeling
confident that they had turned their problems around. But the 76ers
were the last team the Knicks had beaten entering Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   A 76ers team that had been the elixir for what had ailed them
earlier in the season would not go down so easily.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
