<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSKI PRESSURED BY NFL BLITZ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ed Roski thought he had prepared for every
possible contingency in creating a redesigned Coliseum and
preparing a bid for a NFL expansion franchise.
</P>
<P>
   But he now realizes he didn't budget for a psychiatrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could use one right about now,'' Roski said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   As Phase II of the NFL's proposed return to Los Angeles
continues today with a visit by the league's expansion committee,
the Kings owner is having difficulty handling all of the NFL's
stressful blitzes and stunts.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL today will likely announce the New Coliseum as the site
for a team. But Roski, who literally willed the Coliseum back to
life with his support, will be kept hanging as the league goes
about hand-picking an owner or ownership group.
</P>
<P>
   The league wants to see if any other parties will come forward
with a bid, as well as a freshening of the bids by Roski and
Michael Ovitz. It could lead to an auction, ``and I don't think any
of us would have gotten involved if we knew it would come to
that,'' Roski said.
</P>
<P>
   Roski has already agreed to vacate his exclusive deal with the
Coliseum at the behest of the NFL. As personally flummoxed as he
may be, Roski's biggest concern is that the process could kill what
he's been working on for so long, the return of the NFL to L.A.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a real major problem,'' Roski said. ``There are a number
of stakes holders in and around the Coliseum that need to be
addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a long list, including the Coliseum Commission, which has a
lease for the stadium through 2005; the state, which owns the land;
neighborhood business groups involved in the overall downtown
makeover; a handful of conservancies; the federal Department of the
Interior; the museums in Exposition Park; and USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, these people and relationships we've nurtured
would want to know who they're dealing with, and whether they'll be
involved in negotiations, and whether the agreement we worked out
will be honored,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty dangerous. We've worked real hard on this, and it
could potentially be a deal breaker.''
</P>
<P>
   That is especially so should the league say more public money
needs to be attached to the Coliseum deal. The project claims there
is a $348,976,000 public investment in the project. But $85 million
of that is the subjective land value which is owned by the state,
and which happens to be tied to a proposed new lease with the
Coliseum Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Another $223 million is in infrastructure (freeways, access) and
Coliseum renovations that have already taken place. There is only
$40 million of fresh public money in the deal. Stadium construction
costs are to be handled privately by Roski through a private bond
issue secured by stadium revenue.
</P>
<P>
   But every NFL stadium built or renovated in the last five years
has included a substantial financial committee from the public
sector. That would include Cleveland, Baltimore, San Diego, Tampa
and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have (that mentality) in California,'' Roski said.
``There is no way we can ask the city or state to invest in a
football stadium when there are so many other things that need to
be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was upfront with the NFL from the beginning. `We can do it
ourselves with private money.' All they have to do is look at the
Staples Center. There are a lot of minefields, but we can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The expansion committee will meet this morning, then take a bus
tour of new downtown development that will end at the Coliseum and
lead into a 12:30 p.m. news conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
