</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-REDS-SPARKY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sparky Anderson elected to Reds Hall of Fame
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Sparky Anderson easily was the most popular, most
recognizable and most productive manager in the history of the
Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   And yet after the 1978 season, after finishing lower than second
only once in his nine years as manager and after putting two World
Series championship rings on his fingers, he was mysteriously and
unceremoniously fired.
</P>
<P>
   That was 21 years ago and Anderson never revealed why he was
pink-slipped by club president/general manager Dick Wagner, always
an ogre to Reds fans as the man who dismantled The Big Red Machine.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, during a media conference call concerning his
election to the Cincinnati Reds Hall of Fame by the Cincinnati
chapter of the Baseball Writers Association of America, Anderson
offered his reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you now. . .why I think it happened,'' Anderson
said. ``I believe it was because I got a little stubborn, a little
bit high and mighty.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because he was loyal to his coaches and players.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the 1978 season, when the Reds were on their way to a
second straight second place finish in the National League West,
Anderson was told in San Francisco that some coaching changes were
going to be made. Anderson wouldn't name names, but insiders said
Wagner wanted to replace pitching coach Larry Shepard and third
base coach Alex Grammas, both close friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, 'They are not going to be made, not over me, not over
my head,''' Anderson told Wagner. ``I fought it in San Francisco
and it didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   After the season, Anderson took the Reds to Japan for an
exhibition tour and Wagner wanted to discuss coaching changes again
and Anderson told him to wait until the team returned to the United
States, ``But that it still wasn't going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   When Anderson stood firm after the trip, Wagner fired him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just fought too hard over those changes,'' Anderson said.
``They were 50 percent wrong and I was 50 percent wrong. My place
was in the clubhouse and I had no business trying to run things
upstairs. You have to cooperate and not be so arrogant. I can't
look back and blame them. I have to be honest and say I caused half
the problem myself.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Wagner also would not play the free-agent game. He
wouldn't sign free agents and he wouldn't match offers made to his
players by other teams _ pitcher Don Gullett, second baseman Joe
Morgan and infielder/outfielder Pete Rose. They all left as free
agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were not competing by the (free agent) rules that
existed,'' Anderson said. ``And I was a little arrogant then
fighting for a couple of players.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Anderson was hired by the Detroit Tigers (he took
Grammas with him), where he managed for 17 years and matched his
1975 and 1976 World Series championship with a title for the Tigers
in 1984, the only manager to win the World Series in both leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could be coy and say this (Cincinnati Reds Hall of Fame)
doesn't mean much, but it means so much to me. . .the first place I
managed, the first big-league game I ever managed. I'm a dreamer,
always have been, but I could never dream up the great things that
happened to me in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going into the Hall of Fame, well, I'll stay there an
eternity, as long as the world lasts. . .and that boggles your
mind,'' he said. ``All my relatives, for generations and
generations, will know exactly where I am.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt when Anderson turns 70 and becomes eligible
for the National Baseball Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, the
Veteran's committee will sweep him in on the first ballot.
</P>
<P>
   And which hat will he wear, Reds or Tigers?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still talking about that,'' Anderson said. ``But I know
one thing, (then general manager) Bob Howsam will stand next to me.
People thought he was crazy at the time when he hired me at 34 to
manage the Reds. Had he not, I might never have managed in the
major leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was 863-586 (.571) in nine years with the Reds,
2,194-1,835 (.545) for 26 years as a manager.
</P>
<P>
   He will be officially inducted as the Hall's 54th member during
pre-game ceremonies in Cinergy Field on Friday, July 16.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
