<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-BENGALS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    O'Donnell released from Bengals
 &HT;    (EDS: This story runs in place of Bengals draft story. Slug
stays the same.)
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Quarterback Neil O'Donnell's turbulent 10-month
stay with the Bengals ended Monday when he was released by
president and general manager Mike Brown.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell, who signed a four-year, $17.25 million contract in
July after getting cut by the New York Jets, beat out Jeff Blake
for the starting job during training camp.
</P>
<P>
   But he went 2-9 as the starter, and fractured a bone in his
right passing hand Dec. 6 against Buffalo. He spent the final three
weeks on injured reserve.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell became expendable when the Bengals made Oregon's Akili
Smith their top draft pick Saturday. Cincinnati has five
quarterbacks on the roster: Smith, Blake, Paul Justin, Eric Kresser
and rookie seventh-round pick Scott Covington. ``When Neil and I
talked a couple weeks ago, I told him if we drafted a quarterback
high, we would let him go,'' Brown said. ``This is what Neil
wanted. This gives him his best chance (to sign elsewhere).''
</P>
<P>
   In 13 games, O'Donnell completed 212 of 343 passes (61.8
percent) for 2,216 yards, 15 TDs and four interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just didn't work out here,'' Brown said. ``I have a hard
time saying exactly why. He didn't get an early start. It seemed
like he was never comfortable operating our system. That made it
hard for him to pick out the right receiver at the correct time.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the NFL today, you can only keep so many high-priced
quarterbacks. Something had to give. By the end of the year, I
don't think anyone around here had the feeling it was going in the
right direction. We're not looking to continue that.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said Blake will begin the season as the No. 1 quarterback,
but anticipates Smith will push hard for the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want it to be comfortable for both of them,'' Brown said.
``But they're competing, and when you compete, the pressures that
that produces will be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming off their fourth 3-13 record of the 1990s, the Bengals
goal is to score more points. They were outscored an average of
28.3 to 16.8 in '98.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL is an offensive game,'' Brown said. ``Offense and
defense are important, but the top teams today are the teams that
roll up the points.
</P>
<P>
   ``That helps their defenses. It gives them field position. It
gives them less time on the field. It gives them the advantage of
being ahead and taking chances, taking risks. All that helps a
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the way it's been around here in recent years, we haven't
be able to score enough. It's put an undo burden on our defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he's pleased with his second-round pick, West Virginia
cornerback Charles Fisher, Brown will continue to negotiate with
free agents Ashley Ambrose and Ryan McNeil with the hope of adding
experience at a critical position.
</P>
<P>
   ``We filled the need,'' he said. ``We'll talk to unprotected
free agents at cornerback. But it would have to be something that
made sense for us. We're not going to overpay because we have a
sense of need.''
</P>
<P>
   Chick Ludwig writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
