</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-BROWNS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Draft makes Browns' 1999 picture a little clearer
 &HT;    By Sean McClelland
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND, Ohio _ The Cleveland Browns march into this weekend's
mini-camp with nearly 90 bodies on their expansion roster.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a fan, or even if you're head coach Chris Palmer,
that's the good news.
</P>
<P>
   Now, how many of those can play football? And how many will be
there when the NFL officially returns to Cleveland in September for
the first time since Art Modell spirited the original Browns out of
town in 1995?
</P>
<P>
   That's the mystery, and it doesn't figure to be solved until
deep into training camp, if even then.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to put the puzzle together,'' Palmer said.
``Maybe about 30 percent of our squad is clear in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the roster shapes up after the Browns made 11
selections in the NFL Draft:
</P>
<P>
   OFFENSE
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback: For now, Ty Detmer is the starter while top pick
Tim Couch learns his way around the system.
</P>
<P>
   Running back: If the season opened today, former 49ers Terry
Kirby and Marc Edwards would start. Not great, not terrible.
Missing is a third-down or change-of-pace back. Seventh-round pick
Madre Hill could find a niche here if healthy. Jerris McPhail and
six-year veteran Ron Moore add depth. Trading for Tyrone Wheatley
is a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Wideouts: Leslie Sheppard, acquired from Washington, is the most
accomplished talent. Second-round pick Kevin Johnson will get every
chance to be the slot receiver and fifth-rounder Darrin Chiavarini
has the speed and hands to surprise. Freddie Solomon will
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Tight end: Irv Smith. Solid, but no backup visible at this
point. If sixth-round pick James Dearth sticks, it will be as a
long snapper.
</P>
<P>
   Linemen: Deep enough to be ignored on draft day. Tackles are
both Browns, Lomas and Orlando. Center Dave Wohlabaugh arrived from
New England as a free agent. Jim Pyne is set at one guard spot with
fellow expansion-draft refugee Ben Cavil among those competing for
the other.
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSE
</P>
<P>
   Linemen: The signing of Derrick Alexander over the weekend means
the Browns almost certainly will employ a base 4-3 scheme. Palmer
envisions Alexander and John Jurkovic at the tackle spots with
Hurvin McCormack and Roy Barker on the outside. Could be worse.
</P>
<P>
   Linebackers: Chris Spielman is the middle linebacker if his body
holds up. Elijah Alexander is a weakside candidate, although he's
injured and will miss mini-camp. On the strong side, a training
camp battle is shaping up between John Thierry and second-round
pick Rahim Abdullah.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerbacks: Antonio Langham and Corey Fuller should be solid,
but Daylon McCutcheon, a third-rounder from USC, won't be held back
for long.
</P>
<P>
   Safeties: Marquez Pope, at free safety, and University of
California draftee Marquis Smith, a run-stuffing strong safety,
appear to be the best bets at this point.
</P>
<P>
   SPECIALISTS
</P>
<P>
   Place-kicker: Untested Phil Dawson can expect training-camp
competition from a number of free agents, their identities to be
determined.
</P>
<P>
   Punter: Eight-year veteran Chris Gardocki has this spot nailed
down.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
