<HEADER>
A5080 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT     04-19 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS FIRE ROBINSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Just before the start of the season, the
Kings offered Larry Robinson a two-year contract extension, a
reward for his work in 1997-98, when he'd been a finalist for the
Jack Adams Award as the NHL's Coach of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, in a move that to this day puzzles General Manager
Dave Taylor, declined to sign the extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult to understand why he didn't accept it,''
Taylor said Monday afternoon. ``But Larry, he'll tell you, is a
day-to-day person.''
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday, Taylor had concluded that a day-to-day person was the
wrong person for this job and that Robinson had run out of days.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson coached Sunday's season-ending 3-2 loss after being
told by Taylor he would not be back for a fifth season, and Monday,
the Kings officially announced that the contracts of Robinson,
assistant coaches Jay Leach and Rick Green, and goaltending
consultant Don Edwards would not be renewed. Taylor added that he
has yet to begin what promises to be an exhaustive search for the
right coach to lead the Kings into the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not an easy decision and it was not an easy process,''
Taylor said. ``Larry made it easier. He understands, and I think he
agreed with the decision. When I talked to him this morning, he
seemed more relieved than anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, insisting he wants to coach again, said he wasn't at
all relieved at the conclusion of a four-year stint in which his
teams made the playoffs only once, didn't win a postseason game and
posted a cumulative 122-161-45 record with a rebuilding franchise,
including a 32-45-5 mark this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought there would be (relief),'' Robinson said, ``but not
really. I still thought there would be a lot to be done. You want
to go out on top. This is not what I envisioned when I took the
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said he will compile an initial candidate list that could
have as many as 10 names on it, conduct interviews, narrow the
field, conduct more interviews, then make a decision. He said it is
not imperative that a coach be in place before the amateur draft on
June 26.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor added that he wants to hire someone with previous
coaching experience, and would not rule anyone out, including the
well-traveled and controversial Mike Keenan, who was fired earlier
this season by Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Among early candidates are two from the IHL: Long Beach Ice Dogs
coach John Van Boxmeer, who has worked with several of the Kings'
prospects, and Utah Grizzlies coach Butch Goring, who was fired as
Boston's coach in 1986 after a bit more than one season and was a
teammate of Taylor's in Los Angeles in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Said Van Boxmeer, whose team is preparing for the start of the
playoffs: ``It's not an appropriate time for me to be discussing
another job.''
</P>
<P>
   Goring also is believed to be a candidate for the New York
Islanders' job, but said of the position with the Kings,
``Hopefully, they'll put me on the short list and give me the
opportunity to take the next step. It seems like a very strong
match. Obviously, I have a lot of ties there.''
</P>
<P>
   Goring was a candidate for the Kings' job four years ago when
Robinson was hired, and turned down the Mighty Ducks' job a year
ago when he couldn't reach contract terms in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Others who may be considered are former Buffalo Sabres coach Ted
Nolan; Detroit assistant Dave Lewis, another former teammate of
Taylor's, and IHL coaches Dave Tippett of Houston and John Anderson
of Chicago. Taylor would not rule out hiring a college or junior
coach, and said he wants to see if any coaches become available
after the early rounds of the Stanley Cup playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, several factors cost Robinson his job. Taylor said
that when Robinson questioned his coaching abilities at midseason
it sent ``the wrong message'' to the players, and Robinson's
openness and introspection in interviews the entire season also did
nothing to help his cause. Robinson also admitted that being a
stern taskmaster with players who aren't playing well is not in his
nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Larry loved the players so much,'' said left wing Luc
Robitaille, the only King who exceeded expectations this season.
``A lot of guys didn't understand how lucky we were. Usually, if
you're not playing well, you're in the stands. It didn't happen
here. I think a lot of guys didn't understand that. Maybe they
thought they were playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the Kings were devastated by injuries to key
players, since-discarded free-agent pickup Steve Duchesne was a
dismal bust, and Robinson was hurt by the fact that a number of
Kings did not perform as well as they had the year before. Without
naming names, Robinson said the Kings had overrated their talent,
he said he felt his staff had done a ``great'' job with what it had
to work with, and he questioned the character of some of his
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you instill heart and drive and intestinal fortitude
into people who don't have it or don't want it?'' Robinson asked.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the 47-year-old Robinson said he hopes for another
chance, as soon as next season, to try again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'd like to get right back into it,'' Robinson said.
``I don't want to do this forever. My original plan was to retire
at 50 and start doing other things. So if I'm going to do it, I
better get to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
