<SLUG> BC-AMGEN-RESULTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMGEN INC. SHARES DOWN DESPITE EARNINGS OUTLOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: Today in first graf refers to Tuesday.) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   THOUSAND OAKS, Calif. _ Biotechnology drug giant Amgen Inc. is
expected to beat analysts' first-quarter earnings estimates today
on improved sales, but you wouldn't know it by the company's share
price Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Along with virtually every other publicly traded U.S.
pharmaceutical and biotech company, Amgen's shares fell sharply
Monday, dropping $5.875, or 8.7 percent, to close at $60.9375.
Amgen is traded on the technology-heavy Nasdaq stock exchange which
saw its index, the Nasdaq Composite, fall 5.6 percent Monday, its
third-biggest percentage drop this decade.
</P>
<P>
   For Amgen, the one-day drop followed a tough five days of
trading last week that saw its share price fall 14 percent, the
largest one-week decline in nearly two years.
</P>
<P>
   But for all of that, Amgen is actually performing well, company
officials say, and several industry observers expect the firm to
outperform a 44 cents-per-share consensus of analysts surveyed by
First Call Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, people expect the earnings news to be rather
positive,'' said Caroline Copithorne, an analyst at Prudential
Securities in New York. Amgen shares were upgraded Monday by CIBC
Oppenheimer to a strong buy, from a buy rating, and analyst Michael
Sheffery of OrbiMed Advisors LLC said he expects the company to
beat expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Fueling some of the confidence is an announcement Amgen made
last month that it would invest $100 million to develop a prostate
cancer drug it had acquired. The company noted that
higher-than-expected sales of its existing products, particularly
the anti-anemia drug Epogen, would offset the investment, allowing
it to meet analysts' full-year earnings estimates. The company is
expected to earn between $1.80 and $1.85 for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Epogen have grown faster than expected over the last
year thanks to a Clinton administration decision to ease funding
restrictions on the drug. Epogen is paid for almost entirely by
Medicare, the federal health plan for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's sell-off of Amgen and shares of other high-tech
companies comes after months of growth led by Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a big rotation out of Nasdaq names,'' Copithorne
said. ``They're all down significantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Copithorne noted that Eli Lilly and Co. shares fell $9.4375 to
$72.875, Pfizer Inc. dropped $9.125 to $117.9375, and that Internet
stocks almost uniformly fell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
