<SLUG> BC-NY-ABORTION-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT ABORTION PROTEST, POLICE AND MEDIA OUTNUMBER DEMONSTRATORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMHERST, N.Y. _ Braving numbing rain and whistling winds, more
than 80 abortion protesters fanned across the suburbs of Buffalo
Monday morning in the second day of a highly publicized week of
demonstrations, delivering their message at high schools, public
thoroughfares and the area's biggest bookstore, which they said was
selling child pornography.
</P>
<P>
   As was the case on Sunday, there were no reports of violence or
arrests, only a few testy exchanges between abortion-rights
supporters and participants in Operation Save America, the series
of events organized by Operation Rescue, the national anti-abortion
group.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic in Buffalo, not a major headache to begin with, did not
suffer, either.
</P>
<P>
   And with a fortified presence outside abortion clinics and other
locations, police officials said they did not expect much disorder
for the balance of the week, a serene contrast to the maelstrom of
1992, when more than 600 people were arrested during a series of
demonstrations against abortions called the Spring of Life.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for the first two days at least, there has been little
difference between Operation Save America and peaceful
demonstrations in other cities on more mundane subjects, with
people holding homemade signs, talking among their ideological
brethren and waving to honking drivers. Little difference, that is,
except for the intense news media and law enforcement attention.
</P>
<P>
   It was only six months ago that Dr. Barnett Slepian, an Amherst
obstetrician and gynecologist who performed abortions, was killed
in his home by a sniper in a case that made national headlines and
still remains open.
</P>
<P>
   So at some locations Monday, the protesters were outnumbered by
police, or outnumbered by television reporters doing live
broadcasts, giving the whole spectacle the aura of a
much-anticipated Broadway show opening to a less-than-packed house.
</P>
<P>
   That may change on Tuesday, when the first of several
demonstrations will be held outside the Buffalo GYN Womenservices
clinic, where Slepian used to work.
</P>
<P>
   For now, advocates on both sides have been content to interpret
it all to their advantage. ``We're happy that so many of them
didn't show up,'' said Karen Nicholls, a 28-year-old administrative
assistant from Brooklyn who is taking the week off to participate
in counterdemonstrations organized by the abortion-rights group
Refuse and Resist. ``This is a very small circus. A flea circus.''
</P>
<P>
   For abortion opponents, though, the mission of Operation Save
America is not about attendance, or expectations. It is not even
really about abortion, they say; it is, instead, about
strengthening a society weakened by immorality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take a stand, and we declare this city belongs to Jesus,''
said Joe Hermiz, a minister who, with his wife, Tina, drove five
hours from Columbus, Ohio, to participate. ``I call this a
spiritual war, and that's the way the Scriptures describe it.''
</P>
<P>
   With a grab bag of issues like abortion, child pornography,
teen-age sex and school violence, Monday's activities had been
billed by organizers as a move to broaden their agenda. But with
the exception of one large sign accusing Barnes &AMP; Noble of
promoting child pornography by selling books by the photographer
Jock Sturges, most of the signs, the discussion and the pamphlets
during a long day of protests dwelled on abortion. The day was
capped by a Spring of Life reunion dinner attended by more than 200
people.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, there were the occasional flashes of
righteous passion so common to the abortion debate. At the Barnes &AMP;
Noble store, protesters clashed verbally when Rusty Thomas, a
minister who lives near Waco, Texas, spoke thunderously about
America's problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are drowning in a sea of blood,'' said Thomas, his voice
slicing through the drizzling rain. He said ``evil has opened up
like a Pandora's box'' and talked about the need for freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, freedom from religion!'' an abortion-rights supporter
yelled back.
</P>
<P>
   At Kenmore East High School, Bill Nelson, 18, a senior, took
exception to the graphic posters that showed the bodies of Jews in
concentration camps side by side with a picture of an aborted
fetus, and that described both as Holocausts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pro-choice!'' he yelled from a distance, pumping his fist to
the applause of some classmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pro-death!'' an abortion opponent fired back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a woman's issue!'' Nelson continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, to go to bed with a guy!'' the opponent volleyed back.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 minutes later, Nelson, his ire quelled, talked about
how he was annoyed, mostly, that the protesters showed up at his
school. ``They've got no life,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
