<HEADLINE>
A LOOK AT THE STANLEY CUP PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On the dawn of a new playoff season, we ask only
one thing of the hockey Gods.
</P>
<P>
   Well, actually, we have several requests.
</P>
<P>
   Could we please have a Stanley Cup Finals that lasts more than
the minimum four games? New Jersey beat Detroit for the 1994 Cup in
four games, Colorado swept Florida in 1995, and the Red Wings swept
Philadelphia and Washington the last two years. In the case of a
championship playoff series, brevity is not the soul of wit or the
stuff of drama.
</P>
<P>
   And while we're at it, we would like to echo the recent
sentiments of Kings president Tim Leiweke, who said he is rooting
for teams such as New Jersey and Ottawa, which have had outstanding
seasons based more on smart management than on the size of their
bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   At this year's trading deadline, the Red Wings attempted to
purchase a third consecutive title, which would make them the first
team to accomplish the feat since the New York Islanders of the
early 1980s. Here's hoping it doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we aren't nave enough to believe the unlikely event
of a Senators championship would deter future spending by wealthy
U.S.-based teams. But it would be nice to see it's still possible
to build a Cup winner by developing players and following a system.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanley Cup playoffs, particularly the early rounds,
historically have been dauntingly unpredictable. Nonetheless, what
follows is a modest attempt to sort out the events of the next two
months:
</P>
<P>
   WESTERN CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   First round
</P>
<P>
   Mighty Ducks (35-34-13) vs. Detroit (43-32-7). Season series:
Detroit, 3-1. Series outlook: The tandem of Paul Kariya and Teemu
Selanne makes the Mighty Ducks an unattractive first-round opponent
for any team. But the Red Wings simply have too much depth and too
much experience for the Ducks to conquer. The Red Wings have eight
players on their roster who had 48 or more points this season. The
Ducks have five. The longer a series goes, the more important depth
becomes. If the Ducks can get hot on the power play, however, they
will give the Wings some trouble. Prediction: Red Wings in 6.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas (51-19-12) vs. Edmonton (33-37-12). Season series:
Dallas, 3-0-1. Series outlook: The Oilers shocked the Stars in the
first round of the playoffs two years ago. It won't happen this
time. Dallas is more mature, and the absence of suspended
defenseman Derian Hatcher will be balanced by the Oilers' loss of
leading scorer Bill Guerin. The Stars allowed a league-low 168
goals. Prediction: Stars in 5.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado (44-28-10) vs. San Jose (31-33-18). Season series:
Colorado, 3-1. Series outlook: The Avalanche loaded up for the
postseason by adding Theo Fleury to an already-potent offensive
lineup. The scoring records of the Oilers of the 1980s aren't in
any danger, but at the end of the 1990s, the Avalanche is as good
as it gets when it comes to firepower. San Jose added Vincent
Damphousse for its playoff drive, and the Sharks are pointed in the
right direction for the future. But it's hard to imagine them
forcing Colorado and goalie Patrick Roy into a protracted series.
Prediction: Avalanche in 5.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix (39-31-12) vs. St. Louis (37-32-13). Season series: St.
Louis, 2-1-1. Series outlook: The Coyotes were the best team in the
league at the start of the season. They have been a sub-.500 team
ever since. The loss to a broken jaw of leading scorer Jeremy
Roenick on the eve of the playoffs is a severe blow. The Blues, on
the other hand, seem to be coming together at the right time, and
are solid at both ends of the ice, with Pavol Demitra and Pierre
Turgeon leading the way offensively and Al MacInnis and Chris
Pronger fortifying the defense. Prediction: Blues in 6.
</P>
<P>
   Second round
</P>
<P>
   Colorado vs. Detroit. Series outlook: This will be memorable,
great players and two teams that hate each other, which is what
playoff hockey is all about. Colorado, however, has the better
goaltending and is a bit deeper offensively. On the other hand,
Detroit has a better cast of role players. Flip a coin to guess
who'll win this series. Prediction: Avalanche in 7.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas vs. St. Louis. Series outlook: The Stars will regain
Hatcher's services for the series, and he will be useful because
the Blues have some dangerous offensive weapons and are a
well-balanced team. The series will have added intrigue because
Dallas' Brett Hull will be facing his former team. Prediction:
Stars in 5.
</P>
<P>
   Conference finals
</P>
<P>
   Dallas vs. Colorado. Series outlook: The Avalanche will be at a
disadvantage at the start of this series after surviving an
exhausting and emotionally-draining battle with the Red Wings. This
will be the ultimate test for Dallas' defense, but the Stars begin
this series with two games at home and the chance to put the weary
Avalanche in an instant hole. Prediction: Stars in 7.
</P>
<P>
   EASTERN CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   First round
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey (47-24-11) vs. Pittsburgh (38-30-14). Season series:
New Jersey, 4-1. Series outlook: The disciplined Devils were
shocked in the first round last year, but they have become a more
complete team under first-year coach Robbie Ftorek. The Penguins
can be sloppy defensively, and even though they have the reputation
of having an explosive offense because of the presence of NHL
scoring champion Jaromir Jagr, New Jersey actually scored six more
goals than Pittsburgh this season. Prediction: Devils in 5.
</P>
<P>
   Ottawa (44-23-15) vs. Buffalo (37-28-17). Season series: Ottawa,
1-0-4. Series outlook: Buffalo goalie Dominik Hasek is the great
equalizer, though his late-season groin injury adds a note of
concern. The Sabres finished with 12 fewer points than the
Senators, but allowed four fewer goals. Ottawa's rise this season
has been a great story, but in what should be a low-scoring series,
it's hard to pick against Hasek. Prediction: Sabres in 7.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina (34-30-18) vs. Boston (39-30-13). Season series:
Boston, 2-1-1. Series outlook: Playoff hockey arrives in North
Carolina and it will be interesting to see if anybody cares. The
Hurricanes have the third seed in the Eastern Conference and
home-ice advantage because they won the Southeast Division, but
they actually finished with five fewer points than Boston. Nobody
said life is fair. Neither team is overwhelming, but the Bruins'
playoff experience, the outstanding play of former Kings goalie
Byron Dafoe and the coaching of Pat Burns make Boston a clear
favorite. Prediction: Bruins in 6.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto (45-30-7) vs. Philadelphia (37-26-19). Season series:
Philadelphia, 3-1. Series outlook: At midseason, the Flyers looked
like the team to beat in the East. But with Eric Lindros gone
because of his collapsed lung and with Mark Recchi sidelined with
post-concussion syndrome, the Flyers are ripe. Toronto is not great
defensively, but with Mats Sundin leading the way the Leafs had the
league's highest-scoring offense. Toronto's Curtis Joseph also has
the edge in goal over the Flyers' John Vanbiesbrouck. Prediction:
Maple Leafs in 5.
</P>
<P>
   Second round
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey vs. Buffalo: Hasek and New Jersey's Martin Brodeur
met in a playoff series five years ago, with the Devils prevailing
in seven games. In five of the seven games, the winning team scored
two or fewer goals. Expect a similar series. Once again, New Jersey
has the better cast in front of its goalie, and this time, the
series should be shorter, though perhaps no higher-scoring.
Prediction: Devils in 6.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto vs. Boston: The Bruins end the Maple Leafs' surprising
season and continue their own surprising run. Boston has the
defense and goaltending to shut down the high-scoring Leafs, and
the Bruins have enough offense to puncture Toronto's unsteady
defense. Boston won the season series, 3-1-1. Prediction: Bruins in
6.
</P>
<P>
   Conference finals
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey vs. Boston: How do you stop the Devils? It's tough,
because they have four players who scored more than 20 goals this
season and 13 who scored at least 11, nearly twice as many
double-figure goal scorers as the Bruins. Couple that with New
Jersey's solid defense and it will be a tough combination to beat,
unless Dafoe is sensational. Prediction: Devils in 5.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Cup Finals
</P>
<P>
   Dallas vs. New Jersey: By the time these teams meet in the
finals, it will have been nearly seven months since they last faced
each other. In the one-game season series, the Devils recorded a
5-2 victory in Dallas. That game means nothing now. Neither does
the Stars' home-ice advantage. New Jersey won a record 28
regular-season road games. These are two complete teams that play
solid defense and are deep offensively. The important thing is that
after four straight sweeps, the Stanley Cup Finals will finally be
worth watching again. Prediction: New Jersey in 7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
