<HEADLINE>
PROFESSOR AWARDED PRESTIGIOUS GRANT TO WRITE ABOUT NAVAJO HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The Navajo people do not dwell on their past.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's done, gone,'' one Navajo woman says.
</P>
<P>
   So it is left to others to chronicle the story of a culture that
has survived where others have failed, a culture once thought
doomed by the incursion of European settlers.
</P>
<P>
   But as Navajos themselves have declared, their society is not a
museum piece locked in the 19th century. It evolves. It progresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``One hundred years ago, no one predicted there would still be
Indian communities,'' says Arizona State University history
Professor Peter Iverson, who has spent his academic life exploring
Navajo culture and politics. ``The story in 20th century Arizona
and elsewhere is that most people were wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Long an admirer of the culture, Iverson has just been awarded a
Guggenheim Fellowship to write a comprehensive history of the
Navajo. In August, he will leave his teaching duties to conduct
interviews and research and begin writing. He'll return to teaching
in May 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's an important thing to do,'' Iverson says of the
book. ``I'm looking forward to it. You're appropriately humble
about taking it on. It's a big assignment, but it's an honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning a Guggenheim, which will pay Iverson about $30,000, is
equally an honor. He is only the sixth ASU faculty member to win
the prestigious award. Most recipients hail from eastern colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an honor for ASU,'' he says. ``You feel good about
representing the interior West.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Orlen, a poet in the Creative Writing program at the
University of Arizona, is also among this year's 179 Guggenheim
winners.
</P>
<P>
   One of almost 2,800 artists, scholars and scientists who vied
for the award, Iverson could only hope for the best after applying
last winter. When a colleague told him that winners would likely be
contacted in late February, he couldn't resist watching his mailbox
``like a hawk.''
</P>
<P>
   March blew in, and his hopes faded. He comforted himself knowing
he had received two previous awards from the National Endowment for
the Humanities. A Guggenheim seemed like a dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put it on a back burner and turned off the stove,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Then, like an unwatched pot that finally boils, the letter
arrived: ``It is my privilege to inform you that you have been
named a fellow of the John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation . .
.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was absolutely thrilled,'' says Iverson, a modest man who
says he kept expecting to hear that the letter was a terrible
mistake. ``I couldn't believe it. You just can't believe your good
fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   It was no mistake. He first shared the news with his wife,
Karen, his children _ grown and scattered around the country _ and
his mother in Menlo Park, Calif. Because his late father had also
been a university professor, she knew well the prestige of a
Guggenheim.
</P>
<P>
   When Iverson told his ASU colleagues, they applauded his
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been generous with their comments,'' he says.
``People have been kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Iverson has written numerous books on Native Americans,
including last year's ``We're Still Here: American Indians in the
20th Century.'' He is also the author of ``Barry Goldwater: Native
Arizonan,'' a biography of the late Arizona senator.
</P>
<P>
   Indians, especially the Navajo, have intrigued him since
childhood. His maternal grandfather was principal at Navajo schools
in Fort Wingate and Toadlena, N.M., and Keems Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up hearing his stories,'' Iverson says. ``My interest
in the subject is personal and family related.''
</P>
<P>
   After earning his master's degree from the University of
Wisconsin in 1969, Iverson had an offer to interview for a teaching
job at Navajo Community College in Many Farms, the first tribal
college in the country. But the starving student had no money to
make the trip, and someone else got the job. As luck would have it,
that candidate withdrew, and Iverson was given the job over the
phone. He rented a U-Haul and made the trip West.
</P>
<P>
   After three years at the school, now located in Tsaile and
renamed Dine College for the word Navajos call themselves, Iverson
returned to Wisconsin for his doctorate, which he finished in 1975.
He was a visiting assistant professor at ASU for a year, then
taught at the University of Wyoming until re-joining the ASU
faculty in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Although other books have addressed aspects of the Navajo
culture, Iverson says his will be ``sweeping,'' chronicling the
history of the tribe from its migration into the Southwest around
the 14th century.
</P>
<P>
   Other histories, Iverson says, also disparage the Navajo in
focusing on their failures. He has a different perspective on the
community that is equal in size to West Virginia with an estimated
population of 200,000. It is located mostly in northern Arizona and
covers areas of northwestern New Mexico and southern Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to tell a story of success,'' he says. ``Navajos are
winners.''
</P>
<P>
   That success derives partly from the size of the tribe, largest
in the United States, and its geographic location _ what Iverson
calls ``a powerful landscape.'' Navajos inhabit land rich in
resources and noted for such tourist destinations as Monument
Valley and Canyon de Chelly.
</P>
<P>
   Early in their history, Navajos expanded their population by
embracing newcomers. In the 17th century, when Spaniards were
driven out of New Mexico and then returned, Pueblo people sought
refuge with the Navajo and were incorporated into the society.
</P>
<P>
   Times change, and the Navajo Nation has evolved with the times,
Iverson says. Change in Native American communities does not signal
acquiescence any more than it does in Anglo communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't consider ourselves less American than Abraham Lincoln
because we drive cars and he didn't,'' Iverson says. ``All cultures
change. Through contact and conflict, cultures are invigorated.''
</P>
<P>
   One cause for concern, however, is the decline of the Navajo
language, he says. Few Navajo young people speak their native
tongue. And fewer remain on traditional family sheep ranches,
increasingly moving into such towns as Window Rock and Chinle.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson will approach his work not only as an historian but as
an archaeologist and anthropologist as well, tracing the Navajo
roots back more than seven centuries to their origins north of
Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a multidisciplinary enterprise,'' he says. ``That's
what an historian tries to do _ to make connections between
different fields.''
</P>
<P>
   His journey will take him from sources at ASU _ Native American
students and faculty members _ to the seat of the Navajo Nation in
Window Rock to the National Archives in Washington, D.C., where he
will study such documents as old treaties, correspondence and
records on education. He will study the Navajo language with ASU
graduate teaching assistant Alfred Yazzie.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to ensure responsible research, the Navajo
government asks scholars to obtain a permit before beginning a
project. In return, assistance and access to data are provided.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his research will come from materials passed down from
his grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Iverson, 55, will draw on his own wealth of
knowledge gathered over decades as an Indian scholar. He promises a
book meticulously crafted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a strong responsibility,'' he says. ``I have great
respect for Navajo history. It's important to tell the story that
is respectful of tradition but that is honest _ not to say that
there are no problems but to tell the successes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who takes on this task should have the right
background. It's not a book I could have written in my younger
life. This is the right time for me to do this.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
