<HEADER>
A5213 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      04-19 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMOVE THE SILENCER ON GUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Two police officers shot dead within 22 days and the
news is filled with stories about violence and lawlessness and lack
of values and urban expansion and Hollywood irresponsibility and
everything except what counts _ guns.
</P>
<P>
   I'm wondering how many good cops have to die before we can
unscrew the silencers and talk about the growing number of good men
and women suddenly moved to worship at the altar of pistol, rifle,
sawed-off shotgun, musket, mortar and howitzer.
</P>
<P>
   Is two enough?
</P>
<P>
   If you'd like, we can begin the conversation with the argument
made by the National Rifle Association each time someone wants to
talk about America's worshipful fascination with weapons.
</P>
<P>
   They say: Guns aren't the problem.
</P>
<P>
   And, they're correct. Guns aren't the problem. Gun nuts are the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is people who believe guns are the answer. People
who think the only reasonable response to violence is for more
people to have more guns.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, when Phoenix police Officer Marc Atkinson was
killed, an armed citizen named Rory Vertigan fired into the
suspects' car, wounding one of them.
</P>
<P>
   No one else was hurt, but it didn't save the officer.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a heavily armed Chandler police officer named James
Snedigar went into an apartment wearing full body armor and
expecting trouble. It didn't save him. &QL; 
What are our chances? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If someone that well-trained winds up dead, what chance does the
average homeowner with a .22-caliber pistol have? Most people say
they buy guns to protect themselves and their families. To save
lives.
</P>
<P>
   The papers are filled with their stories.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there's the one about the Phoenix teenager who
accidentally shot and killed a young nephew with a gun meant to
protect his family. Or the kid who killed a friend when his
father's gun accidentally discharged. Or the 6-year-old girl killed
by a 7-year-old brother who was playing with a rifle.
</P>
<P>
   Simply owning a gun makes you safe the way simply owning a Bible
makes you holy.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why the gun nuts constantly bring up the Second
Amendment to the U.S. Constitution, the one that reads, in part,
``the right of the people to keep and bear arms shall not be
infringed.''
</P>
<P>
   It's there in plain English, they say. Gun ownership is
guaranteed. It's protected.
</P>
<P>
   And, they're correct.
</P>
<P>
   The right to own a gun isn't the problem. It's the notion that
we all ``need'' to own one.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a new idea.
</P>
<P>
   It can be traced along a row of graves stretching from here to
the invention of gunpowder. &QL; 
Theory into practice &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first time I saw the theory put into practice was 12 years
ago. It involved a fellow named Martin Olsen, an otherwise good man
who believed a pistol could solve the problem of violence.
</P>
<P>
   One day in 1987, Olsen was in the Lost Alaskan Bar in Mesa when
two men started breaking up the place.
</P>
<P>
   Olsen walked out of the bar to get a handgun he kept in the
glove compartment of his car.
</P>
<P>
   Before he got back, the two men fled the bar and drove away in a
truck. Olsen tried to shoot out the vehicle's tires, and missed.
</P>
<P>
   A lovely young woman named Susan Dina was stretched out on a
lounge chair near the pool of the Mesa Super 8 Motel, just across
the street. She lay next to her husband. The couple were in town
from Philadelphia for a friend's wedding.
</P>
<P>
   One of Olsen's bullets struck Susan Dina in the face, killing
her.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years I've spoken many times to the dead woman's
mother, Dolores Heil. Her family has never recovered, and she's
never been able to understand what she calls the ``gun-toting Wild
West'' mentality of the state where her daughter died.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know if Susan had an opinion on the subject. But at
least her silence, unlike ours, is understandable. &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 2315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
