<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-SPORTSNET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECRUITING RESOURCES MADE FOR PROUD PARENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Parents with children playing high school sports get a bad rap,
some deserved, some not.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Howdeshell of Maryville, Tenn., is the proud parent of a
standout high school baseball player. But instead of getting in the
way of the coach _ as some parents are prone to do _ he has found a
way to be proactive in a constructive way.
</P>
<P>
   Howdeshell, who admits that he has grand plans for his son Andy
_ a collegiate baseball prospect at Maryville Heritage High School
_ created a Web site catering to parents with young athletes to
market.
</P>
<P>
   Howdeshell's effort is the High School Baseball Web
(www.hsbaseballweb.com), a one-stop resource for parents who have a
significant investment in their child's athletic future.
</P>
<P>
   Howdeshell is among many sites with this mission. Several sites,
such as Player Portfolio Website and AthleteNetwork.com, help
parents and young athletes get prepared for recruiting or choosing
the right college by assembling the right resources or providing a
service.
</P>
<P>
   Howdeshell's site is the only one known to be created by a
parent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted a site for players, parents and coaches to have
access to information and ideas about high school baseball ... the
college recruiting process, the pro draft, anything that they had a
question about,'' Howdeshell said.
</P>
<P>
   One example of the site's focus is a link to an article by
Baseball Parent magazine titled ``How to target market your son.''
</P>
<P>
   A message board poses such questions as: How many pitches would
be considered too many, in a week, for a 15-year-old high school
pitcher? Or, what does it mean when my son gets a letter and a
``baseball questionnaire'' from a college coach?
</P>
<P>
   Howdeshell launched his noncommercial site nearly two months ago
after scouring the Internet for recruiting information as it
pertains to baseball. At this point, Howdeshell has compiled mostly
a collection of links to articles, high school team sites and
baseball information sources. The site also lists camps and
showcases geared for high school athletes and has a message board
for baseball parents to exchange ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Other sites have the same idea, but they take a different
approach.
</P>
<P>
   Players Portfolio Website (www.playersportfolio.com) allows high
school students to advertise their athletic resume on a personal
Web page. Their pages are indexed in a database that can be
accessed only by recruiters and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Young athletes must complete a brief online application. Upon
receipt, a representative of the Long Island, N.Y.-based site will
contact the athlete and find out what the athlete hopes to
accomplish. Athletes then pay a fee of $50 to $100 and have their
page posted with statistics and video clips.
</P>
<P>
   AthleteNetwork.com (www.athletenetwork.com) of Los Angeles
provides young athletes, parents, coaches and advisers with
resources necessary to make informed decisions. Users can retrieve
expert commentary and information on education, counseling,
parenting and sports psychology.
</P>
<P>
   Diamond Dreams Scouting and Recruiting
(www.allstarbaseball.com), developed by Canadians Mike and Sean
Keady, offers advice to young athletes on finding scholarships and
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball Parent (members.aol.com/baseparent) mostly has
information for youth baseball, but it does have a list of
resources for parents who are looking for a college baseball
program best suited for their children.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone has been to a high school baseball game and watched _
and probably heard _ beaming parents, you will understand that
Howdeshell has cornered a market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that my Web site will give people the information
necessary to help a player achieve his goals,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   SPEAKING OF MARKETING: NPD Online Research of Port Washington,
N.Y., released a survey Monday that found sports sites are becoming
more important to female Web users. The major finding: 36 percent
of females (1,595 participated) who go online retrieve sports news
via the 'Net. Their favorite site: ESPN.com (42 percent).
</P>
<P>
   FANTASY HELP: For fantasy hobbyists who continue to have a life,
here is a book that should help eliminate more of it: Fantasy
Sports Online for Dummies. The guide, written by Jim Keogh and Gus
Nunziata for IDG Books Worldwide of Foster City, Calif., helps
fantasy sports players get the most out of online leagues. For
about $25, the book contains an Internet directory, explanations of
rules and procedures and a companion CD-ROM packed with several
fantasy-league programs.
</P>
<P>
   BROWNS ONLINE: The Cleveland Browns' official site
(www.clevelandbrowns.com) was relaunched less than a week ago.
Besides the standard press-guide information, it has lots of
interaction, including chat sessions, online trivia games, game-day
polls and e-mail postcards. Dawg Pound fans will be disappointed to
find they are not a part of the site.
</P>
<P>
   (Tommy Cummings writes about the Internet for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7397. E-mail:
dragon(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
