u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-19 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: MAKING READING COOL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oprah Winfrey may have her reading club, but other celebrities
are joining efforts to persuade more Americans to pick up a book.
</P>
<P>
   In a campaign designed to make reading cool to young people _
and, by extension, to sell more books _ the actress Whoopi Goldberg
and the talk show host Rosie O'Donnell are being featured in ads
promoting reading as hip.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign from the Association of American Publishers uses
the catchy tag line ``Get caught reading.'' It will kick off the
annual booksellers convention, Book Expo America, next week in Los
Angeles. The promotion includes ads that will run in national
magazines and newspapers through the end of May.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now, publishing has done very little to promote
reading,'' said Patricia Schroeder, the former member of the House
of Representatives and president and chief executive of the book
publishers group. As part of the campaign, the association has
designated May as Get Caught Reading Month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get Caught Reading Month is directed at infrequent or lapsed
readers and will serve as a surprising, eye-catching reminder of
the joys of reading,'' Ms. Schroeder said, ``particularly among 18-
to 34-year-olds who often don't make time for books when the
Internet, television and so much other media compete for their
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schroeder cited industry statistics showing that adults 55
and older account for 32 percent of book purchases in the United
States while people younger than 35 buy only 20 percent of the
books sold.
</P>
<P>
   The ads that will try to increase the number of young book
buyers show Ms. Goldberg reading ``Peter Pan'' and Ms. O'Donnell
reading ``The Bean Trees,'' by Barbara Kingsolver. The ads, created
by Ogilvy &AMP; Mather New York, part of the Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide
unit of WPP Group PLC, are intended to communicate a love of books
and to promote the pleasures of reading.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, Ms. Schroeder said, is to do what milk producers did
by putting milk mustaches on everyone from Spike Lee to Melanie
Griffith _ use star appeal to reach a specific audience without
being preachy.
</P>
<P>
   The featured celebrities in the publishers group's campaign
chose the books they were photographed reading but were limited to
backlist titles to avoid giving the impression that the campaign
was intended to promote authors and publishers of new books.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, which has been endorsed by the main publishing
houses, including Bertelsmann's Random House, Viacom's Simon &AMP;
Schuster and Time Warner's Warner Books, represents a collective
effort involving companies representing virtually every aspect of
the book industry. Businesses donated everything from the paper for
15,000 posters and bookmarks to the printing. Ogilvy &AMP; Mather
volunteered the creative work, and photographers donated their
photos of the celebrities. Ms. Goldberg and Ms. O'Donnell also
volunteered their services.
</P>
<P>
   ``A national book campaign sends an overwhelmingly positive
message throughout this country and is long overdue,'' said Mel
Parker, immediate past chairman of the publisher group's trade
executive committee.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the donated production work, magazines and newspapers
provided free space for the full-page ads. They range from People
magazine and Newsweek to USA Today and The New York Times Book
Review. Other publications include George, Business Week, Reader's
Digest and Disney magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The booksellers, who would be among the biggest beneficiaries if
more people read more often, got involved, too. Barnes &AMP; Noble,
Borders and other bookstores will promote the campaign with window
displays and posters as well as with bookmarks and shopping bags
displaying a ``Get caught reading'' logo. Some will hold special
events based on the theme.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the broad-based support for the project overwhelming,
Ms. Schroeder said, ``It will benefit everyone involved, not to
mention all those people who are inspired to pick up a good book.''
</P>
<P>
   She initially proposed the idea of such a project to the
publishers' association board more than a year and a half ago. At
the time, though, it was greeted with skepticism because some
members were concerned about how the group would pay for such a
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But as interest in it grew, and the donations began trickling
in, the board decided to back the project and set out to make it a
reality. Now, it is likely to be expanded into an annual event in
which the ads will be updated with new celebrity endorsers. For
next year, the actor Bill Murray is already scheduled to be a
celebrity endorser, though it has not been determined which book he
will be photographed reading.
</P>
<P>
   And Ms. Schroeder is walking her own talk. She just completed
``Charming Billy'' by Alice McDermott.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-99 2319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
