A5228 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-BUDGET-COX     04-19 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-BUDGET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Finance Committee passes Senate budget proposal
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Moving the session's most important bill another
step forward, the Senate Finance Committee on Monday approved its
version of the state's budget for 2000-2001, including new money
for schools, tax cuts and state employee pay raises.
</P>
<P>
   Though lawmakers and Gov. George W. Bush have many things they
want to accomplish before the session ends May 31, passing a
spending plan is the top priority for each Legislature and is the
main reason lawmakers gather every two years.
</P>
<P>
   The full House approved its version of the budget last week,
proposing $97 billion in spending and leaving more than $700
million available for other things such as sales and business tax
cuts and the state's savings account.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's version of the plan proposes $98.4 billion in
spending. After the full Senate adopts the Finance Committee's
proposal, representatives from both chambers will gather in a
conference committee to resolve the differences. The House and
Senate must pass the same version of the budget before it can go to
Bush. He has the power to veto portions of the plan, but cannot add
any money to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a good product,'' Sen. Bill Ratliff, R-Mount
Pleasant, said before the committee he heads voted 11-0 to send its
substitute for House Bill 1 to the full Senate. ``It's a product we
can take to conference proudly.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the House version of the bill, the Finance Committee put
much of the proposed revenue growth over the current $88.5 billion
state budget into education. Public schools would get $29.6 billion
under the Senate bill, nearly $3 billion more than the current
$26.7 billion being spent to help educate Texas school children.
The House version of the bill would spend $30.3 billion on public
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we put our gold where our hearts ought to be,''
Ratliff said, referring to new money for schools, children's
protective services and children's health care.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill also contains $428 million for state employee
pay raises. That would equal a roughly 3 percent raise for all
employees, including nonfaculty workers at state colleges and
universities, Ratliff said. The House version did not contain a
general state employees' pay raise, but did leave room for public
school teacher pay raises to be determined by the House Public
Education Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Both proposals accommodate Bush's top priorities of teacher pay
raises, forcing cuts to local school property taxes by spending
more state money on public education and cutting some consumer and
business taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff said the Senate bill covers the state's needs, but
doesn't do as much as he and others would like.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have enough,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander earlier this year said the
state has $94 billion for the 2000-2001 budget years, which begins
Sept. 1. That did not include an estimated $3.3 billion expected to
be left from the current budget or more than $1 billion from the
first payment to the state by the tobacco industry, under terms of
its lawsuit settlement.
</P>
<P>
   As has happened in the past, Rylander is expected to announce
that more money is available for the 2000-2001 budgets. As of last
week, however, Rylander said she still was unaware of any
additional money.
</P>
<P>
   With money from the state's $17.3 billion tobacco settlement
rolling in, both versions of the budget contain a new section to
clearly show where that money is going. Much of it would be used to
create an endowment for an anti-smoking campaign, while part of it
would go to help a teachers' insurance program.
</P>
<P>
   Of importance to Austin, the Senate bill contains $5 million for
the state to purchase 282 acres at Robert Mueller Municipal Airport
after it closes. The land is expected to be used for state office
buildings, and the city is expected to use money from the deal to
help redevelop the area after Austin-Bergstrom International
Airport opens this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Juan B. Elizondo Jr. writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
