<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-ANITA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACELIFT TO BEGIN AT SANTA ANITA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ The sea foam green and pale yellow grandstand
at Santa Anita Park has seen better days.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when the wood and steel pavilion was packed
with eager race fans willing to plunk down a $2 bet on a Citation
or a Seabiscuit or a John Henry. There was a time when a tout with
holes in his shoes could rub elbows with movie stars and captains
of industry.
</P>
<P>
   Hot, humid and smoggy though it was, Monday marked the last day
of that bygone era.
</P>
<P>
   This morning the venerable race track will begin a metamorphosis
as new owner Frank Stronach implements his plan to remake the track
into an entertainment facility and usher in a new era in Southern
California horse racing. When Stronach's epic plan is complete, the
only recognizable thing at Santa Anita may be the San Gabriel
Mountains towering over the backstretch as silent reminders of the
giants that once raced here.
</P>
<P>
   Today the misty memories of 64 years will be swept away like the
cobwebs hanging in the high iron rafters. Work crews will begin a
non-stop reconstruction scheduled to end just in time for the Oak
Tree meet Sept. 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take on a whole new look Tuesday,'' said Craig
Luskey, a construction supervisor with Pave West. ``And by Friday
it will look totally different.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the $18 million first phase of Stronach's
multi-million renovation plan will remake the grandstand and tiled
track apron. The project also includes moving a barn area to the
north parking lot and constructing a new dining room and dorms for
backstretch workers.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, Stronach planned to move the walking ring to the
front of the grandstand and eliminate the downhill turf course. He
has since scrapped both plans, much to the relief of veteran
track-goers. After all, both sites are steeped in the tradition and
lore of Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   ``The place does need some renovation,'' said Dr. Larry Samovar,
a San Diego State University professor and part-owner of Academic
Farm stables.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing stays the same,'' Samovar lamented. ``I guess like
anyone else, though, the older I get the more I dislike change.''
</P>
<P>
   A change that particularly disturbs Samovar is the planned
makeover of box seats just below the glass-windowed press box.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my fellow owners has had an entire box for years,''
Samovar said. ``When this renovation came up he was never consulted
and has yet to be told what will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Some younger race fans don't care about the planned changes.
Many say they are long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the '90s,'' said Enrique Bradley, 31, of Burbank. ``This
place is one of the prettiest tracks I've been do. It could use a
little upgrading though.''
</P>
<P>
   One immediate concern of Jessica Adkins, 27, of Glendale, was
the track's food service.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to bring young people in, they need to have
healthier food choices,'' Adkins said. ``It shouldn't be just hot
dogs and roast beef sandwiches.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing that won't change anytime soon is the racing. Monday
there was plenty of that _ 10 races in all, including the $75,000
Santa Paula Stakes, the $100,000 Valiant Pete Handicap and the
$75,000 Bertrando.
</P>
<P>
   Perfect Six, a 5-1 shot, came out the winner in the four-horse
Santa Paula. The 3-year-old, ridden by meet champion David Flores,
paid $11.40 and $3.60.
</P>
<P>
   In the Valiant Pete, Enjoy the Moment was the winner. Trained by
Bill Spawr and ridden by veteran Laffit Pincay Jr., Enjoy the
Moment paid $7.20, $4.20 and $3.40.
</P>
<P>
   Vetheuil took the Bertrando and paid $22.40, $11.40 and $6.40.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The 84-day meet that ended Monday had its share of bright
spots. For the second straight year, both attendance and overall
handle were up.
</P>
<P>
   The meet had an average daily handle of $11,830,250, a 1.55
percent increase over 1997-98. The total handle was $993,740,990.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Anita Handicap and the Santa Anita Derby each brought
in more than $24 million.
</P>
<P>
   As for attendance, the daily average totaled 12,482 on track _ a
1 percent increase over last year, which was also up 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Top guns: Flores, with 75 wins, won the meet riding title, his
first ever at Santa Anita.... Bob Baffert led all trainers with 42
wins from 172 starters.
</P>
<P>
   Top horses: Reporters and handicappers polled by Santa Anita
chose Free House as Horse of the Meet. General Challenge, winner of
the Santa Anita Derby, was voted 3-year-old colt of the meet.
Excellent Meeting was voted 3-year-old filly of the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
