<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONGTERM-CAPITAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 RIVALS JOIN TO TAKE OVER REVIVED FUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ask Wall Street experts to name two financiers whose
fortunes are tied most closely to the bond market and they would
most likely settle on Jon Corzine, the chairman of Goldman Sachs
Group, and John Meriwether, founder of the hedge fund Long-Term
Capital Management.
</P>
<P>
   So it comes as only a mild shock that Corzine and Meriwether,
longtime rivals and even bitter antagonists as recently as last
fall, have joined forces. Their plan is to head a revived version
of Long-Term Capital free from the banks and brokerage firms that
rescued it from imminent bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the new alliance, which was confirmed by people close
to the hedge fund, were sketchy Monday night. But Corzine and
Meriwether are expected to serve as the lead partners in a new
company that specializes in bond trading. They are seeking to line
up outside investors who could buy the multibillion-dollar fund
from the 14 Wall Street firms, including Goldman itself, that now
own and control it. The effort is in its early stages, the people
close to the hedge fund said.
</P>
<P>
   Long-Term Capital generated riches for its founding investors
for several years but nearly went broke during the panic in world
bond markets last September, just after Russia defaulted on its
debt. The Federal Reserve feared that the collapse of the fund,
which held securities valued in excess of $100 billion, could set
off a huge financial crisis. The Fed arranged for banks and
brokerage firms to keep it solvent with a capital injection of $3.6
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Long-Term Capital has recovered strongly, earning at
least 25 percent profits for its saviors as it sold off risky
securities and reduced the amount of money it borrows to make bets.
</P>
<P>
   Meriwether and his partners have sought for weeks to secure a
future for the hedge fund independent of the Wall Street firms.
They have traveled around the world to explain its near-death
experience to early backers and line up future investment. The
consortium of Wall Street firms seems receptive to a buyout: People
close to the consortium said the banks would consider selling all
or part of its 90 percent stake as early as June.
 &UR;  &LR;  The involvement of Corzine in Long-Term Capital's efforts to
secure a future is rich in paradox. Early this year, Corzine lost
his executive position at Goldman in a board room coup, a rare
public rift at the tight-knit firm.
</P>
<P>
   Other top executives there complained that under Corzine, who
rose up to Goldman's executive suite from the bond-trading floor,
the firm wagered too much in risky bond trading. Goldman suffered
nearly $700 million in trading losses last fall, causing it to
withdraw plans to offer shares to the public at that time. Corzine
kept his position as chairman but recently announced plans to
retire as soon as Goldman completes its public offering, which is
scheduled for early May.
</P>
<P>
   Meriwether's bond-trading career has had similar ups and downs.
As the bond king at Salomon Brothers, Meriwether made that firm a
Wall Street powerhouse only to resign after a bond-trading scandal.
He eventually founded Long-Term Capital and staffed it with his
Salomon colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   The two Wall Street executives were not thought to be friends.
In fact, they battled for top trading talent in the 1980s when they
ran the bond desks at Salomon and Goldman. And, in their more
recent roles, they butted heads in August, when Long-Term Capital
neared collapse.
</P>
<P>
   With Corzine calling the shots, Goldman sought to line up
investors to buy Long-Term Capital for pennies on the dollar. The
bid came even as Goldman itself negotiated to buy Long-Term Capital
as part of the Wall Street consortium. Goldman's independent buyout
offer was backed by Warren Buffett and American International
Group, the insurance giant. If it had succeeded, Goldman would have
taken over Long-Term Capital and Meriwether and his partners would
have been ousted. Several Long-Term Capital partners complained
about Goldman's role in subsequent interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine made another pass at Long-Term Capital in October, when
he called Prince Walid bin Talal of Saudi Arabia to gauge his
interest in buying the hedge fund from the consortium. That effort
failed as well.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear when Meriwether and Corzine decided to join forces
instead of competing against each other, but people close to the
hedge fund said they had been talking for several weeks. Goldman
recently sent a letter to other members of the consortium,
including Merrill Lynch, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, Citigroup and
Chase Manhattan, informing them of Corzine's intention of working
with Meriwether. The letter said that Corzine was acting as an
individual, not as chairman of Goldman.
</P>
<P>
   Both Corzine and Meriwether declined to comment on their plans,
which were first reported Monday in The Financial Times of London.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine has been exploring future options for several months.
Top political figures in New Jersey, where Corzine lives, said the
financier had been actively exploring a bid to run for Senate on
the Democratic ticket in 2000. It could not be determined whether
Corzine's involvement with Meriwether would alter those plans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
