<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-MISSING-LAWYER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSING LAWYER RETURNS AND SURRENDERS TO POLICE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ F. Mac Buckley, the Connecticut lawyer and
boxing promoter who vanished on his way to a hearing seven weeks
ago, turned himself in to the state police Monday morning and
appeared in court a few hours later looking trim and bronzed.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley, who is charged with embezzling several hundred thousand
dollars from clients, was released on a $200,000 bond on the
condition that he immediately check into a locked ward of a
psychiatric hospital in Hartford until a court appearance scheduled
for April 30.
</P>
<P>
   It was a stunning comedown for Buckley, a defense lawyer known
for his fondness for cigars and tall tales, and for representing
mobsters and others in criminal cases. He is a former assistant
federal prosecutor, ran unsuccessfully for Congress and appeared on
ESPN as a commentator during the O.J. Simpson case.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Buckley had called a lawyer who arranged for him to
be interviewed by a psychiatrist for several hours, according to
statements in court Monday. The psychiatrist prepared a letter that
was presented in Superior Court here. Its contents were not
revealed, but Judge Patrick J. Clifford said after reading the
letter that he did not think Buckley was a danger to the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only threat may be to himself at this particular time,''
said Clifford, who entered a not guilty plea on Buckley's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley, 57, whose case had been featured on the Fox television
program ``America's Most Wanted,'' told the authorities little
about where he had been since he disappeared on March 1. The
prosecutor, Herbert E. Carlson Jr., said Buckley's lawyer, Hubert
J. Santos, had said only that his client had been ``down south''
and ``a long distance away.''
</P>
<P>
   The many lawyers who packed the courtroom Monday morning said
they were startled by Buckley's deep tan and sun-lightened hair. He
had lost so much weight _ his wanted poster put him at 230 pounds,
but Monday's booking sheet said he weighed 200 _ that he kept
hiking up his pants during his court appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after Buckley's disappearance, friends said they
feared he might have been harmed by a former client or by an enemy
of one of the many gang members and mobsters he defended over the
years. The police searched the roads and woods between his home in
Marlborough and New Haven, where he had been due in court.
</P>
<P>
   But Buckley was declared a fugitive 11 days after his
disappearance, when warrants were issued charging him with
first-degree larceny and second-degree forgery. A couple he had
represented charged that he had forged their signatures on a check
from an account he held in trust for them, following a settlement
for their daughter's death in a drunken-driving accident. Buckley's
law license was suspended a week after his disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   Santos said his client wanted ``to make sure that the victims
who are mentioned in the arrest warrant are made whole.'' He did
not mention the several other former clients who have gone to the
authorities with accusations that they had lost money Buckley
controlled.
</P>
<P>
   After Buckley surrendered at the state police barracks in
Hartford, he was arrested on the two felony charges, then taken to
court. He was met by his wife, Donna, five daughters, two
grandchildren, a brother and a sister. One daughter put up $20,000
in cash, 10 percent of the amount of the bond, and Buckley posted
bail two hours after his arraignment.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley and Santos were silent as they waded through the
newspaper and television photographers who followed them down the
sidewalk outside court. Santos, a former law partner of Buckley's,
briefly choked up during the arraignment. But Buckley stared coolly
at Clifford the whole time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
