<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5247 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVERGLADES-FIRES-COX     04-19 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADES-FIRES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fire used to battle Everglades blaze
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTON, Fla. _ Forest rangers trying to control a raging
Everglades wildfire that has consumed 120,000 acres are fighting it
the only way they know how: with fire.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, rangers began lighting fires across miles and miles
of sawgrass after the blaze jumped a canal Sunday, engulfing 10,000
acres in just twelve hours, and threatened to sweep westward. If
unchecked, firefighters fear the fire, pushed by shifting easterly
winds, will advance into parts of the Seminole Tribe's Big Cypress
reservation or the urban areas of Collier County. Rangers hope the
controlled back fires _ expected to consume another 100,000 acres _
will leave the out-of-control fire nothing to burn.
</P>
<P>
   By the time they're done, the fire will have consumed 220,000
acres in the famed river of grass that stretches for 2.365 million
acres.
</P>
<P>
   The area totals nearly half that burned in all of last year,
when blazes ignited Memorial Day weekend and continued through the
summer, erupting July 4th weekend in Flagler and Volusia counties
and chasing 70,000 people from their homes. Eventually, 370 homes
and buildings were destroyed or damaged.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, wildfires have engulfed about 130,000 acres,
not including the Everglades fire, which rangers dubbed the
``Deceiving Fire'' because of its unpredictable ferocity. The worst
fire by far ravaged Port St. Lucie, where federal and state
officials raised the tally of destroyed houses to 51 on Monday. St.
Lucie County officials valued the damage at $4.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 127 homes were burned as fires, fanned by 30 mph winds,
streaked through the neighborhoods. The Federal Emergency
Management Agency arrived Monday to begin helping families. And
state legislative leaders decided to seek another $10 million to
battle the wildfires.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, skies in southern Palm Beach County darkened
with a dirty brown haze rising from the Everglades fire Monday
evening.
</P>
<P>
   The fire ignited Friday _ rangers have several theories on how
including sparks from a catalytic converter, but say the source was
definitely not natural _ but didn't grow alarming until Sunday. Up
until then, rangers thought they had the fire hemmed in by four
barriers: Interstate 75 on the south, which the Florida Highway
Patrol shut down Sunday because of heavy smoke; U.S. Highway 27 on
the east; the L-5 canal to the north; and to the west, the Miami
Canal, a 30-foot wide waterway which runs from Lake Okeechobee to
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Wind, dryness fan flames
</P>
<P>
   But about 7 p.m., flames jumped the Miami Canal and streaked
westward, fanned by winds carried south by Saturday's cold front.
</P>
<P>
   ``If not for that one spot, this thing would be close to under
control,'' Division of Forestry forester Erin Albury said Monday as
he stood on the edge of Alligator Alley, his Nomex flame-retardant
jumpsuit splotched with soot. ``Yesterday evening the winds got a
little swirly. One ember was all it took to burn.''
</P>
<P>
   Then on Monday, the humidity dropped to 30 percent, sucking any
bit of moisture from the drought-stricken area. (Monday's drought
index climbed to 713 on a scale of 800.)
</P>
<P>
   Because the fire has burned mostly in the interior of the
Everglades, rangers have been unable to attack by ground. The muck,
Albury said, is too wet for brush trucks and too dry for airboats.
Instead, firefighters and rangers patrol the two highways in water
tankers, making sure embers don't cross and ignite the other side,
and keep watch from above in reconnaissance planes. Monday morning,
the planes spotted an 8-foot-wide airboat trail beyond the Miami
Canal and planned to use it as a fire break. But by 4 p.m., they
determined the trail wasn't holding and started back-burning from
the L-28 canal near the Collier County border.
</P>
<P>
   Using a helicopter from the Bureau of Indian Affairs, rangers
dropped plastic balls packed with mildly explosive chemicals along
I-75, working westward to the canal, to ignite controlled fires,
DOF spokesman John Fish said. They'll also begin burning interior
sections, he said. What worries them most now is shifting wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a cold front comes from the North, it moves to the east
and then works around to the south, just like clockwork,'' Albury
said. ``The problem is, the only wind that's really predictable is
the north wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Ash falls on community
</P>
<P>
   As those winds shifted again Monday afternoon, they sent a dirty
cloud of smoke and ash over the barrel-tiled roofs of Weston. When
the ash landed, it melted like snow, leaving a greasy spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It leaves your clothes kind of greasy,'' said Jon Hess, who
sat by his San Messina neighborhood pool as his daughter played
nearby. ``Yesterday ash was everywhere. My daughter's basketball
game had to be cancelled.''
</P>
<P>
   The fires caught almost everyone off guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a sunny day and from one instant to the other, it's
dark,'' said Carlos Gomez. ``It looked like the Fourth of July over
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Respritory problems increase
</P>
<P>
   Broward County firefighters said the number of calls _ from
complaints about smoke to trouble breathing _ shot up. They warned
people in the neighborhood to stay inside, even Monday when the
skies lightened slightly. Rescue crews also packed additional
inhalers and medicine to cover the increasing respiratory calls,
said spokesman Todd LeDuc.
</P>
<P>
   The fires were a huge inconvenience to residents of Broward and
Miami-Dade, but were expected to do little if any damage to the
Everglades, where fires are part of the natural ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Highway Patrol predicted that I-75 would remain
closed for days as rangers continue battling the blaze and rerouted
most traffic to the Tamiami Trail. Rangers also said that a series
of Florida Power &AMP; Light poles that hold wires supplying power to
much of South Florida are no longer in danger because areas around
them have already burned. They plan to continue fighting the fire
from the air, unless the back-burning fails.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going in front of this fire. We're not going to put
people out there because nothing's in danger, so we won't put
people in danger for sawgrass,'' Albury said. ``But if it continues
westward and we're talking about the Indian reservation, that's a
different ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Drivers can call a Florida Highway Patrol hot line for updates
on road closings due to wildfires and smoke. The number is
800-342-3557.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Staletovich writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
